<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BIRD REMAINING CALM AFTER PACER MELTDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Without much worry, Larry Bird calmly fielded
inquiries on Monday about how to fix things for his basketball
team. Reflecting his stoic sideline demeanor, Coach Bird addressed
the Pacers' problems with all the exuberance of a farmer watching
wheat grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to win four games,'' Bird deadpanned of his team's
0-1 plight against the New York Knicks in the Eastern Conference
finals. ``If we lose tomorrow, I'll be saying the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later Jeff Van Gundy, his Knicks having seized the
home-court advantage from the hottest team in the league, took time
after practice to speak in defense of Patrick Ewing. Animated,
stubborn, the Knick coach would not waver in his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast was surreal. You lose Game 1 in New York, the coach
is in trouble, the franchise center needs to be shipped out, and
the season _ no, Gotham _ is in peril.
</P>
<P>
   In the heartland, Bird yawns and says, ``The Knicks played
pretty good,'' and life returns to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded about what motivational wisdom he imparted to the
Pacers, he smiled and said, ``I told them to take it easy and have
a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Some crisis mode they go into here in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the Pacers are in imminent danger of
getting knocked out by the Knicks, whether Indiana is 48 minutes
away from falling into an 0-2 abyss in the four-of-seven-game
series. Yet with Game 2 approaching on Tuesday night, the sense is
that Bird is looking at his team's Game 1 loss as an aberration
rather than real trouble.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, it is encouraging to see someone shrug his
shoulders about his team's meltdown in the final minutes, as if it
does not faze him that in the history of the National Basketball
Association, the team that has lost the first game of a seven-game
playoff series has gone on to lose the series 79.2 percent of the
time. On another level, the Pacers are beginning to show their
gray.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller, Mark Jackson, Chris Mullin and the oft-injured
Rik Smits are closer to the end of a career than its prime, and the
Knicks made them look awfully old at times on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bird saw this rejuvenated Knick team up close in Game 1. He
watched Allan Houston create his own shots, whereas Reggie Miller
could not. When the Pacers were trying to slow the tempo and pound
the ball inside, Bird watched Latrell Sprewell bring adrenaline
onto the floor and take off in the open court.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Houston is, he can face you up, freeze you and
go right up with it,'' Bird said. ``Reggie, to get his shots he has
to rely more on screens and he's got to rely more going to the
basket and shooting floaters. Really, they're not the same type of
offensive players.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Knicks, he added: ``They're focused, they're
playing harder and they're playing for something now. Whereas in
the regular season, somewhat like us, guys were complaining about
their playing time, they didn't have their unit really set, they
were trying out new things. But they're fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   Perception can change so quickly in this game. For all the
tumult and uncertainty surrounding the Knicks and Van Gundy this
season, Indiana's best and perhaps last chance to win a
championship is now.
</P>
<P>
   Bird's ability to swoop down and improve a gifted veteran team
may go for naught if the Pacers can't solve the Knicks in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry's message was that it's going to be a long series and
we're going to have to look at it that way,'' said Jalen Rose, the
reserve guard who struggled in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bird said he planned to use Dale Davis more down the stretch
instead of having the bruising power forward languish on the bench
in the fourth quarter. He said he wanted to get Miller more shots,
preferably about 18 a game. Having played for much weightier stakes
than a Game 2 in his playing career, however, Bird never went
further than the usual between-game adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, he is almost beyond reproach. The Pacers'
president, Donnie Walsh, often likens Bird's popularity in Indiana
to ``proportions reaching DiMaggio.'' He is a source of great pride
for the Hoosier State, its own Larry Legend who came home to roost.
</P>
<P>
   Bird finally absorbed criticism this season for his unemotional
approach on the sideline _ callers to a radio program wanted to
know why the Pacers coach stood there with his hands in his pockets
as his team was imploding on the floor. He responded by saying no
one knew how badly he wanted to win internally, that his
competitive juices flowed more freely than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he is not watching the wheat grow. Maybe Larry Bird, in
his infinite playoff wisdom, knows more about handling post-season
pressure than anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, only a few certainties have emerged so far: the
Knicks look good, Bird is unconcerned, and Van Gundy, well, he
still can't sleep. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
