</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES EARN A RARE TRIP TO THE FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ For the first time in 24 years and for the second time
in their history, the Buffalo Sabres are going to the Stanley Cup
finals. They clinched the Eastern Conference championship on Monday
night in the Air Canada Center with a 4-2 victory over the Toronto
Maple Leafs, winning the four-of-seven-game series by 4 games to 1.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo will play the winner of the Western Conference finals
between Dallas and Colorado. The Avalanche leads that series by 3-2
with Game 6 in Denver on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres last made the trip to the championship round in 1975,
when they were defeated by the Philadelphia Flyers during the era
of the Broad Street Bullies.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have changed uniform styles, arenas, coaches,
general managers and owners in the past two seasons, the Sabres
have been on a steady rise. They reached the third round last
season before losing to Washington. This spring, the Sabres are at
least one step higher but will probably be the underdog against the
Western winner.
</P>
<P>
   When the Prince of Wales trophy was presented to the Sabres'
captain, Michael Peca, he shook hands with the National Hockey
League executive Colin Campbell but refused even to touch the
trophy. It was not a sign of disrespect, but a gesture that
symbolized how the Sabres have bigger trophies in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get hot, we can be a pretty good team,'' Peca said.
``We're a young team, and we're having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca was asked which opponent he would prefer in the finals.
Like most people around hockey, Peca has enjoyed watching the
Western series, one of the classics of the decade. ``It's been fun
watching their series,'' Peca said, refusing to choose a favorite
for a foe. ``Whoever comes out will be a deserving team.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo broke a 2-2 tie at 11 minutes 35 seconds of the third
period on a goal by Erik Rasmussen, who finished a rush by knocking
in a rebound past Leafs goalie Curtis Joseph after Joseph made a
save on the initial shot by Brian Holzinger.
</P>
<P>
   Although defenseman Tomas Kaberle was near Rasmussen, he did not
check him. Kaberle is a rookie and, like many of his teammates, is
inexperienced at this level. Toronto missed the playoffs in the
previous two seasons but enjoyed a successful regular season with
an entertaining, high-scoring style before beating Philadelphia and
Pittsburgh in the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Quinn, the Toronto coach, said: ``These guys never griped
and kept battling. Nothing in the tank right now. I don't know if
we hit the wall. We believed we had a chance. That's obviously gone
now. We'll remember it all our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Peca did not score or assist on Monday night, he played
well and made a key check. Early in the third period, with the
score still tied, he rammed Toronto's Sergei Berezin into the
boards, putting Berezin out of the game with an undisclosed injury.
Berezin was one of Toronto's prime scoring threats on a team that
has lost several forwards to injuries in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon Ward made it 4-2 by scoring into an empty net with 1:02
remaining after Toronto had pulled Joseph for an extra attacker
during a Leafs power play.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's other goals were scored by Curtis Brown at even
strength and Vaclav Varada on the power play. Toronto's goals were
scored by Steve Sullivan on the power play and Kris King at even
strength. Each team had a goal disallowed after video review.
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hasek, Buffalo's goalie, stopped 20 of 22 Toronto shots
while playing his third consecutive game after missing the first
two in the series with a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek showed a flash of temper that is considered one of his
vulnerabilities, however. After being slashed by Toronto's Mike
Johnson in the second period, Hasek threw his big blocker glove,
flung his stick to the ice, purposely knocked his net askew, picked
up his stick and then fired the water bottle that had been on top
of his net across the ice. No penalty was called. Hasek's groin
injury and his temper _ along with the talent that has made him the
most valuable player in the league for the past two seasons _ could
become critical factors in the pressure of the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was well played and scoreless. The second was
wildly eventful and ended in a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto scored first, at the 33-second mark, a goal credited to
Sullivan, whose long shot was swiped at by Toronto's captain, Mats
Sundin, on its way to the net. Although Sundin was originally
credited with the goal, he apparently missed the puck, which seemed
to hit the stick of a Buffalo defenseman before fluttering over
Hasek's shoulder and across the line.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs seemed to make it 2-0 on a power play at 2:38, but the
goal, by Berezin, was nullified after a video review because Sundin
was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo made it 1-1 on a goal by Brown at 7:14. The Leafs took a
2-1 lead at 12:54 on a goal by King, who knocked in a rebound of a
Sundin shot that hit the goal post. This goal was also reviewed
because Tie Domi was prone, partly in the crease, after being
checked, as the puck crossed the line. But this one counted after
video viewing.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes before, Domi appeared to be stunned when run into
the boards by Richard Smehlik, headfirst. Domi remained on the ice
for a few moments for medical attention, but he skated to the bench
and recovered quickly.
</P>
<P>
   With Toronto's Garry Valk in the penalty box for roughing,
Buffalo tied the score at 2-2 at 16:44 when Varada knocked in his
own rebound from close range after Joseph sprawled while making the
first save. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
