<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROTURF BOUNCES BEFUDDLE DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Artificial turf does strange things to a baseball
game, like control the outcome. That's what the Dodgers are saying.
</P>
<P>
   The fake stuff allowed Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall to double on a
ball hit in front of Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield. The fake
stuff was also the reason Kendall scored on Warren Morris' bloop
single to center field that Devon White short-hopped.
</P>
<P>
   That combination in the eighth inning pushed the Pirates to a
5-4 win against the Dodgers at Three Rivers Stadium on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in an inning in which the Dodgers were protecting a
one-run lead, it was the turf that had the biggest say in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just AstroTurf,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``AstroTurf does funny things. The ball hits in front of you and
bounces, (so) you have to play deep. Funny things happen here. I've
never seen basehits in front of guys that are doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps until Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (26-24) led 4-3 heading into the bottom of the
eighth and were four outs away from their first three-game winning
streak since April 27 through May 1. Then reliever Jamie Arnold
(2-1) walked Kevin Young. Kendall hit a soft liner in front of a
deep Sheffield, who backed off the ball to play the high bounce and
try to keep Young from scoring.
</P>
<P>
   However, Young was running on the pitch and beat Mark
Grudzielanek's relay throw home to score the tying run. Kendall
advanced to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make decisions you don't normally make on
(grass),'' Sheffield said. ``You tell yourself on balls not hit
hard, `Should I go for it and dive on the hard turf or play
conservative and hopefully have the pitcher bail you out by making
a pitch?' . . . When you play with no sleeves, (you can get nasty)
rug burn. I've never dove on it in the outfield. When I played
infield I did, but not in the outfield on turf. You don't want to
risk injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield has been banged up by the Dodgers' recent schedule on
artificial turf. During the Dodgers' recent three-game series in
Cincinnati, Sheffield experienced discomfort in his back from the
hard artificial turf and wore different shoes when he batted than
we he played the field.
</P>
<P>
   The artificial-turf syndrome reared its head again when Morris,
the former College World Series hero for Louisiana State, batted.
He looped a single to center which White chose to short-hop instead
of trying to dive and make an inning-ending catch.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings earlier White committed his first error of the
season when he tried to short-hop Al Martin's basehit. It scored
Abraham Nunez from second, Martin wound up on third and scored on
Ed Sprague's double to make it 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I misjudged that ball and it got under my glove,'' White said.
``The (Morris) situation, I'm not making any excuses. The ball was
placed perfectly. That's how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching the Dodgers lose the first of a three-game series
for the fifth straight time, Johnson was visibly frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't even short-hop the ball because you don't know where
the ball is going to go,'' Johnson said. ``Maybe on a normal field
(Sheffield) catches it chest high. Devo's the best. If that ball
falls in front of him, it falls in front of him. Those balls are
normally outs. Here, they're doubles and triples.''
</P>
<P>
   The judgments in the field weren't the only ones that didn't
work out the Dodgers' way. The second inning was cut short when
Eric Young tried to get to third on an RBI double and was thrown
out.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi met a similar fate on his RBI single in the eighth
which scored Sheffield and gave the Dodgers a 4-3 lead. Mondesi was
thrown out when Young cut the ball off and threw to second.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also hit into three double plays, and after going 1
for 32 with runners in scoring position in winning two of three at
Atlanta, they were 2 for 5 against the Pirates. Even if one was an
infield single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough game to lose,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros
said. ``If you don't play on turf and then come in, the advantage
is going to be with the turf team. That's not why we win or lose,
not because of the turf. We lost because we didn't get the job
done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
