r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-RACE-LADN-(SLANG)     06-01 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAHOUSSAYE RIDES FOUR WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Eddie Delahoussaye, on the downside of a
Hall of Fame career, won't be part of the Triple Crown drama
Saturday at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   But the 47-year-old jockey staged a triple of his own Monday at
Hollywood Park _ and then went one better, finishing with four
winners on the holiday card, including Gourmet Girl in the $208,400
Milady Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do nowadays,'' said Delahoussaye, who had five
mounts, the loser being fifth-place Magellan in the $400,000
Charles Whittingham Handicap, won by River Bay and Alex Solis.
``I'm not riding a lot of horses and I'm not riding a lot of
quality stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye hasn't ridden in a Belmont since he and A.P. Indy
won it in 1992. He and First American finished 16th in the Kentucky
Derby this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four like that gets your adrenaline pumping and keeps you
going,'' said Delahoussaye, who was 7 for 66 at Hollywood Park when
the day began. ``I'm still competitive and I want to win. When I
don't, that's when I'll quit.''
</P>
<P>
   His fourth winner, Lucky Raisin in the nightcap, made it a
3-for-3 day for trainer Julio Canani.
</P>
<P>
   It was Delahoussaye's first quadruple at Hollywood Park in more
than four years and his first anywhere in at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye sent Pico Perdomo-trained Gourmet Girl ($11.20) to
the lead at the rail on the far turn and won the 1 1/16-mile Milady
by two lengths over pacesetting long shot Yolo Lady. It was the
4-year-old's first Grade I victory. Favored Victory Stripes was
third.
</P>
<P>
   Delahoussaye and Magellan were in contention in the Whittingham
_ formerly the Hollywood Turf Handicap _ before the horse tired.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Frankel-trained River Bay ($13.40) rallied from seventh to
win for the first time since he and Solis captured the Sunset
Handicap on the same turf course last July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
