<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-01 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ Sean Elliott's teammates drew a line in the dirt:
Step across it or just go home with the women and children.
</P>
<P>
   It was about heart. It was about giving this city something
historic.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's reputation was as soft and squishy as those Taco
Cabana carne guisada specials he endorsed on local television. His
heart was questioned. His nerve was doubted. His teammates demanded
he step across the line and fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Sean would have gone into the fourth quarter with 19
points,'' Spurs guard Mario Elie said, ``and ended with 19
points.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Sean saw those lines drawn in the dirt, or in his case
on the basketball floor, and cowered.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Elliott stood at the free-throw line in the
waning seconds of a Western Conference finals game against the
Rockets and all but tripped over it. He missed a pair of free
throws that could have iced a Spurs win. He went home looking soft
and shaken.
</P>
<P>
   But not this Sean. This Sean looked Elie in the eyes during a
final, desperate Spurs timeout in a game that looked like it
belonged to the Portland Trail Blazers and said, ``Give me the
ball. I've got one 3 left in the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The words resonated through Elie's head, and the metaphor was
prophetic. The odds seemed impossible _ the Spurs were once down by
18 points in the second half but somehow fought their way back into
the game.
</P>
<P>
   This Sean had spent the day as the most reliable Spur, calmly
firing away and picking off Blazers as if he were wearing a
coonskin cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to deny him,'' said Elie, who inbounded the
ball with 12 seconds remaining and the Spurs down by a bucket. ``He
had that look.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same look that this Sean has shown his teammates all
year, the look Elie demanded again Monday when he shouted at
teammates, ``Come on, it's all about the heart of a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same look the Spurs have craved from their talented
forward for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   During the preseason, Elie got in Elliott's face and stayed
there. His message: Show some heart when it counts.
</P>
<P>
   During the offseason, David Robinson got up early nearly every
morning when Elliott's scarred knees looked as fragile as his
last-second nerve and pushed his friend in the weight room. His
message: We're going to need you, Sean.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, after the Blazers spent 46 minutes launching full assault
on Robinson and Tim Duncan, running the Spurs virtually out of the
building, Elliott knew the final two minutes had to belong to his
deadly shooting gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to hesitate in those situations,'' Elie said. ``He
would look for a pass or maybe wait too long, until the defense was
on him. But he wanted the ball all day. That was the sign of a
great player and a confident player ready to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about a player ready to step across the line drawn in the
dirt. It was about moving beyond the reputation.
</P>
<P>
   After a late timeout when the Spurs still were down by eight
points with just two minutes remaining, Robinson huddled his
teammates and shouted, ``We have to relish this situation. Sean, be
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott grabbed a pass from Duncan with 56.9 seconds remaining
and nailed a 3-pointer to draw his team within 84-81.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after a Robinson steal, a pair of Elie free throws and a
free-throw miss by Portland's Damon Stoudamire, the Spurs were
within 85-83 with 12 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott got a finger-in-the-face scream of encouragement from
coach Gregg Popovich during the final timeout and responded,
``Don't worry.''
</P>
<P>
   After Elie got Elliott the ball along the sideline, Elliott saw
Robinson come open on the post for what could have been a
game-tying shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked him off,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott tiptoed inside the sideline, turned, set his feet behind
the 3-point line and lofted a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `My gosh,''' Popovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Robinson: ``You've got to have some serious, uh (nerve) to
take that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   This Sean does. This Sean shot down the Blazers with maybe the
biggest shot the Spurs franchise has ever seen, giving his team its
first lead of the game and carrying the Spurs to an unlikely 2-0
series lead.
</P>
<P>
   As for the old Sean? The fragile one?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have shot it,'' Elliott said. ``I might not have made
it, but I would have shot it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy, perhaps remembering the cowering
Elliott, said he'd bet $100 to see Elliott make that shot again.
</P>
<P>
   But this Sean and these Spurs just might take that bet. Not to
mention the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
