<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7896 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-SLUMP-HNS &LR;      06-01 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-SLUMP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By CARLTON THOMPSON 
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ Lately it seems the Astros might have as much luck
trying to bench-press an elephant or fight a lion as they've had
hitting opposing pitchers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once the biggest and baddest beasts in the National League
jungle, the Astros have been tamed. And in most cases, it hasn't
exactly been Marlon Perkins taking them into captivity.
</P>
<P>
   The current offensive stench began to filter its way through the
clubhouse almost two weeks ago. Blame it on Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' ace and personal slayer of the Astros hypnotized
the Houston bats, holding them to one run on four hits in eight
innings May 19. They have been in a trance ever since, hitting a
measly .187 in that game and the 11 forgettable offensive showings
that have followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't start swinging the bats better we're going to be
in trouble, because the Cubs are playing some very good baseball
right now,'' said catcher Tony Eusebio, who is hitless in his last
18 at-bats and hasn't driven in a run since the day before Brown
put on the hex.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 5-7 in their last 12 games, and their NL Central
lead has been reduced from four games to one. Considering they are
averaging six hits and three runs in those 12 games, the Astros are
fortunate to have won five of 12.
</P>
<P>
   They can thank the pitching staff for that. The Astros have a
team ERA of 3.06 during the same period the offense has struggled.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros haven't scored more than five runs in any game during
the slump and have been held to three runs or fewer in eight of the
12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to even think about it,'' center fielder Carl
Everett said. ``All those numbers and statistics show is that we're
human. We know we're a good-hitting club. We know that on any given
day, we can make a pitcher wish he hadn't shown up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers have been lining up to face the Astros, and the list of
starters who have trotted to the mound during the baffling 12-game
dry spell hardly classifies as a Who's Who.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is rare because most of the time our offense is going to
be anywhere from decent to good,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``In
the last week, I don't remember us facing anyone who I would
classify as dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you're not swinging the bats very well and you're not
drawing as many walks, an average starter with good control can be
effective against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gardner (San Francisco), Bobby Jones (Colorado) and Todd
Ritchie (Pittsburgh) are hardly menacing presences on the mound,
but the Astros couldn't beat any of them. Russ Ortiz (Giants) and
Kris Benson (Pirates) may develop into staff aces someday. But who
wouldn't have liked the Astros' chances against the pair of
wet-behind-the-ears righthanders, who combined to hold the Astros
to seven hits and three runs in 14 innings?
</P>
<P>
   Chan Ho Park, Shawn Estes, Darryl Kile, Pedro Astacio and
Francisco Cordova also put forth quality efforts against the Astros
over the past two weeks. Brian Bohanon and Astacio are the only
starters they have tagged with losses, and Astacio pitched a
complete game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've faced some people who we should have beaten but we
didn't beat,'' said first baseman Jeff Bagwell, whose .286 average
in the last 12 games looks almost like .400 in relation to how his
teammates have fared. ``The bottom line is that teams are going to
go through stretches like this, and we have to go through it as a
team. The focus always comes back to the offense, but a shutout
might be nice right about now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to defer the blame; I'm just saying that you
win and lose as a team. Sometimes the offense has to pick up the
pitching; sometimes the pitching has to pick up the offense. We're
not going to score 10 runs every night. It's a team game. We'll get
through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Astros' offense goes through so many stretches where
the hitters do everything short of assaulting opposing pitchers,
Bagwell realizes the attention will be just as strong _ maybe
stronger _ when they struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created the monster,'' he said. ``But the full monster
hasn't been out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to injuries that have taken Moises Alou, Ken
Caminiti and Ricky Gutierrez out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't discount the injuries,'' Bagwell said. ``We've had a
lot of guys hitting out of position, and that affects things. I'm
not saying those guys can't do the job, but Billy Spiers is not
comfortable hitting cleanup (his spot in the lineup Friday).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not using injuries as an excuse. The bottom line is that
we're just not swinging the bats well. All I'm saying is that you
can't discount the injuries. We're missing some big boys who we
expect a lot from.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectations are just as high for the players who are
healthy, even if their batting averages are not:
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell has seven hits in his last 46 at-bats, only one for
extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio is 11-for-51 in his last 12 games and has almost as
many strikeouts (10) as hits (11).
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett is in a 7-for-34 rut that has dropped his average
24 points.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers has four hits in his last 33 at-bats and hasn't driven in
a run since May 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to hit better,'' Biggio said. ``I don't know how to
say it more flatly than that. We have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
