<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-HNS &LR;      06-01 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ Patrick Ewing sat in the visitors' locker room at
Market Square Arena, grimacing as he slowly lowered his left leg
into a huge trash bucket filled with ice and water.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ewing had just finished playing 40 minutes, scoring 16 points
and pulling down 10 rebounds in Sunday's 93-90 victory over the
Indiana Pacers in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   And it was Ewing who made the big defensive play, jumping out to
distract Indiana's Reggie Miller just enough to make Miller misfire
on a late 3-point attempt that would have given the Pacers a
one-point lead with 16 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   While it has been mentioned by many that the Knicks are perhaps
better off without Ewing clogging things up, Sunday's game was
Exhibit A in Ewing's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Included in Ewing's Game 1 effort was an 8-for-8 night at the
free-throw line, including four straight in the final 51.3 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick has been great for us,'' said Latrell Sprewell.
``People have been talking about how we're better without him. I've
always said we need that guy, we need him to play well, we need
everybody to play well. Patrick was great for us (Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised. Patrick wants a ring more than anybody on
this team. He's going to come out and play regardless of how he's
feeling. That says a lot about his character.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially since he's playing hurt, which is what he will most
certainly be doing in tonight's Game 2 at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any other body part could hurt him now,'' said
New York coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``I don't think there's any left,
unfortunately. This is as healthy as he's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Four times a day, 25 minutes per session, Ewing has to soak his
left leg to ease the tendinitis in his left Achilles' tendon. The
tissue won't heal until he has at least six straight weeks of
complete rest, but for now, while the Knicks are still in the
playoffs, Ewing ices the leg at home, in his hotel room and in the
locker room after games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all banged up,'' he said, managing a small laugh. ``And I
hurt my (left) shoulder, and I got kneed in the quad (quadriceps
muscles, all in Game 1 against the Pacers).''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is willing to endure the pain, however, if he can milk a
few more victories out of his creaky body.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries have been coming at an increasingly steady pace. A
broken wrist not only caused him to miss all but 26 games last
season but had many doubting he would ever be able to play again.
</P>
<P>
   Then as soon as his wrist began to get better, the tendinitis
began to eat away at Ewing's legs, causing many to doubt whether
the 36-year-old center had enough left in his body to lead the
Knicks on a playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected him to come back from his wrist injury,'' said
teammate Herb Williams, one of Ewing's best friends. ``Everyone
thought it was career-ending. He started to feel good, and then the
Achilles' injury came. Mentally, he went back down a little bit.
And he may still be down. I think he's just pushing his way through
it right now because he has to.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ewing ``has to'' because he's one of ``those,'' linked with
Karl Malone, John Stockton, David Robinson and Charles Barkley as
active members among the NBA's 50 Greatest Players who have not won
a championship.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing and the Knicks came close in 1994, losing to the Rockets
in Game 7 of the NBA Finals. But in this most improbable season,
the Knicks, who were in danger of missing the playoffs with fewer
than 10 games left in the regular season, are three victories away
from advancing to the Finals once again.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about his legacy, and Ewing craves a title and the
attendant acclaim that comes with a championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that embrace (from the fans) won't come until he wins
the title,'' Williams said. ``Why do you think he wants it so
badly? What people don't understand is that he doesn't care what
his role is, and he doesn't care how much pain it takes to get
there. He just wants to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   His role has changed, as have the Knicks, because of Ewing's
injuries. Ewing is no longer the focal point of the offense,
allowing Sprewell, Allan Houston and Chris Childs the freedom to
run the floor in transition, an attack that puts added pressure on
opposing defenses.
</P>
<P>
   That was the difference in Game 1, in which the Knicks were able
to whip the Pacers with a 22-8 edge in fast-break points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he realized that at this point, we're all going to do
it together,'' Houston said. ``Nobody is just going to carry it on
his shoulders. It's going to be everybody doing it together. I
don't know if it was hard for him. All I know is, he does trust his
teammates. I think that makes all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a role he consciously made or one we asked
him to make; it just sort of evolved. We're just doing what we do
best as players. With his injuries, it's just happened. Who knows
whether this would have happened if he was 100 percent healthy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe these things wouldn't have been able to happen. We're
just rolling with it. And he's doing a great job mentally
(adjusting) and still realizing how important he is to the team.
That, to me, takes a bigger person and bigger player to do that, to
be able to do what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even through all the pain, rubdowns, icings and whatever else
Ewing endures to prepare himself for yet another game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you want to win a championship, you'll put your body and
life through anything,'' Williams said. ``I think that is still
what's burning in the back of his mind. He's still got something to
prove.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
