<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7898 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-BLAZERS-HNS     06-01 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-BLAZERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Mario Elie jumped into Sean Elliott's face Monday for
another round of barking. The play had not been called and would
not be for several more possessions. But Elie knew.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was Elliott's game, his moment. So Elie stuck his mug into
Elliott's and pounded on his chest, pulling out the old chestnut
from his Houston days: ``Heart of a champion. Heart of a
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, as the San Antonio Spurs took the court for their
last chance, Elliott told Elie, ``M.E., I've got one 3 left in the
gun.'' He grabbed Elie's bullet inbounds pass, balanced himself
just inside the sideline and, with a hop and one dribble, lofted a
perfect 3-pointer just above Rasheed Wallace's considerable reach,
lifting the Spurs to an 86-85 win over the Portland Trail Blazers
in Game 2 of the Western Conference finals. With the win, San
Antonio took a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 100 bucks right now to see him make the same shot
again,'' said Trail Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy, incredulous that
his team had somehow lost a game in which it never trailed before
Elliott's heroics. ``It was an incredible shot.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio trailed by 18 points in the second half, by eight
with less than two minutes left, and by six in the last minute. But
after Elliott's second 3-pointer of the final minute swished with
nine seconds left, he and David Robinson converged on Portland's
Jim Jackson to swat away his driving jumper, Walt Williams' rushed
11-footer came up short, and the Spurs found themselves halfway to
their first Western Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a good sign,'' Robinson said. ``To be a
championship team, you've got to win games like this. Now, we want
to just go in day in and day out with that confidence, to do it
again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Having found a way to win Monday's game, the Spurs would seem to
have the right to expect anything. They were outshot, outrebounded
and outworked from the outset. Aside from the frontcourt of
Elliott, Robinson and Tim Duncan, they made just two of 19
first-half shots as the Trail Blazers became determined to make the
Spurs' supporting cast beat them.
</P>
<P>
   They double-teamed Duncan hard, allowing him only 11 shots. He
made eight and finished with 23 points, 10 rebounds and five
blocked shots. But he and Robinson could not control the game, and
less than two minutes into the second half, the Trail Blazers led
52-34.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what our problem was,'' said Elliott, who
finished with 22 points. ``We were sleepwalking. They outhustled us
to the boards and outplayed us in the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't match their intensity. I'm pretty sure they thought
they had the game in the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott hit a 3 (he was 6-for-7 from the arc for the game),
and after a Damon Stoudamire jumper for the Blazers, San Antonio
suddenly took over, flying through a 14-0, five-minute run that
brought the 35,260 in the Alamodome to full roar and the Spurs to
the belief they could find a way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was huge for us,'' Robinson said. ``It got us back in the
game. It gave us a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But even after the Spurs pulled within one in the fourth
quarter, the Trail Blazers seemed to pull safely away again.
Jackson, playing most of the second half as Isaiah Rider sat out
with a sprained right knee, hit a trey and then scored on a drive
off a spin move. And Wallace, though unable to duplicate Saturday's
breakthrough 28-point performance, hit a pair of jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Elie and Avery Johnson scored for the Spurs, but when Stoudamire
pulled up for a 15-footer, the Trail Blazers led 84-76 with 1:59
left.
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs came back again. Johnson hit a jumper, then set up
Elliott for another 3. Elie then hit a pair of free throws with
33.3 seconds left to pull the Spurs within 84-83, and with the
Trail Blazers holding a chance at the last possession, the Spurs
put Stoudamire on the line and took their chances.
</P>
<P>
   Stoudamire missed his first free throw, leaving Elliott a chance
to go for the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You practice your whole life for situations just like that,
and to not come through is very frustrating,'' said Stoudamire, who
had 15 points and seven assists. ``It was very important, because
it left us with just a two-point lead playing in San Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurs coach Gregg Popovich gave Elliott the option of sending a
pass inside to gain a tie. Robinson set a screen to set Elliott
free, then cut to the low post as planned.
</P>
<P>
   And Elliott would have had ample reason to abandon the 3 he
thought still in his holster. Stacy Augmon cut in front of Elliott,
forcing Elie to throw ``a Roger Clemens fastball'' that nearly
pulled Elliott out of bounds. But as he regained his balance with
Wallace closing and Augmon and Jackson charging from behind,
Elliott waved off Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for the pass,'' Robinson said. ``I thought,
`What are you doing taking that shot?' You've got to have some
serious, uh, nerve to take that shot.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott, seldom known for such bravado, never doubted his
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just felt good,'' he said. ``Sometimes you get in a
situation you feel like you can't miss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers would have bet anything, or at least
Dunleavy's $100, that Elliott could not have made the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sean took that off-balance 3 in the corner, it looked off
from where I saw it,'' Stoudamire said. ``But that's the kind of
luck this team seems to have when they're playing against us. We
just don't have an answer for a shot like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there was any doubting him, Elliott said he would happily
take and make that shot again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do it again right now,'' he said. ``I'm still feeling
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
