<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE THINGS MEAN A LOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There are going to be nights when Mo Vaughn
doesn't come through in the clutch, nights when the little things
make the difference between an Anaheim Angels victory or defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Against the lowly Minnesota Twins on Monday night, an
eighth-inning nonthrow by shortstop Andy Sheets led to a run, and a
judgment call by third-base coach Larry Bowa cost the Angels one in
a 3-2 loss in front of 20,466 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   After his game-winning three-run homer in Sunday's victory over
Kansas City, Vaughn directed the Angels' attention toward building
some consistency during the series with the last-place Twins.
Instead, Vaughn, who flied to left with two outs in the seventh and
runners at first and second, stood in the on-deck circle and
watched Randy Velarde strike out to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't wait for Mo to do it every night,'' Sheets said. ``We
have to execute and do the small things that win games. We didn't
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The momentum of back-to-back wins was over, lost to pitcher
LaTroy Hawkins, who entered the game with a 1-7 record and a team
that had dropped five straight.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher pitched well in his fourth consecutive solid start,
but the Angels had to settle for taking pleasure in his 2.90 ERA
during that span. A less- pleasant stat: The Angels are in last
place in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was spotted a 2-0 lead after three innings. Todd Greene
and Darin Erstad, who have started to pull out of extended slumps,
provided the offense against Hawkins. Greene, whose homer Saturday
night against Kansas City was his only hit of the homestand, opened
the second by driving a 1-0 fastball into the Angels' bullpen for a
1-0 lead. It was Greene's 10th homer of the year, already a season
high just two months into the season.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, whose first-inning homer Sunday snapped a slide at 2 for
18, began the third by rolling a triple into the right-field
corner. Erstad scored on a single by Velarde, his seventh hit in
the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   But that was it. The Twins came in with just 11 sacrifice flies,
second-worst in the league. On Monday it was their biggest weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team beats you with three sac flies, (that) tells you how
important the little things can be,'' manager Terry Collins said.
``There were some times in the game when we needed to do some
things we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins didn't fault Bowa for sending Greene from second on a
base hit to center by Jeff Huson with one out in the eighth. The
Twins had infielder Denny Hocking in center, but Greene was just
past third when Hocking came up with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The throw was a little off-line, but Twins catcher Terry
Steinbach blocked home plate and held onto the ball when Greene
bowled him over.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was more upset that Greene, who is recovering from
surgery to his right shoulder, didn't slide. He also wasn't pleased
when Huson stayed at first even through the throw from center
wasn't cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how Todd feels tomorrow,'' Collins said. ``That's
what I'm worried about. What will it be like after it stiffens
up?''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbach left the game and wound up at a local hospital for
X-Rays, but he certainly played a big role in this game. His
one-out single in the eighth was his third hit of the game. And he
took third when first baseman Doug Mientkiewicz singled to right.
Mientkiewicz stumbled rounding first and could have been easily
thrown out by Sheets, who took the relay from outfielder Greene.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheets held the ball and blew a chance to get the second
out. When pinch hitter Todd Walker flied to left, it should have
been the final out. Instead, Steinbach scored the eventual winning
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I turned to throw, (Mientkiewicz) was right between me
and the first baseman,'' Sheets said. ``If I throw it it could have
bounced off his head and gone into the dugout. Then the winning run
would have walked home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
