<BODY>
  
!by2! Daily News Staff Writer !dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; ANAHEIM _ Tim Belcher pitched seven innings and received
a no-decision in the Angels 3-2 loss Monday night to the Minnesota
Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Seven innings would have been considered a victory in itself a
month ago when Belcher had a 9.96 ERA and a lot of Angels' people
worried. He was signed in the offseason to a two-year, $10.2
million contract and was expected to provide innings. In three
consecutive starts, he failed to get out of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is getting through those early innings,'' said
Belcher, who lowered his ERA to 7.08. ``Once you start to do it,
your confidence begins to improve. So did my location. I stopped
getting undone by that one inning. I was keeping us in game and
giving us a chance to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's work ethic was cited by manager Terry Collins as a
major reason for the turnaround. In his last four starts, Belcher
has gone seven innings three times with an ERA of 2.90.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work you do between starts can be so critical to what
happens once you take the mound,'' Collins said. ``He had some
adjustments to make in his mechanics and he made them. He knew what
he had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher wasn't flawless Monday. He walked four and twice loaded
the bases but got out of those jams with just one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy does what he has been doing for seven innings, two
runs will win you some games in this league,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Belcher and Steinbach:!off!Belcher and Twins catcher
Terry Steinbach were minor-league battery mates in the Oakland
organization from 1984-86. Steinbach went 2 for 3 against Belcher
and 3 for 4 overall. He singled and scored the eventual wining run
in the eighth against Shigetoshi Hasegawa (1-2) before leaving the
game after an eighth-inning collision with Todd Greene at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an old friend and maybe I go soft on him,'' Belcher
joked.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbach's condition was not funny. He was taken to the
hospital for X-Rays and was diagnosed with a sprained right
shoulder. Because it is his throwing shoulder, Steinbach is
expected to be placed on the 15-day disabled list today.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Quick hits:!off!Tim Salmon, sidelined since May 3 with a
sprained left wrist, will have his cast removed Wednesday....
Minnesota's Cleatus Davidson, who made his major-league debut
Sunday as a pinch runner in Texas, started at shortstop Monday and
stole a base.... The game was played with three umpires after crew
chief Drew Coble returned home for personal reasons. &UR; !dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
