<SLUG> BC-IRON-BUTTERFLY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN BELONGED TO BASSIST OF IRON BUTTERFLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in 1st graf refers to Tuesday.) 
BY DAVID GREENBERG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ The Los Angeles County coroner might determine
as early as today if the skeletal remains found in a heavily wooded
Malibu ravine over the weekend are those of Iron Butterfly bassist
Philip ``Taylor'' Kramer, who disappeared four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also looking into the cause of death,
including the possibility of suicide.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Kramer disappeared, he reportedly called a 911
operator from his cellular phone and threatened to kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Bushy, the acid rock band's drummer and one of its
founders, said he did not believe Kramer killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was a suicide,'' he said. ``That's just not
like Taylor. I've never known him to run away from something. He
just tackles it head on. He had a zest for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart fell when I found out (Saturday) night,'' Bushy said.
``It freaked me out. But it's some sort of closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's sister Kathy refused to dismiss the possibility of foul
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's lots of possibilities, and that's one of them,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers found the remains in and around an aqua 1993 Ford
Aerostar van, which authorities later determined belonged to
Kramer. The 42-year-old musician disappeared Feb. 12, 1995, while
driving to Thousand Oaks from Los Angeles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things that are consistent,'' Los Angeles
County sheriff's Deputy Bruce Thomas said, when asked if he thought
the remains were that of Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   The human skull and bones were found 300 feet below Decker
Canyon Road in west Malibu on Saturday night by hikers
photographing abandoned vehicles, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Kramer said she hopes the remains do not belong to her
missing brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still hoping that it might not be my brother, but we
feel with the van and everything it may be,'' she said. ``We're
just waiting for confirmation right now, and even though we've been
wanting to know what happened, it's still a major shock.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the driver died when the
car went off the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Thomas Schwabe, a member of the coroner's investigations
unit, said Kramer's family is searching for dental records and
possibly X-rays that might contain identifying characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must try and look at as many things as possible,'' he
said, adding that his office's caseload was too heavy to begin the
autopsy Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1952, Kramer joined Iron Butterfly when it re-formed
from 1975 to 1977, Bushy said.
</P>
<P>
   In its first incarnation, with another bassist, the band
skyrocketed to fame in 1969 with its album ``In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida,''
which sold 4million copies.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Kramer started his own computer company, which
he pulled out from bankruptcy shortly before he vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Bushy said Kramer had a desire to stay healthy, doing 1,000
sit-ups a day without fail and up to 1 and one-half hours a day on
a Stairmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities received the call about the body about 7 p.m.
Saturday _ too late to begin the investigation, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, investigators went to the site, which is
being treated as a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the remains were removed that day and the rest on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily wooded ravine is commonly used as a dumping ground
for stolen and junk cars, Thomas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
