</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-MEMORIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1946 KILLING OF 4 BLACKS IS MOURNED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 3rd graf for rewriting to eliminate date and subs 4th graf to
correct date of killings)  (EDS: Note use of racial epithet in the quote in the 16th graf.)  
(lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTWICK, Ga. _ In 1945, returning from the Pacific after four
and half years in the Army, George Dorsey got off the bus in
Monroe, east of Atlanta, and walked down a dirt road to his home.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as other veterans of World War II were honored, Memorial
Day services were held here to remember George Dorsey, not just for
what he did overseas, but because of what happened to him when he
returned.
</P>
<P>
   After living quietly and working at a farm in nearby Walton
County for 10 months, Dorsey, his wife and two others, all black,
were shot to death by a group of about 15 whites, in one of
Georgia's most infamous, and still unsolved, incidents of racial
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   On July 25, 1946, Dorsey and his companions were dragged out of
a car and shot more than 60 times because, people said at the time,
one of them, a farm worker named Roger Malcolm, had stabbed the son
of his white boss. Many people said the boss' son had been having
an affair with Dorothy Dorsey, Malcolm's common-law wife and
Dorsey's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, many whites were outraged by the stabbing.
Eleven days later, less than an hour after Roger Malcolm had been
released on bail from the county jail, George Dorsey, 28, his wife,
Mae, 23, Roger Malcolm, 24, and Dorothy Dorsey, 20, lay lifeless on
the Georgia clay.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, dozens of people commemorated the deaths. In a plain
country church in neighboring Morgan County, about 60 people
listened to an account of the slayings and how George Dorsey, who
risked his life for his country, lost his life when he came home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every generation has the duty and responsibility to take up
the cross and advance the cause of human rights, human dignity and
good human relations,'' Christopher Culbreath, a local city
councilman, said from the pulpit Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``On July 24, 1946, George W. Dorsey answered the call for his
generation,'' Culbreath declared.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting six rows back, Jessie Robinson said she could not help
noticing how different the service was from the one given when
George Dorsey was buried. Mrs. Robinson, 86, was there that day,
when no one dared to mention the cause of George Dorsey's death. It
was too dangerous a subject, she said, so they said a prayer, put
him in the ground and walked away silently.
</P>
<P>
   After the speeches were given Monday, the crowd followed a
bagpipe player to the Mount Perry Missionary Baptist Church
cemetery, where the Dorsey and his wife are buried. An American
flag was folded by two sergeants from McPherson Army Base in
Georgia and handed to George Dorsey's nephew, Columbus Dorsey Jr.
Surrounded by graves marked by small, wooden crosses, Columbus
Dorsey shut his eyes as taps was played. His mother and brother,
sitting beside him, stared straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1946, the killings made national headlines and led to a
six-month FBI investigation. In the end, a federal grand jury of 21
whites and two blacks listened to 100 witnesses and came up with no
indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The case then lay dormant for almost half a century. The site of
the killings, a single-lane bridge over Moore's Ford, a section of
the muddy Apalachee River, was eventually torn down, and life went
on for the residents of this small northeast Georgia county, which
is still mostly farmland and forest.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1991, the case was reopened when a witness, Clinton
Adams, came forward. Adams was 10 when he and a friend saw the four
people being shot again and again in a barrage of bullets that, in
Adams' words, left smoke and bubbles coming out of their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, then a barefoot white boy in overalls, watched in horror
from the edge of a nearby grove of pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   He knew George Dorsey as the neighbor who came over to help chop
wood and who had run two miles to telephone an ambulance when
Adams' father died.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was over there in the war, he was a soldier
fighting,'' said Adams, 63, speaking from his home in Bonifay, Fla.
``But when he came back, he was just a nigger. Him being a veteran
didn't enter anybody's mind. I know I'm not supposed to talk like
that, but that's how it was then.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though he wanted to help, Adams said he thought that
talking would have cost him and his family their lives. Forty-five
years later, after a lifetime of moving from one town to the other
in fear of the Ku Klux Klan, which he believed was behind the
killings, he told the FBI his story. The case was reopened, but no
arrests have been made.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After the killings came back to public attention, a memorial
committee _ made up of blacks and whites and including civil rights
advocates and the athletic director at the University of Georgia _
was formed.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1998 the group, the Moore's Ford Memorial
Committee, has laid granite headstones at the victims' previously
unmarked graves and led a march over the new bridge at the site of
the killings. Monday's service singled out George Dorsey as a
veteran of war.
</P>
<P>
   Holding his uncle's flag tightly, Columbus Dorsey Jr. said he
doubted any arrests would ever be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be a book wrote about it, but justice? No, justice
will never be done,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7926 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELMONT-TOXIC-2Takes-     06-01 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELMONT-TOXIC-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTES SHOW COVER-UP AT NATION'S COSTLIEST SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lax practices by contractors and Los Angeles
school district officials allowed oil-contaminated soil to be used
in site preparation for construction of the costliest school in
U.S. history, a Daily News investigation has found.
</P>
<P>
   Construction notes and financial documents obtained by the Daily
News show contractors building the $170 million Belmont Learning
Center downtown mixed tons of contaminated and clean soil at the
construction site, skewing tests for toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   The financial documents, &UR;  &LR; along with memos written by the Los
Angeles Unified School District's on-site environmental assessor,
provide evidence that officials minimized testing of contaminated
soil to save money and knew that soil contaminated with crude oil
was left at the site and was used in grading the hilly property.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental scientists from the state Department of Toxic
Substances Control and the newly-strengthened school district's
School Safety Team said the documents, written between December
1997 and March 1999, were never turned over to them despite
repeated requests for all information pertaining to soil
contamination at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing the documents obtained by the Daily News, the
safety team called for an immediate and thorough investigation by
the district's director of internal audits and special
investigations, Don Mullinax.
</P>
<P>
   State toxic control officials vowed to immediately open an
investigation into excavation methods used at the site before state
inspectors ordered construction halted in February amid mounting
environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know anything about this,'' said Hamid Saebfar,
chief of southern California clean-up operations for the Department
of Toxic Substances Control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon the field notes we got from (the Daily News), they
diluted waste. That would be a violation of several hazardous
substance laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Groveman, the environmental lawyer heading up the district
team of experts investigating toxic problems at Belmont, said &UR;  &LR; the
documents raise ``serious questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get to the bottom of why these documents are only
now beginning to appear and determine who covered them up and what
reasons they may have had,'' he said. ``We are requesting the
investigation focus on whether any district policies, and state or
local laws were violated.''
</P>
<P>
   Erik Nasarenko, a spokesman for the district, said the school
district will provide all documents relating to soil contamination
to Mullinax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concur with the recommendations of the School Safety
Team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kajima Urban Development, the lead company of Belmont's
construction team, referred questions to Fleishmann-Hilliard, the
public relations firm that represents it. &UR;  &LR; Spokesman Eric Rose at
first promised a quick response but after reviewing the documents
declined comment on behalf of Kajima.
</P>
<P>
   The excavation contractor, Calex Engineering, did not return
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   School board President Victoria Castro, the biggest advocate of
the Belmont complex, was out of town and could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Scott Wildman, chairman of a joint legislative audit
committee investigating Belmont, said he believes the documents
show a deliberate attempt to hide environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soil mixing results were done in an attempt to provide
misleading test results and circumvent every environmental
regulation that exists,'' Wildman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These very questionable decisions ... have definitely put the
safety of children in question.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout 60 pages of hand-written, construction field notes,
Steve Croasdale, an environmental consultant for Law/Crandall,
which was hired by the district to monitor site excavation, warned
that Calex's earth-moving equipment was jeopardizing the validity
of soil samples.
</P>
<P>
   Croasdale made his most provocative observation Oct. 13, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calex is using a Scraper 637 (a type of construction
machinery) to move impacted soil,'' Croasdale wrote. ``The use of a
637 will mix a lot of clean soil with impacted soil, which will
make the sample levels lower than they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Croasdale notes that he attempted to talk to the Calex foreman
overseeing the work, but the supervisor would not stop to talk to
him. Later in the day, Croasdale wrote, the foreman refused to use
another type of equipment, explaining ``he has to use'' the
scraper.
</P>
<P>
   After the foreman's explanation, Croasdale scrawled: ``Their
(sic) will be a lot of clean soil mixed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Law Crandall stood by the content of their
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it as we see it ... We're there for observation
purposes,'' said Ray Hadden, branch manager for the environmental
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The district has all our reports.''
</P>
<P>
   The excavating techniques Croasdale observed that autumn day
were not unique, according to billing requests submitted to the
district March 10, 1999, by an intermediary for Kajima.
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont complex is designed to sit atop a concrete podium,
erected to transform the sloping construction site to a level
surface. Along with the podium, several portions of the site are
being cut and terraced for the school, athletic facilities, retail
stores and a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, excavation workers used the scrapers noted by
Croasdale to complete 84 hours of earth-moving between June 29 and
July 21, 1998, according to the billing request.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment specifications cited on the request show as much as
36,000 cubic yards of potentially contaminated soil was excavated
during the 22-day period using the machinery.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   That's enough soil to cover 20 football fields with a one-foot
layer of dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The soil excavated during the project was moved from a
potentially contaminated site west of the parking structure and
stockpiled temporarily on the location of the school football
field, the billing request states.
</P>
<P>
   Workers tested the soil _ after it had been moved and mixed with
clean soil by the machines _ and discovered a portion was
``suitable for reuse,'' while some that was ``environmentally
unacceptable'' needed to be hauled off the site, the billing
request explains.
</P>
<P>
   The soil ``suitable for reuse'' was dumped as compacted fill at
two sites, including the planned location for the baseball field,
according to the request for payment.
</P>
<P>
   Similar work was completed with the suspect scrapers between
Aug. 6 and Aug. 21, 1998. According to the billing documents,
workers used the equipment to move stockpiled contaminated material
at the football field to the baseball field for additional fill.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Croasdale's notes say procedures by Calex
continued to contaminate clean soil.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 29, 1999, field note, Croasdale wrote he had been
trying to keep clean and contaminated soil separated but the
earth-moving equipment used by the excavator made it difficult to
ensure cross contamination wasn't occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calex has been making new roads on (the) site so some of the
crude oil impacted soil is being spread all around the site.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing copies of the field notes last week, Sen. Tom
Hayden, D-Los Angeles, a longtime critic of Belmont, said the
inspector should be commended for ``putting down what he saw and
knew was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The poor public is led to believe that inspection and
enforcement mean something,'' Hayden said. ``But if all it means is
scribbling down notes on nefarious activities that nobody reads and
filing them in a giant box, the public should be angry. This is a
sad story.''
</P>
<P>
   One year before Croasdale's last mention of potential cross
contamination, Richard Lui, the school district's environmental
health assessor for Belmont, came up with a different solution for
the soil contaminated with crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``This memorandum is to inform you that no additional excavation
of crude oil contaminated soil is required in the southern bleacher
area,'' Lui wrote Jan. 13, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since crude oil is not regulated as a hazardous substance
under (federal law), no additional removal of soil impacted with
crude oil is necessary in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, Lui told the California Regional Water Quality
Control Board that cost considerations played a role in the number
of tests the district conducted on soil at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to test results for a 1,600-cubic-yard soil stockpile,
Lui wrote: ``The results of the analysis indicate that the
contaminant resembles that of crude oil, which is consistent with
the site being located near the Los Angeles City Oil Field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to cost considerations, eight out of the 16 samples were
analyzed. The Los Angeles Unified School District ... feels that
the analysis of the eight samples adequately characterizes the
stockpile, thereby eliminating the need for additional analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Lui added that ``in the interest of saving tax dollars and since
it has been confirmed that the contaminant is crude oil,'' the
district is limiting future tests to only determine whether
petroleum hydrocarbons are present in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the safety team, who asked not to be identified,
said Lui's explanation ``flagrantly neglects the safety of children
to save a small amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Completing the entire scope of soil tests would have cost the
district only a ``few hundred, maybe a few thousand dollars,'' an
independent environmental scientist confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden called Lui's correspondence ``definite proof'' that the
district knew petroleum-contaminated soil was on the site from an
early stage and still failed to take the proper steps to remediate
it.
</P>
<P>
   As the district prepares to pay $1.5 million for a new battery
of environmental tests and millions more to remediate the site,
LAUSD officials could not immediately identify who told Lui that
partial sampling was adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Lui, who continues to help monitor on-site environmental
concerns for the district, did not return several phone calls for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of the district is shot,'' said board member
David Tokofsky, a vocal critic of the repeatedly bungling by
district bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still nobody is taking any blame and no employee has been
dismissed,'' Tokofsky said. ``And, of course, (Castro), the board
member who represents the district that Belmont is in, is missing
in action now and can't be reached.''
</P>
<P>
   When the state halted construction of the half-finished complex
in February, Superintendent Ruben Zacarias instituted a series of
environmental policies, including a requirement to remove or
remediate all petroleum-contaminated soil found on school sites.
</P>
<P>
   That policy was recently put at risk when assistant general
counsel Brad Hogin made several unauthorized amendments to a state
Senate bill governing the selection of school sites.
</P>
<P>
   Hogin inserted a loophole into the bill that would have allowed
districts to avoid reporting petroleum contamination. &UR;  &LR; He cited the
same federal law Lui referenced in his memo to avoid excavating
soil soaked with crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Lui's letter is substantive proof that the District has
been attempting to use a legal loophole to cover up petroleum
contamination at Belmont since at least early 1998,'' Hayden wrote
in a letter to Zacarias on Friday. ``For this cover-up which is a
hazard to children's health, Mr. Lui should be held accountable. He
should be fired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
