<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje, Macedonia) _ If there is an
overwhelming sense that emerges from a walk through the squalid
refugee camps of Macedonia these days, it is despair. Whether it is
the newly arrived refugees who until last week bravely eluded
Yugoslav efforts to expel them from Kosovo, only finally to flee in
the face of dwindling food and unending fear, or the refugees who
have already endured weeks in the overcrowded camps here, Kosovars
are giving up on their dream of returning home soon and are
increasingly desperate to go abroad. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ Ten years after army troops and
tanks were used to smash pro-democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen
Square, more than one hundred relatives of the dead have petitioned
the government to open a criminal investigation of the officials
responsible. By Eric Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECT (Johannesburg) _ Reporter's Notebook on the South
African election Wednesday. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HAMPTONS-FOREVER (New York) _ The questions are always the same:
Have the Hamptons become declasse? Have they been ruined by IPO
arrivistes who eat Godiva somoas and chug $40 shots of Porfidio
tequila with their Southwestern Sushi? Have they been spoiled by
hordes of ``day trippers'' who come hoping per chance to rub elbows
with Steven Spielberg at the Blue Parrot, or Martha Stewart at Nick
&AMP; Toni's? Propelled by a bull market and fueled by celebrity
sightings, change is rippling as never before across the Hamptons,
and it is challenging traditional defenses that have long served to
protect the Hamptons Way of Life, many locals say. By David
Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-MUSEUM (Chicago) _ Finding themselves face-to-face _ or
rather face-to-knee _ with a colossal, roseate statue of
Tutankhamen, museumgoers returned this weekend to the Oriental
Institute for the first time since 1996, when its galleries were
closed to the public for remodeling. By David W. Dunlop.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-JEWS (Undated) _ More than a century ago, leaders of
Reform Judaism declared such practices as wearing skullcaps and
prayer shawls and using Hebrew in services to be the dated relics
of the past, and emphasized instead a focus on social ethics and a
highly cerebral approach to the faith. But in a symbolically
resonant gesture, and with an eye on the approach of a new century,
Reform's rabbinic arm, the Central Conference of American Rabbis,
last week adopted a document that encourages the movement's members
to explore traditional rituals. By Gustav Niebuhr and Nadine
Brozan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-LAWS (Undated) _ A patchwork of state libel laws that was
aimed at protecting makers of agricultural products from food
scares is putting a chill on what kinds of projects broadcasters
and publishers are willing to back. By Melody Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   LAWYERS-ASSESS (New York) _ Two lawyers who have nimbly defended
prosperous Wall Street professionals stood before judges with
lawyers of their own in recent weeks. The cases, though different
in magnitude, highlight the power that defense lawyers wield in
securities-law prosecutions _ and the limits of the Securities and
Exchange Commission's patience with those who may use that power
improperly. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   RAIL-TRAFFIC (Undated) _ On Tuesday, Norfolk Southern and CSX,
which already dominate commercial rail traffic in much of the East,
take over chunks of Conrail. The switch-over will herald the most
sweeping change in a generation in the Northeast's commercial
railroads _ especially in the New York area. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ECON (Tokyo) _ South Korea's efforts to enlist foreign
capital and expertise in an overhaul of its rickety financial
system have gotten bogged down in, of all things, the country's
stunning recovery from economic crisis. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   RUM-DISPUTE (Undated) _ Cuba cannot sell rum in the United
States, but a U.S. court ruling over the country's rights to the
Havana Club trademark has President Fidel Castro of Cuba so mad he
is threatening to market his own brand of Coca-Cola. He's not the
only one fuming. So are executives at Pernod Ricard SA, the French
beverage giant that paid an estimated $50 million to team up with
Cuba to produce and export Havana Club rum. By Ana Radelat.
</P>
<P>
   YEN-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ One of the main culprits in the
global financial crisis of 1997 is sneaking back into the financial
markets. The play, known as a ``carry trade,'' has not caught fire
yet the way it did two years ago. But if this bet does go
mainstream again, it could weaken the yen and buoy the U.S. bond
market, helping keep interest rates lower than they would otherwise
be. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   ANNIVERSARY-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Fifty years ago, an agency
named Doyle Dane Bernbach opened its doors in midtown Manhattan
with 13 employees. From those modest beginnings emerged a shop that
revolutionized advertising with distinctive creative and
operational approaches that still resonate a half century later. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e`` category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN-CENTER-FUNDRAISING (New York) _ As it celebrates its
40th birthday, Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts, the world's
most successful arts complex, is showing its age. Officials are
weighing a vast fund-raising campaign to address the wear and tear
of decades and other gnawing problems, from crippling shortages of
backstage space to troubled acoustics to underground leaks. The
campaign, whose size is still undetermined, could run into the
hundreds of millions of dollars, making it the largest arts
initiative in the city in years. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HARE-INTERVIEW (Undated) _ Interview with playwright David Hare.
By Serge Schmemann.
