<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHR     06-01 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FRONTRIERS AWAIT BUSH IN CALIFORNIA VISIT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ GOP presidential hopeful George W. Bush, even
as he leads the polls in California, has been the political
equivalent of a Stealth bomber here: powerful, well-funded and yet
largely invisible in recent months.
<P>
   But when the Texas legislative session ends this month, the
governor will have to begin to reveal himself as he heads out on
the campaign trail, on what has become the most anticipated tour of
the young political season.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's most populous state, one crucial to the fortunes of
all presidential hopefuls, will see him up close at the end of this
month with a three-day tour of San Diego, Orange County, Los
Angeles, Sacramento, Silicon Valley, San Francisco and Fresno. A
month in advance, tickets are hot-sellers, organizers report.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor will have plenty of company in California
this month. Democratic hopeful Bill Bradley plans an exhaustive
10-day visit, Vice President Al Gore will make his 55th stop in the
state, and GOP hopefuls Elizabeth Dole, Steve Forbes, Lamar
Alexander, Dan Quayle, Pat Buchanan and John McCain also fly in for
fund raising and campaigning. Even with nine months to go before
the crucial March 7 primary, Bush's early successes in California
have created strategic problems for his Republican and Democratic
challengers alike in California. The pack of presidential hopefuls
has been measured against his poll numbers, prodigious fund raising
and long list of endorsements. They will have to battle hard just
for a share of the spotlight he'll grab with his first official
foray into the state.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also have to counter the Bush California strategy, one
which argues that the Texas governor best understands the state and
its issues _ from education to technology _ while also connecting
best with its people, diverse as they are.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is ``suited to California,'' born in Midland, Texas, with
an outlook that's ``Western in nature,'' said his chief campaign
strategist, Karl Rove, in a recent interview with The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an entrepreneur and a risk-taker, and that's the
California spirit,'' said Rove. ``He's demonstrated enormous appeal
to Hispanics, to women, to Democrats and independents.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the next month, he will bring a message aimed directly at
California's issues _ including accountability in schools,
reforming juvenile justice, reducing the welfare rolls, and
maximizing the benefits of the new economy and high-tech industry
to all Americans, Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a particular challenge in California, where Republicans
have suffered dramatic losses among women, Hispanic and independent
voters who consider their candidates as too extreme and intolerant.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush will speak about a ``compassionate, conservative, and
hopeful'' GOP agenda, said Rove. ``The question (he will explore)
is how do we continue the current prosperity _ and make sure it is
shared by all.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the money: Bush has already raised $7.6 million
without even hitting the campaign trail, and campaign insiders say
by the end of June, the Bush camp intends to hit a $15.2 million
mark _ a generous chunk of it from California.
</P>
<P>
   Already, competitors on both sides are preparing to counter the
Texas wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to have an easy time of it,'' said Democratic
campaign strategist Garry South, who engineered the 1998 landslide
victory of Gov. Gray Davis. South insists the political landscapes
are so different that ``a sensible moderate in Texas can look
pretty damn right wing in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are also taking aim at Bush. ``We've already been to
California half a dozen times ... and the California Republican
Party adopted John McCain as their surrogate senator,'' said Howard
Opinsky, spokesman for the Arizona senator. ``We welcome Mr. Bush
to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   And  &LR; Rival campaign strategists suggest that when Californians
know more, they may not be so enamored.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's his position on offshore oil drilling? Where is he on
Proposition 187 and 209 and bilingual education?'' said one key
strategist. ``Bush has not met with a single reporter in
California, or been grilled on California issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In an illustration of just how important California is for his
candidate, Rove, the press-shy tactician for Bush, recently agreed
to talk about the road ahead for his candidate in California. here.
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  He noted that California's significance to the 2000
presidential contest has as much to do with timing and numbers:
Along with Florida and Texas, it accounts for more than 40 percent
of the electoral votes needed to win the presidency. And an early
March 7 California primary date means ``we'll be here a lot,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But challenges also abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations are huge _ and there is no way they could be
sustained,'' Rove said. ``Republicans are so eager, after eight
years in the wilderness, that they're getting ahead of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to recognize it's going to happen. ... There are going
to be bumps,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Californians deeply involved in the Texas governor's effort also
say that he faces frontiers here that are unique to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He'll face his first presidential open primary here ``without a
Republican governor in the statehouse ... (in a state where)
changing demographics and the cybereconomy have changed the way you
can organize a state,'' said GOP strategist Leslie Goodman, a
friend of Bush's and editor of politicalaccess.com, a leading
political Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have their own agenda for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choice, guns and anti-hate legislation,'' said Democratic
strategist Bob Mulholland. ``On those, (Bush) is too extreme for
California.''
</P>
<P>
   And a comparison between Bush and Gore, which is inevitable,
will also contrast ``some striking similarities to the governor's
race'' between Davis and his vanquished GOP challenger Dan Lungren,
said South.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bush) never served in the military in Vietnam; Gore did. ...
(Bush) has been in office less than six years, and never had any
foreign policy experience. He's never had to cast votes on war and
peace,'' South said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a first-time national candidate ... and (Republicans) are
slobbering all over him without having heard him give a speech,''
said South, who has had recent talks on strategy with the Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He predicts, too, that California Latinos will not be easily
wooed by Bush. ``(Republicans) can wear all the sombreros they
want, but Latino voters are not shallow and not led astray by
little acts of symbolism that don't mean anything to their daily
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But the state legislator who helped kick off the Bush tidal
wave, Assemblyman Bruce Thompson of Fallbrook, insists that Bush's
roll-out at the end of the month may surprise all doubters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the kind of leader we haven't seen since Ronald Reagan,''
said Thompson, who along with Assemblyman Bill Leonard began the
state endorsement campaigns which have swept Bush across the
nation. ``He has the ability to convey a message that makes sense
... and people will not be disappointed whatsoever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
