<HEADER>
A7975 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     06-01 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALIOTO MASSING FUNDS FOR WAR CHEST
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ POOR WILLIE BROWN. Remember when he thought he
would run unopposed? Now his limo probably has a bumper sticker,
``Honk if you're running for mayor, damn you!''
<P>
   Clint Reilly is in. Tom Ammiano? Gavin Newsom? Tony Rivera? All
potential honkers.
</P>
<P>
   And now, maybe ... Angela Alioto?
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, Alioto is four years away, but you never know.
She says she'll run when she has $2 million of her own saved, so
she doesn't have to sell her mayoral soul to special interests.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the dough is starting to flow. Attorney Alioto's specialty
is defending the little guy, and she scored her first major win
last week, beating the stuffing out of Janet Reno's massive legal
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto's client is a Sicilian immigrant from a town just down
the road from Angela's grandfather's hometown. The client is an INS
agent in Illinois who was denied promotion for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think the INS would know better than to discriminate
against an immigrant. NOW they know.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto says the verdict is a tribute to her late dad, ex-mayor
Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Angela's fee is about $250,000, and she told buddy Jerry Brown,
``I'm getting close.''
</P>
<P>
   SON OF SWEEP: The Central Station cops continue to invent their
own rules in North Beach. I'm told they closed up the sidewalk cafe
action at midnight last Saturday for the second weekend, although
the law says only that booze must be off the outdoor tables by
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   And now a report that the restaurants are being told by someone
that their waiters must earn $11.50 per hour because they are city
employees, because they work on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   So does this mean hookers must also make $11.50 per hour?
</P>
<P>
   Someone Up There in city power circles doesn't like the sidewalk
cafe action. No telling whom. Mayor Brown's office didn't return my
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   KETCHUP IS FREE: I recently made fun of the high price of
room-service hamburgers at the Fairmont and the Mark Hopkins
hotels. My bad.
</P>
<P>
   From the Trump International Hotel and Tower in New York comes a
note from guest Ed Moose, whose room-service burger was $25, plus
21% delivery and service charge, for a total of $30.25. No extra
charge for the over-cooking, Ed says.
</P>
<P>
   So San Francisco is Bargainville. The Mark Hopkins room-service
burger is $16, plus $2 delivery, 15% gratuity, 8.5% tax, dealer
prep and FOB. The Fairmont's burger is $11, plus $2 delivery, 17%
gratuity, 8.5% tax, yadda yadda.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I never travel without a CPA.
</P>
<P>
   BUM TRIP: A job applicant for the Examiner art department, being
taken to lunch, tripped over a traffic cone near SFMOMA, fell off
the curb, broke nose, had to be pulled from the path of a charging
MUNI bus.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about a struggling artist!
</P>
<P>
   The good news: For once, nobody complained about a MUNI bus
being late.
</P>
<P>
   MORE N.Y. NEWZ: Moose, still on loose, reports that New Year's
Eve dinner and dancing at Manhattan's Rainbow Room will set you
(with date) back $6,000. And a Four Seasons room is $75,000, but it
includes your own piano player (BYO piano?).
</P>
<P>
   At our very own fair-priced Fairmont, the most exclusive suite
has been reserved for Millennium Eve for a mere $43,000.
</P>
<P>
   TU GO, GIRL! At Miramonte High in Orinda, they've got what must
be the most popular Latin Club this side of Latin America. Latin
teacher Mrs. Bisio (been there so long she has Roman-numeral
license plates) has her legions attending bowling parties and toga
dinners.
</P>
<P>
   So revered is Ann Bisio that her students proudly wear ``Air
Bisio'' T-shirts, with a cartoon of their leader in Michael
Jordan-like silhouette, leaping over the Roman Empire.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is retired; Bisio soars on.
</P>
<P>
   YOU GO, GIRL! Happy column 25th anniversary to Pat Steger,
without whom San Francisco high society doesn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   But all these years of Pat making people famous and nobody
writes about Pat. Did you know, for instance, that Steger is an
aviation pioneer?
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Alitalia flight from Lisbon to Milan, Pat liked the
pasta so much that she asked for more. There it is: First airline
passenger in history to request seconds on anything but salted
peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   YOU GONE, GIRL? Will the Giants move into their new ballpark
next year with a new PA voice? It's rumored they will consider
replacing seven-year mike vet Sherry Davis, the first woman PA
voice in big-time sports.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer Sherry's solid, straight-ahead style to the annoying
screamers most teams now employ. And I cheered when she broke the
sound barrier in the old-boys club.
</P>
<P>
   But if a team has guts enough to buck tradition by hiring a
woman to a high-profile job, they should be allowed to make a
change without being accused of discrimination or opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   If the Giants do make a change, here's how they can prove
they're not caving in to the wimpy bleating of a small but vocal
group of overserved chauvinists: Hire another woman.
</P>
<P>
   TIP O' THE DAY: Looking for a career in a fast-growth industry?
Check into BART escalator repair.
</P>
<P>
   A scary situation Monday, as my BART escalator broke and I was
trapped for half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Lame joke, sure, but my joke writers are all stuck in a BART
elevator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
