<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8058 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINDMILLS-$ADV06-COX     06-01 1694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDMILLS-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEAR OF Y2K A BOON FOR MAKERS OF WINDMILLS
 &HT;    1100&AMP;adds. Moving in (a) national and (l) lifestyle categories
for release Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINFIELD, Ala. _ Dusk was still several hours away as Ken
O'Brock tightened the final screws on the windmill he had
constructed on a sweltering spring day in a rolling pasture about
75 miles northwest of Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   If he hustled, O'Brock figured, he could load his equipment onto
the truck with the Ohio WINDMIL license plates and get a good start
on the long drive to his next job in central Florida. As the final
months of the millennium tick down, time is precious for a veteran
windmiller with more business than he can handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing twice as many jobs this year,'' said the owner and
installer of O'Brock Windmills of North Benton, Ohio. ``In one
week, I put up four windmills. One near Athens, Ga. One outside of
Bainbridge, Ga. And two in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Why this surprising surge in a centuries-old technology? Credit
a more modern technological glitch _ the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   Folks are afraid that many computers may shut down at midnight
on Dec. 31, when programs that use only two digits to record dates
won't be able to distinguish the new year 2000 from 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Livestock and crops _ not to mention people _ will get thirsty
awfully fast if the Y2K bug stings computers at power plants, and
electric pumps stop sending water to homes and farms.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, my friend, is ...
</P>
<P>
   Demand for windmills has been ``incredible,'' said Craig Donges,
owner of Ohio Windmills, near Youngstown. ``There's a big concern
for drinking water come the new millennium. My sales have probably
doubled this year. There's been a lot of interest in the Southeast.
Florida, Georgia, the Carolinas have probably been my biggest new
customer base.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuben Neely, a retired elementary school principal, hired
O'Brock to erect a 47-foot windmill on his farm outside Bainbridge,
in southwestern Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not strictly because of Y2K,'' Neely said. ``But I
believe in being prepared. If anything happens, I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Windmills were already in use the last time a new millennium
blew in. ``The earliest reference to a windmill occurs in the works
of Arab writers in the 9th Century AD,'' according to the
Encyclopedia Britannica. Windmills spread through Europe between
the 12th and early 19th Centuries until wind power began to be
replaced, initially by steam power and later the
internal-combustion engine and electric power.
</P>
<P>
   Windmills were at least as important as the six-shooter in
settling the American West. Indeed, they were widely used until the
1930s, when New Deal programs began wiring rural America for
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1854, Daniel Halladay introduced a wind-powered pump in the
United States that is basically the design still used today. A
number of blades are set radially on a wheel, like spokes. The wide
blades are curved and angled to catch even a slight breeze. A tail
vane keeps the wheel facing the wind. The turning wheel provides
power to move a long shaft up and down to pump water from a well.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a five- to seven-mile-per-hour wind'' to turn the
blades enough to power the pump, said O'Brock.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, windmills _ which cost $5,000 and up _ aren't the
only low-tech solutions to a possible millennium meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a tremendous upsurge in demand for hand pumps,''
said David Suey, president of Dempster Industries of Beatrice, Neb.
``We got caught off guard. Didn't know what was happening at first.
Everyone ordering hand pumps. Then a customer mentioned Y2K and it
came to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The hand pumps are priced at about $500 apiece, and the company
usually sells hundreds a year, mostly to Third World customers.
This year, sales are already in the thousands, mostly to domestic
dealers ``in every single state,'' said Suey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come the end of December, we'd better not have more than a
nickel's worth of inventory,'' he said. ``Unless these guys
(predicting Y2K disaster) are the smart ones. Then everyone else
will be wanting a pump.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales are also booming for wood-burning stoves, kerosene
lanterns, food canners and juicers, water filters and all sorts of
other survivalist gear, said Glenda Lehman Ervin, communications
manager of Lehman's in Kidron, Ohio. From its sprawling Midwestern
store and through its globally distributed catalog, Lehman's has
been selling non-electric appliances since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of the founder, Ervin said Lehman's traditional
customers are the Amish, missionaries, homesteaders,
environmentalists and the ``chronically nostalgic'' who savor
old-fashioned items like hand-cranked ice cream churns. This year,
she said, the normal business has been ``overwhelmed'' by
``Y2Kers.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, Lehman's has taken pride in providing ``same-day
service _ shipping the same day we received an order,'' she said.
``We're now four to five weeks behind (on some items). Our pipeline
is choked. We're not set up for this volume of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the boom has been a mixed blessing for a company with a
motto of ``more than a store, it's a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want business based on fears of what may or may not
happen'' on New Year's Day, said Ervin. ``We're in this for the
long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   So is O'Brock, an amiable 59-year-old former farmer who has been
selling and erecting windmills since 1968. With his wife, Sharen,
often serving as his ground crew, O'Brock estimates he has set up
500 to 800 windmills, at least one in every state, including Alaska
and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a handful of independent windmillers like O'Brock
and Donges and Paul Crowley of Ropesville, Texas, who travel around
the country setting up windmills for individual farmers, ranchers
and homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The windmill community is divided into two segments, explained
Randall Swisher, director of the American Wind Energy Association,
a national trade group.
</P>
<P>
   One segment is the commercial energy industry that utilizes huge
``wind farms'' with hundreds of windmills and turbines to generate
electricity for businesses or even communities. The other segment
consists of folks who have a windmill in their backyard to pump
water or to power a small generator, or have several windmills
scattered across a ranch to pump water for cattle on isolated
ranges.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher estimated that there are 30,000 or so of these
individually owned windmills in operation. But the number is
growing rapidly as 1999 breezes toward 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in business since 1888 (and will) set sales records
this year,'' said James Dockel, sales manager for the Aeromotor
Windmill Corp. in San Angelo, Texas. The company manufactures
windmills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first three months were my best year ever,'' said Ellen
Sattler of American Windmills in Diamond Springs, Calif. ``We sell
to people who put it up as a kit. A giant Erector set, I call it.
With the help of a few buddies, a few beers and pizzas, it takes a
couple of days for somebody who is a little bit mechanical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are strictly water pumpers,'' she said. Her customers
are ``normally farmers, but not this year. Now it's Joe
Americana.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Or it's Cyndy Wright, who hired O'Brock to build a windmill in a
pasture on her spread outside Winfield in the hills northwestern
Alabama. An anesthetist at the local hospital and something of a
rural maverick, Wright raises longhorn steers and horses in a
region known more for corn and soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted a windmill. Now I've got one,'' she declared
as O'Brock climbed down from the 40-foot tower after spinning the
wheel, which measured eight feet across, and drawing water on a
windless afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K issue didn't figure in her decision to build the
windmill, she said, ``but it would be nice to be a little
self-sufficient in case something happened.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Pat Halloran, who has a new O'Brock
windmill on his Stone Oak Farm in Oglethorpe County, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted a windmill all my life,'' he said. Rotating atop a
53-foot tower, his windmill provides water to ``trickle irrigate''
a big garden of corn, tomatoes, herbs and other produce.
</P>
<P>
   There is often a good dose of romance and nostalgia mingled in
with the practicality of having a windmill, O'Brock believes. ``Y2K
has provided a good excuse for a lot of people who always wanted a
windmill.''
</P>
<P>
   He includes himself among these windmill lovers. ``I had an old
windmill on my farm and I thought it would be neat to fix it up,''
he said. That was in 1967. He rebuilt his own windmill and has been
building them for others ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times people want to put one up just to look at it,''
said Crowley, of Paul's Windmills in Ropesville, Texas. His shop is
not far from the windmill collection and museum in Lubbock, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   A retired school teacher, Crowley put one up for himself and
``the next thing I knew, I was selling them.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a windmill depends on how deep the well must be and
how tall the tower must be. O'Brock said the tower should be 15
feet taller than any trees or structures within 400 feet. However,
there are exceptions. In Cyndy Wright's pasture, the tower was no
taller than two nearby trees, but the prevailing winds came from
other directions.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brock said he has never fallen from a windmill tower, but came
close once. He had already unfastened his safety belt when a gust
of wind swung the wheel around and knocked him off the platform. A
hook on the unfastened safety belt caught on a tower brace and
saved him.
</P>
<P>
   Every windmill presents a new challenge, he said. And since many
are erected on isolated farms, he often stays with his customers,
making friends while finishing his task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never intend to retire,'' he hollers down from the top of
the tower. ``I like what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
