<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MUCH MONEY, AND SO MUCH CONTROVERSY 
 
CLAY ROBISON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ We all know the old cliche about money not
buying happiness. In the political world, however, we can almost
always depend on it to purchase controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The more dollars there are, the more elected officials and
interest groups have to fight about.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious, recent example of money buying misery is Texas'
huge settlement of its anti-tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what some people may think of him, former Attorney
General Dan Morales scored a huge victory for Texas taxpayers when
he and his team of five high-powered plaintiffs' lawyers overcame
some strong obstacles last year to win a $17.3 billion payout for
the state from cigarette companies.
</P>
<P>
   It was the crowning achievement of Morales' political career,
and he did it without any help from Gov. George W. Bush or the
Texas Legislature. But he was a hero for only a few days before
political controversy over huge lawyers' fees _ which eventually
were to total $3.3 billion _ began to dim his limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, the number of news articles about the legal fees _
egged on by civil justice reformers eager to cash in on another
opportunity to bash trial lawyers _ had surpassed coverage of the
settlement itself. It mattered little to Morales' critics that the
five outside lawyers were to be paid separately by tobacco
companies, not by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the controversy has steadily deepened. Now, Attorney
General John Cornyn, Morales' successor, has openly accused Morales
of fraudulently doctoring contracts in an unsuccessful effort to
help a sixth lawyer, mystery friend Marc Murr, score a $250 million
tobacco payday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Cornyn, federal investigators also are looking into
Morales' dealings with Murr, who has been accused by other lawyers
of contributing little, if anything, to the tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has heatedly denied Cornyn's allegations, leaving the
public to only guess whether there is any real fire or only
overheated politics behind all the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, a Republican, launched his first attack on Morales and
the lawyers' fees last year during Cornyn's election campaign,
which was heavily backed by civil justice reformers who have worked
hard to clamp limits on monetary judgments and lawyers' fees in
lawsuits against doctors, insurance companies and other businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn had recently resigned from the Texas Supreme Court, where
he had often sided with the majority in favor of the so-called
tort-reform restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, despite several political controversies while in
office, was one of Texas' most popular Democrats. And when he
decided not to seek a third term as attorney general, he didn't
rule out the possibility of a future race for governor.
</P>
<P>
   As the dispute over legal fees continued to smolder, the
Legislature was spending the positive part of Morales' legacy.
Lawmakers last week put the finishing touches on a new state budget
that spends or endows $1.8 billion in tobacco payments.
</P>
<P>
   That money represents the first payments _ plus interest _ that
cigarette makers agreed to pay Texas over 25 years. It is earmarked
for health care or health-related programs, largely as Morales
proposed. Some $180 million is appropriated for an important
health-insurance program for low-income children. Because of the
tobacco settlement, thousands of Texas children will get health
care their parents never could have afforded.
</P>
<P>
   Every lawmaker in Austin and the governor _ who also has
criticized the high lawyer fees _ are grateful for the tobacco
windfall. It helped them balance a new $98.1 billion budget while
keeping campaign promises to cut taxes and raise teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   But riches still enrich controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Two Texas Southern University faculty members in Houston are
suing because TSU was left off a list of tobacco-endowed research
and health-care programs at medical schools and health-care
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County, which includes most of Houston, was prepared to
sue until legislators decided not to meddle with its share of the
settlement dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And the American Cancer Society and the Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids are unhappy because the distribution of tobacco
funds seems to be more heavily weighted toward research into
fighting cancer and other smoking-related illnesses than toward
preventing children from smoking in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston, pointed out that Texas is
scheduled to continue receiving significant tobacco payments for
another two decades. More money may be spent on anti-smoking
programs in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the story,'' Coleman added.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it the end of debate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
