<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8108 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-01 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVELERS LODGE THEIR COMPLAINTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent column about hotel rooms struck a nerve with many
readers.
</P>
<P>
   After detailing some of my pet peeves _ peepholes placed too
high on doors, electrical outlets hard to access, tiny bathrooms _
I asked for your insight. And you weren't shy about expressing
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Among responses:
</P>
<P>
   ``As a woman traveling alone, safety is my first priority,''
writes Mary Lee Archer. ``I want an interior room so that in the
evening I don't have to exit my car in a parking lot and walk to
the door. I check for multiple locks and see that all windows are
locked. I also ask for a room near the desk (lobby) if such are
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, good lighting _ a matter of safety as well as
convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The room must also be nonsmoking, but it must have been so
from the beginning. Sometimes I have been given so-called
nonsmoking rooms in which someone had simply removed the ashtrays.
No smoke odor is acceptable; I am allergic to tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOISE POLLUTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier column, I listed one of my priorities as being
near ice and vending machines. But not too near.
</P>
<P>
   ``My worst horror story was at a Holiday Inn,'' Archer writes.
``Everything seemed reasonably all right except that I was directly
across from the ice dispenser. The city had a balloon show the next
day, and balloonists take off about dawn. Beginning at 2 a.m., a
line of balloonists formed filling ice chests! It was simply
dreadful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should add that I wrote Holiday Inn afterward to complain
and received credit (for the night of the balloonists' parade to
the ice machine).''
</P>
<P>
   Riecke Baumann's lodging priorities begin before reaching a
room. A hotel, writes Baumann, should be ``easy to find on the
freeway,'' should provide ``easy parking'' and its lobby should be
``easy to find and near the bathroom since I always need to visit
when I first get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple requirements
</P>
<P>
   Baumann stresses practical preferences:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A telephone next to the bed. Why do they think we want to
get up and go across the room to use or answer the phone?
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Light switches close to the bed, either on the wall or at
the base of the lights, not where I have to strain to reach up to
the top of a lamp.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fresh batteries in the (television) remote control.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fire alarms with fresh batteries. I once had one beep
forever, till I unplugged it, because the batteries were dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Twenty-four hour room service, though being next door to
Denny's, as La Quinta often does, is fine, maybe better.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Employees who can give simple directions. How hard is
that?''
</P>
<P>
   I share reader Lowell Heinz' frustration when he writes: ``All
the rooms I have been in (except one) during some 50 years have
only had one luggage holder. Most couples and some single people
have two suitcases. Where do you put the second one?''
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 7, I empathize, too, with Mrs. Allen Key who writes,
``One of my pet peeves is showers. I'm short, and they (shower
heads) are almost universally installed near the ceiling. Shower
adjustments are also exasperating; the temperature is difficult to
adjust, and the water pressure is so variable that sometimes you
feel as if your body is being pierced, and if you lower it to a
comfortable pressure it stops operating as a shower and runs in the
tub.''
</P>
<P>
   I dare say many of us have encountered reader Doug Acker's
dilemma at trying to sleep on ``a pillow that is narrower than your
head. If you have a king-size bed, why can't the hotel use
king-size pillows?''
</P>
<P>
   Acker also senses a ``total disregard for the business
traveler'' at many lodgings. ``The desk is usually too small (or
round) to work on a laptop, the chair is way too low, and the phone
is by the bed. It would be nice if there were a second phone line
into the room, one for laptop and the other for voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Reader Lorene Windham's main concern is for travelers with
disabilities. ``My husband is left-handed and paralyzed on his
right arm, and we need a room (in which) the bathroom must be
equipped with a grab bar on the left side of the commode,'' she
writes. ``Sound simple? No. At one hotel we were told that they
could not have accommodations for everybody and that most people
are right-handed anyway. Can you believe that? Also, most rooms for
travelers with disabilities only have a king-size bed. Why not two
queens or regular beds?''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Austin asks, ``Why don't they put decent lights in
hotel rooms so we can read in bed? A heat light in the bathroom is
nice, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there a ``perfect'' hotel room? Perhaps not, given our
different needs and peccadillos. But one of the most significant
reader correspondences comes from Alan T. Stutts, dean of the
University of Houston's Conrad N. Hilton College of Hotel and
Restaurant Management, where considerable research focuses on
traveler-friendly accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest gripe,'' Stutts writes, ``is finding that the staff
of a hotel are not empowered to solve my problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
