<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-CO     06-01 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: In seach of Rick's Cafe
 &HT;    For release June 2, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASABLANCA, Morocco _ So, OK, I knew there was no such place as
Rick's Cafe here, but the airport, where Rick shot Maj. Strasser
and he and the sleazy cop, Louie Renault, walked off together into
the mist, it's not there either. Well, it's 30 miles away and it's
new.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Wolfe was right. Even if you've only been there via film,
you can't go home again. The 1942 classic ``Casablanca'' is a
nostalgic, romantic fantasy that has no basis in fact. But we all
want to believe it is real. If you are one of those, today's
Casablanca could be disillusioning.
</P>
<P>
   We want to see it as an exotic place when, in fact, Casablanca _
the 1999 version _ is a teeming metropolitan city of upwards of 3
million. The popular fez and caftans of the Bogey flick are not
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see Casablanca 1942, you've got to go to
Marrakech, about 150 miles down the road. While Casablanca does
have its medina and souks, it is overpowered by skyscrapers, by
major business offices, by men with attache cases, by automatic
teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   My search for Rick's Casablanca took me to Marrakech, a
three-hour bus ride through declining countryside and into the
heart and soul of my visions of Arabian nights as well as World War
II intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Rick, if he were real and still alive, would be running a cafe
in Marrakech _ somewhere off the Jema l-Fna square, a throwback to
the Middle Ages. Strange characters frequent the square, where
charmers still rhapsodize lunging cobras with their flutes, where
aged hucksters recite allegories to entranced young Arabs who
eagerly toss coins onto the storyteller's frayed carpet in hope
that he will continue the story instead of going home to lunch as
he has falsely threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the souk that forms one side of the noisy, crowded, seedy
square, the merchants are at work. With Rick at my side, cigarette
dangling from his lip, Ahmed likely would not try to extract $15
from me for a T-shirt. He would see Rick and he would force the
shirt into my hands. But Rick wasn't there, never was. It was a
battle to get him down to $10 but the shirt probably wasn't worth
$8.
</P>
<P>
   The Casablanca of Rick and Ilsa was created thousands of miles
away, in Hollywood. The real Casablanca of 1942 never was like it
and the Casablanca of 1999 is even further from it. The storyline
was sheer fiction, but it was so good that it has become cult among
American filmgoers.
</P>
<P>
   And, so, you are somewhat disappointed to see the big city, the
teeming thousands in the streets, the airport so far out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the trip to Marrakech somewhat satisfied my search
for the Casablanca of Rick, it wasn't the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Is there nothing here to connect me to 1942, to Victor Laszlo,
to the storyline of romance and intrigue?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is in my hand.
</P>
<P>
   It is a little blue card the border guard handed me as I stepped
into Morocco. I am told to hold onto the card, as it will get me
out of the country. Get me out of the country? As in ``Letters of
Transit,'' those elusive papers Rick eventually gave to Victor? I
have the 1999 version of the ``Letters of Transit?'' I do, I do!
</P>
<P>
   Then it is real. It is 1942. And I have the documents to get
Victor off to Lisbon where he can resume his resistance to the
Nazis. But I am too timid. I return the card to the border guard as
we leave.
</P>
<P>
   There is a hero in this, however, and it is my wife. She's not
handing back those ``Letters of Transit.'' She flicks her eyelashes
at the guard and asks if she can keep the blue card. Obviously a
romantic, he agrees.
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy remains alive! She gives the ``Letters of Transit''
to Rick who, in turn, drives all the way out to that airport with
Louie and turns them over to Victor and Ilsa. As the plane pulls
away, Rick shoots Maj. Strasser and I join Rick, Louie and my wife,
walking toward the misty runway.
</P>
<P>
   It's something we'll always remember _ as time goes by.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
