<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8140 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATF-PIPEBOMBS02-COX     06-01 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATF-PIPEBOMBS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite apparent rise, pipe bombs really an old headache for ATF
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett and A. Scharnhorst
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Each case is startling: a 13-year-old
student in Brazil, Ind., is arrested for attaching seven pipe bombs
to a classmate's family cars; two high school students plant more
than 50 pipe bombs in Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo;
someone puts a pipe bomb in a white paper bag in a planter outside
the ballroom hosting the Palm Beach Lakes High School prom.
</P>
<P>
   The pipe bomb, a simple explosive device made from readily
available household items and some gunpowder, suddenly has the
nation's attention. The basic directions for making a pipe bomb are
available in public libraries and on the Internet, and it seems
their use is escalating with each frightful news report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's paying more attention,'' said John D'Angelo, a
spokesman with the Federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
in Washington. But, he said, ``Pipe bomb incidents happen all the
time. I think the stats show there really hasn't been a huge
increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1995, only California and Illinois topped
Florida in the discovery of explosive devices, including pipe
bombs, records show. More than 1,500 bombs were found in Florida in
those years. Between 1991 and 1995 _ the last year for which the
ATF has statistics _ pipe bombings resulted in an average of $1.25
million in damage annually, federal data show.
</P>
<P>
   As with many pipe bombing cases across the country, federal and
local investigators still are searching for those responsible for
the bomb found at the Palm Beach Lakes prom at the Sheraton Hotel
in West Palm Beach on May 15, officials said. The case is a
priority for West Palm Beach and school district police and ATF
agents, but investigating a pipe bomb can sometimes seem futile,
investigators admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike a firearms case, where oftentimes you can identify
where the gun came from from tracing a serial number . . . , there
is nothing that will make a pipe bomb singularly identifiable to
one individual,'' D'Angelo said. ``It's a piece in a large puzzle.
It's rare. . . . You don't come across the smoking gun in something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ATF says pipe bombs have become the most common
explosive device used by criminals in the United States _ the ideal
weapon for the do-it-yourself, entry-level terrorist. Pipe bombs
are low-tech, inexpensive, easy to build and, for these reasons,
difficult for investigators to link to the bomber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more primitive the device, the harder it is to trace,''
said Roy Bordes, president of the Bordes Group Inc., an Orlando
securities design company. ``You can track the powder and the
wiring. With a lot of work, you can even trace the nails _ find
what batch, what press and what (hardware store) they were sold at.
But when you find the (store), can you link the nails to the buyer
or the bomber? That's a real tough one.''
</P>
<P>
   The unsophisticated construction of the pipe bomb at the Palm
Beach Lakes prom puts it at the opposite end of the spectrum from a
device such as the one that blew up Pan Am Flight 103 over
Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb that brought down the jet was so technically complex _
Semtex plastic explosives with a computerized Czech-made detonator
triggered by altitude _ that only a limited number of terrorists
could be considered suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the bomb was traced to two Libyans because of a
microchip. Pipe bombs typically leave no such distinct signatures,
and the one found at the prom _ believed to consist of gun powder,
PVC pipe, nails and masking tape _ was basic.
</P>
<P>
   Olympics bomb was complex
</P>
<P>
   The deadly explosive device that went off at Centennial Park at
the Atlanta Olympics three years ago was a far more complex pipe
bomb, with 11 parts, including a 12-volt battery, alarm clock,
steel plate, foam padding and two kinds of tape.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say most of the pipe bomb cases they solve are the
result of detective work involving interviews with people, rather
than lab work involving forensic evidence. When it comes to
primitive devices, identifying disgruntled employees, or unhappy
students, or jealous lovers usually is most fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple pipe bomb is something anyone can put together,''
said Bordes. ``Part of the problem is that the Internet has
provided everybody with a massive research field. Anyone with a
computer mouse and a screen can learn how to make bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   The bomb recipes on the Internet have been available for
decades. How-to books on homemade explosives and violent revolution
written by radical anti-war activists have moved from bookshelves
to Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone who wanted to make a bomb in the '40s could
have gone to their local library and found out how,'' said Susan
Ellerin, president of STAT Resources, a security consulting company
in Chestnut Hill, Mass. ``What has happened is that the media now
has exposed it to people who otherwise might not have been clever
enough to find it. This generation is most able to access
information. They are so computer literate and their search tools
are so sophisticated, they just can locate things easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the brother of convicted Unabomber Theodore
Kaczynski, a victim of one of his bombings and the mother of a
victim of the Oklahoma City bombing made a plea for Internet
companies to purge bomb-building instructions.
</P>
<P>
   David Kaczynski, Unabomber victim Gary Wright and Marsha Kight,
whose daughter died in the Oklahoma City blast, appeared at a news
conference to ask America Online, Microsoft, Walt Disney and Yahoo!
to voluntarily police the vast array of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Industry spokesmen said companies do what they can, but
questioned whether it is possible to scan the content of every Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't tolerate any bomb-making information to be posted on
AOL Web pages, chat rooms or any other areas of service,'' said AOL
spokesman Andrew Weinstein. ``When we find it, we remove it.''
</P>
<P>
   Go Network uses automated filters to find and block sites filled
with violent language, said Amanda Higgins of Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not 100 percent foolproof,'' she said. ``There's an awful
lot of sites out there. The Internet is still a relatively new
medium. There's still a little bit of the wild, wild Web aspect of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Era of teen unrest?
</P>
<P>
   The fear among law enforcement and security specialists is the
killings at Columbine High School in Colorado and the rash of
shooting and bomb threat incidents that followed could signal a new
era of teen unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that school is about to end for the summer,
so we'll have a cooling off period,'' said Bordes, who in the wake
of Columbine has begun working with Orlando school officials. ``The
$64,000 question is whether we're looking at a major long-term
problem. It will be interesting to see how the next school year
flies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Moffett and A. Scharnhorst writes for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla. Reuters News Service contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
