<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY: Welfare reform cut benefits
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ More than 400,000 children and 250,000 adults
lost health insurance in 1997 because welfare reform laws
disqualified them for Medicaid coverage, Families USA reports in
the first national study to correlate welfare reform with health
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the children should not have lost Medicaid coverage, but
few states have taken significant advantage of federal laws and
dollars to expand Medicaid eligibility for low-wage working
families and reach those who are eligible, says the national health
consumer group's report, ``Losing Health Insurance: The Unintended
Consequences of Welfare Reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are seeing is the tip of the iceberg,'' Families USA
executive director Ron Pollack said, because 1997 was the first
year welfare reform was implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Many welfare recipients will start reaching the two-year time
limit requiring them to work or lose benefits on July 1, he said,
and families will begin reaching lifetime welfare limits three
years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reward many are receiving for coming off welfare, even
when they get jobs, is the loss of health care coverage,'' Pollack
said. ``And while politicians from both sides of the aisle are
celebrating the reduction in the welfare rolls, they are ignoring
this nasty side effect of welfare reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's welfare rolls shrank by 26 percent in 1997 and by 17
percent last year when 198,683 went off public assistance in the
two years, compared with national decreases of 20 percent and 13
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Families USA used data from the federal Department of Human
Services, Health Care Financing Administration and Census Bureau.
The report is available on www.familiesusa.org.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
