</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-POLLUTION-COMPROMISE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Both sides settle for less with pollution bill compromise
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, his allies in the Texas
Legislature and industry groups did not get exactly what they
wanted in a bill to reduce air pollution from older industrial
plants. The governor, who led the charge for a program that was
virtually all carrot, wound up with one that includes a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental activists and their legislative allies wanted a
program that was virtually all stick. But confronted with the
political reality of a popular governor and a conservative
Legislature, they had to settle for much less.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, sometimes you get a bill that doesn't
completely please anyone but partially pleases everyone,'' said
Rep. Ray Allen, R-Grand Prairie, the House sponsor of the plan.
``Sometimes that's the best you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan received final approval from the Senate and House on
Sunday and now goes to Bush, who said he would sign it. Under the
measure, Senate Bill 766, most of the older industrial plants would
be encouraged _ though not required _ to trim emissions.
</P>
<P>
   However, plants emitting the largest amounts would be coerced
into installing pollution controls by sharply rising fees. If they
don't ``volunteer'' to cut back by September 2001, the fee on their
emissions in excess of 4,000 tons a year would triple annually,
starting at $26 a ton.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 2005 the owners or operators of such plants
would have to pay $2,106 a ton. But by curbing emissions under a
so-called voluntary pollution-reduction permit, they could avoid
fees entirely on emissions in excess of 4,000 tons and pay just $26
a ton for the first 4,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 800 industrial plants that were in existence or under
construction were exempted, or grandfathered, from emissions rules
by state lawmakers when they adopted clean-air legislation in 1971.
Bush's top environmental priority for the legislative session has
been to reduce those emissions using a voluntary approach. Critics
wanted the reductions mandated.
</P>
<P>
   Bush welcomed the compromise bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff worked with members of the House and Senate to come
up with a bill that will encourage plants that are grandfathered to
meet standards, and there is a little incentive in the bill,'' the
governor said. ``I think it is proper. I'm glad it's in the bill to
encourage those that are still grandfathered to meet deadlines for
the State of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also supports a mandatory clean air provision in a bill
deregulating the electric-utility industry. That bill requires
owners of grandfathered power plants to reduce emissions but allows
them to charge consumers for the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's chief opponent in the Legislature on the question of
grandfathered emissions, Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, did not sound
nearly as pleased with the final wording of SB 766. ``Our goal was
to close the loophole for grandfathered emissions,'' Maxey said.
``That is not done. But it is more than the environmentalists
expected us to get when we started out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally politics on the governor's part. Governor Bush
needs a bill to look green'' for a likely presidential race, Maxey
added.
</P>
<P>
   Tom ``Smitty'' Smith, director of the consumer group Public
Citizen, described the compromise as a good first step. ``But it's
important we lay the blame for refusing to go farther on the
governor,'' Smith said. ``A majority of the grandfathered plants
are going to become great-grandfathered plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry groups were not completely satisfied, either. Ben
Sebree, vice president of governmental affairs for the Texas Oil
and Gas Association, a trade group representing producers, refiners
and pipeline companies, said his organization supported the concept
of voluntary reductions. Tripling the fees leaves large plants with
essentially no option, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an attempt to move it from voluntary to mandatory,''
Sebree said. ``And to a large extent that guts the spirit of the
bill. We're neutral on it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest source of grandfathered emissions _ lignite-fired
generators at the Aluminum Company of America's aluminum smelter
near Rockdale, about 50 miles east of Austin _ gets a bit of a
break. The bill allows Alcoa to make substantial reductions in
emissions of nitrogen oxides but to forgo reductions of sulfur
dioxide. Alcoa officials had argued that the high cost of reducing
sulfur emissions might force the plant to close. Sulfur dioxide
contributes to haze and acid rain; nitrogen oxides form
ground-level ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph K.M. Haurwitz writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
