<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MILOSEVIC02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Milosevic indictment amounts to little
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem with justice is that it takes confidence in the
system to produce results.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment last week of Yugoslavian President Slobodan
Milosevic by the International War Crimes Tribunal is an
interesting turn in the ongoing Balkan saga. However, the
tribunal's efforts in capturing indicted war criminals and bringing
them to trial has been nothing short of futile. In fact, its
failure has undermined confidence in the tribunal itself _ thus
making it little more than a sham body with few means of enforcing
its legal activities.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a war crimes tribunal is an unfortunate necessity in
a world of ever-increasing technological warfare. Previous wars in
the Balkans have proven medium-sized armies have the potential to
devastate entire races of people with lightening-quick attacks. The
massacre of Muslims during the Bosnia War and now of the Kosovars
in the current conflict demonstrate the need for just such a
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   But, like legal bodies in this nation, any court has the power
to act only with enforcement. It takes a police force to serve
warrants and arrest suspects once a court approves them.
</P>
<P>
   The War Crimes Tribunal in the Hague, Netherlands, does not have
a police force. It has no way of forcing extradition or arrests. It
can only raise its voice to perceived injustice and hope the
criminals are somehow brought to them.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to the Bosnia War, where Yugoslav forces decimated
United Nations-established ``safe havens'' for Bosnia Muslims.
Bosnian Serb leaders Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic have been
under indictment for instigating those actions by this same War
Crimes Tribunal. The tribunal knows where each is, what they do and
where they live. But the tribunal does not have a force that can
extricate them from Bosnia and deliver them for prosecution, and
thus far nations with military forces are reluctant to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   In the current situation, the indictment of Milosevic and his
deputies looks to have two possible consequences. First, it serves
to justify the continued NATO air campaign against Serbia, making
the campaign an attack on war criminals leading a ``rogue'' state.
Second, it makes any attempt at negotiations even more difficult to
commence. Any cease-fire agreement with a convicted war criminal
will probably not have to be honored once the conviction is
secured, leaving Serbia, if it capitulates, to the will of
international bodies to determine its future.
</P>
<P>
   It is important to see a generally-respected international body
taking action against a leader who is a threat to his own citizens
and the stability of an entire region. Unfortunately, without the
means to enforce that action, and without the international
confidence necessary to pressure for Milosevic's arrest, the
indictment is only an official recognition of the terror Milosevic
has wrought.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
