A8146 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-LAMB-COLUMN02-CO     06-01 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-LAMB-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Proposed Ohio bill lets dying patient expire peacefully
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ No one liked it when emergency doctors and medics
were compelled to unleash electric shock paddles, long breathing
tubes and hypodermic needles in their desperate revival effort so a
dying patient might live to vegetate another day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember times when families were blocking the paramedic's
way of getting to the patient or cussing at them or threatening to
sue,'' says Dr. David Keseg, one of about 200 emergency specialists
in the south-suburban practice of Premier Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   But if a nursing home or family member dialed 911, it didn't
matter if a dying patient had made it clear in both a living will
and whispered pleas that he or she wanted to die without frenzy.
Living wills don't apply to ambulance staffs. They were legally
required until May 20 to do everything they could to restore the
heartbeat of that barely recognizable loved one in the fetal
position.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency doctors and paramedics have lost lawsuits in Ohio both
for reviving someone who didn't want to be revived and for not
reviving someone whose family wanted a heroic effort, says Dr.
David Romano, who served with Keseg on the committee that drafted
the new law's rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have literally been in situations where I've had two family
members tell me, 'You do everything or we'll sue you,' and two
other family members say, 'If you do anything, we'll sue you,'''
says Romano, director of the emergency departments at the Mercy
hospitals in Springfield and Urbana and a Beavercreek ambulance
staff member for 10 years before he became a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is House Bill 354, called ``DNR Comfort Care'' for
``do not resuscitate.'' It means people who are terminally ill or
have end-stage organ disease can, with their physician's
authorization, receive assurance of dying as peacefully as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment in basic Comfort Care is a choice to forgo all
elements of CPR from emergency personnel. Or the patient can choose
Comfort Care Arrest, which authorizes medical treatment up to the
point when the breathing or heartbeat stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``These situations happen many, many times a day in every
community in the state of Ohio,'' Romano says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the dominant end-of-life topic in public discussion has been
the debate on whether assisted suicide is mercy or murder, a far
rarer contingency. By focusing on whether it's fair to end
someone's life, we have ignored the far more pertinent question of
when it's fair to save someone's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing written that says the only way you can meet
your maker is with somebody thumping on your chest and somebody
putting a plastic tube down your throat,'' Romano says. ``But for
some reason, people in this country in the last 30 years have
developed the sense that that has to happen to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, he says, people whose hearts stop beating have less
than a 5 percent rate of surviving and regaining their faculties.
For people who already are very sick, that rate is virtually zero.
</P>
<P>
   But Romano remembers a recent survey in which ``John Q. Public
thinks that rate is 60 percent or more. So there's a huge
discrepancy between reality and expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   Living wills still enable people to declare that they don't want
to be heroically saved in other cases when they are barely alive.
They should be backed up by a durable power of attorney for health
care, which authorizes someone else to speak for them, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency personnel now can turn their attention to keeping a
hopeless Comfort Care patient relatively comfortable with
medication, a clear breathing passage, other first aid and
emotional support.
</P>
<P>
   No law is perfect. The state does not provide Comfort Care
enrollees with the bracelets or necklaces they need to identify
themselves. But if they can't afford jewelry, they can still go to
a hospital for a plastic identification bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   It won't save a life, but might save a death from being more
gruesome than it has to be.
</P>
<P>
   TO ENROLL in or learn more about either new DNR program, write
to the Ohio Department of Health at 246 N. High St., Columbus, Ohio
43215, call Wanda Roy at (614) 466-5076 or receive enrollment forms
at the ODH Web site, www.odh.state.oh.us/
</P>
<P>
   records/records-f.htm. Click on ``forms'' and then ``Do Not
Resuscitate'' to navigate the cumbersome site.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
