<P>
   AUTOMOTIVE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS _ FORD MUSTANG GT _ Maybe the folks at Ford who
created the '99 Mustang have been out in the sun too long; or maybe
they're so caught up in the ongoing fascination with things
Egyptian that they really think it makes sense to say that the new
'Stang is visually comparable to a pyramid. Those Egyptian
pyramids, they should remember, have been stuck, immovable and
immutable, in the sand for millennia. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3-column color photograph of the
1999 Ford Mustang GT and 2-column color photo of interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE -- Fact box previewing the 1999 Ford Mustang
GT.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC -- Don't expect top quality auto repair at a
cut-rate price (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Includes
1-column color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is available after 2 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ Mustang history quiz. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY. 15.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ Nora Carter's automotive column is not available
this week.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-PROTEGE _ A review of the Mazda Protege. (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ This year's college graduates seem to be earnest
about investing for their future _ but not necessarily prepared for
the task. Few have gotten any formal education in managing their
investments, and a surprising percentage say they rely on parents
or even on comtemporaries for financial advice. They will need
plenty of help. We review a first-class book on the basics of
investment. Conclusion: You can do it yourself, but most will want
to turn the job over to pros, meaning mutual funds. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   REUNION _ Nearly a half-century ago, an American soldier took in
a homeless Korean boy and became `like a daddy' to him; recently,
through a stroke of luck, they were united again. (Schrade, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHRITIS-TREATMENT _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Two out of five Americans
with chronic joint symptoms haven't sought a doctor's diagnosis,
according to research by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention. And even among those diagnosed with arthritis, nearly
three out of five are not undergoing treatment for it. One reason
is many people's stomachs can't handle the longtime drug of choice
for arthritis, nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) such
as aspirin, ibuprofen and naproxen. But two recently approved drugs
called cox-2 inhibitors have shown success in relieving arthritis
pain without upsetting the stomach. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
