<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-ETIQUETTE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Wireless phones are everywhere.
So who better to lay some of the ground rules for mobile-phone
etiquette than Peggy Post, great-granddaughter-in-law to Emily
Post, author of ``Emily Post's Etiquette.'' Peggy Post wrote the
75th anniversary edition of the guide, and suggests common-sense
courtesy when using wireless phones. By FRANCES INGRAHAM. (Photo
available on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR'S-RETREAT (Berlin, N.Y.) _ In the foothills of Misery
Mountain, on land where he spent boyhood summers, author Caleb Carr
is planning to restore an 18th century farmhouse as a writing
haven. The author of the historical thrillers ``The Alienist'' and
``Angel of Darkness,'' makes clear his love for the location in the
Taconic foothills. By TIM O'BRIEN.
</P>
<P>
   INLAID-FLOORS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Inlaid floors have become a
popular decorating trend for 1999. Inlay is the art of arranging
wood pieces and other materials such as tile, marble, stone and
metal into geometric or free-form patterns and designs. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM. (Photo available on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   SCONCES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Wall sconces, which generally feature
sockets for candles that are fixed to a shelf or tray, add ambience
to any room, including the patio. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   CLICKER-TRAINING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Pet owners who have attempted
to train their animals know the frustration of trying to
communicate and to judge how quickly a pet learns. But clicker
training, which uses sounds and positive reinforcement, offers some
hope. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   FLY-FISHING (San Francisco) _ Deep in Golden Gate Park and far
from the madding crowd, people are standing on the banks of three
shallow concrete ponds, motionless but for the flicks of their
wrists, the arcs of their fishing rods, the pirouettes of their
lines. They're practicing fly casting, right in the middle of the
city. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   TRANSSEXUAL-SUIT (San Francisco) _ A male-to-female transsexual
who was disqualified from entering the San Francisco police academy
after failing a psychological test is suing the city, alleging
gender discrimination. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TROUBLED-AIRLINE (San Francisco) _ Troubled Philippine Airlines
has until Friday to come up with $200 million to pay part of its
$2.3 billion debt _ or Manila will consider alternatives to the
regime of PAL's major shareholder, multimillionaire Lucio Tan,
according to Philippines Secretary of Trade and Industry Jose T.
Pardo. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PHANTOM-TECHNOLOGY (San Francisco) _ Computers have
revolutionized filmmaking in the six summers since audiences first
gasped at the dinosaurs in ``Jurassic Park.'' Today, viewers are
flocking to the latest CGI-driven film, ``The Phantom Menace,'' the
relentlessly hyped fourth installment in filmmaker George Lucas'
``Star Wars'' series. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MALES (San Francisco) _ All Hail, the Alpha Male. At least
that's the new trend on TV these days. Although the female viewer
is still coveted, she is also more plentiful. But the male _ in TV
Land he's the elusive prize, all channel surfing,
short-attention-span testosterone and a tendency to buy a lot of
things advertised. He's the Holy Grail of Nielsen ratings. By TIM
GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-MAULDIN (San Francisco) _ Cartoonist Bill Mauldin is
out with the 50th anniversary edition of his cartoons about Willie
and Joe during World War II. He produced 228 pages of outstanding
drawings and prose as he followed the 45th Division through Italy
and France, and his book of drawings remains a classic, half a
century later. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CATFISH (San Marcos, Texas) _ Eating a mess of catfish is the
ultimate goal of going through the trouble of cleaning them, with a
multitude of recipes available for a fine fish meal. One of the
easiest, although it can make you believe the kitchen is on fire,
is the blackened catfish. By RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ A recent column on hotels struck a
nerve with many readers. I invited input and got it. Here are some
reader recommendations for making overnight accommodations more
tolerable. By HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Adam Werbach, the 26-year-old
former president of the Sierra Club, environmental film producer
and three-year resident of the Mission District, is considering
throwing his hat _ well, bicycle helmet _ into the ring to
challenge San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Using money they made from their
high school Christmas dance, seven St. Ignatius seniors entered the
world of social activism earlier this month when they flew to
Washington, D.C., and joined 5,000 others in a protest against a
U.S. military training facility nicknamed ``The School of the
Assassins.'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ It looks like members of the
National Rifle Association are on the verge of some real
unpleasantness. And that has less to do with the justice of their
position than with their tactics. Keep it up, and it won't be long
before NRA stands for ``Not Relevant Anymore.'' By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ We all know the old cliche
about money not buying happiness. In the political world, however,
we can almost always depend on it to purchase controversy.The more
dollars there are, the more elected officials and interest groups
have to fight about. One obvious, recent example of money buying
misery is Texas' huge settlement of its anti-tobacco lawsuit.By
CLAY ROBISON
</P>
