<SLUG> BC-CATFISH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CATCH TO FINISH, CATFISH IS GREAT EATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RALPH WININGHAM  
 c.1999 San Express Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ In about twice the time it takes to read
this paragraph, old Uncle Willis could skin, clip off the fins,
behead and remove the insides of a three-pound channel catfish.
</P>
<P>
   Working at a fish cleaning shop and processing a couple tons of
fish a week finely honed his skill to a point he was like a machine
_ a very smelly machine.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many people who fish have lost the knack or
desire to clean their own catch, and others were never taught the
proper technique.
</P>
<P>
   Doing their best to change that situation, at least with the
younger fishing generation, is the Texas Agriculture Extension
Service with it's recently created Texas 4-H Sportfishing Program.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hysmith and Brian Triplett, both county extension agents,
were demonstrated part of the program recently at the 4th annual
Texas Fly Fishing and Outdoor Show at Southwest Texas University's
Aquarena Springs in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with harvesting fish as a food
source,'' Triplett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a lot of kids involved, some of whom don't have
a chance to learn from their father or grandfather,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the program is a long-term, community-based
sportfishing and aquatic resources education effort that teaches
such skills as freshwater and saltwater angling, tackle crafting,
aquatic ecology, resource management and ethics _ and the basics of
how to clean a fish.
</P>
<P>
   Hysmith, who is based in College Station, carefully explains
that the whiskered cats are popular for both catching and eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Channel cats are the most popular and are readily identifiable
because of their forked tail,'' he said, explaining that other
species in Texas include bullheads, flatheads and blues.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaning process starts the same for any catfish, with the
cleaner grabbing the freshly killed fish by the head, avoiding the
spines on the dorsal and pectoral fins.
</P>
<P>
   ``These spines will jab you and they hurt a lot. Each spine has
little barbs, just like a sting ray barb,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hysmith added that any fish whose gills have turned white should
be avoided as having been dead too long and may not be safe to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the head with your fingers and thumbs wrapped around the
back of the pectoral fins, carefully avoiding the dorsal spine, the
cleaner uses a sharp fillet knife to cut through the skin behind
the fish's head, around the pectoral fins and down across its
belly.
</P>
<P>
   The dorsal fin is then removed by cutting at an angle on both
sides of the fin and pulling it out with a pair of skinning pliers.
The same pliers are then used to grab the cut skin, which is pulled
away from the flesh toward the tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the skin comes off in one piece and other times you
have to pull it off a little at a time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The anal and pelvic fins are removed the same way as the dorsal
fin, and most people leave on the tail fin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be sure to save the stomach area. That is where they get the
catfish nuggets you buy at the store,'' Hysmith said.
</P>
<P>
   Firmly gripping the body of the skinned fish with one hand and
pulling up on the head of the fish with the other, the head and
most of the intestines are removed as the head breaks free from the
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skinning a fish is quite a process, but it just takes
practice,'' Hysmith said.
</P>
<P>
   Eating a mess of catfish is the ultimate goal of going through
the trouble of cleaning them, with a multitude of recipes available
for a fine fish meal.
</P>
<P>
   One of the easiest, although it can make you believe the kitchen
is on fire, is the following recipe for blackened catfish.
</P>
<P>
   If you try to cook this in your kitchen, make sure the exhaust
fan is going full blast.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer to use a propane cooker on the deck or at the camp
site, but do whatever makes you happy and gets the job done. (Be
advised: this is a hot and spicy dish.)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKENED CATFISH
</P>
<P>
   6 catfish fillets
</P>
<P>
   2 tbsp paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 tsp salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tsp lemon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tsp garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tsp cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tsp black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tsp basil
</P>
<P>
   1 tsp onion powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tsp thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   Mix all spices in a large bowl and set aside. Melt butter and
pour into another large bowl. Dip fillets into melted butter, then
coat both sides with spice mix. Place coated fillets on a sheet of
waxed paper. Heat a cast iron skillet over high heat about 10
minutes or until skillet is very hot. Place three fillets at a time
in the skillet and drizzle with about 1 tablespoon of butter for
each fillet. Cook on high heat for about two minutes per side. The
cooking fillets will smoke, a lot, so preparing this dish outside
is highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (In Texas, youngsters or adults interested in the 4-H
Sportfishing Program may obtain further information from the local
county extension agent, or by calling the state office at
409-845-1214. The state also publishes a pamphlet outlining
fish-cleaning techniques and other information called the ``Texas
Freshwater Fish Identification Guide'' that is available from the
extension agents.)
</P>
</TEXT>
