<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR SILENCE FROM THE NRA 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ His name is Chet. He lives in an outer Albany
suburb. He called me to complain about gun control.
</P>
<P>
   There should be no restrictions whatever on gun ownership, Chet
was saying. Guns aren't the problem. People are the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Are you in the National Rifle Association, I asked him? Sure.
Well, I let him know that it looks like he and his pals are on the
verge of some real unpleasantness. And that has less to do with the
justice of their position than with their tactics. According to all
the polls, people are losing patience with the NRA's intransigence.
Keep it up, and it won't be long before NRA stands for ``Not
Relevant Anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Second Amendment to the U.S. Constitution gives
citizens a presumptive right to own guns. Some of the gun-control
people will argue that, because of the amendment's wording, that
right applies not to individuals but to state militias. They're
wrong. The Supreme Court of the United States ruled years ago that
the right of gun ownership applies to people, not to institutions.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean, however, that the right to own a gun can't be
reasonably regulated, or shouldn't be. Regulation becomes
unconstitutional only when it's so oppressive that it infringes
upon the basic right itself.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same deal with abortion, by the way. That's why the
current abortion debate focuses on the edges of the issue _ on
parental notification, late-term abortions and public funding for
them. The basic right to an abortion _ whether you like it or not,
and most people wince at it _ is settled law.
</P>
<P>
   The abortion rights crowd fights all that fiercely, the same way
the NRA fights any attempt at regulating gun ownership. In their
tactics and their stark, mindless terror that their rights somehow
will be taken away, these two groups resemble one another more than
they differ.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the problem. Three in five Americans call themselves
moderates. But the terms of political debate in this society seem
increasingly set by the extremists on both sides. It's when the
extremists become too shrill that people in the middle begin to
press for concrete action from their politicians. That's when
things get nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Generally politicians are content to sit back, collect campaign
dollars from pressure groups and maintain the status quo so the
money keeps rolling in. It's only when public pressure on them
mounts that they'll actually take action on controversial issues.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with tobacco. The tobacco industry, like
the NRA, was giving heavily to Republicans. So the Democrats began
a drumbeat against tobacco use. They were so successful in fanning
the flames of people in the middle that, eventually, the
Republicans turned their backs on their contributors and hopped on
board.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with schoolchildren with guns popping into class, the same
thing is happening with guns. The Senate, controlled by
Republicans, recently passed gun-control legislation it had
rejected just a week earlier. And gun-control forces are rubbing
their hands together in glee as this debate intensifies.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of all this is the fear of many honest, law-abiding
gun owners that federal agents in black helicopters will land in
their front yards one morning and confiscate their firearms.
That'll never happen, even though some gun-control fans unabashedly
would love to see it.
</P>
<P>
   But gun nuts running around proclaiming their love for weaponry
and their opposition to any regulation, no matter how modest or
reasonable, hurt their cause rather than help it.
</P>
<P>
   I've been around politics a long time. I've seen this stuff
before. You don't convince people by infuriating them. If Chet and
his buddies want to avoid some bruising defeats, it's time to adopt
a new tactic:
</P>
<P>
   Just shut up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
