<HEADLINE>
SCONCES ADD FLAIR TO ANY ROOM, INDOORS OR OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Wall sconces add ambience to any room, including
the patio.
</P>
<P>
   The term sconce is used to describe a variety of lighting
devices. It is most commonly associated with a wall light that
generally features sockets for candles that are fixed to a shelf or
tray that projects from a back plate.
</P>
<P>
   Sconces can also have one or more branches of light with candle
sockets and a broad lip or circular collar to catch the dripping
wax.
</P>
<P>
   These wall lighting fixtures evolved from the candle and back
plate brackets used in medieval times, where they illuminated walls
from castles to more humble dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the centuries, various materials have been used for
wall sconces, including wrought iron, pewter, silver, copper,
brass, carved wood, gilded wood and glazed earthenware.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the second half of the 17th century that carvers
and gilders began enhancing the basic elements of the sconce
(candleholder and back plate) with more decorative elements.
Backing the sconce with mirrored glass doubled the candle power.
</P>
<P>
   Sconces were also decoratively painted, gilded and japanned
(varnished with a special type of lacquer). Some even featured a
needlework back plate surrounded by a shaped or molded wood frame.
</P>
<P>
   From the late 17th century through the middle of the 18th
century, sconces were sometimes referred to as girandole (a
branched candleholder often attached to a wall mirror). Girandoles
were originally symbols of luxury and opulence.
</P>
<P>
   Girandoles feature very elaborate brackets with lights and often
with branched candlesticks.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of the rococo style in the mid-19th century restored
the elaboration of the girandole. The sconce evolved into a gas
bracket during the Victorian era and was wired for electricity for
the revival of period furnishings in the Edwardian era.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the electric sconce is often outfitted with a
candle-flame bulb (and perhaps decorator shades) and faux cardboard
candles replete with make-believe melting wax.
</P>
<P>
   Sconces also come in a variety of contemporary designs, from
frosted glass to durable resins, that bear no resemblance to their
ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to pay $30 or more for a candle sconce, and from $60 up
to $400 or more for an electric version.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1300EDT &QL; 
