<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INLAID-FLOORS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INLAYS TURN FLOORS INTO SHOWPIECES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Inlaid floors have become a popular decorating
trend for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Custom wood floors add so much beauty to a home,'' said Ed
Korczak, executive director of the National Wood Flooring
Association in Ellisville, Mo. ``Customizing wood floors is a great
way to show off your sense of style.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Korczak, adding inlay to wooden floors may make a
room appear larger or complement a certain look, from country to
contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   Inlay is the art of arranging wood pieces and other materials
such as tile, marble, stone and metal into geometric or free-form
patterns and designs.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Floors of Oshkosh in Winneconne, Wis., founded in 1991,
features a catalog of inlaid medallions and borders to customize
hardwood floors. The company also specializes in custom-order
designs.
</P>
<P>
   Customers send floor samples for the company's designers to
duplicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 90 percent of the inlay work that we do goes into
new homes,'' said Dick Norton, marketing manager for Oshkosh.
``About seven years ago, we were only doing border replacements for
worn-out floors from the turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   All designs are factory assembled and ready for glue-down
installation and finishing at the job site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of modern technology, the saws that are used to cut
wood are very high-tech,'' Norton said. Laser technology, which is
computer-directed, cuts finer curves than most straight saws, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, it's a piece of cake to cut something like a delicate
rose pattern or any other intricate design,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Floors by Oshkosh has designed some high-profile
floors, including the sound stage for ``Saturday Night Live'' and
floors for the films ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``The Perfect Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done work all over the world,'' Norton said. ``We
reproduced an exact replica of a blackened and distressed castle
floor and a $3,000 inlay medallion for a ceiling in a house in
Canada to conceal a pull-down stair.''
</P>
<P>
   Designs are based on anything from photos and fabric to
staircases or favorite flowers and plants. Ivy is very popular for
outlining eating areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't feel that you have to use inlay designs through the
whole house,'' Norton said. ``Medallions are perfect if you have
the space or wish to mirror the shape of the ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Borders can be just as decorative, especially when they are used
to define an area, Norton explained. ``Homeowners like to use them
to separate one room from another or just to define an area in a
large room.''
</P>
<P>
   They also work well in front of fireplaces and stair landings or
to patch in where a wall has been removed during renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Color is achieved by combining woods: maple for white tones,
poplar for pale green, red oak for a pinkish cast, mahogany for
browns, walnut for dark brown, yellowheart for yellow and
purpleheart for grape tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``For colors such as blue and red, the wood must be impregnated
with the color,'' Norton said. ``This way if you refinish the floor
by sanding it down, you'll never lose the color.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden floors in general are considered a good investment to
help a house hold its value and sell faster and for more money,
according to a recent nationwide survey of residential real estate
agents by the National Wood Flooring Association.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Nichols, owner of the Wood Floor Store in Latham, N.Y.,
said that hardwood floors are practical for allergy suffers,
because wood doesn't harbor dust and microorganisms as other floor
coverings do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also refinish and repair a wood floor,'' Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   They also are timeless and resilient, which can reduce body
fatigue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one place you don't want to install a hardwood floor is
over concrete in the basement,'' advised David Hartson, co-owner
with Tony Poutre of P&AMP;H Premiere Hardwood Floors in Albany.
``There, you should look to a machine-made wooden floor, where the
layers of wood are laminated and stabilized so it's not affected by
humidity and warp.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping hardwood floors clean is a must because sand and grit
act like sandpaper. High-gloss finishes tend to show scuff marks,
scratches, traffic areas and dirt more readily than satin finishes,
according to the National Wood Flooring Association. A softer
finish reveals the natural character, color and grain of the wood
more readily than a gloss finish.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on wear and tear, a wooden floor shouldn't have to be
buffed out and recoated for at least five to seven years, Hartson
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
