<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR'S-RETREAT-HNS &LR;      06-01 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR'S-RETREAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR SEEKS WRITING HAVEN WITH A VIEW OF MISERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN, N.Y. _ In the foothills of Misery Mountain, on land
where he spent boyhood summers, author Caleb Carr is planning to
restore an 18th-century farmhouse as a writing haven.
</P>
<P>
   Carr, author of the historical thrillers ``The Alienist'' and
``Angel of Darkness,'' bought the 1,560-acre property in April for
$975,000.
</P>
<P>
   To Carr, who spent summers in Cherry Plain, it is more like
home. The land was owned by his great-aunt, Emily Henrotin, but
left the family when she died in the mid-1960s. His mother, whose
family bought the neighboring farm in the 1950s, still lives down
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all sort of comes full circle,'' said Carr, 43. ``It had
always been a dream of everyone in the family to buy the place and
get it back in the family.'' Carr purchased the property from the
estate of Hazard E. Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   As he graciously showed off the property one recent day, Carr
made clear his love for its location in the Taconic foothills of
eartern New York. The farmhouse nestles in a remote corner, more
than a mile down a dirt road, with the sounds of a nearby creek
rushing by. The property ends at the Massachusetts border, and it
includes Misery Mountain _ named for its three ragged peaks that
have challenged many a climber _ and another, closer mountain
nearby that is unnamed.
</P>
<P>
   The farmhouse has been largely empty since the 1960s, and it is
in need of considerable work. Its dining room is a marvel, a step
back in time to the mid-18th century, and three other rooms are
original.
</P>
<P>
   A three-bay garage out back is dilapidated, and two barns
elsewhere on the property are in need of serious repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task of putting it back on its feet is really daunting,''
Carr said. He has an engineer coming to evaluate the property and
tell him how much it will cost to restore it to working order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything can be salvaged. It'll take quite a bit of
time,'' he said. ``I would like to spend as much time as I can up
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr fought off an attempt by New York state to acquire the
land: The Taconic Trail runs across the top of the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that, they'd want access from down here,'' he said.
``It's always been a farm, not a recreational site, so I've been
trying to re-establish it as a farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Goodermote is a farmer who works some of the land. The
author won't work the rest himself, but he wants to see it thrive
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really aren't many places like this left anywhere unless
you want to go out to Montana,'' he said. ``For me, it being a
fairly easy drive down to New York, that mattered a lot. The family
history did matter because I have very fond memories of our
great-aunt. When the farm was up and running, they would let us
come here and work on it. It was really the center of activity in
this town. It's very reminiscent of another time. That's what I
like about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr has an apartment in New York City, and between books he
often works rewriting scripts in Los Angeles. He says he is ready
to write a third novel, though he is uncertain he wants to write
another sequel to his two best-sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The novels focus on Dr. Laszlo Kreizler, a specialist in mental
disorders _ or alienist as they were called at the time _ who
investigates serial killings in the late 19th century. Carr knows
the public and publisher would like a third novel in the series,
but he also wants to avoid the fate of Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, who
grew so tired of Sherlock Holmes he tried to kill off his own hero.
</P>
<P>
   While Carr is still uncertain what his next book will be about,
he is sure where it will be written.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the main purpose of it, to get it mainly up on its feet
so I can spend much of my time up here writing,'' he said. ``It's
really the only spot in the world I've been to that was really
removed. The whole valley is self-contained and secure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
