<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8254 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALIENS-VIDEO-LADN &LR;      06-01 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALIENS-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALIENS' FILMS EVOLVED OVER LIFE OF SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: ``Tuesday'' in 5th graf refers to June 1) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Most actors wouldn't consider playing a synthetic
being in a sci-fi picture as a turning point in their careers. But
that's exactly what it was for Lance Henriksen when he took on the
role of Bishop, an android, in the 1986 James Cameron film
``Aliens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I'm going to work in a certain way, and if I don't
see it on the screen myself, then I'm going to get out of acting,''
says Henriksen, who recently finished up three years of starring in
``Millennium,'' the dark, brooding series from Chris (``X-Files'')
Carter on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bishop was an innocent,'' he says of the android who was
programmed not to harm people. ``I really loved playing him for
that reason,'' Hendriksen says, adding that he used his emotional
life of when he was 12 to get into character.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop was a change of pace for Henriksen, who often has been
cast in tough guy roles such as gunfighters and cops, including one
in an earlier Cameron film, ``Terminator.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Henriksen saw what he was looking for up on the screen,
and you can, too, with the release Tuesday of ``The Alien Legacy''
from 20th Century Fox Home Video on both VHS and DVD. All four of
the ``Alien'' films, which star Sigourney Weaver as the
unbelievably resilent Ripley, have been digitally remastered.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron's ``Aliens'' is, of course, the sequel to Ridley Scott's
terrifying 1979 ``Alien,'' which introduced the world to one of
cinema's most nightmarish creatures. ``Alien'' has been called a
``haunted-house movie in space,'' but that doesn't do it justice.
Scott created, with the help of artist H.R. Giger's fantastic
visions, a futuristic gothic tale. The creature begins as a sort of
incubus or succubus, attaching itself to the face of an
unsuspecting body. It eventually grows _ like a cancer _ inside the
individual, tearing forth at an unexpected time. (Those who have
seen it will never forget John Hurt's chest-bursting moment.) The
alien equals our most primal fear _ the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   When Cameron came around to do the sequel, he took a different
tack, opting for an unrelenting action movie more akin to a war
flick. But the films have one thing in common _ great special
effects that still hold up. Considering that they were made before
computer-generated images, it's doubly amazing. There were four
men, Henriksen says, inside the giant animatronic queen that Ripley
faces off against in ``Aliens.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor says that his favorite memory of the shoot, which took
place in London, was when they were going to spend a couple of
hundred thousand dollars on an animatronic model of Bishop so that
it could be bounced around during a climactic scene. Henriksen,
instead, suggested that he learn to move like the model. ``So, we
put wires on the wrist of the (Bishop) doll and bounced it across
the floor. Then I started matching the movements of the doll, and
it worked perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that the scene where he is ripped in half by the
creature took two weeks to film, but now would take a lot less
because of CGI. (By the way, Bishop lives _ he is a synthetic.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing about Jim Cameron is that he puts every dollar
on the screen,'' says Henriksen about the man behind the most
expensive movie ever made.
</P>
<P>
   While the first two ``Alien'' movies were quite influential,
being both commercial and artistic successes, the latter two went
in different directions. ``Aliens 3,'' in which Ripley crash lands
on a penal colony planet after her escape from her last battle with
the creatures _ only to find one growing in her _ takes a middle
ground between the gothic and the action genres. The 1992 film
never fully gels but has some interesting moments, and picked up an
Oscar nomination for special effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alien Resurrection'' is more a tongue-in-cheek action picture.
The 1997 film was written by Joss Whedon, the man behind TV's
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and has a hip, fun, over-the-top
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Henriksen, who was also in ``Alien 3'' as Bishop's creature,
says that while working on ``Aliens,'' cast members hoped that
``Scott would do the third and Jim do the fourth, so there would be
this competitive slant on it.''
</P>
<P>
   While that didn't happen, the four ``Aliens'' movies are the
most consistently exciting of any movie series, which is why fans
of the films should be thrilled with this new release.
</P>
<P>
   This five-tape gift pack includes a 66-minute documentary that
contains interviews with Scott and Cameron, the film's special
effects creators and crew, and ``Aliens,'' which has been re-edited
to include 17 minutes deleted from the original.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
