<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8257 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MALES-HNS &LR;      06-01 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MALES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE AIMS TO TURN ON VIEWERS WITH GUY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ All hail the Alpha Male.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the new trend on television these days. Although
the female viewer is still coveted, she is also more plentiful. But
the male _ in TV Land he's the elusive prize, all channel surfing,
short-attention-span testosterone and a tendency to buy a lot of
things advertised. He's the Holy Grail of Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, meaning last season, the way to hook males was
with comedies. Or cop shows. But the wily, or just dumbfoundedly
bored, males gave up and moved on. Where? To wrestling, mostly. And
pay-cable channels on which they can glimpse the occasional nipple.
</P>
<P>
   That shift of the male phalanx set off alarms in Hollywood,
where television executives got out the charts and graphs and came
up with a brilliant new idea: Programming for the YesterMale,
pre-women's lib, pre-cuddling after sex, pre-toilet seat down. You
know, the man's man, the proud remote-toting Neanderthal.
</P>
<P>
   So while wrestling remains central to the mix, the ante has been
raised, first by USA Networks, which recently launched a series
called ``Happy Hour.'' Hosted by Frank Zappa's sons, Ahmet and
Dweezil, ``Happy Hour'' (Saturday nights) is a rollicking variety
show with music, dancing, celebrity guest stars (actors, musicians,
athletes), stupid games and a good dose of scantily clad
navel-shaking by 10 women known as the ``Bombshell'' dancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy Hour'' cashes in on its goal of being fun, brainless,
dumb and sexy all at once. USA loves the show. Why? Because it's
where the boys are.
</P>
<P>
   Next out of the gate is ``The X Show'' on the FX cable channel.
The daily, one-hour ``talk/magazine series'' appears Wednesday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   This show is essentially Barbara Walters' ``The View'' with four
males who make TV out of hot-property guy magazines such as Maxim,
Details and Men's Health.
</P>
<P>
   Tips are given on women (called ``Gettin' It''), finance,
sports, entertainment, technology, sex, clothes, self-improvement,
office survival and gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four hosts is Mark DeCarlo, best known as host of the
syndicated ``Studs,'' a show that took ``The Dating Game'' out on
the town and gave it a cheap lap dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X Show'' has a pedigree that leads back to the Y
chromosome. Producers Gary Auerbach and Mark Cronin are responsible
for ``Singled Out'' on MTV _ a show that took ``Studs'' to a frat
party, stopping for Trojans along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Cronin has been a producer, writer and contributor for
``numerous Howard Stern projects,'' so at least you know where this
show is going.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, ``The X Show'' understands the male mind. It has
a bulldog for a mascot. It has aggro-male sports commentator Jim
Rome as a special correspondent. It will use Perfect 10 magazine
(for those who don't need fake breasts) model of the year Ashley
Degenford in a variety of ways. For instance, the show's unofficial
motto is ``total honesty and no male models.''
</P>
<P>
   So during the fashion segments, Degenford _ and other Perfect 10
talent _ will model suits, ties, underwear, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Degenford, in fact, has been dubbed the show's
``lingerie-wearing movie premiere and red-carpet- event
correspondent.'' Basically, she'll be an ``Entertainment
Tonight''-style reporter, only with less clothing.
</P>
<P>
   On ``The X Show'' there will be weekly ``Pretty Girl;; pageants,
culling nonpro models from the ranks of everyday female workers _
such as ``masseuses, latte makers and more.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, promises the network, is only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   But the series that really helped define this genre is Comedy
Central's ``The Man Show,'' which debuts June 16 following ``South
Park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Show'' is described as ``an unapologetic look at
things men like, do and think.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, ``The Man Show'' was developed at ABC, which passed.
It then moved to Fox, which also passed. Finally, Comedy Central
revamped the concept and turned ``The Man Show'' into a weekly,
30-minute tribute to testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   Co-hosted by Jimmy Kimmel (who co-hosts ``Win Ben Stein's
Money,'' the channel's entertaining game show) and Adam Carolla
(who co-hosts MTV's extremely popular ``Loveline''), ``The Man
Show'' is the most blatantly ironic take on the Alpha Male trend.
</P>
<P>
   It says, with a wink, leer and a flex of the bicep, that, hey,
we get it, this is just us goofing on Oprah and Her Lot. Each
episode starts with a ``Manologue.'' There is sketch comedy. There
are celebrity guests. There are _ of course _ man-on-the-street
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the Juggy Dance Squad.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case that concept needs explaining, a word often used in
association with the Juggy Dance Squad is ``bodacious.'' They are
fueled by the sounds of a man called The Fox, who guzzles beer,
sings and plays the piano. The audience is fueled by loads of beer
_ dispensed by the lovely Juggy Dance Squad.
</P>
<P>
   Recurring segments include ``Man-O-Vations'' (all the great
things made for men, such as WWF books on tape, the alcho-derm
patch, etc.); ``Household Hints From Adult Film Stars'' (no,
really); ``Movies Men Don't Want to See,'' and ``Father and Son
with Jimmy and Kevin Kimmel,'' with dad telling little 5-year-old
Kevin ``the importance of ESPN'' and when to double down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Man Show'' was created by Stone Stanley Productions, which
does ``Loveline'' and another man-attracting offering for FX called
``Bobcat's Big Ass Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable is the home of these shows because it can target niches
almost without risk. Any audience is good audience, but all the
better if you can get stupid or ironic enough to latch on to males.
In the broadcast network universe a gender-equal approach is almost
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's one network daring to seek, almost exclusively,
males. And that's UPN, not exactly known for brilliant strategies
in its short existence. Still, as the country's sixth network and
with carte blanche to create an identity, UPN has probably wisely
gone for males. It has lower overhead, and if it can get the
desired demographic to advertisers, it doesn't have to beat CBS for
total viewers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
