<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      06-01 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE NIGHT INSPECTOR &QL; 
 &UR; Frederick Busch (Harmony, $23)
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of this novel, set in New York City in 1867, is
William Bartholomew, a former Union sniper who was maimed when his
rifle exploded in his face during the Civil War. He covers his
disfigurement with a pasteboard mask, but there's little else
hidden in this grim, atmospheric story that weaves postwar history
with the author's imaginings about the people with whom Bartholomew
associates. One of them is Herman Melville, whose books ``The
Whale'' and ``The Ambiguities'' Bartholomew has read. Now,
Melville's writing career is lagging and he works as a customs
inspector. Bartholomew first approaches him in an eatery, and as
they talk, Melville becomes fascinated with the mask, as
Bartholomew knows he must _ after all, he says, Melville wrote
about ``men who struck through the mask or curtain or surface of
things not to do harm by the striking per se, but to learn what lay
on the other side.'' With Bartholomew, Melville and other
characters, Busch (``Girl''s) builds a story around violent
memories of the war and an attempt to rescue ``the last crop of
slavery,'' a group of children held in Florida. The novel closes
with Bartholomew attending a reading by Charles Dickens, whose
world Busch imagined in his 1978 novel, ``The Mutual Friend.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A MAN'S TURF: THE PERFECT LAWN &QL; 
 &UR; Warren Schultz (Potter, $35)
</P>
<P>
   ``And God said, Let the Earth bring forth grass ''.`` .''``
.''`` and the Earth brought forth grass ''.`` .''`` .''``''
(Genesis 1:11-12). This book, an obvious Father's Day ploy, is full
of pictures of grass so green you have to squint when you look at
it. There are other photos that aren't so easy to explain, like the
one of a shirtless Humphrey Bogart raking what looks to be a pile
of dead weeds across a patch of dirt. We thought this might
symbolize (begin itals) failed (end itals) grass, but as we read
along we realized that it was the manliness of the raker Schultz
was trying to point out. And point it out he does, again and again,
without a notion of how silly he sounds. ``Is a man ever more of a
man than when he's standing, hose in hand, on his own front lawn as
the air cools on a summer evening?'' he asks. We are not making
this up. He includes tips on growing different grasses, the rules
of mowing, close-up views of sprinklers and weeds, and a picture of
helmet-clad lawn-mower racers who ``put their manhood on the line
and raise the fun of mowing to a new level.'' Happy Father's Day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SHIP OF GOLD IN THE DEEP BLUE SEA &QL; 
 &UR; Gary Kinder (Vintage, $14)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is Kinder's marvelous account of treasure
hunter Tommy Thompson's efforts to find and recover the cargo of
the paddle steamer Central America, which sank in the Atlantic
Ocean in 1857, taking with it hundreds of passengers and a fortune
from the California gold fields. The book begins with a narrative
account of the sinking of the Central America, the tense and
poignant story of a brave captain, his terrified passengers and
crew, and their efforts to survive a raging storm at sea. From
there, Kinder leaps ahead more than 100 years to the odd group of
men, lead by the eccentric Thompson, who went searching for the
wreck under 8,000 feet of water off South Carolina. Kinder drew
from survivors' accounts for chapters on the sinking of the ship,
and from Thompson's sonar and at-sea logs for passages on the
search and on confrontations at sea with other treasure hunters who
wanted the gold for themselves. Kinder also describes the
cutting-edge technology Thompson used to recover the gold, and the
legal maneuvers through which he claimed the right to salvage it.
This is a suspense-filled adventure story, and Kinder does a superb
job of telling it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; 100 BOOTS &QL; 
 &UR; Eleanor Antin (Running, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   They are a collective presence to Antin, these boots _ she
refers to them as ``he.'' In 1970, she was a frustrated artist
trying to figure out how to show her work to people without
depending on the white walls of the New York galleries. Then she
hit upon an idea that could be had for the price of a postcard and
a 6-cent stamp. She would find a hero _ she envisioned an outsider
like Don Quixote _ who could carry a long, narrative work of art
that she would send out through the mail. The boots themselves came
to her in a dream, and the next day, she went to an Army-Navy store
and bought them: 100 black, rubber boots. The first postcard, which
went out to about 1,000 artists, writers, critics, museums,
galleries, universities, libraries and other unsuspecting
recipients, was mailed on March 15, 1971, and was called ``100
Boots Facing the Sea'' _ it's on the cover of this book. The next
was ``100 Boots on the Way to Church,'' then ``100 Boots at the
Bank,'' and so on. Antin's address was on the cards, and some
people wrote back (a few asked her to leave them alone). All
together, there were 51 postcards mailed over more than two years _
the last was ``100 Boots Go on Vacation'' on July 9, 1973. The
mailings were so successful that the boots appeared at the Museum
of Modern Art for two months before the series ended. This book
contains all 51 postcards. If you like it, go to a used-book store
and look for an even more delightful book called ``The Red Couch,''
by photographers Kevin Clarke and Horst Wackerbarth (with brief
text by William Least Heat-Moon). &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Reach Correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson &LR; worldnet.att.net) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
