<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8285 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FT30.PEARL-LADN     06-01 1843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FT30.PEARL-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Runs with PEARL-GO box)  
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Frank Hartwell was in a cheerful mood as he finished
his rounds as a tour guide on the USS Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? He could personally share in the collective pride
over Mighty Mo, one of America's most celebrated warships.
Hartwell, who joined the Navy while his family was living in Santa
Monica, had been assigned to the destroyer Satterlee during World
War II, and had guarded the Missouri's flank during the furious
battles of Iwo Jima and Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had picket duty. We formed the protection ring around
her,'' Hartwell said. He laughed. ``In other words, we were
expendable. Our job was to keep the kamikazes (Japanese suicide
bombers) off the big ships.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he stood just a few feet from a plaque on the Missouri's
deck that commemorates the exact spot where Japan signed a
surrender document in September 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The sun was shining here in Hawaii. Douglas MacArthur's voice,
recorded at the surrender ceremony, boomed from a loudspeaker
overhead: ``May God preserve it ... These proceedings are closed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hartwell's enjoyment of the moment was short-lived, as is
the case with most visitors to the Missouri, which has tied up in
Pearl Harbor since the end of January. Even on these decks, the eye
is naturally drawn forward, to a point just off the bow, where the
gleaming white USS Arizona Memorial lies silently in the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've visited it nine times,'' Hartwell said. ``I can't help
choking up every time, seeing those 1,177 names. It just grabs
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two memorials, in unique juxtaposition, seize
visitors in radically different ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona is a symbol of the start of America's war in the
Pacific. In Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941, it was
torn apart when a bomb from overhead crashed into an ammunition
magazine, sending the battleship to the harbor floor in less than
nine minutes. Its loss of 1,177 crewmen _ 77 percent of the 1,535
men assigned to the ship at the time _ constitutes the single
greatest naval disaster in American history.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri, with its famous Surrender Deck, represents the
other bookend of World War II _ its conclusion. And its history is
as storied as the Arizona's is tragic. The Missouri, whose hull was
laid in 1941, was in action as recently as 1991, when its tomahawk
missiles pounded Iraqi positions in Kuwait and Baghdad during
Operation Desert Storm.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri was decommissioned the next year (the second time
in its history it had been mothballed) and ultimately came to rest
here as a kind of museum at anchor. As if in a symbolically
protective gesture, the Missouri's famed 16-inch guns point
directly over the top of the Arizona, which lies submerged a few
hundred feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The Mighty Mo has already proven to be an irresistible lure for
tourists stopping in to see the Arizona. In its first two months
here, it drew 88,852 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Its contrasts with the Arizona extend well beyond the histories
of the two ships. The USS Arizona Memorial is administered by the
National Park Service, and its documentary film, boat ride into the
harbor and visit to the memorial are all provided at no cost. The
Battleship Missouri Memorial is maintained by the private USS
Missouri Memorial Association, and it charges adults anywhere from
$10 for general admission to $29 for a deluxe tour.
</P>
<P>
   As a tourist attraction, the Missouri is very much in a state of
evolution. ``Since opening (it), we've found that visitors are
fascinated about seeing its interior and how sailors lived and
worked,'' said Don Hess, the memorial's vice president of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate the curiosity, the memorial association is
gradually making over various rooms in the ship as exhibits in an
attempt to show how they were used.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, visitors can peek in on an officer's stateroom and
the ward room, and wander through the bridge. As an inducement to
pop for the higher-priced tour, the ship recently opened its combat
engagement center _ the ship's nerve center during an attack _ to
its Signature Tour patrons only.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, there are further plans to open the
mess deck and crew berthing area. ``If you come back a year from
now, there will be so much more open,'' said spokesman Patrick
Dugan. ``We just need time to get it all ready. It came into Hawaii
on Father's Day last year, and it needed some work. It was rusty.
It needed a paint job. A lot of work was done before its grand
opening in January.''
</P>
<P>
   Even for the standard admission _ $10 for adults, $6 for
children ages 4 to 12 _ the Missouri is well worth the visit.
</P>
<P>
   It's intriguing to walk through the area of the Surrender Deck,
where black-and-white photos of the event are displayed and
MacArthur's voice transports you back into history.
</P>
<P>
   Another visitors' favorite: the 16-inch guns, which stretch out
ominously along the forward deck. They were capable of firing
2,000-pound shells for distances of 20 miles or more. Imagine a Geo
Metro being tossed from Catalina Island and taking out the Ports o'
Call restaurant in San Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Missouri are collected at a ticket booth next to
the USS Arizona Memorial parking lot, then ferried over the bridge
to Ford Island on open-air trolleys.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, the ship already shows signs of being
cluttered up with tourist trappings. The pier alongside it, for
example, has become home to all manner of military vehicles (many
draped with camouflage netting) that have absolutely nothing to do
with naval warfare.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona, by contrast, is maintaining a longstanding
tradition of quiet dignity. At this hallowed site, anything more
would be crass.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors are first given a priority number. It is essential:
Some 1.5 million people visit this park every year, with the summer
months experiencing the greatest crush.
</P>
<P>
   When your number is called, you file into a theater to watch a
brief documentary film. Mercifully, the lights are dimmed for this
presentation; many visitors, particularly those who are old enough
to have lived through Pearl Harbor and the horrors of the war, dab
at their eyes as details of the Arizona's demise are presented.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unbelievably lucky shot, really. A Japanese plane
dropped a 1,760-pound armor-piercing bomb that landed alongside the
second turret, crashed through four decks and detonated in the
ship's forward ammunition magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The concussion, according to Walter Lord's 1957 best seller
``Day of Infamy,'' was more like a ``whoom'' than a ``bang,'' but
it was so great that it stalled the engine of a pickup truck being
driven along Ford Island by an aviation ordnance man.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion literally blew off the Arizona's bow and ignited
fires that burned for 2 1/2 days. In less than nine minutes, the
ship was at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was well-timed, because seven U.S. battleships were
lined up like cars at a toll booth along the east side of Ford
Island: the Nevada, Arizona, Tennessee, West Virginia, Maryland,
Oklahoma and California. (Today, the Missouri is tied up roughly
where the Maryland and Oklahoma sat side by side.)
</P>
<P>
   The element of surprise in the attack was also extreme. U.S.
practice for an attack had been so extensive that in the early
stages the presumption was widespread _ from lowest rank to highest
_ that this was just another drill. According to Lord's book, one
commander even assumed that a diving plane was some hot-dogging
U.S. aviator, and tried to get the number on the plane to report
him.
</P>
<P>
   Early warning systems were fairly primitive in that day, too,
but one was working fine. The story of its operation is one of the
most wrenching of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   At a radar placement near Kahuku on Oahu's north shore, the
screen suddenly filled with blips just after 7 a.m. _ nearly an
hour before the attack would begin. The operators had picked up the
first wave of Japanese attack planes, launched from aircraft
carriers 230 miles to the north of the island. But when the
operators, both privates, breathlessly relayed their news to an
Army lieutenant at Fort Shafter on the western outskirts of
Honolulu, the lieutenant surmised that the they'd merely picked up
a cluster of inbound U.S. planes and told them, ``Look, don't worry
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese arrived at Pearl Harbor about a half hour later,
and carried out their two-hour attack nearly without challenge.
</P>
<P>
   As devastating as the attack was, it could have been much worse.
The American fleet of aircraft carriers was out to sea at the time,
and it would prove to be a key component of the war in the Pacific.
Also, while the attack pilots concentrated on the ships in the
harbor, they ignored the repair and construction facilities, the
fuel storage tanks and the submarine base.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the U.S. was able to recover rather quickly. In fact,
although Battleship Row endured the brunt of the attack, five of
the seven ships were salvaged and were back in action during the
war. Only two were utter losses: the Oklahoma, which capsized, and
the Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Today, visitors assemble on a sun-washed dock to climb into the
launch that will carry them to the USS Arizona Memorial. The boat
is manned by young sailors in crisp white uniforms. It's impossible
to look at them and not think of their Navy forebears, slowly
stirring on a Sunday morning 58 years ago, oblivious to the sudden
tragedy that was about to be visited on them from high overhead.
</P>
<P>
   At the memorial itself, conversation tends to be hushed. The
184-foot slab of concrete spans the midsection of the ship, and the
hulk lies just inches below the surface of the water, an aft turret
and other rusted remnants protruding here and there. Many of the
crewmen remain entombed below.
</P>
<P>
   In the shrine room, at the end closest to Ford Island, a marble
wall contains the names of the ship's 1,177 dead _ which represent
more than half of the 2,340 military deaths suffered in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   It's a moving experience to survey the names, all the more so if
you've heard a personal remembrance.
</P>
<P>
   My dad used to play baseball in Princeville, Ill., with one of
these guys. Jack Sniff. Said to be a pretty good pitcher as a
teen-ager before duty called. And there he is, listed among the
U.S. Marines who were assigned to the Arizona: J.B. Sniff, CPL.
</P>
<P>
   Later, out on the center section of the memorial, park ranger
Mary Kalishevich indicated a slick of oil near the protruding
turret. No, she says, that did not come from the launch that
brought us out here. It still gurgles forth from this sunken ship,
all these years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea how much oil was on the ship when she was
sunk,'' Kalishevich said, ``and we have no idea how much oil is
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a myth out here _ that when the last survivor dies,
she will stop crying tears of oil for her crewmen to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
