<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, June 2,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WOMEN _ KUKES, Albania _ Vjollca Lushnaj witnessed
profound joy and horror in a single night. Her daughter was born in
a Kosovo hospital amid Serb attacks and NATO bombs. Three days
later, she was trudging across the border of Albania, a new refugee
and new mother, husband-less after he decided to remain behind to
fight with the Kosovo Liberation Army. Most of the Kosovo refugees
are women and children, as most families are without the men. A
look at how the mothers of Kosovo are coping, and the help they
need. (Holmes, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION _ Setup story for Tuesday's South African
election, in which Nelson Mandela is appealing to whites to
``become part of the majority'' and support his heavily favored
African National Congress in this week's national election.
(Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WOMEN _ WASHINGTON _ Women have always strongly supported
Al Gore in his quest for office, and a new group of female
supporters is being formed Tuesday with the backing of first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton. But will Gore's backing of the Kosovo war
erode that support? (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The federal antitrust trial against
Microsoft Corp. resumes after a three-month break. (Glass, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OKEFENOKEE-FIRES _ Wildfires continue to grow in a remote area
of the Okefenokee Swamp in Florida and Georgia. The fires had
spread to 50,000 acres and moved into Georgia on Sunday. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH LOCATOR MAP.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-HEARING _ CONYERS, Ga. _ A judge will decide today
whether T.J. Solomon should be tried as an adult fir shooting six
of his Heritage High School Classmates. The community is divided on
the issue. Some say let the juvenile justice system work; let
Solomon be rehabilitated. Others say he should be tried as an adult
because he committed adult crimes. (Stanford, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LIGHTHOUSE _ CAPE HATTERAS, N.C. _ Final preparations for the
mid-June move of the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse are under way. We
report on Tuesday's news conference. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATF-PIPEBOMBS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The pipe bomb, a simple
explosive device made from readily available household items and
some gunpowder, suddenly has the nation's attention. The basic
directions for making a pipe bomb are available in public libraries
and on the Internet, and it seems their use is escalating with each
frightful news report. ``Everyone's paying more attention,'' said
John D'Angelo, a spokesman with the Federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms in Washington. But, he said, ``Pipe bomb
incidents happen all the time. I think the stats show there really
hasn't been a huge increase.'' (Moffett and Scharnhorst, Palm Beach
Post) 36. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-STUDY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ More than 400,000 children and
250,000 adults lost health insurance in 1997 because welfare reform
laws disqualified them for Medicaid coverage, Families USA reports
in the first national study to correlate welfare reform with health
coverage. Most of the children should not have lost Medicaid
coverage, but few states have taken significant advantage of
federal laws and dollars to expand Medicaid eligibility for
low-wage working families and reach those who are eligible, says
the national health consumer group's report, ``Losing Health
Insurance: The Unintended Consequences of Welfare Reform.'' (Lamb,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-POLLUTION-COMPROMISE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush,
his allies in the Texas Legislature and industry groups did not get
exactly what they wanted in a bill to reduce air pollution from
older industrial plants. The governor, who led the charge for a
program that was virtually all carrot, wound up with one that
includes a stick. Environmental activists and their legislative
allies wanted a program that was virtually all stick. But
confronted with the political reality of a popular governor and a
conservative Legislature, they had to settle for much less.
(Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
