<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, June 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-ISLAND (Vozrozhdeniye Island, Uzbekistan) _ In the
spring of 1988, Soviet germ scientists secretly transferred
hundreds of tons of anthrax bacteria _ enough to destroy the world
many times over _ almost a thousand miles to this remote island in
the heart of the inland Aral Sea, according to American and Central
Asian officials. Here Russian soldiers dug huge pits and poured the
sludge into the ground, burying the germs and, Moscow hoped, a
grave political threat. Today, Vozrozhdeniye Island _ or
Renaissance Island, as it translates from the Russian _ is the
world's largest anthrax burial ground. American military scientists
and intelligence experts who have secretly been traveling here for
the past four years to survey the island and take samples of the
buried bacteria have discovered that some of the anthrax spores are
still alive _ and potentially deadly. By Judy Miller.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO military planners heard
Tuesday how many troops and tanks the allies and other countries
would provide for the beefed-up, 45,000-strong peacekeeping force
planned for Kosovo if diplomacy brings a settlement there. But
allied officials said Russia, a key diplomatic player, was keeping
its distance. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY (Berlin) _ Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin
and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, the European Union's envoy,
met Tuesday with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and
German Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder on Kosovo. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Three weeks after Russia and the
world's seven richest nations agreed to set off on a joint quest
for peace in Yugoslavia, both Russia and its Western partners are
still at a loss to define Moscow's role in the process. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ Developments in Kosovo policy. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   The Times is also working on developments out of Serbia; Elie
Wiesel's visit to refugee camps in Skopje, Macedonia; and NATO
bombs falling inside Albania.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Final
curtain-raiser on the South African election on Wednesday: how race
has defined the election. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-BOTHA (Cape Town, South Africa) _ An appeals court
Tuesday set aside the contempt conviction of former President P.W.
Botha for refusing to appear before the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission, which is investigating the crimes of the apartheid era.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO (Washington) _ The U.S. government's dissatisfaction
with how Mexico investigated accusations of drug corruption
involving President Ernesto Zedillo's closest aide reflects the
mistrust that continues to shape the two governments' dealings on
matters of criminal justice. Officials say it also reflects the
difficulty that Washington continues to have in handling reports of
corruption that involve high-level Mexican officials. By Tim
Golden.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Serpang, Indonesia) _ One year after a
paroxysm of rioting in which ethnic Chinese were the targets of
widespread vandalism, arson and rape, Chinese all across the
country have been preparing for new attacks before next Monday's
general election. But something utterly unexpected has happened.
The election campaign, in most parts of the country, has so far
been mainly peaceful. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Istanbul) _ When the Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan finished his extraordinary testimony on the opening
day of his treason trial Monday, he left many Turks and Kurds dazed
and surprised. His abject apology for years of war and avowed
determination to re-invent himself as a democrat seemed dubious but
also tantalizing. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CORSICA-PREFECT (Ajaccio, Corsica) _ French politicians of all
factions were stunned by the first ever arrest of a serving
prefect, France's top official on this Mediterranean island. The
arrest has set off something of a national crisis, even wiping the
war in Kosovo off the front pages. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DRUG-ENTERPRISE (Washington) _ The Supreme Court ruled
Tuesday that jurors must unanimously agree on three crimes for
conviction on a federal drug law, the continuing criminal
enterprise charge; will serve as roundup. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDIA-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ President Clinton on
Tuesday ordered the Federal Trade Commission and Justice Department
to conduct a study of the marketing of mayhem by Hollywood _ a
month after he ordered the surgeon general to conduct a study of
effects of violence in entertainment on youth. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Washington) _ President Clinton plans to ask
Congress this week to grant temporary ``most favored nation''
status to China, setting the stage for a bitter debate on Capitol
Hill, where lawmakers are angry about the theft of nuclear secrets.
By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-GORE (Washington) _ Hillary Rodham Hillary reaches
out to women voters to support Vide President Al Gore, who lags
behind Gov. George W. Bush of Texas among that group in polls. By
Katharine E. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The Microsoft trial resumed
Tuesday. By Joel Brinkley. (Moving in `f' category code.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-SPARROW (Everglades National Park, Fla.) _ Scientists
say the plight of the threatened Cape Sable Seaside sparrow
reflects the failing health of the Everglades ecosystem, a vast
wetland wilderness splintered by canals and dikes and threatened by
urban development. As Congress, in July, takes up a $7.8 billion
engineering plan to restore the swamplands to ecological health,
some environmentalists and wildlife officials say the sparrow is
the test of whether the plan can succeed. The controversy reflects
how politically complicated and interconnected the problems in the
Everglades are, and how difficult any solution will be. By James C.
McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With a map.
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-TORT-REFORM _ Alabama, where a family who sued over
$1,200 in satellite dish payments won a startling $581 million, is
taking steps to curb the big jury verdicts that have given the
state a reputation for dispensing ``jackpot justice.'' By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL (Littleton, Colo.) _ The backpacks dotting Columbine
High School's hallways have been there since panicked students
abandoned them and ran from gunfire and terror nearly six weeks
ago. Tuesday, most of the nearly 2,000 students and faculty members
were to return for the first time and retrieve items they left
behind April 20, when they ran from the building as Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold opened fire. By Mindy Sink.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLEMENT-STUDY (Undated) _ Androstenedione, the supplement
taken to boost athletic performance, did not enhance
muscle-building or increase testosterone in the blood but appeared
to produce adverse health effects in a small study of young men,
published in the latest issue of The Journal of the American
Medical Association. By Kenneth B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ ``Liberties,'' by Maureen Dowd.
</P>
