<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8307 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-     06-01 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION EAGER TO TELL FORT CHADBOURNE'S STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRONTE, Texas _ Just off U.S. 277, about 11 miles northeast of
this West Texas town, a part of Texas history is crumbling away
amid prickly pear cactus, spreading mesquites and a thumping oil
well pump.
</P>
<P>
   It is Fort Chadbourne, one of a line of U.S. forts built in the
mid-1800s to protect the settlers from angry Comanches and to halt
the Comanches' traditional trek through the West Texas plains into
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of the state's history, but it doesn't belong to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1852, Chadbourne was used primarily to defend a stop on
the Butterfield Overland Mail route from 1858 to 1861. The fort was
surrendered to Confederate Col. Henry E. McCulloch in February
1861. The Texas Militia occupied the fort for a while, and then
U.S. troops moved back in after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't linger.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of water and wood made it an almost impossible place to
maintain, and the army moved out. Some historians say the fort was
abandoned in 1868; others say they stayed until 1873. In either
case, they left the native sandstone buildings to the scorching
West Texas heat and winds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sitting on a small hillside, only a few remnants of the old
fort remain. A long barracks is still discernible. The roof is long
gone and cactus and cedars have sprouted up in what were once
living quarters for A and K companies of the 8th U.S. Infantry.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby are an officers quarters, a small hospital and a house
that was built for Robert E. Lee. He was to serve as an officer at
the small fort, but by the time the house was prepared, he received
orders to go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The fort is on private property now and has been since 1876,
when Garland G. Odom established the Odom Luckett Land and
Livestock Co. on more than 100,000 acres of West Texas. The fort
was his first headquarters and has remained in the same family all
these years.
</P>
<P>
   Garland Richards, who grew up playing on the crumbling fort, is
the current owner, and he is trying to save what is left. He and
his family have established the Fort Chadbourne Foundation and have
a number of fund-raisers planned. They hope to preserve the
decaying buildings, as well as construct a museum and visitor's
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offered this fort to Texas Parks and Wildlife Department
about 20 years ago,'' Richards said. ``We thought they were going
to take it, but one afternoon they called and said they couldn't do
it. They didn't have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards' family has given tours of the fort since 1969. Every
school bus in the surrounding counties has made the trip up the
winding asphalt drive that runs through the fort.
</P>
<P>
   Richards has collected an array of artifacts from the fort area
and is more than willing to share them with interested visitors.
Still, there is no formal museum, no place for visitors to read
about the fort, nothing in the way of available facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders from nearby Abilene, Winters, Bronte and other
West Texas towns serve as board members on the foundation. They
believe they can raise the money needed to save the fort and turn
it into an educational tourist stop.
</P>
<P>
   The first public effort will be June 26, when the Bronte Chamber
of Commerce sponsors Fort Chadbourne Day, a day of tours, free
beans and cornbread and a free dance. Donations will be accepted.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact the foundation at (915) 743-2555.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422 or e-mail: Artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
