<P>
   HALAL-BUTCHERS (New York) _ In almost any neighborhood in
America where Muslims make their home, halal meat shops are the new
butchers in an old-fashioned way. To non-Muslims the shops can be
mysterious, even intimidating. But to others they are a happy
addition to the checkerboard of tiny, specialty food shops _ places
with impeccable meat and intensely personal service. Even as the
production of meat nationwide becomes increasingly industrialized,
analysts say that Halal meat is nevertheless the fastest growing
style of specialty butchering in the country. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-CAKES (New York) _ When a woman walked into Magnificent
Confections a few weeks ago, she wanted a simple cake for her son's
30th birthday. But by the end of her visit, she had ordered a white
sculpted elephant, with it's trunk turned up, dressed with jewelry.
``She got obsessed,'' said Lege Sulit, a co-owner of Magnificent
Confections, a tiny bakery on the Upper East Side. But in New York
today, she isn't alone in her obsession. The party cake has become
an over-the-top symbol of creativity and, some would say,
competitive excess. By Monique Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUE-SAUCE (Undated) _ Beyond the basic barbecue sauce. By
Steven Raichlen. With recipes.
</P>
