<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-ACTIVIST-BOS &LR;      06-01 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ACTIVIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB ACTIVIST DEFIES BOMBING TO RECORD ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ For the last two months, just about everyone who
could get out of Kosovo did.
</P>
<P>
   But Natasha Kandic keeps going back.
</P>
<P>
   As director of the Belgrade-based Humanitarian Law Center, she
has returned repeatedly to Kosovo, defying NATO's bombs and
Slobodan Milosevic's police, to check on friends and gather
firsthand accounts of human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   With most major roads destroyed, she negotiates the twisting,
narrow back roads of Kosovo, her files stuffed into a black canvas
bag with ``Codman Square Health Center'' stamped on it, a gift
received during a visit to Boston last year.
</P>
<P>
   Her stories of atrocities, in dry, straightforward prose that is
chilling in its spareness, may later be included in submissions to
the International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia at
The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few human rights activists to get inside Kosovo,
Kandic is even more unusual in that she is a Serb. Sitting at an
outdoor cafe in the Yugoslav capital, the 50-year-old shrugs off
her unusual background.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many Serbs interested in human rights,'' she said.
``You just don't hear about them.''
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that Serb forces have been accused of the
lion's share of human rights abuses in Kosovo that have accompanied
the forced explusion of nearly 1 million ethnic Albanians from the
province. But she expressed frustration that Serb authorities have
refused to give her access to areas where NATO has bombed
civilians. She wants to document atrocities by NATO, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian government has said that the ethnic Albanians who
fled Kosovo did so to escape NATO's bombing. She is one of the few
here publicly willing to call that story ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of Albanians were expelled, by orders,'' she
said. ``Some left on their own. The official statements that
Albanian refugees are fleeing NATO bombardment are stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Kandic provides a perspective lacking in most contemporary
accounts of what is happening in Kosovo. For example, she said that
some Serbs have risked their lives to protect Albanian friends and
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   She said that witness accounts are consistent in blaming Serb
paramilitary units and police for most acts of terror. She said
that soldiers from the Yugoslav Army, most of them conscripts from
towns and villages in southern Serbia, have by and large behaved
better than the paramilitary units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Albanians have told me that the Yugoslav Army were
sometimes kind to them, that the soldiers sometimes gave them food,
that some of the soldiers were crying, seeing the condition of the
children,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kandic considered it crucial not to lump all Serbs together. She
is dedicated to the principle that all human life is sacred, and
that to dehumanize any segment of the population, be it Albanian or
Serb, inevitably leads to conflict.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after NATO began bombing Yugoslavia, and Serb forces
began the wholesale explusion of ethnic Albanians from their homes,
Kandic drove into Pristina, the capital of Kosovo. She saw Serbs
and Albanians standing side by side, guarding the entrance to their
apartment building next door to her office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had agreed that Serbs would defend Albanians from the
police, the Albanians would defend the Serbs from the KLA and all
would defend themselves from paramilitaries,'' she said. Such
solidarity is rare in the countryside, but not in Pristina, she
said. (The KLA is the acronym for the Kosovo Liberation Army.)
</P>
<P>
   Kandic is well-known for her fearlessness. After her friend and
colleague, the human rights lawyer Bajram Keljmendi, was murdered
near Pristina the day after NATO began bombing, Kandic went looking
for Fehmi Agani, a 66-year-old sociology professor and human rights
activist. As a member of the Albanian delegation at the failed
peace talks in France, Agani was at risk for assassination, she
believed. He was later found murdered.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to Agani's house, Kandic's car was stopped by police.
When the commanding officer found out two of Kandic's companions
were Albanian, he ordered them out of the car. When Kandic
protested, the police officer ordered her back into the car, then
walked over and slammed the car door on her legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said Serbia is being ruined by Serbs like me,'' she
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   It is a charge she has heard before, that she is a traitor, that
she is a collaborator with the Americans and Western Europeans who
want to impose their will on Serbia. Kandic, however, said the
adoption and application of human rights laws will bring about a
more stable, prosperous Yugoslavia, one that would be welcomed back
into the international community, improving the quality of life for
all its 10 million citizens, Serbs and minorities alike.
</P>
<P>
   But in a society where even the most tepid criticism of the
status quo is treated as treason by the government, Kandic is
regularly marginalized. Anatella Riha, who worked as a researcher
for Kandic for three years, said she often hears people dismiss
Kandic as a self-loathing Serb.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say she hates Serbs. I don't think she does,'' said
Riha. ``I think she believes that freedom of the press, freedom of
movement and speech, all these human rights help Serbs as much as
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kandic's name is brought up in conversation here in cafes
or government buildings, the word ``crazy'' is often used, as a
term of both endearment and derision.
</P>
<P>
   Riha, who interviewed rape victims in Bosnia as part of her work
for Kandic, suggested that ``you have to be a little crazy to do
this job in this place. I think Natasha is crazy in a good way. I
think she is very brave.''
</P>
<P>
   Surviving on the generosity of private donors, and laboring
under a government that has empowered itself to shut down any
organization it deems subversive, Kandic's office has compiled
evidence of war crimes in Bosnia and Croatia, where Serbs were both
victims and perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   Some of her stories capture the venal brutality of Kosovo. A
woman she interviewed in a refugee camp in Montenegro told how some
local men and her son, Nezvat, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men in uniforms and caps on their heads came into their
yard,'' Kandic recounted in one of her memos. ``They seemed to be
drunk and shouted and cursed. They told her she would not be
killed, that they would let her live so she would pine for her dead
son. They killed the men with knives. Nezvat bled to death in his
mother's arms.''
</P>
<P>
   She then reads from an account given to her by an Albanian man
who fled Pec after the bombing started. Serb forces burst into the
man's home and shouted, ``You have one minute to leave!''
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter-in-law put her baby in the cradle, and then one of
the uniformed men kicked it so hard that the baby fell out of the
cradle and started to scream,'' the man told Kandic.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them ordered my son Blerim to stay behind. My son
remained silent, but my wife and I started to cry and plead with
them to let us stay, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a rifle pointed at Blerim's temple. I tried to go back
and help him, but then I heard a shot and saw Blerim taken up in
the air before he crumpled down in a heap at my father's feet. They
got hold of me, too, but then my wife rushed and took me out of the
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we left the room we heard three more shots. I heard them
shouting that we should go to Clinton. Blerim's body was left
behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
