<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-01 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BOOST FOR NATO 
</HEADLINE>
   (w and k coding.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Thank you, Joschka Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   The German foreign minister has performed an extremely useful
service by showing that his government's allegedly flat-out
opposition to using ground troops in Kosovo is not what it seems.
And Fischer has provided fresh evidence of the one development
since the air campaign began two months ago that has surprised both
the Serbs and most Western analysts: the relentless unity of NATO
to see this horror end on its terms.
</P>
<P>
   As a critical month begins, Fischer made it clear what use of
ground troops Chancellor Walter Schroeder called ``unthinkable''
and what use of them might be anything but that.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings here with US officials, Fischer stressed that his
boss was referring to a British trial balloon about ground troops
going in before a peace agreement but after Serb forces had been
weakened even more than they already have been by the bombing. That
scenario would put Germany's coalition government in an impossible
bind and create major constitutional problems, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the wrong scenario. What's really going on is an
effort to negotiate an agreement with Russia that would incorporate
NATO's principles in a UN Security Council resolution. That would
be a clear signal to Slobodan Milosevic that he is ``completely
isolated'' _ and, worse, because of the military consequences of a
refusal to comply.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to raise a question of whether Germany would
have a different view about combat troops in such an event. But
nobody asked it until Margaret Warner of ``The NewsHour with Jim
Lehrer'' had the sense to put it to him directly in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a legal standpoint, this would be a quite different
position for us and this would then have political discussion. We
must very carefully go ahead step by step.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, what Schroeder called ``unthinkable'' was more
like a straw man. The much more likely event is a Persian Gulf-like
situation precipitated by a Serb refusal to comply with a UN
resolution. That still leaves the difficult negotiations to produce
such a resolution that have been going on among US Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbot, Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, and
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari on behalf of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some substantial progress,'' he told Warner. ``We
have now reached a door for a peaceful solution. And in the next
days I think it would be very, very important whether we can manage
to get the door open or not.''
</P>
<P>
   If the talks succeed, Fischer sees China's role in the Security
Council as a problem but not an obstacle. His view is that a
solution would not cause ``real problems'' for the
sovereignty-fixated Chinese that would produce a veto. But even as
the diplomacy has intensified, so has the inexorable demonstration
of NATO's united will. In the space of a week, ground forces on
Kosovo's borders have been virtually doubled to a level of 50,000
and the bombing has escalated to include the entire economic
infrastructure of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every day, the will behind this campaign is reinforced by
a conference call linking Fischer with his counterparts here, as
well as in London, Paris, and Rome. The obvious bump ahead is what
to do should the talks with Russia break down, but the key NATO
leaders have not retreated an inch from the insistence that this
mess can only end with the withdrawal of all Serb forces of all
kinds from Kosovo, their replacement with a military force built
around NATO to keep peace, the return of all refugees, and the
re-establishment of an autonomous Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In the current muddle, and with the horror caused by the tiny
number of bombs that miss their targets and kill civilians, it's
understandable that US public opinion is more divided than at the
bombing's commencement. But the polls will respond to developments,
and this is the month when big ones will come almost on top of each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer was the perfect voice to contribute to the debate. He
comes to his job from a lifetime of peace activism, including
opposition to the Cold War's conflicts in Third World proxy states.
But he also has a special empathy with the plight of refugees,
coming from an ethnic German family in Hungary for 200 years that
was kicked out after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The enemy this time, he says, is the ``aggressive nationalism''
that wreaked such havoc and horror in the 1930s and 1940s and
cannot be allowed to take root again _ in the Balkans of all
tinder-box places under the sick banner of some dictator's dream of
a Greater Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the real problem,'' he told Margaret Warner. ``You
have the Greater Albania, you have the Greater Bulgaria _ the
Balkans are full of ``Greaters'' _ and this means bloodshed,
nothing else.'' Stopping it in Kosovo is a challenge that cannot be
avoided or fumbled. And Fischer's important message is that Germany
will be there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
