<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-PAYETTE-BOS &LR;      06-01 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-PAYETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUT CAPTURES ATTENTION OF CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The eyes of Canada are fixed on the stars this week
as a new national hero, Julie Payette, a 35-year-old Montrealer
with an infectious smile, engaging style, and a string of
accomplishments that has given her a reputation as a Renaissance
woman, rides space shuttle Discovery to glory.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually the red-haired astronaut is riding Discovery on a
rather humdrum supply mission to the nascent International Space
Station. Her main job will be replacing a malfunctioning set of
power cells, not the sexiest of space chores.
</P>
<P>
   But don't try telling Canadians there's nothing special about
this jaunt above the atmosphere. This country is in the grip of
``Julie fever,'' burning most intensely in Payette's native Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   She's become a cultural icon, compared not so much to John Glenn
or other space worthies as to pop diva Celine Dion and hockey
legend Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's our most glamorous astronaut. . . . She flies jets,
speaks six languages, and holds two engineering degrees,'' gushed
columnist Margaret Wente in the Globe and Mail newspaper. ``And she
looks terrific in a jumpsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Liftoff from Cape Canaveral was Thursday, and Canada went gaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnifique!'' crowed a Quebec televison newswoman reporting
live from Florida as the space shuttle carrying Payette and her six
fellow astronauts rose atop a flower of flame from the launch pad
at the Kennedy Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   Payette's leap into the celebrity stratosphere is a bit tough to
understand. Seven other Canadians have preceded her into orbit, and
Canadian astronauts have completed more space missions than those
from any other country except the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Payette is not even the first Canadian woman astronaut, an honor
that went to Roberta Bondar in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Payette has captured the popular imagination in a nation
that is seldom given to hero-worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians, suddenly, are genuinely excited about space, and
perhaps that's partly driven by Julie Payette's own huge enthusiasm
and engaging style,'' said John Manley, Canada's minister of
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Astronaut Marc Garneau, the first Canadian in space, said: ``She
has a personality that attracts people, she looks great, and she
speaks well. Plus, she has all those accomplishments.''
</P>
<P>
   Payette's achievements include an engineering degree from McGill
University and a master's degree in applied science from the
University of Toronto. She plays piano at the concert level, can
pipe a sweet tune on the flute, and is described as an exceedingly
gifted soprano, who has sung with the famed Tafelmusik Baroque
Orchestra Choir.
</P>
<P>
   She is fluent in French, English, and Russian and can hold a
conversation in Spanish, Italian, and German.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother always said there's room for improvement,'' Payette
recently told reporters. ``You just have to apply yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   She's an expert scuba diver, earned her wings as a jet pilot
with the Canadian Armed Forces, has designed computer systems for
IBM-Canada, is a former speech researcher for Bell-Northern
Research, and has done work in ``natural language processing,
automatic speech recognition, and the application of interactive
technology to space,'' according to the official biography from the
Canadian Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been afraid of missing the boat, of not being good
enough, afraid of not being able to accomplish what's asked of
me,'' Payette said.
</P>
<P>
   Also: She plays racquetball and squash with a savagery that
frightens her male spacemates. ``You don't want to challenge Julie
to any physical sport,'' said Chris Hadfield, another Canadian
astronaut. ``She'll demolish you.''
</P>
<P>
   As a girl, Payette briefly pondered a career as a flight
attendant. However, inspired by the Apollo missions _ along with a
prepubescent crush on astronaut Neil Armstrong, whose photo was
taped to her bedroom door _ she finally set her sights a few
hundred miles higher.
</P>
<P>
   She was seriously bitten by the space bug at around age 8,
immersing herself in science magazines and announcing to her family
that someday she was going to tumble about in zero gravity. But she
didn't seriously seek to try on a spacesuit until 1992, when she
heard that the Canadian Space Agency was recruiting its second
class of astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   She's been a publicity deliverance for Canada's space program
and the US National Aeronautics and Space Administration. ``I don't
think there's anyone quite like Julie either in Canada or the US,''
said NASA head Dan Goldin.
</P>
<P>
   She's happy to share her professional life, but can be extremely
reticent to discuss anything personal. At the news conference in
August announcing the flight, she refused to disclose her marital
status.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a person sans histoire,'' she told reporters, showing a
rather Gallic flair for drama. The Canadian Space Agency later
confirmed she is wed to Montreal engineer Francois Brisette.
</P>
<P>
   In Quebec, she's become so famous that French-language media
seldom bother using her surname: ``Julie En Orbite!'' proclaimed
Journal de Montreal on Friday in the monster headline imposed on
photographs covering the front page. Quebec aired more-or-less
nonstop coverage the day of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Quebec's Parti Quebecois, committed to separatism and officially
disdainful of all things Canadian, ignored the fact that Payette
proudly wears the Maple Leaf emblem on her arm, issuing an official
resolution in the provincial legislature wishing her godspeed and
safe return.
</P>
<P>
   But she's not simply a Quebecois phenomenon. From Newfoundland
to British Columbia, Juliemania has gripped Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The country's media, which hitherto have shown little interest
in celestial exploration, have lately been deluging Canadians with
weighty articles and television looks at whither the space program
and at what cost. Canada pumps $245 million a year into its space
agency and has pledged $1 billion over the next two decades toward
construction of the International Space Station. Such figures
usually appall Canadian commentators, if they bother to comment at
all. But since Payette hopped aboard, the money has mostly been
portrayed as well spent.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been breathless features about Julie's menu in
space (macaroni and cheese, bean-and-mushroom ratatouille, lots of
vitamins) and what CDs will accompany her journey (Celine Dion,
Sarah McLachlan, and choir music). Other articles have been
dedicated to the intricacies of Julie's high-tech space toilet and
analyses of how Julie will snuggle into her space sleeping bag.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the attention of Canada was riveted when Payette
issued her official au revoir on videotape shortly before blasting
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you feel some of the specialness that's in the air, the
magic of the moment, as I do,'' she said. ``My friends, I'm nothing
without you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
