<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8350 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WETLANDS-ART-BOS &LR;      06-01 1822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WETLANDS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE FIGHTS TO TURN TIDE ON VANISHING WETLANDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A backhoe operator digs delicate tidal pools in the mud
next to a former roadhouse in Newburyport, Mass., trying to create
an oasis for egrets and other shorebirds just beyond the parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Workers plant green clumps of marsh grass along the Neponset
River near Boston, turning part of an old drive-in site into a
landscape that 17th-century Puritans would have recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod National Seashore officials flood a dried-out marsh
next to Provincetown's airport, drowning the reeds that moved in
after the marsh was drained in a misguided attempt to kill
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   After centuries of watching much of nature's most valuable real
estate disappear beneath cities, farms and other human
constructions, Massachusetts is taking a national lead in fighting
back. Across the state, government agencies and private groups are
restoring swamps and marshes, investing millions to recreate
terrain that our forebears regarded as wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to ... undo past damage is just terribly
exciting,'' said Christy Foote-Smith, chief of the state's Wetlands
Restoration and Banking Program, which is helping with about 100
restoration projects in various stages of development. ``We're on a
very steep learning curve, but we're making excellent progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have learned only recently how valuable wetlands
really are, sometimes by the bad things that happened when they
disappeared. Wetlands prevent floods by absorbing water in their
soils, trap pollutants that otherwise would contaminate drinking
water, provide a nursery for many species of fish and host
communities of plants and animals not found anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Audubon Society estimates that the services of
a single acre of wetlands is worth about $170,000 to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, undoing the past is a tall order. Since colonial
times, 30 percent of American wetlands have been destroyed,
including 230,000 acres of marsh in Massachusetts buried beneath
places such as Boston's Back Bay and Logan Airport. The current
development boom nibbles away at still more.
</P>
<P>
   But even the 3,000 acres Governor Paul Cellucci hopes will be
restored by 2010 would bring Massachusetts to the brink of a
milestone achieved by few, if any, other states: creating more
wetlands than it destroys. Tighter laws since the 1970s have cut
wetland loss to less than 50 acres a year, so that even a few new
acres a year would be enough to offset the losses _ likely for the
first time since the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   That would make Massachusetts a model for the federal
government's longstanding effort to stop the decline of wetlands, a
policy called ``no net loss'' by former President George Bush.
Despite the policy, the country loses 100,000 acres annually,
though some huge projects, such as restoration of the Florida
Everglades, eventually will tilt the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of acres (of restored wetlands) in Massachusetts
will be very helpful in moving us toward the annual goal,'' said
Michael Davis, deputy assistant secretary of the Army for civil
works. Though no official records are kept, he said, ``It's a
fairly small club of `no net loss' states.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is risk in trying to recreate something as complex
as a wetland, which as the name implies, requires a careful mixing
of water and land to thrive. Tiny mistakes in the land contours or
water flows can be magnified over time, sometimes creating a field
instead of a marsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly a lot of science behind this, but there's a
bit of art, too. It's definitely experimental,'' said Gary Clayton,
vice president for operations at Massachusetts Audubon Society,
which is creating a two-acre salt marsh in Newburyport's Joppa
Flats.
</P>
<P>
   The wetland restoration movement is especially remarkable
considering how callously wetlands were treated until recently.
Dorchester's Neponset Marsh, hundreds of gorgeous acres that
stretch out from the home site of a former British colonial
governor, was used as a dumping ground in the 1960s for muck
dredged from the river bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the layer of spongy peat that underlies the marsh is
buried beneath up to eight feet of dredge material and a towering
reed called phragmites has overrun most of the land, giving it the
look of a Kansas wheat field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more or less an upland meadow. The water is almost
gone,'' said Rich Kleiman, wetlands specialist for the state office
of environmental affairs, standing in one section so dry that
knee-high meadow grass has grown in. ``We've only become more
enlightened to the value of these areas in recent times.''
</P>
<P>
   As governments learned to appreciate swamps and marshes, state
and federal laws made wholesale destruction of them more difficult,
reducing the national loss rate from 290,000 acres a year in the
1980s to 100,000 acres. In Massachusetts, legally permitted losses
dropped from 1,500 acres a year to 15 acres a year in the 1990s,
although additional acres are probably filled illegally or are too
small to come under regulatory scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush's ``no net loss'' declaration in 1988 committed
the nation, at least rhetorically, to building new wetlands to
offset the continued losses.
</P>
<P>
   The early experiments were discouraging. Massachusetts began
requiring developers to create wetlands to offset years of damage,
but a recent University of Massachusetts at Amherst study showed
that almost half of these efforts fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You typically end up with a lot of wet meadows'' instead of
land where water is an intimate part of its character, said Peter
Veneman, a soil scientist at the university who co-authored the
study. The trouble, he said, is that developers created something
that looked like a wetland and then did little follow-up to see how
the water actually flowed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most wetland restoration efforts springing up across the
country aren't trying to put wetlands in places they never were.
Instead, activists and government officials find wetlands that have
either been damaged or destroyed, and try to bring water back to
them, a policy Veneman said has a much better chance of succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   In the Neponset Marsh, the Metropolitan District Commission
plans to begin restoring wetlands as early as next winter, using a
$425,000 federal grant to remove the dredge materials, knock holes
in an earthen dike and increase the size of a culvert to give a
stream more room to spread out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You break through the dike, you create the right elevation and
the water does the rest. . . . It's not super complicated,'' said
Kleiman. He said the increased saltwater will kill off the
phragmites, and allow the native spartina grass to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 100 restoration projects that the state is tracking
are simpler than the Neponset restoration, so-called ``pipes
projects'' where the wetland is damaged, but not destroyed, and
water flow can be restored with plumbing changes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the National Park Service last week formally
unveiled a new, larger culvert in Provincetown that, by itself,
will restore 90 acres of wetland, the most in state history. The
$377,000 project allows more saltwater into the marsh, driving out
the phragmites and bringing back shellfish and possibly juvenile
striped bass.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the restoration may improve mosquito control on the
land, which was drained in the 1930s to get rid of mosquitoes.
Project manager Norm Farris said the culvert will allow fish called
mummichogs into the marsh to eat mosquito larvae.
</P>
<P>
   However, not all of the projects are so simple.
</P>
<P>
   At long-awaited Pope John Paul II Park in Dorchester, a section
of Boston, the Metropolitan District Commission is creating a whole
new landscape, including a narrow band along the Neponset River
where contractors have excavated to the water level and begun
planting spartina grasses that would have grown there before the
property became a landfill and drive-in movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   And, on the North Shore, the Massachusetts Audubon Society is
turning the area below the old Sportsman's Lodge in Newburyport
into a wetland that includes three tide pools, called salt pannes,
that could serve as feeding areas for shorebirds.
</P>
<P>
   The $180,000 project requires contractors to excavate down to a
clay layer that will hold water in the pannes, and cut new channels
into the mud to allow water to flow in. Adding to the complexity,
each panne is at a different elevation in hopes of creating
slightly different plant and animal mixes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect we'll be going back in subsequent years and
making some adjustment'' to the marsh, said Audubon's Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they're surprised how quickly wetland
restoration has caught on with the public, government and
businesses alike. Foote-Smith of the Wetlands Restoration program
said 171 possible wetland projects have been identified in the
Neponset River watershed alone, the first of 28 major river systems
the state is scouring for candidate sites.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, corporations such as Gillette Co. have formed a
partnership with the state to restore 300 acres of wetlands over
the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is climbing on the wetlands restoration bandwagon,''
said Foote-Smith, who figures she needs all the help she can get
since it will cost perhaps $30 million to $60 million to meet the
state goal of 3,000 acres restored.
</P>
<P>
   When, and if, Massachusetts achieves ``no net loss'' of wetlands
as a result of all that, will depend in part on how many of these
restored acres are on land that had stopped being wetland
altogether, and whether regulators can push developers to create
quality replacement wetlands for those they destroy.
</P>
<P>
   But it will also depend on whether regulators continue to limit
development to only a few acres a year. A single big project, such
as the proposed New Bedford Airport, could mean the difference
between gain and loss for the year.
</P>
<P>
   And state officials know the political winds can shift on
protecting wetlands, sometimes viewed as an obstacle to economic
development. ``Wetlands are still the most maligned environmental
resource and conservation commissions are among the most maligned
environmental practitioners,'' said DEP assistant commissioner
Arleen O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis, the deputy assistant secretary of the Army, said
Massachusetts' restoration program makes him optimistic that the
United States can go from losing to gaining wetlands in the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not satisfied with that 100,000-acre loss,'' Davis
said. ``We're seeing states like Massachusetts step up and
respond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
