<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8352 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-MATTHIESSEN-BO     06-01 1656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-MATTHIESSEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WRITER'S WIDE, WILD WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``In the old days, I was very arrogant,'' Peter
Matthiessen over lunch recently. ``I used to say, `I'll write it
and you sell it.' But maybe those days have passed.'' The author,
craggy-faced and dressed in a blue blazer, blue sweater, and blue
polo shirt, clears his palate with a swig of lager. ``I remember a
good friend of mine going out on tour two months before he died,
knowing he was going to die. He felt he owed it to his publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, you're not only talking about your book . . .
you're talking about yourself, and I have always hated that.'' At
age 72, and possessing a body of work the equal of any of his
American contemporaries, novelist or nonfiction specialist,
Matthiessen seemingly has little left to prove _ whether he chooses
to play the publicity game or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bone By Bone,'' his latest book, completes an ambitious
trilogy launched in 1990 with the haunting novel ``Killing Mr.
Watson.'' Set in southwestern Florida a century ago, the trilogy
chronicles the fortunes, and misfortunes, of Edgar J. ``Bloody''
Watson, a local sugar-cane baron gunned down by neighbors in 1910
in cold-blooded revenge for Watson's own murderous deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Man's River,'' the second volume, fleshes out the Watson
legend through the eyes of one of his sons, Lucius Watson; it
appeared to largely enthusiastic reviews in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   With ``Bone By Bone'' Matthiessen returns the focus of his
storytelling to Watson himself, recasting the saga as autobiography
and thus completing a literary trifecta that deserves comparison to
Cormac McCarthy's superb Border Trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   In Matthiessen's case, dividing the yarn into three parts was
somewhat arbitrary from the outset. He wrote the story in one
sweeping take, totalling some 2,000 pages, and then spent nearly a
decade chopping up the narrative and adding connective tissue.
``Lost Man's River'' remains his favorite of the three, an
admission few novelists would make unless pressed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still like it the best, although `Bone By Bone' has the
strongest voice,'' he says. ``Even if it's not a voice everyone is
going to love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't write Watson as a lovable character. But if
the reader doesn't have sympathy for Watson . . . then I've failed
somehow. Watson is part of our turn-of-the-century entrepreneurial
tradition. He's way out in the swamps running a 40-acre cane
plantation, and he's got competition coming in with full government
backing, taking advantage of immigrant and black labor. We've seen
this everywhere. If you're making money, somehow you're above moral
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watson is quite aware of men like Ford and Rockefeller and
Gould, who were not nice guys, either. People died for the fortunes
these guys made. Watson sees that, but he also has flaws that do
him in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen's dark joke these days is that someday he will knit
the original manuscript back together again, minus the scaffolding.
``I don't particularly care if it's published or not,'' he
declares. ``I just want it somewhere in its proper form. It would
be kind of a hobby, maybe leading to it being rediscovered 40 years
later. Like `Moby-Dick' was.''
</P>
<P>
   His publisher, Matthiessen adds, ``goes white as this tablecloth
whenever I mention it. My wife does, too. It would be hard work. As
Don DeLillo once told me, the real joy of writing is not cutting
bad stuff but cutting good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen has certainly produced more than his share of good
stuff: more than 20 books in all, a prodigious output that had
solidified his reputation as the peerless chronicler of lost tribes
and endangered species, fearsome predators and political martyrs.
The titles alone _ ``At Play in the Fields of the Lord,'' ``Far
Tortuga,'' ``The Tree Where Man Was Born,'' ``Sand Rivers,'' ``In
The Spirit of Crazy Horse,'' ``The Snow Leopard'' (winner of the
1978 National Book Award) _ suggest the widest possible world by
which one authorial imagination can be engaged.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Snow Leopard,'' serialized in The New Yorker, remains a
particular favorite of many Matthiessen fans. The book grew out of
several influences in his life, including the death of
Matthiessen's second wife (he is remarried now and has two grown
children), his friendship with wildlife expert George Schaller, and
his interest in Zen Buddhism, another subject he is uncomfortable
discussing (he teaches a meditation class at his home on Long
Island when he is in residence). The result is a mystical account
of a 250-mile trip through Tibet undertaken by Matthiessen and
Schaller in search of the rare snow leopard. It also nearly _
underscore nearly _ brought Matthiessen the commercial success that
has otherwise eluded him, an injustice that helps explain his
current commitment to modest self-promotion. A commitment at odds
with Matthiessen's embrace of Zen Buddhism and its ideology of
egolessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wandered onto the best-seller list for a couple of
weeks,'' he relates with a wry smile, ``but I'm strictly a bottom
feeder. My one chance was `The Snow Leopard,' which got a . . .
rave on the front page of the Sunday New York Times Book Review.
The publisher was beside himself with joy. Unfortunately no one
ever saw the review. That week, the Times went on strike.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was ``In The Spirit of Crazy Horse,'' published
in 1983. Depicting the militant activities of the American Indian
Movement and one of its leaders, Leonard Peltier, who was convicted
of killing two FBI agents in South Dakota, the book was pulled from
circulation by Viking Press after Matthiessen was slapped with a
$49 million libel suit by FBI officials and William Janklow, then
governor of South Dakota. The book is back in print  &UR; today &LR; ,
although Peltier remains in prison while the suit against author
and publisher drags on.
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen regards the lawsuit as more dispiriting than
harrowing. For sheer terror, there was the time back in 1961 when
he and some fellow travelers were taken prisoner during a civil
uprising in the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were going to be shot,'' he recalls. ``We heard
later that more than 200 white people were killed in that same area
that night. I'm still not sure why we were spared.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently there was a field trip to study grizzy bears in
Montana. Matthiessen's guide was Doug Peacock, renowned in
eco-warrior circles as a kind of latter-day Paul Bunyan of the
wilderness. In one day on foot, the pair spotted 18 bears, or
``about 17 more than I cared to see,'' says Matthiessen.
</P>
<P>
   Was he scared? ``Oh yeah. The Park Service was keeping people
out, we had to brush out the trails ourselves. We could hear snorts
and snuffles as we waded along. I kept saying, `Doug, let's sing
something so the bears will know we're here. Like ``The
Marseillaise,'' or Cyndi Lauper.' '' Matthiessen laughs. ``But Doug
wouldn't allow it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His interest in the Watson legend dates back 55 years, when
Matthiessen took a boat ride through the Everglades with his
father, who had heard of Watson's dark reputation _ and his murder.
Matthiessen returned to southwestern Florida in the 1980s,
intending to write a sprawling regional novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things I wanted to write about were there,'' he
explains. ``Traditional Indian people. The environment and nature.
Social justice and violence. The Watson story was supposed to be
one strand, but it was so strong it took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen got hold of a few Watson letters and one surviving
picture of him, but for years the family would have nothing to do
with the author. One Watson daughter had married a local bank
president and was uncomfortable with inquiries into her father's
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had an agreement not to speak about Watson, partly
because everything written about him was so lurid,'' says
Matthiessen. ``I think I interviewed everybody over 90 in southwest
Florida, including two of his daughters. Now they all want to talk
to me, because they know that whatever I write about him it can't
be as bad as the myth.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen pushes back his plate and swallows the last of his
beer. Into the dining room strolls poet Derek Walcott, the Nobel
laureate, who walks immediately over to Matthiessen's table and
greets him warmly. While the two writers make small talk, another
party enters the room. Actor Anthony Quinn sits down with his wife
and two young children. Wolcott leaves, and when Quinn is pointed
out to Matthiessen, he leans back and nods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Quinn story,'' he offers. ``It involves Cesar Chavez,
the California labor leader, who was the most impressive man I've
ever known. Chavez and I were exactly the same age, we'd been in
the Navy at the same time, we liked the same music, the same boxers
and ball clubs. He was very sweet and gentle and a funny man, but
also very tough. And very angry about the humiliation his people _
the farm workers _ had suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway,'' Matthiessen continues, ``this dumb novel came out in
which a Chavez-like character gets assassinated. Now, Cesar himself
did not go around armed and would not let his bodyguards carry
guns, either, although he was constantly under death threats. He
didn't want someone else to die protecting him.''
</P>
<P>
   He gestures toward the actor. ``I understand Quinn was signed to
make the movie. I called the publisher myself, not to block
publication of the book but to explain how a movie version could
put Cesar's life at risk. Quinn later backed out of the movie deal.
I've always admired him for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthiessen rises to leave. ``Do you think it inappropriate if I
go over and introduce myself?'' he asks. A moment later, author and
actor are deep in conversation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
