<HEADER>
A8354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-HARLEY--BOS     06-01 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HARLEY--BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEY-DAVIDSON'S HISTORY OF SELLING MENACE TO THE UNMENACING 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUTLAW MACHINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harley-Davidson and the Search for the American Soul &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Brock Yates &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown, 249 pp., illustrated, $24 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Coca-Cola, Mickey Mouse, and Stetson hats, the
Harley-Davidson motorcycle is an American icon. Cherished by its
owners despite _ no, because of _ its low-tech image, it's a brash
and noisy symbol of personal freedom, individual control, and not a
little bit of menace.
</P>
<P>
   But something has happened to Harley's bad-guy persona, and
that's the central theme of ``Outlaw Machine.'' Brock Yates, an
accomplished automotive writer, attributes the 1990s resurrection
of the financially troubled Harley-Davidson Motor Co. to a gaggle
of well-heeled graybeard riders who carry cell phones in their
black leather jackets. They are America's yuppie outlaws, men
(mostly) who climb aboard their growling Harleys on weekends and
slip quietly back behind their neat desks on Monday mornings.
There's even an acronym for them: RUBs, as in Rich Urban Bikers.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Yates points out, the family-founded Harley-Davidson
company (one Harley and three Davidsons) spent the first half of
the 20th century courting wholesome Americans. But in its issue
dated July 21, 1947, Life magazine published a photo of a boozy
biker on a Harley helping to terrorize the tiny town of Hollister,
Calif. Never mind that the picture was apparently staged. From that
day on, Harley became the transportation of choice for bikers
intending to rape and pillage. That image _ as well as the Invasion
of the Japanese Bikes, which began in 1959 _ nearly drove the
company over a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, Harley never really acknowledged its dark side. The
company, based in Milwaukee, was steeped in Midwestern values. It
wasn't until the hero of ``Outlaw Machine,'' Willie G. Davidson,
began peddling the trappings of the bad biker lifestyle to
orthodontists and investment bankers that the company righted
itself and prospered again. Today, Harley gear _ heavy on denim and
leather _ is a $100-million-a-year business within the company's
$2-billion-a-year business, available in boutiques down at your
local mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outlaw Machine'' is a book that even a nonbiker can like, but
not love. Yates traces Harley's history from 1903, and readers who
don't know a V-twin from an identical twin may occasionally find
themselves suffering from glazed-eye syndrome. The writer is a
pretty good social observer, however, and gets it right with
descriptions of, say, many of Harley's newer customers as ``tort
lawyers who hadn't ridden anything since a ten-speed in Harvard
Square.''
</P>
<P>
   But that reveals the problem with ``Outlaw Machine.'' Just who
are these tort lawyers? And just who are the sinister bikers whose
lifestyle has created such wannabes? Brock describes them well, but
we never really meet them. What are they thinking? What are they
saying? There are only occasional hints, such as the small scene
when the flinty-eyed, leather-clad biker at Daytona's annual bike
week pulls out his cell phone and hollers, ``Jennifer, you know
your bedtime. Do what the babysitter says!''
</P>
<P>
   We need more of that in ``Outlaw Machine.'' And we could use
more of Willie G. Davidson, the superbiker who, Yates tells us, is
the brilliant marketer able to work both sides of the street. It is
this particular Davidson who is chiefly responsible for selling
Harley-Davidson's image of menace to unmenacing folks and thereby
enabling the company to survive and prosper. It is this Davidson
who understands that a Harley answers the call for a return to the
cowboy way of life. And it is this Davidson who appears hither and
yon in the book, but we learn more about him from his
black-and-white photograph than from Yates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outlaw Machine'' is worthwhile for both motorcycle mavens and
Americana aficionados, but it doesn't let us hear the voices of the
people _ especially the riders _ who are responsible for this
particular slice of American pie. In other words, it lacks what has
ultimately made the icon that Brock Yates calls ``God's own
American-made Harley-Davidson'' so popular despite its flaws: soul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1504EDT &QL; 
