<HEADLINE>
DEBT-LADEN PHILIPPINE CARRIER FACES DEMISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCSISCO _ Philippine Airlines has until Friday to come up
with $200 million to pay part of its debt or Manila will consider
alternatives to the regime of PAL's major shareholder,
multimillionaire Lucio Tan, a government official said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the airline laid off 5,000 workers, suffered a
pilots' strike and a shutdown, and two of its aircraft were seized
by U.S. marshals acting on behalf of creditors. A San Francisco
federal bankruptcy court overturned the seizure, but problems
continue for PAL and Tan, its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Tan, a political supporter of Philippine President Joseph
Estrada, has asked for a one-month extension of the June 4
deadline. But Secretary of Trade and Industry Jose T. Pardo said
that Estrada's government wouldn't give Tan the extension he
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president stands firmly on June 4,'' Pardo said in during
a stop in San Francisco. ``By June 5, that's the end of it. It's a
new ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Pardo, the Philippines will consider using aircraft
from the country's three domestic airlines if PAL is grounded.
This, he said, coupled with expected compensatory increases in
flights to the Philippines by international airlines, should ensure
the country is served by long-haul carriers.
</P>
<P>
   PAL has debts of $2.3 billion. Among its creditors are the
Export-Import Bank of the United States, which is owed $350 million
for the Boeing 747-400 aircraft it financed for PAL. The airline
suspended payments on its debt almost a year ago, and lost a
reported $250 million in the last nine months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pardo, Tan requested asked the Philippine
government to help the beleaguered airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the president has made clear government resources should
not be drawn for stressed businesses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tan, who holds 70 percent of PAL, has pledged to put up $100
million and recruit investors to pony up the other half. One of the
richest men in the Philippines, Tan said prospective investors have
demanded a guarantee that workers will not strike for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Pardo said Manila was taking a dim view of the no-strike demand.
``The government has committed to protect the interests of labor,''
he said of Estrada's populist administration.
</P>
<P>
   Should Tan not come up with a restructuring plan that satisfies
creditors and the government, Pardo said, ``there will be a basis
for the government to start a different track, and maybe open it up
to investors we have waiting on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't name the investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
