<HEADLINE>
OH, THOSE LOOPY LAWS! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's illegal for mourners at a wake in Massachusetts to eat more
than three sandwiches. In Maine, it's against the law to step out
of a plane in flight. And in Vermont, whistling underwater is
definitely illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Those are three silly laws that at last look were still on the
books. And there are plenty more. Here are some of them:
</P>
<P>
   --In New York, the penalty for jumping off a building is death.
</P>
<P>
   --In Connecticut, you can be stopped by the police for biking
over 65 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   --In Cleveland, you can't catch mice without a hunting license.
</P>
<P>
   --In California, it is illegal to set a mousetrap without a
hunting license.
</P>
<P>
   --In Rhode Island, it is an offense to throw pickle juice on a
trolley.
</P>
<P>
   --In Ohio, you're breaking the law if you get a fish drunk.
</P>
<P>
   --In New Hampshire, citizens may not relieve themselves while
looking up. But that's only on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   --And in Arizona, it is illegal to hunt camels within the state
borders.
</P>
<P>
   (With thanks to Stormy3058(at)aol.com Inc., www.dumblaws.com,
and faithful contributor Mike Schuster of Foxborough.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which US capital city is closest to a border to
another state? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: New Zealand's Ninety Mile Beach is 62 miles long. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``We'd like to get consumers to hang up the phone or rip
up their mail.'' _ Betsy Broder of the Federal Trade Commission,
speaking to Consumer Reports about those too-good-to-be-true
unsolicited travel deals. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Yummy! One of the wonderful things about visiting Vermont is the
fresh and tasty specialty food produced there. Here's just a sample
of the variety: Stonewood Farm's turkey, Dakin Farm's ham, Green
Mountain Coffee Roasters' java, the Westminster Cracker Co.'s
old-fashioned square cracker, Cabot Creamery's cheese to go with
it, Catamount Brewing Co.'s beer, and the Snow Farm Vineyard and
Winery's wine. And you can't talk about Vermont food without
mentioning Ben &AMP; Jerry's ice cream and frozen yogurt. Suddenly
we're famished. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: Last week we wondered why what appeared to be a bird-food
vending machine was next to a sign warning against feeding the
birds at Walt Disney World's Boardwalk entertainment district.
Linda Scanlon of Medfield and P.T. Crotty of Malden write that the
vending machine contains fish food. Hmmm . . . seems that we saw
some feathered fellows munching away anyhow. That explains the
warning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R.C. of Danvers (that's me) wonders whether it is possible to
buy an adapter so that a phone bought in Korea will work in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Travel bookshelf: The art and architecture of France is
unforgettable, and we're not just talking about Paris. Neither is
Sidra Stich, author of ``Art-Sites France: Art + Architecture
Contemporary Handbook'' (Art-Sites, $19.95; phone 415-437-2456, fax
415-701-0633, or visit www.artsitespress.com). This illustrated
travel guide and handbook tells where you can see the most
impressive work from the current and past few decades in and around
Paris and the provinces. Museums, art centers, exhibition halls,
galleries, vanguard buildings, and a host of other sites are
covered. Why, even the architecture of Disneyland Paris is
included. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Not so rocky: Here's a nice-sounding combination of activity and
luxury. The Lodge and Spa at Cordillera, a chateau-style property
in Vail Valley, Colo., offers a four-day/three-night all-inclusive
``Exploration of Yourself Hut Trip'' that combines communal rustic
living, healthy and tasty dining, massage, yoga, flower essence
therapy classes, and hiking in Colorado's incomparable high
Rockies. Dates are July 20-23, Aug. 26-29, and Sept. 9-12, and the
cost is $899 per person. For more information, call the Lodge &AMP; Spa
at 800-877-3529, write to PO Box 1110, Edwards, CO 81623, or, on
the Web, visit www.cordillera-vail.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Trenton, N.J. The city is on the banks of the
Delaware River, which forms the border between New Jersey and
Pennsylvania. Next closest is Providence _ in some spots the city's
corporate limits are about two miles from the Massachusetts border.
(With thanks to Gordon Hartig of Westford, Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
