<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LLAMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE LLAMAS, WILL TREK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT GREYLOCK, Mass. _ The llama trek through the hills was
about to start, and hike leader Laurie Moon was giving the group a
quick introduction to llamas.
</P>
<P>
   They are ``very sweet,'' she told the 17 adults and children
assembled at the Berkshires trailhead. They are not aggressive
toward people. They are good at spotting wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Then she introduced the hikers to one of the four llamas on the
trek, an 8-month-old white one on a lead. ``This here is Benny,''
said Moon. ``Hmmmm,'' Benny uttered cordially, making the humming
sound that is to llamas what barks are to dogs. One well-timed hum
was all it took for this group to fall in love with llamas.
</P>
<P>
   Moon was not surprised. ``Sometimes it's love at first sight,
and sometimes it takes place over the course of the hike,'' said
Moon, 47, a Great Barrington writer, editor, yoga teacher, and
self-described ``llama ambassador.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But toward the end of it, what you start seeing is people who
want to take the animal home with them. There is a real connection
that goes on between llamas and humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon owns five llamas that function as pack animals and tour
guides in her 1 1/2-year-old llama trekking company, Moon Mountain
Llamas. ``They've added a lot to my life,'' she told the group.
</P>
<P>
   And she to theirs. How many llamas can boast of the rich
opportunities her small herd enjoys? During the summer months, her
llamas will trek with hikers at least three or four times a week,
happily carrying their packs and picnics, sloshing through streams,
and mingling with wildlife. ``Llamas get a kick out of hiking,''
said Moon. ``Without it, they would just be stuck in a pasture.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more and more New Englanders are ``enriching'' llamas'
lives this way. According to Nelson Leonard of the Oregon-based
Llama Association of North America, there are about 120,000 llamas
in the US, and while they've been hot in the Western states for
about a decade, ``the population is growing fastest on the East
Coast.'' Partly, they are popular for their soft alpaca-like fleece
and as guard animals. But their value as ``pleasure animals'' is
steadily increasing in the East.
</P>
<P>
   One of these pleasures is llama treks. Two llama trek companies
have formed in Massachusetts in the last two years _ Laurie Moon's
and Berkshire Mountain Llama Treks in Lee. Moon said her business
is increasing, and she has ``as much business as I want to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the question: Why would you need a llama for a hike
anyway, especially a moderate loop like this one from Northrup
Trail on the Lanesborough side of Mount Greylock to Rounds Rock, a
mile and a half away.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: You don't exactly need a llama. You can't ride one.
Well, children can, but not adults: The average 300-400-pound male
llama _ bred for lugging potatoes in Peru _ can haul heavy loads
behind him, but not carry them on his back.
</P>
<P>
   They are, in effect, fleecy animal sherpas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carry everything, be it lunch or overnight tents or yoga
mats,'' said Moon, whose Berkshires-born llamas are second-and
third generation descendants of Chilean animals.
</P>
<P>
   But llamas have another, more subtle function, according to
Moon. They enhance the hiking experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Llamas are very Zen animals,'' said Moon, who has been known
to merge the two facets of her career _ teaching yoga and raising
llamas _ by leading yoga hikes. (She combines hiking with breathing
and stretching exercises, plus meditation with the llamas.)
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so quiet and meditative and alert,'' Moon said. ``On
a hike, llamas tend to go slow. And because they are so alert and
their hearing is so good, they will see wildlife that otherwise we
would miss. They add a whole new element to being in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I like them?'' she asked rhetorically. ``I think the
same reason you would like a dog. They remind me to slow down. They
teach what is important in life. Eating, sleeping, listening to
your body.''
</P>
<P>
   The hikers might not have been acutely tuned into their bodies
that day, but clearly everyone was enjoying the company of these
exotic, long-necked members of the camelid family, with their
intriguing names like Wisteria Rose, Brian Boru, and Cuchulain, and
an appearance that several hikers agreed was strikingly Dr.
Suess-like.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled up with the day's snack, which included fresh fruit and
M&AMP;Ms, the animals were remarkably good-natured and tolerant of the
junior hikers, most of whom were so anxious to try out every llama
that some animals were not only led but pushed.
</P>
<P>
   At times Moon had to intervene on behalf of the adults.
``Remember parents,'' she called out. ``If you want to lead a
llama, you get a chance, too.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the hike seemed less like a trek than llama traffic
control. The animals were not always inclined to stay on the trail
and protect the natural habitat, as Appalachian Mountain Club
naturalist Correen Seacord was urging the humans to do. Brian
Boru's basket of food supplies kept bumping into trees and getting
stuck on twigs, and at one point Wisteria Rose plopped on the
ground with no warning and decided she was ready for a break.
</P>
<P>
   But no one was complaining. One cheerful hiker was Janice
Salveson , 70, who had brought along her two 5-year-old
grandchildren, Alexandra Salveson and Liam Quinn. A seasoned
walker, Salveson has hiked the Grand Canyon three times in the last
five years, albeit without llamas. ``But this is fun too,'' she
hastened to add.
</P>
<P>
   Erica Bronstein had come with her 7-year-old daughter, Julia,
because ``I love hiking and Julia doesn't.'' She thought the
novelty of llamas would increase the hike appeal for her daughter,
and she was right. ``Usually she starts to complain pretty quickly,
but she did great. Leading a llama kept her interest up,'' said
Bronstein. ``Even if it is a little weird to go on a hike for a
couple of miles with a llama to carry out snacks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
