u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-GOODING-ART-BO     06-01 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GOODING-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODING FACES HIS MOST CHALLENGING ROLE IN `INSTINCT' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Jon Turteltaub is explaining why he hired Cuba Gooding
Jr. to star in his new film, ``Instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, which opens Friday, Gooding plays an ambitious
young psychiatrist bent on bringing back to the speaking world a
primatologist (Anthony Hopkins) who has been rendered silent after
living with African gorillas for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Turteltaub think Gooding, who earned his 1997 Oscar
yelling ``Show me the money!'' in ``Jerry Maguire,'' could play the
cerebral role? The answer lay in Gooding's 1991 debut in ``Boyz N
the Hood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a gentleness in (the film) that said he doesn't have
to jump on a table and dance to get your attention,'' the director
said.
</P>
<P>
   Turteltaub's comment made Gooding, sitting nearby in a chic
ensemble of black V-neck top and pin-striped black pants, begin
chuckling ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Pepsi knew that,'' he said, referring to the company
that featured him in three high-energy Pepsi One commercials.
``They don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only brazen comment erupting from Gooding's lips
during the interview. After all, publicity tours can get tedious.
Poised between the tail end of morning and afternoon interviews and
a flight to Detroit for more interviews, Gooding and Turteltaub
fielded questions with giddy, vaudevillian-style humor.
</P>
<P>
   And there was eating, lots of eating, courtesy of the fruit bowl
in the Four Seasons room that served as Gooding's Boston home for a
night. Oh, yeah, and they also discussed the film, which gives
Gooding his first leading role in a serious drama since winning the
Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding, 30, began his entertainment career early. The son of
the Main Ingredient lead singer Cuba Gooding Sr., he made his
professional debut break dancing in the 1984 Olympics closing
ceremonies in Los Angeles, where he lived with his family.
</P>
<P>
   The gig helped him get an agent. Then he started appearing in
commercials and had guest roles in television series like ``Hill
Street Blues'' before ``Boyz N the Hood'' kicked off his
feature-film career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct'' was inspired by Daniel Quinn's contemporary novel
``Ishmael,'' in which a man and an ape sit in a room talking about
the environment and human nature. In it, Quinn suggests that there
are two types of humans: takers, who use the environment for their
own benefit, and leavers, who live in peaceful balance with the
world. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Animal instruction &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Instinct,'' screenwriter Gerald DiPego leaves in the
gorillas, providing lush flashbacks to Africa, where Hopkins's
character, Ethan Powell, has lived peacefully with and been
instructed by a gorilla family. When Powell returns to the United
States mute after killing two men in Africa, his recovery involves
teaching Gooding's career-focused character what he learned from
the gorillas about the leavers and the takers.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding enjoyed working with Hopkins and Donald Sutherland, who
has a brief role as Gooding's mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it was very intense, sometimes it was very relaxed,
and sometimes it was straight out boring,'' said Gooding. ``But for
the most part it was something I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to taking the project for its starring role
opportunity, Gooding also grabbed ``Instinct'' because he sensed it
could answer the question ``Can Cuba act?'' What better way to
prove it than to go head to head with some of the world's greatest
actors?
</P>
<P>
   Gooding hadn't had many opportunities to show his talent in
recent roles. He followed up ``Jerry Maguire'' with small parts in
``As Good as It Gets'' and ``What Dreams May Come.'' He wanted to
break out of that rut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately a lot of the characters I've done have been very
energetic and flamboyant,'' said Gooding. ``Here's one that as a
psychiatrist I sit and I listen and let people speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooding will have another chance to show his leading-man prowess
this summer. He and costar Skeet Ulrich will try to save the West
Coast from nuclear disaster by keeping toxic materials below 50
degrees in ``Chill Factor,'' an action film directed by Hugh
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But first there's ``Instinct.'' The film's producer and director
began pursuing Gooding right after ``Jerry Maguire'' was released,
even before the Oscar, said Turteltaub.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard Hollywood executives say black actors don't appeal
to European audiences, who can give American films blockbuster
box-office numbers. And a Screen Actors Guild report issued in May
shows that black representation in film and television dropped
almost 1 percent, to 13.4 percent, in 1998. However, casting an
African-American actor in the lead didn't give the makers of
``Instinct'' pause.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in the role that says it has to be a black
actor or a white actor,'' said Turteltaub, who suddenly turned
serious amid the volley of jokes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hollywood and race &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His casual attitude about casting an African-American actor
masks the fact that Hollywood is still hung up on race, said
Gooding. Putting a black actor in the lead role took a lot of
``guts,'' he said. ``And I say `guts' because there's so many
issues that are raised when you have . . . a (Hollywood) community
that is so caught up in what is a black film and what isn't a black
film.''
</P>
<P>
   And all of that becomes even more complicated when the actor in
question is perceived as selling out. Which brings us back to those
pesky Pepsi One commercials, which showcased Gooding's high energy
and neon-bright smile.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics faulted Gooding for doing them, although an
increasing number of stars, from Jennifer Lopez to David Duchovny,
appear in or voice commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding said he did the ads because Pepsi had never featured a
black actor. And hey, he's a Pepsi man; he likes the product.
</P>
<P>
   Bubbling beneath those explanations, however, was another
motivation: a Hollywood rejection story that Gooding told
reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   He had been talking to Andrew Davis, director of ``The
Fugitive'' and ``Chain Reaction,'' about starring in a movie
Gooding wouldn't name. Davis wanted to hire Gooding. The film
studio preferred an actor with more ``clout,'' said Gooding.
</P>
<P>
   The project went ahead without Gooding and Davis. However, the
name-brand actor remained. Gooding grabbed the high-profile Pepsi
One opportunity to ensure that wouldn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, when it comes to Hollywood, you want to get name
recognition,'' said Gooding, the joke-cracking funny man suddenly
transformed into a calculating professional. ``So I'm trying to
keep my exposure up there and deal with it because it is show
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
