<HEADLINE>
DEGAS AND NEW ORLEANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To celebrate the 300th anniversary of French influence in
Louisiana, the New Orleans Museum of Art has assembled virtually
all of the works that Edgar Degas created during his sojourn in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Degas and New Orleans: A French Impressionist in America''
runs through Aug. 29 before traveling to Copenhagen for its only
other showing.
</P>
<P>
   Admired today as the quintessential Parisian painter, Degas was,
as he himself put it, almost a son of Louisiana _ his mother was
born in New Orleans. When he came to New Orleans for a family visit
in 1872, both of his brothers were in business and living with
French-Creole relatives in the city. During the few short months of
Degas's stay, he created a body of unforgettable works that are at
the heart of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheraton New Orleans Hotel is the official hotel of the
exhibition and offers special packages to the show. For
information, call 877-66-DEGAS. Packages are also offered by
Destination Management; for information, call 800-366-8882. For
individual tickets, call TicketMaster at 800-409-9959.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Avis becoming more accessible &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avis Rent A Car has agreed to make each of its 36 shuttle
systems accessible to those who use wheelchairs. The out-of-court
settlement resolves a complaint filed by a traveler who uses a
wheelchair and claimed that Avis violated the Americans with
Disabilities Act. The Justice Department reported Thursday that
Avis has agreed to have at least one wheelchair-accessible vehicle
in all its locations by December 2000 (Boston already has at least
one). ``As the summer travel season begins this weekend, airline
travelers who use wheelchairs will be able to go from the airport
terminal to their rental cars as easily as other customers,'' said
Bill Lann Lee, acting assistant attorney general for civil rights.
``This is a model agreement and Avis should be highly commended for
its cooperation and, more significantly, its desire to provide the
best possible service to its customers with disabilities.'' For
information on the settlement, call the ADA information line at
800-514-0301.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Film festival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Newport International Film Festival begins Tuesday and
continues through June 6. This year's festival features four US and
three world premieres along with features and documentaries
representing 15 countries. The 75 screenings will be shown at
Newport theaters, hotels, mansions, and outdoors at the
International Tennis Hall of Fame. For information on the festival,
call 401-848-9443 or, on the Web, visit
www.newportfilmfestival.com. For tickets, call 401-421-2787.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Old Port Festival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first major festival of the summer in northern New England,
the Old Port Festival in Portland, Maine, is expected to attracte
some 50,000 people on June 6. More than 30 hours of musical
entertainment will take place on seven stages, along with a variety
of local and international cuisine. The festival begins with a
parade from City Hall at 11 a.m. and continues through 5 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sabena is introducing a new ``2-for-1'' Business Class offer on
its daily flights from New York, Newark, and Boston to Brussels for
travel between July 1 and Aug. 31. With the purchase of a full fare
Business Class ticket, the second ticket is free. To qualify, both
passengers must travel together for the entire journey. For
details, see a travel agent or call Sabena at 800-955-2000.
</P>
