<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I DON'T THINK WE'RE IN KANSAS ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ My irrepressible friend, Joe King, has recently
returned from an adventure into the future. Yes, Joe, among his
other talents, is a time traveler. He is back from a place known as
ProsperUtopia, where the public sector has withered away and the
free market has blossomed into unchallenged domination. Joe told me
many wild tales _ all in a breathless voice. For the first time in
his life, Joe said, he experienced bliss.
</P>
<P>
   It all began one day when Joe received an offer in the mail for
a time-travel debit card from the Bank of the Next Dimension. As
instructed, he hugged the card against his bare chest in the
requisite show of adulation for the free economy, and before he
could say spend, spend, spend, he had landed in ProsperUtopia, and
his bank account was being debited for the adventure at a pace that
could only be described as cosmic.
</P>
<P>
   Joe found himself standing in a beautiful glade. Here the trees
were a greener green than any trees he had ever seen. The sky was a
bluer blue. The clouds were a puffier puffy, the birds' chirps a
chirpier chirp.
</P>
<P>
   Joe was admiring nature's bounty when he began to experience
trouble breathing. He told himself he was being silly, and he drew
a deep breath just to prove it. But something was certainly a
little funny. The trees and sky and clouds and birds all bespoke of
fresh, clean air. Yet Joe's breaths came harder and harder.
</P>
<P>
   Just then a young man appeared from behind a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi,'' he said. ``I'm Boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe could not speak, so he nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Boom saw right away what ailed Joe. ``Come with me. I'll help
you,'' he said. ``I know perfectly well I shouldn't help you. I've
been trained only to perform my market tasks. If an action has no
material market value, it is useless. I know this. Pursue only that
which is in your self-interest _ it is best for everyone. But,'' he
said, breaking off his recitation, ``I can't help myself from
helping you. It will be my undoing. I know this, too. But so be it.
Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   Boom produced an emergency oxygen kit that kept Joe alive until
he could be properly outfitted in town with a PBD, or Permanent
Breathing Device.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have them,'' Boom explained, pointing to the tiny
flesh-colored pads that practically vanished from sight just below
his nostrils. ``We have no oxygen left on earth. But,'' he added
merrily, ``who needs oxygen when you have a perfect market for its
sale and distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never breathed better,'' said Joe, once the color
returned to his face with his nostril pads securely in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's competition for you,'' Boom replied. ``We in
ProsperUtopia are blessed with the purest oxygen _ and at an
excellent price. The market fixes everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bravo!'' Joe exclaimed. ``But what if you can't afford to pay
for your oxygen?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here is rich,'' Boom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have known,'' Joe replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or dead,'' Boom added.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the birds and the trees _ how do they survive?'' Joe
wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fake,'' Boom answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so beautiful,'' Joe offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so fake,'' Boom said. ``You'll like it here in
ProsperUtopia. We're not just rich. Every single one of us is
happy, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the sky is very beautiful,'' said Joe.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Levingston, former director of the Business and
Economics Journalism Program at Boston University, can be reached
at dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
