<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALIST PONDERS POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Adam Werbach, the 26-year-old former president
of the Sierra Club, environmental film producer and three-year
resident of San Francisco, is considering throwing his hat _ well,
bicycle helmet _ into the ring as a candidate for mayor of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Werbach, who is still on the board of the Sierra Club, as well
as Common Cause and Stern Grove, is serious about running against
Mayor Willie Brown. Werbach says he has acquired nondeveloper
backers, a campaign consultant who once worked in the Clinton ``war
room'' and North Woods Productions to do the media.
</P>
<P>
   North Woods made the famous ads for Gov. Jesse Ventura of
Minnesota, showing a Jesse action figure fighting with ``Evil
Special Interest Man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will make a decision in two weeks,'' Werbach said over a
burrito Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is a great place to visit, but it's getting hard
to live here,'' Werbach said. ``The only buses that work in San
Francisco are tourist buses.''
</P>
<P>
   Call Werbach a bike-riding tree hugger, but he managed the
Sierra Club's $50 million budget and fought off an ugly
anti-immigration resolution backed by dissident members. But he's
still so young that when he said he had to talk to his family about
running, he meant his parents.
</P>
<P>
   According to Werbach, when he was young _ well, younger _ his
parents would take him to San Francisco from Los Angles and say,
``You see, this is what life can be like. These are called
neighborhoods. Neighborhoods!''
</P>
<P>
   Werbach told me, ``This is the city of Joe DiMaggio, that's why
I moved here. Joe DiMaggio wouldn't be born here today. Fishermen
can't live here anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   As this fan of the late newspaper columnist Herb Caen and
escapee from L.A. put it: ``I cannot accept that Baghdad-by-the-Bay
becomes Beverly Hills-by-the-Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't an environmentalist run for mayor? San Franciscans
are an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Brown's recent efforts to make San Francisco streets safe
seem to be working _ in Cape Cod, anyway. Consider this passage
from an editorial headlined ``California Courtesy'' in my folks'
hometown paper, the Falmouth (Mass.) Enterprise:
</P>
<P>
   ``In San Francisco, drivers actually stop to let people cross
the street. That drivers face a hefty fine for not giving way to
pedestrians doesn't explain all of it. If that were the case, cars
would push their luck; but instead, they automatically wait to turn
until pedestrians are out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   And the date of this Falmouth Enterprise was not 1953.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
