<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-WOMEN02-COX     06-01 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WOMEN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HILLARY CLINTON URGES WOMEN TO SUPPORT GORE'S CANDIDACY
 &HT;    310&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton urged women to
support Vice President Al Gore's presidential bid Tuesday, giving
his campaign a jump start with a key Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is an exceptional father and husband, a tireless advocate
for children and families, and he is my choice, and I hope your
choice, for the next president of the United States,'' Clinton said
at a Gore campaign rally.
</P>
<P>
   The rally included the release of 4,500 pledges of support from
prominent Democratic women around the country, including Sens.
Barbara Boxer of California and Patty Murray of Washington, 12
House members, Gov. Joan Finney of Kansas and former Gov. Ann
Richards of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his remarks, pledged to put women's health issues at
the top of his agenda and to fight for equal pay for equal work. He
also vowed to kill any Republican attempts to limit abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Gore called Mrs. Clinton ``a powerful role model'' and ``a
cherished friend.'' He made no mention of the fact that she is
considering running for the the U.S. Senate seat being vacated in
New York next year by Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's wife, Tipper, alluded to Clinton's political
ambitions in her remarks to the crowd at the Mayflower Hotel. ``I
wish I had a chance this morning to endorse someone for some other
race,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, during a two-day visit to Texas last week, said he was
``excited'' about the prospect of Clinton running of the Senate in
New York while he is running for president. He said her candidacy
would motivate Democratic activists up and down the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary would only complement Gore and energize voters who
have not been very energized recently,'' said Stephanie Cohen of
Emily's List, a political action committee that raises money for
women Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore needs help with women, whose vote was crucial to Bill
Clinton's election in 1992 and re-election in 1996. A Pew Research
Center poll in April found that the ``gender gap'' that helped the
Clinton-Gore ticket in those elections is evaporating following the
past year's impeachment proceedings and the military conflict in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Pew's hypothetical horse race, Gore lagged behind Texas Gov.
George W. Bush among women, 52-42 percent. By comparison, in 1996,
women preferred Bill Clinton over Bob Dole, 55-37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hawkesworth, director of the Center for the American Woman
and Politics at Rutgers University, said the defection of women
from the Democratic Party was apparent in the 1998 congressional
election, with older women leading the way. ``There has been a
great deal of speculation that ethical concerns underlie this
defection,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Lichtman, a presidential historian at American University,
said a Senate campaign by Mrs. Clinton could ``keep all the Clinton
administration controversies alive'' and ``make the emergence of
Gore as his own man more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, as a consequence, Gore has sought to distance himself
from the sexual scandals of the Clinton presidency by frequently
citing his 29 years of faithful marriage, his four children and the
expected birth of his first grandchild at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's rally, as he does in most campaign appearances, he
referred to Tipper as ``my very best friend and lifelong love.'' He
said she has ``taught me the meaning of a strong, loving
partnership that lasts for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's lone opponent for
the 2000 Democratic nomination, has a breakfast fund-raiser
scheduled Wednesday with women supporters. The speaker is author
and former journalist Anna Quindlen, who will endorse Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
