<HEADER>
A8414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN02-CO     06-01 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Cesspool secrets
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A fellow I know, who has made a success of himself
in his job as a journalist, and I were on our way to lunch, which
is a way of life in this world center of journalism, when we
stopped by the men's room on the floor of the building where he
offices.
</P>
<P>
   I was in the process of washing my hands when he interrupted our
conversation _ appropriately enough, we were discussing national
politics _ to point out a particularly large cap screw on a portion
of plumbing that sprouted from above the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what would happen,'' he asked, his eyes glinting,
``if we should take a screwdriver and pry away that cap?''
</P>
<P>
   Before I could say that I didn't, he went ahead and told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would result in such a force of water that it could not be
stemmed until a team of factory-trained, craftsmen plumbers were
called forth to undo the damage we had created.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he giggled.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't want to, but I had to. I had to ask how he happened to
have acquired such knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned it in college,'' he said, smirking a self-satisfied
smirk. ``That's what we would do in the men's room of the
administration building, and then run like the dickens.''
</P>
<P>
   I knew he had been a 1960s-style rebel. Little did I know.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't do that sort of thing anymore, do you?'' I
asked, edging toward the door, readying myself to run like the
dickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't,'' he said, sighing wistfully. ``Now I'm a mature
adult with a responsible position and I conduct myself
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he told me what it is that he does now.
</P>
<P>
   From one time to another, as he stops by the men's room to and
from his office, he makes it a point to drop a bit of change into
the basin of the wall-mounted, male-engineered device of his
choice, as if it were a wishing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the purpose of this is to clog up the pipes?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he explained, shaking his head. ``The coins are
too heavy to flush. They simply remain there from day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   And from day to day, he keeps adding nickels, dimes, quarters,
even pennies.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose being ... ?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a scientific experiment,'' he explained. ``How much money
will it take for someone to reach their hand into the basin and
fish out the change?''
</P>
<P>
   In case you're interested, the top price so far has been 73
cents.
</P>
<P>
   But it should be noted, from a scientific aspect, the results of
the experiment may be slightly skewed, in that the only other
office on the floor with access to the men's room is a law firm.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
