<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYS-MUSCLES-BOS &LR;      06-01 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-MUSCLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FAULTS MUSCLED MALE ACTION MODELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Retransmitting for clients)  
 For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame it on Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   For years, researchers have pointed at Barbie for being a bad
role model for the ideal woman: an incredibly busty blonde with a
super-tiny waist.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a Harvard psychiatrist says Star Wars' Luke Skywalker's big
biceps are bad for boys.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Pope, a researcher at McLean Hospital in Belmont,
Mass., has studied how the plastic body shapes of Star Wars and GI
Joe toy figures have bulked up since they were introduced in the
1960s and '70s. He believes the action figures promote an
unrealistic body image for young men, encouraging them to use
steroids and lift weights compulsively.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, when Luke Skywalker figures first appeared on toy store
shelves, he had a boyish figure and wore a white robe that covered
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two decades later when a Skywalker figure was
re-released, his partially open robe hung over chiseled pectoral
muscles, large thighs, and a smaller waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite clear that Luke in the 1990s has been spending a
lot of time in the gym,'' Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Pope and other researchers are worried that the toys _ and other
images bombarding boys _ are promoting a super-muscular he-man
body.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, researchers measured the circumference of GI Joe's
waist, chest and biceps at different stages in his development over
the years. Such specific comparisons could not be done with the
Star Wars figures because of the clothing they wore.
</P>
<P>
   Then the researchers scaled these measurements to the height of
an actual man.
</P>
<P>
   Pope said the original GI Joe from the 1960s, scaled to human
dimensions, would have a bicep circumference of about 11 1/2
inches, similar to an ordinary man.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, a GI Joe Extreme purchased in 1997 for the study
would have a bicep circumference of 26 inches, larger than any
bodybuilder in history. A dedicated weight-lifter would have about
16-inch biceps, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   His study of the evolution of action figures is in the current
issue of the International Journal of Eating Disorders. The study's
findings should be cautiously interpreted, Pope said, because he
doesn't know if the bulky toy images are the cause or the result of
boys favoring the bar-bouncer look.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Charness, a spokesman for Hasbro Inc., which makes GI Joe
and the Star Wars figures, said their sizes have gone up and down
over the years and some of the more buffed-up ones have actually
sold poorly. Charness said the GI Joe Extreme released in 1995 was
``a one-year wonder that has come and gone,'' because it didn't
sell well. In 1995, Luke Skywalker was also a he-man. ``But kids
didn't like them. And some of the collectors didn't think they were
realistic-looking. And since Star Wars is such a fan-based product
line, we reacted accordingly and changed Luke back to regular
proportions in 1996,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Area gym owners said the trend is actually going away from the
bulky look. ``They are shying away from the competitive
body-building look. Now they want some muscle tone, but not to be
huge,'' said Marco Costentino, co-owner of four Gold's Gyms in the
Boston area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8436 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-WOMEN-0602-COX     06-01 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-WOMEN-0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MANY WOMEN REFUGEES FACE HARDSHIPS IN UNFAMILIAR ROLE AS SINGLE
MOMS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ She is only 22, but with her wane face and
sunken eyes, she looks years older. It has been an arduous two
months for Vjollca Lushnaj, alone and struggling as a new mother
and a new refugee in a gritty tent city in northern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken woman from a small village in southern Kosovo
experienced profound joy and intense horror in a single night. In
early April, her first child, a daughter named Arianita was born in
a hospital in the southern Kosovo city of Prizren amid Serb attacks
and NATO bombs. Ten minutes after she gave birth, the electricity
was cut and explosions rattled the windows of the delivery room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so happy when I saw the baby. She looked so healthy and
now I was a mother. But the ugly part of the world was not far
away,'' Lushnaj recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the more than 800,000 ethnic Albanian refugees pushed
out of Kosovo by Yugoslav and Serb military forces and paramilitary
gangs are women and children. Most are families without husbands
and fathers, as many young men were either forcefully separated
from their families, or chose to break away and join the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA).
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the trauma of their expulsion from Kosovo and
difficult new life as refugees, the women have been thrust into
new, unfamiliar roles as single parents and the sole providers of
emotional stability and sustenance for their children.
</P>
<P>
   After Lushnaj gave birth to her daughter, the next day with her
consent, her husband, Avdi, kissed his wife and baby good-bye and
escaped to the mountains cast his lot with a KLA guerilla group
that is barely holding its own against Serb forces inside Kosovo,
the embattled southern province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, she and her newborn were fleeing across the
border of Albania and into a chaotic new world of food-handouts,
water rations and daily apprehension over what the future will be.
</P>
<P>
   For some, especially those from the smaller towns and rural
villages, most daily tasks outside the home, even fetching bread
from the local bakery or fuel for the stove, were tasks handled by
the men. Now, they struggle to learn how to acquire disposable
diapers and milk for their babies, and whether there will be a
school for their older children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women are now the decision-makers and the ripple effect on
the children of a disorganized, distraught or confused
decision-maker is extensive,'' said Christina Moore, a clinical
psychologist working in Kukes for the nonprofit aid group Medecins
Sans Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders).
</P>
<P>
   The women struggle to adjust to life in the camps and answer the
incessant questions of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understand everything. Everyday they ask about their
father. Is he safe? Does
</P>
<P>
   he have enough to eat? I tell them we will go home soon. Your
father is alive and he has plenty,'' said Hyrie Trolli, 27, who
fled with her two sons, Agron 9, and Arben, 7, while her husband,
Muq, stayed behind.
</P>
<P>
   Tears well in her eyes and her voice drops to a whisper, out of
range of her sons: ``But I don't believe it. I've lost the hope. I
don't think I'll meet him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists say the ethnic Albanian refugees are fortunate
that their Kosovo society was close-knit and extended families --
uncles, aunts, cousins and grandparents -- often lived in the same
house. That support system has been transplanted to the refugee
camps, with older uncles or grandfathers stepping in to the
father's role.
</P>
<P>
   As for the women, Moore has found that many are coping by doing,
in a fashion she equates with the Rosie-the-riveter phenomenon of
World War II, when American women quickly and effectively filled
the jobs of men who had gone off to war.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp distinction of the Kosovar refugees is the extreme
trauma many of the women themselves have experienced in being
uprooted from their lives and forced into a life as castaways in a
foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, they find comfort in the fact that they are not
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps enormously that they are surrounded by women who've
had the same terrible experiences,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other women in the camps are enduring the same
hardships. In the Kukes I camp, an entire row of tents are filled
with women and children from the same village, Dragacina, which
also was the home of the young mother, Lushnaj.
</P>
<P>
   The new mother, Lushnaj, arrived in the refugee camp anemic,
dehydrated and unable to breastfeed. Italian doctors treated her,
gave her fluids and made her healthy again.
</P>
<P>
   But the pain of separation from her husband, and concern for her
new baby are not so easily soothed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said good-bye and kept repeating: 'Take good care of the
baby. Take good care of the baby.' He repeated these words and 'I
hope I see you again.' He repeated them over and over until he
finally walked away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
