<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8441 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BACKSTREETBOYS-TEX     06-01 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACKSTREETBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKSTREET BOYS ARE BACK _ ON TOP OF THE CHARTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   The country giant's record for one-week CD sales in the United
States has just been broken by pop disposables the Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando, Fla.-based quintet sold 1.13 million copies of its
new CD, Millennium, the first week it hit the bins. That shattered
Brooks' record of 1.08 million, set less than six months ago with
Double Live.
</P>
<P>
   The pop music industry is, obviously, playing a very cruel joke
on Garth. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Brooks writes a healthy chunk of his lyrics. The Backstreet Boys
write, well, some of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks can play an instrument. The Backstreet Boys do not or
cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks can sing. The Backstreet Boys? Take away the slick
production and the coats of honey-glazed, factory-made harmonies
poured on their records _ and you've got a definite maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The Backstreet Boys, in other words, are being nicely rewarded
for being mediocre. They're the Titanic and Felicity of pop music _
middle-of-the-road, squeaky-clean, annoyingly cute pin-ups who,
like the casts of Titanic and Felicity, have discovered the secret
of success: teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age girls _ or their moms _ are the ones who've scooped up
the Boys' two efforts, Millennium and its 7-million-selling
predecessor, 1997's Backstreet Boys, the group's debut.
</P>
<P>
   They're the ones who, for the past several weeks, were glued to
MTV, watching the Boys count down to Millennium's May 18 arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, MTV _ the driving force behind Backstreet Boys'
teeny-bop-pop winning ticket. Over the past several weeks, the Boys
have been a constant staple on MTV _ hosting shows, doing
interviews, plugging their new single and video, I Want It That
Way.
</P>
<P>
   The Backstreet Boys aren't any better or worse than 'N Sync or
C-Note; they're simply masters of mass marketing. After seeing the
group on MTV 24-7, of course you're gonna go out and buy the
record. And when 'N Sync puts out a new disc, the same thing will
probably happen. And, again, it will work.
</P>
<P>
   But pop music survives _ and thrives _ on such vicious cycles:
Today's mega-hot 'N Sync or 98 Degrees is tomorrow's Jordan Knight,
an embarrassment, a joke, a slice of a memory for some girl who,
years ago, used to plaster her bedroom with New Kids on the Block
posters but now won't even admit to owning one of their tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The Backstreet Boys _ don't worry, they'll get theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, though, what they offer isn't that bad. Their music
is a place where a 14-year-old girl can live out her junior-high
fantasies: the relationship that will never crumble, the boyfriend
who will never cheat, promises that'll never be broken. ``Don't
care what you do/As long as you love me,'' the Boys guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Their music does not reflect the cold realities of growing up in
1999: school shootings, drug overdoses, abusive parents, teen
pregnancy, AIDS. The closest the Backstreet Boys come to touching
on reality: One of 'em has a coupla tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   You want them that way, though. You want them to keep singing
their sweet, pretty songs about falling in love. You want them to
remain clean and cute.
</P>
<P>
   Anything's better, you figure, than your kid liking Marilyn
Manson.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Backstreet Boys are as harmless and temporary as
the group waiting to take their place _ 98 Degrees, Five, C-Note,
whoever. But for the next few minutes, girls will continue to buy
their records, get Mom and Dad to foot the bill for posters,
T-shirts, concert tickets. And more records set by artists with
more talent will probably be broken.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as quickly as it all came along, it will all go away _
until the next new clone on the block moves in.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
