   &UR; FINANCIAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE-SMALL-CAP (Undated) _ Spurred by the strengthening
economy, frenetic takeover activity, and hints of higher inflation
that would make it easier for smaller firms to raise prices,
small-company stock indexes have jumped 10 percent since April
after lagging larger companies by the widest margins in a
generation. But even small-cap fans aren't sure these stocks will
ever approach the valuations they often achieved in the past. By
Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES&AMP;NOBLE-AMAZON (Undated) _ How does the almost certain
collapse of the Ingram deal affect Barnes &AMP; Noble's catch-up
strategy against Amazon.com? By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-ONLINE (Undated) _ The rapidly changing world of online
trading: Merrill Lynch announces plans to give all its five million
clients access to online trading by the end of the year and
E(asterik)Trade Inc. says it will buy Telebanc Financial, an online
bank, in a stock deal valued at about $1.8 billion. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   LIBERTY-MEDIA (Undated) _ Liberty Media Group, the
cable-television programming company, says it will buy Associated
Group Inc. for $2.8 billion, giving it a nationwide wireless phone
and Internet network. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDUCATION  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON-JEWS (Princeton, N.J.) _ Jewish enrollment at
Princeton University has fallen 40 percent since the high-water
mark of the early 1980s, and Jewish students and faculty members
are asking why. Campus life for Jews, they say, has never been
better. By Karen W. Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HALAL-BUTCHERS (New York) _ In almost any neighborhood in
America where Muslims make their home, halal meat shops are the new
butchers in an old-fashioned way. And as the production of meat
nationwide becomes increasingly industrialized, analysts say that
Halal meat is nevertheless the fastest growing style of specialty
butchering in the country. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-CAKES (New York) _ The party cake has become an
over-the-top symbol of creativity and, some would say, competitive
excess. By Monique Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUE-SAUCE (Undated) _ Beyond the basic barbecue sauce. By
Steven Raichlen. With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PUSHKIN-ANNIVERSARY (Moscow) _ With days to go before the 200th
anniversary of the birth of Russia's greatest and most beloved
poet, it is a wonder that Russians are not sick of Aleksandr
Pushkin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-MOCA _ The Massachusets Museum of Contemporary Art, the
sprawling visual and performing arts center that opened last
weekend, looks like a museum that the Shakers might have built, if
the Shakers had liked very large, multi-media works of art and
performance events poised on the cutting-edge of computer imaging
technology. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CALDER-SCULPTURE (Undated) _ An important Alexander Calder
sculpture, once promised to the Whitney Museum of American Art but
sold at auction to an anonymous private collector two weeks ago,
may be headed to the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art instead. By
Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   MASTERPIECE-NEWSLETTER (Undated) _ There's now a newsletter for
``Masterpiece Theater'' fanatics. By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY-THEATER-REVIEW _ Wilborn Hampton reviews Beckett's ``Happy
Days'' at the Jean Cocteau theater.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-REMEMBERED (New York) _ D.J.R. Bruckner reviews
``Tennessee Williams Remembered'' at ArcLight.
</P>
<P>
   TRANCE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Eder reviews ``Paris
Trance,'' by Geoff Dyer (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux).
</P>
