<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      06-01 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH SOLE IN A CALIFORNIA POT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This is the second of eight columns by Thomas Keller, the chef and
owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, Calif. He is also the
author, with Michael Ruhlman and Susie Heller, of ``The French
Laundry Cookbook'' (October 1999, Artisan). His collaborator on
these columns is Ruhlman.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Classic French cuisine has long had a reputation in this country
for being stuffy and rigid, but the opposite, in fact, is true:
classic French cuisine is dynamic and infinitely renewable, a
source I return to again and again for ideas and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   During my five years at the restaurant, I have served hundreds
of original dishes. They didn't just materialize out of air. Almost
every one of them has a reference to something that came before it,
and this dish is a good example of how a classic preparation can be
transformed into something that feels both modern and regional.
</P>
<P>
   I learned sole Veronique when I was a young cook, and it was
straight out of Escoffier's 1903 text, Le Guide Culinaire. A piece
of sole is folded into a package and poached in a little fish
stock, lemon juice and wine; this liquid, called a cuisson, is
reduced and mounted with butter to make the sauce, and the plate is
garnished with very cold skinned grapes.
</P>
<P>
   I fixed on this preparation because it uses grapes, and I am
cooking in the heart of the California wine country. Right now, I'm
using the perlette grape, a round green variety that keeps its
crunch after you peel it and has a slightly acidic quality that
enhances the fish and offsets the rich sauce.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the fact that a flat piece of fish was folded to give it
more dimension. I decided to add another layer of complexity by
stuffing this package. I couldn't stuff it with fresh grapes
because of their size and water content, but dried grapes, I
thought, would work perfectly. I use California raisins, bound with
rich brioche, herbs and butter. This simple notion of stuffing adds
contrasting colors, flavors and textures (most notably the chewy
raisins) to what had been a plain piece of fish.
</P>
<P>
   Then I wrap the fish in plastic and poach it in water _ a great
technique that's easy, efficient and especially good for this dish.
It lets the delicate stuffed fish hold its shape, and it makes it
possible to cook many portions at the same time. (I use this
technique, which I call ``boil in a bag,'' for various poultry
dishes as well.)
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce, I enrich a reduced fumet with hollandaise and
cream. Then I glaze the dish beneath a broiler and garnish it with
peeled seedless green grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe looks long, but it's really not so daunting if you do
it in stages. In fact, it's perfect for a dinner party, because
everything other than making the hollandaise and poaching the fish
can be done a day head. And there's little guesswork: the packages
cook perfectly every time because the temperature of the water is
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced to its essence, sole Veronique is fish and grapes. My
sole Veronique has additional flavors and textures, but because
I've stayed within the perimeters of a classic French preparation,
the dish doesn't feel confusing or overwrought. And now it is a
quintessential Napa Valley dish, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILLET OF SOLE VERONIQUE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 30 minutes, plus 1 to 2 hours for soaking fish
bones
</P>
<P>
   2 1}- to 2-pound whole gray sole, each cut into 4 fillets, bones
reserved for fish fumet For the fish fumet:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces (1\ cup) sliced button mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sliced onion
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sliced leeks
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   } cup sauvignon blanc or other dry white wine For the stuffing:
</P>
<P>
   [ cup sultanas (golden raisins)
</P>
<P>
   [ cup black raisins
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups diced brioche (\ inch by \ inch) or Pepperidge Farms
thin-sliced white bread
</P>
<P>
   1\ tablespoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   [ cup melted butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground white pepper to taste For the
hollandaise sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   \ cup melted clarified butter
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon lemon juice For the glacage:
</P>
<P>
   } cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   \ cup unsweetened whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   16 white seedless grapes for garnish (peeled and cut in half if
you wish).
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare a fish fumet: cut the fish bones into 2-inch pieces,
and soak in cold water until all traces of blood are gone, 1 to 2
hours. In a 4-quart saucepan over medium heat, heat the canola oil
and add the drained bones. Cover, and allow to steam 2 minutes. Add
the mushrooms, onions, leeks, parsley, wine and 3 cups of water.
Bring to a boil; then reduce heat to low. Simmer, partly covered,
30 minutes. (During this time, prepare the stuffing.) Remove from
heat, and let the fumet settle for 10 minutes. Place a clean
kitchen towel over a bowl, and pour the fumet through the towel;
avoid straining the sediment that has settled to the bottom of the
pan. Pour 2 cups of the fumet into a medium saucepan and set aside;
refrigerate or freeze the remainder for another purpose.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare the stuffing: in a small saucepan over low heat,
combine the sultanas and the black raisins with \ cup water. Simmer
until all the water is absorbed and the raisins have plumped, about
8 minutes. In a large mixing bowl, combine the diced brioche,
chopped parsley, shallots and melted butter. Drain the raisins on
paper towels, and add to the mixture. Season with salt and white
pepper to taste, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare the hollandaise sauce: in a 1-quart stainless steel
mixing bowl or the top of a double boiler, combine the egg yolk
with 1 tablespoon water. Place the bowl over simmering water, and
whisk the yolk until it thickens and resembles mayonnaise. Remove
from the heat, and slowly whisk in the clarified butter and lemon
juice. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prepare the glacage: place the saucepan of fish fumet over
medium-high heat and bring to a boil. Reduce the fumet to about \
cup. Add the heavy cream to the fumet, and reduce the mixture to a
total of } cup. While the mixture is still hot, whisk in the
hollandaise sauce, followed by the whipped cream. Keep in a warm
place; do not reboil.
</P>
<P>
   5. Fill a large casserole half full of water, place over
medium-high heat and bring to a simmer. Place the sole fillets
between pieces of plastic wrap, and pound lightly with a kitchen
mallet to flatten to an even thickness. Place the fillets on a flat
surface with the skinned side up. Season with salt and pepper to
taste. Put equal amounts of stuffing on each fillet, and roll the
fillets around the stuffing. Place each rolled fillet on a piece of
plastic wrap, and roll tightly, securing each end with a knot.
Transfer the sole packets to the simmering water, and cook 5
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, cut one end of each sole packet. Lightly press the
uncut end, and the rolled sole will slide out. Divide the glacage
evenly among 8 or 4 plates, place the stuffed sole in the center,
and garnish with the grapes. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 as a first course, or 4 as an entree.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
