<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRILL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-01 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BOBBY FLAY'S BOY MEETS GRILL': COOKING UP CELEBRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Bobby Flay's latest book, ``Bobby Flay's Boy Meets Grill''
(Hyperion, 1999), there is a lot of Bobby. He appears on no less
than 20 pages. And on most pages lacking the freckle-faced Flay,
there is his name in large block letters.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity cookbooks are nothing new; Sophia Loren, Patti LaBelle
and, of course, Martha Stewart have all sold plenty of them. But it
is a little different when a serious chef fits himself into this
mold.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Flay's television shows may be satisfied with a volume
of flattering photographs. But cooks are another story.
</P>
<P>
   Flay, the chef at Bolo and Mesa Grill in Manhattan, didn't
always take this approach. His first two books, ``Bobby Flay's Bold
American Food'' (Warner Books, 1994) and ``Bobby Flay's From My
Kitchen To Your Table'' (Clarkson N. Potter, 1998), were flashy and
exciting, and contained real information and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just a year since his last book, Flay has cranked out this
volume. He offers few lessons, and the recipes, though they work,
feel stretched and strained.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the steamed clams with chili coconut broth. The dish is
delicious, but the route from beginning to finish feels a bit like
going south to get north. You begin with a large pot on the stove,
in which you assemble a fragrant broth of garlic, ginger, coconut
milk, clam juice and spinach. The clams are then added to this hot
broth. At this point, all you need to do to is put a lid on the pot
and turn the heat to high.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a grill cookbook, and Flay has found a way to
include one. He has you haul the heavy, hot pot out to the grill to
steam. Not only is this dangerous and illogical, but who has a
grill with a cover that can accommodate a pot holding 80 clams?
Flay also offers recipes for risotto on the grill and meats sauteed
in a pan on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, Flay writes, ``Simplicity is the whole
thing in grilling start to finish.'' He extols the importance of
quality meats and fish.
</P>
<P>
   And then he smothers perfectly good cuts of meat and pieces of
fish in loads of heavily spiced sauces. Do people really want lamb
chops with a tarragon marinade and pineapple pecan relish? Even a
basic hamburger is loaded up with double Cheddar cheese, grilled
Vidalia onions and horseradish mustard _ a big, bright, scary
construction that looks as if it could take your jaw out of joint.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Flay is recycling already. Grilled onion marmalade is
almost identical to a recipe in his first book. The technique
differs slightly _ the onions are, of course, grilled in the new
book _ but the essential ingredients remain the same: red onions,
red wine vinegar, creme de cassis, grenadine and red wine. He does
the same sort of repetition with two tuna and mango dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Flay is a talented chef with two highly successful restaurants.
And he is young, just 34. His cooking should be evolving, and his
legions of fans _ of his cooking shows, ``Hot Off the Grill'' and
``Grillin' and Chillin,''' both on the Food Network, and his
restaurants _ should benefit from observing it happen through his
books. But nothing about this new book signals growth in his
cooking, just growth in his celebrity. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LITTLENECK CLAMS STEAMED IN GREEN CHILI-COCONUT MILK BROTH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Bobby Flay's Boy Meets Grill'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 poblano peppers
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil, more for brushing
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 large red onion, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peeled and coarsely chopped ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 cups clam juice
</P>
<P>
   1 14-ounce can unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 serrano or jalapeno pepper, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   { cup packed spinach leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   80 littleneck clams, scrubbed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat a gas or charcoal grill to high. Brush poblano peppers
with olive oil, and season with salt and pepper. Grill until
charred on all sides. Place in bowl, cover with plastic wrap and
let sit for 15 minutes; then peel, halve, seed and coarsely chop
peppers.
</P>
<P>
   2. Reduce grill heat to medium high. On stove, heat oil in large
enamel-coated Dutch oven or any other large, shallow pot until
almost smoking. Add onion, and cook until soft, for 4 to 5 minutes.
Add garlic and ginger, and cook for 2 minutes. Add wine, and reduce
mixture until almost dry. Add clam juice, coconut milk and poblano
and serrano peppers, and bring to boil. Add spinach leaves, and
cook until just wilted, 1 to 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. In batches, transfer mixture to blender, add { cup water and
blend until smooth. Return mixture to pot, and bring to boil. Add
honey, and season with salt and pepper. Add clams, stir, cover and
place on the grill. Cover grill, and cook until all clams open, for
10 to 12 minutes. (Or keep pot on stove, turn heat to high and cook
until clams open, about 10 to 12 minutes.) To serve, pour clams and
their broth into large serving bowl. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
