<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURDOCK-WEED-NYT &LR;      06-01 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURDOCK-WEED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WONDERFUL ROOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MELISSA CLARK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On most farms and suburban lawns, burdock is the
enemy, a tenacious, burr-covered weed. But that's only what burdock
reveals of itself above ground. Below, as good cooks are coming to
realize, is a wonderful root.
</P>
<P>
   It has a crunchy, firm texture, which can stand up to being
lightly sauteed, steamed or pickled. When slowly braised, simmered
or boiled, the root shows its mellow side and becomes meltingly
tender. Cooked in broth or water, burdock tastes delicately of
artichokes, mushrooms and potatoes, reminiscent of salsify. The
high heat of roasting or grilling concentrates its flavor and
brings out a nutty sweetness like a parsnip. (Chefs debate whether
it's better to cook burdock peeled or unpeeled, but since the peel
contains much of the flavor, most burdock lovers just give the root
a good, long scrub.)
</P>
<P>
   Alex Paffenroth, the owner of Paffenroth Gardens, a farm in
Warwick, N.Y., says that for years he ignored the burdock growing
wild on his onion farm, until he started selling onions at farmers'
markets. Then he began to look for more interesting crops to offer,
and a friend suggested burdock, which he noticed on sale in
Chinatown. Paffenroth planted a garden variety developed in Japan,
because it has a straight, carrotlike taproot, which is easier to
harvest than the wild variety. Now, he sells organic burdock for $4
a pound at the Greenmarket in Union Square. And he keeps a sign
next to the bin explaining what it is and how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Berley, the chef of Angelica's Kitchen, needs no lesson.
``I'm crazy about burdock,'' he said. ``It's got this amazing,
loamy smell and really tastes like you're eating something from the
soil.'' Angelica's goes through 50 pounds of burdock a week.
</P>
<P>
   Even if chefs don't always mention it on their menus, some use
it as a crunchy garnish or to sweeten and enhance a sauce. Michel
Nishan, the chef at Heartbeat, takes advantage of the root's
sticklike shape and stacks it like Lincoln logs into a little
house, which he fills with a root vegetable slaw. At Tropica,
Franck Deletrain gives humble burdock lavish treatment, serving it
with fluke sashimi and an osetra vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't know what it is, it can spark a conversation,
and they'll learn something new,'' said Rocco DiSpirito, the chef
of Union Pacific. ``I like when an ingredient can do that.''
DiSpirito uses pickled burdock in an appetizer of head cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gesualdi, the chef at the Tonic, solves the unfamiliarity
problem by dicing the root and frying it into luscious little
fritters. Most diners eat it without question as a tempting party
hors d'oeuvres.
</P>
<P>
   But some chefs revel in burdock's strangeness. Normand Laprise
of Cena discovered burdock when he was traveling in Japan, where it
is called ``gobo.'' It makes an appearance at most Japanese meals,
either dyed bright orange and pickled or slivered and simmered in
stews and soups. At Cena, Laprise uses it all season long, from
January to July. After that, local burdock becomes slightly bitter.
</P>
<P>
   He's currently serving burdock pureed into a sweet soup and
roasted, with sauteed morels, a poached egg and caviar. ``I think
maybe it's because winter is so long in Quebec, but I love to use
different local root vegetables, and burdock grows all over
Canada,'' said Laprise, who is from Montreal. ``It must like the
cold.''
</P>
<P>
   As a plant that originated in Siberia, burdock should. Now, it
flourishes in cool climates all over the world. It probably made
its way to the Americas stubbornly stuck to the fur of livestock.
But even those sticky, prickly burrs have something to redeem them.
Apparently, they were the inspiration for Velcro. And everyone
knows what that is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERIYAKI-STYLE BURDOCK AND CARROT SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Peter Berley, Angelica's Kitchen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus 1 hour's chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound burdock root, scrubbed
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds carrots, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup mirin
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces ginger root, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches watercress
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sesame seeds, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Slice burdock and carrots into matchsticks. In a heavy pan,
whisk together honey, soy sauce, mirin, apple cider, sesame oil and
ginger.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add vegetables to pan, and bring mixture to a boil over high
heat. Reduce heat to low; cover, and simmer 30 minutes or until
vegetables are tender.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer the vegetables and marinade to a bowl, and let them
cool. Cover, and chill for at least 1 hour. Serve over watercress,
and garnish with scallions, sesame seeds and lemon. Yield: 4
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHILLED BURDOCK SOUP WITH RHUBARB JELLY, MINT OIL AND HERBS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Normand Laprise, Cena &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus 3 hours' chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound burdock root, peeled and cut into {-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 cups vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup mint leaves, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Rhubarb jelly (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons freshly chopped herbs, such as chervil, chives, or
parsley.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium soup pot, heat olive oil over medium-high heat
and saute onions until soft, about 10 minutes. Add burdock, stock
and milk; bring to a boil. Cover and simmer 30 minutes, until
burdock is tender.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a blender, puree soup. Strain through a sieve to remove
fibers. Chill at least 3 hours. Season with salt and pepper to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a small bowl, stir together oil and mint. Ladle soup into
bowls; put a tablespoon of rhubarb jelly in a mound in center. Dot
soup with mint oil and garnish with herbs. Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RHUBARB JELLY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes, plus 2 hours chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   { of a lemongrass stalk, pounded with the side of a knife and
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup peeled, diced rhubarb
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon powdered unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sherry vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small saucepan, bring 1/3 cup water, sugar and
lemongrass to a simmer over medium heat. Remove from heat and let
rest 15 minutes. Strain through a sieve and discard solids.
</P>
<P>
   2. Return syrup to saucepan and bring it back to a simmer. Add
rhubarb; simmer 1 minute. Turn off heat, add gelatin and stir
gently to dissolve it. Stir in sherry vinegar and transfer mixture
to a small bowl. Chill until set, about 2 hours. Yield: { cup.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
