<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY FOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's fun to re-introduce a classic, once commonplace dish that
has all but vanished from the repertory of most home cooks. It's
even better when you can make it a little bit better.
</P>
<P>
   The dish is the fool, a sublimely easy spring and summer fruit
dessert that is little more than fruit and stiffly whipped cream,
sweetened with sugar. The fool can be made with almost any fruit _
even stone fruits like mangoes or peaches _ but is best with
berries, especially strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Fools can be stiffened with gelatin or enriched with eggs, but
my recent experiments show both additions to be wasted effort. The
eggs add an unnecessary degree of luxury, and the gelatin makes the
fool too much like the Jell-O salads I remember from the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Yet playing around with the recipe led me to what I consider an
improvement. I used to cut up the berries, sugar them, then crush
them with a potato masher before folding in the cream. This time, I
pureed half the berries and left the other half in quarter-inch
thick chunks. I was pleased with the results, in which pink whipped
cream enrobed slightly chewy berries.
</P>
<P>
   If you have perfectly ripe, sweet berries, you may reduce the
sugar called for by half. On the other hand, some berries are so
tart that you will need more. I add a bit of vanilla extract to the
cream for flavor, but you can consider this optional, or substitute
any flavored liqueur. Most people will advise you to whip cream
with perfectly cold implements, and this is worthwhile if you are
working by hand. But an electric mixer makes such fast work of the
job that the danger is in overwhipping. Stop beating as soon as the
cream holds peaks that do not droop.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a fool should be eaten right away, before the juice
from the berries thins the cream. But the method here allows you to
prepare the fool an hour or two in advance without a loss in
quality; just cover it in the refrigerator until you're ready to
eat it.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: The same ingredients can be combined nearly as
swiftly to produce the simplest possible fruit gratin, a gently
warmed, lightly caramelized version of a fool that is no more
delicious but slightly more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   STRAWBERRY FOOL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Hull strawberries, then wash them and chop into \-inch thick
pieces. Toss with half the sugar and wait 10 minutes, stirring
occasionally, until they give up their juices.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place half the strawberries and all the juice in a blender
and puree. Pour puree back in bowl with chopped strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   3. Whip the cream with remaining sugar and vanilla until cream
is stiff and holds peaks easily. Fold berries and cream together
and serve immediately, or refrigerate for up to two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: To make a gratin, preheat broiler, setting rack close
to heat source. Hull and slice berries, and toss them in a gratin
dish with half the sugar. Beat cream with half the remaining sugar
and the vanilla, just until it holds soft peaks. Top berries with
cream and sprinkle with remaining sugar. Broil carefully, rotating
dish so that cream browns all over. Remove and serve.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
