<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMET-WINSLOWBOY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAMET, KNOWN FOR RAW, POWERFUL PLAYS, DIRECTS A GENTEEL MOVIE ABOUT
HEROISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Winslow Boy'' is a first for writer-director David Mamet,
best known for his writing for the theater, including the plays
``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' ``Oleanna,'' ``American Buffalo'' and
``Sexual Perversity in Chicago'' (which became the movie ``About
Last Night''). It's one of several firsts, actually.
</P>
<P>
   For one, it's the first piece Mamet has directed that he didn't
write, having come from the 1946 Terence Rattigan play about a
British family involved in a legal battle to prove their young
son's innocence after he's thrown out of military school.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the first Mamet film that qualifies for a G rating.
Unlike such characters as the foul-mouthed real estate salesmen in
``Glengarry Glen Ross'' _ which brought Mamet the Pulitzer Prize in
1984, as well as his generally accepted title as America's leading
playwright _ the genteel characters in ``Winslow'' lack the profane
punch common to his plays and other movies.
</P>
<P>
   Just as importantly, though, ``The Winslow Boy'' is Mamet's
first unabashed look at heroism.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of `Winslow Boy,' their struggle has cost them, it
would seem, everything,'' he says. ``They gave up their health,
their wealth, their prospects, their emotional stability. And at
the end this question is, `Is it worth it?' And that, to me, is the
question of the movie, because it's an open question.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Mamet's own writing does, ``Winslow Boy'' delves into
the differences between what's right and what's just. It also has
the kind of dramatic surprise you'd expect in a Mamet work, even
though the kind of Old Testament evil that hovers over Mamet
material such as ``The Verdict'' and ``The Untouchables'' isn't to
be found here.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet's interest in ``Winslow Boy'' is in line with his own
Chicago background. His works portray a working-class interest in
digging straight to the heart of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about Chicago,'' he says, ``is people say
writing is not an ethereal, ivory tower profession. It's just the
profession of somebody who can write. It's that strong tradition of
playwrights and newspaper writers becoming novelists. Chicago is
the spiritual home of Theodore Dreiser and Richard Wright and
Sherwood Anderson. People who looked around and said, `What's going
on in the world?' The tradition of the working man and the working
woman as individual thinkers is very much a Midwest tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look at Chicago theater,'' he offers. ``There was Second
City, which I kinda came out of, because I used to work (there) as
a busboy when I was 13, 14 years old. I saw Robert Klein there, and
Peter Boyle, David Steinberg, and the great Fred Willard. And
before them, there was the Compass Players, with Mike Nichols and
Elaine May. Those guys were cultural heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago theater that Mamet helped create in the 1970s was
like the punk movement, where anger and a hunger to shake things up
were motivating factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my generation,'' Mamet muses, ``there was a spontaneous
groundswell of people who just came out of the streets _ people in
their 20s _ who just started putting on plays. We didn't know any
better, and we were too young to be careerist. That was the Chicago
theater of the time. By accident, I got a job teaching theater at
this college in Vermont. And a couple of guys I'd been working with
_ they were 21 and I was 22 _ came back to Chicago with me and we
started a theater. One of them was William H. Macy.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the depth of talent in Chicago in those days,
Mamet cites the first reading of his play ``American Buffalo.'' It
was performed by, among others, Joey Mantegna and Dennis Franz,
then members of the Organic Theater, along with Mesach Taylor, John
Heard and the late J.T. Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   It was during that period that Mamet turned to directing his own
work, out of the simplest motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to New York,'' he remembers, ``and was hawking my plays
around and other people were directing my plays and I would nod and
say, maybe they know better than I do. Then after a while, I
thought, even if they do know better than I do, I'd rather do it
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   That he has done. Fluidly moving between stage and screen, he
broke into the movie business with the reworking of the script for
``The Postman Always Rings Twice'' in 1981 and then directed his
own script for the film ``House of Games'' in 1987. Since then, he
has directed his own scripts for the movies ``Things Change,
Homicide'' and ``Oleanna.'' And last year, he had an art-house hit
with the film ``The Spanish Prisoner.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7032. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
