<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MELISSA CLARK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Chinese Flatbread &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many years ago at a Mongolian barbecue restaurant in New
Jersey, I was served little pan-fried breads, relatively flat and
no bigger than an index card. They were plain but for the sesame
seeds on top. The restaurant has since closed, and I have searched
high and low for a recipe. Can you help? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Those flaky breads are called shao bing, a term that loosely
translates as ``roasted cakes.'' They are an ancient staple:
traditionally, they were slapped against the searing sides of a
clay oven, where they adhered and baked. Now, they are pan-fried or
baked in a conventional oven.
</P>
<P>
   Shao bing can be split open, like small pita breads, and stuffed
with all manner of stir-fries to make sandwiches. The Chinese also
eat them for breakfast with bowls of warm soy milk. They are always
best eaten hot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cream of Tartar &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is cream of tartar, and how do you use it in baking? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Cream of tartar, or potassium acid tartrate, is a powder
either extracted from fresh grapes or derived from deposits that
accumulate on the insides of wine barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Most commonly, it is the acid component in baking powder that
makes cakes and cookies and quick breads rise. About \ teaspoon
baking soda plus { teaspoon cream of tartar yields the equivalent
of 1 teaspoon baking powder.
</P>
<P>
   Cream of tartar may also be added to fondant, pulled sugar and
frosting in order to produce a creamier consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Adding about [ teaspoon cream of tartar for each egg white
before beating will decrease alkalinity and make the final beaten
whites much more stable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Burned Pot: Safe to Use? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've burned a nice stainless-steel pot. It might have been
coated with something because it had a slightly chemical smell when
it burned. Is it still safe to cook with, or should I get rid of
it?
</P>
<P>
   A. If the pot is simply stainless steel, it should be perfectly
fine. Stainless steel does tend to discolor and may develop a
splotchy rainbow effect when exposed to high heat.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the pot had a nonstick coating, you would have to
maintain a temperature of 550 degrees or higher for at least three
hours in order for the coating to melt and burn. (After all that,
the pot could not be used again.)
</P>
<P>
   The odor you smelled could simply have been the smell of
burning. Or if the pot has plastic handles, it's possible that the
odor might have been the smell of the plastic as it softened in the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Substituting Potato Starch &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I make a flourless chocolate cake at Passover, could I
substitute potato starch for cornstarch and still get the same
results?
</P>
<P>
   A. You can, but you should use one and a half times as much
potato starch as cornstarch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1606EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-01 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCHANT WHO WASN'T AFRAID OF THE UNKNOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ One Saturday evening in 1947, a battered jalopy fueled
with black market gasoline jounced out of Paris in the direction of
the Loire Valley. At the wheel was Lucien Legrand, 31, and he was
off to buy some wine, which was not easy to find in Paris just
after the war.
</P>
<P>
   He needed a source of supply for his family's celebrated
epicerie, or luxury grocery store, at 1 rue de la Banque on the
Right Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew nothing about wine,'' he recalled many years later,
adding that he had been armed only with the name of a winemaker in
the town of Amboise. By Sunday night he was back in the city with a
barrel of dry white sauvignon d'Amboise, which he would bottle
himself. He had found his wine and his life's passion.
</P>
<P>
   Legrand Filles &AMP; Fils, Legrand's grocery with a large stock of
wine, is in the financial district, near the Bibliotheque National
and Comedie Francaise. As such, it has counted bankers,
stockbrokers and actors among its clientele.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Legrand died, on Feb. 15 at 83, he had become one of
France's most admired wine merchants.
</P>
<P>
   I first met Legrand some 20 years ago through a friend who had
invited me to visit the labyrinthine cellars under the Legrand
shop. They were said to have once been the catacombs of a church a
few blocks away. It was not a story Legrand was about to deny.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguished those cellars, and their proprietor, was an
absence of wines with famous names. Indeed, throughout his life,
Legrand was scornful of the hype that attended many well-known
wines. He was a fierce advocate of the simple, unembellished wines
from little-known vineyards all over France _ and of the artisans
who made them.
</P>
<P>
   He was never much of a fan of Bordeaux. ``I recognize the
quality of the great Bordeaux wines,'' he said, ``but for my taste,
they are too intellectual, too severe. They are not joyous, sensual
wines; they don't make you feel like celebrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Legrand was the enemy of all pretension. Fiona Beeston, a writer
who sold wine for him for five years, recalled her early days with
him. While she had been trained in the ``spit it all out'' school
of wine tasting, Legrand believed that ``you learned by drinking,
not tasting.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days when French businesses shut down for lunch, members
of the Legrand staff gathered at midday for a serious meal. In her
book ``Mes Hommes du Vin'' (Plon, 1989), Ms. Beeston described her
first Legrand lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he asked me what I thought of the wine, an unknown little
Marcillac, I ran down to the sales floor to get my special tasting
glass, hoping my palate was still clean,'' she wrote. ``When I
returned to the table, everyone was tucking into an enormous bowl
of tripe, the smell of which filled the room.
</P>
<P>
   When I said I couldn't taste like that, he broke out laughing
and said, `My God, it's not going to be easy to teach this
Englishwoman.' He gave me my wine in an old mustard jar and told me
to drink it with the food.''
</P>
<P>
   A slight man with a natty mustache, Legrand enjoyed talking
about wine as much as he did selling it. On my first visit, he
handed me a glass and asked my opinion. As I searched for words, he
delivered his own brief but impressive opinion, free of technical
jargon and the flowery inanities beloved of wine writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My passion is the little wines,'' he once said. ``Anyone can
buy a first growth; all you have to have is enough money. But to
discover a good everyday wine, ah, that's something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the early 1950s, he was an ardent supporter of
Beaujolais, then rarely drunk outside its region. He frowned on
chaptalization, the practice of adding sugar to Beaujolais to boost
its alcoholic content, and he didn't like sugar added to Champagne
to make it sweeter. He found and supported producers who would make
these wines for him in the unadorned styles he preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Legrand was proud to be a caviste, or wine merchant, but he
thought of himself principally as an epicier, a grocer. ``Before
the war, the epiciers were a strong, respected group in Paris,'' he
said, proud of the symbol of their trade, an impeccably white
apron.
</P>
<P>
   Legrand Filles &AMP; Fils, with its 1900s facade and elegant
interior, is still at 1 rue de la Banque, run by one of Lucien's
daughters, Francine. A son, Yves, runs a wine shop in
Issy-les-Moulineaux, outside Paris. Much of the Legrand store is
still occupied by a line of ancient coffee roasters that attracted
a loyal clientele before Legrand was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my parents' time, coffee was far more important than
wine,'' he once said. On a recent visit, his belief in little-known
producers could still be felt. Among the wines featured were a
Champagne from J.M. Tarlent and a fleurie from Domaine du Vissoux,
both difficult to find in France much less in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The windows of the back of the store face the Galerie Vivienne,
one of the hidden passageways filled with small shops that are a
feature of midtown Paris. In those windows are a vast selection of
corkscrews, glassware and other wine artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when Lucien liked to pause in the afternoon
for tea,'' Ms. Beeston recalled. ``There were some well-known
actresses who would slip in through the Galerie Vivienne to join
him. He loved it, even if his wife did not.''
</P>
<P>
   A true connoisseur, Legrand knew that wine is one of the good
things in life. But not the only thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
