<SLUG> BC-PHONE-ETIQUETTE-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE BLOOD OF ETIQUETTE OFFERS ADVICE ON CELL PHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Wireless phones seem to be everywhere these days.
Too bad they don't come with instructions on when to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Who better to lay some of the ground rules for mobile-phone
etiquette than Peggy Post, great-granddaughter-in-law to Emily
Post, author of ``Emily Post's Etiquette.''
</P>
<P>
   Post wrote the 75th anniversary edition (it's the 16th) of the
etiquette guide, and is a contributing editor at Good Housekeeping
and Parents magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless phones have become an accepted part of the way we
live today,'' Post said through a traditional telephone line.
Because the wireless phones can be used from virtually anywhere,
their users need to remember common-sense courtesy, she cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   The number of wireless-phone users in the United States has
grown from 1.6 million in 1988 to more than 69 million today,
according to Cellular One, an equipment and service provider, and
more than half of all Americans are expected to have wireless
phones by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey commissioned by Cellular One, New Yorkers
said wireless phones are most appropriate for safety, emergencies
and scheduling situations. (In fact, 98,000 people place 911 calls
each day from mobile phones.) However, a majority of those surveyed
didn't approve of using wireless phones during social gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2 percent of New Yorkers polled said they approved of
holding a phone conversation at the table, although 95 percent said
taking a call from a baby sitter is acceptable, and 75 percent had
no problem with work-related calls.
</P>
<P>
   Post stressed that the cell phone should never be placed on the
table during a meal.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Trimble, who with her husband, Geoff, owns La Serre
restaurant in Albany, sees that rule broken regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks ago, there was a party of four _ two couples
_ and one of the women was on the phone four times to her child,''
Trimble said. ``Her phone rang four times in less than an hour and
a half, and each call lasted five to six minutes. The wait staff
didn't know when to serve their food. If I had been the other
couple, I would have walked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Post recently joined forces with Cellular One to raise
wireless-etiquette awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Results from a nationwide survey indicated that many wireless
users need to improve their phone etiquette and put people ahead of
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted in eight states and four metropolitan
areas by Fleishman-Hillard Research in St. Louis. For the New York
state portion, 2,628 people responded from 33 upstate counties, in
Cellular One service areas. Of the New Yorkers surveyed, 56 percent
said they would rather visit the dentist than sit next to someone
talking on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting next to someone on a train in the New York City
area who was discussing very intimate details,'' Post said. ``I
found that to be very inappropriate. One should never discuss
confidential material that's social or work-related on a wireless
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones are technologically advanced so callers no longer
need to shout to be heard, Post said. But she still recommended
calling from a quiet or private place.
</P>
<P>
   Not inconveniencing others is the key, Post said. Whether you're
driving or standing in a checkout line, you should be paying
attention and not holding up anyone else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
