<SLUG> BC-TRANSSEXUAL-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSSEXUAL FILES SUIT OVER DENIAL OF POLICE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A male-to-female transsexual who was
disqualified from entering the San Francisco police academy after
failing a psychological test is suing the city, alleging gender
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Cristiana Rivas, 39, filed a lawsuit in San Francisco Superior
Court last month and is seeking damages for lost wages, humiliation
and embarrassment. Rivas said that one of the city's psychologists
referred to her as a cross-dresser while another questioned why she
didn't pursue a career in cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no doubt in my mind that I passed all the exams,''
said Rivas, a former employee with the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms. ``I don't have any psychological problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Christopher Rivas underwent a sex change operation and
also passed the San Francisco Police Department's written, oral,
lie-detector and physical tests, along with a thorough background
check.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, she quit her job with the federal agency to
prepare for enrollment in the police academy at the end of the
month. But then she was told she had failed the psychological
portion of her application and was, therefore, disqualified from
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't told why she had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Rivas filed a $3 million claim with Department of
Human Resources' Equal Employment Opportunity Division. It was
turned down in January. Rivas has appealed that decision to the
Civil Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   City officials deny any kind of gender discrimination claims and
say Rivas was screened out for other psychological reasons that
they cannot disclose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her gender was not the basis on which she was not accepted,''
said Lori Giorgi, the chief attorney for public protection in the
City Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgi said the psychological test found that Rivas was not
suitable.
</P>
<P>
   Rivas believes the department, or at least its psychiatrists,
are not comfortable dealing with transgender applicants because
they don't understand the issues. For example, Rivas said, she was
referred to as a cross-dresser during her first evaluation with the
city-affiliated psychiatrist, who then asked her to explain the
difference between cross-dressing and transsexualism.
</P>
<P>
   When Rivas was evaluated by an independent psychologist
following her appeal of her disqualification, she said, the
psychologist asked her whether she had patronized a bar known for
transsexual prostitution and whether she had considered working in
the cosmetics field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat there and just told him, `I'm a professional woman with
a professional degree, and I want a professional career,''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgi said investigators who handled Rivas' claim with the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission had looked into that
allegation and found it to be untrue.
</P>
<P>
   The psychologists ``emphatically deny that those statements were
made,'' Giorgi said. ``We don't ask about someone's gender
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Giorgi said the city would fight the lawsuit. She said Rivas and
any applicant had the right to take the exam again if they didn't
pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
