<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-THEMEPARK-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I KNOW HOW I SCREAMED THIS SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ I try to remember how to bend my knees and lift
my feet off the ground. It's either a hot flash or a demon theme
park thrill ride.
</P>
<P>
   I am on the grounds of Universal Studio's new Islands of
Adventure, next to a 30-acre dining and entertainment complex
called City Walk, next to three planned plush hotels.
</P>
<P>
   There must have been moments spent laughing and having a good
time, but my memory is flooded with dark flashes of me screaming,
screaming until my throat hurts, holding on so tight I bruised my
right leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not just theme park rides,'' says Steven Spielberg,
Universal's creative consultant. ``These are entertainment
achievements beyond anything I've ever seen anywhere else in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   At Islands of Adventure, which opened Friday just 15 miles down
the road from Disney World, the assault on your senses is at once
exhilarating and frightening.
</P>
<P>
   Spread across approximately 110 acres, the park features five
themed islands: Seuss Landing, Marvel Super Hero Island, Toon
Lagoon, the Lost Continent and Jurassic Park. Next door, visitors
can partake of CityWalk, an entertainment complex featuring themed
restaurants _ including one from celebrity chef Emeril Lagasse _ as
well as nightclubs, shops and a 20-screen, 5,000-seat movie
megaplex.
</P>
<P>
   When added to the existing 9-year-old theme park _ Universal
Studios Florida _ they make up Universal Studios Escape, a three-
or four-day vacation destination where families can eat, sleep and
play without ever leaving the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out, Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   THE PORT OF ENTRY AND BEYOND: ``When I was a kid, I couldn't
wait to get to the Magic Kingdom,'' the bus driver is telling me
after a long day at the park. ``I used to live to make the 30-hour
drive from New York here. But after seeing this, I don't even think
about Mickey.''
</P>
<P>
   If it didn't measure up before, Islands of Adventure easily
positions Universal Studios to do battle with the folks who brought
us Mickey Mouse and the Magic Kingdom more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the compactness of Universal's newest theme park
allows visitors to easily walk from one attraction to the next. At
Disney World, guests must take a monorail, bus or car to get from
one event to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Although I didn't sample every attraction _ mostly for lack of
guts _ the islands were close enough that I was able to walk the
entire distance in just a few hours. To take in more than the
sights, to indulge every taste bud, would require at least a couple
of days, especially with kids in tow.
</P>
<P>
   For another, guests are less likely to just stand in line at
Universal. Visitors learn the detailed ``back stories'' of the
major attractions through video and audio.
</P>
<P>
   I began at the beginning, the Port of Entry, and headed to Seuss
Landing, a whimsical and colorful place where the characters of
Theodor ``Dr. Seuss'' Geisel spring to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't wait to build this,'' said Lisa Girolami, Seuss
Landing's executive producer. ``When you're reading the books, the
characters literally jump off the page.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual to see the Cat in the Hat and Thing One and
Thing Two skipping around the park. If that isn't enough, go into
the house and take a seat on the couch for the Cat in the Hat ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Cat in the Hat invites Thing One and Thing Two inside and,
well, you know the story.
</P>
<P>
   If you liked the story at all, you'll love this up-close view
from the couch. The constant spinning put a pinch in my stomach,
but I'd endure anything to be near these characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing this world to life, we needed to tell the story,
including how bad greed and prejudice are, and the importance of
reading,'' said Girolami. ``We had to roll all of those things into
this land.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, I headed to the Lost Continent, home of the Dueling
Dragons double coaster, Poseidon's Fury and The Eighth Voyage of
Sinbad, a live-action show.
</P>
<P>
   I hated The Eighth Voyage of Sinbad. The acting is atrocious,
the lines worse, and they had the nerve to typecast an
African-American woman as the evil one. Did I mention I hated it?
</P>
<P>
   For Poseidon's Fury, visitors pass through a 42-foot-long water
vortex containing 17,500 gallons of swirling water into a kind of
theater-in-the-round for a battle between Poseidon (water) and his
archenemy Zeus (fire).
</P>
<P>
   As for the roller coaster _ I didn't have the nerve to do battle
with a dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to the Incredible Hulk roller coaster on Marvel
Super Hero Island. Evil. Evil. Evil. There was no way I was going
to get in this steel contraption.
</P>
<P>
   According to park officials, Hulk's propulsion G-force is the
same as that experienced by an F-16 pilot on takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   I did, however, partake of the amazing adventures of Spider-Man,
but only because my tour guide said it was a piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   She lied. I screamed so long and loud my throat hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the first to combine rapidly moving vehicles with
vivid sets, filmed action and pyrotechnic special effects, the ride
sweeps you into a raging battle between Spider-Man and a cast of
super-villains. The conflicts rage around, above and under you and
burst through movie screens straight at you.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor Octopus ultimately takes aim at riders with his Doomsday
Anti-gravity gun, which zaps you 400 feet into the air before
plunging you down the same 400 feet toward the dark street.
</P>
<P>
   You know it's not really happening, but it feels like it is. You
pray for your life.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   EDIBLE WONDERS: For the stomach, Islands of Adventure offers
everything from gourmet to green _ as in green eggs and ham ($5.29
with fries) at the Green Eggs and Ham Cafe in Seuss Landing. (The
eggs are colored with herbs, by the way.) Jurassic Park serves
half-pound dino burgers, and Toon Lagoon has such fare as Dagwood
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   For finer dining, Islands of Adventure offers Mythos on the Lost
Continent and the Confisco Grille at the Port of Entry. Mythos was
my favorite. Nestled in a massive volcanic rock formation, it is
perfect for a romantic evening.
</P>
<P>
   Guests sit on chairs that weigh 75 pounds each and cost more
than $500, but the prices were a little more reasonable. I had a
bowl of Maine lobster corn bisque ($4), pan-roasted fish provencale
with roasted garlic mashed potatoes ($13.50), and warm chocolate
banana gooey cake with peanut butter ice cream ($5.25) _ which I
would have delivered to me once a week if I could afford it.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's CityWalk, with its half-dozen shops, clubs and
restaurants, ranging from Emeril's _ operated by celebrity chef
Emeril Lagasse _ to Jimmy Buffet's Margaritaville, and from the
Hard Rock Cafe to the Motown Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   I loved Pat O'Brien's Orlando and the Latin Quarter _ with one
exception: half-naked women never did anything for me.
</P>
<P>
   LAY MY WEARY BODY DOWN: Once the day is over and your legs feel
like tons of steel, there's no better place to be than the
Portofino Bay Hotel. If you can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   The 750-room Portofino Bay, Universal's version of Portofino,
Italy, is scheduled to open Sept. 1. Guests will get complimentary
white robes, complimentary breakfast in the morning and
complimentary hors d'oeuvres in the evening. They will sleep on
big, high beds covered in white Egyptian cotton linens, so fluffy
they look like pillows of clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Portofino Bay is the first of five hotels planned at the theme
park. The Hard Rock Hotel will open in 2000, and the Royal Pacific
Resort in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   All the hotels will be connected to each other and to the theme
parks by a chain of scenic waterways. In addition to more
traditional forms of transportation, guests will be able to take
water taxis from their hotels to Universal destinations and back.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've visited the Islands of Adventure, you may think you
don't want to come back. But you will. Bone-tired,
sensory-overloaded, you'll have to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Those Marvel Super Heroes did me in. Oh, did I tell you about
the Jurassic Park River Ride? Dropped me 85 feet. I escaped
Tyrannosaurus Rex, but I think I hurt my leg.
</P>
<P>
   I need some sleep.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IT COSTS
</P>
<P>
   Admission to Islands of Adventure is $42 a day; $34 for ages 3
to 9; free for those under 3. Separate admission tickets are
required for Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Parking is $6.
</P>
<P>
   A soda is $2.
</P>
<P>
   Green eggs and ham and fries _ $5.29 at the Cat in the Hat Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Half-pound dino burger _ $4.99 in the Jurassic Park cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Pan-roasted corvina (fish) provencale with roasted garlic mashed
potatoes _ $13.50 at the Mythos restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirt, $18-$24
</P>
<P>
   Polo shirt, $30-$40
</P>
<P>
   Cat in the Hat hat, $15
</P>
<P>
   Betty Boop License Plate, $15
</P>
<P>
   Jurassic Park miner's helmet with lantern, $12
</P>
<P>
   Fossilized insect candy, $2.50
</P>
<P>
   Slinkies, yo-yos, rock candy _ $2-$6 at the Toon Toys shop in
Toon Lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   You can skip lines altogether, for a price. For $1,500 plus tax,
up to 15 people can take an eight-hour guided tour with unlimited
access to rides. A five-hour option is $110 a person. Reservations
are required. Call (407) 363-8295.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Islands of Adventure, call toll-free
(888) 837-2273.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A KID RATES THE PARK
</P>
<P>
   Cary Glines, 16, a junior at Palmetto High School in Miami,
rated Islands of Adventure for The Miami Herald:
</P>
<P>
   In an overall rating of this park from 1-10, I'd give it a 10.
</P>
<P>
   Incredible Hulk roller coaster: 10. It shoots up really fast,
and stays fast. And it's long.
</P>
<P>
   Dueling Dragons double roller coaster: 10. It's cool how you
come close together. It's fast the whole time.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor Doom's Freefall: Lame. You don't fall fast enough. (The
ride was running at half-speed during our preview visit.)
</P>
<P>
   Spider-Man ride: 9.5 ``It's not just a sit-down 3-D thing.''
(Said Annette Whitman, 18, of Tampa: ``It's the neatest thing I've
ever done.'')
</P>
<P>
   Jurassic Park River Adventure: 8. Cool, but not long enough.
(Pete McDaniel, 7, of Richmond, Va., loved it so much he wanted to
go again; brother David, 4, was less enthusiastic.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A MOM RATES THE PARK
</P>
<P>
   Intrepid Star-Telegram reporter Gracie Bonds Staples, mother of
two, filed this report:
</P>
<P>
   I also give the park a 10, but I was bothered by much of the
violence and didn't have the guts to get on many of the rides.
</P>
<P>
   Incredible Hulk roller coaster: Evil.
</P>
<P>
   Dueling Dragons double roller coaster: Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor Doom's Freefall: Et cetera.
</P>
<P>
   Spider-Man ride: Even if it is make-believe 3-D action, who
wants to fall 400 feet? Believe me, this doesn't feel like play.
</P>
<P>
   Jurassic Park River Ride: Same here. If you ask me, there's not
much difference between dropping 85 feet and 400 feet.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
