<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESIDENTIAL-PAY02-CO     06-01 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESIDENTIAL-PAY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GROUPS WANT CANDIDATES TO OPPOSE PRESIDENTIAL PAY HIKE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An alliance of conservatives and liberals asked
presidential contenders Tuesday to oppose a move doubling the
salary of the job they are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president suffers no real privations,'' said a letter that
asked the candidates how they stand on a congressional effort to
increase the pay to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know,'' it continued, ``the President currently enjoys
a salary of $200,000 per year, with perquisites, a $50,000 expense
allowance, living expense benefits that befit a king, plus a near
certain prospect, if desired, of becoming a multimillionaire upon
leaving office.''
</P>
<P>
   Signers of the letter included liberals such as consumer
activist Ralph Nader and the environmentalist Green Party, as well
as conservative leader Paul Weyrich of the Free Congress
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   A House subcommittee last month, with little public notice,
added a provision to a spending bill to increase the salary of the
next president when he or she takes office in 2001. Some public
interest groups and former presidential aides have advocated the
pay hike, which would be the first in 30 years for the chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   However, opponents charge that the salary boost for the
president is a disguised effort to increase pay for many senior
officials. As long as the president's salary is held to its current
level, it ``acts as a cap on the salaries of Members of Congress
and federal judges,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-pay raise coalition sent their letter to 11 of the top
presidential contenders, with the exception of former Red Cross
chief Elizabeth Dole, who has already denounced the pay increase.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, a Republican hopeful, sent a letter last week to House
Speaker Dennis Hastert calling the proposal ``ill-advised.'' The
``perks'' of the presidency such as a Camp David weekend retreat, a
bowling alley, a putting green, and movie theaters add up to
millions of dollars in value, Dole wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to the other candidates brought no immediate
responses on the pay hike issue.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
