<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TRAVEL-CAJUNTOUR1     06-01 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TRAVEL-CAJUNTOUR1STTAKE30 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four perfect days in Cajun country
 &HT;    EDs: Resending for those who need it.
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since Louisiana is celebrating its French heritage with
Francofete, this is a great year to join the party with a trip to
Cajun country.
</P>
<P>
   Cajun country is called Acadiana on maps because the Cajuns
originally came from Acadia, now Nova Scotia. It is a large, mostly
rural region _ some of it flat prairie, some of it coastal, and
some of it marsh and swamp. Getting around takes some time and
choosing itineraries can be difficult given how much there is to
see and, more importantly, eat.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are four agendas that could be experienced together
during a long weekend or separately. They are by no means a
complete guide, and they are highly subjective: The greatest
emphasis is put on where to eat, with music a close second. Someone
else might tell you where all the galleries, shops and museums are.
But for me, the essence of Cajun country is in the fresh crawfish
and oysters, the gumbo and the etouffee, the boudin and fresh game.
</P>
<P>
   These four itineraries fan out from Lafayette, but by all means
buy a map and tailor the trip to your plans . And keep in mind that
part of the fun is getting there: I never tire of driving back
roads in Cajun country, through sugar cane fields and past crawfish
ponds, by shotgun shacks and plantation homes, along bayous and
over swamps. Turn on the radio and find a station with a French
deejay and Cajun music playing. You might find out about a nearby
festival or a dance hall while you're listening.
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE
</P>
<P>
   Fred's Lounge, Mamou
</P>
<P>
   Open for dancing and a live radio broadcast every Saturday
morning _ and only Saturday morning _ Fred's Lounge is the essence
of the Cajun joie de vivre. You wouldn't necessarily know that,
pulling into this flat scruffy prairie town surrounded by crawfish
ponds. But in this small bar off La. 13 (318-468-5411), farmers in
overalls have gathered for decades to drink beer, waltz and speak
in French to one another about their crops or their kids. A band
sets up in the middle of the room; the accordion player and singer
keeps himself going with Miller Lites, cigarettes and throat spray.
He sings French lyrics in a high voice as the accordion wheezes.
The bar's owner, Tante Sue Vasseur, keeps herself going with a pint
of Hot Damn _ cinnamon schnapps _ tucked into her jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Dancers on small swatches of floor waltz and two-step at their
own risk: A handwritten sign on the back wall reads, ''This is not
a dance hall. If you get hurt dancing we are not responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jada Gentile drives 2 1/2 hours from Texas every Saturday to
dance at Fred's.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just love the Cajun people,'' she says between dances.
''They're so warm, and if you have any stress or anything, it just
goes. The Cajun people pull you in like family.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred's attracts a lot of camera-toting tourists, which worried
me, but what I quickly learned was that no amount of outside
traffic changes the place. The locals still come, and they display
an unerring curiosity and unjaded friendliness toward newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Dupuis, one of Gentile's dance partners, speaks French with
me. He invites me to dinner the following week at his home in
Opelousas _ he and his wife are hosting some French tourists and he
thinks I might enjoy it. He even invites me to stay with his
family.
</P>
<P>
   I ask him why his wife is not with him at Fred's.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has a problem handling this,'' he says. ''It's a little on
the rough side for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Eunice
</P>
<P>
   After Fred's, drive south on La. 13 to Eunice, a larger town
whose street signs are in French and English, and head to Johnson's
Grocery at 700 E. Maple St. (318-457-9314) for an authentic Cajun
breakfast. Line up between aisles of motor oil and Moon Pies under
the ''Rue Boudin'' sign. At the back of the store, a man behind the
meat counter doles out links of boudin _ steamed Cajun sausage made
from rice and pork and ooh-wee hot spices. It costs about $1 a
link, and it tastes better with a cold beer, which you have to buy
at the gas station down the street. I know it's barely noon, but
trust me. Around here, this is highly traditional.
</P>
<P>
   After ''breakfast,'' visit the Acadian Cultural Center (250 W.
Park Ave.; 318-457-8490). One of several such centers in the state,
it tells the story of the Acadians who settled on the prairies of
southern Louisiana. The center offers more than a dozen educational
films, any of which the staff will play pretty much on request. We
watched one on the forced migration of Acadians to Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The Acadians migrated to Louisiana from what is now Nova Scotia
in 1755. They were originally from France, and when they refused to
become British subjects, they were exiled, and many wound up in
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The center also has music, dancing and cooking demonstrations
and a historical exhibit with artifacts and information on
everything from accordions to crawfish nets.
</P>
<P>
   Palace Cafe, Opelousas
</P>
<P>
   From Eunice, take U.S. 190 East to Opelousas, where, if you are
hungry again, you can grab a bite at the Palace Cafe (318-942-2142)
right on the main street. The oldest restaurant in town, it has
classic diner food such as milkshakes, onion rings, and rural
goodies like liver and onions and fried chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Washington
</P>
<P>
   Next, head north on I-49 to Washington, a quaint, one-stoplight
town on a sleepy bayou, full of historic homes _ many of which are
open for tours. Call ahead from the tourist center (318-826-3627)
on Main Street to arrange one.
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction here, however, is the shopping at the Old
Washington Antique School Mall Flea Market (318-826-3580) not far
from Main. It has acres of antique furniture, jewelry, toys and
knickknacks, and the prices are quite fair. It is open every
Friday, Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Don't say I didn't warn you about the Country House Bed &AMP;
Breakfast. It feels more like Grandma's than a historic home. The
bed in our room had a plastic mattress cover that woke me every
time I rolled over, and the bathroom left a few things to be
desired.
</P>
<P>
   But what the place lacks in antiques and luxury it makes up for
in its hostess. An elegant woman with long, delicate fingers and a
low, husky voice, June Lowrey is immediately warm and inviting. And
over breakfast _ a delicious egg souffle _ she wove tales of being
a farmer's wife, and then, after her husband died, of living the
artist's life in the French Quarter in New Orleans. Her pencil
sketches are for sale and are good. Ask for a tour of her studio,
behind the main house in a 19th century cottage she had moved to
the property.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the two rooms inside the house, there is a private
cottage with twin beds that can be pushed together.
</P>
<P>
   The Steamboat Warehouse Restaurant is about the only place in
Washington to eat. It's a relic from the era when the town was the
largest steamboat port between New Orleans and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Decked out in cypress beams and steamboat paraphernalia, the
restaurant has a few knockout specialities that make up for
otherwise so-so fare. The fried seafood dishes are among the best
offerings, and I had a perfectly sauteed soft-shell crab. And then
there were those Sidesaddle Angels _ an appetizer of humongous
shrimp, each stuffed with an oyster, wrapped in smoky, peppery
bacon and deep-fried. Served with a remoulade sauce, it was the
evening's undisputed champion.
</P>
<P>
   DAY TWO
</P>
<P>
   Bois des Chenes, Lafayette
</P>
<P>
   I really like this B&AMP;B, despite its location in Lafayette, a
city I don't feel like hanging around in when there are small towns
to explore. This 1820 Acadian plantation home (318-233-7816) is
simple and elegant, with period antiques, traditional and very
comfortable bedding and fluffy towels in the bathroom. There are
three suites in the carriage house, where we stayed, but our room
was so private we thought we had the place to ourselves. Two more
suites are in the main house, each with a sitting room.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast began with toast with sugared orange rinds and
continued with french toast with three kinds of syrup and crisp
bacon. The owners, Coerte and Marjorie Voorhies, speak French, and
Coerte is a geologist with a wealth of knowledge on the swamps of
south Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Swamp tour,
</P>
<P>
   Lake Martin-Cypress Island Swamp
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things about Bois des Chenes is that Coerte
Voorhies and his son, Kim, offer swamp tours, which are two hours
and cost $40 per person. They take outboard motorboats to either
the Atchafalaya Swamp and Lake Martin-Cypress Island Swamp. My
husband and I and an Ohio family went with Kim to Lake
Martin-Cypress Island Swamp, a 22,000-acre preserve about 20
minutes from Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen a lot of swamps in several different vessels, but
this tour beat them all. Voorhies took the five of us to a swamp so
crammed with alligators, birds and other wildlife I wondered if
there was Viagra in the water.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of the eternally chatty Kim Voorhies: ''We've got
wildlife out the yin-yang here.''
</P>
<P>
   The birds fly here to nest each spring, so if you really want to
see a lot _ like 70,000 pairs _ that's the time to go. The trees
were covered in snowy egrets, herons and my favorite, the
candy-pink roseate spoonbills.
</P>
<P>
   The swamp itself is stunning with scrubby button bushes, tupelo
trees and cypress trees draped in Spanish moss. The water's surface
looked almost silver at times because of a thick carpet of algae.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the Grand Canyon of Louisiana,'' Voorhies likes to
say.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
