<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8535 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MAULDIN-H     06-01 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-MAULDIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOONIST BILL MAULDIN'S BOOK REMAINS A CLASSIC, 50 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ To a generation raised on Panama, the Persian
Gulf War and Kosovo as examples of the United States going to
battle, it may not mean much to hear comparisons of Bill Mauldin
with Ernie Pyle from the days of World War II. But for those who
were in the infantry, it means a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin is the cartoonist whose Willie and Joe drawings from the
Second World War captured the weariness and weirdness of the
American foot soldier better than anyone has, before or since. He
produced 228 pages of outstanding drawings and prose as he followed
the 45th Division through Italy and France, and his book, ``Up
Front: Fiftieth Anniversary Edition,'' (W.W. Norton, 228 pages,
$19.95) remains a classic, half a century later.
</P>
<P>
   In a contemporary review of ``Up Front,'' which was published by
Henry Holt in 1945, John P. Marquand said, ``There are very few
good books written about any war, and World War II is no exception.
In spite of the enormous number of titles, it would not require
more than the fingers of one hand to enumerate distinguished World
War II works on fighting men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most writers who have tackled this war would have succeeded
better had they left their ideologies and preconceived notions
behind them. ... War is simply war, and when you use wishful
thinking on it the result is an obvious distortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Marquand praised Ernie Pyle, saying the war correspondent ``has
achieved unique and perhaps lasting distinction simply by setting
down what he has seen, without permitting himself the luxury of
undue interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is high praise, indeed, to say that Bill Mauldin's short
volume, ``Up Front,'' compares favorably with Ernie Pyle's `Brave
Men,' but any reader will see that they are the same piece of
goods, produced with the same understanding, clarity and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Mauldin's cartoons are smile-to-yourself rather than
laugh-out-loud funny. There's one of a squad walking underneath a
balcony with a woman looking down. ``She must be very purty,'' says
Willie. ``Th' whole column is wheezin' at her.'' Another has a kid
lieutenant ranting against Joe about his sloppy combat outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straighten those shoulders,'' the youngster says. ``How long
you been in the Army?''
</P>
<P>
   There's one of Willie and Joe on a hill captured from the
Germans, looking down at their old positions in Anzio and saying,
``My God! Here they wuz an' there we wuz.'' And there's the one of
an MP telling three combat vets looking at his ribbons, ``The
yellow one is fer national defense, th' red one wit' white stripes
is fer very good conduct, and th' real purty one wit' all th'
colors is fer bein' in this theater of operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin's understanding of infantryman was just as good in prose
as it was in cartoons. He writes, ``While a guy at home is sweating
over his income tax and Victory garden, a dogface somewhere is
getting great joy out of wiggling his little finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it just to see it move and to prove that he is still
alive and able to move it. Life is stripped down to bare essentials
for him when he is living from minute to minute, wondering if each
is his last. Because he is fundamentally no different from his
countryman at home, he would probably be sweating just as hard over
his income tax and Victory garden if he were home.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauldin hits the mark again and again while talking about such
things as mud, rear-echelon goldbricks, sleeping in rain-swollen
foxholes and the overblown difference between Germans and Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   There's a cartoon of one officer saying to another, ``Beautiful
view. Is there one for the enlisted men?'' And one of a soldier
saying as he sits hip-deep in a foxhole during a bombardment in the
rain, ``Wisht I could stand up an' git some sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all part and parcel, says Mauldin, of the ``sometimes
downright funny things that always go along with misery.''
</P>
<P>
   Every part of ``Up Front'' translates well to 1999. The fear,
black humor and front-line craziness are the same as when Mauldin
first drew his cartoons. Any soldier marking time until Kosovo
turns into a ground war should snap up a copy and get ready for the
worst, as seen through Mauldin's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   They also should find ``Back Home,'' Mauldin's book on returning
veterans, published in 1947 by William Sloane. It includes cartoons
such as one of a vet coming out of a pawn shop flipping a coin,
saying, ``Who said my medals wouldn't buy me a cuppa coffee?'' And
one vet in a hospital bed asking others, ``How's things outside,
boys? Am I still a war hero or a drain on th' taxpayers?''
</P>
<P>
   As Marquand wrote at the end of the Second World War, Mauldin's
books ``should be required reading for everyone who has a husband,
sweetheart, brother, or son in the infantry, and it might not be
such a bad idea for the war college to study it. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone who reads it does not understand what Bill Mauldin
says and implies, it is time he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the war college, staff officers and the public have
had half a century to consider what Mauldin ``says and implies,''
and there doesn't seem to have been much change in the way this
country looks at war. The 50th anniversary edition of ``Up Front''
gives them one more chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
