<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PHANTOM-TECHNOLO     06-01 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PHANTOM-TECHNOLOGY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PHANTOM MENACE' IS LATEST TO RELY ON COMPUTER-GENERATED IMAGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alien spaceships fire laser blasts amidst
hurtling asteroids; a dinosaur stomps through New York City,
crushing skyscrapers, yuppies and taxis; a luxury liner rams an
iceberg and slowly sinks into a haunting North Atlantic abyss.
</P>
<P>
   And it looks real _ as real as a National Geographic documentary
_ to popcorn-munching movie-goers who pack the multiplexes to see
the latest action flicks using computer-generated imagery, or CGI.
</P>
<P>
   Computers have revolutionized filmmaking in the six summers
since audiences first gasped at the dinosaurs IN ``Jurassic Park.''
These slithering, ravenous, building-sized critters looked real _
more real, some critics sneered, than the human characters they
tried to munch.
</P>
<P>
   Today, viewers are flocking to the latest CGI-driven film, ``The
Phantom Menace,'' the fourth installment in filmmaker George Lucas'
``Star Wars'' series.
</P>
<P>
   In filmmaking, more and more of the film is made of digital
``backlots'' and ``sets,'' says Christian Rouet, senior technology
officer at Industrial Light &AMP; Magic, Lucas' CGI firm in San Rafael,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of delivering their lines and movements on a sound
stage, actors increasingly emote in front of a ``blue screen'' _
literally, a blue screen _ onto which the sets, spaceships,
dinosaurs, aliens, tornadoes, tsunamis, volcanoes or whatever are
later digitally ``painted.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, in ``Phantom Menace,'' Liam Neeson, Natalie Portman
and the other actors spend much of their time talking to, fighting
with or running away from characters who are not really ``there'' _
not, that is, until they're painted onto a digitized screen by a
computer artist.
</P>
<P>
   The amphibious alien Jar Jar Binks owes his existence to a
radical digital mutation of actor Ahmed Best's performance.
</P>
<P>
   With a computer, ``You can create entire worlds. You can take a
city street and add buildings and add crowds or add monuments. You
can change the weather,'' says Ron Kutak of the International
Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees in Los Angeles, which is
pushing to unionize CGI workers.
</P>
<P>
   All is not well in the CGI world, though.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, CGI is apparently here to stay. It isn't just a
short-lived Hollywood gimmick like Sensurround, Smell-O-Vision and
3-D eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, CGI hasn't lived up to all of its
expectations. Contrary to prophecies in the early 1990s, CGI hasn't
cut filmmaking costs by replacing expensive sets with digitally
generated images. Rather, movie making costs have soared _ in part,
ironically, because of the high cost of CGI itself.
</P>
<P>
   While filmmakers seriously underestimated the costs of CGI, the
technology isn't entirely to blame. Movies with $100 million-plus
budgets are no longer uncommon. ``Titanic,'' which relies heavily
on CGI, reportedly cost $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Pixar Animation Studios of Richmond, Calif., said its
first-quarter profits had plunged 76 percent, despite its highly
profitable, all-computerized movie ``A Bug's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger they are, the harder they fall: The heavy reliance on
costly CGI means filmmakers risk losing everything _ perhaps entire
studios _ by sinking fortunes into big, special effects-driven
films. Hence, they launch marketing campaigns so aggressive _ like
that of ``The Phantom Menace'' _ that they risk irritating
audiences before the movie even comes out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, just before the financial flop of the CGI-generated
thriller ``Godzilla,'' CGI leaders warned filmmakers about
over-relying on special effects.
</P>
<P>
   A good story is essential to a film, ``which is something they
seem to have forgotten,'' Steve Ross, a top executive at CGI firm
Digital Domain, warned at an industry conference in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Flustered by the ``Godzilla'' embarrassment, some studios have
cut back on CGI. Others have stopped contracting CGI work to
outside firms and, instead, are saving money by having the work
performed by in-house teams.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some independent CGI firms are laying off workers.
Kutak, who is executive director of Local 700 of IATSE _ the
Editors Guild for film editors _ expects the layoffs to make it
easier to unionize CGI workers.
</P>
<P>
   Many CGI workers haven't been interested in joining a union
until recently because most tended to be computer-savvy young
people who, because of their age, ``don't think about medical
benefits, pension etc.,'' observes Cate Bangs, a TV and film
production designer who is also president of Local 847 of IATSE in
Sherman Oaks, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Kutak says that although CGI is here to stay and has replaced
traditional filmmaking technologies, for now the business is a
``very low-profit business . . . because it's competitively bid.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another union issue is the possibility that filmmakers might
begin using digitally generated ``actors.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Rouet's many goals is to create digitized ``actors'' as
real-looking and believable as humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good actors have the ability to really go into a character and
be so touching and expressive,'' Rouet says. ''We want to achieve
exactly the same thing with digital characters.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, TV advertisers began using digital techniques
to portray dead actors such as Fred Astaire and John Wayne. Union
officials want to be sure filmmakers don't digitally reproduce an
actor's face without payment, according to Rafe Greenlee of the
Screen Actors Guild in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Digitized filmmaking raises aesthetic concerns as well.
</P>
<P>
   Having to act in front of something that isn't there is tough on
actors, acknowledges Stan Winston, who co-founded one of the
leading CGI firms, Digital Domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to the greatest actors, 50 percent of a
performance is reacting: An actor gives his best performance when
he is acting against another great actor,'' says Winston, who works
in Van Nuys, Calif. ``Now, take the actor away and give the actor
no one to act with, (and) you do not have the possibility of the
strongest performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The real cinematic revolution might come when computerized
filmmaking allows every personal computer user to be his or her own
``director'' _ to make an entire movie just by pointing and
clicking a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Rouet envisions the day when CGI will be so cheap that ordinary
people can create their own movies, complete with sets and
``actors,'' on a tabletop personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear,'' Rouet says, ``that the (computer)
technology is going to become affordable at some point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
