<P>
   BORDERS _ATLANTA _ Borders Group, in a deal to be announced
today, has taken a minority stake in an Atlanta start-up company
called Sprout that will eventually let the chain's stores print
high-quality paperbacks in the store in about 15 minutes. (Bond,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SUPERCOM _ ATLANTA _ A preview of SuperComm, the premier
telecom get-together in which tens of thousands of execs, sales
types and techies converge, June 6-10 in Atlanta. Speakers include
Microsoft Corp. President Steve Ballmer, Cisco Systems President
John Chambers and Delta Air Lines CIO Charles Feld. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED-COMPUTERS _ GAINESVILLE, Ga. _ Tony Perrone of
Gainesville lost the use of his legs in 1986 when a jack under a
truck he was working on broke. He had been a network administrator
for an international company. When he recovered, he still had his
knowledge of computers, but found companies unwilling to give him a
job because he was in a wheelchair. So he started North Georgia
Wheelers, a group that trains disabled people to use computers so
they can work at home. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-FAA _ The millennium bug hasn't shut down a single computer
at the Federal Aviation Administration but it has still given the
agency that regulates the country's air space a pretty rough ride
in the past several months. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL-SHOE _ ATLANTA _ Will Van Straden, an opera singer, is
serious about music _ but he also wants it to be fun for amatuer
musicians, especially children. That wish led to his being issued
U.S. Patent 5855080 in January. The patent protects a ``musical
shoe'' that's played by tapping your feet. But this isn't your
old-fashioned tap-dance shoe. Van Straden's shoe is battery-powered
and plays music with an electronic sound similar to a keyboard.
(Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS _ FORD MUSTANG GT _ Maybe the folks at Ford who
created the '99 Mustang have been out in the sun too long; or maybe
they're so caught up in the ongoing fascination with things
Egyptian that they really think it makes sense to say that the new
'Stang is visually comparable to a pyramid. Those Egyptian
pyramids, they should remember, have been stuck, immovable and
immutable, in the sand for millennia. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3-column color photograph of the
1999 Ford Mustang GT and 2-column color photo of interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE -- Fact box previewing the 1999 Ford Mustang
GT.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC -- Don't expect top quality auto repair at a
cut-rate price (Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Includes
1-column color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ Mustang history quiz. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY. 15.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ Nora Carter's automotive column is not available
this week.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-PROTEGE _ A review of the Mazda Protege. (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ This year's college graduates seem to be earnest
about investing for their future _ but not necessarily prepared for
the task. Few have gotten any formal education in managing their
investments, and a surprising percentage say they rely on parents
or even on comtemporaries for financial advice. They will need
plenty of help. We review a first-class book on the basics of
investment. Conclusion: You can do it yourself, but most will want
to turn the job over to pros, meaning mutual funds. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
