<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8673 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLICKER-TRAINING-HNS &LR;      06-01 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLICKER-TRAINING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINING ANIMALS A CLICK AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Pet owners who have attempted to train their
animals know the frustration of trying to communicate and to judge
how quickly a pet learns. But clicker training, which uses sounds
and positive reinforcement, offers some hope.
</P>
<P>
   The method was originally developed by marine mammal trainers
for work with dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever seen the killer whale shows at Sea World,
you've seen clicker training in action,'' said Alexandra Kurland,
author of ``Clicker Training for your Horse'' ($24.95, Sunshine
Books, 1998) and a specialist in animal behavior. The resident of
Delmar, N.Y., owns horses and is an experienced rider, teacher and
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   The clicker method is among those used to teach horses the
proper carriage for dressage, a special type of riding that
requires the horse to maneuver and perform difficult steps
controlled by slight movements of the rider.
</P>
<P>
   The clicker method takes its name from the acoustical toy
clickers used by some trainers to signal a positive answer to the
animal. Others use vocal signals such as a click or cluck with the
tongue or snap of the fingers. The sound means that the animal has
earned a reward: a chance to try again, a small piece of kibble, a
pat or voice response of ``good boy'' or ``good girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clicker training represents a radical departure from many
traditional training methods that are often based on physical force
and punishment,'' Kurland said. She has also studied round-pen
training with John Lyons, an advocate of nonviolent training, and
is a graduate and teacher of Linda Tellingham-Jones' Touch, a
system of using manual contact to improve physical and behavioral
problems in horses.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kurland, clicker training is very forgiving, using
positive reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your horse is always alert, waiting for the click and trying
to figure out what is it that it has to do to earn this
reinforcement,'' Kurland said. She said children, too, can learn to
clicker train their pets.
</P>
<P>
   The method also works with llamas, dogs, goldfish, iguanas,
hamsters, goats, chickens, parrots and cats, according to Kurland.
``Cats naturally target,'' she said. ``Anyone who has ever played
with a cat knows this. My target-trained cats follow me everywhere
I go around the house, and they come instantly when they're
called.''
</P>
<P>
   The author said that she started clicker training in 1993 just
to amuse herself and her horse, but quickly found that the two were
learning to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start out in clicker training, never start with your
goal,'' she said. ``With clicker training, you are always creating
comfort zones for your animal with this bridging signal that links
a desired behavior to a reward.''
</P>
<P>
   The signal and reward have to be timed so the animal associates
the goal and the treat. A delay will only confuse the animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can give your horse important information just by changing
your treat,'' said Kurland, who gives her horses peppermints for
special behavior. ``Jackpot! When that mint comes out, they know
they have done something particularly wonderful and will make an
extra effort the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurland recommends the following steps for introducing a horse
to the clicker:
</P>
<P>
   Start by teaching it to touch any safe target, such as a very
small orange lane-marking cone, a ball on a stick or a plastic lid.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, keep the horse in the stall with a stall guard
across the door so it can move around freely yet keep you safe if
it gets too excited. If treats make the horse rambunctious, don't
scold, simply step out of range.
</P>
<P>
   Begin target training by holding the cone or other object up in
front of the horse. When it sniffs the object, instantly click and
provide the treat. If the horse starts nudging you for treats while
you are offering the cone, step away. Let the horse explore and
think things through until it learns that going directly to the
vending machine _ you _ never earns a treat. The horse will soon
learn that it is in control and can make you click when it bumps
the cone, not when it sniffs your fingers, pushes or bumping you.
</P>
<P>
   Never demand behavior from your horse. Raise your standards in
small enough steps so that the horse continues to be successful.
Remember that horses learn at different rates and some may need
more intermediate steps than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your horse loses interest or seems confused, you may have
been asking for too much, too soon,'' Kurland said. ``Go back to a
point in the training where your horse can be successful and
rebuild form there.''
</P>
<P>
   Horses catch on to it pretty quickly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kurland said that solving a horse's training problems can be
like unraveling the clues in a detective story.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep following the threads until they bring you to the
core issues your horse or pet is facing,'' Kurland said. ``If you
let them, they will take you to the most basic layers of training
that need work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
