<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTERPIECE-NEWSLETTE     06-01 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTERPIECE-NEWSLETTER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TV NEWSLETTER FOR ANGLOPHILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It began innocently enough, like one of Miss Marple's trips to
the village store and its post office in St. Mary Mead.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Finke and Evelyn Mellon, casually obsessive experts on
British television who both live on New York's Long Island, were
struck by the number of people who would ask whether the actress
playing Jane Bennet in ``Pride and Prejudice'' was the same one who
played Sarah Layton in ``The Jewel in the Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, of course not. It was Susannah Harker in ``Pride and
Prejudice'' and Geraldine James in ``The Jewel in the Crown.'' But
the questions left them more convinced than ever that there was a
universe of people out there as obsessed with the prim minutiae of
British television as they were.
</P>
<P>
   For several years the two had talked of finding a way to keep up
with the programs and actors on British television, and now they
have decided that while, heaven forbid, there may not always be an
England, there will always be Anglophiles. A result, beginning with
the first issue in December 1997, was The Anglo-Files: A Newsletter
for Fans of British Television, which Ms. Finke produces each month
with stray contributions from or consultations with Ms. Mellon.
</P>
<P>
   It is a numbingly detailed and exhaustive compendium on the
period dramas, murder mysteries and reborn classics of British
television and allied planets in theater and film, as well as a
reminder that in a culture addicted to New! More! Hotter! Sexier!
there is still a fiercely loyal constituency for old, less, cooler
and a bit dowdy.
</P>
<P>
   Each issue of their 'zine for the BBC and PBS set includes nine
single-spaced pages of listings, notes, gossip and trivia about
British programs being broadcast in the United States. (The
newsletter is always nine pages because any more would tip the
scale toward extra postage.) There is a summary of each show, a
complete cast listing and jauntily written, Playbill-like notes on
each performer.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Finke, as editor, does nearly all the work. Ms. Mellon has
the prestigious post of correspondent at large. Her 86-year-old
English mum, Mabs Turner, who sends along relevant clippings from
British newspapers, is listed as the United Kingdom correspondent.
Ms. Finke's computer, Sir Winston, and her printer, Lady Macbeth,
round out the masthead.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they are only up to 169 loyal subscribers, who pay $30
for 12 issues. But Ms. Finke, who is 68 and lives in East Quogue,
N.Y., said she was sure that there was a silent majority out there
whose idea of a great night was sitting at home watching Paul
McGann in Charles Dickens' ``Our Mutual Friend,'' Joan Hickson as
Agatha Christie's Miss Marple, anything on Mobil Masterpiece
Theater or the rest of the imported British canon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started this, I said to Eve that you and I are two
people in a majority that's out there that's just as crazy as we
are,'' Ms. Finke said. ``I guarantee you that we are not the only
people who sit bolt upright in bed and think, `Where did I see that
actor before?'''
</P>
<P>
   The Anglo-Files can trace its beginnings to the mid-1980s, when
Ms. Mellon and Ms. Finke became friends while working for a
child-care agency, Little Flower Children's Services. Ms. Finke, a
former assistant producer for a German television station, came to
the United States from Hamburg, which she calls ``surely the most
English of German cities.'' Ms. Mellon grew up in Herne Bay, a
seaside village on the Kentish coast of England, and now lives in
Port Jefferson, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   During drives to Brooklyn for visits with the families of
children in foster care, the women would discuss their mutual
passion for British television, which for Ms. Finke began with
``The Forsythe Saga'' and ``The Pallisers'' and reached the level
of addiction with her first (and still favorite) Miss Marple
mystery, ``Murder at the Vicarage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Finke began taping every British television program and
writing down the cast listings, with each actor cross-referenced to
earlier performances. In 1996 she decided to turn her fixation into
the newsletter. She and Ms. Mellon began searching for preview
information from Bravo, PBS and A&AMP;E listings, and went into
business. Ms. Finke put up library notices, took out small
advertisements in publications favored by Anglophiles and sent
letters to people who seemed likely customers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Finke keeps her two televisions running regularly,
programming the VCR on one and setting the VCR manually on the
other. She spends a week writing and at least two hours a day
researching clippings and notes in American newspapers, press
releases, a British television guide and the Daily Mail of London.
And then there are the countless hours spent stuffing envelopes or
corresponding with subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The publication is nowhere near the break-even point, but it is
more a labor of love than a business proposition for Ms. Finke, who
is retired.
</P>
<P>
   A typical issue might open with a seasonally appropriate
quotation from Swinburne, Wordsworth or Dylan Thomas. Then comes an
essay or reminiscence, like Ms. Finke's account of a visit 43 years
ago to the Greek island of Paros or an important news flash, like
British showings in the Oscars or Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   The guts of each issue are the listings of all the British
dramas scheduled that month on PBS or cable stations, with plot
summaries and knowing sketches of the players. The initiated
understand the shorthand, like MP for ``Mobil Masterpiece
Theater,'' MM for Miss Marple and SH for Sherlock Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the listings sound like the cast of an Edward Gorey
black comedy: ``Robert Lang was the odious Colonel Prothero in
`Murder at the Vicarage'; Chief Superintendent in Morse: `The
Settling of the Sun'; Gladstone in MP-`Parnell and the
Englishwoman'; and a cameo in MP-`Bramwell' III, `Cholera'
episode.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they get a little catty, as in the casting of
``Frenchman's Creek'' for ``Mobil Masterpiece Theater'': ``Anthony
Delon. Speaking of assets _ he is the son of the French actor Alain
Delon and has inherited his father's great looks, but apparently
not his acting talents.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Aficionados can learn that Struan Rodger, ``red hair, pale face,
looks like a young Red Buttons''; that Peter Jeffreys ``belongs to
the vast store of British actors with very prominent noses,'' and
that Ian McNeice, ``a little butterball, was the nasty George in
MP-`The Blackheath Poisonings.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled in are notes from subscribers, mea culpas, obituaries
(most recently of the actors Sir Dirk Bogarde and Oliver Reed), and
assorted digressions, like an item wondering just why the Queen
needs a handbag or irregular features like Actor of the Month.
</P>
<P>
   Of the June 1998 honoree David Jason, for example, there is this
description: ``Short, cocky, bug-eyed, he reminds me of my demented
pug, Ling-Ling, who in an earlier incarnation must have been
responsible for the creation of the word pugnacious.'' Ling-Ling,
it must be reported, has passed on, but Jason continues to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   This year's March issue had a helpful breakdown for those having
problems with their Nigels, Ians and Iains, differentiating, among
others, Nigel Bruce from Nigel Davenport from Nigel Terry from
Nigel Hawthorne; Ian Bannen from Ian Brimble from Ian Richardson
from Ian McKellen and Iain Glen from Iain Cutherbertson from Iain
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   April's issue threw in the Ruperts for good measure, giving the
particulars for Rupert Everett, Rupert Graves, Rupert Penry-Jones,
Rupert Holiday-Evans and Rupert Vansittart.
</P>
<P>
   With her cramped work space overflowing with 200 tapes, dry
sense of humor and tendency to rattle on cheerfully, Ms. Finke has
the air of someone who belongs in her own listings. She works from
her one-story bungalow, with its daffodils and magnolias and
English garden out back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops, just kicked the baby kitten, but that's redundant isn't
it?'' she said. ``I hope you're not drowning in my palaver.''
</P>
<P>
   She sees the appeal of British drama as its complex mixture of
an idealized past and the stuff of human existence then and now.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times it's a return to what we think of as a nicer world,''
she said, ``but there's nothing nice in most of Dickens or if
you're a servant in `Upstairs Downstairs.' So it's a dream world in
some ways of thatched cottages and quaint villages. But then we
know the English have the same problems we have with race relations
and drug abuse and child abuse and spousal abuse. The Daily Mail
says that even the queen mother is 4 million pounds in debt.''
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest appeal of British television, Ms. Mellon said,
is probably that it is not American television.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the lure, Ms. Finke plows ahead, heartened by the
response to new programs like ``Berkeley Square,'' a variation on
the theme of ``Upstairs, Downstairs,'' and convinced that her brand
of Anglophilia is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say, for once, I think I hit this right at the right
time,'' she said. ``Look at the Oscars. Look at Broadway. It's
wall-to-wall Brits. They're taking over the U.S., aren't they?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
