<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-1STLD-WR     06-01 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAGA OF SOPHIE'S BREAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Restores tag line in last graf)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Thank goodness there'll always be an England. Lacking a
monarchy of our own, where else could we get such vicarious
thrills?
</P>
<P>
   British politicians were tending to business last week as usual:
Parliament erupted in a furor over welfare reform, Prime Minister
Tony Blair stuck his neck out again to press for continued NATO
bombing of the Serbs, the Welsh opened their experimental new
assembly and Queen Elizabeth blessed the fabulous annual Chelsea
garden show.
</P>
<P>
   But the big news that gripped the public was the naked right
breast of Prince Edward's fiancee, Sophie Rhys-Jones, and the giant
press dust-up it produced.
</P>
<P>
   Here in America we like to snoop into the private lives of the
rich and famous every bit as much as the British, but we don't have
the flair they do for being nosy amid dramatic hair-pulling and
theatrical whining and wailing.
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky was a long-running sexy American distraction,
yet our reaction to her tawdry little affair with President Clinton
was to despise her and try to fire him. Too serious. No fun in
that.
</P>
<P>
   But with her exposed bosom Sophie, 34, has suddenly replaced the
late Diana as a glamorous, wronged royal (she will shortly become
one when she marries Queen Elizabeth's youngest son on June 19.)
Her new role is enhanced by the fact that her betrayer, former
colleague Kara Noble, is a satisfactorily nasty villain in the
tradition of Linda Tripp. Now this is the stuff of great gossip.
</P>
<P>
   The London Sun, an irrepressible and irresponsible tabloid,
printed an 11-year-old snapshot of Sophie giggling in the back seat
of a car after a male colleague pulled up her bikini top to expose
her breast. Noble, who snapped the picture, was said to be jealous
of Sophie for hitting the marital jackpot. In a fury because she
was not invited to the wedding, Noble sold the photo to the Sun for
an estimated $165,000.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next was a verbal hurricane, British style.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusually tart response, the palace condemned the
publication of the picture as ``premeditated cruelty'' and
threatened to haul the Sun before the independent Press Complaints
Commission. The radio station for which Noble worked summarily
sacked her. The Daily Record called Noble a ``female Judas'' whose
lucre was ``filthily and foully earned.''
</P>
<P>
   London's other newspapers also weighed in angrily, attacking the
Sun for committing what they called an inexcusable atrocity against
a happy bride-to-be. Newspapers in Germany, Belgium, Italy and
Holland ran excitable stories hyping the incident and thoughtfully
reproducing the offending picture so their readers could see what
the fuss was all about.
</P>
<P>
   Here in America, however, public reaction was relatively tame.
We have seen half-naked women before. And we have yet to be
captivated by the fair Sophie, clothed or not.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Ferguson, the estranged wife of Prince Andrew, once
titillated us with that beau who kissed her toes, but now she is a
matronly shill for diet products and a tad boring. It is still up
to Prince Charles and his longtime love Camilla Parker Bowles to
feed basic public curiosity about the royals. And the fun couple
didn't fail us last week; Camilla's son Tom Parker Bowles was
caught using drugs, for which he was supposedly upbraided by
Charles.
</P>
<P>
   But the London newspapers worked themselves into a frenzy over
Sophie's bare breast because after Diana's death press honchos had
piously promised to lay off the royals and treat them with more
respect. The bad tabloid days were supposed to be over. Even David
Yelland, the Sun editor, had observed that the game of harassment,
misrepresentation and invasion of privacy that the press had played
with Diana went too far.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's outcry drove the Sun to apologize for publishing the
picture, trying to grovel its way out of trouble by admitting a
mistake. But the Daily Telegraph harrumphed that the apology was
nothing but an insincere ``preemptive cringe'' designed to get
Buckingham Palace to withdraw its official complaint. (So far, the
Palace is sticking to its guns.)
</P>
<P>
   A major rival, the Mirror, ran a front page headline over
Yelland's picture asking, ``Is this the most stupid man in
Britain?'' The Daily Record went the Mirror one better by asking,
``Is this the most cruel man in Britain?''
</P>
<P>
   The Times sniffed, ``Sorry doesn't quite fit the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The backlash even reached the Sun's reclusive owner. ``What is
it with Rupert Murdoch?'' the Telegraph asked sarcastically, noting
that the 68-year-old publisher had asked his peers to avoid
``intrusive publicity'' about his own marriage breakup and romance
with a 31-year-old woman. ``Yet his papers offer no mercy to other
members of the human race,'' the Telegraph complained.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this furor was undoubtedly born of genuine sympathy for
the humiliated Sophie. But it is not irrelevant that London's many
newspapers are engaged in an intense circulation war, trying every
twist and turn to win readers. In America, most cities support only
one or two newspapers. But in London newspapers breed like rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   It's a media jungle out there. Being polite doesn't sell
newspapers, particularly tabloids. Screaming and hollering do.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail,
at means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1735EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
