<HEADER>
A8692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-NY     06-01 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER RIOTS, ELECTION-TIME MOOD IN INDONESIA IS CALM  
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SERPANG, Indonesia _ This time, Enin Supriyanto is ready. Like
other ethnic Chinese here, he has his escape plan, his emergency
telephone numbers and his extra rations.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, surrounded by the music of frogs and the
sweet scent of clove cigarettes, he took his turn on neighborhood
watch, sitting by a barbed-wire barricade at the gated entrance of
his housing complex until well past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   One year after a paroxysm of rioting in which ethnic Chinese
were the targets of widespread vandalism, arson and rape, Chinese
all across the country have been preparing for new attacks before
the general election next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some bought guns. Some are paying military units to guard
commercial areas. Many of those who can afford to have left the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But something utterly unexpected has happened. The election
campaign, in most parts of the country, has so far been mainly
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   The threatening telephone calls to Chinese residents and the
anonymous leaflets and rumors of attacks that have circulated in
Chinese communities have not reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting by their barbed-wire barricade, Enin and a dozen of his
neighbors strummed a guitar, played cards and discussed their
tennis strokes over late-night snacks and glasses of hot Ovaltine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are playing cards, we are eating noodles, we are talking
nonsense,'' Enin said, happily relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Although Indonesia's Chinese people know that they can become
targets of violence at any time, as they have been periodically
over the decades, there is an emerging hope here that something
fundamental may be starting to change.
</P>
<P>
   The cautiously upbeat mood among the residents here in the
western suburbs of Jakarta is repeated among political analysts _
both Chinese and non-Chinese _ as they survey the national scene.
</P>
<P>
   After the shock of the riots and the forced resignation of
President Suharto last year, the analysts say, Indonesia's Chinese
may be inching toward the mainstream of society.
</P>
<P>
   Adapting a pattern set by centuries of Dutch colonization,
Suharto created what one analyst called a ``golden cage'' for the
Chinese. They were offered economic opportunity in exchange for
their support and their exclusion from the country's political and
cultural life.
</P>
<P>
   They constitute less than 4 percent of the population in this
country of more than 200 million, but they control the bulk of its
private commerce _ ranging from small rice merchants to billionaire
tycoons.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto's departure after 32 years of rule opened the way for a
reorganization of all aspects of society, from freeing the press to
forming political parties to redefining the role of Indonesians of
Chinese ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Led by a better-educated, better-integrated younger generation,
many of the Chinese have begun to seek a new, more active place in
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been convinced for about 30 years that everything was
fine,'' said Daniel S. Lev, an expert on Indonesia at the
University of Washington. ``They were isolated in a sense _ they
were denied any right to participate politically, but there was, at
the higher levels, a payoff: you got rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for many, what happened last May came as a really brutal
shock, because the part of the deal they forgot was that if things
got serious they would have to serve as scapegoats.''
</P>
<P>
   Hari Tjan, a political analyst with the independent Center for
Strategic and International Studies, who is an ethnic Chinese, said
of the riots, ``The cost was very high, but it is a learning
process that has been started.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, he said, there has also been a change in the
attitudes of indigenous political leaders, who he said ``don't want
to play this Chinese card anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am amazed that their conscience as human beings has
revived,'' Tjan said, ``and it is a wonderful, encouraging
development. Nearly all the parties are now embracing the Chinese
and telling them, `You are one of us. Please work together for the
country.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a country where Chinese schools, newspapers, signboards and
public ceremonies were banned by Suharto, it has been an
extraordinary sight at some political rallies to see, among the
crowds, traditional Chinese lion and dragon dances.
</P>
<P>
   As they feel freer to redefine their role, Chinese people here
have launched a debate over whether to assert their cultural
separateness or to try to blend in to the broader national
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese have banded together to form a culturally based
political party. Others have chosen not to emphasize their
separateness and have joined some of the other 47 parties engaged
in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some responded to the riots by reaching out in solidarity to the
overseas Chinese diaspora in other nations, said Anugerah Pekerti,
an Indonesian Chinese who is chairman of World Vision Indonesia, an
aid organization.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Pekerti himself, advocate instead a process he
calls ``Indonesianization,'' in which the country's scores of
disparate ethnic groups will draw closer together in a common
identity.
</P>
<P>
   The debate illustrates an essential and wide-ranging change from
Suharto's father-knows-best era: Indonesians are reconstructing
their nation on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   And the basic lesson the Chinese seem to be applying, in the
often-quoted words of the Indonesian Chinese political analyst
Arief Budiman, is: ``If you remain timid, you will forever be
trampled on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-BOTHA-NYT &LR;      06-01 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOTHA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTHA'S CONTEMPT CONVICTION REVERSED
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa _ An appeals court on Tuesday set aside
the contempt conviction of former President P.W. Botha for refusing
to appear before the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which was
created to investigate the crimes of the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling makes it unlikely that the defiant Botha, 83, will
suffer any punishment for the killings and bombings conducted by
his government or for refusing to say whether he had directly
ordered any of them.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the appeals panel went out of its way to praise
the work of the commission. It made its ruling entirely on the
basis of a technicality related to the date on which the subpoena
for Botha was issued.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a face-to-face plea from Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the
commission's chairman, Botha had repeatedly refused to appear
voluntarily. On Dec. 5, 1997, the commission issued a subpoena
commanding him to meet with it on Dec. 19. After he failed to
appear, a court in the town of George, near his retirement home in
Wilderness, found him guilty of contempt and sentenced him to
either a year in jail or a fine of about $1,600.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the Cape High Court ruled that on Dec. 5, the
commission's legal mandate to exist was due to expire on Dec. 14,
so it had acted beyond its power by issuing a subpoena for Dec. 19.
Only on Dec. 10 did President Nelson Mandela sign legislation
extending the commission's life.
</P>
<P>
   In the court's decision, Judge Selwyn Selikowitz noted that the
commission ``has undertaken a noble and invaluable task for the
country, but it still remains a statutory body.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge in George had refused to allow Botha's legal
team to make an argument over the dates, and Selikowitz said on
Tuesday that he had ``misdirected himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling could add to the irritation of blacks who feel that
the courts are biased against them. The judge who found Botha
guilty was black; both judges on the Cape High Court panel that
overruled him are white.
</P>
<P>
   After the ruling, Botha responded to interview requests by
reading a statement over the telephone. It did not discuss the
merits of the decision or the role of the commission, but expressed
his family's gratitude and pleasure that the judges had acted
independently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our beautiful country cannot afford to be in a state of
despair,'' Botha went on, not making it exactly clear what state of
despair he referred to. ``Minority rights as well as cultural
rights should be maintained. South Africa should press on in the
knowledge that God is in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Botha governed the country for 11 years, during which the
half-secret war against black liberation guerrillas became ever
more brutal, with activists simply kidnapped and killed. After
Botha suffered a stroke in 1989, he was replaced by F.W. de Klerk,
who ultimately invited the guerrillas to return and started the
process that led to the 1994 elections.
</P>
<P>
   A Truth Commission spokesman said he hoped that the decision
would not slow down reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed in the verdict, but we have to respect the
court's decision,'' the spokesman, Pila Ngqumba, told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor said the government would study the ruling and
decide whether to appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
