<HEADLINE>
CALDER SCULPTURE MAY HEAD TO MUSEUM IN BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: San Francisco)  (dal) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An important Alexander Calder sculpture, once
promised to the Whitney Museum of American Art but sold at auction
to an anonymous private collector two weeks ago, may be headed for
a museum collection after all. But it is likely to be the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art, not the Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer of the Calder, a painted wood-and-wire work called
``Constellation,'' has been identified as Donald G. Fisher, the
founder of the Gap, by several people with knowledge of his
collection. They added that Fisher and his wife, Doris, who are
among the San Francisco museum's largest benefactors, usually
bought with the intention of giving the works to the museum. Fisher
is a longtime trustee there.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is traveling and could not be reached for comment. David
A. Ross, the director of the San Francisco museum, also declined to
comment for the record. Ross headed the Whitney until a year ago,
leaving for San Francisco after seven often stormy years in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Calder made ``Constellation,'' which is considered the most
complex work in his constellation series, in 1941 for Philip
Johnson, the architect, and his sister, Theodate Severns. In 1981,
Mrs. Severns and her husband, Scott, promised the work to the
Whitney. Several months ago, however, Mrs. Severns, who is 91 and
is ill, asked to be released from her promise.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney, in a move that stunned the museum world, allowed
``Constellation'' to be sold at Sotheby's, where on May 18 it
brought $1.9 million, more than double the presale estimate.
Proceeds from the sale are going into a trust that will provide
income to the Severns for the rest of their lives. The Whitney will
then receive what is left.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the deal said the Whitney should have bought an
annuity for the Severns and kept ``Constellation'' for its
collection. ``The Whitney lost a masterwork, without a doubt,''
said Alexander S.C. Rower, the director of the Calder Foundation
and the artist's grandson.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at Sotheby's seemed to agree. The Fishers, who are
well-known collectors of Calder's work, had to compete with four
other bidders for ``Constellation.'' ``Don loves Calder and has a
wonderful Calder collection,'' Rower said. ``His collection is
certainly growing.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, ``Constellation'' seemed destined to go to San
Francisco, because the underbidder was Charles Schwab, the
investment company founder, whose wife, Helen, is also on the board
of the San Francisco museum. A spokeswoman for Schwab declined to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
