<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DISCUSSES DETAILS OF POSSIBLE PEACEKEEPING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO military planners heard on Tuesday how
many troops and tanks the allies and other countries would provide
for the beefed-up, 45,000-strong peacekeeping force planned for
Kosovo if diplomacy brings a settlement. But allied officials said
Russia, a key diplomatic player, was keeping its distance.
</P>
<P>
   The allies kept up the military pressure on Serbian forces with
778 missions Monday night, including 319 bombing runs and 89
attacks on Serbian air defenses. Air attacks on Serbian forces
fighting rebel Kosovo Liberation Army troops near the Albanian
border continued Tuesday, and international observers reported that
seven bombs fell on Albanian territory.
</P>
<P>
   One allied official said the attacks, in an area where Serbian
forces have often shown little concern about crossing the border,
were deliberate, and allied spokesmen said the bombing would
continue to intensify in what could be a crucial two weeks of
negotiations. ``It's a convergence of increased bombing and
diplomacy,'' one Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   If peace does break out, Britain has alerted up to 12,000 light
infantry soldiers to be ready to join its 5,300 troops already in
Macedonia for a peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, and France said
this week that it could provide 6,000 to 7,000 troops, about as
many as the United States has said it is willing to offer. Italy
also has close to 8,000 soldiers in Albania, where they are helping
refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 NATO allies agreed last week that because of widespread
destruction and dislocation in Kosovo, restoring normal life and
security there would take more than the 28,000 peacekeeping
soldiers they had planned to send in earlier this spring if
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had accepted a negotiated
settlement providing autonomy for the province.
</P>
<P>
   Many European officials say they are now hoping that a new
diplomatic push by former Russian Prime Minister Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin could produce Yugoslav agreement to an international
peacekeeping force. They also hope that Russia would join the push
by the time eight industrial democracies, including the United
States and Russia, gather in Cologne, Germany, on June 18 for a
summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Cologne meeting is seen as a crucial negotiating deadline,
but whether Chernomyrdin can persuade Milosevic to accept terms
that would get the allies to stop the bombing is still uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   One allied official said Tuesday that the larger NATO force now
being planned if diplomacy does succeed would have about 45,000
soldiers from NATO countries and other neutral or formerly
communist nations that have cooperation agreements with the
alliance. Another 10,000 troops would remain outside Kosovo
providing supplies and other support, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Military representatives from NATO and 12 non-NATO countries
attended a conference on the peacekeeping mission Tuesday at the
allied military headquarters in Mons, Belgium. They offered
individual combat, logistical, and engineering units for an
international force big enough to move into the province after the
fighting stops and escort hundreds of thousands of refugees back to
their shattered homes. Officials said final decisions would be made
after allied commanders reviewed the offers and some participating
countries got approval from their parliaments.
</P>
<P>
   Peacekeepers would go in, according to NATO, only if a new round
of diplomacy finally produced agreement by Milosevic to stop the
fighting and withdraw Serbian forces from Kosovo. If diplomacy
fails by the time of the June 18 meeting, one official here said,
the allies might then have to start formal planning for a much
larger force to fight its way into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which has about 1,500 peacekeepers serving with allied
forces in Bosnia, has refused so far to participate in planning for
a peacekeeping force, according to officials here. Russia suspended
all formal cooperation with the alliance after it started bombing
military targets in Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bombing, an allied military spokesman, Maj. Gen.
Walter Jertz, said on Tuesday that 40,000 Serbian troops remained
in Kosovo, about as many as there were when the allies started the
air operation 70 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said Milosevic was
forcing men in their 50s to join the Yugoslav army. ``He is now
drawing on his last human resources to keep the numbers level,''
Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Jertz described ``fierce fighting'' between Serbian forces and
the ethnic Albanian KLA near the border with Albania on Monday, and
said that NATO airplanes had bombed 84 pieces of Serbian combat
equipment in the battle zone.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, Jertz said, the allies had bombed 314 Serbian
artillery pieces, 120 tanks and 203 other armored vehicles in
Kosovo since the beginning of the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The allies hoped bombing would force a halt to Serbian attacks
against the ethnic Albanian majority in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Milosevic's army, police and paramilitary forces
continued combat operations that have now driven 800,000 ethnic
Albanians out of Kosovo and forced most of the rest, nearly
600,000, to take to the hills.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have flown 31,529 individual missions in 70 days,
Jertz said, including thousands of strikes against Serbian
anti-aircraft missiles and the radar and communications sites that
the air defense system uses to target attacking planes.
</P>
<P>
   Allied air attacks, Jertz said, had done moderate to severe
damage to all nine military airfields in Serbia, destroyed more
than 100 Serbian warplanes, and driven most of the rest out of the
skies during NATO operations. About two-thirds of the least
sophisticated Serbian anti-aircraft missiles had been destroyed, he
said, and 12 percent of the more advanced SA-6 missiles had been
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   But despite more than two months of bombing, according to the
allies, the Serbian military still has 59 percent of its petroleum
reserves. More than 40 percent of Yugoslavia's joint
military-civilian fuel reserves and 63 percent of its oil storage
plants remain untouched by the bombing, and 71 percent of the
ammunition storage capacity remains, the alliance says.
</P>
<P>
   With allied attacks focusing more and more on installations like
power plants, bridges and roads that civilians are also using, Shea
said, it was inevitable that there would be more Yugoslav civilian
casualties, though allied pilots do their best to avoid striking
civilian targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
