<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-EXCAVATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH POLICE DIG FOR REMAINS OF IRA VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ The family of Jean McConville, a mother of 10
who was executed by the Irish Republican Army in 1972 because she
comforted a dying British soldier, waited and hoped Tuesday that
her remains would be found by Irish police.
</P>
<P>
   Police were excavating a beach in the Irish Republic near the
Northern Ireland border. Seven other families and scores of
relatives also waited to see whether police would find remains of
their loved ones _ also IRA victims, most of them Roman Catholics,
who were executed as traitors.
</P>
<P>
   Irish police were acting on information provided last week by
the overwhelmingly Catholic IRA, which acknowledges the executions
but has not apologized for them. Police are digging and dredging in
four counties of the Irish Republic for the remains of eight
persons executed in the 1970s and 1980s, at the height of the
sectarian violence between Northern Ireland's Protestant majority
and the Catholic minority.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA moved the bodies across the border apparently to avoid
any involvement with its enemies in the north _ the police of the
Royal Ulster Constabulary.
</P>
<P>
   The highly public search has become an emotional issue both here
in the Irish Republic and in British Northern Ireland, further
complicating the stalled peace effort in the north.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Irish national television reported that the
IRA had said that it had given all the information it had and that
it hoped the bodies would be found to ``end the anguish'' of the
waiting families. But Seamus McKendry, a son-in-law of Mrs.
McConville, said he wants more details on how to find the bodies.
``If they want to end the anguish,'' he said, ``let them do it. Or
nobody's going to trust them as a political party.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRA disclosure of the information was apparently designed to
improve its image and to help Sinn Fein, its political wing, in
both the peace effort and local elections on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has observed a cease-fire for 22 months, but has refused
to disarm. This has given Protestant leaders grounds for denying
Sinn Fein cabinet-level posts in the new Northern Ireland Assembly,
which was created to carry out political changes approved last year
in the Belfast peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is intended to give minority Catholics more power
in the north, and to increase the influence in northern affairs of
the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic, to the south.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, acting on information provided by the IRA through a
Catholic priest, police found the remains of one man, Eamon Molloy,
in a coffin in a church cemetery in County Louth, near the Northern
Ireland border. But other locations identified by the IRA have been
dug and dredged by hundreds of police for three days without the
discovery of other remains.
</P>
<P>
   The Sinn Fein president, Gerry Adams, has called on the IRA to
provide full details to help police find the remains. But other
northern politicians, including Dr. Phillip McGarry, the president
of the mainstream Alliance Party, a 60-40 mix of Protestants and
Catholics, have attacked the Sinn Fein statements as disingenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McConville, a 39-year-old Protestant married to a Catholic,
was abducted in the presence of her children by an IRA gang a few
days before Christmas 1972. A local guerrilla committee had judged
her a traitor for comforting the dying soldier, who had been shot
in front of her home.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, some of the McConvilles gathered near a beach in the
village of Templetown, just across Carlingford Loch from Northern
Ireland. As police dug with huge mechanical excavators and ordinary
shovels, some of her children said they would wait longer, but that
they were losing hope. At dinner time, the police were still
searching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
