<HEADLINE>
MANY CAR SHOPPERS BEING DRIVEN TO LEASE  
 (ADV: MATERIAL FOR THREE BOXES AT END) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Hardly anybody walks into an auto showroom these days
without drawing up a budget and checking it twice.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are so expensive that few consumers can buy one outright.
That means some kind of financing will be necessary, and monthly
payments will result.
</P>
<P>
   Yet car shoppers who focus too much on the monthly outlays to
the exclusion of other costs may live to regret it. That's because
a preoccupation with payments often leads car shoppers to leasing,
which frequently is more expensive than buying, say consumer
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people are paying the full sticker price or more for
leased cars,'' consumer advocate W. James Bragg writes in his book
``Car Buyer's and Leaser's Negotiating Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Hegyi, an assistant Arizona attorney general, estimates
that dealers make three to four times the profit on leases than on
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two or three years your lease will end, and dealers will
have another chance to earn several thousand dollars in commissions
by selling or leasing you a new car,'' Hegyi said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that leasing is inherently worse than buying. The
financial attractiveness of either approach depends largely on the
numbers you input.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that because the leasing process is more complex and
consumers don't understand it as well, dealers have the advantage.
It's not merely a matter of bickering over prices, car options and
trade-in values, as with a sale. You also have to contemplate
factors such as the likely number of miles you may drive and the
car's residual value at the end of the term.
</P>
<P>
   ``These transactions are so complicated that most people don't
know if they're getting a good or bad deal,'' Hegyi said.
</P>
<P>
   He adds that people who lease cars typically must carry more
extensive auto insurance, which may add several hundred dollars a
year in expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, people who exceed the annual mileage allowance _
usually 12,000 to 15,000 _ face additional outlays at the end of
the lease. So do those who don't keep their cars in good shape. If
you don't keep up with oil changes and other required maintenance,
``the lender can even declare you in default in midlease and
repossess the car,'' Hegyi said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, you'll face a hefty penalty if you terminate a
rental agreement early.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury, some finance companies won't let you
leave the state with a leased car, according to Hegyi.
</P>
<P>
   Given all of these drawbacks and more, what explains the
considerable popularity of leasing, which accounts for about
one-third of all auto transactions?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, leasing may be the only recourse for cash-strapped
individuals who can't afford a large down payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most consumers, the monthly payment is still the Number 1
issue on their minds,'' said Greg Swan, general sales manager for
Midway Chevrolet Isuzu in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Those monthly lease payments are almost always lower than what
you would face in purchasing, for the obvious reason that you're
not paying for a vehicle's residual value.
</P>
<P>
   While you will face various upfront fees with leasing _
including sales taxes, vehicle-registration charges, the first
month's payment, a refundable security deposit and the oddly named
``lease-acquisition'' fee _ the total outlay will be less than if
you're buying.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, supporters say leasing provides more flexibility
than buying in that you can exercise an option to purchase the car
or simply turn it back to the dealer after the rental period
expires. No headaches about maintenance bills and no need to sell
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have the option to return the car than be stuck
with it,'' Swan said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, leasing, with the lower monthly payments involved, may be
the only way for some people to gain access to a luxury car. Let's
face it _ car shopping is a highly emotional exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leasing lets you drive a larger, more powerful,
better-equipped BMW,'' a marketing blurb on the German automaker's
Web site reads.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates also point out that the the lack of a down payment on
a lease frees up cash that you can invest or put to other uses.
Virtually all vehicles depreciate, so it may be unwise to invest
thousands of dollars in one, the argument goes.
</P>
<P>
   Depreciation perhaps explains why leasing has become more
common. Although most Americans would rather own their own home
than rent, they don't seem to feel the same way about cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find that people would rather own real estate because
there haven't been too many times over the last 100 years that real
estate has lost money,'' said Mike Mullan, fleet manager at Midway
Chevrolet Isuzu.
</P>
<P>
   Tax laws don't necessarily provide any advantages for people who
lease.
</P>
<P>
   If you use the car for work, you can deduct that portion of your
lease payment attributable to business use, along with normal
operating costs and maintenance. But you also can deduct operating
costs and maintenance for business usage on a purchased car.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you can't directly write off the interest you pay to
buy a new car, you can get a deduction by financing a purchase
through a home-equity loan _ a nice break if you're not using the
vehicle for business.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Osinski, a Phoenix certified public accountant, says the
primary tax advantage associated with leasing reflects the fact
that you face limits on how much depreciation you can deduct on a
purchase. As a general rule, he says leasing makes sense from a tax
standpoint only if you use the vehicle for business and expect to
replace it within three years. The tax rules are tricky, however,
so it's wise to consult an adviser if you use a car for business
and think the this angle may be decisive.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, taxes are only one of many aspects that weigh on
the lease-or-buy decision. Emotional satisfaction, cash flow and
upfront money all factor in, as do your negotiating skills,
financial acumen, driving habits and plans.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the longer you're willing to drive the same car, the
more attractive purchasing becomes from a financial standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to squeeze every drop of value from the money you
spend on a car,'' Bragg writes, ``is to drive it until the wheels
fall off.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
BUY OR LEASE? &QL; 
 &QL; 
You make the call &QL; 
The decision to lease or buy a new vehicle largely boils down to
personal circumstances and attitudes. Answer yes or no to the
following questions, which were adapted from the ``Car Buyer's and
Leaser's Negotiating Bible'' by W. James Bragg, to determine which
option may be best for you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Do you value the image of driving a late-model vehicle?
</P>
<P>
   2. Do you look forward to receiving title to your car?
</P>
<P>
   3. Would you prefer to drive a more expensive car than you can
afford to buy?
</P>
<P>
   4. Do you typically keep your vehicles five years or more?
</P>
<P>
   5. Would you invest the money that you don't have to spend on a
down payment?
</P>
<P>
   6. Do you drive considerably more than 15,000 miles a year?
</P>
<P>
   7. Are you likely to need a different vehicle in three years?
</P>
<P>
   8. Are you able to make a fairly large down payment?
</P>
<P>
   9. Do you always want to drive a car covered by the original
manufacturer's warranty?
</P>
<P>
   10. Is pride of ownership in a car important to you? &QL; 
Scoring: Leasing makes sense if you mostly answered ``yes'' to the
odd-numbered questions and ``no'' to the even-numbered ones. Buying
makes sense if you mostly did the reverse. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DOING IT RIGHT &QC; 
 &QL; 
Getting a good lease &QL; 
Assuming you plan to lease a car, here are some recommendations for
doing it right, as suggested by Hugh Hegyi of the Arizona Attorney
General's office.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Don't focus on the monthly payment amount to the exclusion of
other costs.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Plan to negotiate these six factors: the value of the car,
the amount due at the time of signing, all miscellaneous fees, the
depreciation amount, the yearly mileage allowance and the cost of
buying the vehicle at the end of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   - Discuss each cost component, and ask for an itemization in
writing.
</P>
<P>
   - Avoid ``open-end'' leases, which require you to pay more if
the car is worth less than expected at the lease's termination.
</P>
<P>
   - Shop for interest rates before you get to the dealer, and
remember that this also can be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   - Be willing to back away from a deal if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   - Make sure you understand everything in the lease, and don't
rush into a decision.
</P>
<P>
   - Take as many notes as possible. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE LANGUAGE OF LEASING &QC; 
 &QL; 
Key terms &QL; 
 &QL; 
- Capitalized cost: The price of a leased vehicle, including
upfront charges.
</P>
<P>
   - Depreciation: The amount the vehicle's value erodes over time.
</P>
<P>
   - Finance rate: The number, expressed as either a percentage or
``money factor,'' that indicates how costly a leasing package is.
</P>
<P>
   - Money factor: A decimal that relates to the interest rate on
some leasing contracts. You multiply it by 24 _ regardless of how
long the term of the lease is _ to get the approximate interest
rate. For example, a money factor of 0.00345, when multipled by 24,
equals an interest rate of 0.0828, or 8.28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   - Residual value: The estimated worth of the car when the rental
period expires. The residual value equals the capitalized cost less
depreciation. &QL; 
 &QL; 
