<HEADER>
A8710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HALAL-BUTCHERS-ART-3T     06-01 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALAL-BUTCHERS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE NEW NEIGHBORHOOD BUTCHERS ACT IN AN OLD-FASHIONED WAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., N.J.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Along Ninth Avenue and on East 96th Street in
Manhattan, on Atlantic Avenue in Brooklyn and Ocean Parkway in
Queens _ in fact, in almost any neighborhood in America where
Muslims make their home _ halal meat shops are the new butchers in
an old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   Where small storefronts once housed Italian, French and kosher
butchers, shops now declare that their meat is halal.
</P>
<P>
   To non-Muslims the shops can be mysterious, even intimidating.
But to others they are a happy addition to the checkerboard of
tiny, specialty food shops in the city, places with impeccable meat
and intensely personal service. Even as the production of meat
nationwide becomes increasingly industrialized, analysts say that
halal meat is nevertheless the fastest growing style of specialty
butchering in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The halal sign promises that the meat has been ritually
slaughtered according to Islamic law. The signs also signal a spot
where, in rooms behind the meat counter, small groups gather for
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning, at noon, at dusk and again late at night,
there is taxicab gridlock in front of halal butchers on Ninth
Avenue in Manhattan as drivers stop for prayer. After feeding their
spirits, the drivers often pick up several pounds of halal meat on
the way back to their taxis.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny storefront butchers are intimate places where the
butcher knows his customers' names, family news and favorite cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The shops stock only beef, goat and lamb, and cut it to a
customer's specifications or to suit a particular recipe.
</P>
<P>
   To many of halal's admirers, religious and secular, it signifies
clean, fresh meat. By custom, halal meat is delivered to butchers
in whole carcasses, rather than cut into pieces before shipping.
</P>
<P>
   It is handled in much smaller quantities and by fewer people
than fresh packaged meat or conventional butcher-shop meat. And it
is generally fresher. But except for the religious ritual
surrounding the slaughter, its processing and handling are governed
by the same Agriculture Department regulations that affect all meat
in this country.
</P>
<P>
   The word halal is a Koranic term meaning that which is untied or
loosened. According to Islamic law, halal meat is killed by a
Muslim using a sharp knife, deploying no more than two strokes to
the jugular vein and invoking the name of Allah.
</P>
<P>
   Meat killed in any other fashion is considered haram, or
forbidden, food, along with meat from cloven-foot animals, donkeys,
horses, predatory animals and carrion-feeding birds.
</P>
<P>
   Around this simple code have evolved a host of Muslim eating
traditions, ranging from eating only with the right hand and eating
only when seated on the floor to celebrating certain foods, dates
for instance.
</P>
<P>
   These customs, said Phil Parshall, the author of ``Inside the
Community: Understanding Muslims Through Their Traditions'' (Baker
Books, 1994), emulate Mohammed's habits and are descriptive of some
Muslims, but not proscriptive to all Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Among devout Muslims, sensual pleasure is suspect. Islam's
teachings focus on morality and enlightenment, hard work and
harmony. The believer eats to live but does not live to eat. The
toothsome character of halal meat, therefore, arises by
coincidence, not design.
</P>
<P>
   But among food-loving Americans willing to pay a premium of up
to 30 percent, halal meat, typically tender and delicate in flavor,
is finding thousands of devotees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my customers drive over an hour to get here,'' said
Mohammed Hebbar, the owner of Salama Halal Meat in San Francisco.
``Lots of them aren't even Muslims. They come because they know
halal meat is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Halal regulations, like much Islamic dietary law, are similar to
those governing kosher meat, but this is not the reason that Jews,
Christians, Buddhists and agnostics have begun to buy from halal
butchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about religion,'' said Serena Arenson, 36, who
teaches at an elementary school in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the glass display case at Nusrat Comak Halal Meat
Shop on Ninth Avenue, Ms. Arenson said that stories about
contaminated meat throughout the country, along with the demise of
local kosher butchers and the rise of kosher meat empires, prompted
her interest in halal meat, which is typically sold from tiny
family-owned storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship she has developed over four years with Comak,
the store's owner, as well as the quality of meat he sells, make
her unwilling to shop elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Muslims, on the other hand, are bound to cook and eat only halal
meat. With more than a billion adherents to Islam worldwide and, it
is estimated, six million to eight million followers in the United
States, Muslims alone would create a substantial market for halal,
leaving out of account all the health-conscious and
quality-conscious non-Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Abe Batcha, the owner of Halal Meat USA, one of the two major
halal slaughterhouses on the East Coast, said that his sales have
doubled each of the 12 years he has operated his squat, cinderblock
processing plant in Paterson, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The plant, he said, processes 1,500 to 2,000 head of beef, goat
and lamb each week. He supplies 300 small shops in New York, New
Jersey, Connecticut and Pennsylvania, as well as four major
wholesalers, who sell halal meat as far south as North Carolina and
as far west as Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, he can't meet the demand. More people are
turning Muslim, especially younger people, said Batcha, who was a
farmer in his native Russia. And with the end of farm supports,
which subsidized the labor-intensive raising of small farm animals,
the supply of small animals is going down.
</P>
<P>
   One week recently, for instance, Batcha ordered 400 lambs but
was able to buy only 40.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one other major Agriculture Department-approved
halal processing center, in Trenton, N.J., Batcha said, and the
beef, lamb and goat he and his competitor can buy are virtually the
only halal meat available in the New York metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Islamic dietary code, many customs relating to meat
handling have evolved. Halal meat, for instance, is almost never
more than two days old, is never frozen and is almost always sold
by the slaughterhouse to the retailer as a whole carcass, rather
than cut into portions.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Islamic slaughtering procedure, the animal must
be treated gently, must never see the knife and must be killed by
one, or a maximum of two, swift slices to the jugular vein by a
Muslim who evokes the name of Allah while slaughtering the animal.
Afterward, the blood must be completely drained from the carcass.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make holy, swift and humane as possible the loss
of life,'' said Mrat Olgun, who emigrated from Turkey and oversees
the ritual slaughter. ``We are forbidden to use guns or kill for
pleasure, only for food. That is what it means, halal.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing floor at Halal Meat USA bears little resemblance to
conventional slaughterhouses. Like most meat processors, the 30 men
who work the 8,000-square-foot concrete floor wear blood-splattered
aprons, shin-high rubber boots, down vests and baseball caps.
</P>
<P>
   But when I visited Halal Meat USA in May, unlike other
meat-processing centers I have seen, a mood of calm reverence
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Even under duress.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a young steer panicked in the narrow corridor that
runs from the dock where trucks unload the cattle as far as the
killing floor.
</P>
<P>
   Although less than 2 years old, the steer weighed more than
1,000 pounds and was so agitated that, instead of following in the
steps of hundreds of thousands of heads of cattle that have been
herded down the hall over the last 12 years, it jumped the
four-foot gate between the corridor and the killing floor.
</P>
<P>
   The meat processors, a federal meat inspector and two observers
backed away, as six other men subdued the steer using nothing more
than their hands and their wits. There were no stun guns, no clubs,
no curses. The killing floor became a gentle rodeo as the six men
cajoled and massaged the steer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on,'' they cooed. ``Come on.'' They whispered and petted
the animal to his knees and, finally, to his side on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Only then did Olgun stride toward the steer, with a 22-inch
butcher knife tucked behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the name of Allah, Allah is great,'' Olgun whispered in
Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   The razor-sharp edge of his knife flashed as it arced through
the air. ``In the name of Allah, Allah is great,'' he whispered
again. In one swift motion, Olgun slit the steer's throat. ``In the
name of Allah, Allah is great,'' he said a third time.
</P>
<P>
   Olgun stood still as the slaughtered steer was clamped into a
harness and raised about 10 feet above the floor by a winch. Except
for wiping his knife clean, he didn't move for the eight minutes it
took for the blood to drain from the carcass.
</P>
<P>
   Among Muslims, Olgun is considered holy. Like every halal
butcher interviewed, Mohamed Soliman, who owns Halal Meat Market on
Atlantic Avenue in Brooklyn, said that meat is only as pure as the
heart of the one who slaughtered the animal.
</P>
<P>
   Such conviction, however, does little to convince traditional
American steak eaters, who tend to dismiss halal meat as too young
and lean to be well marbled, too fresh to have garnered the
distinct flavor of a steer that is three to four years old and
whose meat has been aged up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   History could have predicted that halal food would eventually
stand at an ecumenical and multicultural crossroads. Islamic
culture has long overleaped racial and ethnic boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The perception of Muslim culture has for some time been formed
in the United States by thoughts of terrorists and black
separatists, breakaway groups, which are shunned by most Muslims.
Likewise, even sophisticated diners who heard the word halal used
to think exclusively of Arabic-style cooking.
</P>
<P>
   But as Muslims emigrate to this country and conversions to Islam
increase, the diversity of the culture and cuisine are becoming
better known. Arab, Indonesian, Pakistani, East African, North
African, Turkish, Greek, French, Cambodian and American halal cooks
have over the centuries each developed distinct cooking styles.
</P>
<P>
   As with any lean, unaged beef, halal meat is at its best
simmered slowly with full-flavored seasonings, aromatic vegetables
and spices. Likewise, the unassertive meat tastes better when
marinated or treated to a boisterous spice rub before grilling or
sauteing.
</P>
<P>
   One need look no further than a halal meat shop for cooking
inspiration: most carry cinnamon, ginger, black pepper, curry
powder, coriander, cloves and turmeric. But this selection alone
would be contrary to the spirit of halal cooking and would
needlessly limit the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Technique alone may not be enough to bring out the best in halal
meat. Sipping the tea that is customarily offered to customers in
many halal meat shops, a shopper recently complimented the brew and
asked what sort of tea leaf had been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah,'' Comak said at his halal market. ``It tastes good because
I make it with an open heart. If I made it any other way, the tea
would taste bitter to you.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SAMPLING OF SHOPS
</P>
<P>
   For first-time shoppers, a halal meat shop can be confusing. The
meat is not displayed in ready-to-cook cuts. The spices and
condiments are often unfamiliar. The butcher sometimes speaks
little English and can therefore seem unhelpful.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 30 or so halal butchers who were interviewed for
this article were knowledgeable, and once the language barrier was
surmounted, eager to please. Most shops display a poster of
standard meat cuts, and pointing, gestures and smiles make for a
common language. Many halal butchers also delight in seeing the
recipe, or a picture of the dish that a customer is shopping for.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a sampling of the tiny shops where some English is
spoken. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HALAL MEAT CO., 232 Atlantic Avenue, near Gourd Street,
Brooklyn, (718) 625-2781.
</P>
<P>
   HALAL MEAT MARKET, 304 Atlantic Avenue, near Smith Street,
Brooklyn, (718) 797-4795. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FERTILE CRESCENT, 570 Atlantic Avenue, near Fourth Avenue,
Brooklyn, (718) 797-3066. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHAND AND HALAL MEAT, 43-37 Main Street, near Elder Avenue,
Flushing, Queens, (718) 886-2117. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HALAL MEAT GROCERY, 526 Ninth Avenue, near 39th Street,
Manhattan, (212) 695-3061. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HASON ORMAN SUPERIOR HALAL MEAT MARKET, 4105 Park Avenue, near
41st Street, Union City, N.J., (201) 863-9080. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTANI KEBABS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes, plus overnight chilling &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the spice rub:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons ground coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground clove
</P>
<P>
   For the kebabs:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds halal beef cut into about 16 1{-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, peeled and cut into 8 wedges
</P>
<P>
   1 red pepper, cut into 8 wedges
</P>
<P>
   8 cherry tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine all the ingredients for the spice rub in a large
bowl. Add beef cubes, toss and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   2. One hour before serving, remove beef from marinade and let it
come to room temperature. Light charcoal grill, or preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   3. Take four large or eight small skewers, and thread the beef
onto them in chunks, alternating with chunks of onion, pepper and
tomatoes. Grill over white coals 10 minutes; turn, and continue
grilling about 5 minutes, until meat is tender.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Marinade can be used on chicken, beef or lamb. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SENEGALESE SUMMER GOAT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 10 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   2{ pounds boneless goat (or lamb), cut into one-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons coconut oil
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon African bird pepper or other hot red pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 white onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 red pepper, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   { cup white raisins
</P>
<P>
   { cup shredded unsweetened coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 cup thick unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   6 cups cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsalted peanuts, lightly toasted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a cast-iron skillet, toast the curry powder over medium
heat for 2 minutes, stirring constantly to avoid burning. Add goat
or lamb, and toss well. Season with salt, and toss. Raise heat to
medium high, add coconut oil and continue cooking, stirring often,
until meat is brown on all sides, about 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add black pepper, bird pepper, garlic, onions and red pepper,
and stir. Add chicken broth, reduce heat to low, cover pot and
simmer for an hour, checking to be sure the meat is covered with
liquid and adding water, if necessary, to cover.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add raisins and coconut, and bring the mixture to a boil.
Remove from heat, beat in the coconut milk and serve over rice,
garnished with peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
