<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VIOLENCE02-CO     06-01 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIOLENCE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ORDERS STUDY OF MARKETING VIOLENT ENTERTAINMENT
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, leveling some of his strongest
crtiticism of the entertainment industry for marketing violence to
children, ordered a $1 million study Tuesday to determine whether
movie makers, TV networks and video game manufacturers
inappropriately target youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children are being fed a dependable daily dose of
violence,'' Clinton declared in a Rose Garden ceremony in which he
displayed video game advertisements, one of which stated, ``Kill
your friends, guilt free.''
</P>
<P>
   I know this stuff sells, but that doesn't make it right,'' the
president said.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the administration's opposition to the ``Joe Camel''
advertising of the tobacco industry, Clinton said, ``If you look at
some of these ads, it's hard to argue with a straight face that the
games were made for adults in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential study of the entertainment industry's marketing
techniques will be conducted jointly by the Justice Department and
the Federal Trade Commission over the next 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Both agencies have subpoena power, and White House officials
suggested that their study would use that power in order to obtain
private documents from the industry reflecting their strategy for
marketing their products to children.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky, on hand for the White House
announcement, said his staff will, as in probes of the tobacco and
alcohol industries, look into the entertainment companies' internal
marketing records even if that requires subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope we could talk to these companies and get
voluntary compliance,'' Pitofsky said. ``But certainly if we feel
that we can't complete our responsibility here, we're going to turn
to compulsory processes.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said, ``We want to work with the
entertainment industry and not against it.'' She added, ``We hope
to improve the industry's knowledge base so that it too can make
better choices that are in the best interest of parents and
children.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also used the ceremony to urge stricter
enforcement of rating codes for movies and to criticize the
television networks for including new violent programs in their
schedules for next fall. ``The time has come to show some
restraint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a White House fact sheet cited a study last year as
saying only 9 percent of video-game rental outlets stopped minors
from renting material deemed suitable only for adults.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the Motion Picture
Association of America, Hollywood's primary lobbying organization
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, the group's president, Jack Valenti, cautioned
the White House and Congress against taking aim ``at easy targets''
to blame for the recent student shootings at Columbine High School
in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Littleton tragedy, however, the president has
repeatedly criticized the gun manufacturing and entertainment
industries and the gun owners lobby. The gun industry has long been
a political opponent of Clinton's, but entertainment industry
giants are among the president's staunchest financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, joining the president at Tuesday's
ceremony, observed that the shootings at Columbine High School
``has literally pierced the heart of America'' and that consensus
is building to ``do all we can'' to change ``America's culture of
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and the first lady both cited studies dating back
25 years documenting links between violence in the media and the
effects it has on children's behavior. The president noted that by
the time the typical American child reaches the age of 18, he or
she has seen 200,000 dramatized acts of violence and 40,000
dramatized murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boundary between fantasy and reality violence, which is a
clear line for most adults, can become very blurred for vulnerable
children,'' the president said. ``Kids steeped in the culture of
violence do become desensitized to it and more capable of
committing it themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the president's guests at the ceremony was 9-year Arthur
Sawe, a fourth grader in Seattle, Wash., who alerted his mother to
video game ads that touted a game as ``more fun than shooting your
neighbor's cats.'' His actions eventually brought the ad to the
attention of the news media and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might get in trouble with my mommy,'' he said in
introducing the president, ``but instead I am here at the White
House today.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
