<P>
   BRONTE, Texas _ Just off U.S. 277, about 11 miles northeast of
this West Texas town, there is a part of Texas history crumbling
away amid prickly pear cactus, spreading mesquites and a thumping
oil well pump. It is Fort Chadbourne, one of a line of U.S. forts
built in the mid-1800s to protect the settlers from angry Comanches
and to halt the Comanches' traditional trek through the West Texas
plains into Mexico. It is part of the state's history, but it
doesn't belong to the state. By ART CHAPMAN. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
