</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONOPOLY POWER KEY ISSUE AS MICROSOFT TRIAL RESUMES
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Microsoft antitrust trial resumed Tuesday after
a three-month break with the government arguing that the software
giant had won the Internet browser wars and needed to be curbed as
an illicit monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Fisher, economics professor at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, testified that Microsoft's monopoly power
harms consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the packed federal courtroom, David Boies, the lead
Justice Department attorney, said before 10 network TV cameras that
Fisher had summarized the key points of the case while ``gently
correcting some of the errors of his former student.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies was referring to MIT professor Richard Schmalensee,
Microsoft's own economic witness, who contended earlier in the
trial that such emerging technologies as handheld computers
threaten Microsoft's Windows dominance over computer operating
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Under friendly questioning from Boies, Fisher characterized
Schmalensee's conclusion that Microsoft lacks monopoly power as
``muddled,'' ``mixed up,'' ``confused,'' and ``deeply flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great mistake to think that we are talking about
competition in software in general,'' he said at one point. ``We're
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The broader issues within the computer software industry, which
Schmalensee saw as undergoing dynamic change, are ``not relevant
here,'' Fisher said. ``This question is about the personal computer
operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who also testified for the government during the trial's
first phase, claimed that Microsoft's monopoly perch enables the
company to charge ``super-high prices'' and make ``super-high
profits'' from Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's tactics sufficiently eroded rival Netscape
Communications Corp.'s market share to rule out the chance that
software vendors would switch from Windows to Netscape as an
applications platform, Fisher claimed.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting its own rebuttal case, Microsoft is likely to
focus on America Online Inc.'s purchase of Netscape. That dealt,
originally announced as a $4.2 billion acquisition on Nov. 23,
later rose in price to around $10 billion as stock prices soared.
</P>
<P>
   The government and 19 states have accused Microsoft of using its
dominance over operating systems to gain unfair market share in
other sectors, including the browser software needed to surf the
World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
