<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX DOLLARS FOR RELIGIOUS SCHOOLS WILL CORRUPT RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It takes a special kind of arrogance to fly in the face of
history and the wisdom of our founding fathers. Those who are
pushing school voucher or tuition tax credit legislation in order
to fund private and religious schools ignore the fact that our
nation has enjoyed religious liberty precisely because we have kept
government and taxpayer dollars away from religion.
</P>
<P>
   School voucher systems are touted as allowing a parent to choose
a private or religious school instead of a public school for their
child.
</P>
<P>
   The taxpayer money that the state normally gives the public
school for each enrolled student would then go to the private
school the parent selects. Experience has shown, however, it's the
religious and private schools who select student applicants. The
parents don't have the choice.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition tax credit systems give parents who send their child to
a religious or private school a tax write-off on their state taxes.
In other words, it exempts parents who send their children to
private schools from the amount of tax they would normally have to
pay. It's a back-door approach to funding religious schools with
tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson and James Madison understood the problems with
taxing to fund church institutions. And they resisted any tax
support of religious institutions as corrosive of religions,
damaging to individual conscience, and dangerous to government.
</P>
<P>
   After Virginia repealed its tax laws in support of the Anglican
Church in 1779, some state legislators under pressure from the
Anglican Church sought to pass legislation for a general tax in
support of all Christian religions. Madison responded with his
famous `Memorial and Remonstrance Against Religious Assessment` in
which he argued that religion be left to the conviction and
conscience of the individual. Religious beliefs, he maintained,
should be `totally exempt` from the state's funding or
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Not afraid of strong, even inflammatory language, Madison wrote
against government or tax support to help establish religions,
`experience witnesseth that ecclesiastical establishments, instead
of maintaining the purity and efficacy of Religion, have had a
contrary operation ... What have been its fruits? More or less in
all places, pride and indolence in the Clergy; ignorance and
servility in the laity; in both, superstition, bigotry and
persecution.`
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, in his Statute for Establishing Religious Freedom,
which was adopted by Virginia in 1786, states that `to compel a man
to furnish contributions of money for the propagation of opinions
which he disbelieves, is sinful and tyrannical; that even forcing
him to support this or that teacher of his own religious
persuasion, is depriving him of the comfortable liberty of giving
his contributions to the particular pastor, whose morals he would
make his pattern, and whose powers he feels more persuasive to
righteousness.`
</P>
<P>
   It should be clear that forcing anyone to pay taxes to religious
institutions violates that person's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, 15 states are currently considering voucher systems that
would use taxpayer funds to help support religious schools. The
governors of New Mexico, Pennsylvania, Florida and Texas have urged
passage of voucher laws. And 10 states are presently considering
tuition tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the states in our country, including Wyoming
and Florida, have specific language in their declarations or bills
of rights that forbids giving tax money to any church, sect,
religious group or sectarian institution. In many of the remaining
states, the language isn't that specific, but has been understood
to forbid such a distribution of state money.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at least two state legislatures, Alaska and Michigan,
are considering constitutional amendments to allow tax dollars to
go to religious institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher and tuition tax credit plans are sold to the public as a
way for the poorer children to attend private or religious schools.
In practice, however, voucher plans do not give students the amount
of money necessary to enter most private schools. Parents must
spend additional money to pay the costs. Vouchers, where they have
been tried, have not helped students from poor families. And in
order to use the tuition tax credit, a family must have enough cash
on hand to meet the tuition and wait for tax time to have a portion
repaid.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ohio's voucher program that was just struck down by the
Ohio Supreme Court hurt the poor. The Cleveland voucher system
diverted $5.25 million from Ohio's program to aid disadvantaged
students.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, religious organizations have been fortunate;
only one state's voucher system has withstood court challenges --
Wisconsin's.
</P>
<P>
   The state supreme court upheld the Milwaukee voucher program.
The U.S. Supreme Court declined to hear an appeal. Fortunate,
because inevitably and rightfully with taxpayer dollars comes
government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee voucher plan requires private and religious
schools to use `random selection` in choosing students. Two
Lutheran schools were disqualified from participating in the
voucher system based upon applicant questionnaires that favored
children raised as Lutherans. The schools were ordered to resubmit
a random selection plan by the state department of public
instruction or be denied access to the program.
</P>
<P>
   Already, those religious schools that participate in the
Wisconsin voucher system are feeling the pressure of government
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher systems or tuition tax credit plans will give government
agencies the opportunity and the power to insert themselves into
religious schools. There will inevitably be state education
department evaluations of the academic programs in religious
schools. Teachers in those schools will eventually have to reach
the state's requirements for qualification as a teacher. Hiring and
firing, which in church organizations has been exempt from state or
federal labor practices, will undoubtedly fall under these laws,
after the first court challenge by someone fired from a church
school that accepts state voucher funds.
</P>
<P>
   Rightfully, when taxpayer funds are being spent for these
programs, government scrutiny of church schools will dramatically
increase. And along with increased scrutiny there will be further
state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   There is always a steep price to be paid when an organization
accepts government funds. Church schools will be no exception.
</P>
<P>
   And if government funding of a specific church denomination's
schools becomes not only important but necessary, think what
leverage that will give powerful political alliances in terms of
demanding church support in return for continued funding. How
corrosive will that be to religion?
</P>
<P>
   Only short-sighted or naive church leaders back these government
funding schemes. To keep religion free, keep it separated from
government -- that's the Jefferson-Madison message. It's true
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
