<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA'S NICKNAME IN A STATE OF FLUX  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES    
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many thanks to the readers who suggested alternatives to
``Sunshine State'' a s Florida's nickname; a tad fewer thanks to
those who think our nickname is fine as it is, and no thanks
whatsoever to the Venice woman who thought Florida's new nickname
should be, ``Florida: Where Papers Pay and Publish Rambling
Idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dear R.F.: I hope you get your wish and your new license plate
is so wide and heavy that your rear bumper scrapes on the ground
when you drive. Phhhpppttt!)
</P>
<P>
   So much for that.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on to the nominations, which I would loosely classify in
three categories: Not Bad, Too Obvious, and Perhaps Congress Should
Consider a Five-Day Waiting Period for Typewriters.
</P>
<P>
   In the Not Bad category, Barbara Smith of Sarasota suggests
``The Altered State'' ``because ever since I got here people have
been telling me how much everything has changed and how much better
it used to be, but then they go on changing it.''
</P>
<P>
   This would be a good alternative nickname were it not for the
fact that outsiders, not to mention the Chamber of Commerce, will
interpret this nickname to mean that we're soft on drugs, rather
than deeply alarmed about unchecked development. Also, I believe it
is the title of a movie, which would only add to the confusion and
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Diersing was clearly riding the same train of thought
when he came up with ``The Transient State'' ``because things are
always in a state of flux and the population is always changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Diersing apparently realized quickly that inviting more homeless
to Florida might not be a good idea for a variety of reasons, so he
came up with a second, much better, suggestion: ``The Melting Pot
State'' ``Because 1) Florida's population is composed of many
different groups of people from all parts of the world, and 2) If
you hang around all summer like we do, you will definitely melt!''
</P>
<P>
   Many people latched on the Tourist/Retiree theme, which is
certainly understandable. Many cast their ballots, so to speak, for
``The Snowbird State.'' Snowbird was so popular that some even
favored making it the state bird, if for no other reason than to
throw a wrench into the mockingbird/scrub jay debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``God's Waiting Room'' got several votes, though you've got to
think the ACLU would tie that one up in court forever.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the ornithological theme, Gordon Mills of
Sarasota suggested ``Early Birdland,'' apparently making reference
to some people's penchant for late-afternoon dining, not their
taste for earthworms.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think our license plates should send a message to
tourists. Jim Brenock of Sarasota suggested ``We're Glad You're
Gone for the Summer'' and Carlton Martin of Holmes Beach was
thinking along the same lines with ``Come Visit But Don't Stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of tourists, the anti-Disney contingent also had
something to say. ``The Mickey Mouse State'' was a popular
suggestion and I like it, too, except I fear it will only inspire
Michael Eisner to even greater depredations.
</P>
<P>
   Weather and critters weighed heavily on the minds of some
respondents. ``The Hurricane State'' got a lot of votes, though I
think the folks in North Carolina may have something to say about
that one.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquitoes, alligators and cockroaches had their advocates,
though I was rather disappointed that no one shared my enthusiasm
for the lowly love bug.
</P>
<P>
   Several voted for ``The Lightning State,'' a plausible
suggestion given our leadership in that category. However, I
believe a Tampa Bay sports team calls itself that, and it hasn't
proven particularly lucky. Similarly, we probably want to avoid
intra-state squabbles with our new nickname, which rules out
Gators, Seminoles and even Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks in Arizona got wind of this contest and many wrote to
wonder what the heck I was complaining about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling yourself `The Sunshine State' is kind of presumptuous,
inasmuch as Arizona gets more days of sunshine per year than does
Florida. We also have a higher rate of melanoma in Tucson than you
do, so melanoma state is out,'' said Don LaVanway of Green ``it's
not really green'' Valley, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Penny, also of Arizona, points out that Tucson, known as
``The Old Pueblo,'' tried to change its name to ``The Sunshine
Factory'' a few years ago and has since changed back to ``The Old
Pueblo.'' I don't bring this up for any reason other than point out
that it is never too late to correct the error of our ways.
</P>
<P>
   Some other suggestions I liked include ``The Lawnmower State,''
``Whatever Happened to the Lotto Money State,'' ``The Strip-Mall
State,'' ``Giant Theme Park Overkill State,'' ``Armadillos Make
Good Eating State'' and ``The Mildew State.''
</P>
<P>
   My favorite? A tough call. But I think we've got to go with the
suggestion of Marty Hahne, who said he came up with this one after
breathing bug spray all morning:
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida: The Optional Stop On Red State.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
