<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Africans go to polls in all-race elections
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The task awaiting Thabo Mbeki must seem like following Muhammad
Ali as heavyweight champion or succeeding George Washington as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are lining up at polling places across South Africa today
to participate in the country's second all-race elections. If the
results go as has been widely predicted, Mbeki will become the
country's new president _ succeeding Nelson Mandela, the
prisoner-turned-president and Nobel Peace Prize winner who inspires
reverence both inside and outside South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Today's elections are to choose a new parliament. Polls show
that the African National Congress party _ Mandela's party _ will
again win an overwhelming victory. The newly elected members will
convene June 16 to choose the new president, Mbeki, who has already
succeeded Mandela as party leader.
</P>
<P>
   The only question most analysts have is whether the ANC will win
the two-thirds majority that would enable the party to amend the
constitution without the votes of other parties. Opponents have
urged voters to deny the ANC that margin, saying it is a mistake to
hand too much to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, 80, will retire having realized most of his dreams. Not
only has South Africa's governmental oppression of the black
majority been overturned, but Mandela is credited by many with
fostering a spirit of forgiveness and racial reconciliation that,
while far from complete, has progressed further than almost anyone
predicted a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki will face much different challenges. Unemployment is 38
percent. Rampant crime is discouraging foreign investment. Wealth
remains concentrated in white hands, while many blacks lack
adequate schools, housing, water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, who turns 57 this month (and whose name is pronounced
TAH-bo mm-BECK-y), is the son of Govan Mbeki, a prominent ANC
activist who spent time imprisoned with Mandela. The younger Mbeki
spent most of his life in exile, earning a master's degree at
Sussex University in England, undergoing guerilla training in the
Soviet Union and serving the ANC as a spokesman, diplomat and
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   He has left his Marxist leanings behind, and has advocated an
``African renaissance'' based on devotion to African culture
combined with free-market capitalism. No sudden shifts in policy
are expected, as Mbeki, now deputy president, has already been
overseeing the day-to-day operations of the government as Mandela
concentrated on broader themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thabo has been running the government for several years,''
Mandela said recently, ``and I have only been the nominal
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
