<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BOOKS-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COOL AND CREEPY SUMMER FOR BOOK-LOVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was the best of times, it was the worst of times ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Where new books are concerned, Summer '99 is half of Charles
Dickens' famous line from ``A Tale of Two Cities.'' The ``good''
half. Whether you like fiction or nonfiction, finely crafted
literature or blood-and-sex potboilers, Bob Woodward or Patricia
Cornwell, the next few months offer the perfect books for you. Even
Ralph Ellison and Ernest Hemingway are back from the grave. There
may never have been a better, more eclectic batch of
June/July/August titles to take to the beach or the mountains or
just to read while scrunched up in your favorite chair at home.
</P>
<P>
   They will include:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hannibal'' by Thomas Harris (Dell/Delacorte, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Hannibal Lecter's back, and nobody
writes a creepier whodunit than Harris. It would be almost
impossible for ``Hannibal'' to live up to its advance hype, but
they've been saying that about ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace,'' and the lines outside movie theaters remain long. The
publisher has ordered 1 million copies for ``Hannibal's'' first
printing; 100,000 is the average for a sure-fire bestseller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juneteenth,'' by Ralph Ellison (Random House, $25).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: The deceased author was a literary
treasure. ``Invisible Man'' remains a classic, and we can assume or
at least hope canny posthumous editing will result in a novel that
is almost if not equally as insightful and moving. It's unusual for
much-anticipated ``literary'' fiction to be released during the
summer, when lighter reading fare is the tradition, but the title
makes the June 19 release date obligatory. (''Juneteenth'' is the
annual celebration of June 19, 1865, when Texas slaves finally
learned they had been emancipated by Abraham Lincoln two years
earlier.)
</P>
<P>
   The plot involves a racist senator, who, shot by a would-be
assassin, calls to his side a black preacher he has known since
childhood. Their tangled relationship can be viewed as a microcosm
of 1960s American race relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black Notice,'' by Patricia Cornwell (Putnam, $25.95).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Cornwell's brainchild, Dr. Kay
Scarpetta, is once again on the trail of a fiendish serial killer,
this one imported to the United States from France. As usual,
Cornwell's graphic descriptions of autopsies and Scarpetta's
ongoing emotional flounderings fill up lots of fast-paced pages.
Fans of the series will not be disappointed; this is the best
Scarpetta yarn in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shadow: Five Presidents and the Legacy of Watergate,'' by Bob
Woodward (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: The author is arguably the American
journalist who has the most insights (and sources) involving modern
American government. True, some of Woodward's last books have been
tired tomes crammed with rehashed political gossip. ``Five
Presidents'' is rumored to be much, much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``True at First Light,'' by Ernest Hemingway, edited by Patrick
Hemingway (Scribner, $26.)
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Ernest Hemingway wrote it, sort of.
Son Patrick reworked a dusty, previously unpublished 800-page
manuscript about one of Papa's African dalliances. This being the
100th anniversary of Hemingway's birth, his fans will gladly invest
$26 to see whether ``True at First Light'' might be a final,
glorious gift from a great writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buxton Spice,'' by Oonya Kempadoo (Dutton, $21.95).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Advance buzz has Kempadoo pegged as
the hot new writer of '99. She's a native of Guyana, and, natch,
this tale of young Lula and her hometown of Tamarind Grove is set
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First World War,'' by John Keegan (Knopf, $35).
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
