<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will cover most of the Western states
Wednesday as an expansive whirlpool of high-level chill moves
southeast from the Pacific Northwest. Clusters of showers and some
strong thunderstorms will develop near the west slopes of the
central and northern Rockies during afternoon as a series of jet
stream disturbances embedded in the whirlpool cause the moist,
unstable air to rise rapidly. Strong wind gusts and hail will
accompany some of the storms especially in Wyoming and Montana.
Farther west, unseasonably cool air will surge south through the
Pacific Northwest. Scattered coastal and mountain showers will
occur in the chilly air.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the day will have ample sunshine from the eastern
Rockies to the central Mississippi Valley. Late in the day, potent
thunderstorms will erupt from the eastern slopes of the Rockies to
the western Plains as the disturbance over the Western states moves
slowly east. Clusters of strong thunderstorms will continue into
the night over the western and central Plains, but tranquil
conditions will linger farther east.
</P>
<P>
   Warm and humid weather will persist over most of the East.
Coastal areas will have a mixture of clouds and limited hazy
sunshine with little chance for rain. Meanwhile, showers and
thunderstorms will develop from the eastern Ohio and Tennessee
valleys to the Appalachians as a sluggish cold front moves east. In
the wake of the front, clouds will linger for a time, but less
humid conditions will spread across the northern Mississippi Valley
and Great Lakes states during the day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hurricane Season &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The six-month Atlantic hurricane season began Tuesday, but the
most active time in the season is still a few months away. Although
tropical oceans have warmed above the 80 degree temperature
threshold for hurricane development, vigorous winds near 50,000
feet will rip apart most seedling clusters of thunderstorms roaming
the Atlantic. These winds will relax as the summer progresses, with
the heart of hurricane season arriving in the middle of September.
A normal season produces 10 tropical storms, six of which reach
hurricane status with winds of at least 65 knots. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8746 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-BOOKS-2ndTake-     06-01 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BOOKS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: Knopf, $35). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You want this book because: Megabestselling novelist Tom Clancy
declares Keegan ``is the best historian working today, period.''
All Keegan's books condense complex military strategy into
understandable, gripping prose that reads like the finest fiction.
Besides, read this 700-page monster on the beach and you'll impress
everyone with your intellectualism and bulging biceps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timbuktu,'' by Paul Auster (Holt, $22).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Paul Auster is arguably the finest
living American writer, period. His novels are each brilliantly
crafted and fabulously quirky; ``Timbuktu,'' for instance, views
the world through the eyes of Mr. Bones, a dog who follows his
grubby master on a Don Quixote-like adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comrades,'' by Stephen Ambrose (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $21).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Ambrose's gritty, unsentimental
style is perfect for creating word portraits of a dozen men whose
courage, ambition and/or downright decency set them apart. Another
critic has referred to ``Comrades'' as ``Ambrose Lite''; a better
term would be ``Ambrose reader-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``White Oleander,'' by Janet Fitch (Little, Brown, $24).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Oprah said so, and, for the first
time in a while, her TV Book Club selection has launched an obscure
novel onto the bestseller list. In truth, this yarn, narrated by
12-year-old Astrid as she grows up in a series of foster homes
while her mother serves out a jail term, is populated with
predictable characters; the writing isn't all that great if you
break it down sentence by sentence. Somehow, though, the sum of the
whole overcomes the mediocrity of the parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nudist on the Late Shift and Other True Tales of Silicon
Valley,'' by Po Bronson (Random House, $25).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: It's nice to learn that people who
struck it rich are even dafter than the rest of us. We've always
assumed that entrepreneurs in this Bay Area high-tech enclave were
oddballs _ Apple's Steve Jobs and Steve Wozniak were the first
early examples _ and Bronson assures us they are in especially
entertaining ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granny Dan,'' by Danielle Steel (Delacorte, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: You always enjoy Steel's
adjective-laden, hormone-pulsating prose. This time around, a
lovely 17-year-old faces the dangers and excitement of 1902 Russia.
The big love scene begins on Page 102, if you want to skip ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farewell: A Memoir of Texas Childhood,'' by Horton Foote
(Scribner, $24).
</P>
<P>
   You want this book because: Among all these other books,
``Farewell'' may be the best. Foote, one of Texas's most beloved
wordsmiths, hits new literary heights with recollections of a
childhood spent among colorful relatives and family friends.
</P>
<P>
   Also noteworthy:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Girl's Guide to Hunting and Fishing,'' by Melissa Banks
(Viking, $23.95): Banks' agent got this book extra publicity by
offering it only to female publishing-house buyers. It's funny in
several places, but not as consistently hilarious as Viking
publicists would like you to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Turn of the Century,'' by Kurt Andersen (Random House,
$24.95): Because Andersen is already so well-known as a staff
writer for New Yorker magazine, this failed attempt at social and
political satire has received far more attention than it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Whole Woman,'' by Germaine Greer (Knopf, $25): ``The
Female Eunuch'' taught us that anger tempered with common sense is
constructive; ``The Whole Woman'' proves that anger tempered with
more anger is simply bile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Stranger Here Myself,'' by Bill Bryson (Broadway, $25):
Bryson is the funniest author among all modern-day humorists. This
collection of short essays about the whiny expatriot's return to
America is hysterically entertaining enough to bring a smile to the
face of, well, Germaine Greer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deadlines &AMP; Datelines,'' by Dan Rather (Morrow, $23): Hey, Tom
Brokaw had a bestseller with ``The Greatest Generation,'' didn't
he? Even if this collection of career anecdotes proves Rather
doesn't have much to say in print, he doesn't want to be left out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
