A8749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDELSBLATT-NYT &LR;      06-01 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDELSBLATT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET JOURNAL EUROPE, GERMAN PAPER ANNOUNCE PARTNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Hoping to fend off the Financial Times of
London in Continental Europe, Dow Jones &AMP; Co. on Tuesday announced
an alliance with Germany's biggest daily business newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Dow Jones agreed to exchange a stake in the Wall
Street Journal Europe for a stake in Handelsblatt, owned by
Verlagsgruppe Georg von Holtzbrinck of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers plan to use each other's reporting, with each
allowing the other to translate and publish its material on the
same day.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance is the latest turn in a heated rivalry to
dominate Europe's business press.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times, owned by Pearson PLC, has teamed up with
the German magazine publisher Gruner &AMP; Jahr to introduce a new
German-language version of its salmon-colored daily.
</P>
<P>
   Employing about 100 reporters and editors in Germany, the
newspaper is expected to start later this year and compete directly
with Handelsblatt.
</P>
<P>
   Dieter von Holtzbrinck, chairman of Holtzbrinck in Duesseldorf,
said his partnership with the Journal was not a defensive reaction
to The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a reaction, but it is really a coincidence,'' he
said at a news conference here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Elliott House, president of Dow Jones International, said
the alliance would strengthen both papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point here is not to homogenize these two publications,''
she said. ``We want to use our relative strengths to enhance each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1983, the Wall Street Journal Europe says its
circulation is about 70,000, with about 57,000 outside Britain. The
Financial Times claims a circulation of about 367,000, about
113,000 in Continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe's increasingly integrated economy, the competition to
dominate its business media has become increasingly important and
heated.
</P>
<P>
   The newest stage of the rivalry poses an intriguing test for two
opposing language strategies in Europe's polyglot market.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because English is the most common denominator for many
Europeans, both the Financial Times and the Wall Street Journal
Europe come closer than any other daily newspapers to being
Europe-wide publications.
</P>
<P>
   But the German-speaking region of Europe is substantial _ more
than 80 million people in Germany plus those in Austria and much of
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones refuses to provide financial details about the Wall
Street Journal Europe, though the company says it has been
profitable for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Holtzbrinck, owned by the Holtzbrinck family, is one of
Germany's biggest publishing and media groups. Besides
Handelsblatt, it owns book publishers including Henry Holt, Farrar
Straus &AMP; Giroux in the United States, and scientific and technical
journals and the influential German weekly Die Zeit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Holtzbrinck will acquire 49 percent of the
Wall Street Journal Europe, while Dow Jones will acquire 22 percent
of Handelsblatt. In addition, Holtzbrinck is acquiring part of Dow
Jones' minority stakes in a Czech publishing venture and the German
financial news agency VWD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
