<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1822EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIGHTHOUSE-COX     06-01 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTHOUSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lighthouse being readied for new location as residents voice
concerns about move
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUXTON, N.C. _ As a brisk breeze hinted at the official start of
the Atlantic hurricane season, moving expert Peter Friesen said
Tuesday not even powerful winds would deter this month's relocation
of the 129-year-old Cape Hatteras Lighthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it is not going to fall over,'' Friesen said as workers
made final preparations for the historic Outer Banks beacon's
disputed move, expected to start in mid-June and take a month.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many opponents of the move are Dare County officials,
who sued in federal court to block the $11.8 million federal
project but decided to drop the lawsuit in April. They had argued
that once the lighthouse was moved, the sand dunes and man-made
erosion control barriers that had protected the tower would be
allowed to deteriorate. According to the suit, erosion would
threaten nearby N.C. 12 and the fishing and tourist village of
Buxton, washed over by Hurricane Emily in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals who fought hard to stop the move of this lighthouse
are now waiting to see what will happen,'' said Dewey Parr, 68, a
Buxton businessman and a columnist for The Island Breeze, a local
newspaper. ``They are not wanting it to fall. It is the most
treasured monument we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   National Park Service officials said contractors have taken
precautions, including the installation of monitors to signal
whether the 200-foot-tall lighthouse leans or existing cracks
worsen during the relocation. As it is being moved, the tower could
withstand hurricane winds up to 180 mph, said Friesen, of Lynden,
Wash., who has moved more than 4,000 buildings, including three New
England lighthouses.
</P>
<P>
   The company moving the Cape Hatteras Lighthouse, International
Chimney Corp. of Buffalo, N.Y., hired 77-year-old Friesen as a
consultant for the critical job of lifting and pushing the
lighthouse to its new home 2,900 feet inland.
</P>
<P>
   The preparation work since January has been tedious, slow and
sandy, with a stream of tourists snapping pictures from a nearby
parking lot. The black-and-white candy-striped lighthouse,
threatened by waves striking 150 feet from its base, is now closed
to the public. It is scheduled to reopen in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a big waste of money,'' said Cecil Pope, 49, of
Richmond, Va., vacationing this week on North Carolina's Outer
Banks. ``I would say just let things go.''
</P>
<P>
   Based upon the recommendation of the National Academy of
Sciences that moving the lighthouse would be the best way to
protect it, the National Park Service secured congressional funding
to relocate the lighthouse and three other structures. Two are
houses once occupied by lighthouse keepers, and the third is a
brick building that once stored oil for the lighthouse flame.
``Anything can happen,'' said Friesen, who nearly tumbled out of a
pickup truck during the news briefing when the tailgate popped open
as the truck traveled along the lighthouse's route. ``But we've
always got it under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Crews have chipped away the lighthouse's granite underpinnings
and braced its base and sides with temporary supports. Seven
massive steel beams have been slid under the tower's base.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Friday or Saturday, 100 hydraulic jacks attached to the
steel beams will begin the week-long process of lifting the tower
five feet from its sandy hole. Once the lighthouse is lifted, crews
will begin replacing the temporary supports underneath the
lighthouse with ``roll beams.'' Attached to those beams are 100
metal rollers, which will travel along a mat of hardened steel laid
out in the lighthouse's path. Underneath the steel is a foot of
gravel over packed sand. Hydraulic devices will then push the
lighthouse, traveling up to 100 feet during a 12-hour workday,
until it finally arrives at its recently poured concrete
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be boring,'' Friesen said, ``if you are going to
spend days watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
