<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8769 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      06-01 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. OFFICIALS SOUND FLEXIBLE AS PEACE EFFORT GAINS STEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL And ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States moved Tuesday to bolster
accelerating diplomatic efforts to end the 70-day-old conflict in
Yugoslavia by signaling a willingness to suspend allied bombing and
to consider a smaller U.S. role in a post-war security force in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced that U.S.-led air strikes will ease in
Kosovo beginning on Thursday to permit air drops of humanitarian
supplies by civilian aircraft arranged by the private International
Rescue Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials voiced new U.S. flexibility on
the eve of Wednesday's peace mission to Belgrade by former Russian
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari, the Balkan envoy for the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who coordinated delicate
preparations for the mission during meetings in Bonn with
Chernomyrdin, Ahtisaari and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott, struck an optimistic note.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgrade-bound envoys ``are on the way of finding a
political solution to the conflict'' with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott, a confidante of President Clinton and fluent Russian
speaker who has been leading U.S. efforts to fashion a U.S.-Russian
peace plan, was more cautious. The envoys' success ``depends on
hard decisions by the Belgrade leadership,'' Talbott said in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials in Washington said the envoys
would press Milosevic to clarify his announcement that Yugoslavia
is willing to halt the ouster of ethnic Albanian Muslims from
Kosovo, withdraw most of the 40,000 Serbian troops from Kosovo and
accept an international security force authorized by the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials said in a letter delivered Tuesday to German
officials that Milosevic will accept ``a United Nations presence,
mandate and other elements to be decided by a U.N. Security Council
resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the envoys need to
see Milosevic personally because ``it is important for there to be
an explanation by Milosevic as to what it is he means.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart opened the door to
suspension of U.S.-led bombing raids as well as a smaller U.S. role
in the post-war security force planned to oversee the return of
more than one million Kosovo refugees to their homes inside the
Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have long avoided public discussion of a
suspension of the bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have basically said what we need to see to see a
suspension,'' Lockhart told reporters. ``We've been very clear on
what they need to do for a suspension of the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   To win a bombing halt, Lockhart said, Milosevic must halt ethnic
cleansing in Kosovo, begin troop withdrawals and agree to allied
conditions for a post-war security force.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also raised the possibility that the Clinton
administration might consider a post-war international security
force for Kosovo with a smaller U.S. contingent than previously
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller U.S. component might address Milosevic's demands that
troops from the United States, Britain and France be excluded from
the post-war security force because the nations' forces took part
in the grueling bombardment of his country for more than two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said it is ``difficult to imagine'' that a post-war
security force in Kosovo could be effective without U.S.
participation. But he added that the White House would be willing
to ``take a look'' at a plan for a reduced U.S. role.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the White House will only insist that the
international security force that heads into Kosovo be clearly
under NATO's command, with clear lines of authority.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton was expected to announce the
U.S. share of the peace-keeping force during a commencement address
at the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo., on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the U.S. component of the
peace-keeping force will be no more than 15 percent of the
50,000-member post-war security force or about 7,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a Memorial Day address at Arlington National
Cemetery on Monday, underscored that the United States will take a
more modest role than it took in 1995 when U.S. forces made up half
of the 60,000- strong allied force that went into Bosnia to enforce
a U.S.-brokered peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this military campaign, the United States has borne a large
share of the burden, as we must, because we have a greater capacity
to bear that burden,'' Clinton declared. ``But all Americans should
know ... that when the peacekeeping force goes in there, the
overwhelming majority of people will be European.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari said that the composition of the post-war
international security force in Kosovo ``is something that we
should look as a practical issue and not try to politicize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari said the international security force that heads into
Kosovo has to be able to create a secure environment that will
encourage displaced Kosovar refugees to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the participation of ``certain countries is of
vital importance so that we can create that security feeling _
which is absolutely vital,'' Ahtisaari said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The International Rescue Committee, a private New York-based
refugee relief organization, said Tuesday that it will begin two
air drops daily of food supplies to ethnic Albanian refugees inside
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Reynold Levy, the organization's president, said two
Russian-made Antonov-26 cargo planes flown by Moldovan crews will
depart from an airport in Pescara, Italy, early Thursday and fly in
tandem over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Each cargo drop will supply enough food to feed about 4,000
adults for one day. The flights will continue indefinitely, the
group said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization planned to air drop leaflets over Kosovo on
Wednesday alerting refugees about the impending food deliveries.
The organization sent letters to NATO and Yugoslav officials
telling them of the flights.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com. Eric Rosenberg can be reached at
202-298-6920 and at the email address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
