A8772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICAL-SHOE-COX     06-01 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-SHOE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Musical shoe' would have children tapping their feet
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Will Van Straden, an opera singer, is serious about
music _ but he also wants it to be fun for amateur musicians,
especially children. That wish led to his being issued U.S. Patent
5855080 in January.
</P>
<P>
   The patent protects a ``musical shoe'' that's played by tapping
your feet. But this isn't your old-fashioned tap-dance shoe. Van
Straden's shoe is battery-powered and plays music with an
electronic sound similar to a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Van Straden, a Netherlands native who now lives in Atlanta, was
sitting at a piano one day and picking out a tune.
</P>
<P>
   And, as so many musicians and would-be musicians do, he was
tapping his feet as he played.
</P>
<P>
   That's when he had the idea for a musical shoe that would be
simple to play, that would play music with a ``non-annoying'' sound
that could be turned off when the player _ or parents _ wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each shoe has eight color-coded buttons embedded in the bottom
of the sole, and each button plays one of eight notes in an octave,
which means different tunes can be played,'' said Van Straden, 41.
One shoe has eight notes in a lower octave, the other eight notes
in a higher octave.
</P>
<P>
   As some people can ``play by ear'' on pianos, some people would
be able to ``play by foot,'' picking out tunes as they step on the
buttons.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have no sense of music, they could use simple
sheet music, pointing out which buttons, and in what sequence, to
step on to play a tune.
</P>
<P>
   The small batteries, a switch and other electronic elements of
the music apparatus can be embedded in the rubber soles of sport
shoes or other types of casual shoes.
</P>
<P>
   When turned off, the shoes are regular shoes. When turned on,
tunes can be played while strolling down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more of a novelty item than anything else, but I think
children would love the shoes,'' said Van Straden, who works
through a New York agent to sing with various opera companies in
the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is the place to be for novelties and toys,'' he said.
``It's a multibillion-dollar market.''
</P>
<P>
   He is seeking a manufacturer to make and market the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Tharpe writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
