<HEADER>
A8778 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOODNEWS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-01 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;       
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 
 EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but 
 the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is 
 enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff 
 aims to change that. This regular round-up column will make 
 practical sense of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as 
 well as offering offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food 
 news to put on your plate.  FOOD IN THE NEWS: Cholesterol Cutter Reaches the Market  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; An expensive new margarinelike spread that
promises to lower your cholesterol level hit grocery store shelves
last week.
<P>
   Called Benecol, the spread promises to cut LDL cholesterol
levels by as much as 14 percent if consumers eat at least three
11/2 teaspoon servings a day.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are based on study published last year in the New
England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration earlier this month cleared the
way for spreads like Benecol, which are among the first wave of
``nutraceuticals'' or ``functional foods.'' The products are
fortified with compounds targeting specific health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other low-cholesterol margarines that help limit intake
of LDL _ the most harmful type of cholesterol _ Benecol promises to
help stop the body from absorbing cholesterol. Some studies
indicate that, in addition to blocking bad cholesterol, it also
blocks the good.
</P>
<P>
   The secret in Benecol is stanol ester, a plant compound
extracted from pine fiber used to make paper. Several studies,
including a long-term look at 500 people in Finland who ate Benecol
regularly over several years, showed reductions in cholesterol by
as much as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The spread is sold in 5-ounce boxes of 21 individual servings
for $4.50-$5.50 at several supermarkets and pharmacies, including
Safeway, Lucky, Walgreens and Long's.
</P>
<P>
   Benecol's manufacturers report the spread has no harmful side
effects. However, other studies show that, in some people, the body
compensates for loss of cholesterol by producing more of it. And
the absorption of some nutrients, like beta-carotene and lycopene,
which help the body fight heart disease and cancer, may be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   But the small amounts recommended aren't a risk, says Liz
Applegate, a professor of nutrition at the University of California
at Davis, who discusses Benecol in her latest book, ``Eat Your Way
to a Healthy Heart'' (Prentice Hall, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually quite safe,'' she says. People consume small
amounts of naturally occurring stanol esters every day, she says.
</P>
<P>
   But, Applegate warns, it doesn't mean you can put Benecol on
your bagel and then slather it with cream cheese or eat a plate of
bacon and eggs and hope to attain lower cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the point. You need to eat it as part of a
heart-healthy diet,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Benecol should be substituted for other butters or margarines,
not eaten in addition to them, she says.
</P>
<P>
   The light version, which isn't recommended for cooking but is
slightly sweeter and less greasy than the regular version, has 3
grams of fat and 30 calories per 11/2 teaspoons. The regular
version contains 5 grams of fat _ some of it unhealthy saturated
fat _ and 45 calories per 1 teaspoon serving.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil Consumer Healthcare, the pharmaceutical arm of Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, created the product. For a look at the studies behind the
new spread, see McNeil's Web site at  &LR; www.benecol.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Look for other spreads using stanol ester to be on supermarket
shelves soon. Among them is Take Control, a product from Lipton
that promises a 7 percent to 10 percent reduction in cholesterol
levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
