<HEADER>
A8779 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TASTE-MIX-SFCHRON &LR;      06-01 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-MIX-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASTER'S CHOICE  
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  People may be looking for shortcuts, but when it
comes to margaritas, the answer does not lie in prepared mixes.
Today's panel tasted nine mixes from grocers' shelves, freezers and
refrigerator cases, but only one broke the 50-point mark.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike a homemade margaritas, the mixes were composed primarily
of water and high-fructose corn syrup. Only one had fresh lime
juice; the others were made with concentrates or with a blend of
citric acid and natural and artificial flavors.
</P>
<P>
   The panel tasted the mixes plain and then combined with the
amount of tequila recommended by each product manufacturer.
Panelists were divided on what they liked and disliked, but all
agreed that none of the mixes produced a margarita even close to a
homemade version.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sauza  &LR; (1-liter bottle, $2.99 at Beverages &AMP; More!) took top
honors. One panelist described it as nicely balanced, and another
thought it tasted like a ``classic margarita.'' But others
perceived a chemical flavor and aroma. Two would buy it, two might
buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Two products tied for second place:  &UR; Bacardi &LR;  (10-ounce frozen
can, $1.99 at many supermarkets) and  &UR; Mr.&AMP; Mrs. T &LR;  (1 liter, $3.99
at many supermarkets).
</P>
<P>
   With Bacardi, two panelists thought the proportion of tequila to
mix was too high. One panelist liked the mix alone but not with
tequila. But another thought it looked ``like fresh-squeezed lime
juice.'' One would buy it, two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   One taster liked Mr. &AMP; Mrs. T with tequila added, and another
thought it was well balanced even though the finish was bitter. But
others detected a medicinal taste. One would buy it, two might buy
it, two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jose Cuervo &LR;  (1 liter, $3.99 at many supermarkets) scored one
point lower than Bacardi and Mr. &AMP; Mrs. T. One panelist described
its taste as clean with a ``good sour finish.'' But others thought
it was not balanced and tasted bitter. One would buy it, one might
buy it, and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trader Joe's  &LR; (32-ounce refrigerated jug, $1.99 at Trader
Joe's) _ the only brand with fresh juices _ scored just one point
lower than Jose Cuervo. Despite the fact that the label said it was
made with fresh juices, two panelists thought it tasted artificial.
One likened it to limeade, but others found it bracing and sharp.
Two would buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Four mixes scored too low to rate: Ruffner, Finest Call, Major
Pete's and Ass Kickin'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
