<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8781 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEARN-SFCHRON &LR;      06-01 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Marion Cunningham, best known for her revisions
of  the Fannie Farmer cookbooks, now crusades to get more people
to 
 cook at home. This column, based on her book ``Learning to Cook 
 With Marion Cunningham'' (Knopf, 1999), is expected to be 
 available every two weeks from the San Francisco Chronicle via 
 New York Times News Service. It especially targets novice cooks. 
 &HT;     This week, we present the main story, a sidebar on preparing 
 fruit for dessert and the recipe for the main-dish soup.   LEARNING TO COOK: Try Corn Soup and Tortillas for Supper  
   
 By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Mexican Corn Soup makes a very good supper, served
with warm tortillas. Put small dishes of sour cream, chopped green
chiles and fresh coriander leaves on the table. You can add any or
all of these condiments to the soup or sprinkle them on the warm
tortillas, then fold them into quarters.
<P>
   As for dessert, beginning cooks often think that few ingredients
and simple directions mean the recipe isn't as good as one with
many ingredients and more complicated instructions. Nothing could
be further from the truth _ generally, the simpler the better.
</P>
<P>
   Try either of the accompanying ideas for serving fruit as a
finale. Both are close to foolproof, and I predict you will make
them many times.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TIPS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the Corn.  &LR; If you are using fresh ears of corn, pull
off the husks and silks (silks are the shiny threadlike strings
that are under the husks) and discard them.
</P>
<P>
   To cut the corn kernels off the cob, hold each ear of corn
upright, with the small end of the cob on the cutting surface.
Using a sharp knife, cut the kernels away from the cob, cutting two
or three rows off at a time. Discard the cobs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Masa Harina.  &LR; Masa harina can be found in most supermarkets.
Buy the package labeled ``Masa Harina,''  &LR; not  &LR; ``Instant Masa
Harina.'' Masa harina is a corn flour commonly used in Mexico and
made from cooked, dried corn. It is added to today's soup recipe to
give flavor and to act as a thickener. Store the leftover masa in
the refrigerator or freezer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Marion Cunningham, Bay Area cooking teacher, is the author of
``Learning to Cook,'' ``Cooking With Children,'' ``The Fannie
Farmer Cookbook'' and ``The Breakfast Book,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; AND FOR DESSERT, TRY FRUIT &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Strawberries &LR; . When strawberries are sweet and ripe, try serving
them with their stems on with a bowl of sour cream and one of brown
sugar, so you can dip them into the cream and sugar, then pop them
right into your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Oranges &LR; . Peel 4 or 5 oranges and separate them into individual
sections. Cut the sections crosswise into 4 or 5 pieces. Put the
pieces of orange in a bowl, and stir in about 2/3 cup of orange
marmalade. Stir to mix and coat the orange pieces with the
marmalade. Cover the bowl and chill. Serve in pretty stemmed
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; MEXICAN CORN SOUP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This soup makes a whole meal. Top it with sour cream, chopped
green chiles and cilantro. Serve it with corn tortillas that you
have wrapped in foil and warmed in a 350 degree oven for 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ingredients: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh corn kernels (about 6 ears), or frozen corn kernels
</P>
<P>
   41/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   21/2 tablespoons masa harina
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 teaspoons chopped green chiles (from a 4-ounce can)
</P>
<P>
   A few sprigs cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Instructions: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing Fresh Corn: &LR;  If using fresh corn, first cut the
kernels from the cob with a sharp knife. The best way is to stand
the cob upright on a cutting board, with one hand securing the
upper end. Using a large sharp knife, cut downward, slicing the
kernels from the cob. You'll be surprised how easy this is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Making the Soup:  &LR; Put the corn _ fresh or frozen _ into a
heavy-bottom pot with the milk and salt and set over medium heat.
Bring to a boil, reduce to a simmer, and cook gently for 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a pint (2-cup) jar with a lid, vigorously shake together the
masa harina and the water. Add the mixture to the soup, stirring to
blend in well and heat through, about 4 to 5 minutes. The masa
harina will thicken the soup as well as flavor it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Serving the Soup: &LR;  Ladle soup into warm bowls. Drop a
tablespoon of sour cream in the center of each bowl, add a heaping
teaspoon of chopped green chiles, and finish with some cilantro
leaves and a sprinkle of freshly ground pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 380 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g protein, 47 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 17 g fat (10 g saturated), 50 mg cholesterol, 442
mg sodium, 7 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
