<HEADER>
A8784 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKGINGER-SFCHRON &LR;      06-01 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKGINGER-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 COOK'S BOOKS _ `A Spoonful of Ginger' Aims to Soothe and Comfort    By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Just before I hopped a plane to Seattle, I tucked
Nina Simonds' ``A Spoonful of Ginger'' into my bag.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was heading north to spend a few days caring for my best
friend, a recently retired chef who had abdominal surgery and faced
weeks in bed.
</P>
<P>
   The book promises irresistible, health-giving recipes from Asian
kitchens. What better way to test the claim than with an old friend
in need of some restorative food?
</P>
<P>
   We both fell in love with the book, which is much more than
prescriptions for healing broths infused with Chinese herbs
(although there are plenty of those recipes).
</P>
<P>
   ``A Spoonful of Ginger'' is a solid guide through a wide range
of generally simple-to-prepare Korean, Chinese and Japanese
recipes. A smart collection of lists and sidebars provides history,
philosophy and practical tips for using Asian ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Simonds, a Westerner who has studied Asian cooking for 25 years,
doesn't pretend to be an expert in medical cooking. Rather, she
presents health information in the form of reporting, using
herbalists, doctors and restaurateurs as experts.
</P>
<P>
   She promotes preventive eating based on the Eastern theory of
combining foods that are yin and yang _ that is, cooling or
heating. Health depends on finding a balance between the two, as
well as eating food that matches the season. Beef, for example, is
warming and good for winter dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Crab is considered a yin, or cooling, food and helps activate
blood circulation. Paired with ginger, as in Steamed Crabs with
Ginger Dipping Sauce, which I made one night, it is said to help a
person fight infections and regain strength. It's wonderfully
flavorful, too. That is part of the charm of Simonds' book. Unlike
many health-oriented cookbooks focusing on what  &LR; not  &LR; to eat, ``A
Spoonful of Ginger'' emphasizes what  &LR; to &LR;  eat.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Chinese approach to food as medicine centers on
soup, which Simonds says is second only to tea as a preferred way
of dispensing healing herbs and tonics. I'm sold on her
clear-steaming method. It produces an intense, clear broth without
leaving the soup's solid ingredients flavorless.
</P>
<P>
   For Clear-Steamed Chicken Soup with Ginger, I steamed the
ingredients for two hours in a dish sealed tightly with foil and
set over simmering water. I used one of her variations _
eliminating the salt and adding thin squares of prosciutto before
the two-hour steam bath and ripe cantaloupe balls at the end _ to
produce a wondrous dish with a floral perfume and a perfect balance
of sweet and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, we gave the book high marks for clean, sensible layout;
an extensive array of soups and congees (rice porridges); and a
list of tonics with ingredients spelled out in Chinese _ perfect
for taking to the local Chinese herbalist.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike many books on Chinese cooking, where the ingredient
list can be 30 items long and techniques complex, ``A Spoonful of
Ginger'' makes Asian cooking accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; One exception might be scallion pancakes. I made a stack to serve
with the soup. The recipe was labor-intensive, requiring three
sessions of technical kneading, rolling and resting and a long time
to fry each disk individually in hot corn oil.
</P>
<P>
   They were terrific, but I'm not sure I'd go through the effort
again _ unless a sick friend said they'd make her feel better.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``A Spoonful of Ginger,'' by Nina Simonds (Alfred A. Knopf, &LR; 
 &LR; 1999; 320 pages; $30). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CLEAR-STEAMED CHICKEN SOUP WITH GINGER
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken, about 3 to 31/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   6 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   13/4 cups rice wine, preferably Shaoxing wine
</P>
<P>
   10 whole scallions, ends trimmed and smashed lightly with the
flat side of a knife
</P>
<P>
   10 slices fresh ginger, the size of a quarter, smashed with the
flat side of a knife
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Instructions: Remove any fat from the cavity opening and around
neck of chicken. Rinse lightly and drain. Using a heavy knife or
cleaver, cut the chicken into 10 to 12 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 quarts water until boiling and blanch the chicken pieces
for a minute after the water boils to cleanse them. Drain the
chicken (discard the water), then rinse in cold water and drain
again.
</P>
<P>
   Place the chicken pieces and the rest of the ingredients, except
the salt, in a heat-proof pot or 2-quart souffle dish. Cover
tightly with heavy-duty aluminum foil and place on a steamer tray
or small rack.
</P>
<P>
   Fill a wok with enough water to just reach the bottom of the
steamer rack or tray; heat until boiling. Place the rack or tray
over the boiling water, cover and steam for 2 hours over high heat,
replacing boiling water in the wok as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, steam the soup in the oven: Preheat the oven to
425 degrees. Place the ingredients in a Dutch oven or casserole
with a lid and, before putting on the cover, wrap the top tightly
with heavy-duty aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pot in a lasagna pan or a casserole and fill with 11/2
inches of boiling water. Bake for 2 hours, replenishing the boiling
water as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Skim the top of the broth to remove fat and impurities. Add the
salt. Remove the ginger and scallions. Ladle the soup and chicken
pieces into serving bowls.
</P>
<P>
   To reheat and retain a clear broth, steam or bake in a closed
pot for 10 to 15 minutes, or until piping hot.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 215 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g protein, 2 g carbohydrate,
6 &LR;   &LR; g fat (2 g saturated), 75 mg cholesterol, 436 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
