<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-LAMB-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the
recipe  for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow 
 in optional trim.   SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Oberon's Lamb Never Gets Lost  
   
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Sometimes the best recipes also have the most
interesting stories. The lamb skewers from Oberon are based on a
family recipe given to owner Zoran Matulic by his mother, who lives
in the coastal town of Split in what is now Croatia.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This recipe has it all _ the lamb skewers are easy to put
together, are done ahead and are perfect for outdoor grilling.
</P>
<P>
   The ground lamb mixture is stirred together the day before and
allowed to rest. The chile-mint yogurt sauce can also be made ahead
to blend flavors or at the last minute, depending on the cook's
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time to serve, the host needs only to form the logs,
thread the skewers and quickly cook the meat. The combination of
sweet onions, scallions and garlic really helps to bring out a
sweet, intense flavor in the lamb.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the best dishes served at Oberon, which has
accents of Middle Eastern, French and Italian cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Matulic, the owner and host, had been the ``front man'' at many
of the city's best restaurants before going out on his own at
Oberon. He's a consummate host, and the restaurant has become
popular among those who want to have a comfortable, pampering place
for a quiet conversation. Prices are moderate, which helps make it
a prime neighborhood destination.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Oberon, 1450 Lombard St. (near Van Ness), San Francisco; (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 885-6555. Dinner nightly. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE SECRETS &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Sweating the onions.  &LR; This produces a more rounded sweet flavor
that brings out the sweetness of the lamb.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Overnight marinating.  &LR; Letting the ground mixture rest
overnight infuses flavor throughout the meat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fire and ice.  &LR; The combination of hot cayenne and cooling mint
in the yogurt dipping sauce lends a dramatic note to the entire
dish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LAMB SKEWERS WITH SPICY YOGURT DRESSING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups finely diced yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground lamb
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions (white part only), minced
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Spicy Yogurt Dressing (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The day before serving:  &LR; Heat the olive oil in a saute pan over
low heat. Add the onion and saute slowly until translucent. Drain
any excess oil.
</P>
<P>
   Break up the lamb into a bowl. Add the onion, scallions, garlic,
mint, salt and pepper. Mix well. Cover and refrigerate overnight.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, soak 16 six-inch wooden skewers in water.
(This helps prevent the skewers from burning on the grill.)
</P>
<P>
   Divide the lamb mixture into 16 equal pieces. Shape each piece
into a 1-inch-diameter log, approximately 3 inches long. Thread
each log lengthwise onto a skewer.
</P>
<P>
   Place the skewers on a hot grill and cook for about 5 minutes,
turning once, until the lamb is medium-rare.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with the yogurt dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 200 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 6 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 9 g fat (2 g saturated), 72 mg cholesterol, 74 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SPICY YOGURT DRESSING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Mix together all ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Serve at room temperature with the lamb skewers.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 9 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 0 g fat, 1 mg cholesterol, 10 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
