<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Borders to begin 'Sprout'ing books
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Sprout Inc. has landed a deal with
Borders Group Inc. to help the giant bookstore chain print
paperback books inside stores while customers wait.
</P>
<P>
   Sprout, a digital book wholesaler, was launched two years ago as
a high-tech middleman for obscure and out-of-print books. With
Sprout's on-demand publishing technology, retailers can print
high-quality paperbacks in single or multiple copies in about 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Borders, which bought a 20 percent interest in Sprout, will give
the fledgling wholesaler a major avenue of distribution for the new
technology. Borders, the nation's second-largest book chain, will
first test Sprout's technology at the retailer's distribution site
in LaVergne, Tenn. Next year, Borders will likely start printing
paperbacks in as many as 260 stores around the country. ``This is a
new technology in the industry, so we want to get comfortable with
it first,'' said Borders spokeswoman Ann Binkley. On-demand print
capability has been available for several years, but publishers and
retailers have been slow to react.
</P>
<P>
   Borders, which trails Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble in Web book
sales, sees the alliance with Sprout as a way to buffer Internet
competition by offering more in-store services, Binkley said.
Borders also plans to work with Sprout to expand the number of book
titles available on digital databases. Sprout currently has about
1,300 titles.
</P>
<P>
   For book retailers, on-demand printing cuts the costs of storing
and shipping, and it frees up shelf space occupied by slow-moving
titles. Store return about a third of their inventory to publishers
because the books don't sell. ``Our technology should help
eliminate the availability and returns problems that have plagued
this industry,'' said Pat Brannan, chief executive of Sprout.
</P>
<P>
   Sprout is looking to land similar pacts with other large chains
and independent booksellers. Sprout's printing setup, which
consists of digital printers and book binders, costs about $40,000
to buy, or about $1,000 a month to lease. Sprout also gets a
portion of the sale of each book printed by the retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
