<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, June 2. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-5 (Phoenix) - From the facts alone, it would seem
that Scott Falater was a very deliberate, very efficient murderer.
After stabbing his wife, Yarmila, 44 times in their Phoenix home in
1996, court records show, Falater put on gloves, dragged her body
to their pool, rolled her in and held her head under. He then
sealed a blood-splattered face guard, clothes and the knife in a
Tupperware container, stuffed it in a garbage bag and hid it in the
back of his Volvo. But Falater _ an engineer, inventor, loving
father and leader in his church _ said he cannot remember any of
it. Instead, he claims, he wasn't even awake. Day 5 of the trial.
By JERRY KAMMER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCHOOL-INDICTMENTS (Phoenix) - Criminal indictments were announced
Tuesday against nine current or former Arizona school district
officials on charges ranging from fraud and bid rigging to misusing
public funds and accepting kickbacks. By HAL MATTERN. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOYS RANCH (Phoenix) - The state of Arizona says Boys Ranch has met
its demands to improve operations and so grants the controversial
facility a license. The action comes about a year after the death
of a teenager at Boys Ranch and while a criminal case sparked by
the death continues. . By PAT FLANNERY. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
