correspondent ANNE STEPHENSON, Special to the Republic. Story moved
in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CARLEASING (Phoenix) - Hardly anybody walks into an auto showroom
these days without drawing up a budget and checking it twice. Cars
are so expensive that few consumers can buy one outright. That
means some kind of financing will be necessary, and monthly
payments will result. Yet car shoppers who focus too much on the
monthly outlays to the exclusion of other costs may live to regret
it. That's because a preoccupation with payments often leads car
shoppers to leasing, which frequently is more expensive than
buying, say consumer advocates. With material for three boxes. By
RUSS WILES. Story moved in the ``F'' and ``L'' categories. &QL; 
