<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-MOCA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN APPRAISAL: ART CENTER HAS ROOM FOR THE BIG AND THE NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(dal) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ADAMS, Mass. _ The Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary
Art, the sprawling complex that opened last weekend in the heart of
this old New England mill town, looks like a museum that the
Shakers might have built, if the Shakers had liked very large,
multimedia works of art and performance events poised on the
cutting edge of computer imaging technology.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, more than 10 years in the making, has a home so
plainly beautiful it barely needs art. Given the horrors that
regularly pass for museums in the late 20th century, this
represents a much better than average start, maybe even a miracle
that is undiminished by a few missteps in the opening shows and an
awkward just-moved-in sense of presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Carved out of five buildings in a 27-structure mill complex
dating from the 19th century, the arts center is the work of Henry
Moss and Simeon Bruner of Bruner/Cott &AMP; Associates of Cambridge,
Mass. Their redesign has created a series of linked spaces, large
and small, most of them elegant and serene in proportion and bathed
in natural light.
</P>
<P>
   Some galleries are distinguished by double-height ceilings;
others have been opened up by replacing columns with ingenious
systems of ceiling struts that look like they've been there all
along. And while new white walls were built in many places, plenty
of other walls were simply cleaned and patched, leaving layers of
plastering and distressed paint or mismatched brick patterns that
suggest abstract frescoes.
</P>
<P>
   As with Moss and Bruner's overall plan, these contrasting walls
express an exemplary balance of old and new, paying homage to the
building's history while enhancing its new incarnation.
</P>
<P>
   This incarnation was touch and go for most of a decade. The
brainchild of Thomas Krens while he was director of the Williams
College Museum of Art, the center, known as Mass MOCA, was made a
reality by Joseph Thompson, who took over when Krens left for the
directorship of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in 1988. It has
subsequently overcome many obstacles, with Thompson sometimes
working without salary and with only one other staff member. Last
fall the Dia Center for the Arts, which had been on the brink of
agreeing to lend large chunks of its collection, found its own
building, in Beacon, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps to be excused that after these challenges, the
center's opening slate of exhibitions and performance events is a
mixed bag in terms of quality. The largest exhibition, ``Test
Site,'' is freighted with less-than-inspiring works by big-name
artists, most of them borrowed from other institutions, especially
the Guggenheim, at the last minute. In galleries featuring works by
Carl Andre, Robert Morris, Bruce Nauman, John Chamberlain and James
Rosenquist, the art often feels much like furniture in a model
home, a stand-in for something real. In some cases this may reflect
first-time-out inexperience: several sculptures seem shoved into
spaces too small for them, most egregiously in the case of Dan
Flavin's fluorescent light works, forced to compete with muscular
ventilation ducts that obtrude from an uncharacteristically low
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the inaugural weekend was electric with a sense of
relief, delight and possibility. The good news is that, overall,
there are several instances where the center's stated mission is
shown to be worthy and attainable _ that is, to show large works of
art that other museums would have difficulty displaying and to
commission and otherwise foster works that mix disciplines and
media in new ways.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's ability to handle extra-large artworks, for
example, is confirmed by Robert Rauschenberg's ``\ Mile or 2
Furlong,'' a typically exuberant work of painting, sculpture,
collage and assemblage that involves 206 panels, takes up much of
the available wall space in a gallery nearly the size of a football
field and is the centerpiece of ``Test Site.''
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1981 and still in progress, this work has some ups and
downs of its own, but it looks quite a bit better here than it did
last year at the Ace Gallery in SoHo during Rauschenberg's
two-museum retrospective at the Guggenheim.
</P>
<P>
   It is in fact a retrospective in its own right, a spectacular
summation of Rauschenberg's involvement with found materials
(especially fabrics), his appetite for photographic imagery and the
myriad transfer techniques, often of his own invention, by which he
incorporates these images into his art.
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of the big-is-better approach is the display of
Joseph Beuys' ``Lightning With Stag in Its Glare,'' a handsome,
funereal sculptural installation centering on a 16-foot-high slab
of heavily worked bronze suspended by a noose from the ceiling. The
work belongs to the Philadelphia Museum of Art, which cannot
exhibit it until it raises the roof of one of its galleries and was
happy to lend it while it does so.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Generally things are more interesting when the displays edge
into new territory with younger or unknown artists. The museum's
intention to commission works of art is well represented by ``Tree
Logic,'' a Magritte-like installation piece by a young Australian
artist named Natalie Jeremijenko that consists of six good-size
saplings suspended upside down in the newly sodded and cobblestoned
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Another commission, Tony Oursler's installation ``Optics,''
feels a bit like a work in progress, but it shows this artist,
known for animating objects and dummies with little video images,
moving successfully away from his signature formula. This new work
involves several forms of video projection, glass sculptures and a
talking light bulb.
</P>
<P>
   It tackles the history of optics, reminds us that Lucifer means
light, and plays on the fact that the first lenses were used in the
13th century to view shadow plays _ often involving struggles
between angels and devils.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a small freestanding glass screen across which a
tiny naked figure magically slithers, crawls and shape-shifts, like
a soul trapped for eternity within the tendrils of a manuscript
illumination.
</P>
<P>
   Other technological feats include Bill T. Jones'
``Ghostcatching,'' which uses something called ``motion-capture
technology'' to transform the dancer's body into an astoundingly
fluid yet corporeal drawing in space that multiplies, divides and
moves through thickets of drawn line.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly impressive was ``Jet Lag,'' a performance
collaboration between the artists/architects Diller &AMP; Scofidio and
the Builders Association, which was founded five years ago by
Marianne Weems, a former member of New York's Wooster Group, which
had its American debut on Friday night. Performed in the center's
new black-box theater, the work told two true stories concerning
what I would call travel in extremis. In the process they combined
real actors and video images or computer-generated sets in ways
that often made the audience gasp.
</P>
<P>
   Most memorably, two actors stood on the stage while a huge
digital image created the illusion that they were on a moving
walkway in an airport. Luckily the drama, acting and staging
withstood such potentially sensational effects: the story was about
a Long Island grandmother who in 1969 kidnapped her grandson and
flew with him between New York and Paris more than 150 times in
seven months, never leaving the airport in either city, and finally
dying of jet lag.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious pros and cons to be gleaned from the museum's
maiden voyage. Like other new museums, it needs to be wary of
bigness for the sake of bigness. Large works of art can be like
blockbuster exhibitions: as with famous names like van Gogh or
Monet, scale can create the illusion of importance where little
exists. To devote the center's enormous spaces only to large works
of art would limit both Mass MOCA's program and its audience's
understanding of art.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting-edge technology, like size, can also be impressive for
its own sake. Luckily, after the building itself, the biggest cause
for celebration so far are the works of Oursler, Jones and Diller &AMP;
Scofidio. They prove that in the right hands, the latest
technological wizardry is just another viable artistic material.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
