<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8803 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLCAP-MARKETPLACE-     06-01 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLCAP-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SMALL-CAP STOCKS ON A TEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Small-cap stocks are on a tear, but can they make up all the
lost ground of the last few years?
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the strengthening economy, frenetic takeover activity
and hints of higher inflation that would make it easier for smaller
concerns to raise prices, small-company stock indexes have jumped
10 percent since April after lagging behind the larger companies
that fill the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index by the widest
margins in a generation. Small stocks even held up well the last
three weeks, while the broad market dropped about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many market strategists expect small-cap companies _ with market
values up to $1 billion to $2 billion _ to continue to outperform
the larger-company stocks that have fueled the stock market boom.
Despite their strong returns so far in the second quarter,
smaller-company stocks remain near their cheapest valuations in
memory, compared with other stocks. Not only could that give them
an extra boost if the stock market goes up, but, perhaps as
demonstrated this month, it could provide a cushion compared with
bigger-company stocks if the market falters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this could be the real thing for a while,'' said
Jeremy Siegel, professor of finance at the Wharton School at the
University of Pennsylvania. ``I am impressed with the relative
strength they've been showing over the last several weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But even small-cap fans are not sure these stocks will ever
approach the valuations they often achieved in the past, when they
occasionally traded at more than twice the price-to-earnings ratios
of bigger stocks.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, while small stocks used to be the only place many
investors put money allocated for higher-risk investments, nowadays
emerging markets, Internet stocks, options and other riskier bets
draw much of that money. Second, larger companies will benefit more
from continued economic globalization. And third, some say, the
generally inflationary era of the last few decades is not likely to
repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   T. Rowe Price's New Horizons fund has been a longtime barometer
for small-cap valuations. Until this year, the fund's
price-to-earnings ratio fluctuated between one and two times the
P/E of the S&AMP;P 500. But it fell to 0.78 at the end of March, the
lowest level in 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should get used to seeing smaller-company stocks trade
at lower relative valuations mostly because the rising prices of
goods and services that has paced small-stock performance since the
end of World War II will not be a big factor again, predicts James
Paulsen, chief investment officer at Wells Capital Management, the
investment-management arm of Wells Fargo &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to a new relative valuation range,'' he said.
``All of these historical relationships are going by the wayside.
Small-cap investors at least have to give some thought to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel agrees. ``I'm still not of the belief that they're going
to outperform big stocks'' over the long term, he said. ``The
globalization of the world economy is still going to be a major
theme in the next decade, and big-cap stocks are going to benefit
most from that scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of that will hurt small-cap stocks anytime soon,
given how much they have trailed the rest of the market. The
Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks had its worst year ever
against the S&AMP;P in 1998, lagging behind by 30.8 percent. And the
last two times the New Horizons fund's P/E relative to the S&AMP;P
dipped below one _ it hit 0.95 in March 1977 and September 1990 _
small stocks subsequently outperformed for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Further, predicts Mary Lisanti, a longtime small-cap fund
manager, smaller company stocks' earnings growth will eventually
overtake that of larger companies, causing their current valuation
discounts to narrow. ``There's no question they're cheap; everybody
knows that,'' said Ms. Lisanti, chief investment officer for
equities at Northstar Investment Management in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the best of times'' to be a small-cap investor,
she added. ``The risk is still relatively low, the fundamentals are
starting to improve, and no one is paying attention. You have a
window of opportunity here for a couple of months before everybody
gets excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Corporate insiders have noticed. ``We're seeing a higher level
of buying in small-cap stocks'' by executives of these companies,
said Bob Gabele, director of insider research at First Call/Thomson
Financial. ``Insiders play for value, and they're saying there's a
lot of value in these small-cap companies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most compelling evidence in support of a small-cap
renaissance may be what amounts to a wave of corporate arbitrage
that is washing over small stocks. Larger companies have been
acquiring small-cap companies this year at a furious pace.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch predicts the number of small-cap mergers and
acquisitions this year involving companies with market values of
under $2 billion will be the highest in a decade. Most notable is
the surge in leveraged-buyout activity, in which an investor group
acquires a company mostly with debt and uses its cash flow or asset
sales to repay the money. In fact, Merrill Lynch estimates there
will be as many small-cap leveraged buyouts in 1999 as in the
previous four years.
</P>
<P>
   Why so many deals? In large part because bigger companies have
been able to offer good-sized premiums to persuade small company
managements and shareholders to sell. At the same time, the bigger
players still are able to use the acquisitions to bolster their
per-share earnings immediately by paying for them with their own
more richly valued stock.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is even some irony here: Stocks are trading at their
loftiest levels since the heyday of the Nifty 50, the large growth
stocks that led the market's charge in the late 1960s and early
1970s, as many investors have abandoned the notion of Benjamin
Graham and David Dodd that stocks should be bought at prices that
reflect their underlying value. But by rapidly buying these small
companies on the cheap _ and using their own more expensive stock
to pay for it _ larger companies are taking advantage of the sort
of unusual price discrepancies that students of the famous
investing scholars love.
</P>
<P>
   The current activity amounts to ``a Graham-and-Dodd behavior
that we haven't seen in the market'' in some time, said Satya
Pradhuman, the director of small-cap research at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Preston Athey, manager of the T. Rowe Price Small-Cap Value
fund, said 18 out of about 210 companies in his fund have been
taken over in the last seven months.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has takeover activity been so high among small
companies, he said. ``This is new and different,'' Athey added.
``The disparity in valuations has become so large that the
economics of doing a deal are just overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   For mutual-fund investors, small-cap funds with strong
three-year returns through April 30 include Robertson Stephens
Emerging Growth A, with a 29.6 percent three-year annualized
return; Berger New Generation, 23.4 percent; Oppenheimer Enterprise
A, B and C shares, 23.2 percent, 22.3 percent and 22.3 percent,
respectively; Value Line Special Situations, 22.5 percent; Dreyfus
Emerging Leaders, 21.9 percent, and Baron Growth and Income, 19.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The funds are open to new investors, have at least $100 million
in net assets and require no more than a $5,000 initial purchase.
All data are from Morningstar Inc., the fund tracking company in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   One reason often cited for the difficulty small stocks may have
in the future is their lack of liquidity _ the ability to buy or
sell large blocks of stocks easily without affecting the price
through your own transaction. That could keep many large
institutional investors away. But that very effect has contributed
to small stocks' recent rally, says Jean-Marie Eveillard, the
Societe General fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   Since large stocks had been beating small stocks by such wide
margins until recently, pension funds, foundations and other large
money managers have had to buy huge blocks of smaller-company
stocks to bring their portfolio weightings back in line with their
targets, Eveillard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After four years of big stocks doing so much better, you
probably have entire portfolios that are almost 100 percent in
big-growth stocks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy for them to rebalance,'' he added, because
liquidity is with the big growth companies, not with smaller ones.
So when big portfolio managers do go into the market to buy smaller
companies, shareholders in those stocks get a significant pop.
</P>
<P>
   Eveillard predicts the valuation gap will continue to narrow,
though he is less certain how that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two ways the gap in valuations can close,'' he said.
``One is for small stocks to catch up; another way is for big
stocks to catch down. So far it has been more a matter of small
stocks catching up, but who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
