</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: Updates and adds four stories: KOSOVO-REFUGEES-WIESEL,
YUGO-GENERAL-KILLED, KOSOVO-MINING and KOSOVO-ALBANIA.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages of stories on Kosovo for
Wednesday, June 2.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ A look at the White House's current
thinking on a Kosovo timetable and the option of using ground
troops. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO military planners heard
Tuesday how many troops and tanks the allies and other countries
would provide for the beefed-up, 45,000-strong peacekeeping force
planned for Kosovo if diplomacy brings a settlement there. But
allied officials said Russia, a key diplomatic player, was keeping
its distance. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY (Berlin) _ Germany on Tuesday received a letter
from the Yugoslav government in which President Slobodan Milosevic
said he was ready to withdraw forces from Kosovo and accept a
``United Nations presence'' in the Serbian province. But Milosevic
also demanded an immediate end to NATO's 70-day-old bombardment if
a settlement is to be reached and made clear that significant
differences with the West remain. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Three weeks after Russia and the
world's seven richest nations agreed to set off on a joint quest
for peace in Yugoslavia, both Russia and its Western partners are
still at a loss to define Moscow's role in the process. By
Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES-WIESEL (Cegrane, Macedonia) _ Elie Wiesel, the
Nobel winner and Holocaust survivor, began a three day tour of
refugee camps Tuesday at the request of President Clinton.
Administration officials said the visit was designed to refocus
attention on the moral argument that they say lies behind NATO's
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana, Albania) _ NATO bombs strayed across the
Kosovo border Tuesday and hit the Albanian town that is the main
crossing point for refugees who are fleeing Kosovo. One refugee was
injured, though not seriously, in the attack just after he had
crossed the border, said officials who are monitoring the border.
By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MINING (Undated) _ A number of unofficial partition plans
for Kosovo have been discussed in the past few weeks and they all
raise the question of who gets control of the important mining
region in the province's northern section, around the city of
Mitrovica. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-GENERAL-KILLED (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ One of Yugoslavia's
top generals has been killed by NATO bombing, the first
high-ranking asualty of the air campaign, news reports here said.
(No byline.)
</P>
