<SLUG> BC-PRIZE-EDUCATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT WRITER WINS $43,000 PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maryland)  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTERTOWN, Md. Over a million students graduated from American
colleges this spring, but it is a safe bet that few enjoyed the day
more than Luke Owens.
</P>
<P>
   At the graduation ceremony of Washington College here on May 23,
Owens received the Sophie Kerr Prize, awarded each year to the best
writer in the senior class. With it came a tax-free cash grant of
$43,238.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised,'' said Owens, who had submitted a 27-page
poetry portfolio including poems like ``The Art of Lifting
Stones,'' which deftly linked muddy riverbeds to memories of his
father to man's relationship with God. ``Lots of people told me
that I deserved it, which is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens 21, of Rising Sun, in the northeastern corner of Maryland,
plans to use the money to pay off his student loans. He says he
will continue to write and perhaps go on to graduate school in
English.
</P>
<P>
   Every graduating senior is eligible for the prize, though only
14 students submitted entries this year. The reward is rich: Its
cash value is more than four times larger than the National Book
Award and eight times larger than the Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The Sophie Kerr Prize comes from a $500,000 trust fund given in
1965 to Washington College, a liberal arts institution with about
1,000 students, by Sophie Kerr, an Eastern Shore native and romance
novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Why she chose Washington College is not entirely clear. She grew
up on a farm 60 miles from the college and later attended nearby
Hood College, in Frederick, Md. Her affinity for Washington College
might have come from an honorary degree she received there in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   The Kerr will stipulates that half the annual earnings from her
estate must ``be awarded to the senior student at graduation who
shall have been chosen as having the best ability and promise for
future fulfillment in the field of literary endeavor.'' The other
half of the income subsidizes scholarships and visiting speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The selection committee is composed of English Department
faculty members and Washington College's president, John S. Toll.
The committee reads portfolios and then meets, usually for about
four hours, to choose a winner by secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling myself that if I didn't get it, I was not going
to cry at graduation,'' said Janet Ely, a senior from Towson, a
suburb north of Baltimore ``But I get sweaty palms thinking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other contenders take a more light-hearted approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of money, but people make such a big deal out of
it,'' said Ray Cummings of Owings Mills, northwest of Baltimore.
``I refuse to let myself get hung up on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee members say they understand how stressful the
selection process can be. And they acknowledge that the sheer
amount of prize money is worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be taken the wrong way: the odds are in my favor, the
gods are with me,'' said Robert Mooney, an English professor. ``But
no one is going to hit the jackpot on writing right away. My sense
is that maturity does prevail. This is not necessarily indicative
of the writing life.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the Sophie Kerr Prize will be worth an estimated
$55,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the department say the Sophie Kerr Fund helps improve
the writing program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps bring students to the college who are very serious
about literature,'' said Richard Gillin, chairman of the English
Department. ``We're very fortunate to have an awful lot of students
who are interested in writing. It has had a campus cultural
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Some student writers at Washington College are indeed serious
about their enterprise. The Literary House, a rambling old building
on the outskirts of campus, is a center of intellectual life for
them. The house is filled with sofas and comfortable chairs;
students convene there to critique one another's work and hold
poetry readings. The house cat, named Edith Wharton, wanders freely
and often curls up in the lap of a reading student.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the young writers dream of winning their school's top
prize even though it has inspired a superstition, the Sophie Kerr
Curse: No winner of the prize has yet become a great or even
notable writer.
</P>
<P>
   While the curse evokes eye-rolls and groans from members of the
English Department, it is alive and well in the minds of students.
</P>
<P>
   This year's winner, Owens, laughed when asked about the hex and
said, ``This is my chance to prove it wrong for the record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
