<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT OVERRULES CONVICTION OF DRUG KINGPIN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Chicago, San Francisco)   (dal) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court ruled on Tuesday that in order to
convict a drug kingpin of running a ``continuing criminal
enterprise,'' jurors must unanimously agree that the defendant
committed each of a series of individual drug offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-to-3 decision placed a new burden on federal prosecutors
to use precision in framing cases brought under one of the more
powerful laws in the federal anti-drug arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   The 1970 law imposes a minimum 20-year sentence for engaging in
a continuing criminal enterprise, defined as a ``continuing series
of violations'' of federal drug laws. The Justice Department, along
with most of the federal appeals courts, including the 7th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, in Chicago, in this case, took the view
that a jury need only agree that the prosecution had proven a
``series'' of crimes, without the need for all jurors to vote to
convict on the individual crimes that made up the series.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling Tuesday, the Supreme Court set aside the 1994
conviction of the leader of a Chicago drug gang, the Undertaker
Vice Lords. The defendant, Eddie Richardson, who received a life
sentence, was convicted of running a continuing criminal enterprise
through repeated sales of cocaine and heroin from 1984 through
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors had been instructed that they did not all have to
agree on the specific crimes that comprised the series _ a total of
at least three crimes, under the trial judge's instructions,
although the statute itself does not specify a number _ as long as
they did agree that there had been a series of them. Under this
view, the element of the offense that required a unanimous jury
verdict was the ``series.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority on Tuesday, Justice Stephen G. Breyer
said that the individual offenses were themselves elements of the
offense, at least three of which had to be proven beyond a
reasonable doubt to the satisfaction of a unanimous jury.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer said this interpretation both reflected the traditional
way of interpreting a criminal law, to require proof of each
element of the offense, and also guarded against ``the dangers of
unfairness'' that would result from permitting ``wide disagreement
among the jurors about just what the defendant did, or did not,
do.'' Noting that federal drug offenses include a wide range of
behavior, from the relatively trivial to the extremely serious,
Breyer said failure to require specificity from the jury would
raise constitutional problems.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy warned that
the ruling would be ``disruptive'' and would make convictions under
the statute ``remarkably more difficult.'' He said the ``whole
design and purpose of the statute'' was to attack a pattern, rather
than just a few individual crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In reply, Breyer countered that it should not be unduly
difficult for prosecutors to prove a few specific crimes among the
many that are typically involved in a criminal enterprise case. On
the other hand, he said, if it turns out to be difficult in a given
case, ``would that difficulty in proving individual specific
transactions not tend to cast doubt upon the existence of the
requisite `series'?''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, along with Justices John
Paul Stevens, Antonin Scalia, David H. Souter and Clarence Thomas,
joined the majority opinion in Richardson vs. U.S., No. 97-8629.
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Ruth Bader Ginsburg signed Justice
Kennedy's dissenting opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to its six opinions last week and five the week
before, the court issued only one opinion on Tuesday. The
early-June lull, so close to the end of the term, was due to the
fact that many difficult cases were argued in late April, with
first drafts of opinions in those cases only now beginning to
circulate among the justices.
</P>
<P>
   Among the court's other actions on Tuesday were these:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIA LIABILITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A week after ruling that the police violate the Constitution
when they permit reporters and photographers to accompany them into
a private home to witness a search or arrest, the court declined to
address the question of the news media's own liability for
participating in such ``ride-alongs.''
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the justices turned down an appeal by CNN from
a ruling by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in San
Francisco. In one of the cases the justices addressed last week,
the search by federal wildlife agents of a Montana ranch, the 9th
Circuit ruled last year that the network was effectively a joint
``government actor,'' sharing the agents' legal status and
liability.
</P>
<P>
   The justices' refusal to hear the network's appeal, CNN vs.
Berger, No. 97-1914, had little if any practical significance,
because the 9th Circuit was already obliged to reconsider the case
under the court's ruling last week. There are a number of factual
disputes to be resolved over what parts of the ranch were searched
and whether the owners consented to the agents' entry into their
home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COPYRIGHT DISPUTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Also without comment, the court refused to hear an appeal by the
West Publishing Co., a dominant presence in the field of legal
publishing, from a decision that it was not entitled to copyright
the system of page numbering that it uses, as well as some factual
information that it adds, to the judicial opinions it publishes.
</P>
<P>
   The opinions themselves, as public documents, may not be
copyrighted. West has fought a long battle to prevent electronic
competitors from undercutting its market by making its distinctive
arrangements of the opinions easy to cite without buying its
products.
</P>
<P>
   In two rulings last year, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
in New York, ruled against West and in favor of two CD-ROM
publishers. The appeals court based its rulings on a 1991 Supreme
Court case that rejected a copyright claim for arrangements of
facts, such as those in a telephone directory. The cases on Tuesday
were West Publishing vs. Matthew Bender &AMP; Co., No. 98-1500, and
West Publishing vs. HyperLaw Inc., No. 98-1519.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
