<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SIGN ONE DRAFTEE, LOSE ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins beat the midnight deadline for locking up
one of their draft picks Tuesday but failed to come to terms with
another.
</P>
<P>
   In the fold is defenseman Eric Van Acker, a 6-foot-5-inch,
220-pound blue liner from Baie Comeau of the Quebec League. Van
Acker, 20, was selected in the ninth round (No. 218 overall) in the
1997 draft. In 65 games this season, Van Acker had one goal and six
assists as well as 202 penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant general manager Mike O'Connell said Van Acker has work
to do to improve enough to play in the NHL. ``He has to work on his
agility,'' said O'Connell. ``He has good hockey sense and a great
attitude. Eric has shown improvement with his junior team since we
drafted him in 1997 and he has had the benefit of attending two of
our training camps (1997 and '98).''
</P>
<P>
   The defenseman the Bruins were unable to sign was 20-year-old
Jim Baxter, a 6-2, 186-pounder from Oshawa of the Ontario League.
Baxter was taken with the 180th pick (seventh round) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 66 regular-season games, Baxter had 22 goals and 74 points
before racking up 12 points, four of them goals, in 14 playoff
games. Baxter will go back into the entry draft, which is scheduled
for June 26 at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The situation with unsigned defenseman Ben Clymer is
significantly less clear. Clymer, who was taken by Boston in the
second round in 1997 (No. 27 overall), left the University of
Minnesota to play junior hockey for the Seattle Thunderbirds of the
Western Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   He is currently listed as a defected player. Because of a
loophole in the collective bargaining agreement, Clymer believes,
he should be declared a total free agent since he has been unable
to come to terms with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   The club, on the other hand, believes that it retains his
rights, so the conflict will go to arbitration.
</P>
</TEXT>
