<HEADLINE>
A HORSE NAMED BOB
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mounted patrol of the San Francisco Police Department will
hold a christening ceremony on June 9 in the Golden Gate Park
stables for a horse named Bob.
</P>
<P>
   The horse, bought for the patrol with the name Chip, is to be
renamed after  &UR; Bob Geary &LR; , the officer who in 1988 campaigned
against proposed city budget cuts that would have done away with
the mounted unit. The 86 percent vote for the city proposition to
keep the horses was the highest proportion of any vote before then.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the horses in the unit arrive with other names and are
renamed after legendary cops, the unit's  &UR; Laura Bianchi  &LR; said. The
unit presently includes horses named Tom, Jack and Bill, for cops
famous in the '40s and '50s, and Ernie, after the late  &UR; Ernie &LR; 
 &UR; Provost &LR; , the first African American officer in the mounted patrol.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted _ despite the Lone Ranger's ``Heigh-ho,
Silver'' _ that the equine Bob won't gallop into the Sunset
(Dd &LR; istrict) at the sound of his name. ``They don't respond to
their names,'' said Bianchi. ``They're not like dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BELGRADE BEASTS KNOW WHEN BOMBS ARE COMING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Animals in the Belgrade zoo, able to hear sounds that humans
can't, are providing their keepers with distant early warnings of
approaching bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo director  &UR; Vuk Bojovic &LR;  said the sound of the animals
screeching in response is ``one of the strangest and most
disturbing concerts you can hear anywhere. It builds up in
intensity as the planes approach ... and when the bombs start
falling it's like a choir of the insane: peacocks screaming, wolves
howling, dogs barking, chimpanzees rattling their  &LR; cages &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Michelle Pfeiffer  &LR; talked to the Times of London about the
difficulties of starring as Titania in ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream.'' ``My costume was like a moth's wing,'' she said,
``breathtaking but minimal. So my whole performance became about
keeping my ass covered.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The perils of gum disease? A recent survey conducted by Scope
mouthwash, reported in Wireless Flash, found that  &UR; Clint &LR; 
 &UR; Eastwood  &LR; and  &UR; Goldie Hawn  &LR; are the least kissable movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Wolfsonian Museum in Miami Beach is using some of a huge
settlement that Florida received from tobacco companies to pay for
an exhibition of matchbooks collected by  &UR; King Farouk &LR;  of Egypt in
the '30s, '40s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Dan Poppelreiter &LR; , just back from Rio, remarks on an
inventive use of technology: Ladies peddling their wares
(themselves) on the beach employ laser pointers to attract
customers by marking them with dots of light.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR;  is not pleased about plans to floodlight
Windsor Castle in celebration of the millennium next year, says the
New York Daily News. The lights will cost $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV Guide has named  &UR; Roy Rogers &LR; ' ``Happy Trails'' the best TV
theme song of all time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DECODING D.C. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ During a recent White House state dinner for the prime
minister of Japan,  &UR; Brooke Shearer &LR;  shocked etiquette sticklers by
picking up her cell phone, dialing and chattering away, says
Washingtonian magazine. Shearer, who is an adviser to the
Department of the Interior, wife of Deputy Secretary of State
 &UR; Strobe Talbott &LR;  and major friend of  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; , ignored her
seat mate, General  &UR; Henry Shelton &LR; , chair of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Outgoing Treasury Secretary  &UR; Robert Rubin &LR; , mobbed by
autograph-seekers after recent testimony at a House hearing,
refused requests to sign dollar bills, reports Roll Call. ``That's
defacing it,'' said Rubin, whose signature is already printed on
the currency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GLIDING THROUGH THE BOUTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The French department store Printemps has hired a team of
``Webcamers'' as high-tech personal shoppers, says W.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the cyber salespeople wears in-line skates and carries a
mini-computer and digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   A client calling from home, for example, wishes to check out the
store's selection of red dresses. The Webcamer skates over,
photographs the choices, then transmits the pictures to the home
shopper's computer. ``They'll even snap a photo of the yellow
blouse with the red pants to see if it matches,'' says W.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``If pets ruled the world, I have to believe that it would be in
better shape than it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Martin Goldstein, in his new book, ``The Nature of Animal
Healing'' (Knopf; $25) cq.
</P>
