<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-WOMEN-ART-     06-01 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF, SELES, SANCHEZ VICARIO HEAD TO SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Like clockwork, their sorority meets once a year, every
year, on the red clay of Paris in springtime. For the past decade,
Steffi Graf, Monica Seles, and Arantxa Sanchez Vicario have exerted
a virtual monopoly on the French Open. The older they get, the
nicer it is to slide along on the clay and let the surface do their
walking for them. All three deployed that skill in reaching the
semifinals on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Second-seeded Lindsay Davenport, the defending U.S. Open
champion but an unwilling slider here, paid most for her inhibition
when Graf pulled off the only upset of the quarterfinals, 6-1, 6-7
(5-7), 6-3. Graf, seeded sixth after missing the 1998 French Open
because of knee surgery, thus achieved her first Grand Slam
semifinal since she won at Flushing Meadows in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Also making his first Grand Slam semifinal since Flushing
Meadows in 1996 was Andre Agassi, the only American-born player
left in either singles. Agassi's surprising French Open run, which
continued on Tuesday with a 6-2, 6-2, 6-0 quarterfinal rout of
Marcelo Filippini, is even more surprising because sliding is not
part of his game and clay is not his best surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially on clay, experience obviously helps, and patience
at times,'' said Graf, a 16-year veteran whose 85 victories
represent a Roland Garros record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surface obviously has specialists, like Arantxa, like
Monica,'' said Graf, who modestly left herself off the list of
dirtball doyennes when referring to Sanchez Vicario and Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the top-ranked and precocious Martina Hingis, a
champion at all three other Grand Slam events when she was only 16,
has been able to crack this exclusive club in Paris. Only Croatia's
Iva Majoli, who captured the 1997 title and has not won anything
since, has had the temerity to join the triumvirate.
</P>
<P>
   But an injured Majoli did not play here this year, and on
Tuesday the usual threesome, along with the omnipresent Hingis,
moved into the semifinals to the surprise of nobody, Davenport
included.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the games I was winning were a struggle,'' said
Davenport, who claimed only four combined in the first and third
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport scraped through the second set's tiebreaker, but Graf
saved one set point by ripping a raucous forehand crosscourt but
succumbed to the backhand drive and forehand drop-shot combination
that Davenport invented on the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was getting some shots on clay that maybe on another
surface you can't get to; maybe because it's a little slower you
can slide to the ball,'' Davenport said. ``I don't move so great
anyways, and on clay it makes it even worse. It's slippery and I
don't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graf, Seles and Sanchez Vicario do like it, and have the
trophies to prove it. At 29, Graf is a five-time French Open
champion and eight-time finalist; Seles is a three-time champion
who fell in last year's finale to Sanchez Vicario, also a
three-time winner here.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, now 25, reached the semifinals for the seventh time
Tuesday following a 6-1, 6-4 demolition of Spain's Conchita
Martinez, whose 18 titles on clay qualified her for honorable
mention on Graf's list of surface specialists but did not help her
handle Seles' brute power.
</P>
<P>
   An out of shape and out of sorts Seles performed here last year
only three weeks after the death of her father-coach, Karolj. This
year's version is fitter and more inclined to be a fighter, a
quality Seles will need in her semifinal against Graf, who leads
their rivalry by 9-5. But Graf was the runner-up when Seles
collected her 1990 and 1992 French Open titles and lost, 7-5, 6-1,
in their most recent Grand Slam confrontation at the Australian
Open quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario, 27, loves Roland Garros so much she named her
Yorkshire Terrier after it. On Tuesday, she kept her title defense
on track with a 6-2, 6-4 victory against Austria's 34th-ranked
Silvia Plischke, playing in her first Grand Slam quarterfinal.
Sanchez Vicario, who had decided against wrist surgery at the end
of last year, pronounced herself an improved player with each
passing round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think I've always done very well here; I've won three
times,'' said Sanchez Vicario, whose claim on the 1999 championship
has been overlooked. ``There's something special when I come here,
even my game is getting better and better every day. Even when I'm
not doing so well, I raise to play my best tennis here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez Vicario figures to need her best tennis when she takes a
1-9 record against the aspiring champion, Hingis, in Thursday's
semifinals. Hingis carved up Barbara Schwartz, the 125th-ranked
Austrian qualifier, 6-2, 6-2. Schwartz had shocked fifth-seeded
Venus Williams in the Round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Williams, who confessed to underestimating and
underscouting Schwartz, Hingis did not merely research her
opponent's game, she assimilated it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best is just to get everything back and don't think where
it goes to,'' Hingis said. ``She had to have some part of a game
which is good, pretty dangerous, I think, into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the present, the 18-year-old Hingis had all the answers
to the 20-year-old Schwartz. ``I anticipated much better toward the
middle of the first set already, just made her a little bit nervous
because of that,'' Hingis said. ``I was there, maybe sometimes
unexpected. I almost didn't miss anything; I just made her play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus, she was there, but then somehow she probably lost her
mind,'' Hingis said about Williams, who blew a 6-2 one-set lead
against Schwartz. ``I think I played very clever today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
