<HEADER>
A8828 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-ELECTION-2TAK     06-01 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN A CHANGED SOUTH AFRICA, RACE IS STILL A FACTOR IN
ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Even on the eve of South Africa's
second post-apartheid elections, race was still a dominating
factor: Thabo Mbeki, who is virtually certain to become this
country's next president, on Tuesday put out an open letter not to
all South Africans, but to whites.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki, who is President Nelson Mandela's heir apparent, said in
the letter, printed in newspapers on Tuesday, that there are some
in the country who insist on issuing negative messages suggesting
that whites are an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is done to gain short-term political advantage without
regard to either the truth or the well-being of the white
population,'' he wrote, adding that whites should ``reject the
message of fear and despair'' peddled by opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   As South Africans go the polls Wednesday, they have much to
celebrate. In 1994, the year of the first all-race elections, the
fear of civil war hung in the air and violence crackled on the
ground. During the campaign season, whites hoarded canned goods and
ammunition, while blacks died by the thousands in bloody clashes.
</P>
<P>
   None of that is true today. Indeed, a mere five years later,
South Africans seem so adept at democracy that there has been a
kind of ho-humness to this campaign season. But race continues to
divide this society and despite all the campaigning, South Africans
of different races are expected to go their separate ways when they
step into the voting booth.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, who has had an unerring sense of the gesture that
could, at least for a few moments, bring out the patriotism in all
South Africans, will retire. But his African National Congress
party is expected to win easily, capturing the vast majority of
black votes and perhaps even two-thirds of the seats in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-old Mandela, who has often campaigned until he is
hoarse, remains beloved. But his departure is not unexpected, and
many South Africans are taking it in stride. They talk with
fondness of a hero who needs help climbing stairs now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is tired,'' said Rebecca Dlamini, 36, a nurse's aide from
Soweto. ``He should be allowed to go rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some South Africans even look forward to the leadership of
Mbeki, 56. He is seen here as a man who may crack the whip better
than Mandela did. Bookish, pipe-smoking and reserved, Mbeki does
not have Mandela's moral authority. But he is considered a shrewd
administrator: perhaps the man to tackle the country's most
persistent problems and, as he promises, to speed up change.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, the British-educated Mbeki has been
working on his image, often trading in his crisp suits for sport
shirts and plunging into crowds to shake hands. Polls indicate that
his popularity has risen about 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But polls also indicate that the ANC has not managed to attract
most of the white or mixed-race voters _ about 23 percent of the
population. Two white-led parties have been locked in a tight
battle for those voters, with both parties harping on the fears of
these groups that the country's black majority will ignore their
rights.
</P>
<P>
   One of the parties is the the National Party, which first
imposed apartheid on South Africa and has renamed itself the New
National Party. It is feeding whites' fears with posters referring
to the president of neighboring Zimbabwe, Robert Mugabe, who is
trying to expropriate land from white farmers without paying them
for it.
</P>
<P>
   The other largely white party, the Liberal Democratic Party, has
been even more forthright with its slogan, ``fight back.'' Its
leader, Tony Leon, regularly warns his audiences that a two-thirds
majority could mean a lifetime presidency for Mbeki or ``anything
else the ANC wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The country that Mbeki will inherit is already far different
than the one of which Mandela took charge. Under the leadership of
the ANC, the country has adopted a new constitution _ one of the
most liberal in the world. And it has passed more than 500 laws,
revamping a legal system that once did not allow blacks to vote and
contended that they needed only a rudimentary education.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a million new homes have been built since the
last election, and telephone and electric lines now crisscross even
squatter camps. Millions of people have been given access to clean
water, health care and school feeding programs.
</P>
<P>
   But problems still abound. The crime rates have soared. More
than 500,000 jobs have been lost as the country's once isolated and
protected economy has tried to compete on the global market.
Hoped-for foreign investment has not materialized. And the country
has one of the fastest-growing AIDS infection rates in the world.
Poor schools and corruption also remain issues.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the giddy feelings of triumph that accompanied
the country's first all-race elections have faded. And some South
Africans believe the country is more racially polarized than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys indicate that blacks and whites hold widely differing
views. Blacks are optimistic about the future. Whites are not _
though they still control the vast majority of the country's wealth
and have only a 4 percent unemployment rate, compared with nearly
40 percent for the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, blacks say joblessness is the country's
biggest problem. Whites say it is crime. The two groups even rate
leaders differently. Mandela is the most popular leader among
blacks. But Leon rates highest among whites.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As the campaign came to an end, Mbeki's letter was just one sign
of the divisions. The campaign's waning days were marked by bitter
exchanges by all the participants. As he closed the ANC campaign at
a rally in Soweto, Mbeki taunted the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the elections are over, the opposition parties will
continue to cry waa, waa, waa,'' Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Leon accused the state-owned television of
towing the ANC line. And the leader of the New National Party,
Martinus van Schalwyk, took Leon to task for being ``isolationist
and adverserial,'' and said he is trying to take a the same course
that whites took in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has not been totally absent from the campaign trail.
And in some parts of the country _ particularly in rural areas and
in squatter camps _ political freedom is still elusive. There have
been clashes between ANC supporters and members of two other
black-led parties _ the new United Democratic Party, headed by
Bantu Holomisa, and the ANC's chief rival in 1994, the Inkatha
Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been nothing that compares with the level of
violence that existed five years ago. Nevertheless more than 80,000
soldiers and police officers will be deployed to keep the peace on
Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the 1994 elections, each of South Africa's 22 million
voters could basically walk into a voting booth, present any kind
of document and vote. Some of the country's 15,000 polling places
are still just white plastic tents pitched on the side of the road
and furnished with cardboard stalls for privacy.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, voters will have to produce new bar-coded
identification documents if they want to vote, and hundreds of
computers will be collecting and counting the votes in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
   The euphoria of election day in 1994 is unlikely to be matched
Wednesday. But if voter registration is any indication, turnout
should be high. The country's election commission says that more
than 80 percent of the voting age population has registered. And
many blacks say the thrill of voting has not worn off yet.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when polls opened early for the elderly and the
infirm, Ernest Ndlamgisa, 71, who walks slowly and needs a cane,
was the first to make his mark at a voting booth in Thokoza, on the
outskirts of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's nice to vote,'' Ndlamgisa said. ``I like it. I still
want to vote next time too, if I'm still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
