</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BEST TEAM ON THE ROAD HAS THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Column will be updated after game) 
(jt) 
 By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In he hours leading up to the clash, the sounds
were not quite what they were in the wee hours before Agincourt,
when, as Shakespeare related, the warriors in the near-flung French
and English camps saw each others' campfires, and listened as
``steed threatens steed'' and the ``armorers'' prepared the knights
``with busy hammers.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before and the morning before Game 2 in the Eastern
Conference finals between the Knicks and the Pacers Tuesday night
in Market Square Arena here, the sounds were the thump of a
basketball in practice, the squeak of sneakers and talk of
expectations, executions (in running their plays, that is) and
possible exaltations.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing how the Knicks had vanquished the favored and home-team
Pacers in the first game of the four-of-seven-game series, Mark
Jackson, the former Knick point guard and the current Pacer point
guard, was asked if his team felt a sense of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same desperation as Game 1,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but an observer might nod and wonder, ``but only more
so?''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, all games in the playoffs are significant _ players
know that no matter how far ahead or how far behind a team is in a
series, there is always the chance for a reversal of fortune. But
staring the Pacers in their collective, determined faces was the
distinct and rather ugly possibility that if they lost again
Tuesday night they would go into Madison Square Garden to resume
the series, down two games to zero, and play the next two games
before that wild and crazy Gotham crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same kind of crowd from which the rather cloistered
chess champ, Bobby Fischer, taken years ago to a basketball game at
the Garden for the first time and seated in the first row, heard
the thunderous roar of the crowd, turned and looked wide-eyed over
his shoulder, and asked his companion, ``Are they dangerous?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not physically _ it wasn't a hockey crowd, after all _ but
possibly psychically.
</P>
<P>
   Of course an athlete must feel loose and confident if he is to
perform at his apex. And Larry Bird, the Pacers' head coach, and a
former player of some note, understands this fully. He acknowledged
that the Pacers would have to get back quicker on defense to stop
the Knick fast break, that Rik Smits his 7-foot-4-inch center had
to be more aggressive on offense and perhaps a little less
aggressive on defense _ no silly fouls! And he said, too, that his
estimable star sub, Jalen Rose, couldn't take his Knick
counterpart, Latrell Sprewell, as a personal insult, but must
remain in the flow of the team game, and he acknowledged that it
was important for Jackson to not only post-up effectively against
the likes of Chris Childs, but to make those jump hooks from four
feet out that he rolled off the rim in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that and more, Bird also laid the underpinnings for a
potential loss in Game 2. ``We're a good road team,'' he said.
``We've had success this season on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. And the success included no road losses to Milwaukee and
Philadelphia, since the Pacers swept the Bucks and 76ers in the
first two rounds of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It is also true that Jackson, having played for the Knicks for
five seasons, starting in 1987, is hardly a stranger to the Garden,
nor are Chris Mullin or Sam Perkins, both of whom, like Jackson,
are from New York City. And when Jackson was asked about a New York
tabloid headline that called this series the ``Knicks versus
Hicks,'' he said he found it curious. ``We have three guys from New
York City,'' he said, ``I don't know where the Knick guys are from,
but I'd bet none of them have ever been to downtown Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing is from Jamaica (not Queens) and Boston; Allan
Houston is from Louisville; Larry Johnson is from Tyler, Texas;
Sprewell is from Milwaukee; Childs is from Bakersfield, Calif., and
Charlie Ward is from Tallahassee. Only Marcus Camby and Chris
Dudley are even neighbors, from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   And to Reggie Miller, the Great Knick Villain, the Garden is
like a second home. Tensions with the Knicks are generally a happy
sop to him _ though his 3-point shot with his team down by a point
with 12 seconds to go in Game 1 ended by the ball hitting the front
rim. But it is only too quickly remembered by Knick fans how he
burned them for 39 points in Game 5 of the 1994 conference finals,
his 8 points in the final 8.9 seconds to co-opt Game 1 of the 1995
second-round series and his 3-pointer in last year's second-round
series, which necessitated an overtime, in which the Pacers
triumphed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought Knicks-Pacers would be a war,'' Rose said.
``And now we have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, to paraphrase Jackson, same ol', same ol' desperation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
