u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      06-01 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISNEROS LAWYER QUESTIONS GOVERNMENT'S KEY WITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lawyer for former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros said Tuesday he would attack the credibility of the woman
who has agreed to be the government's star witness when Cisneros
goes on trial for an alleged conspiracy to conceal payments he made
to her following their affair.
</P>
<P>
   And lawyer Barry Simon said the defense opposes the government's
use of tape-recorded telephone conversations that Linda Jones,
known by her married name Linda Medlar, had with Cisneros before
and after he was confirmed as the secretary of Housing and Urban
Development in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has admitted the tapes were altered,'' Simon told U.S.
District Judge Stanley Sporkin during a hearing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackowski, a prosecutor working with Independent Counsel
David Barrett, said the government would use the tapes to show
Jones, Cisneros and two of his aides, John Rosales and Sylvia Arce,
conspired to conceal $250,000 in payments Cisneros made to Jones
after their publicly acknowledged affair.
</P>
<P>
   Jackowski said Jones' testimony will make it easier for the
government to get the tapes admitted as evidence and would reduce
the expected length of the trial from eight to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The four defendants were named in a 21-count federal indictment
in December 1997 alleging conspiracy and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin, who has grown restless with delays in the case, has a
trial date of July 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Folks, we have to get this thing going,'' Sporkin said. ``It's
been so long now, I really don't understand why this case cannot be
tried like any other case.''
</P>
<P>
   He ruled last year that the independent counsel had the right to
bring Cisneros to trial on charges that he lied to the FBI about
payments to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court upheld that ruling this year, paving the
way for the trial to resume in Sporkin's court. Although Cisneros
can seek a review by the Supreme Court, his lawyers said he would
not ask for an emergency stay that would further delay the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are anxious for this case to come to trial,'' said Barrett,
who has spent more than $7 million investigating the affair of
Cisneros, a former mayor of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, of Lubbock, Texas, is serving time in a federal prison
for bank fraud, money laundering and obstruction of justice.
Prosecutors have offered a reduced prison sentence for Jones in
exchange for cooperation in the case against Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda Medlar has agreed to testify on behalf of the United
States,'' Jackowski told the court.
</P>
<P>
   That set off legal bantering between prosecutors and Simon, who
recounted how Jones was first offered immunity, then indicted after
prosecutors discovered the tapes she had submitted were not the
originals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, Mrs. Medlar's second round of cooperation
complicates the hearing tremendously,'' Simon argued.
</P>
<P>
   Simon pledged to challenge the legality of the tapes under
wiretapping statutes and the authenticity of the recordings in
light of Jones' admission they were altered.
</P>
<P>
   Jackowski countered that Jones ``edited out very few of these
tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosales and Arce have declined government offers to testify
against Cisneros, according to a source close to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who was HUD secretary from 1993 to 1996, is president
of the Spanish-language television network Univision in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI says Cisneros told investigators he had paid Jones about
$60,000 before he was nominated for the HUD position. The
indictment charges Cisneros paid her $250,000, including $73,000
after he took office on Jan. 21, 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
