<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8835 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI &LR;      06-01 0315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPOT-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Wednesday, June
2, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-CANADA (Seattle) _ The decline and threat of extinction
facing salmon runs along the coast of British Columbia,
particularly in fast-growing areas, has come to mirror that of the
Pacific Northwest, a conference on Pacific fish habitat heard
Tuesday. While millions of sockeye salmon still swim far up the
Fraser River, other runs are rapidly declining as Canada's last
frontier is paved, subdivided, logged and farmed.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (Seattle) _ Two years after being taken back by China,
Hong Kong is doing better politically and worse economically than
was expected in 1997, according to a delegation visiting Seattle.
Four Hong Kong spokesmen, two associated with the Hong Kong
government and two from the opposition Democratic Party, addressed
the Asia Society in Seattle on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (Story will move in the ``i'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   COLUMN-RAMSEY (Undated) _ Bill Bryant knew he would face some
critics, but he hadn't expected this. Invited to a forum at Seattle
University last week to speak in favor of the World Trade
Organization, he found himself the only one of five panelists
clearly defending it, and with the audience clearly against him.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle hosts the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-THIEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ The umpire who used instant replay
was right, despite what AL president Gene Budig says.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
