<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-HOME-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2ND-QUARTER SHORTFALL FOR AMERICAN HOME PRODUCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Home Products, the drug maker that has been prone to
public calamities over the last several years, found itself in
another one Tuesday when it announced that its earnings for the
second quarter would be 20.5 percent less than expected because of
weak demand for its agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the pharmaceutical company, the world's
seventh-largest, caught most analysts and investors by surprise and
was the latest entry in a growing list of troubles. The company had
two failed mega-mergers last year and withdrew several of its drugs
from the market because of health concerns, notably the diet drug
fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   The second-quarter shortfall is expected to cut 11 cents a
diluted share, or 5.8 percent, from the company's estimated annual
income of $1.89 a share. With the revision, earnings at American
Home Products will most likely decline in the second quarter and
for the year, giving the company one of the worst performances in
the industry. Most large pharmaceutical companies have routinely
posted quarterly earnings gains of 12 percent or more, with some,
like Warner-Lambert, posting gains well above 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The news sent investors fleeing. The company's shares dropped
$5.625, or 9.7 percent, to $52. The setback erased the stock's 2
percent gain for the year, one of the industry's best, leaving it
with a negative return of 7.76 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts had long known that the company's agricultural
division was a lackluster performer, most were surprised by the
severity of the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bomb,'' Jack Lamberton, a managing director of HSBC
Securities, said of the announcement. ``American Home Products was
slow to recognize the threat of biotechnology in the agricultural
sector. They may have been trying to correct that last year with
their failed attempt'' to merge with Monsanto.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products, based in Madison, N.J., attributed the
declines in its agricultural sector to reduced demand for grain in
the United States and the company's international markets. The
company's agricultural division, which includes brand-name
herbicides Arsenal and Prowl, had pretax income last year of $494.9
million and sales of $2.19 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday that all agricultural companies had
suffered from declines in grain demand but that American Home
Products might have been especially hurt by price competition from
Monsanto. By reducing its prices on its popular Roundup herbicides,
Monsanto appeared to have lured sales away from the American Home
Products brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the past year, there has been a lot of repositioning in
the agricultural industry,'' said Tom Brakel, an analyst at Mehta
Partners, a biopharmaceutical research firm. ``American Home
Products didn't have an aggressive strategy like Monsanto or Du
Pont. Sales at American Home's agricultural business could be down
40 percent by the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted Tuesday that American Home's misfortunes with its
agricultural products might be a mixed blessed. Company executives
appear eager to sell it, a move that analysts applaud. American
Home's pharmaceutical division, which accounted for 66 percent of
the company's $13 billion in sales last year, has performed quite
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never liked the company being in agribusiness anyway,'' said
David Saks, a managing director at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``This may be the
straw that breaks the company from expanding it. Now we may see
some kind of deal on the pharmaceutical end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
