</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE INJURED IN NATO BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(dal) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ NATO bombs strayed across the Kosovo border on
Tuesday and hit the Albanian town that is the main crossing point
for refugees fleeing Kosovo. One refugee was injured, though not
seriously, in the attack just after he had crossed the border, said
officials monitoring the border.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesmen said that the bombing was a mistake, although one
NATO official said the bombs were deliberately dropped.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the second day in a row of heavy bombing in southern
Kosovo, and despite the nearness of the explosions, 50 ethnic
Albanian refugees crossed the border into Morini. On Monday, the
bombs also fell within several hundred yards of refugees on the
move, raising fears that additional refugees could be injured or
possibly killed in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it's a major source of concern,'' said Andrea
Angeli, a spokesman for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, which monitors regional military activity.
``But at the same time, we know there is increased military
activity of NATO in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, Serbian forces stepped up their attacks on Albanian
border villages, shelling Morini, the town that NATO bombed. The
shelling damaged concrete border bunkers, but no one was hurt,
Angeli said.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian mortars, apparently for the first time in the conflict,
also hit an Albanian military position on this side of the border,
Angeli said. Until now, Serbian attacks into Albania over several
months had largely focused on areas where the Kosovo Liberation
Army rebels are reportedly based. ``What happened last night is
certainly an escalation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Angeli said seven bombs fell in the early afternoon, scattered
from 500 yards to within two miles of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Angeli said that a refugee, 30, whom the Serbian police had held
in prison, was hit by shrapnel but not seriously injured. The man,
also suffering from shock, was treated at an Italian refugee camp
near Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Serbian forces continued shelling small border
villages used by the KLA as transit areas into Kosovo, destroying a
crossing in Pogaj. For the first time, four shells fell into the
largest town in the area, Krume. Two exploded, setting off panic,
but no one was injured, Angeli said.
</P>
</TEXT>
