<P>
   (NYT2) VOZROZHDENIYE ISLAND, Uzbekistan -- June 1, 1999 --
ANTHRAX-ISLAND-1, 6-1 -- An abandoned laboratory, left, and animal
houses, right, on this remote island in the heart of the inland
Aral Sea which was used by Russian scientists working on
experiments involving anthrax. In 1988, Russian soldiers dug huge
pits and poured sludge containing anthrax into the ground here,
burying not only the germs but, Moscow hoped, a grave political
threat. Today the island is the world's largest anthrax burial
ground. (Judith Miller/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) VOZROZHDENIYE ISLAND, Uzbekistan -- June 1, 1999 --
ANTHRAX-ISLAND-2, 6-1 -- Cages which housed animals used in anthrax
experiments, at an abandoned facility on this remote island in the
heart of the inland Aral Sea. In 1988, Russian soldiers dug huge
pits and poured sludge containing anthrax into the ground on the
island, burying not only the germs but, Moscow hoped, a grave
political threat. Today the island is the world's largest anthrax
burial ground. (Judith Miller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) VOZROZHDENIYE ISLAND, Uzbekistan -- June 1, 1999 --
ANTHRAX-ISLAND-3, 6-1 -- Two men walk through an abandoned Soviet
facility used for experiments with anthrax on a remote island in
the heart of the inland Aral Sea. In 1988, Russian soldiers dug
huge pits and poured sludge containing anthrax into the ground in
what today is the world's largest anthrax burial ground. (Judith
Miller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
