<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA HINTS AT ACCEPTING ALLIANCE DEMANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Raising hopes for a diplomatic end to the crisis in
Kosovo, a war-weary Yugoslavia said Tuesday it would accept the
general conditions of the Group of Eight nations' demands for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Balkans negotiator Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish
President Martii Ahtisaari were expected to head to Belgrade
Wednesday for what could be make-or-break talks with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   At a separate meeting in Brussels, military officials from more
than 30 nations met to draft plans for an international security
force in Kosovo that would ensure that ethnic Albanians can return
to their homes safely.
</P>
<P>
   The group meeting at NATO's military headquarters, representing
19 NATO nations and 12 partner countries, will help create a force
of 50,000, nearly double the number originally envisioned more than
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, meanwhile, awaits word Wednesday on a legal attempt
to stop the bombing. A United Nations court is expected to decide
whether the NATO bombing is illegal and should be halted
immediately, as Yugoslavia claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing decisive days'' that could determine an
``escalation'' of the war or a genuine move toward peace, German
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said Tuesday, as Chernomyrdin and
Ahtisaari met in Bonn with their US colleague, Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting Wednesday marks the fifth time Chernomyrdin has met
with Milosevic since NATO began bombing March 24, but it would be
the first time someone from the military alliance accompanied him.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's foreign minister, Zivadin Jovanovic, Tuesday sent a
letter to Fischer reiterating that Yugoslavia was ready to accept
the five principles laid out by the G-8. The G-8 consists of seven
industrialized nations plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions are that Yugoslav troops pull out of Kosovo, that
the fighting and repression in the province stop, that the hundreds
of thousands of refugees driven from Kosovo be allowed to return,
and that Milosevic allow an interim political administration of
Kosovo and an international peacekeeping force there.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials toned down their usual defiance of NATO and
emphasized their willingness to reach a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia has accepted G-8 principles including a United
Nations presence, mandate, and other elements to be decided by a UN
Security Council resolution in accordance with the United Nations
charter,'' Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, one Yugoslav cabinet minister, Goran Matic, was
optimistic that a deal could be done, but warned that the United
States and Britain might want to block a deal so the bombing could
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the acceptance of G-8 principles was the endgame,
Matic replied, ``I hope so. I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain why, he said, ``Let's wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Matic was uncharacteristically conciliatory, saying: ``We are
ready to accept a peaceful solution based on the G-8 peace plan.
This is our basic principle.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Italy responded cautiously to Belgrade's
tentative olive branch, saying that Milosevic must meet NATO's
demands if he wants NATO to stop bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Western allies also are suspicious of Milosevic, who is
notorious for a negotiating tactic of bringing a crisis to the
brink, making a concession, then taking advantage of the breathing
room to escalate the crisis again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need evidence. We can't abide only by a general acceptance
of principles,'' said Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, in
Washington to meet with US Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright. ``Milosevic has shown time and time again'' that he
``wants to leave an opening, step forward, and then step back,''
Dini said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no time for tricks,'' Dini said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari said it was unclear whether Belgrade was willing to
accept the peace plan outlined by the G-8 principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clarity has to be sought from the Yugoslav end,'' he said
Tuesday night during a break with his talks with Chernomyrdin and
Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main sticking points _ a dispute that goes back to
the failed peace talks in France early this year _ is the makeup of
the peacekeeping force. The alliance is insisting that the troops
be NATO-led.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, apparently uncomfortable with the idea of being
monitored by armed troops from the nations that have been bombing
Yugoslavia for more than two months, wants an international force
that excludes certain nations.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Yugoslav news organization Beta,
Yugoslav General Nebojsa Pavkovic said troops from the NATO
countries leading the bombing, the United States, Britain, France,
and Germany, would not be acceptable inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The G-8 principles do not specify the makeup of the peacekeeping
troops. Nor do they stipulate whether any Yugoslav troops could
stay in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, anxious that the long-separatist ethnic Albanians
will take Kosovo away, does not want to pull all of its troops out.
Western allies worry that if Serb troops stay, many ethnic Albanian
refugees will be afraid to come back, and Milosevic might renew
trouble in the province.
</P>
<P>
   As diplomats pushed ahead with their mission, NATO conducted its
own, hammering Yugoslavia with bombs. In Kosovo, American
``Warthog'' attack planes hit Serbian forces who were fighting
Kosovo Liberation Army rebels along the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30 p.m. Tuesday, NATO was bombing in and around Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Matic had predicted as much, saying that NATO always steps up
its bombing right after Chernomyrdin meets with Milosevic, or
whenever there is progress toward a political solution. ``We have a
saying in Belgrade: `Watch out, Chernomyrdin is coming,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes also apparently hit four defensive bunkers on the
Albanian sideby mistake, according to an Albanian military officer.
NATO has not confirmed that account.
</P>
<P>
   The hills and shoreline of Albania are peppered with as many as
700,000 of the concrete, dome-shaped ``pillbox'' bunkers, a vestige
of the rule of Cold War Albanian dictator Enver Hoxha.
</P>
<P>
   Hoxha built the bunkers and provided Albania with a heavy
arsenal of small weaponry, insisting to his people that they were
under threat of an assault from the West. Most of the guns were
looted by Albanian rebels during riots two years ago, and some of
these weapons have been sold to ethnic Albanian fighters in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said NATO will not compromise
on its demands for a peacekeeping force. ``There must be a command
and control structure that is NATO's in charge of any peacekeeping
operation,'' Cohen told reporters after making a speech to a
suburban Washington high school.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also reiterated that NATO would not pause the bombing in
the face of diplomatic progress. Belgrade has insisted that bombing
must stop before there is a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pause would only serve Milosevic's interests,'' Cohen said.
``He is seeking to try to divide the alliance. He is seeking delay.
We are now at the point where the air campaign is being intensified
on a 24-hour basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
