<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS APPEAR PREDESTINED TO CLAIM WEST TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ None of the players and coaches involved wants to
admit it, but there is a sense of predestination looming over the
Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs, the fortunate team, will not acknowledge
what appears to be their fate because they want to avoid a letdown
this weekend on the road. And the Portland Trail Blazers, the
undone ones, refuse to give credence to the theory because the
seemingly inevitable is not in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   But as the clubs exited the Alamodome floor after the Spurs'
dramatic 86-85 victory on Monday night, the thought had to cross
their minds and linger.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain the off-balanced, game-winning 3-pointer by
Sean Elliott that gave the Spurs their first lead with nine seconds
remaining? The slender forward has been known as an anticlutch
player throughout his 10-year career.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain San Antonio's five victories in six meetings
this season with Portland, all of which were decided in the final
minute? How else to explain the Blazers' ability to play wisely
down the stretch against the seasoned Utah Jazz but make error
after error in the waning moments against the Spurs?
</P>
<P>
   Damon Stoudamire, the Portland point guard who missed an
opportunity to give the Blazers a 3-point lead by missing 1 of 2
free throws only three seconds before Elliott's miracle shot,
seemed to sense that his team was doomed when he spoke
exasperatedly about its ineffectiveness against the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just so sick and tired of losing to this team,''
Stoudamire said. ``They are a real thorn in our side.''
</P>
<P>
   A thorn that is halfway toward becoming a fatal injury. With
Game 3 scheduled for Friday night at Portland's Rose Garden, the
Spurs hold a two-games-to-none lead despite having failed to
dominate the Blazers in either of the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was the Blazers who controlled much of Monday's
game. Playing efficiently on both ends of the floor, the Blazers
led by 14 points at halftime and by 18 early in the third quarter.
Never in the two teams' five previous games had they been separated
by such a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Spurs made their charges, the Trail Blazers seemed
prepared. After a 14-0 run pulled the Spurs within 3 points midway
through the third quarter, the Blazers pushed the lead back to 9
points early in the fourth. Later in the quarter, the Blazers did
it again, increasing a 1-point advantage with five minutes
remaining to 8 points three minutes later. With one minute left,
the Blazers' lead stood at a comfortable 6 points, making a victory
for the Spurs seem impossible.
</P>
<P>
   That is when unusual things started to happen, and the Blazers
lost their poise. Stoudamire committed his seventh turnover and
Elliott made him pay with a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' Rasheed Wallace made a weak pass attempt that ended
up in the hands of David Robinson, which led to two free throws by
Mario Elie for the Spurs. Then, after Stoudamire split his pair of
free throws, Stacey Augmon decided against playing it safe and
gambled for a steal of Elie's inbounds pass to Elliott, giving
Elliott just enough space to get off his wondrous 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   When two jump shots by the Blazers' Jimmy Jackson and Walt
Williams fell short of the basket on the final possession, Portland
felt the sting of losing the second straight game it could have
won. With seven seconds left in Game 1, Wallace missed an open
20-footer that could have tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Rider, the Blazers' shooting guard who missed the last 17
minutes of the game with a sore knee, was succinct in describing
the difference between the Spurs and the Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We choked,'' Rider said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the late collapse, Mike Dunleavy, the Blazers' coach,
found little fault with his team. He instead described the outcome
as something that was almost unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the way we played,'' Dunleavy said. ``It took
an incredible shot to beat us. I'm not down about this. I told the
guys you have nothing to hang your head about. This is progress.
It's getting harder and harder for this team to beat us here.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Spurs continue to do so, even when it seems they should
not win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portland deserved to win,'' Elie said, ``but we didn't quit.
That's the sign of a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is also the sign of destiny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
