<HEADER>
A8858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-BOTHA-BOS &LR;      06-01 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BOTHA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT OVERTURNS BOTHA CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Apartheid's last hard-line president, P.W. Botha,
Tuesday won his long legal battle with the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission, the panel charged with investigating South Africa's
violent past.
</P>
<P>
   Botha appealed against a lower court conviction handed down last
August for defying a summons to appear before the panel, and his
sentence, a $1,600 fine and 12 months in jail, suspended for three
years, was set aside. The commission sought to question the former
president about his role in state-sanctioned human-rights. Botha
called the panel a witchhunt and a ``circus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is mindful of the fact that there will be many who
may consider that (the appeal ruling) is unjust,'' wrote Cape High
Court Judge Selwyn Selikowitz in his decision. Selikowitz made up
his mind on the basis of a technicality. ``This court is duty-bound
to uphold and protect the Constitution and administer justice to
all persons alike without fear, favor, or prejudice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, handed down on the eve of South Africa's second
all-race elections, is a potential setback in the country's attempt
to reestablish the rule of law after decades of racist brutality.
</P>
<P>
   The Truth and Reconciliation Commission was predicated on a
simple but unprecedented trade-off: perpetrators of human-rights
abuses could gain amnesty in exchange for full disclosure of acts
of politically motivated violence. Those who refused to appear
before the panel or failed to meet its criteria faced possible
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   But that deal has been undermined in recent months. The ruling
African National Congress tried to block the commission's final
report last October on grounds that human-rights violations
committed in the course of the struggle for liberation should not
be weighed on the same scale as those committed by the apartheid
state. The report held the ANC accountable for its actions. The bid
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the ANC floated a proposal to amend the law
establishing the commission to include group as well as individual
amnesty. At the same time, the office of the national director of
public prosecutions has indicated that it will probably pursue
cases only against past perpetrators of murder.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility now exists that, after a long trial and
conviction for refusing to acknowledge the legitimacy of the
commission, Botha may never be brought to account, even though
senior generals from his security structures have testified under
oath before the commission that the former president gave the
command for a number of criminal acts, including the 1986 bombing
of the headquarters of the South African Council of Churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a blow at a symbolic level,'' said Brandon Hamber, an
analyst of the commission at the Center for the Study on Violence
and Reconciliation in Johannesburg. ``We are now confronted with a
case where a prominent figure could walk away scot-free'' without
facing legal scrutiny for past actions before either the commission
or a court.
</P>
<P>
   Selikowitz found that the commission issued its subpoena against
Botha five days after the commission's mandate had expired.
Parliament subsequently passed a law extending the commission's
life span, but at the time it issued its summons against the former
president, the commission did not technically have the authority to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutor Bruce Morrison, acting on behalf of the
commission, has not decided whether to take the case to the
Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, 83, ruled from 1978 to 1989 with escalating brutality,
but was edged out after a suffering a stroke by F.W. De Klerk, who
instituted sweeping reforms in 1990 leading to the demise of
apartheid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
