<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-PULLOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI-ALLIED ARMY STEPS UP WITHDRAWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAFAR FALOUS, Lebanon _ As Israel's proxy army continued its
retreat Tuesday from a strategic position just north of the
Israeli-occupied zone, Hezbollah guerrillas showed they would not
lessen their resistance to the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah claimed responsibility for two road-side bombs that
killed two members of the retreating SLA and wounded one. The SLA
is a small Lebanese militia that Israel pays to help defend the
9-mile wide self-proclaimed security zone it occupies in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The roadside attacks, the trademark of Hezbollah in a war of
attrition that it appears to be winning, followed the SLA's
pullback from outposts of Jezzine that they had held for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas also reportedly opened fire on an SLA convoy of
old tanks and personnel carriers Monday night as it withdrew from
the area of Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
   Although the SLA pullout is seen as setting the stage for a
larger Israeli withdrawal from the security zone, there was no sign
Tuesday that the fighting would end soon.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli warplanes struck back repeatedly at the guerrillas,
hitting a Hezbollah stronghold in the Iqlim al-Toufah ridges and
the Krum al-Arz mountain around the ``Jezzine pocket,'' a region of
rocky hillsides and villages that surround the predominantly
Christian town of Jezzine. Three civilians were reportedly injured
in those Israeli airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Nadim Salem, who represents the Jezzine area in the Lebanese
parliament, said Tuesday that the Hezbollah attacks and the Israeli
reprisals only served to increase the anxiety many residents feel.
</P>
<P>
   That anxiety is increasing in the as the SLA pushes ahead with
what it claims will be a staged withdrawal over the next two weeks.
Many Christians fear the Shiite Muslim militants of Hezbollah may
detain and even execute as collaborators SLA loyalists, most of
whom are Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a breeze of optimism,'' Salem said, referring to the
announcement over the weekend that the SLA militia would be pulling
out of the town. ``Now it is the other way around. . . . It is an
atmosphere of fear.''
</P>
<P>
   As Salem spoke on a roadside near the checkpoint, his voice was
drowned out by the sound of Israeli warplanes streaking overhead.
Then there was a a thundering explosion as a missile slammed into a
hillside nearby as a plume of gray smoke rose over the horizon.
Moments later, Hezbollah mortar fire could be heard responding to
the Israeli attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want security,'' Salem added. ``They are not very
concerned about international policy. All they want is to live in
peace, to govern themselves, and to stay in their homes and their
land. That's all they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah leaders have insisted that those who collaborated with
the SLA should surrender now and face trial, but the
Iranian-financed and Syrian-backed resistance fighters maintain
that they would not enter the town by force. Since Lebanon is
officially at war with Israel, the militiamen are regarded as
traitors, their crime punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents are hoping that the Lebanese Army will fill the
vacuum in Jezzine. The pullback is seen as a test of whether the
Lebanese government can maintain order if Israel withdraws.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said the SLA withdrawal was an independent
decision of SLA leaders who have suffered substantial losses, even
losing two of their commanders, in recent weeks. Still, the move is
seen by most observers as a possible precursor of a total Israeli
withdrawal, promised within a year by new Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Just past the checkpoint on the road out of Jezzine Tuesday,
Fouad Issa, 45, who lives in Beirut but owns a business in Jezzine,
was optimistic about the the pullout of SLA forces and saw it as a
``liberation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis came here in force. They did not ask any questions,''
he said. ``They must depart the same way. No conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   (Material from wire services was was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
