</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALABAMA-TORT-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATURE PASSES CAP ON DAMAGE AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For more than a decade, no issue has divided Alabama
politics like that of tort revision, the effort to limit the
enormous damage awards that have made the state's juries fabled for
their generosity to plaintiffs. Even civil rights has been pushed
aside as the defining question for Alabama's politicians, whose
source of campaign money largely depends on their position on jury
verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, after a jury awarded $581 million to a family
that was overcharged $1,200 for two satellite dishes, even the
state's trial lawyers knew they could no longer prevent the
overhaul of the Alabama civil liability system long advocated by
business owners. The resulting compromise between the two sides led
the state Legislature to pass the state's first serious effort to
revise the tort system, the final and most important piece of which
was unanimously approved by the state House of Representatives on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which was earlier passed by the Senate and which Gov.
Donald Siegelman has promised to sign in the next week, places a
ceiling on punitive damages awarded by juries, the kind of damages
intended to punish a defendant for misconduct, which often soar
into the millions in Alabama. Business leaders were also hoping for
a limit on damages that compensate a plaintiff for financial losses
and pain and suffering, but were unable to achieve that in
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill limits punitive damages in noninjury cases against
large businesses to three times the compensatory damages, or
$500,000, whichever is greater. For verdicts against small
businesses, the limits are $50,000, or 10 percent of the business'
net worth, whichever is greater. In injury cases, the caps are
three times compensatory damages, or $1.5 million, whichever is
greater, for all businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's journey to join 22 other states with caps or
prohibitions on punitive damages was a difficult one, and its
outcome was uncertain until just a few weeks ago. The state has a
long populist history of antagonism to insurance companies and
other big businesses, particularly in rural counties, and it also
has some of the weakest consumer protection regulations in the
country. The combination of those factors produced a series of jury
verdicts that often seemed so outlandish they became the
centerpiece of the national business-backed movement that its
leaders call tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a nursing-home orderly sued a finance company for
overcharging him by $1,000 on a car loan; he was awarded $50
million in punitive damages by the jury. Two years earlier, a jury
awarded a man $4 million because his BMW had been repainted by the
automaker without his knowledge. That decision was struck down by
the U.S. Supreme Court, which called the award ``grossly
excessive''; it was later reduced to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Breedlove, president of the Alabama Trial Lawyers
Association, argued that the big awards, and the fear they
engendered among business owners, created a de facto consumer
protection system in a state that lacks many of the antifraud laws
of other states. But he said the size of the satellite-dish award
provided the incentive both sides needed to reach an agreement that
had long proved elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courthouse has been the only place where the consumers of
Alabama get a real opportunity for justice,'' Breedlove said. ``I
think that is still the case under this compromise, and we have now
put behind us the most divisive issue of the last decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Breedlove said he was particularly pleased that the Legislature
had not placed caps on awards in wrongful-death cases, or on claims
of mental anguish.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Business Council of Alabama, Bill O'Connor,
said business owners did not achieve everything they wanted but
were nonetheless glad to have settled an issue that he said had
hurt the state's business climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never know how many businesses wouldn't consider Alabama
because of these outrageous verdicts that have been issued, how
often we didn't make the cut,'' O'Connor said. ``But we've got a
reasonable accord now that should eliminate that hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature also passed a bill that limits
``jury-shopping,'' in which plaintiffs often filed their cases in
rural counties with histories of large verdicts, and a bill which
makes it harder to get a case certified as a class action. Both
those bills were signed last month by Siegelman, who has never been
known as a fervent proponent of tort revision. But in his campaign
last year he promised business leaders he would sign ``reasonable''
tort legislation, and he said in an interview on Tuesday that this
package meets that definition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In earlier years, we had proposals like forcing consumers to
be responsible for contracts they initialed, even if a business
lied to them,'' Siegelman said. ``That kind of thing just wasn't
reasonable, but putting a cap on these unfair lawsuits, which has
hurt our reputation in the business community, is what this state
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   In his various campaigns over the years, Siegelman, a Democrat,
has received hundreds of thousands of dollars from trial lawyers
groups, just as other candidates have received similar amounts from
business leaders, significantly driving up the cost of a statewide
campaign in Alabama. The support of business owners advocating tort
revision was crucial to the election last year of Lt. Gov. Steve
Windom, a Republican, who played a leading role in getting the
Senate to approve the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue of trial lawyers versus business owners has almost
replaced the idea of political parties in Alabama,'' said Dr.
William H. Stewart, chairman of the political science department at
the University of Alabama. ``Now that it's over, I wonder what
we're all going to talk about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
