<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supercomm trade show returns to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here they come again.
</P>
<P>
   SuperComm, the premier telecommunications trade show, will
return to the Georgia World Congress Center starting Sunday.
Organizers promised more attendees, zippier demonstrations and
higher-energy executive presentations.
</P>
<P>
   About 46,000 people came to Supercomm in 1998, and more are
expected this this time around, said Matthew J. Flanagan, president
of the Telecommunications Industry Association, an event sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   As enticement, those who come to the show will have a show floor
with hundreds of company booths _ including the usual array of
magic shows and glitzy, big-screen videos _ as well as more than
200 conferences and 800 speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of Supercomm has always been the conferences,''
Flanagan said. ``These are the movers and shakers of the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving the event's keynote address Tuesday morning at 8 a.m.
will be Microsoft President Steven Ballmer.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Cisco Systems President John Chamber will speak.
Author John Naisbitt will give the closing address Thursday at 8
a.m. Other high-powered speakers include Carleton Firoina, group
president of Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Among innovations new to this year's show will be a series of
financial presentations by communications companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We noticed that last year we have 1,200 financial
professionals _ analysts, brokers and others,'' said Jack Chalden,
Supercomm general manager. ``We thought it would be wise to create
something for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The show itself is drawing a different shade of
telecommunications professionals as the long-discussed convergence
of broadcast and communications comes to be, said Roy Neal,
president of the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association.
``The seeds of the policy changes of the past are only now
beginning to take root.''
</P>
<P>
   The show now draws from the established corporate giants, as
well as the hyper-ambitious start-ups, he said. ``The next
Netscape, the new Microsoft, the next Lucent are at the show. We
just don't know who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit hours are from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. on Tuesday, June 8; from
9 a.m. to 5 p.m. on June 9, and from 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. on June 10.
For information about the show, call (312-559-4600) or see the
event's site on the Internet's World Wide Web (www.iec.org).
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
