   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-KOSOVO (Washington) _ The United States moves to bolster
accelerating diplomatic efforts to end the 70-day-old conflict in
Yugoslavia by signaling a willingness to suspend allied bombing and
to consider a smaller U.S. role in a post-war security force in
Kosovo. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-WOMEN (Washington) _ With Tipper Gore and Hillary Rodham
Clinton by his side, Vice President Al Gore makes his pitch to
female voters who have been the mainstay of Democratic support
during the Clinton years. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-TRIAL (Washington) _ A lawyer for former Housing
Secretary Henry Cisneros says he will attack the credibility of
Linda Medlar Jones, the woman who has agreed to be the government's
star witness when Cisneros goes on trial for an alleged conspiracy
to conceal payments he made to her following their affair. By GARY
MARTIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush, in a
post-legislative, pre-presidential campaign news conference,
acknowledges he's getting a late start behind his rivals for the
Republican presidential nomination, but vows he's a ``battler.''
He's a rich battler, too, having raised far more than any of his
competitors. By CLAY ROBISON and THADDEUS HERRICK.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATURE-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ On the morning after the
Texas Legislature finished its work for this session, Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry was talking about the ``homework'' he will assign state
senators in preparation for the 2001 session. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LEBANON (Jerusalem) _ Hezbollah guerrillas are making it
hard for Israel's forces to withdraw from a section of the
so-called security zone in southern Lebanon. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (London) _ Thank goodness there'll always be a
United Kingdom. Someone has to keep the rest of us amused. Last
week a furor erupted in Parliament over welfare reform, and Prime
Minister Tony Blair edged out further on a shaky limb to press
NATO's war against Yugoslavia. But the only thing that gripped the
public was a photo in the Sun of Prince Edward's fiancee, Sophie
Rhys-Jones, with a breast bared and the giant press dust-up it
produced. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Milwaukee) _ Mired in their worst slump since 1997
with four consecutive losses, the Houston Astros try to snap out of
it tonight as they open a three-game series against the Milwaukee
Brewers. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
