<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMPUTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defense supercomputer gets major overhaul
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON,Ohio _ A supercomputer center at Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base is getting even more super under a $17 million upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade is being made to the Aeronautical Systems Center's
Major Shared Resource Center, one of four supercomputer centers in
the Defense Department. Military and university scientists around
the nation run massive problems on MSRC's computers over high-speed
data networks.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians were installing a Compaq Alphaserver ES40 system in
the the main computer room Tuesday when MSRC managers gave
reporters a tour of the center.
</P>
<P>
   The Compaq system will triple the center's computing power and
bring its peak performance to the equivalent of 2.4 million Pentium
II computers networked together, according to an Air Force
statement.
</P>
<P>
   All that computing power is packed into a cluster of nondescript
black cabinets. John Blair, MSRC deputy director, was almost
apologetic for the lack of flashy bells and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we get something new in it gets less
sexy-looking,'' he said. But he added the new system has four times
the power, one tenth the cost and half the maintenance of the Cray
C90 system it's replacing.
</P>
<P>
   The upgrade also includes improvements in the center's memory,
storage and networking capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said scientists use the center's vast powers to simulate
the performance of things as small as molecules and as big as
battlefields. One scientist has been using it to simulate
techniques for making the B-1B bomber less visible to radar, Blair
said.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-based simulation is becoming such a basic tool in the
acquisition business that the Air Force Materiel Command, based at
Wright-Pat, is moving to what it calls simulation based
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said this means a new weapon or aircraft will be evaluated
in computer simulations from the time it's first conceived through
design, production and later upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third major upgrade the center has undergone since
it opened in 1996. Nichols Research Corp., based in Huntsville,
Ala., set up and supports the center under a contract worth $157.9
million over eight years
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-01-99 1834E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
