A8882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-VOTE-BOS &LR;      06-01 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS NATION VOTES, SOME AFRIKANERS PLOT TO SECEDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA _ About 18 million people are expected to vote
Wednesday in South Africa's second all-race elections. Jan
Groenewold is not one of them. Instead of marking a ballot,
Groenewold will be on a farm not far from the capital, laying the
first bricks of a secessionist Afrikaner state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't mobilize and resist, blacks will run all over
us,'' he said. ``To establish the right relationship with South
Africa, we must find a political solution for our people first. We
must have a territorial base.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years after losing power, Afrikaners face their worst
crisis of identity and place since the Boer War a century ago. They
are disillusioned and deeply fragmented, chafing against black-led
overhaul of education, sports, and labor, and they are divided over
how to be part of a democratic society in which they are greatly
outnumbered.
</P>
<P>
   Some have embraced the end of minority rule. Others have
emigrated. Many just keep their heads down. And some are circling
the ox carts in the name of Volk _ the people _ and Fatherland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we're in bondage under democracy,'' said Constand
Viljoen, former chief-of-staff of the apartheid military machine,
who is fighting for Afrikaner self-determination as leader of the
Freedom Front, a political party. ``Our history is riddled with the
quest for freedom. We fought wars for it. We're still the same
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Afrikaners have no hope of regaining power. Five parties are
vying for their votes. The National Party, once led by stern,
finger-wagging guardians of white privilege, now has at its helm a
man derisively nicknamed ``Kortbroek,'' or ``short pants,'' because
he looks like a school boy.
</P>
<P>
   The arithmetic of political power is simple. Whites make up
about 10 percent of the South African electorate, with
Afrikaans-speakers accounting for a little more than half of the
white electorate, about 1 million votes. Divided among the five
parties, the numbers become negligible.
</P>
<P>
   The New National Party, a makeover of the organization that
ruled by apartheid for 46 years and won 20 percent of the overall
vote five years ago, is struggling for 5 percent this year,
according to most polls. It runs a real risk of losing control of
the one province it governs, the Western Cape, and its status as
the official opposition party to the ANC.
</P>
<P>
   Three other parties, including Viljoen's, might together net 2
percent of the total vote. Perhaps most insulting, the Democratic
Party, heir to a long tradition of white, liberal opposition during
the apartheid era, has vigorously sought and appears to be winning
the bulk of white Afrikaans-speaking voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is the end of the road for Afrikaner politics,''
said Tom Lodge, a political scientist at the University of the
Witwatersrand in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Since the demise of apartheid five years ago, Afrikaners have
watched the credibility of their elders crumble. The Dutch Reformed
Church admitted that it erred in promoting a biblical rationale for
apartheid. Senior politicians have been hauled before courts and
commissions to explain past deeds.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is confusion over who is and isn't an
Afrikaner. Jac Comradie, a language historian at the Rand Afrikaans
University in Johannesburg, argues that anyone who speaks Afrikaans
as a primary language should qualify as an Afrikaner. His
definition therefore includes as Afrikaners the mixed-race, or
``coloured,'' community spread across the southern coast. The
reality, he said, is that politicians and others seeking Afrikaner
self-determination see the Volk as white.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a people at war with ourselves,'' said A.J.
``Blokkies'' de Beer, director of Oranjewerkers, an organization
studying ways to preserve Afrikaner culture amid majority rule.
``We haven't ever been this disillusioned. While we were in power
we didn't have to do the soul-searching we must do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Afrikaner ancestors fled persecution and war in Europe. They
fought the British and the Zulus in Africa in a quest for autonomy.
Now, stuck without a motherland to return to, their descendents
want their own schools, churches, and police force. ``Freedom is
the essence of the Boere Afrikaner. Even right now, I feel it
here,'' de Beer said, gripping his gut.
</P>
<P>
   But forces are working against them. Not only have they lost
power, they lost the laws of racial separation that shielded them.
As democracy sinks its roots deeper, Afrikaner youth are being
exposed to new cultures and ways of thinking. Some are reaching out
to different religions.
</P>
<P>
   Groenewold says the only thing to do is start from scratch. The
mistake Afrikaners made, he argues, wasn't apartheid, but a
reliance on black labor. ``We need to occupy our own land, do our
own work, and defend it,'' he said. ``If you use others, you cannot
deny them rights.''
</P>
<P>
   A former cofounder of the extreme right-wing Afrikaner
Resistance Movement, Groenewold and others bought an idle farm 15
miles southeast of Pretoria three years ago, and are slowly
converting it into what they hope will become a completely
self-sufficient town. They scraped their own roads and tapped their
own water source. They have a formidable security gate at the
farm's entrance, a handful of houses, and a radio station. The
four-color flag of the 19th century Transvaal Republic flutters
over a makeshift school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to attract 5,000 people,'' he said. So far they are a
small collection of retired professionals and drifters.
</P>
<P>
   Viljoen isn't ready to abandon the political approach to
self-determination. The retired general has been negotiating with
Nelson Mandela and the African National Congress since 1993 for
some guarantee of Afrikaner group rights. His original thinking was
simple: If Afrikaners could not contain blacks in separate
homelands within South Africa, then they should have a homeland for
themselves, where they could run their own schools and provide
their own policing.
</P>
<P>
   For both political and logistical reasons, however, a
geographically defined Afrikaner homeland has been a nonstarter _
even though the ANC recognized in 1993 the principle of Afrikaner
self-determination. Viljoen now wants to create Afrikaner cantons,
towns and regions where the Volk are the majority. The problem is
that he may soon be out of job. If the Freedom Front stumbles badly
at the polls, Viljoen could lose his seat in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   It is not possible, however, for many Afrikaners to embrace the
ideal of a multiracial national identity. ``Our individual freedom
is tied to our freedom as a people,'' De Beer said. ``I cannot be
free if my people have no control as a group.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is so, the Volk will feel homeless in the land of their
birth for a long time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
