<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8884 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-MEXICO-2TAKES(TR     06-01 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-MEXICO-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCORD OVER INVESTIGATION OF ZEDILLO AIDE REFLECTS MISTRUST
BETWEEN U.S. AND MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By TIM GOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Earlier this year, as President Clinton prepared to
visit Mexico, law-enforcement officials there disclosed what they
cast as an extraordinary break from the country's long tradition of
immunity for those at the highest levels of power.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, officials said, they had been probing
allegations of drug corruption involving President Ernesto
Zedillo's closest aide, his powerful private secretary. After an
inquiry begun at the urging of the aide himself, investigators had
found the charges baseless, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to the Mexicans' dismay, the matter of the presidential
secretary, Jose Liebano Saenz Ortiz, has not been so easily put to
rest.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, senior officials including Attorney General Janet
Reno privately questioned the thoroughness of the Mexican inquiry,
prompting Reno's Mexican counterpart to insist that he would
consider any new evidence that emerged. But American officials said
they have grown only more suspicious, and have stepped up their own
intelligence efforts to learn about Saenz (pronounced ``signs'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that there is an issue of trust here,'' said the
Mexican attorney general, Jorge Madrazo. ``But I don't understand
how they can trust us on some issues and not on others. When we
have the evidence, we act.''
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials acknowledge that the accusations against
Saenz are unproven, the two governments' quiet discord over his
case reflects the deep mistrust that shapes their dealings on
matters of criminal justice. Officials said it also reflects the
difficulty that Washington has in handling reports of corruption
that involve high-level Mexican officials.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they were confident that their concerns
about Saenz had reached President Zedillo. Still, they were openly
relieved last week after Zedillo decided against naming him
interior minister, a post vacated by Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who
is running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said the allegations against Saenz came from
half a dozen sources, including several drug traffickers. All of
these people offered second-hand information about the aide's
activities, or claimed ties to him that they could not prove. At
least one of them failed a lie-detector test, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But according to two U.S. officials, the CIA has deemed reports
about Saenz serious enough to place him in the category of
foreign-government officials about whom it believes there are
credible allegations of wrongdoing. The allegations were also aired
recently at a private congressional briefing by drug-enforcement
and intelligence officials, after which congressional officials
wrote leaders of both the Senate and the House to recommend they
hear the same presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Saenz, 49, has acted as the president's de facto chief of staff,
and as his trusted emissary in dealings with political groups,
military leaders and others.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And like Zedillo, who was handed the governing party's
presidential candidacy after the assassination of Luis Donaldo
Colosio in 1994, Saenz reached the inner circle of Mexican politics
after a sudden, unlikely ascent.
</P>
<P>
   A famously affable man who graduated from Texas A&AMP;M University,
Saenz worked as a high-level administrator in the state tourism and
mining industries and the customs service. He later went to work
for Colosio and was one of the few Colosio aides who remained in
the campaign with Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, both the Mexican attorney general, Jorge Madrazo,
and Saenz traced some of the reports of his ties to illicit
activities to unscrupulous former associates who had sought to take
advantage of his political rise.
</P>
<P>
   A businessman with whom Saenz had been friendly while growing up
in Ciudad Juarez, for instance, was claiming that Saenz was his
friend and partner decades later, when the man's activities came
under scrutiny from federal drug-enforcement agents. Mexican
officials said the man's claims appeared to be completely false.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials also emphasized that it was Saenz who
initiated the federal investigation into his activities, in a
letter to Madrazo on May 24, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this is totally absurd to me,'' Saenz said in an
interview. ``I do not have any responsibility for dealing with
these matters. I do not go to meetings about them. I don't have
information about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Saenz went to the authorities after receiving a mysterious,
sealed envelope that contained a partial copy of notes taken on the
statement of a pilot for the country's biggest drug cartel. The
pilot was quoted as saying the cartel boss, Amado Carrillo Fuentes,
had given Saenz a house in a posh Mexico City suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The notes came to light after the army general who had taken
them, Jesus Gutierrez Rebollo, was arrested on corruption charges
in February 1997, while serving as Mexico's drug-enforcement chief.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said investigators searched extensively for
the house Saenz had purportedly received, checking property records
and canvassing two Mexico City suburbs. A similar effort was made
to trace a fleet of vehicles that a jailed drug smuggler claimed
had been given by traffickers to the press operation of Colosio's
campaign, which was directed by Saenz.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo said both searches were fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Another allegation against Saenz emerged last year from a
U.S.Customs investigation into the laundering of illegal drug
profits along the border between the two countries. An American
undercover agent and his informant, posing as money launderers, had
been introduced to a Mexican state prosecutor who they thought was
corrupt. The prosecutor, too, was talking about Liebano Saenz.
</P>
<P>
   According to several American officials and a confidential U.S.
government report on the case, the Mexican prosecutor, Arturo Pacho
Ruiz, said Saenz might be interested in meeting the men to discuss
laundering some money of his own.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting never happened. Still, the Customs Service chief
in San Diego, Edward W. Logan, passed the allegations along to the
head of an organized-crime force working for Madrazo. In an
interview, Madrazo said details of the case were conveyed to
President Zedillo, who ordered an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But Madrazo said the prosecutor had made several outrageous
claims, and retracted all of them after he was arrested. Saenz said
he had no recollection of Pacho Ruiz, who has been jailed on money
laundering charges, but acknowledged that the two of them had
apparently worked contemporaneously in the Mexican customs service,
where Saenz was the director of operations between late 1988 and
early 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Mexican organized-crime unit, Samuel Gonzalez
Ruiz, was hearing other stories about Saenz from a man who had
served as a bodyguard for Amado Carrillo Fuentes before the
trafficker's death in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to a copy of a sworn deposition given to Mexican
prosecutors on April 18, 1998, by the bodyguard, Jose Jaime Olvera
Olvera, after he entered Mexico's fledgling witness-protection
program, he had begun hearing a lot about Saenz.
</P>
<P>
   In May, 1996, he said, two of Carrillo Fuentes' associates told
the cartel leader that they had talked with ``people who were
directly with'' Saenz and that he should assemble the most of the
country's other major traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   At a summit of about 60 fellow traffickers at one of his Mexico
City homes, Carrillo Fuentes said Saenz had offered to assure the
protection of their smuggling activities in return for $100 million
and a strict ban on cocaine sales in Mexico, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Olvera said the traffickers eventually counteroffered $60
million, with Carrillo Fuentes paying half, and that the money was
delivered one morning in early August 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch at a suburban Mexico City restaurant, the money was
delivered to an older man referred to as ``General'' and two
younger lawyers, Olvera stated.
</P>
<P>
   On the drive home, he added, Carrillo Fuentes told his bodyguard
``that everything was going to get better because everything had
been arranged with Liebano Saenz Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is unclear whether the traffickers received
high-level support, U.S. and Mexican officials noted that the story
was one of several told by drug informants describing a huge payoff
by the Carrillo Fuentes gang. Yet it never made clear how Saenz,
who has no law-enforcement responsibilities, could assure the
traffickers' protection.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in an interview last September, Madrazo, the attorney
general, referred to him as one of the most important informants
ever developed by the organized-crime unit. But six months later,
in another interview in which he dismissed each of the allegations
against Saenz, Madrazo disparaged the bodyguard's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a guy who had psychiatric problems,'' Madrazo said,
citing a medical assessment. ``For us his information has no value.
His information is totally false.''
</P>
<P>
   Several U.S. officials disputed that view, saying American
drug-enforcement agents had met with Olvera and found him credible.
</P>
<P>
   Olvera was murdered on a Mexico City street last September, soon
after signing a letter asking that his government protection be
removed.
</P>
<P>
   American law-enforcement officials are skeptical about the
authenticity of the letter.
</P>
<P>
   United States officials said they were also troubled about the
Mexican investigation because Gonzalez Ruiz, the organized-crime
chief who ran the inquiry, was relieved of his job after he and
another official submitted Saenz to seven hours of questioning.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, it was all they talked about,'' one official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said of the organized-crime unit's
inquiry. ``Then it was just gone.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo disclosed the investigation and exonerated Saenz on Feb.
5, shortly after he agreed to discuss the case with a reporter for
The New York Times. Madrazo and Gonzalez Ruiz both strongly denied
that the case had anything to do with his departure from the
organized-crime force, and both said they were fully confident of
Saenz's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   But when Madrazo briefed a group of senior American
law-enforcement officials on Feb. 25, he received a notably
skeptical response, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Justice Department official familiar with the
meeting, Madrazo was questioned by the deputy chief of the Drug
Enforcement Administration, Donnie Marshall, about steps not taken
in the inquiry. Another official said Reno asked how the
investigation could be closed when leads had gone unpursued,
prompting Madrazo to say it would remain open.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, who denied that any real conflict had emerged between
the two governments over the issue, said he told the American
officials he would consider any new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, American officials said they have received no
indication that the investigation is continuing. But they added
that there is little they can do other than collect information.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Reno and Marshall said they had no comment on the
case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
