s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTE/BROWN-DANCE-$AD     06-01 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTE/BROWN-DANCE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MARRIAGE OF OPPOSITES, A MERGER OF EQUALS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Christopher Reardon's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was
about Les Ballets de Monte Carlo.  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Elisa Monte is hardly the first dancemaker to marry
her muse. George Balanchine, in the final tally, exchanged vows
with four of his best ballerinas. But Ms. Monte, who left Martha
Graham's company in 1982 to run her own troupe, has taken an
unusual step by sharing artistic direction equally with her spouse,
the former Graham dancer David Brown.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, when the company long known as Elisa Monte Dance
opens a two-week season at the Joyce Theater, the marquee for the
first time will read Monte/Brown Dance. The dancers will perform
three new works by Brown along with two by Ms. Monte. The couple
shares credit for a sixth new piece, ``Run to the Rock,'' a
rhapsodic solo danced to Nina Simone's husky rendition of
``Sinnerman.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's ascendance has not come easily, though. In recent
interviews, both together and apart, he and Ms. Monte described it
as the most turbulent phase in their 22-year relationship. At
times, they wondered if their marriage, and troupe, would survive.
</P>
<P>
   Since they live and rehearse in the same space _ a NoHo loft
that is also home to their 15-year-old daughter, Elia _ the strain
was hard to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many moments when I thought, `This is too hard,'''
said Ms. Monte, 53, who once pulled a door off its hinges and threw
it at Brown. ``But after 20 years, I think any relationship has
gone through times when you ask, `Is this really where we should
be?'''
</P>
<P>
   They met in 1977, while dancing for Graham, and the chemistry
between them was palpable. Ms. Monte asked Brown, seven years her
junior, to be her partner in her first dance, the sultry
``Treading,'' which Alvin Ailey added to his company's repertory.
They soon moved in together and married a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're opposites,'' said Brown, noting contrasts that in some
cases seem trivial (their birthdays are exactly six months apart)
but in others bear directly on their choreography (she responds
intuitively to music, while he tends to analyze written scores).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm big and exuberant and out there,'' he said of their
personalities. ``But I conceal a lot. Elisa's more withdrawn _
she'll say five words to my 50 _but also more honest.''
</P>
<P>
   One trait they share is a penchant for dancing that is
emotionally expressive and points to universally experiences. Ms.
Brown calls it ``abstract realism.''
</P>
<P>
   As her leading dancer, Brown had always played a creative role.
But he longed to make dances he could call his own, something he
did not feel Ms. Monte fully supported. ``I wanted to go off and do
my own work at one point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he did. Twice, in fact, he went to Tunisia to make a dance
for a project concerning the African diaspora. (Brown is Jamaican.)
His tenacity convinced Ms. Monte that he was serious about
choreographing. It also informed one of her new dances, a
full-company work whose rhythmic complexities and shifting patterns
reflect the tension between independence and belonging. The piece
is called ``Amor Fati,'' Latin for ``Love Your Fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown takes up the same theme in his elegiac new quintet,
``Maquette.'' But in rehearsal, he appeared more intent on refining
the formal geometries and lyrical inflections of ``Niagara'' and
``Petits Pois,'' both set to Shostakovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's development can be looked at as taking away from me,''
Ms. Monte said. ``But I'm still doing what I want to do, how I want
to do it. In fact, it's easier. I'm sharing responsibility, and our
relationship is healthier because of it.'' Like any partnership,
though, it took a leap of faith. ``It required getting rid of the
immediate protectivism and getting past that initial fear of `Is
this diminishing me?' It doesn't have to be that, and it's
certainly not that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
