</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLICY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO MEET WITH JOINT CHIEFS ABOUT USING GROUND TROOPS IN
KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time since NATO's air war began 70
days ago, President Clinton is meeting with his Joint Chiefs of
Staff on Thursday to discuss options for using ground troops if
NATO decides to invade Kosovo, NATO and administration officials
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is holding the session as the administration and NATO
are facing increasing time pressure to deal with the issue of an
invasion force. In order to have troops numbering about 150,000 in
place in the Kosovo region by mid-August, decisions to deploy them
would have to be made by mid-June, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even mid-June for a decision may be too late, a senior Pentagon
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision-making window also is narrowing as leaders focus on
the approaching diplomatic summit of the Group of 7 and Russia in
Cologne, Germany, where the Kosovo conflict is expected to dominate
the agenda between Clinton and the Russian president, Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has repeatedly tried to avoid public discussion
of combat forces, fearful of public opinion polls that show there
is little appetite for such a venture and of a backlash over the
American casualties that would inevitably occur. Some NATO allies,
particularly Britain, have argued that leaving open the threat of
deploying ground troops could increase pressure on President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to agree to a diplomatic
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and NATO have already approved the
composition of a force of 48,000 NATO troops described as needed
for peacekeeping in Kosovo once a settlement is achieved.
</P>
<P>
   But with a successful diplomatic outcome still far from certain,
NATO officials said that the administration has to look at the
options for an invasion force to defeat the Yugoslav military and
clear Kosovo for the return of more than 800,000 ethnic Albanian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The American commander of NATO, Gen. Wesley Clark, who has made
little secret of his belief in the need for an invasion force, was
told last week by the Pentagon not to come for Thursday's White
House meeting, a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want a vigorous presentation of what they know he
will present and what he thinks is necessary to win,'' the official
said of the administration's reluctance about an invasion force.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's encounter between Clinton, the chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton, the vice-chairman, Gen. Joseph
Ralston, and the heads of the four services, would cover the gamut
of military options for Kosovo, with the invasion force the newest
element on the agenda, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the war began, Clinton has often met with Shelton and
Ralston but not with the full complement of his military advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration continues to concentrate its efforts on the
air strikes coupled with diplomacy and would like to have a
diplomatic solution in place by the time of the meetings in Cologne
between Clinton and Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, proves to be
intractable during a meeting scheduled on Wednesday in Belgrade
with the special Russian envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and President
Maarti Ahtisaari of Finland, about a possible agreement to the end
of the conflict, the administration will, at the very least, have
to consider an invasion force.
</P>
<P>
   And if the June 18 summit fails to produce a diplomatic
solution, the administration should be ready with a decision on an
invasion force, a NATO diplomat said. A decision on an invasion
force ``did not drop from the sky'' and had to be prepared now, the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next few days, a week, there will be serious discussion
of ground troops for the first time,'' an administration official
said. ``People are coming to the point of very sobering talks about
ground troops. It's all coming to a point of convergence.''
</P>
<P>
   In this context, ground troops means a contingent of more than
150,000 troops, which would come mostly from the United States,
Britain, and possibly France, NATO officials said. NATO can mount
such a force with only some partners if the other members do not
veto.
</P>
<P>
   In Bonn last week, Secretary of Defense William Cohen discussed
the option of an invasion force with his colleagues from four NATO
countries. He did not advocate an invasion force and did not
mention the number of troops that the United States would be
willing to commit, a NATO official said. But he laid the ground
work for a possible invasion force, by asking Germany to refrain
from saying that it would block NATO from sending such a force, a
NATO diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder,
declared combat troops ``unthinkable'' and said his government
would block such a move. In the last week, German officials have
been less outspoken against combat troops but have been pushing a
diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
   At the Bonn meeting attended by Cohen, and in other discussions,
NATO officials said that Britain has offered 50,000 troops for an
invasion force.
</P>
<P>
   The British prime minister, Tony Blair, has been forthright in
his statements that an invasion force may be necessary. British
diplomats have told their American counterparts that in the end,
the British government believes combat troops will be needed if the
Yugoslav military is to be forced out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that Clark briefed the ministers of defense
of Britain, France, Germany, and Italy early last week on how an
invasion force would operate.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable for getting troops to Albania and Macedonia, the
most likely staging areas for an invasion into Kosovo, would be
dictated largely by the onset of the Kosovo winter in October. The
Serbian troops would have to be out of Kosovo by October for there
to be any reasonable chance for the refugees now squatting in tent
cities in Macedonia and Albania to return home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
