<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLETON SCHOOL REOPENED TO PUPILS TO RECOVER BELONGINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MINDY SINK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Columbine High School students were allowed
back inside the bullet-scarred building Tuesday to retrieve their
backpacks and other personal items for the first time since the
shooting here on April 20.
</P>
<P>
   The students, some in tears and many accompanied by parents and
teachers, collected art projects, gym clothes, organizers and other
items left behind that sunny Tuesday morning six weeks ago when two
of their fellow students, Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17,
opened fire inside the school. They killed 12 students, a teacher
and themselves in the worst school shooting in the nation's
history.
</P>
<P>
   For some students on Tuesday, returning to the partially
boarded-up school, where bullet holes were visible in the walls and
most doorknobs had been removed by investigators, brought a closing
to a painful period. For others, it dredged up feelings of fear and
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt nervous,'' said Michelle Cowles, 16, as she shook and
tried to hold back tears. ``I didn't want to come back here
today.'' Michelle, like many of the other students, was leaving the
school with a white garbage bag full of supplies from her locker.
``It felt good to get in there and get out again. I want to start
my life again.''
</P>
<P>
   And like many others, Michelle was not only accompanied by her
father, but was keeping close to him, holding his hand and
embracing him as they left the school. Grief counselors were also
at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Many students described an eerie scene inside Columbine, where
time seemed to have stood still in some classrooms, many of which
had been marked ``cleared'' or ``no evidence'' by the
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird being back in there,'' said Amanda Wiegard, a
16-year-old who will be a junior in the fall. ``Like, in the math
room all the windows were shot out, but the desks were right where
we left them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the shootings, many students were in their fifth
period classrooms, while others were at lunch. On Tuesday, students
met with their fifth period teachers and were escorted back to
those classrooms in groups of 15 to 25. Officials had already
emptied the lockers, after spending weeks searching for bombs and
other evidence, and numbered the contents for students to pick up
in the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   For some, returning to those classrooms was unsettling, as they
counted students forever missing from their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in fifth period English class with Steve Curnow,'' said
Katie Jorgenson, 14, who carried a heavy bag of gym clothes, winter
coats and school notebooks over her shoulder. ``I just felt numb in
there today. I didn't want to go back when it's not fixed and it's
smelly and there's broken glass. They told us the glass was from
the SWAT teams, but I think they just said that to make us feel
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie's mother, Julie Jorgenson, felt differently about
Tuesday's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great,'' she said. ``We need to get over
these hurdles and get back to normal. No one should have to go
through what these kids did.''
</P>
<P>
   County mental health officials and school administrators said
walking back into Columbine was a first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of apprehension on the faces of the students as
they entered the school today, but as they left I saw a sense of
relief,'' said Joanne Doherty, the deputy director for the
Jefferson County Center for Mental Health. ``This is yet another
step in the road for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Many students came Tuesday hoping for a final glimpse of what
they remembered seeing and hearing in those terrifying moments on
April 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw down the hall where the science classroom was, and we
saw where carpet was torn up, maybe from a spilled soda or blood
evidence, they said,'' said Erica McClaugherty, 14, who will be a
sophomore in the fall. ``I was kind of creeped out. It's scary that
such a safe place to me can be so shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   Erica said she was in the cafeteria taking pictures of friends
when the shooting began and only heard the shots. ``I want to see
those pictures so bad, and I don't know if the film or the camera
is OK,'' she said. The sprinklers went off during the shooting, and
items left on the floors were water-damaged.
</P>
<P>
   If Erica's pictures turn out, they may also be the final images
of the school library, the site of most of the shootings, and where
the gunmen killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The parts of the school that were damaged will be rebuilt by the
fall, but officials said they did not have designs completed for
the reconstruction. They said they expected to begin demolition
work in the cafeteria and in the library, which is still considered
a crime scene, within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no structural damage, but we will be taking out
walls, windows and doors,'' said George Latuda, construction
manager for the school. Latuda said that the changes in the
cafeteria would be small but that there would be major changes in
the library.
</P>
<P>
   The school's nearly 2,000 students and faculty will be allowed
to visit the school again on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
