<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Charles Enters Food Fray &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles has accused supporters of genetically modified
food of using ``emotional blackmail'' to cover up its dangers by
arguing its production is necessary to feed the world's population.
He warned that approval of such crops, labeled ``Frankenstein
food'' by a growing number of critics in Britain, would see the
country ``embarking on an Orwellian future.''
</P>
<P>
   France: Islamists Go on Trial &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four men went on trial in Paris on charges of having a
role in the wave of pro-Islamist bombings that terrorized France in
1995. The attacks, which killed 10 people and wounded more than
100, were apparently intended to punish France for siding with the
Algerian government in that country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Judge Is Charged &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Mexico City judge, Maria Campuzano Caballero, who in January
1998 released without trial a man who had confessed to murdering an
American businessman, was charged with judicial violations for
improperly issuing her ruling. After prosecutors issued a warrant
for her arrest, Ms. Campuzano appeared voluntarily before a judge
who charged her and released her on bail. Zarate's confessed
murderer, whom Ms. Campuzano called a ``modern Robin Hood,'' is on
trial on unrelated charges.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Mixed Message on Zedillo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-one percent of Mexicans approve of the way Ernesto Zedillo
is handling his presidency, according to a national poll of 1,191
people by the newspaper Reforma. That is a 4 percent decline from
March, Zedillo's most popular moment. But fewer are pessimistic
about the economy, which could help the governing party as it tries
to retain the presidency in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Kashmir Maneuvering &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In coming talks with Pakistan, Defense Minister George Fernandes
said India would consider allowing militants occupying a swath of
Indian territory in Kashmir safe passage into Pakistan-occupied
Kashmir. India maintains that the militants are pawns of Pakistan,
which Pakistan denies. India pressed its seventh day of air raids
against the militants with the aim of driving them out of their
hideouts.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: Ta Mok Aides to Testify &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said three former Khmer Rouge guerrillas
would be summoned to testify for the prosecution in a trial of
their former boss, Ta Mok, who was captured on March 6. The three
men _ a former bodyguard and two former commanders _ had already
defected to the government side at the time and had been given new
posts in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Suharto Son Quizzed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The oldest son of former President Suharto, Sigit Harjodjudanto,
was questioned at the attorney general's office about the family's
accumulation of wealth. The most prominent of the six Suharto
children, Siti Hardiyanti Rukmana, who was minister of Social
Welfare in her father's last cabinet, was questioned on Monday.
Some local commentators have dismissed the questioning as a
pre-election ploy by the ruling party to distance itself from the
Suharto legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: U.N. Aide Takes Up Post &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The head of a U.N. mission to East Timor, Ian Martin, took up
his post and said an end to violence is a prerequisite for the
holding of a referendum on independence, scheduled for August. At
the same time, Indonesia's leading presidential candidate, Megawati
Sukarnoputri, made a campaign stop in the disputed territory and
indicated that she opposed independence.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Suharto Off Banknote &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The gently smiling face of former President Suharto, along with
the motto ``Father of Development,'' will disappear from
Indonesia's highest-denomination banknote, the 50,000 rupiah. New
banknotes replace Suharto's image with that of Soepratman, the man
who wrote Indonesia's national anthem. The 50,000-rupiah note _
worth about $20 before the dramatic currency devaluations that
began in 1997 _ is now worth $6.20.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Iran: Khatami Aide Elected &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A close ally of President Mohammed Khatami was elected mayor of
Tehran by the capital's city council. The new mayor, Morteza
Alviri, replaces Gholamhossein Karabaschi, who is serving a
two-year prison sentence on charges of corruption. Karabaschi had
been made a target of Khatami's opponents, but Alviri's election
has been seen as a sign of Khatami's strength.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
