<HEADER>
A8930 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-2TAK     06-01 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LETTER TO GERMANY, MILOSEVIC ACCEPTS VAGUE PRINCIPLES OF PEACE
ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-POLICY) 
(rm) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Germany on Tuesday received a letter from the Yugoslav
government in which President Slobodan Milosevic said he was ready
to withdraw forces from Kosovo and accept a ``United Nations
presence'' in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic also demanded an immediate end to NATO's
70-day-old bombardment if a settlement is to be reached and made
clear that significant differences with the West remain.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, formally accepting broad principles for a peace
accord set on May 6 by the Group of Seven industrialized countries
and Russia, arrived as the Finnish president, Martti Ahtissari,
prepared to travel to Belgrade on Wednesday for the first meeting
between a Western leader and Milosevic since the NATO bombing
began.
</P>
<P>
   The planned visit, and the decision by Ahtissari to talk to a
man indicted last week on war crimes charges, suggested that
diplomacy has advanced enough to necessitate a direct exchange,
however unpalatable such a meeting may be.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said Ahtissari's visit reflects a conviction
among Western governments that Milosevic is beginning to cede under
the pressure of bombing and that time is running out for a
diplomatic settlement that would avert a possible ground invasion
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is deeply reluctant to contemplate the use of
ground forces, but military planners believe preparations must be
made in the next few weeks if the threat of an invasion is to be
credible.
</P>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said that Ahtissari
would take with him a detailed settlement plan. In effect, said a
senior Western official, ``the plan shows how we believe the broad
principles now agreed to by Yugoslavia would work on an operational
level.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter received Tuesday by Germany, Milosevic committed
Yugoslavia to the vague terms laid out May 6, including the
withdrawal from Kosovo of ``military, police and paramilitary
forces'' and acceptance of the deployment there of ``effective
international civil and security presences.''
</P>
<P>
   But the letter made no commitment to withdrawing all Serbian
forces from the province, a central allied demand which, in
deference to Russia, was not spelled out in the May 6 statement.
</P>
<P>
   The letter also indicated nothing more than an acceptance of ``a
United Nations presence, mandate and other elements to be decided
by a U.N. Security Council Resolution'' _ an undertaking that
appears to fall far short of Washington's demand for a force in
Kosovo that would have NATO at its core.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was also quick to accept a ``United Nations presence''
in Croatia and Bosnia at difficult moments in the wars there,
presences he later exploited to consolidate the Serbian position by
playing on the ambiguities of the U.N. mandate and the weakness of
the forces deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central unresolved issue remains what comes out of Kosovo
and what goes in,'' said Michael Steiner, chief diplomatic adviser
to Gerhard Schroeder, the German chancellor. ``We need all the
Serbian troops out, other than a possible symbolic presence, and a
convincing military deployment that only NATO can provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said that Ahtissari would spell this out to
Milosevic and make clear that he must accept NATO's terms rather
than the May 6 statement.
</P>
<P>
   Because up to now talks with Milosevic have been conducted by a
Russian, Viktor Chernomyrdin, NATO is concerned that the Yugoslav
leader may have received a diluted version of the alliance's
demands, officials said. Ahtissari's presence was therefore
critical at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's conditions include the withdrawal of all Serbian forces,
Belgrade's acceptance of an international force in Kosovo with NATO
at its core, and the return of close to one million ethnic
Albanians who have been driven from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not settle for less,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright told a news conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``It's important for there to be an explanation by
Milosevic as to what it is he means.''
</P>
<P>
   She spoke after a meeting with the Italian foreign minister,
Lamberto Dini, who said that Milosevic had to accept the conditions
set on May 6 as well as NATO's demands and had to begin to withdraw
forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is not accepted and is not verifiable, then I do not
think it will be possible for the alliance to come to an agreement
on the suspension of bombing,'' Dini said.
</P>
<P>
   This statement, from a country that has been among the more
eager to end the bombing, suggested that the Clinton administration
has convinced its allies that only what would amount to a clear
admission of defeat by Milosevic would suffice to stop the bombing
and open the way to a settlement.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The rejection by Serbia of a NATO deployment in Kosovo
precipitated the start of the bombing on March 24. The bombing, in
turn, proved a catalyst to an already prepared and partially
executed Serbian campaign to evict the ethnic Albanian population
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott held talks in Bonn on
Tuesday with Chernomyrdin, Russia's envoy, and Ahtisaari, who is
representing the European Union. The discussions, also attended by
Schroeder, focused on how to narrow differences with Yugoslavia,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is to accompany Ahtisaari to Belgrade on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the talks Tuesday, Schroeder told a news conference, ``We
are on the way to a political solution of the problem and
substantial progress has been made.''
</P>
<P>
   The German government, a coalition of Social Democrats and
environmentalist Greens, has been increasingly eager to suggest
that progress is being made because pressure is mounting in both
parties for a halt to the bombing. The government is also deeply
opposed to a NATO ground invasion, which would become a more likely
option if the current diplomacy fails.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtissari said Tuesday in an interview with Finnish radio that
he was not going to Belgrade to negotiate with Milosevic. ``This is
no regular negotiating situation,'' he said. His statement
reflected NATO's official position that its demands are
nonnegotiable.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, however, it is clear that several difficult issues
will be reviewed with Milosevic. The first is what signal he would
have to give to demonstrate that his commitment to a settlement is
genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's broken promise after promise,'' the British Defense
Secretary, George Robertson, said Tuesday of Milosevic. ``We must
not and we cannot trust his word. We can only judge him on what he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   In its letter to the German government, Yugoslavia said that,
``In order to achieve a successful solution, it is necessary
immediately to end the NATO aerial bombardment and to concentrate
on a political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO governments _ particularly Britain and the United
States _ would clearly want some strong tangible indication that
Serbian troops had started to withdraw en masse from Kosovo before
the bombing was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Another difficult issue is what Serbian forces, if any, would be
allowed to remain in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Milosevic was likely to maneuver to increase the
number of Russians in any peacekeeping force, try to concentrate
this Russian presence in the northern part of Kosovo to which Serbs
are most attached, and attempt to keep the British and American
contingents to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   But Steiner said that any deployment that suggested a division
of Kosovo into two zones _ one mainly Russia and one controlled by
NATO countries _ ``cannot be acceptable as an aim, because it might
imply an imminent division of the province.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadly, Western officials said the aim was to move toward
agreement on a settlement by the time of the summit meeting of
Group of Seven countries and Russia in Cologne, Germany, in two
weeks. If no agreement could be reached before then, the pressure
to look seriously at a ground invasion and prepare for it might
become overwhelming, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
