<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker relieved to receive recognition
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Rocker has done well so far as the Braves'
closer, and he can hold up his Rolaids Relief Man National League
pitcher of the month award to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   He capped off the month Monday with his ninth save in 10
chances, bringing his season total to 10. He was 1-1 with a 0.60
ERA in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice little milestone, I guess. Next stop is 20,''
Rocker said of hitting double digits in saves for the first time in
his career. He had only three saves in his career before this year:
two in Atlanta, one in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's save came against Colorado, the team that cost him a
blown save in his first save opportunity as the Braves' closer in
Denver on April 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad to redeem myself against them,'' Rocker said. ``If
a team beats you, you can get it in your head, `That team owns me.'
It's good to prove to yourself you can get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker hasn't allowed a run in his last 11 appearances, dating
to May 7 when he ran into trouble against the Padres. That was his
only blemish in an otherwise dominant month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go out and throw strikes I can fare well against
anybody,'' Rocker said. ``Lately I've been making some good pitches
and getting away with mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   For someone who was a starter until last season, Rocker is
taking to this closer business well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really saw myself as a reliever,'' he said, and there
was a good reason _ it took him 30-45 minutes to warm up.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker has found ways around that, using a four- or five-run
lead or deficit in the later innings as his cue to start stretching
his legs and his arm. He now needs only five minutes to get his arm
nearly ready. That little sprint to the mound? It's about more than
psyching himself up to pitch and being a quirky left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to run six or eight sprints before I started,'' Rocker
said. ``I'm 80 percent loose in the pen. That sprint warms me up a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving them in
</P>
<P>
   When Ryan Klesko drove in a run in the sixth inning Monday, it
raised his average to .200 with runners in scoring position. That
makes him the weak link of the big hitters in the Braves lineup in
that category, behind Brian Jordan (.418), Bret Boone (.357),
Andruw Jones (.327), Chipper Jones (.277) and Javy Lopez (.275).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot better than the 1-for-15 stretch,'' Klesko
said, referring to the mini-slump he endured in April after
returning from a sore hamstring. ``I'm not going to worry about it
because I've only got 120 some at-bats (126). I definitely wasn't
happy with it, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko is hitting better overall. His batting average climbed
from .260 to .286 in the last seven games in May. During that span
he went 9-for-22 and hit safely in six games.
</P>
<P>
   More on Chen
</P>
<P>
   As rookie Bruce Chen headed off to AAA Richmond, Braves pitching
coach Leo Mazzone had this to say about his potential: ``It's just
a matter of getting more innings. He's handled himself real well.
He should be a solid big leaguer someday.
</P>
<P>
   Chen lost his shot at the fifth starter's spot in spring
training and failed to regain it from Odalis Perez in his two
starts while John Smoltz was on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quality in spurts,'' Mazzone said. ``It can be his
fastball, his breaking ball or his change-up.Etc.
</P>
<P>
   When the amateur draft begins today, the Braves won't make their
first pick until the second round, 81st overall. Atlanta lost its
picks at 30th (first round) and 36th (sandwich pick) overall as
compensation for signing free agent Jordan this offseason. ...
Pitcher Damian Moss has been reinstated from the disabled list and
optioned to Class A Macon, where he is scheduled to start today.
Moss is returning from elbow transplant surgery last June 24. The
native Australian is 28-29 with a 3.93 ERA in four years in the
minors.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
