<SLUG> BC-IMPALA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CHEVROLET STEERS THE IMPALA DOWN MEMORY LANE
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not be for your father's Impala, but the advertising
promoting the latest model of that Chevrolet might take him back a
few years.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Chevy has revived its popular 1950s song ``See
the U.S.A. in your Chevrolet'' in a new campaign for the 2000 model
Impala.
</P>
<P>
   For some potential car buyers, the ads may hark back to another
era of automobiles. But the updated marketing message is clearly
aimed at today's consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attempt was not to be nostalgic but to simply take a great
piece of equity we had and _ if you're going to promote the pure
pleasure of driving _ what better way than to show the inside of
the vehicle and have a song that's all about the joy of driving?''
asked Bill Ludwig, vice chairman and chief creative officer of
Campbell-Ewald Advertising in Warren, Mich., which created the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The national TV campaign began running during the Memorial Day
weekend when two 30-second spots were introduced on the
Indianapolis 500 broadcast by ABC. Print ads are set to begin
appearing this month in weekly news magazines. Chevrolet, the
largest division at the General Motors Corp., plans to use regional
direct-marketing to augment the promotion later this year.
</P>
<P>
   One spot focuses on a woman gazing happily at the world, while a
contemporary version of the trademark song plays in the background.
A narrator asks, ``When was the last time you drove, just for the
fun of it? Why doesn't somebody bring that back?'' Viewers then see
shots of the new Impala on the road, and learn that the woman is a
passenger in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's tag line is ``Let's go for a drive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `No one says that anymore,''' said Ludwig of
Campbell-Ewald, part of the Interpublic Group of Companies. ``They
say, `Let's go to the store, let's go pick up the laundry and let's
go to work.' But no one says, `Hey, let's go for a drive.'''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is meant to emphasize the pleasure of riding in an
Impala, which carries a sticker price of around $19,000 to $23,000.
``It's very different than the zippy little runabout you might
experience in a smaller Japanese car or Volkswagen,'' Ludwig said.
``We were trying to get at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet began shipping the 2000 Impala to its 4,300 dealers on
April 8. The company said consumer research had determined that
customers ``want a car that satisfies the head, yet appeals to the
heart,'' said Jim Jandasek, director of passenger car advertising
and sales promotion for Chevrolet; the campaign was created with
that in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The updated Chevrolet theme song is likely to get some attention
simply because of its nostalgic appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the noise level of automobile advertising is so
difficult to break through, it seems to me that if a company had
something that worked once upon a time _ and if it can be made
relevant to today's target market _ there is no reason why they
shouldn't go with it,'' said Clive Chajet, the president of Chajet
Consultancy in New York, which advises corporations on
brand-building strategies.
</P>
<P>
   He did, though, warn of a potential pitfall of using a familiar
tag line or tune. ``The risk is that if it's not updated, the image
gets frozen in time,'' Chajet said, ``and it becomes, to use an
auto term, your grandfather's Oldsmobile'' _ or Impala. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
