<SLUG> BC-CISCO-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC ENDING INQUIRY INTO CISCO SYSTEMS' PARTNERSHIP TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said on Tuesday that it was ending
its nine-month investigation into partnership discussions that
Cisco Systems Inc., the No. 1 maker of data communications
equipment, held in recent years with two rivals, Lucent
Technologies Inc. and the Nortel Networks Corp. of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry's end means that for the time being, Cisco will
escape the sort of regulatory and legal pressure that the
government has brought to bear on two other titans of cyberspace,
the Intel Corp. and the Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that the FTC concluded in this routine inquiry that
the practices that they had asked about were not really an issue,''
Dan Scheinman, Cisco's general counsel and vice president for legal
and governmental affairs, said Tuesday. ``And ultimately it shows
that Cisco is a company which has been very cautious, very
conservative about how it approaches these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Streitfeld, a spokeswoman for the commission, said the
investigation had ended but declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the FTC began its investigation by asking Cisco
for documents relating to partnership discussions the company had
held with Lucent and Nortel in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Executives who have seen the commission's original inquiry
letter said the investigation was prompted at least partly by news
reports last summer in which Cisco executives indicated the company
would be willing to agree not to compete in certain areas as part
of a deal with a potential partner.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear a few years ago that Cisco, the biggest maker of
Internet switches, was on a collision course with Lucent and
Nortel, North America's biggest makers of traditional telephone
equipment. Cisco is trying to make its gear capable of transmitting
phone calls while Lucent and Nortel want to become forces in the
data world.
</P>
<P>
   An article in The New York Times last July reported that John T.
Chambers, Cisco's chief executive, had decided essentially to go it
alone after trying and failing to form alliances with Lucent or
Nortel. The article also reported that Cisco was willing to forgo
competing in the core telecommunications markets for big phone
switches and corporate phone systems in return for any potential
partner agreeing to refrain from moving into Cisco's main product
area: high-speed Internet switches.
</P>
<P>
   But Lucent and Nortel refused that deal because the data market
was growing much faster than the market for traditional phone gear.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco provided two boxes of documents to the FTC, which was
concerned that the company had improperly attempted to divide the
communications market. After nine months, the commission apparently
concluded that Cisco did not behave improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Three months before the inquiry began, Nortel agreed to acquire
Bay Networks Inc., another big data communications company, for
$9.1 billion in stock. In January, Lucent agreed to acquire Ascend
Communications Inc., one of Cisco's main foes, for $20 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
