<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8950 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SOPRANOS-ART-2TAKE     06-01 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOPRANOS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMPATHETIC BRUTES IN A POP MASTERPIECE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The absurdist view of history, the version that probably makes
the most sense in the age of Monicagate and the Washington follies,
suggests that it's people's little quirks and kinks that make big
things happen. Modern wars and coups are really the products of
mood swings and temper tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' the groundbreaking HBO series that begins
reruns of its first 13 episodes on Wednesday at 9 p.m., subscribes
to this absurd view. Ruffled pride, paranoia and childish score
settling, rather than any grand plan, determine its characters'
fates.
</P>
<P>
   Take Livia Soprano, an ominous matriarch who subtly coerces
Junior, her mobster brother-in-law, to take out a contract on the
life of his rival, her son Tony. Why would a mother do such a
thing? Out of paranoia and spite, it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   On learning that Tony has been seeing a psychiatrist, she is
seized with the certainty that he spends his therapy sessions
denouncing her. As for Junior: When his girlfriend boasts in a nail
salon of Junior's prowess at oral sex, the news filters back to
Tony, who ribs his uncle about bedroom etiquette that Tony and his
macho cronies scorn as unmanly. Junior's humiliation deepens the
potentially murderous breach between uncle and nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of 13 hours, these accumulated conflicts have
the force of Greek tragedy. Or is it a Chekhov comedy replayed in
the profanity-littered argot of New Jersey hoodlums? ``The
Sopranos'' is often funny, but the laughter it elicits doesn't come
from one-liners but from a deeper recognition of the screaming
little baby inside every grown-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' more than any American television in memory,
looks, feels and sounds like real life. Watch any episode and
you're likely to come away with the queasy feeling of having
consumed a greasy slice of late-90s America with its surreal
mixture of prosperity and brutishness.
</P>
<P>
   Tony, a northern New Jersey mob boss in his early 40s, isn't an
exotic evil king holed up in a fortified stone castle. He is a
middle-class family man who, except for his occupation, is pretty
much like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' sustains its hyper-realism with an eye and ear
so perfectly attuned to geographic details and cultural and social
nuances that it just may be the greatest work of American popular
culture of the last quarter century.
</P>
<P>
   It was 25 years ago that the second of Francis Ford Coppola's
``Godfather'' movies was released. Together with its 1972
forerunner, it brought a new and deeper strain of tragic realism
into American culture. ``The Sopranos'' carries ``The Godfather's''
epic themes into the present, turning tragedy into comedy and vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   This show's greatness lies in its creation of at least a dozen
indelible characters whom we come to know as intimately as our best
friends. At the center looms James Gandolfini's Tony, a huggable
hairy-shouldered grizzly bear of a man who cherishes his family,
watches the History Channel and blows off steam by pumping iron in
the basement of his fancy New Jersey home.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the blue one day, Tony begins suffering devastating panic
attacks. When it's discovered there's nothing physically wrong with
him, he begins seeing Dr. Jennifer Melfi (Lorraine Bracco), a local
psychiatrist recommended by the doctor who lives next door.
</P>
<P>
   There are essentially two Tonys. One is a mobster involved in
theft, loan-sharking, drugs and corrupt unions. This Tony takes
brutal pleasure in beating up and killing people who cross him. The
other Tony is a straitlaced family man who frets that his two
teen-age children have discovered he isn't really in ``waste
management,'' as he claims.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Tony who flares up when his daughter mentions sex at
the dinner table and announces that in his house it is still 1954.
Yet this devoted family man is also part owner of a topless bar and
has a girlfriend who is a Russian prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal Tony and the righteous Tony become grotesquely
connected after a soccer coach in his daughter's high school
impregnates one of her friends. The moralistic Tony goes ballistic.
The criminal Tony considers enlisting his cronies to carry out a
savage act of vigilante justice.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Marchand's Livia is as duplicitous and complicated as her
son. This 70-year-old termagant, who may or may not be suffering
from early-stage Alzheimer's, turns on Tony after he moves her out
of her house (for her own protection) to a luxurious retirement
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Livia, whose bitterness goes bone-deep, sees her son's
generosity as an unforgivable betrayal. Tony, she announces, has
dumped her into a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gandolfini and Ms. Marchand, Edie Falco (as Tony's loyal,
sharp-tongued wife, Carmela), Ms. Bracco and Michael Imperioli (as
Christopher Moltisanti, Tony's dumb, hotheaded nephew, who itches
to be a ``made'' member of the Mafia) have the roles of a lifetime
in the series.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, ``The Sopranos,'' rather than the wobbly,
histrionic ``Godfather, Part 3,'' is the real sequel to Coppola's
early-70s masterpieces, which made the modern Mafia a dark metaphor
for the immigrant experience and upward mobility in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' pays overt homage to the ``Godfather'' movies
with dramatic techniques like crosscutting between scenes of
extreme violence and domestic warmth, and interspersing the
narrative with semihallucinatory flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The thugs, especially Christopher, are so entranced with the
mystique of the ``Godfather'' movies that they quote (and sometimes
misquote) its dialogue. Christopher desperately aspires to the
imperial glamour of Marlon Brando and Al Pacino, and one episode
finds him working on an inept screenplay about mob life and
fantasizing a Hollywood career as a writer and actor.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as it owes to ``The Godfather,'' ``The Sopranos''
also refutes the towering solemnity of the Coppola films. Tony and
his pals have none of the royal demeanor of ``The Godfather's''
kingpins. Most are crude, bigoted, semiliterate boors who seem out
of place in the contemporary world.
</P>
<P>
   The underworld in ``The Sopranos'' is strictly small potatoes,
and it's fading. Tony, who's smarter than his colleagues,
recognizes that this seamy little world with its grim code of
loyalty is obsolescent. The Corleones in ``The Godfather'' were
made of sterner stuff. Even in their worst moments, they wouldn't
dream of taking their anxieties to a shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the finest scenes in ``The Sopranos'' take place in Dr.
Melfi's office. Ms. Bracco's coolheaded psychiatrist drops all the
right buzzwords, prodding her client toward insights into his
childhood and his relationship with his parents, and dispensing
Prozac and Lithium when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Her give-and-take with Tony may be the most realistic depiction
of psychotherapy ever depicted in a mainstream movie or television
show. Tony even develops a classic case of transference (drawn out
in eerie, erotic dream sequences) in which he briefly imagines he's
in love with Dr. Melfi.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Sopranos'' ultimately demystifies psychotherapy as
much as it demystifies the world of ``The Godfather.''
Psychotherapy proves useful for Tony, but it hasn't the slightest
impact on his criminal character.
</P>
<P>
   In forcing us to empathize with a thug whom we watch committing
heinous acts, ``The Sopranos'' evokes a profound moral ambiguity.
One of the series' most haunting moments finds Tony's teen-age
daughter, Meadow, crouched on the stairs furtively watching her
parents remove guns and cash from a hiding place in preparation for
an imminent raid by federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   How does a nice middle-class teen-ager deal with the fact that
her adored father is a thief and a killer? In the series' most
poignant moment, she bluntly inquires, ``Dad, are you in the
Mafia?'' during a car trip to Maine, where she and Tony are
visiting colleges. Tony fudges a response that she takes as
confirmation, and shortly afterward slips off to murder an FBI
informant he happens to see at a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' walks a fine line. As much as it banalizes its
mobsters, it refuses to trivialize their viciousness. Tony's
brutality is all the more disturbing because it erupts from within
a social framework of apparent normalcy. That framework includes a
devout young priest, who like Dr. Melfi, smoothly sidesteps the
deeper moral issues of Tony's life.
</P>
<P>
   The closest he comes to admitting evil is during a therapy
session in which he offers the lame excuse that what he does is no
worse than a businessman illegally dumping toxic waste. Isn't that
how we all get by without tearing ourselves to pieces? All values
are relative, aren't they? And besides the other guy is worse. As
Tony Soprano would put it in his best macho swagger, ``You do what
you gotta do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
