<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8955 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERRILL-ONLINE-2NDTAK     06-01 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERRILL-ONLINE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: their client.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since much of the trading at online brokerages represents an
increase in activity, traditional firms are not seeing declines in
their business. But their growth is far slower than that of firms
like Schwab and E(STAR)Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Solotar, a brokerage stock analyst at Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, said, ``Online trading raises a new threat, but the
retail brokerage business is still extraordinarily profitable.''
Even so, she said Merrill was risking some medium-term profits to
increase its growth rate. As customers move from full commission to
the discount program, she predicted that Merrill's profits could be
cut by as much as 10 percent in two years.
</P>
<P>
   And she expressed skepticism that people would choose Merrill
simply as a discount broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most likely, the Merrill Lynch client will continue to use the
services of a financial consultant, but they may also decide to do
some trading online,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the full-service brokers, including Merrill, are hoping
that Internet trading will shift clients from per-trade commissions
to flat annual fees. They have been offering these so-called wrap
accounts for more than a decade, but the appeal has been limited.
For example, only 2 percent of Merrill's customers use its previous
flat-fee account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to see this as the beginning of the death knell
of transaction pricing,'' Komansky said. ``It will eliminate the
last vestiges of the perception that there exists a conflict
between the client and the broker. Under the new structure, the
broker will get compensated the same for saying, `No, don't do
that,' as for executing a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Solotar, the analyst, said she did not have high hopes
for the flat-fee account, because ``the fee-based accounts are very
profitable for Merrill, but unless you are a very active trader
they don't make much sense for the client.''
</P>
<P>
   Though analysts said Merrill's entry might also cause trouble
for discount brokerages, David Pottruck, co-chief executive of
Schwab, said he was not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Merrill Lynch dropping their prices to match
Schwab is an endorsement of our value in the marketplace,''
Pottruck said. ``We've been competing successfully with
lower-priced discount brokers for years. Now we are competing with
a very large new discount broker that has the same price we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has been moving to differentiate itself from cheaper
competitors, like E(STAR)Trade, by offering more advice. Currently
its telephone service representatives will recommend which mutual
funds clients should buy. Within a year, Pottruck said, it will
make buy and sell picks for individual stocks as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cotsakos of E(STAR)Trade was similarly dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are late to the party, and there is nothing new here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   What was new with E(STAR)Trade Tuesday was a $1.8 billion
acquisition of Telebanc Financial Corp., which offers banking over
the telephone and the Internet. Cotsakos said the company hopes to
combine Telebank's deposit products with its own brokerage service
to create a one-stop online financial marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The price is astoundingly high by traditional measures.
E(STAR)Trade is paying some $25,000 for each of Telebank's 70,000
customers. That's more than the average customer has on deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Cotsakos said that since E(STAR)Trade's stock is even more
highly valued than Telebank's stock, the deal will nonetheless
increase the company's earnings per share. Moreover, he said that
the principal purpose of the acquisition was to gain access to
products that E(STAR)Trade can sell to its existing customers.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham agreed that the deal is sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't justify this on the ground of the accounts
E(STAR)Trade acquired,'' he said. ``What they got was a nine-month
head start in brining banking products to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage executives, however, expressed skepticism that banking
products would produce much value for E(STAR)Trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classic banking business that serves the mass market is
not a very good business,'' said Pottruck of Schwab. ``The margins
are small and it earns a low PE ratio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
