<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8958 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MERRILL-ONLINE-ART-     06-01 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MERRILL-ONLINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH, BENDING TO THE TIMES, TO PROVIDE ONLINE TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(Eds: Note that the word STAR within parentheses has been used in
the 13th graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to
many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch, which grew to be the nation's top
retail brokerage house through an army of 14,000 stock brokers
mixing advice with salesmanship, bent to the pressures of online
competition Tuesday, announcing that it would add a low-cost
service for people who want to trade on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Like leading firms in many industries, Merrill has been
struggling to find a way to compete with cheaper online upstarts.
From bookstores to travel agencies, companies must decide how much
to risk their existing large and profitable businesses in order to
do battle with small, money-losing but rapidly growing Internet
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Merrill held the line, arguing that customers would
be willing to pay its higher fees in return for superior service
and in-depth analysis. But ultimately it decided that Internet
trading was neither a fad nor a small segment of the market.
Indeed, now one in every seven stock trades in the United States is
performed over the Internet, according to Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in September, Merrill, which now typically charges $80
to $100 for an average trade, will let customers trade online for
$29.95, matching Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the largest brokerage firm
on the Internet. But those customers will not get access to
research or guidance from a broker. Alternately, customers can pay
an annual fee of at least $1,500 for unlimited free trading and
advice, either online or through a broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see just by observing the growth of Schwab's asset
base that there was a segment of the market that wants to use
technology and only technology,'' said David Komansky, the chairman
of Merrill. ``And it became clear to us we had to disaggregate our
services and price competitively.''
</P>
<P>
   While a few of the other traditional full-service brokerage
firms have introduced online trading in one form or another,
analysts say that most of them will have to go much further to
match Merrill, along with Schwab and the online brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts a lot of pressure on other full-service firms to
respond in kind,'' said Bill Burnham, an electronic-commerce
analyst at Credit Suisse. ``Merrill is two years late to the game
but you have to hand it to them, they didn't get half pregnant.
They looked at Schwab and said if you can't beat them, join them.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has gone beyond what the other full-service brokers have
done and invited its clients to have both full-service accounts and
discount Internet trading accounts at the same time, with trades
from all of them reported on one statement. There are two other
full-service firms with low-cost Internet units, Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, but they have separated
their Internet units from their full-service operations.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill considered a separate Internet unit as well, but decided
it needed to reach out to its existing customers because an
increasing number of them had already opened a separate account to
try online trading on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it will be the rule that people use multiple
forms of accounts with us,'' said Komansky.
</P>
<P>
   A few other full-service firms, like Prudential Securities,
offer Internet trading, but only as part of the more expensive
flat-fee accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest losers from all of this may not be the brokerage
firms but the brokers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about E-trade saying, `Boot your broker,''' said
Christos Cotsakos, the chairman of E(STAR)Trade group, a big online
broker. ``This is Merrill booting their own brokers.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill argues that while some brokers may lose business in the
short run, the move is necessary to attract a new generation of
clients for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run this makes their life easier, but I'm certain
as we speak many of them have apprehensions,'' Komansky said. The
brokers, he said, ``will still do very well so long as they are
willing to provide value added for their client.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Since much of the trading at online brokerages represents an
increase in activity, traditional firms are not seeing declines in
their business. But their growth is far slower than that of firms
like Schwab and E(STAR)Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Solotar, a brokerage stock analyst at Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, said, ``Online trading raises a new threat, but the
retail brokerage business is still extraordinarily profitable.''
Even so, she said Merrill was risking some medium-term profits to
increase its growth rate. As customers move from full commission to
the discount program, she predicted that Merrill's profits could be
cut by as much as 10 percent in two years.
</P>
<P>
   And she expressed skepticism that people would choose Merrill
simply as a discount broker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most likely, the Merrill Lynch client will continue to use the
services of a financial consultant, but they may also decide to do
some trading online,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the full-service brokers, including Merrill, are hoping
that Internet trading will shift clients from per-trade commissions
to flat annual fees. They have been offering these so-called wrap
accounts for more than a decade, but the appeal has been limited.
For example, only 2 percent of Merrill's customers use its previous
flat-fee account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to see this as the beginning of the death knell
of transaction pricing,'' Komansky said. ``It will eliminate the
last vestiges of the perception that there exists a conflict
between the client and the broker. Under the new structure, the
broker will get compensated the same for saying, `No, don't do
that,' as for executing a trade.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Solotar, the analyst, said she did not have high hopes
for the flat-fee account, because ``the fee-based accounts are very
profitable for Merrill, but unless you are a very active trader
they don't make much sense for the client.''
</P>
<P>
   Though analysts said Merrill's entry might also cause trouble
for discount brokerages, David Pottruck, co-chief executive of
Schwab, said he was not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Merrill Lynch dropping their prices to match
Schwab is an endorsement of our value in the marketplace,''
Pottruck said. ``We've been competing successfully with
lower-priced discount brokers for years. Now we are competing with
a very large new discount broker that has the same price we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab has been moving to differentiate itself from cheaper
competitors, like E(STAR)Trade, by offering more advice. Currently
its telephone service representatives will recommend which mutual
funds clients should buy. Within a year, Pottruck said, it will
make buy and sell picks for individual stocks as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cotsakos of E(STAR)Trade was similarly dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are late to the party, and there is nothing new here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   What was new with E(STAR)Trade Tuesday was a $1.8 billion
acquisition of Telebanc Financial Corp., which offers banking over
the telephone and the Internet. Cotsakos said the company hopes to
combine Telebank's deposit products with its own brokerage service
to create a one-stop online financial marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The price is astoundingly high by traditional measures.
E(STAR)Trade is paying some $25,000 for each of Telebank's 70,000
customers. That's more than the average customer has on deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Cotsakos said that since E(STAR)Trade's stock is even more
highly valued than Telebank's stock, the deal will nonetheless
increase the company's earnings per share. Moreover, he said that
the principal purpose of the acquisition was to gain access to
products that E(STAR)Trade can sell to its existing customers.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham agreed that the deal is sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't justify this on the ground of the accounts
E(STAR)Trade acquired,'' he said. ``What they got was a nine-month
head start in brining banking products to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage executives, however, expressed skepticism that banking
products would produce much value for E(STAR)Trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classic banking business that serves the mass market is
not a very good business,'' said Pottruck of Schwab. ``The margins
are small and it earns a low PE ratio.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
