A8964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEIGHT-LOSS-DRUG-ART-     06-01 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIGHT-LOSS-DRUG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DIET DRUG SELLS WELL, BUT IT DIDN'T SET A RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After one month on the market, the diet drug Xenical, made by
Hoffmann-La Roche, will not go down as the most successful new
pharmaceutical in history, but analysts remain confident that it
will become a best seller.
</P>
<P>
   Xenical, which the Food and Drug Administration approved in late
April, accounted for 96,485 prescriptions during its first four
weeks on the market. By contrast, Viagra, Pfizer's impotency pill,
and Celebrex, Monsanto's arthritis drug, had prescriptions in their
first months of 367,857 and 150,113, respectively, according to IMS
Health, an industry consultant. The introductions of Viagra and
Celebrex were two of the most successful in pharmaceutical history.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Xenical did not topple Viagra, analysts insist that
its first weeks of sales are stellar, allowing it to build momentum
as more doctors become comfortable with how it works.
</P>
<P>
   After Xenical was introduced, the drug received much fanfare as
a fad drug. Analysts now expect sales to increase as Hoffmann-La
Roche combats the fad image by telling doctors about the drug's
therapeutic advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that momentum for Xenical not peak too early,''
said Viren Mehta, a partner at Mehta Partners, a biopharmaceutical
research firm. ``You want to have an educated group of physicians
about the drug. Hoffmann-La Roche has studies under way that point
out the science of the drug.''
</P>
<P>
   From its first week on the market, Xenical has sparked
controversy. A new kind of drug, it blocks the body's absorption of
dietary fat. Despite its new mechanism, Xenical brought
recollections of fen-phen, a weight-loss drug cocktail that was
removed from the market in 1997 over concerns that it caused heart
valve damage.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to that worry, critics noted that many patients who used
Xenical lost modest amounts of weight _ typically 5 percent to 10
percent of their body weight _ and risked some messy side effects,
including fecal incontinence, if they did not reduce their fat
intake.
</P>
<P>
   Xenical's case was further hurt by an immediate Internet market,
similar to the universal cyberspace availability of Viagra and
Propecia, Merck's hair loss pill. To overcome this shady beginning,
Hoffmann-La Roche has not offered Xenical samples to doctors.
</P>
<P>
   While some doctors remain critical of Xenical _ dismissing it
because it produces a loss of modest amounts of weight _ others are
becoming avid fans. Hoffmann-La Roche has 2,000 sales
representatives peddling the drug, and their message is apparently
taking hold in some hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Xenical in treating obesity, it is important to
note that it does something that other diet drugs don't do,'' said
Dr. Louis Aronne, director of the Comprehensive Weight Control
Program at New York Hospital. ``You can use it to treat obese
people and not worry about it causing cardiovascular side effects.
A lot of obese patients have cardiovascular risks.''
</P>
<P>
   To promote Xenical's benefits further, Hoffmann-La Roche expects
to begin advertising it directly to consumers sometime in the third
quarter of 1999. The ads are expected to loft sales of Xenical,
which most analysts expect to hit $750 million to $1 billion at
their peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sales will be erratic,'' said Neil Sweig, an analyst with
Southeast Research Partners. ``But that's the market. People who
take this type of drug are never satisfied. They want the easy way
out to lose weight. In this market, there is not any loyalty
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
