<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-WIESEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIESEL TOURS REFUGEE CAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEGRANE, Macedonia _ Elie Wiesel, the Holocaust survivor and
Nobel winner, began a three-day tour of refugee camps on Tuesday at
the request of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the visit was designed to focus
attention on the moral argument that they say underpins NATO's
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia. Wiesel has spoken of the
Biblical injunction ``to not stand idly by.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiesel's visit to Macedonia, and later to Albania, stood in
contrast to the routine of congressmen, European diplomats and
celebrities briefly touring refugee camps for a momentary taste of
suffering. Spending three hours in the blistering sun engaging
refugees in simple but telling conversations, Wiesel, a professor
and moral philosopher, made an impassioned call for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not allow winter to set in here,'' he said as he
surveyed the sprawling camp that holds 40,000 refugees. ``We must
end this.'' But Wiesel found himself, like the administration,
citing a moral imperative to resist President Slobodan Milosevic,
while shying away from asking to intensify the war with a ground
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a military expert,'' he said. ``I can't make
statements about air power versus ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit received only spotty coverage from American news
organizations. Of the four major networks, only CNN did a piece on
Wiesel's visit. American officials said fading interest in the
Kosovo story is complicating their efforts to build a strong public
consensus on military action.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Reeker, a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy here, said
``People have lost focus on why we are doing what we are doing. You
need a person like Wiesel to keep your moral philosophy on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Macedonia Wiesel blazed a trail like few other visiting
dignitaries. While other delegations have traveled in long convoys
of armored Chevrolet Suburbans, Wiesel traveled in an ordinary
white van. His entourage, excluding aides sent by the
administration, consisted of a single friend. And instead of
engaging refugees in innocuous conversation, Wiesel, 70, asked
piercing questions, while refusing to compare what was happening in
Kosovo with the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in drawing analogies,'' he said. ``There were
no camps to receive us.''
</P>
<P>
   But he painstakingly elicited testimony from refugees about
atrocities they witnessed. He urged teachers to encourage their
students to write their tales, predicting that a great book
chronicling the exodus would be written one day by someone now
living in the camp.
</P>
<P>
   He asked one parent what he did to lull his traumatized young
children to sleep at night. ``Do you tell them stories? Do you sing
them lullabies?'' The man said he recited ``stories about home.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiesel, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1986, stopped Barije
Redinica, 16, as she walked by in the camp. ``Tell me, what do you
think of when you wake up in the morning?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That I will go home,'' Ms. Redinica said.
</P>
<P>
   After another refugee, Besim Piraj, described watching Serb
soldiers kill some of his acquaintances from his village in Kosovo,
Wiesel asked, ``What do you think of human beings who do that?''
Piraj said he believed no one ``who had a spirit'' could do such a
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Wiesel later said that he believed those who commit atrocities
are not sadists, but men who so completely rationalize their
actions that they believe they are doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   While avoiding specifics, he called for action in Kosovo. He
said that he saw life as a series of pivotal moments, and that the
refugee crisis is one of those moments.
</P>
<P>
   For Americans, he said, Kosovo is a ``moral war'' that
challenges its moral character.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging over Wiesel's visit was the phrase ``never again'' and
the nagging question of whether anything had changed 50 years after
the Holocaust. Wiesel insisted it had, saying Washington's response
in Kosovo was far better than the ambivalence it showed during the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Washington's action in Kosovo should have come far
earlier. If the West had moved against Milosevic a decade ago, he
said, the tragedy in Kosovo would have been prevented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have foreseen Kosovo,'' he said. ``Why didn't we?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
