A8972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-COMMERCE-BOS &LR;      06-01 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-COMMERCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH BULLISH ON NET; ETRADE BUYS BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as one of the financial world's old-line stalwarts took a
bold step into the future, a next-generation investment firm made
one leap further.
</P>
<P>
   The nascent battle for control over the money world's new
frontier, the Internet, heated up Tuesday, as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
the nation's largest stock brokerage, said it would offer on-line
trading, and ETrade Group Inc., an Internet brokerage, announced it
was expanding into Web-based banking.
</P>
<P>
   Both moves reflect warp-speed changes in the financial services
world. Traditional money management companies are racing to decide
how they will adapt to the rise of electronic commerce, while hot
new firms, some simply virtual shops in cyberspace, are working to
build Web-based financial empires.
</P>
<P>
   Both moves are likely to spark similar changes at other
brokerages and banks, both mainstream and new-fangled. And both
moves underscore the drive among banks, brokerages, mutual fund
firms, and insurers to become all things to all customers by
offering ``one-stop'' financial shopping with a variety of products
and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a paradigm shift with the individual
investor,'' said Harvard Business School professor Samuel Hayes,
referring to the rise of an investing culture in which individuals
want to trade stocks and conduct other financial business on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``As consumers change, both banks and brokerages are having to
change their spots,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Merrill Lynch, the epitome of traditional,
old-world stockbroking, will offer its clients full on-line trading
beginning in December. The giant, which had dismissed Web traders
barely a year ago as a reckless aberration, now acknowledges it
cannot afford to ignore the fact that one in four retail stock
trades is now made on line.
</P>
<P>
   Matching the low costs pioneered by Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the
nation's largest discount brokerage, Merrill will let its 5 million
customers buy or sell securities over the Internet for $29.95 a
trade. Alternatively, clients can pay a flat annual fee of $1,500
for unlimited trading. Merrill said it would also create an account
that would permit checking, savings, and investment activities
through the Internet, all with one monthly statement.
</P>
<P>
   The move portends a different world for Merrill's 16,000
wing-tipped, suspendered stockbrokers, who routinely earn
triple-digit commissions for each trade they execute. Now the
company's brokers will become more like modern financial advisers,
who are compensated on the basis of a client's investment returns,
and not on trading commissions. Merrill Lynch fell 8 3/4 to close
at 75 1/4 Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers wonder whether Merrill isn't moving too late.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Farkas, head of global financial services at consulting
firm Bain &AMP; Co., called the brokerage's announcement ``defensive, a
`me, too' move'' that follows, rather than preempts, the growth of
rival Web-based brokerages, which have captured a significant
amount of the on-line trading market in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be caught short as mainline money management houses turn
to the Internet, ETrade, the nation's second largest on-line
brokerage, will pay $1.8 billion in stock for TeleBanc Financial
Corp. of Arlington, Va., a Web-only bank with 11,000 accounts and
$2.6 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   ETrade's idea is to sell loans, credit cards, checking accounts,
and other traditional banking services over the Web, all through a
cash management account insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. Palo Alto, Calif.-based ETrade paid a 40 percent premium to
TeleBanc's closing price on Friday, a measure of how much the
successful on-line brokerage wants to be the nation's first virtual
financial services shop.
</P>
<P>
   While some traditional banks, like BankBoston Corp., have forged
ahead with successful on-line banking services, Internet-only banks
are a novel and unproven concept. There are barely a half-dozen
such banks that are FDIC-insured. The idea behind Web-only banks,
which compete by offering checking accounts earning more interest
than those at traditional banks, is that costs are lower because
they have bare-bones staffing levels and no branches or ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``ETrade's deal is the first shot in the battle to control
on-line banking,'' said e-commerce analyst Bill Burnham of Credit
Suisse First Boston. ``This will put the fear of God in traditional
banks, which are seeing barbarians at the gate.'' CSFB estimates
the number of on-line banking accounts rising to 9 million by 2000,
up from 5.5 million in 1998, and 2 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While ETrade's acquisition of Telebanc is the first leap by an
on-line brokerage into Web-based banking, it is also a strange echo
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, ETrade is doing what Merrill Lynch did in the
1970s, when it revolutionized personal finance by introducing its
Cash Management Account, which allows clients to write checks,
charge purchases, manage investments, and conduct business via one
account.
</P>
<P>
   Other investment firms, notably Boston-based Fidelity
Investments, the nation's biggest mutual fund firm, have similar
products. But unlike ETrade and TeleBanc, most one-stop financial
providers still have a physical place of business to which a
customer can turn.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is impressed by ETrade's move, which is designed to
keep the firm in business as the pace of growth in on-line trading
slows. Boston-based Forrester Research Inc. said Tuesday that the
on-line brokerage was ``entering a no-man's land,'' in which
customers willing to bank on line still want a traditional
bricks-and-mortar bank behind their Web-based accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most consumers want a physical presence for making deposits
and getting cash,'' Forrester analyst James P. Punishill wrote in a
recent note. ETrade slipped 5 3/16 Tuesday to close at 39 5/16,
while shares in Telebanc rose 8 to close at 74 1/2, both on Nasdaq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
