<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA: A TRADITION OF BASHING TRADITION  
 FLORIDA: TERM-LIMITS CROONERS ARE CHANGING TUNES  
 UTAH: GOP FROZEN AS HATCH WEIGHS RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1996, Louisiana Republicans ignored the national party's
tradition of letting Iowa hold the first presidential caucuses and
scheduled Louisiana's caucuses first instead. The intent was to
grab some national attention for the Louisiana GOP, which like many
Republican Parties in the South was on the move. But the attention
gained was not what the party had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the cutting in front cause interstate party strife,
but the caucuses were a bust. Most major candidates ignored them,
lest they be punished later by Iowa voters, and the 20,000 voters
who took part ended up standing in line for hours because there
were only 42 caucus sites.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Louisiana GOP is talking about voting first again come
Election 2000, perhaps as early as Jan. 29, even if such an advance
date again causes party strife and leads many candidates to shy
away. (There is some thought about holding a primary rather than
caucuses, and thus taking on New Hampshire, which traditionally
holds the first presidential primary.)
</P>
<P>
   But whatever and wherever the possible interstate strife,
Louisiana party leaders hope in the early voting of Election 2000
to head off the bothersome delays that plagued the early voting of
Election 1996. How?
</P>
<P>
   The party's state Executive Committee has recommended that next
year's first-in-the-nation balloting be via the Internet, which in
itself would be a first in the nation. Party officials have
contacted computer and Internet specialists about ways to proceed,
including what steps to take to prevent voting fraud and how to
provide Internet access to party members who do not own computers.
</P>
<P>
   One possible access answer: Party members who own computers
could volunteer as ``block hosts'' and allow their homes or offices
to be designated official voting sites.
</P>
<P>
   Will it work?
</P>
<P>
   Like a number of top party members, State Rep. Charles D.
Lancaster Jr. of Metairie wants to give Internet voting a try.
``This is the best idea that I've seen in a couple of years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of other party members have serious doubts.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. John L. Dardenne Jr. of Baton Rouge calls the
proposal ``www.bad-idea.com.''
</P>
<P>
   A final vote on the proposal will be taken by the party's State
Central Committee on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   TERM-LIMITS CROONERS ARE CHANGING TUNES
</P>
<P>
   Tillie Fowler was a champion of term limits when she served on
the City Council of Jacksonville, Fla., in the 1980s, proclaiming
often that no one should serve in the same public office longer
than eight years. Good as her word, when her eight years on the
council were up, in 1992, she ran for the House of Representatives,
proclaiming that she would serve there only four terms. ``Eight is
Enough'' was her campaign mantra.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of representing Florida's 4th Congressional
District, Ms. Fowler, a popular conservative Republican, is having
some second thoughts _ to the delight of Republican leaders, the
despair of Democratic leaders and the disgust of leaders of the
term-limits lobby.
</P>
<P>
   She is not alone in this. Half a dozen or so other members of
Congress who made similar promises are also wavering. And in any
event, she says she will not make a final decision until the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   But in the for-what-it's-worth department, the other day she
filed a finance report with the Federal Election Commission, as
required by law, that showed she had taken in almost $500,000 in
campaign contributions from people who would like her to seek a
fifth term. She said she had not solicited a cent of the money and
therefore, she insisted, her political future was a ``nonissue'' at
this point.
</P>
<P>
   All of which led Paul Jacobs, the executive director of U.S.
Term Limits, an advocacy group, to comment:
</P>
<P>
   ``It leaves one wondering if anyone in Washington could even
define honesty, much less live by it.''
</P>
<P>
   UTAH GOP FROZEN AS HATCH WEIGHS RUN
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, asked fellow
Republican leaders in the state not to endorse any Republican
presidential hopeful until he had decided whether to become one of
those hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he says he has not made up his mind. But under quiet
pressure from those fellow Republicans, many of them supporters of
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, he says he is about to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a long shot,'' Hatch told The Deseret News of Salt
Lake City last week. ``So if I do, it won't be an ego thing. I'd be
running because I'm worried about the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk in some Republican circles in Utah is that what Hatch
may have in mind is a favorite son candidacy, which might increase
his influence at the Republican National Convention, might spark
speculation about his vice-presidential potential and, at a
minimum, might give him a nice political boost going into a Senate
re-election campaign next year.
</P>
<P>
   His view of Bush?
</P>
<P>
   Hatch says he will probably support him if does not run himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
