<HEADLINE>
NORTHWEST'S PROBLEMS WITH DWINDLING SALMON HEAD NORTH TO B.C. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Threats to salmon runs along the coast of
British Columbia, particularly in fast-growing areas, have become
so severe they mirror those of the Pacific Northwest, a symposium
on Pacific fish habitat heard Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While millions of sockeye salmon still swim far up the Fraser
River, other runs are rapidly declining as Canada's last frontier
is paved, subdivided, logged and farmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of urgency is greater in the Pacific Northwest than
it is here... But it is coming here,'' said John Fraser, a former
Canadian cabinet minister who is chairman of the newly created
Pacific Fisheries Resource Conservation Council. ``We've got to be
part of your solution,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The habitat conference in Vancouver, B.C., came as United States
and Canadian negotiators have privately reported progress in
breaking the five-year impasse over renewal of a fisheries treaty
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse has produced rare confrontations, notably the 1997
blockade of the Alaska ferry Malaspina by British Columbia
fishermen angry over Alaskans catching salmon bound for Canadian
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Even if an accord is reached, however, Canada will need help in
solving a multiplicity of problems, many of its own making.
Fisheries enforcement is underfunded. Inadequate research has left
large gaps in knowledge of the condition of salmon runs,
particularly on British Columbia's central coast.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Puget Sound area, where governments at all levels are
working together to address the recent endangered species listing
of chinook salmon, Canada's national government and the government
of British Columbia have engaged in a prolonged, vicious feud.
</P>
<P>
   B.C. Premier Glen Clark has accused the federal government of
making ``treasonous'' concessions to the United States. Canadian
fisheries minister David Anderson has cut the provincial government
out of any role in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, Canada and British Columbia, get together! It is our
last chance to protect habitat,'' said Vicky Husband, a leader of
the Sierra Club of British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   One major problem is shared by the two countries. The rapid
urbanization of Puget Sound, lower Vancouver Island and the lower
Fraser River valley has wiped out salmon streams on both sides of
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Two million people now live in the lower Fraser Valley.
``Twenty-eight percent of all salmon streams have simply
disappeared,'' said Otto Langer, chief habitat expert for Fisheries
and Oceans Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of alarm bells should be going off,'' Langer said. ``The
future seems to be one of urban sprawl all the way from Olympia to
Hope.'' (Hope is a town at the mouth of the Fraser River Canyon,
about 100 miles east of Vancouver.)
</P>
<P>
   Problems outlined with British Columbia's salmon runs include:
</P>
<P>
   _Vanishing coho: Recently caught by the millions, coho salmon
now are imperiled in all major British Columbia river systems. The
near-extinction of coho in the Fraser and Thompson rivers led to
severe fishing restrictions last year.
</P>
<P>
   _Signs of Sockeye decline: Sockeye will be abundant this summer
in the Chilko and Horsefly rivers, tributaries of the Fraser.
Elsewhere the picture is not so clear.
</P>
<P>
   A once-enormous sockeye run in Rivers Inlet along the coast has
vanished. The inlet has been heavily logged, but there have also
been indications of high mortality at sea.
</P>
<P>
   _Subdivisions along streams: The lower Fraser valley may have as
many as 4 million people by 2020. As it grows, guidelines for
protecting streams are widely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The development footprint in the lower Fraser valley has left
a devastating impact on most streams, many of which historically
supported, and some of which still support, viable salmon
populations,'' said a report from Fisheries and Oceans Canada.
</P>
<P>
   _The suffering Skeena: The Skeena River, in northern British
Columbia, has been the second most productive salmon stream on
Canada's west coast. But it is suffering. In trying to rebuild the
river, fisheries officials would like to see 1 million salmon
escape up the Skeena to spawn this year.
</P>
<P>
   But only about 600,000 fish will even approach the river, and
some will be caught in Alaskan waters north of Prince Rupert. The
Alaska catch is a major point of tension between the United States
and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Just north of the Skeena, Southeast Alaska's salmon fishery is
booming. Southeast Alaska-based fishing boats will take an
estimated 3 million sockeye this year. ``We're sitting pretty,''
according to a slide shown Tuesday by Alaska's Department of Fish
and Game.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Valentine, British Columbia's deputy fisheries minister,
took a pointed shot at Alaska. He blamed ``distant interception''
for problems in watersheds ranging from the Skeena south to the
Columbia River in Washington and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Canada has taken decisive measures, particularly in the last
year. It has imposed extensive restrictions on fisheries. Unlike
agencies in the United States, however, Fisheries and Oceans Canada
lacks the money even to monitor fish runs in remote places. A
U.S.-financed aid package is one of the rumored provisions of a
fish deal.
</P>
<P>
   Some 13,000 people have left British Columbia's fisheries
industry in the past half-decade. The mood at the conference
Tuesday was to endure additional cuts if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we swallow the bitter pill now and make the sacrifices
necessary to assure the long-term recovery of salmon?'' asked Arnie
Narcisse, co-chair of the BC Aboriginal Fisheries Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bitter pill in a place once used to resources that never
ran out. Iona Campagnolo, another former Canadian Cabinet minister
who led Tuesday's symposium, closed by observing: ``The rules under
which we've operated were written for few people exploiting an
abundant planet. Now we have many people and a seemingly tiny
planet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
