<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-WNBA-BOS &LR;      06-01 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WNBA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA STAYING OUT OF NEW ENGLAND FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Professional women's basketball will not be returning to New
England _ not in the near future, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's National Basketball Association Tuesday said that
neither Boston nor Hartford is among the cities being considered
for expansion when the league grows from 12 to 16 teams in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA teams are owned by and operated in conjunction with the 29
NBA franchises. The Celtics did not apply for a WNBA franchise, and
Hartford is out of the running because it has no NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   Celtics spokesman Jeff Twiss said the club opted not to seek a
women's team in order to focus on getting the men's team back on
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had thought about it, but we are concentrating our focus on
getting the men's basketball team back to the championships,'' he
said. ``So before we add the WNBA, let's focus on getting down to
the playoff hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartford, on the other hand, does want a team but is being
denied. The city was home to the New England Blizzard, a top
attendance draw in the rival ABL, which folded last December.
Officials there have been courting the WNBA ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed that the Celtics didn't even apply, and they
could play some of the games here, '' Connecticut Lt. Gov. Jodi
Rell said Tuesday. ``But I'm most disappointed that the WNBA
doesn't change its policy.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not bound to happen, WNBA president Val Ackerman said in
a telephone news conference last week. ``We're mindful of the
interest we've seen for women's pro basketball in non-NBA cities,
particularly in some of the college hotbeds,'' she said. ``At this
point for us the model we have now is too compelling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
