<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8977 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COWARD-THEATER-$ADV06     06-01 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWARD-THEATER-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWIGGY AND NOEL COWARD TAKE ONE MORE TURN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Matthew Gurewitsch writes about the arts for The Wall Street
Journal and other publications.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   His name notwithstanding, he missed being born on Christmas by
more than a week. His name notwithstanding, he was a brave man,
brave enough to fire off epigrams for the West End in London in the
wake of Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   The world has not forgotten Noel Coward (eventually Sir Noel),
playwright of ``Hay Fever'' and ``Private Lives,''
composer-lyricist of ``Mad About the Boy'' and ``Mad Dogs and
Englishmen,'' unmatched interpreter of his own mischief.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan Morley, the London theater critic for The Spectator and
Playbill, summed up Coward's genius in the title of his biography,
the first: ``A Talent to Amuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Coward died in 1973. Were he alive, he would be celebrating his
100th birthday on Dec. 16. One of many observances on either shore
of the Atlantic this centennial year, Morley's Off Broadway
valentine, ``If Love Were All,'' opens on Thursday at the Lucille
Lortel Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The show strings a score of Coward tunes on a thread of Coward's
reminiscences about his muse and co-star, Gertrude Lawrence.
Included are scenes from the plays he wrote with her in mind,
notably ``Private Lives,'' with which the squabbling lovebirds
Amanda and Elyot kept London and Depression-era New York in
stitches.
</P>
<P>
   By this time in their early 30s, Noel and Gertie had been fast
friends for more than half their lives. They met in Euston Station,
London, child actors en route to an engagement in Liverpool.
</P>
<P>
   ``She confided to me that her name was Gertrude Lawrence,''
Coward later wrote, ``but that I should call her Gertie because
everybody did. She then gave me an orange, told me a few mildly
dirty stories, and I loved her from that moment onwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Gertie died in 1952, at 54. ``I wish so deeply, so very
deeply,'' Coward told the newspapers, ``that I could see her just
once more, playing in a play of mine.'' Though the point is made
lightly, ``If Love Were All'' unfolds in Coward's mind as he writes
that tenderly self-centered tribute.
</P>
<P>
   What inspired the show and its particular form, Morley said
after an early preview, was the answer the dying Coward gave when
Morley asked him if he still thought about Gertie. ``Every night
when I go to sleep and every morning when I wake up,'' replied
Coward, ``I see her in that white Molyneux dress on the `Private
Lives' terrace, and she never goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   In various forms and under various titles, from cabaret act to
West End attraction, Morley's two-character tribute has been around
for some 15 years. By his estimate, it has played in more than 30
locales, from London and the Far East to the Bay Street Theater in
Sag Harbor. Later this year, Alan Ayckbourn will direct it as
``Noel and Gertie'' in London.
</P>
<P>
   But what sets the New York edition apart, Morley said, is the
cast: Twiggy, the former model Lesley Hornby from London who
starred in ``The Boy Friend,'' the film spoof of the '20s, and on
Broadway with Tommy Tune in ``My One and Only,'' also set in the
'20s; and Harry Groener, whose notable credits as a song and dance
man include the Broadway musical ``Crazy for You.'' With those two
on board, the show has acquired, for the first time, tap numbers in
authentic period style.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had very good players,'' Morley said, ``but none with
that real show-biz quality. It's been 10 years since Twiggy first
wanted to do the piece. Last summer, at Sag Harbor, it finally
happened. Like Gertie, she's a great star before she's a great
actor or singer or dancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Impersonation, though, is not the goal. ``If you go down that
route, you're asking for trouble,'' said Groener, who has purposely
kept his study of recorded Noeliana to a minimum. ``Too many people
knew Coward and have seen him before.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those who did is Twiggy, who at 49 regards doing a
musical as the best way to stay slim. She and Coward met three
times, first at Firefly, his house in Jamaica, in her stick-figure
supermodel days.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours before a recent preview, she tucked into a
triple-decker turkey sandwich (no fries) and reminisced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very nervous,'' she said, sounding like Eliza Doolittle
before she met Henry Higgins. ``He was so famous, and famous for
his wicked tongue. But he was so lovely. We got on a treat.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, when Coward was back in England, depressed and
suffering from emphysema, the actor Robert Stephens made it his
mission to cheer up his friend with a daily surprise. One day, he
called Twiggy and asked her to do the next day's honors. By now,
her friend Ken Russell had cast her as the lead in his movie ``The
Boy Friend,'' undeterred by the fact that she had never acted, sung
or danced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned as I went along,'' said Twiggy, in perfect tune with
the spirit of Gertie. Gertie had no formal training for her
profession, either, and spoke of her gifts with shrewd humility.
``I am not what you'd call wonderfully talented,'' she said, ``but
I am light on my feet and I do make the best of things.'' As Agnes
de Mille put it with tart Yankee candor, ``She can't sing, but who
cares?''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Twiggy reminded Coward of his old platonic flame,
she seems to have charmed him. ``When he found out I was just
learning my dances to `The Boy Friend,' he said, `Show me!'''
Twiggy recalled. ``Then he got up and danced with me. Just then
there came a loud knock on the door and in walked Merle Oberon,
looking absolutely gorgeous. I couldn't believe it. And she joined
us for tea.''
</P>
<P>
   Twiggy's final encounter with Coward took place in a London
hospital. He told her she should play Elvira, and she thought,
``Who's Elvira?'' A scene from ``Blithe Spirit'' in the current
show gives the answer: the inconvenient ghost of the first wife of
the play's harried, remarried protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, when Twiggy was thinking seriously about
playing Gertie, a snapshot from Firefly turned up, which she took
as a favorable sign. Through Leigh Lawson, her husband and the
director of ``If Love Were All,'' she can point to another link:
``When Leigh's mum was 23, she was the first front-of-house manager
at the brand-new Phoenix Theater, which opened with `Private
Lives.' She watched every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Icon of the '60s that she was, Twiggy finds it not strange at
all to be turning back the clock to her parents' generation. ``I
think of the '20s and '30s as my period,'' she offered between
healthy bites of sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the music, the clothes, the style. The '20s must have
been a wonderful time if you had money. They would have been a
nightmare if you were poor.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused a moment. ``I would probably have been a maid,'' she
added, with timing worthy of Amanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
