<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8979 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYE-EYE_SFCHRON &LR;      06-01 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYE-EYE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Eye Surgeon Is in a Business With High Visibility  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Dr. Gary Kawesch has an eye for business as well as medicine.
<P>
   The 35-year-old ophthalmologist does as many as a dozen
vision-correction surgeries an hour at his Laser Eye Center of
Silicon Valley. At $2,200 per cornea, he grosses close to $10
million a year and nets ``in the low seven figures.''
</P>
<P>
   That's more than many neighboring high-tech companies make. Of
course, it helps that Kawesch specializes in the fastest-growing
field of elective surgery in America. And unlike most doctors, he
doesn't have to haggle with managed care providers because most
patients pay out of their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kawesch also has focused on marketing and management as
well as medicine to build his practice.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kawesch strategically located his surgical center
near a freeway on-ramp in San Jose, to make it easier for customers
from Santa Cruz and San Francisco to reach him.
</P>
<P>
   He also provides provides free limo pickup and dropoff service
to clients. ``I recognize people are paying out of pocket for a
luxury item and their time is valuable,'' said Kawesch.
</P>
<P>
   And he joined an entrepreneurs group to gain management
expertise and mentoring.
</P>
<P>
   While most doctors devote little money or attention to
marketing, those who specialize in elective procedures often spend
tens of thousands or hundreds of thousands of dollars a year. But
few have a marketing budget as big as Kawesch.
</P>
<P>
   He spends about $750,000 a year on advertising, including
30-second TV spots, a 30-minute infomercial, radio and Internet
ads. A year and a half ago, Kawesch even took out a billboard on
Highway 101.
</P>
<P>
   His company has 28 employees, including 10 in marketing and
``patient education.''
</P>
<P>
   His Web site ( &LR; www.2020eyesite.com &LR; ) includes testimonials from
satisfied customers, articles he's authored, seminars he's holding
and multimedia interviews with Kawesch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Kawesch's clients include TV Judge Joe Brown, Eddie Murphy's
wife and athletes from the A's, 49ers, Raiders, Sharks and
Cleveland Indians. He has done 13,000 procedures since 1992, and
said he owns about a third of the laser vision correction market in
Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians and prospective patients may balk at Kawesch's
promotional style in a medical world where quiet referrals are the
norm.
</P>
<P>
   Kawesch's services ``are perhaps over-marketed,'' according to
Ken Coleman, president of iCEO, a Woodside company specializing in
providing interim chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Coleman decided to have vision-correction surgery,
he went to Kawesch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy going to the volume leader,'' Coleman said. ``It's
been shown that the (doctor) who does the most of a certain
procedure is often the best person to go to.'' Coleman is pleased
with the results. His vision went from 20-200 to better than 20-20.
</P>
<P>
   Kawesch may be the most visible eye surgeon in the Valley, but
he is hardly alone. Edward Manche, director of cornea and
refractive surgery at Stanford University's School of Medicine,
does about as many procedures per month as Kawesch and even charges
$300 more per eye.
</P>
<P>
   But the two 35-year-old doctors couldn't be more different in
style. While Manche drives a 1989 Honda, Kawesch tools around in a
1994 yellow Lamborghini.
</P>
<P>
   Both physicians specialize in the popular laser surgery
treatment called LASIK, short for Laser-Assisted In-Situ
Keratomileusis.
</P>
<P>
   In this quick and generally painless procedure, a machine called
a microkeratome first slices and lifts up a thin flap of tissue
from the surface of the cornea. A laser is then used to reshape the
exposed corneal surface and the flap is then replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The typical computer-controlled procedure takes only seconds,
involves no stitches and little discomfort and patients can see the
results almost instantaneously. It is estimated that more than
800,000 such procedures will be conducted in the United States this
year, about double last year's total.
</P>
<P>
   Although most patients rave about LASIK, industry studies show 3
to 4 percent notice some nighttime side effects such as haloes or
star-bursts around lights.
</P>
<P>
   The worse a person's eyesight, the greater the likelihood of
needing to go back for a little resculpting of the cornea _ what
Kawesch calls ``a touch-up.'' If a patient can't see the big E on
the eye chart at half the normal distance without corrective
lenses, Kawesch said the chances of needing a second procedure is
about 20 percent. The additional cost is $100 per eye.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is expensive in part because of the high cost of
the equipment. The laser machines, which come from VISX of Santa
Clara and Japan's Nidek, cost about $500,000 each, and Kawesch has
to pay VISX a royalty of $260 per eye each time he uses the VISX
machine. ``It's like buying a Mercedes and having to pay the
company every time you turn on the ignition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kawesch uses the Nidek machine on about 80 percent of his
patients, not because of the savings in royalty payments, but
because he claims it treats a broader area of the cornea and thus
lessens the potential night-time halo effect. However, he said VISX
machines are the only ones that work on farsightedness and also are
better for treating some astigmatisms.
</P>
<P>
   Kawesch went to the University of California at Los Angeles
medical school after graduating from Yale and was drawn to laser
surgery. ``I like high-tech and I like to see results fast,'' he
explained. In addition, unlike most other types of surgery, ``there
are not a lot of emergencies and the lifestyle is good.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the same year he finished his residency in
ophthalmology, Kawesch purchased the eye surgery practice in San
Jose from a doctor who ran into licensing problems over allegations
of performing unnecessary operations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential risk of guilt by association, Kawesch
decided buying the practice made sense. ``I saw it as a diamond in
the rough,'' Kawesch recalled. ``The area is wealthy and people are
enamored of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than locate in a conventional, high-priced medical
building, Kawesch leased a former bank branch close to a Highway
280 on-ramp and converted it into a surgery center.
</P>
<P>
   Since he had no formal business training, Kawesch joined the
Young Entrepreneurs' Organization to get some management tips. He
was paired with a mentor from the World Presidents Organization,
Tom Herman, who heads the Alamo Group, an East Bay financial
services company, and is a former CEO of Delta California
Industries and Grand Auto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately liked Gary's interest in patient care,'' said
Herman, who has helped Kawesch analyze his business and evaluate
new surgery center locations.
</P>
<P>
   By keeping a database of more than 30,000 callers and
pinpointing where inquiries were coming from over the past two
years, Kawesch was able to identify the East Bay as a market where
he could expand without cutting into his existing business.
</P>
<P>
   He recently leased another abandoned bank branch with ``nice
curb appeal and parking,'' this time in Pleasanton. He plans to
hire another surgeon for this second surgery center to spread the
load and a slice of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8980 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYESIDE-FORWIRES &LR;      06-01 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYESIDE-FOR </SLUG>
 WIRES  
 `Physician Extenders' Can Help  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Doctors who get paid by health maintenance organizations can't
increase their revenues as easily as those who do elective
procedures paid for by patients.
<P>
   But they can still take steps to control costs and attract new
clients, business consultants say. Some doctors are using
``physician extenders'' the same way lawyers use paralegals.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Bernstein, vice president of marketing for Health Care
System, a large Tacoma, Wash., physician group and hospital system,
said doctors increasingly are using nurse practitioners and
physician assistants to take patient histories and blood pressure,
deal with some patients' chronic problems and handle chores that
save doctors' time for more critical jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Successful medical groups also increasingly have Web sites to
provide clients important health information and links to other
resources online, which also cuts demands on the doctors, according
to Bernstein. She said that primary care physicians also are using
phone centers like McKesson HBOC's Access Call Center Group in
Phoenix to respond to patients during non-office hours.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors can also do a better job negotiating with managed care
outfits, according to John Sterling, vice president of Smock
Management Consultants in Lake Forest, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians don't usually do this very well,'' he said. Those
who are sophisticated, run good-sized practices or have savvy
contract administrators or consultants can often negotiate better
deals with insurers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, doctors might win additional payments if they keep
patients healthier and admit a lower than normal proportion of
clients to hospitals. Another tactic is to provide services that
are not covered by health insurers, suggests Jeffrey Denning of
Practice Performance Group in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he notes that a number of obstetricians and
gynecologists have gone into the lucrative tummy tuck and
liposuction business, and dermatologists are treating so-called
spider veins that are not covered by most insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who are limited by strict Medicare reimbursement fees on
heart surgery or cataract operations, might look at serving
well-off foreigners who frequently seek medical attention in the
United States and pay full fare, Denning said. Obviously it helps
if you speak a foreign language or have cross-cultural connections.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
