<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BABY-BROKER-NY     06-01 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BABY-BROKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY SMUGGLING SUSPECT CALLED COMPASSIONATE, NOT GREEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)  (sidebar with MEXICO-BABY-SMUGGLING) 
(bl) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOUGLAS, Ariz. _ Mario Manuel Reyes Burgueno, a lawyer charged
with smuggling Mexican babies into the United States, is well known
throughout this community on the Arizona-Mexico border as a devout
Catholic and a staunch opponent of abortion. And his lawyers say
his efforts to get Mexican children adopted in the United States
were motivated by religious conviction and humanitarian compassion
and not by greed.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes, a 40-year-old father of four, was arrested last week on
charges that he helped arrange the illegal adoption of Mexican
children by parents in the United States and collected large cash
payments. In a bail hearing for Reyes on Tuesday in U.S. District
Court in Tucson, his attorney, Ivan Abrams, said that Reyes was
attempting to help ``unwanted children of prostitutes in large
measure and very poor people who couldn't afford to bring another
child into this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams added, ``His intentions were good.''
</P>
<P>
   No bail was set for Reyes. However a hearing was set for June 8
at U.S. District Court in Brooklyn. Abrams said his client is broke
and that his parents may have to put up their house to help him pay
bail, if one is set.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Abrams explained that his client ``loathes
abortion'' and that he even wrote his law school dissertation on
strategies for preventing illegal abortions in Mexico by
establishing more adoption agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not trying to hurt anyone,'' Abrams said.
</P>
<P>
   People here, in Reyes' hometown want to believe that is true.
Father Luis Chavez, Reyes' priest said that after rumors began to
swirl last fall that police were investigating Reyes, the lawyer
assured him that he had done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   When church members asked about Reyes' predicament, the priest
said, he became defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think God is going to treat him badly,'' Chavez said
he told members of the church. ``He took children who were going to
be aborted, or who were going to probably live in misery and gave
them a chance to have good homes.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the other side of the border in Agua Prieta, the stories
about Reyes are not as generous.
</P>
<P>
   Eunicia Soto, who runs an independent orphanage in Agua Prieta,
said she would occasionally run into Reyes at the local courthouse
and he would ask her if she had any children available for
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told him no,'' she recalled, ``He would tell me, `Your
problem is that you hold on too tight to your children.'''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to allegations that Reyes was paid about $20,000 for
each of the adoptions he arranged, she asked, ``If he is such a
humanitarian who wanted to help poor children, then why did he
charge so much money?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
