<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS RELEASE RECEIVER DAVIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ As expected, the Dallas Cowboys released wide
receiver Billy Davis Tuesday to free up room under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who cleared out his locker weeks ago, became expendable
when the Cowboys signed free-agent receiver Raghib Ismail and
re-signed Ernie Mills. Davis' release saves the Cowboys $800,000,
leaving the club little more than $1 million under the $57.28
million cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy made some great plays for us, I'm sorry to lose him,''
owner Jerry Jones said. ``We had expectations of him being our
second receiver. When that didn't work out it was just too much for
us with him playing exclusively on special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was the first day teams could release roster players or
sign unrestricted free agents since April 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are left with six receivers: three front-line
players in Michael Irvin, Mills and Ismail; little-used backup Jeff
Ogden; and two unsigned rookies, fourth-round draft pick Wane
McGarity of Texas and sixth-round selection Martay Jenkins of
Nebraska-Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is coming off his most productive season in his four-year
NFL career. He finished second on the team with 39 receptions for
691 yards and three touchdowns. His 17.7-yards-per-catch average
ranked him fourth in the NFC and 11th in the NFL. He had just three
receptions before last season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' agent, Jordan Woy, could not be reached to comment on the
receiver's prospects for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player; he'll help a team,'' Jones said. NO
DECISION ON SANDERS
</P>
<P>
   It remains possible that the Cowboys could release All-Pro
cornerback Deion Sanders if Jerry Jones thinks Sanders' surgically
repaired big toe would prevent him from contributing this season.
Releasing Sanders would free up $6.5 million on the salary cap.
However, the Cowboys are more likely to wait in order to evaluate
Sanders' progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just no change. He's on the roster,'' Jones said. ``I
have no comment right now on what we're doing one way or the other.
I know what I'd like to do.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
