<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/ PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON  Online Retail Strategies
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have a kitchenware company and would like to expand the
business by selling online. I am interested in learning about the
best strategies and also how to keep from losing retail customers
if I price online items for less than I sell them for in the store.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are lots of recipes for selling stuff online and whole
books on the subject like ``Selling Online for Dummies'' (IDG
Books, by Leslie Heeter Lundquist).
</P>
<P>
   We took your question to Scott Galloway, chief executive of
Prophet Brand Strategy, which helps companies like Adidas and Wells
Fargo with their marketing strategies, including e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In moving from physical store to electronic delivery _ what
Galloway calls ``going analog to digital,'' it is easy to get
overcome by fear, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to clearly define what you hope to gain from
an Internet site. For example, is it to increase your value to
customers? To win more sales? To provide more customer service and
lower phone service costs? To test new products or brands?
</P>
<P>
   When you try a new sales channel, stay focused on just one or
two things, Galloway says.
</P>
<P>
   Since consumers commonly use multiple sales channels, from
stores and catalogs to phone and online sites, effective retailers
use a combination of approaches. For example, Galloway says
Williams-Sonoma collects e-mail addresses in its stores for its
bridal registry and then pitches products to this targeted audience
through other sales channels.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid cannibalizing your current customers, Galloway
recommends offering products for the same price online, even though
sales costs may be lower than in your store. David Aaker, a
marketing professor at the University of California at Berkeley
Haas School of Business, agrees that a standard ``pricing
umbrella'' is usually the best strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do want to compete on price, consider establishing new
brands,'' says Aaker, who recently joined Prophet Brand Strategy as
vice chairman. Just as Gap has different brands for different price
points, from Banana Republic to Gap to Old Navy, you might be able
to sell different merchandise or sub-brands online.
</P>
<P>
   Aaker offers four tips to building a brand on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   _View the Internet as a home for the loyalist. Use it as a way
to keep your most passionate customers happy and stimulated.
</P>
<P>
   _Create links with your other communication programs, such as
advertising and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   _Have strong branded features such as information on or links to
related products or services, such as recipes or nonstick products.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW02 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  _Make the ``look and feel'' of your Web site consistent with the
personality of your stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Virtual Headquarters
</P>
<P>
   Q: Colleagues in Michigan, Missouri and California are planning
to create a consulting group organized as a limited liability
company. We will provide data analysis services to health &UR;  &LR; care
organizations located virtually anywhere. All work can be handled
via e-mail and other electronic means, so there is no required
physical place &UR;  &LR; of business. What issues determine which state the
LLC should be registered in? Will we need to register as a
``foreign company'' in other states?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: As you no doubt already know, one of the major benefits of
limited liability companies is that they are taxed like
partnerships. There is no double taxation at the corporate and
personal levels since income flows directly to the owners, who pay
taxes according to the state laws where they reside.
</P>
<P>
   However, you should check out the LLC laws and costs of
incorporation in each of the three states where the owners live,
according to Kevin Leek, a lawyer and author of ``Kiplinger's Small
Business Attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   He also notes that each state has its own rules on what
constitutes doing business in that state and whether sales or other
taxes apply.
</P>
<P>
   For physical goods, the rules are simpler; for electronic
delivery of services of the type you are providing, the rules are
less clear. It may depend on whether you are actually spending time
in other states.
</P>
<P>
   As for having to file as a ``foreign'' company in every state
where you provide service, Leek suggests that most states have
exemptions for onetime events, and for companies that don't have an
actual office or employee in that state. However, if you are
supposed to register and do not, some states can bring certain
penalties. And if you get sued in a state where you have not
properly registered, the owners could lose the benefit of limited
liability since the LLC might not be recognized.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to check up on LLC laws and requirements in the
states where you plan to operate. Places to start are legal Web
sites like Block Financial's  &LR; www.blocksoft.com/legal &LR; , West
Group's &LR;  www.westlaw.com  &LR; and CCH Inc.'s &UR;  &LR; www.cch.com &LR; . &UR;  &LR; You
probably will want to consult an attorney, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
