<SLUG> BC-SPINNER-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 AOL Trying to Catch Internet Music Wave  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
America Online Inc. yesterday said it is paying about $400 million
in stock to buy two key Internet music companies and consolidate
their operations in San Francisco.
<P>
   AOL, moving to jump into the rapidly developing field of online
music, will buy privately held Spinner Networks Inc., a 3-year-old
San Francisco company that ``broadcasts'' about 2 million popular
songs each day through the Internet. Spinner Networks reaches about
1.5 million listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the world's largest consumer online company will buy
privately held Nullsoft Inc., a small Sedona, Ariz., firm that
makes WinAmp, the most popular software program used to play
downloadable songs encoded in the MP3 compression format.
</P>
<P>
   Nullsoft's staff will move to Spinner's headquarters on Alabama
Street and become part of what local audio-related companies are
trying to dub the ``Audio Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited about the Nullsoft guys joining forces with us
in San Francisco,'' said Dave Samuel, Spinner CEO and founder.
</P>
<P>
   The WinAmp program, which has about 5 million users, is one of
the key products that in the past year fueled the grassroots
popularity of MP3-encoded music played on desktop computers and
distributed via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3 groundswell showed how music can be transmitted in
digital form directly to consumers on the Internet, which has
caused the recording industry to start gearing up for a major shift
in how it distributes music in the future.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is hoping to catch the wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Combining these leading Internet music brands with the
audience reach of our brands will lift music online to the next
level of popularity,'' AOL President Bob Pittman said in a news
release. ``We plan to build downloadable music, Internet radio and
overall music features into each of our brands.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
