<HEADLINE>
IRVIN HASN'T SOUGHT TRADE FROM COWBOYS, AGENT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The agent for Michael Irvin said yesterday the
Dallas Cowboys' all-time leading receiver is concerned about his
contract status, but he has made no contact with any NFL teams
regarding a possible trade.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Endicott, Irvin's agent, said he is miffed that the
Cowboys have yet to offer a contract extension and that his client
was used as possible trade bait prior to the NFL draft in April.
Endicott said Irvin would endorse a trade if the Cowboys are not
planning to offer the 12-year veteran an extension that would keep
him with the team for the remainder of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who did not attend Tuesday's voluntary workout at Valley
Ranch and was unavailable to comment, is entering the final year of
his current deal. The Cowboys have already extended the contracts
of Troy Aikman and Emmitt Smith to guarantee they will end their
careers as Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The contract situation ``would concern any player,'' Endicott
said. ``Michael is not demanding a trade or anything else. Michael
knows they talked to some teams about trading him over the winter;
that's still stuck there. He said if that's what they want to do,
that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said he would not comment on whether
he plans to offer Irvin a contract extension. But he added he's not
concerned about Irvin not being at the workout Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the 11 years I have been involved here, the
way he competes on the field, it's not a big issue,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Endicott also said Irvin is not irked about being de-emphasized
in the new offense coach Chan Gailey installed last season. Irvin,
33, led the team with 74 receptions last year, but caught only one
touchdown pass. His 1,057 yards receiving was his second-lowest
total of the past eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sat down and talked about his future, where we think he
is. I think we are all on the same page,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The re-signing of Ernie Mills, who was on pace to set career
marks in catches and yards before an injury cut his season short,
and the recent free-agent signing of Raghib Ismail, should help
Irvin find more space to maneuver in Gailey's favored multiple
receiver sets.
</P>
<P>
   The offense ``gives the opportunity to those who get open,''
Gailey said. ``We don't force the ball, we let reads dictate where
we throw the football.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
