<SLUG> BC-E-TRADE-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 E-Trade Acquires Telebanc for $1.8 Billion   &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Online broker E-Trade, in a bid to expand its menu of financial
products, agreed yesterday to buy Telebanc, the nation's largest
Internet-based bank, for $1.8 billion in stock.
<P>
   The move will let Palo Alto's E-Trade, the No. 2 electronic
broker, offer federally insured savings and checking accounts and
let customers pay bills online. It represents a giant step in the
company's campaign to postion itself as a full-line financial
services company based on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pushing the envelope in building a broader online
financial services strategy,'' said U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray
analyst Stephen Franco.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade announced the Telebanc takeover the same day securities
industry powerhouse Merrill Lynch unveiled plans for a low-cost
online brokerage service, something it once said it would never do.
The two moves highlighted the growing power of the Internet as a
medium for consumers to manage their finances.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of E-Trade fell $5.19 to $39.31 on a day the stocks of
electronic brokerages plummeted across the board. Telebanc's stock
surged $8 to $74.50.
</P>
<P>
   Telebanc, headquartered in Arlington, Va., is chartered as a
savings and loan, but has no traditional branches. It had $1.3
billion in deposits and 60,000 customer accounts nationwide at the
end of March, making it by far the largest Internet-only bank.
</P>
<P>
   Still, its online business is dwarfed by those of many
traditional banks, including industry leader Wells Fargo, which has
more than 840,000 Internet customers.
</P>
<P>
   Telebanc provides an array of deposit products, including
checking and money market accounts, and certificates of deposit.
E-Trade offers checking linked to a customer's brokerage account,
but money in such accounts is not federally insured.
</P>
<P>
   Because it doesn't have to pay for a branch network, Telebanc's
costs are lower than those of traditional banks, allowing it to
offer such bargains as free checking and bill payment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One thing it doesn't have though is automated teller machines.
The company reimburses certain customers for the fees other banks
charge for using their ATMs, up to $1.50 four times a month.
E-Trade said it will continue the rebates for the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also doesn't make loans. E-Trade currently offer loans,
such as mortgages and credit cards, through third-party vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike online trading, brokerages, &LR; which has exploded in
popularity, Internet banking has grown much more slowly. Analysts
say that's because consumers don't have a compelling reason to bank
online comparable to the huge commissions savings available from
Internet stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic bankers believe that's about to change. They say the
Internet will become consumers' preferred place to receive and pay
bills, making trips to the mailbox unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next year or two, online banking will explode like
online brokerage,'' said Telebanc Executive Vice President Larry
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Telebanc will continue to operate as a separate unit of E-Trade.
The companies said they expect to keep all of the bank's 130
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Telebanc had revenue of $107.7 million and a profit of $1
million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade's purchase price values the company at about $13.8
million per employee, astronomical compared to takeovers in other
industries, but below the amount-per-employee in some other
recently announced Internet takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
