<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8998 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISCO-FINBUDGET_SFCHR     06-01 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-FINBUDGET </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 U.S. to Drop Its Antitrust Probe of Cisco  &HT;     By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Federal Trade Commission today is expected to exonerate Cisco
Systems Inc. after an eight-month investigation concluded that the
networking giant did not attempt to carve up the lucrative
data-transfer market in separate talks with Lucent Technologies
Inc. and Nortel Networks.
<P>
   ``The commission was satisfied that there was nothing
inappropriate in our discussions and that telecommunications is one
of the most competitive markets that exists,'' Cisco general
counsel Dan Scheinman said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Scheinman said nothing in the commission's probe, which wrapped
up last Friday, warranted further examination into possible
antitrust violations.
</P>
<P>
   An FTC spokeswoman confirmed that the investigation is closed.
She declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is the second Silicon Valley company cleared of federal
scrutiny this year. In March, the FTC settled antitrust charges
with Intel Corp. Ironically, Cisco's news came on the same day that
the Department of Justice resumed its heated antitrust case against
Microsoft Corp. in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders said the FTC appeared to be satisfied with
Cisco's explanation that talks with telecommunications heavyweights
Nortel and Lucent were principally to explore approaches to new
markets _ not plans to divide markets.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry may have been further dampened by Lucent's
acquisition of Cisco rival Ascend in January for $20 billion, as
well as Nortel's $9.1 billion buyout of another Cisco competitor,
Bay Networks Inc., last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one took this investigation seriously,'' said analyst Paul
Johnson of BancBoston Robertson Stephens in New York. ``Anyone
close to Lucent and Cisco knows these are fierce competitors with
very little overlap in terms of product. There was no collusion
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, the FTC asked Cisco for information about concurrent
talks it had with Lucent and Nortel in 1997 and 1998 about
potential partnerships in the fast-changing communications market,
which is shifting toward an emphasis on data rather than voice
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The probe was sparked by a story in the New York Times last
summer, which noted how the evolution in technology was forcing a
convergence _ rather than competition _ between makers of
data-networking equipment, like Cisco, and established,
telephone-based companies like Northern Telecom and Lucent. The
article speculated about a wide-ranging partnership or a titanic
merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to do a blockbuster merger with somebody
else,'' Cisco CEO John Chambers told the Times. ``Zero chance. It
would be a disaster for the shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers did acknowledge that Cisco approached North America's
largest makers of traditional telecommunications equipment in early
1997 about possible business partnerships. But talks with both
companies were scotched because each insisted on making products
that compete with Cisco technology.
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts said it is legal for competitors to discuss
cooperative alliances if they lead to the development of
less-expensive and better products in complementary areas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the specter of an FTC investigation, Cisco has
maintained its acquiring ways. This year it has purchased four
companies, including several voice technology firms that compete
directly with Lucent and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose-based Cisco is expected to disclose another strategic
partnership later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The networking company's stock slid $1.94, to $107.06 per share,
in trading yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
