<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8999 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPPLEMENT-STUDY-BOS &LR;      06-01 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPPLEMENT-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT RAISES DOUBTS ABOUT MUSCLE ENHANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is merely preliminary evidence, not a medical bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   But an Iowa State study of the nutritional supplement
androstenedione _ which became alternately famous and notorious
last year when Mark McGwire paused from his record 70-home run
exploits to reveal that he uses it _ is cautionary, if not
conclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Published in the prestigious Journal of the American Medical
Association, the study indicates that, after being administered in
three daily doses of 100 milligrams each, andro did not enhance
muscle strength but it caused a significant lowering of ``good''
cholesterol and increased blood estrogen levels, which could lead
to enlarged breasts, heart disease, and pancreatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dosage involved _ far less than the 500-1,200
milligrams recommended in advertisements for andro _ and the size
of the sampling _ 30 men, ages 19-26 _ are not sufficient to
extrapolate definitive determinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a first step, and an appropriate first step,'' said Dr.
Joel Finkelstein, senior author of a far more wide-ranging
Massachusetts General Hospital andro study that was commissioned by
Major League Baseball. ``It's a nice study that demonstrates that
at this dose of androstenedione, they were unable to show any
effect on muscle strength or testosterone.''
</P>
<P>
   The MGH study is not ready for release, and Finkelstein was
unable to project a target date. Nor would he divulge the
particulars of the study, underwritten so that Major League
Baseball can decide whether to follow the lead of the International
Olympic Committee, professional tennis, the National Football
League, and the NCAA by banning the steroid-like substance, which
is legal and sold without prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of the Iowa State subjects underwent eight weeks of
resistance bodybuilding training, and 10 of them were given andro.
The study found that there was no difference in muscle strength
between those who took andro and those who were given a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine, according to Finkelstein, as far as it goes. ``A
study of wider doses is needed,'' he said. ``It's possible that
higher levels of androstenedione will raise the testosterone
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Rich Levin said Major League Baseball is reserving
comment until the MGH report is released. Champion Nutrition of
Concord, Calif., for which McGwire endorses andro, did not return
telephone calls from the Globe. And Experimental and Applied
Sciences Inc. of Golden, Colo., a distributor that supplies the
androstenedione derivative Andro 6 and funded the Iowa State study,
preached a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``EAS finds the research from Iowa State University to be very
interesting and suggests that it be taken into account by anyone
considering taking androstenedione,'' said a company statement.
</P>
<P>
   At Fenway Park before Tueday night's Tigers-Red Sox game, a
thoroughly unscientific survey of the constituency to whom
androstenedione research would be most pertinent _ the ballplayers
_ indicated a distinct lack of concern about the study, perhaps
because of a widespread lack of use of the product.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek and Tigers outfielder Gregg
Jefferies said they know of no teammates who take andro, and most
of the players canvassed professed no inclination to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I'd want is something to increase strength and
durability,'' said Varitek, ``and I get that in the weight room.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
