<HEADER>
A9008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      06-01 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch to Offer OnLine Stock Trading
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch plans to add a low-cost service for people who
want to trade on the Internet. Instead of its average charge of $80
to $100 for a trade, the brokerage firm will let customers trade on
line for $29.95, matching the fee charged by Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.
But customers will not have access to research or guidance from a
broker. In addition, customers of Merrill Lynch can pay an annual
fee of at least $1,500 for unlimited trading and advice, either on
line or through a broker.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Media Buys Associated
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Media Group, the television programming company
controlled by John Malone, expanded into the wireless
communications business by agreeing to acquire Associated Group of
Pittsburgh in a complicated stock deal that involves AT&AMP;T.
Associated is the largest investor in Teligent, which provides
telephone and data communications services to companies using
advanced wireless technology.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Ends Cisco Investigation
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said that it was ending its
nine-month investigation into partnership discussions that Cisco
Systems, the maker of data communications gear, held in recent
years with two rivals. That means that Cisco will escape the sort
of regulatory and legal pressure that the government has brought to
bear on Intel and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts Still Confident in Xenical
</P>
<P>
   After a month on the market, the diet drug Xenical, made by
Hoffmann-La Roche, will not go down as the most successful
pharmaceutical introduction in history, but analysts are confident
that it will be a best seller.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Mostly Fall, but Dow Rallies
</P>
<P>
   Stocks sold off early in the session on concerns that the
Federal Reserve might raise interest rates later this month. The
Dow Jones industrial average later recovered, closing up 36.52
points, to 10,596.26, but the Nasdaq composite index declined 58.49
points, or 2.37 percent, to 2,470.52. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 7.58 points, to 1,294.26.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices slumped, pushing yields to their highest level in
more than a year. The yield of the benchmark 30-year bond rose to
5.94 percent, from 5.82 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing Rose in May
</P>
<P>
   The rebound in U.S. manufacturing accelerated in May and more
factories reported paying higher prices for materials, a National
Association of Purchasing Management survey showed. Separately, the
Conference Board reported that its index of leading economic
indicators fell one-tenth of 1 percent in April, its first monthly
decline in almost a year. And the Commerce Department said that the
country's construction spending unexpectedly fell 2.4 percent in
April, the first decline in six months.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Antitrust Trial Reopens
</P>
<P>
   After a three-month recess and inconclusive efforts to settle
the Microsoft antitrust case, the trial's rebuttal phase opened
with a concerted attack on the previous testimony of Microsoft's
chief economic witness.
</P>
<P>
   Handover of Conrail Goes Smoothly
</P>
<P>
   CSX and Norfolk Southern railroads took over the Conrail system
in one of the most complex handoffs in railroad history and for the
first day, at least, trains throughout the Northeast ran close to
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   America Online in Two Music Deals
</P>
<P>
   America Online said it would buy two Internet music companies,
Spinner Networks and Nullsoft, for $400 million in stock. The
acquisitions underscore the growing popularity of listening to
music over the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
