<HEADLINE>
BURN KEEPING OPTIONS OPEN IN GOAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While growing up in Denver, Matt Jordan had an opportunity not
available to most young goalkeepers. Beginning at age 17, Jordan
trained with the Colorado Foxes of the American Professional Soccer
League.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that training was learning from Mark Dodd, who was
quickly rising to the ranks of top American-born keepers.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Jordan and Dodd have joined forces to help the
Burn become one of the top teams in Major League Soccer this
season. Tendinitis in his left knee has sidelined Dodd, leaving the
23-year-old Jordan to fill the starting role Dodd had the past
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd has missed 11 of the Burn's 12 games, but Jordan _ who
played only 45 minutes last season _ has posted a league-best 52
saves. Now that Dodd is almost recovered, Burn coach Dave Dir must
decide which of his goalkeepers will get the playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Dir minds. A former goalkeeper, he recognizes that a
roster with a promising rookie and a proven veteran battling for
goalkeeping minutes is a luxury that allows him experience in the
net as well as optimism for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good problem to have, if they don't let the pressure
from the outside \Raffect\S their egos,'' Dir said. ``To be a good
goalkeeper you have to have a little bit of ego but enough to be
humble when you need to. I think they both have that quality.''
</P>
<P>
   After months of rehabilitation, Dodd said his knee is about 85
percent recovered. But his immediate emphasis isn't to regain the
starting spot; it's to fully regain his strength.
</P>
<P>
   That works well for Dir, whose plan is to let Jordan start for
now because the Burn is 6-4 with him in net, and undefeated in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, at this point the motivation is not to get this guy's
job or anything like that,'' Dodd said. ``The motivation is to get
yourself 100 percent healthy and then look at the situation. I
think it all sorts itself out as the season goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition will likely heat up; nearly two-thirds of the
regular season remains. The Burn has three more games against
defending MLS champion and league-leading Chicago, and four against
two-time MLS champion D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd offers experience, especially in pressure situations. He
has been a finalist for MLS goalkeeper of the year all three
seasons, earning the honor in 1996. Last year, his save on a
penalty kick by Kansas City's Preki ultimately clinched a playoff
spot for the Burn.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has not been tested with such pressure this season, but
his success to this point is undeniable. Jordan is among the MLS
leaders in several goalkeeping statistics, including second in
shutouts (four) and goals-against average (0.64).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's incredibly quick, I think the quickest in the league,''
Dir said of Jordan. ``I always felt that Mark played with his
brain. He can read the game with his experience. Matt does a lot
with his physical attributes, and he's still learning to read the
game from that standpoint. But it's obvious that he's not let many
goals in this season. It will be scary to see what he does when he
gets that down.''
</P>
<P>
   Dir said he will decide who to play and when based largely on
which goalkeeper's skills will help the team most in certain
situations. Pressure situations such as shootouts and
playoff-deciding games might tip the scales in favor of Dodd's
knowledge over Jordan's athletic ability. That seemed to be
</P>
<P>
   Dir's thought when he gave Dodd his first appearance this season
in the final minutes of a 1-1 tie against San Jose on May 22,
before the game went into a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the rookie can learn from the veteran and whether Dodd
can get a push from the up-and-coming Jordan could help determine
the Burn's success this season. And both said that takes priority
over who's getting the next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a long season, and there are so many hills and
valleys and injuries and situations where players think about
whether they're starting or not,'' Dodd said. ``And what Dave
wants, and what every team wants, is to have a team that's
interchangeable. That's what you need ultimately to become a
champion.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
