<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON ENDORSES GORE, TRYING TO BOOST HIS STANDING AMONG
WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his support among women lagging, Vice
President Al Gore on Tuesday sought the help of Hillary Rodham
Clinton to spark excitement for his presidential candidacy _ even
at the risk that her star power would upstage him.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally at a downtown hotel, Mrs. Clinton attracted a crowd
of about 300 women, and Gore basked in the reflected glory, trying
to show little concern that she too might run for office and divert
attention and money from his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has fought harder on behalf of America's families and
children,'' Mrs. Clinton declared as she endorsed Gore for
president, her large diamond necklace and earrings flashing under
the lights. ``And no one will fight harder and be more effective at
keeping those priorities on our nation's agenda into the next
century.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that Gore would ``not let the clock be turned
back'' on abortion rights, not mentioning that while he was in the
House of Representatives he voted against abortion rights numerous
times.
</P>
<P>
   The rally, at the Mayflower Hotel, was unusual for several
reasons, not the least of which was that Gore felt the need to
invigorate what should be a reliable constituency in an election
still 18 months away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk about women's issues, we are talking about the
issues that touch all of our families and all our lives,'' Gore
said to the women, many of them longtime Gore supporters. ``Women
deserve a president who `gets' that and who will fight for the
equality women deserve and craft the policies of support their
families need.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not even officially announced his candidacy, although
his aides said Tuesday that he would do so June 16. That is far
earlier than had once seemed necessary for the incumbent vice
president and shows how intense the competition is.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's event was notable too because it united three figures
_ Mrs. Clinton, Gore and his wife, Tipper _ who by their assemblage
brought to mind the absent fourth.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was down the street at the White House,
was mentioned only in passing. Still, he loomed in a contradictory
way.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the Gore campaign wanted to signal that Gore
was the opposite of Clinton _ a devoted husband whose private life
would not lead to the kind of political upheaval brought on by
Clinton's extramarital affair. As Gore said of his wife, ``She has
taught me the meaning of a strong, loving partnership that lasts
for life.'' Mrs. Clinton called Gore a ``remarkable husband and
father.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, as he boasted of his advocacy of numerous
issues important to women, the vice president was really boasting
of the Clinton presidency _ in passing the Family Medical Leave
Act, in rebuffing any erosion of abortion rights, and in
restricting children's access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing was clear: The Gore campaign needs to attract
women.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Gore told the crowd point blank: ``One of the main goals
of the campaign will be to energize women to support Al. We need
your help to share with the country his vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinion surveys have consistently shown Gore lagging behind two
Republican presidential prospects, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and
Elizabeth Dole, both in general and among women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that he is not doing well with anybody, and
therefore he's not doing well with women,'' one Democratic
consultant said. ``Part of the overall problem is that people _
women, men, old, young _ don't know much about Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Mandel, director of the Eagleton Institute for Politics and
a specialist in women's voting patterns, said that Gore had a
built-in advantage because women tended to vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no strong evidence from voting behavior in the past
two decades that women will cross over in large numbers and vote
for Republican women,'' Ms. Mandel said, with an eye on Mrs. Dole's
pitch to women. ``It's Gore's to lose, as far as women are
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally gave Gore a chance to recite his support for issues on
which women have tended to focus, even though those issues affect
the population at large.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Clinton, he did not use the word ``abortion,'' but he
said, ``I will always, always defend a woman's right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Every time Congress has tried to play politics with
that fundamental, personal right, imposing gag rules and attaching
anti-choice language to any bill they can think of, we have stood
up to them and stopped them. If they try it again, we'll stop them
again. And if they try it after the year 2000, with your help, I'll
stop them. That hard-won right will be safe with me as your
president.''
</P>
<P>
   While representing a relatively conservative Tennessee
congressional district in the House in the 1970s and '80s, Gore
voted in favor of numerous anti-abortion bills. The National Right
to Life Committee gave him a favorable rating of 84 percent between
1977 and 1984; the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League rated him as voting with the anti-abortion side 80 percent
of the time. As a senator, he voted more in favor of abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been outspoken about his position on a proposed ban
on certain late-term abortions, but his aides said Tuesday that he
would allow such a procedure if it were necessary to protect the
health of the woman, which is the same view held by Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
