<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW RECOVERS, NASDAQ FALLS AMID INTEREST-RATE WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks sold off early Tuesday on concerns that the
Federal Reserve might raise interest rates later this month. But
late in the day, the Dow Jones industrial average recovered, while
the NASDAQ composite index declined.
</P>
<P>
   The interest rate worries were sparked by results from a monthly
survey of the nation's purchasing managers. The survey showed that
growth and inflationary pressures in the manufacturing sector were
both stronger than expected in May.
</P>
<P>
   The report caused a selloff in the bond market, where interest
rates rose to their highest levels in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks also slumped after the report was released. But the Dow
Jones industrial average, which at one point during the morning was
down 150 points, rallied later on, largely on the strength of
cyclical stocks like Alcoa, Caterpillar and International Paper,
issues that depend most heavily on a strong economy to generate
profits. The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 10,596.26, up
36.52 points.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ, however, fell 58.49 points, or 2.37 percent, to
2,470.52. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, dragged down by
technology giants like Intel and Microsoft, fell 7.58 points, or
six-tenths of a percent, to 1,294.26.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purchasing managers' numbers were not comfortable,'' said
Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst at Prudential Securities. ``For
the time being, this is a market that is fixated on numbers, not
earnings.'' He added, referring to the employment report, due out
Friday, ``The wage component of that report will be closely
scrutinized by the Fed, and by the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments by William McDonough, president of the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York, reinforced the impression that policy-makers seem
increasingly concerned that inflationary pressures are building in
the economy. On Tuesday, McDonough said the Fed was wary about
April's sharp increase in consumer prices _ the largest monthly
increase in more than nine years. He warned markets not to assume
the big jump was merely a one-time event.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in interest rates is causing equity strategists and
money managers to reposition their portfolios. It was disclosed
Tuesday that Jeff Vinik, the former lead portfolio of Fidelity's
Magellan fund who now heads his own asset management firm, cut his
equity exposure by about $3 billion during the first quarter,
selling out positions in Intel, Microsoft and Compaq Computer,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   And last week Christine Callies, chief investment strategist at
Credit Suisse First Boston, announced the first shift in her model
portfolio in more than two years by paring her position in stocks.
``We cut our equity exposure because the market is becoming
increasingly sensitive to the back-up in interest rates,'' she said
Tuesday. ``Over the next year, we expect the total return on stocks
will lag that of bonds by about seven percentage points.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Callies lowered her equity exposure by 5 percent, to 55
percent. Thirty percent of her portfolio is in bonds and 15 percent
is in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Financial service stocks, which are acutely sensitive to rising
interest rates, were hammered Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, a Dow component, fell 1 3/4, to 42 15/16. Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter slumped 4 3/4, to 91 3/4. Lehman Brothers
dropped 3, to 51 3/8. Charles Schwab declined 6, to 99 1/2. And
Merrill Lynch, which on Tuesday disclosed an expanded Internet
trading service, fell 8 3/4, to 75 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Computer and other technology stocks also suffered.
Hewlett-Packard and IBM were two of the biggest losers among Dow
stocks. Hewlett-Packard fell 4 3/16, to 90 1/8, and IBM dropped 4,
to 112. Intel, which said Tuesday that it had agreed to buy
Dialogic Corp. for about $780 million in cash, fell 3 3/8, to 50
11/16. Microsoft fell 2 3/16, to 78 1/2. America Online shed 6 1/8,
to 113 1/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
