<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TIPPER'S TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Back in 1995, my mother felt that Al Gore needed a
little boost.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote him a letter telling him what a great job he had done
hosting the pope's visit to Baltimore. She also told him that, no
matter what anyone else said, she thought he was really sexy.
</P>
<P>
   She addressed the letter to The Honorable Albert Gore Jr., Home
of the Vice President, Observatory Circle, 37th Street and
Massachusetts Avenue Northwest, Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   It came back a few days later, stamped ``Addressee Unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   I knew then that Al Gore was in trouble. If he made such a faint
impression on the government he was reinventing, would he seem any
more vivid to the rest of the country?
</P>
<P>
   Too bad he didn't get that maternal pat on the back. Because now
he is clearly in a shame spiral about his lack of sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain Tipper Gore's lusty cheerleading Tuesday on
the ``Today'' show?
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was her role to loosen up her ironing board of a
husband, Mrs. Gore told NBC's Claire Shipman: ``If you're talking
about the fact that the man is somewhat reserved, yeah, he is. . .
. That's the way he was when he was 17 when I met him. That was
something I liked in him _ handsome, sexy, a little reserved. Watch
out, America.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shipman also reported that Mrs. Gore made a racy joke to
journalists about ``her husband's bedtime attire, or lack
thereof.''
</P>
<P>
   The dread lovey-dovey.
</P>
<P>
   When a politician lacks that essential spark, his wife often
jumps in and vouches for his sex appeal.
</P>
<P>
   I remember when Kitty Dukakis tried to do this for her ironing
board of a husband, Michael. The passionate Kitty did her best to
make the passionless Michael seem sentient, but it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalynn attempted to spice up Jimmy (the Cardigan) Carter by
confiding during a Barbara Walters interview that she and her
husband liked to sleep in the same bed.
</P>
<P>
   Political wives sharing erotic moments is just plain yucky. This
is worse than T.M.I. It's M.T.M.I., Much Too Much Information.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it backfires. When a wife has to hawk her husband's
sexiness with a megaphone, it just makes him seem even less sexy.
</P>
<P>
   You never heard Jackie or Hillary promoting their husbands'
sexuality. With Jack and Bill, of course, the problem was libidinal
overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores are always broadcasting what a frisky couple they are,
with tales of romantic insouciance on planes and in limos. He even
said they were the inspiration for the preppy Romeo and Juliet in
``Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   They want to project this image not only to jazz up Al but also
to contrast their own stable marriage with the Clintons' difficult
one.
</P>
<P>
   But after the sexual Armageddon of the last year, it is passing
strange to see Gore's biggest supporters trying to transform him
into a stud.
</P>
<P>
   It is also weird that the same Democrats who argued during
impeachment that a politician's sex life was nobody's business are
now promoting Gore's sex life as a selling point.
</P>
<P>
   At the Mayflower Hotel on Tuesday morning, Hillary and Tipper
headlined a ``Women for Gore'' pep rally, but it didn't seem all
that peppy with only half the meeting room filled.
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists had assumed that the candidate's Good Husband
credentials would impress women voters post-Monica. And on family
leave, abortion rights, women's health, the environment and gun
control, Gore's record is extremely women-friendly. But his
advisers are alarmed that he has lost a lot of the women's support
that helped elect and re-elect Bill Clinton and sustain him through
the Monica morass.
</P>
<P>
   For women, Al and Bill are the Good Boy-Bad Boy archetypes. Al
does the dishes and changes the diapers and wears the white chef's
hat at backyard barbecues. Bill is the seductive contractor who
runs off with the client's wife.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of women to the president and vice president may
seem mystifying: sticking with Bill through so many egregious
episodes, and now turning on Al despite his sterling behavior. But
women are always ambivalent about male archetypes. And the Gore
campaign's attempt to sexualize the candidate will not help.
</P>
<P>
   If Al really is a tiger, then Tipper is really lucky. But I wish
she would keep it to herself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
