<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOPEZ STILL SEEKING U.S. OPEN CROWN
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When we last spotted her on a fairway at a U.S. Women's Open,
Nancy Lopez waved a white flag of surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez laughed as her golf towel flapped in the breeze while one
of her irons served as an ad-lib flagpole. The move was a
tongue-in-cheek tribute to the difficulty of Blackwolf Run Golf
Course, where Lopez shot 18-over par for 36 holes, missing the cut
at the 1998 event.
</P>
<P>
   Meant to be a moment of levity, Lopez's action may some day
provide a fitting epitaph for a Hall of Fame career. Although she
has 48 victories in LPGA tour events, Lopez is best known for the
one that has gotten away: the Women's Open. The tour's
most-recognized working mother has nine top-10 finishes in 19
appearances, including four seconds, but has never captured the
most prestigious title in women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, 42, resumes pursuit of her personal Holy Grail Thursday
at Old Waverly Golf Club in West Point, Miss. She will arrive with
a pair of creaking, arthritic knees and the knowledge that she
already is older than the oldest champion in Open history (Fay
Crocker, 40, in 1955).
</P>
<P>
   Lopez also knows something else. This figures to be her best
chance before retirement to cheat Father Time and pick up an Open
title because of her familiarity with the course.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez lives in Albany, Ga., a short plane ride away, and has
been a frequent visitor to Old Waverly in recent years. When the
course opened in 1988, she joined designer Jerry Pate, Ben Crenshaw
and the late Heather Farr in a four-player match to christen the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Old Waverly has got me more excited than I've been
about the Open in years,'' said Lopez, whose most recent runner-up
finish came in 1997, when she lost by a stroke to Alison Nicholas.
``Last year, I knew in my heart that (Blackwolf Run) was not a
course I was going to win on because it was not one of my
favorites. This course should be more friendly to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played there many times. I know it a lot better than I've
known past U.S. Open courses. I consider that a big plus in my
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Might that be enough to allow the most celebrated runner-up in
Women's Open history to finally find the winner's circle? Or is
Lopez destined to follow the same career path as Sam Snead, who
owns the PGA Tour record for tournament victories (81) but never
captured a U.S. Open title?
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb, the LPGA tour's leading money winner, said Lopez
still has the physical tools to win an Open despite a record that
shows just one tournament triumph since 1993. But Webb wondered
Lopez's mental approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to win a golf tournament, especially when you tell
yourself, `I've got to win this week,' '' Webb said. ``That's a lot
of pressure to put on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Lopez will be ladling on the self-induced pressure this
week. In her heart, she knows this may be her last, best chance to
fill the one remaining void in an otherwise glittering career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I never win an Open, I would have to say something would be
missing in my career,'' Lopez said. ``But it's not in God's plans
if it doesn't happen, and I just have to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIAL, GOLF MUSEUM TO PAY TRIBUTE TO HOGAN
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Hogan, widow of Fort Worth golf legend Ben Hogan, will
log significant frequent flyer miles this week while accepting
honors in the name of her late husband.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, who died in 1997, will be honored Wednesday at the
Memorial Tournament in Dublin, Ohio. Valerie Hogan is scheduled to
attend while tournament officials unveil a plaque in tribute to
Hogan in Memorial Park at Muirfield Village Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Hogan also is scheduled to attend Tuesday's unveiling of
the Ben Hogan Room at the U.S. Golf Association Museum in Far
Hills, N.J. Also known as Golf House, the museum will be home to a
1,000-square-foot display of more than 300 personal items donated
by the Hogan family.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those items, for the past four decades, had been on
display at Colonial Country Club in Fort Worth, Texas. But it was
Hogan's wish for the items to be placed in a museum setting upon
his death, hence the move to Golf House.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 members from two Fort Worth country clubs, Colonial
and Shady Oaks, have made plans to join Valerie Hogan for Tuesday's
unveiling at Golf House. Included is Marty Leonard, daughter of
Colonial founder Marvin Leonard. The room opens to the public for
the first time June 9. JACK APPEARS BACK
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus considers this week's Memorial Tournament the acid
test in determining whether his artificial left hip will permit him
to play the quality of golf that will make him want to compete in
future major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, 59, has expressed plans to compete in the 1999 U.S.
Open. But that is contingent upon a satisfactory effort at the
Memorial, which will mark Nicklaus' first appearance at a PGA Tour
event this season. At least one fellow competitor expects big
things from the Golden Bear based on his performance at the Bell
Atlantic Classic, where Nicklaus finished 18th in a Senior Tour
event on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   It marked Nicklaus' first tournament since finishing 13th at the
U.S. Senior Open in July 1998. John Grace, a Fort Worth resident
and Senior Tour competitor, played in both events and said it was
easy to notice the difference in Nicklaus' swing and comfort level
on the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like night and day,'' Grace said. ``He looks so much
better now. Last summer, you could tell he was struggling just to
walk. But when I watched him (last month), Jack's swing looked
fantastic to me.'' PAK'S ADJUSTMENT PERIOD
</P>
<P>
   Se Ri Pak, defending champ at the U.S. Women's Open and 1998
LPGA rookie of the year, finds her game in comparative free fall
heading into Thursday's title defense.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who claimed two major championships among her four
victories last season, has averaged just $5,424 per start this year
(11 tournaments, $59,669). She does not rank among the LPGA's top
10 in any statistical category.
</P>
<P>
   During the off-season, Pak broke ties with her business manager
and her swing coach, the renowned David Leadbetter. Pak, 21, said
she has found it more difficult to focus on the course this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that easy after last year,'' Pak said. ``I need to
find a better balance with my game and my private life. I need to
focus better on the course. I'm thinking about too many other
things.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
