alone in turn 4, breaking a right-side wheel. The track's
15-foot-high catch fence initially contained the tire, deflecting
it back on the track, but then a trailing car driven by John Paul
Jr. knocked it into the grandstand, killing Pyatte instantly. (Cox
News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) AGUA PRIETA, Mexico -- June 1, 1999 --
MEXICO-BABY-SMUGGLING, 6-1 -- Martina Toscano Quiroz, center, with
her children, Sussena Enriquez, 11, left, and Aurelia, 12, in their
two- room shack near the Mexican border with Arizona. Last week, a
lawyer and two women in New York were arrested and charged with
running a cross-country baby-smuggling ring that the U.S.
government says sold Ms. Toscano's children, and at least 14
others, for up to $22,000 each to couples in New York, preying on
their desperation to have children. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ATLANTA -- June 1, 1999 -- OLY-BILLYPAYNE-COX-2, 6-1 --
ACOG chief Billy Payne, on hand to dedicate the Georgia
International Horse Park in 1995, presents the Atlanta Cup trophy
to Maria Mehrdorf, of Germany, winner of the three-day event. In
recent days, Payne cashed out, his land deals bringing in more than
$1 million in profit without putting a dime of his own money into
it. (Curtis Compton/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ATLANTA -- June 1, 1999 -- OLY-BILLYPAYNE-COX-1, 6-1 --
ACOG chief Billy Payne in Atlanta. In recent days, the Olympic czar
cashed out, his land deals bringing in more than $1 million in
profit without putting a dime of his own money into it. (William
Berry/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) VENICE, Fla.-- June 1, 1999 -- FL-WILDFIRES-FLOATER-2
---, 6-1 -- From left, Phil Segestrom, Angie Edbrooke and Julie
Verde look at smoke billowing from wildfires while parked on the
South Moon Drive overpass on Tuesday. Fire officials called for
reinforcements as they battled a huge wind-whipped fire in the
Okefenokee Swamp that already was being fought by crews from across
the nation. (Armando Solares/Sarasota Herald Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) VENICE, Fla.-- June 1, 1999 -- FL-WILDFIRES-FLOATER-1
---, 6-1 -- Trucks make their way northbound up I-75 on Tuesday as
smoke billows from wildfires in the background. Fire officials
called for reinforcements as they battled a huge wind-whipped fire
in the Okefenokee Swamp that already was being fought by crews from
across the nation. (Armando Solares/Sarasota Herald Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LITTLETON, Colo. -- June 1, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL, 6-1 --
Columbine High School students leave the school after retrieving
personal belongings on Tuesday. The students were allowed back for
the first time since the bloodbath six weeks ago to retrieve
backpacks and other belongings they left behind when they ran for
their lives. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) VOZROZHDENIYE ISLAND, Uzbekistan -- June 1, 1999 --
ANTHRAX-ISLAND-3, 6-1 -- Two men walk through an abandoned Soviet
facility used for experiments with anthrax on a remote island in
the heart of the inland Aral Sea. In 1988, Russian soldiers dug
huge pits and poured sludge containing anthrax into the ground in
what today is the world's largest anthrax burial ground. (Judith
Miller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) EAST QUOGUE, N.Y. -- June 1, 1999 --
MASTERPIECE-NEWSLETTER, 6-1 -- Edith Finke (with Paddington),
producer of the Anglo-Files: A Newsletter for Fans of British
Television. It is a numbingly detailed and exhaustive compendium on
the period dramas, murder mysteries and reborn classics of British
television and allied planets in theater and film, as well as a
reminder that in a culture addicted to New! More! Hotter! Sexier!
there is still a fiercely loyal constituency for old, less, cooler
and a bit dowdy. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- June 1, 1999 -- MASS-MOCA-2, 6-1
-- Joseph Beuys' ``Lightning with Stag in its Glare,'' in the
Fulkerson Gallery at the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art
in North Adams. The museum, which has been more than 10 years in
the making, has a home so plainly beautiful it barely needs art.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- June 1, 1999 -- MASS-MOCA-1, 6-1
-- The Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art in North Adams. The
Massachusets Museum of Contemporary Art, the sprawling visual and
performing arts center that opened last weekend, looks like a
museum that the Shakers might have built, if the Shakers had liked
very large, multi-media works of art and performance events poised
on the cutting-edge of computer imaging technology. (Jeffery A.
Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PRINCETON, N.J. -- June 1, 1999 -- PRINCETON-JEWS-2, 6-1
-- Steve Steinberg plays his guitar during a Reformed Jewish
service at Princeton. Jews on campus along with Prof. Stanley Katz,
a professor and president-elect of the university's Center for
Jewish Life, are trying to raise Princeton's Jewish enrollment,
presently at 10 percent, which has dropped from a high of 18
percent. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PRINCETON, N.J. -- June 1, 1999 -- PRINCETON-JEWS-1, 6-1
-- Prof. Stanley Katz, a professor and president-elect of its
Center for Jewish Life at Princeton, in his office during an
interview. Katz and other Jews on campus are trying to raise
Princeton's Jewish enrollment, presently at 10 percent, which has
dropped from a high of 18 percent. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- June 1, 1999 -- MOVIES-GOODING-BOS, 6-1 --
Actor Cuba Gooding, Jr., during an interview in April. In his new
movie, ``Instinct,'' which opens Friday, Gooding plays an ambitious
young psychiatrist bent on bringing back to the speaking world a
primatologist, played by Anthony Hopkins, who has been rendered
silent after living with African gorillas for two years.
(Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 1, 1999 -- PARTY-CAKES, 6-1 -- A cake is
prepared at Saint Ambroeus, on New York's Madison Avenue. The party
cake has become an over-the-top symbol of creativity and, some
would say, competitive excess. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 1, 1999 -- HALAL-BUTCHERS, 6-1 -- Khalid
Pervez, right, owns the Halal Meat Company in Brooklyn. In almost
any neighborhood in America where Muslims make their home, halal
meat shops are the new butchers in an old-fashioned way. To
non-Muslims the shops can be mysterious, even intimidating. But to
others they are a happy addition to the checkerboard of tiny,
specialty food shops which provide impeccable meat and intensely
personal service. (Ozier Muhammad, right, Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- June 1, 1999 -- CLINTON-MEDIA-VIOLENCE, 6-1
-- President Clinton talks to Arthur Sawe, 9, of Seattle, as Mrs.
Clinton takes the podium during a ceremony in the Rose Garden of
the White House on Tuesday. Clinton on Tuesday ordered the Federal
Trade Commission and Justice Department to conduct a study of the
marketing of mayhem by Hollywood. Sawe, whose concerns about
violent video games inspired stricter enforcement of video game
ratings in Washington state, addressed the event. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- June 1, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-GORE-2, 6-1 --
Vice President Al Gore embraces first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
on Tuesday after Mrs. Clinton addressed a group of women voters.
Mrs. Clinton reached out to women voters on Tuesday calling for
them to support Gore, who lags behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush
among that group in recent polls. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) VOZROZHDENIYE ISLAND, Uzbekistan -- June 1, 1999 --
ANTHRAX-ISLAND-2, 6-1 -- Cages which housed animals used in anthrax
experiments, at an abandoned facility on this remote island in the
heart of the inland Aral Sea. In 1988, Russian soldiers dug huge
pits and poured sludge containing anthrax into the ground on the
island, burying not only the germs but, Moscow hoped, a grave
political threat. Today the island is the world's largest anthrax
burial ground. (Judith Miller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) VOZROZHDENIYE ISLAND, Uzbekistan -- June 1, 1999 --
ANTHRAX-ISLAND-1, 6-1 -- An abandoned laboratory, left, and animal
houses, right, on this remote island in the heart of the inland
Aral Sea which was used by Russian scientists working on
experiments involving anthrax. In 1988, Russian soldiers dug huge
pits and poured sludge containing anthrax into the ground here,
burying not only the germs but, Moscow hoped, a grave political
threat. Today the island is the world's largest anthrax burial
ground. (Judith Miller/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- June 1, 1999 -- MRSCLINTON-GORE, 6-1 --
Vice President Al Gore, right, talks with Tony Coelho, center, his
campaign chairman, on Tuesday outside a hotel after Gore and first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton addressed a group of women supporters.
Mrs. Clinton reached out to women voters to support Gore, who lags
behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush among that group in recent polls.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
