attended by Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., in Marietta on Saturday. In a May
press release, Barr denounced Wiccans; Amazing Lizardo, right,
pokes fun at the congressman by wearing a king's crown stating
``Bob Barr For King-USA.'' (David Tulis/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) MONTROSE, N.Y. -- June 1, 1999 --
NY-DISCIPLINE-PRINCIPAL, 6-1 -- Dr. Joanne Falinski's 6-year-long
dispute with the school district has generated 6,000 pages of legal
papers, so far. Dr. Falinski, who had been principal at the Furnace
Woods Elementary School for 10 years until her suspension, is
accused of 55 charges of misconduct and insubordination on grounds
that she discouraged five children from receiving special
education. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) HOBOKEN, N.J. -- June 1, 1999 -- NY-COMMUTER-TAX, 6-1 --
Gov. Christine Todd Whitman during the evening rush hour Tuesday at
a Hoboken train station, where she announced that the state had
sued New York over its commuter tax. The suit charges that it is a
Constitutional violation for New York to continue levying the 0.45
percent wage tax on the thousands of workers who live in
Connecticut, Pennsylvania and New Jersey. (Keith Meyers/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- June 1, 1999 -- ANTHRAX-ISLAND-4-B&AMP;W, 6-1 --
Yusup Kamalov, an Uzbek scientist who heads the Union for the
Defense of the Aral Sea, an independent environmental group, stands
in front of a former fishing trawler on the bed of the Aral Sea. In
1988, Russian soldiers buried anthrax on Vozrozhedeniye Island, a
remote island in the heart of the inland Aral Sea. Kamalov says the
Russians ``have never come clean about these programs.'' (Eric
Hilger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
