<HEADER>
A9031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-GENERAL-KILLED-N     06-01 0159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-GENERAL-KILLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV GENERAL KILLED IN BOMBING RAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ One of Yugoslavia's top generals has been
killed by NATO bombing, the first high-ranking casualty of the air
campaign, news reports here said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Ljubisa Velickovic, the deputy chief of staff and
former air force chief, was killed on Monday night near Belgrade. A
local radio station, Radio Pancevo, which in the past has proved
reliable, reported the death on Tuesday, citing military sources.
The official state news has yet to mention the general's death.
</P>
<P>
   Velickovic was killed while visiting ``first defense lines''
near Belgrade, Radio Pancevo said, most likely an anti-aircraft
unit for which he was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Velickovic, a pilot by training, was one of the most popular and
respected generals in Yugoslavia, the radio station said. His
funeral will be on Thursday, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
