<HEADLINE>
TRIMMER HOWARD LEADS TCU INTO NCAA OUTDOOR TRACK MEET
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bryan Howard realized how fast he could be when he felt his
slowest.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's top sprinter didn't feel quite so fleet at the Western
Athletic Conference track meet on May 22, when he struggled with
asthma. Yet he still finished with his fastest time of the year in
the 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   His time of 20.14 seconds gave him a No. 4 national ranking in
the event heading into the NCAA Outdoor Track and Field
Championships, which begin Wednesday at Bronco Stadium in Boise,
Idaho. The senior from Moreno Valley, Calif., also clocked a 10.13
in the 100 meters, which matched his previous best in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Even more encouraging was his ability to run stride-for-stride
with defending NCAA 100 meters champion Leonard Myles-Mills of
Brigham Young, who beat Howard by .03 seconds in the 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My asthma was flaring up and I didn't have my inhaler with
me,'' Howard said. ``Plus I started cramping up in the 100.
Considering all of that, to run that fast felt good. I felt I could
have run faster. And Leonard, well, I figured if I can run with
him, I can run with anyone. Well, I ran with him and I could have
beaten him.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard didn't think anything of the sort a year ago when he
plodded through a season overweight and out of shape after
transferring from Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 NCAA indoor champion in the 55 meters, Howard left
Auburn in the messy wake of coach Harvey Glance's resignation and
was out of training for months before reporting to TCU in January
of 1998 weighing 196 pounds, nearly 25 more than his current
weight. He sat out the indoor season _ ``I didn't want to embarrass
myself,'' he said _ and felt he had hit bottom in a difficult
outdoor season.
</P>
<P>
   But Howard amazed himself by earning a spot in the national top
10 with a 10.19 100 meters and running a powerful leadoff leg on
the Horned Frogs' NCAA champion 4x100 team, which ran a collegiate
record 38.04.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I was shocked,'' Howard said. ``I don't know how I
managed to run 10.19. Last year, I never felt right, but I came
back as a contender. After last season, I knew something good was
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in top shape at 173 pounds, the 5-foot-11 Howard said he
will challenge Myles-Mills, second-seeded Coby Miller of Auburn and
No. 1 John Capel of Florida, who ran 19.99 three weeks ago, for the
national championship. To that end, he declined an invitation to
run in the 100 meters despite his No. 8 national ranking in order
to concentrate on the 200 meters and the 4x100 relay.
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Monte Stratton said the lighter workload will give
Howard an advantage over the other top contenders, all of whom will
double in the 100 and 200 meters. Myles-Mills and Capel will also
run on relay teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The double is not impossible, but it's very difficult,''
Stratton said. ``To win it, you'd have to run six rounds of sprints
against the highest-level competition, as well as two rounds of the
relay. This way, he'll be fresher and his strength will be more of
a factor in the 200.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard will need that strength to give TCU the lead in the relay
against the likes of Florida, Southern Cal and Brigham Young. That
will be essential in the final because the Frogs will be running
without their regular No. 3 man, Lindel Frater, who is out with a
hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnny Collins, normally a 400-meter specialist, replacing
Frater on a squad that also included Jarmiene Holloway and `Flash'
Williams, the Frogs ran a best time of 38.84, not quite up to the
national-best 38.64 they posted with Frater, but still good enough
to make TCU the team to beat, especially if Williams is back to 100
percent after missing a month with a hamstring injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If `Flash' is full speed, we're ready for anyone,'' Stratton
said, ``and he's been running full out in practice. We won't be the
prohibitive favorite like we would if we had our A team. Without
them, we're just one of the boys. But we have as good a chance as
any of the boys. We'll be right there with all of them.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
