<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WOMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MAKES BID FOR VOTE OF WOMEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to bolster his standing with female voters
that have been vital to past Democratic victories, Al Gore vowed
Tuesday to protect abortion rights and to pursue health care,
education and gun-control initiatives that are popular with women.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president made his pitch at a ``Women for Gore'' event
where his White House bid was endorsed by first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and a host of prominent female politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will formally announce his presidential bid June 16 in his
hometown of Carthage, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The women's event was intended to energize a constituency that
was crucial to Bill Clinton's two White House victories but has
been less enthusiastic about his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Early surveys show a softness in support for Gore among women
and a willingness to consider top Republican contenders for the
White House, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former Red Cross chief
Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``In comparison to Clinton, Gore has less of that empathetic
quality, the ``he understands my problems''' said Andrew Kohut, who
directs polling for the Pew Research Center. A recent Pew survey
had Gore trailing Bush and Dole among women, although not as badly
as among men.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his supporters have clearly felt pressured to emphasize
the vice president's commitment to women's issues and his intention
to continue popular initiatives begun during the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president recited a laundry list of measures targeted
at female voters, such as making preschool available to all
children, increasing breast cancer research funding and cracking
down on guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get guns away from our children and criminals,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said many of his proposals were tailored to modern
families, such as extending the Family Medical Leave Act to give
parents time so they can meet with their children's teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of sentimentalizing families that no longer exist,
let's give families the help they need,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also pounded on an issue that has been critical to Democrats'
success with many women, particularly young professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Although he never actually used the word ``abortion,'' Gore made
it clear that he supported the right of women to choose to end
their pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will always, always defend a woman's right to choose,'' said
Gore to loud applause. He emphasized that he intended to block
Republican efforts to chip away at abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Congress has tried to play politics with that
fundamental personal right in imposing gag rules and attaching anti
-choice language to any bill they can think of, we have stopped
them,'' he said. ``If they try it after the year 2000, with your
help I'll stop them. That hard won right will be safe with me as
your president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's unequivocal support for abortion rights clearly
differentiates him from his Republican opponents, including Bush,
who successfully prodded the Legislature this session to pass a law
requiring parents to be notified before their minor daughters could
get an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also cited the influence of his mother, Pauline, who he
said was one of the first women to graduate from Vanderbilt law
school. And he lauded the work on mental health spearheaded by his
wife, Tipper, who earlier had lavished praise on her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want America to know the Al Gore I love,'' she said. Tipper
Gore also noted the political axiom that clearly she hopes holds
true in November of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we all know from past elections, when women vote, Democrats
win,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who is extremely popular with professional
women, also lauded Gore for pushing issues that affect women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been out in front for women, for families and
children throughout his life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, however, have fretted that Hillary Clinton's
ability to help Gore will be hampered by her own political
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore will have the backing of other political women,
including a number of prominent members of Congress and state
legislatures. The campaign said Gore had received 4,500 pledges of
support from women in every state .
</P>
<P>
   One of those backers is Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, who
complimented Gore's commitment to education.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston congresswoman told the crowd that Gore ``will not
have to stutter over whether teachers get increased pay or improve
the quality of teaching. He will stand front and center and say
teachers are the backbone of America.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in the largely supportive Democratic audience there
were voices of ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting for him to win me over,'' said 25-year old Bronwen
Clark, who works for a Democratic consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Her colleague Tonya Koslo, 30, added, ``He's going to have to
prove himself a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore also had a defender in Abby Rozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like the only person who likes him in my office. He has a
lot of integrity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rozen, 25, said she recognizes that Gore has not been a good
campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a tin ear,'' she said. ``He can sing loudly, but not on
key.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
