u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-01 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DEFENDANTS TAKE STAND AS DEFENSE RESTS IN LOUIMA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a month of often graphic accounts and a
dramatic midtrial guilty plea by one defendant, testimony in the
Abner Louima police brutality case sputtered to an end Tuesday when
the only officer who had said he would take the witness stand
changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Sgt. Michael Bellomo, who is charged with trying
to cover up part of the assault on Louima by other officers, means
that none of the defendants have testified in their own defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo had been the only one of the defendants whose lawyer had
said at the trial's start that he planned to take the stand, but
the sergeant told reporters Tuesday that he decided over the long
holiday weekend not to testify after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I re-evaluated it,'' Bellomo, 37, said outside the courtroom
in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn. He said that all the evidence
that the jury needed about his role in the case had already entered
the record through other witnesses, so that his testimony was no
longer required.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors from the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn say that
Bellomo tried to cover up the beating of Louima in a police car by
four officers after Louima was arrested following a melee outside a
Brooklyn nightclub. One of those officers, Justin Volpe, pleaded
guilty last week to participating in the beating in the police car
and with ramming a stick in Louima's rectum in a restroom at the
70th Precinct station house in Brooklyn. Bellomo is not charged
with participating in any of the assaults or with trying to cover
up the restroom attack.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant's lawyer, John Patten, told reporters that ``if
you're in trouble'' in a trial, ``you have nothing to lose'' by
taking the witness stand, but that considering the evidence
presented in the trial, ``we felt we were in a good position.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tuesday, instead of hearing Bellomo personally deny the
cover-up charge and watch him try to hold his own under
cross-examination, jurors and spectators heard only two brief
witnesses whom the sergeant's lawyer had called to testify about
specific points in his case.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the three officers still on trial had rested their
defenses earlier Tuesday or last week after calling few or no
witnesses, so once Bellomo's two witnesses had concluded, Judge
Eugene Nickerson told the jurors that they would hear closing
arguments Wednesday and begin deliberating Thursday after he
instructs them on the laws governing the case.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors will not have to deliberate on the most notorious
defendant in the case _ the one prosecutors painted as Louima's
chief torturer in the police station restroom _ because that
defendant, Volpe, interrupted the trial on May 25 to plead guilty
to various accusations, including the attack in the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that the assault occurred after Louima was
arrested in a street melee and that Volpe mistakenly believed that
it was Louima who had punched him during the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the restroom attack tore Louima's rectum and
bladder, requiring two months of hospitalization and three
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe, who was dismissed from the police force, could be
sentenced to up to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that the three men still on trial with Bellomo _
Officers Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese _ also
took part in the assault in the police car, and that Schwarz held
Louima down while Volpe assaulted him in the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors have charged that Bellomo also tried to cover up
an assault by Volpe on another man, Patrick Antoine, after the
street brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Because Louima and Antoine, both Haitian immigrants, are black,
and the officers are white, the case has had bitter racial
overtones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
