<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCETON-JEWS-ART-750&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCETON PUZZLE: WHERE HAVE JEWISH STUDENTS GONE?
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make  individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ As a high school student 50 years ago, Stanley
Katz thought Princeton University was paradise, a place inhabited
by pipe-smoking scholars with patches on their elbows and
mustaches. ``I said, `Katz, that's you.'''
</P>
<P>
   But as he learned more about Princeton, it dawned on him ``that
this was the last place in the Ivy League _ except maybe Dartmouth
_ that was for me,'' he said. ``It became clear to me that if not
anti-Semitic, it wasn't congenial to Jews.'' He went to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Today Katz is a Princeton professor and president-elect of its
Center for Jewish Life, and the university is a far more welcoming
place. The president, the provost and the dean of the college are
Jewish. So are many of the faculty members. Katz's center is a
lively place, with a large kosher kitchen and a stream of events,
from casino nights and swing dances to Talmud classes and Friday
night services.
</P>
<P>
   So how can it be, Katz and other Jews on campus are asking, that
Princeton's Jewish enrollment has fallen by nearly half since the
early 1980s _ to about 10 percent, or about 450 undergraduates,
from a high of 18 percent? Why do other Ivy League campuses _
Harvard, Yale, Columbia, Penn _ manage to keep Jewish populations
of at least a quarter and in some cases more than a third? (The
figures, drawn from surveys by the University of California at Los
Angeles that ask first-year college students their religious
preferences, are considered rough estimates.)
</P>
<P>
   The decline in Jewish enrollment at Princeton is not new: the
surveys suggest that it reached the present level in the early
'90s. And the figures closely track a nationwide pattern; the
percentage of college students who identify themselves as Jews has
declined steadily over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But in April, a series of front-page articles in The Daily
Princetonian, the student newspaper, called attention to the
decline and touched off a campuswide debate.
</P>
<P>
   It is a touchy subject, and not just because Princeton thought
it had long since put to rest its ancient reputation for
anti-Semitism. Many Jews and non-Jews on campus point out that even
at 10 percent, Princeton's Jewish enrollment far exceeds the Jewish
makeup of the general population, which is roughly two percent.
(Minority enrollment _ black, Hispanic and Asian-American students
_ is now 27 percent, not markedly different from the general
population.)
</P>
<P>
   And some Jewish students and professors say they fear the
discussion could make matters worse, by discouraging Jewish high
school students from applying to Princeton. ``This series of
articles likely hurt the likelihood of Princeton gaining more
Jewish students,'' a sophomore, Rebecca Opdyke, wrote in a letter
to the student newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Other Jewish students protested that the articles did not
capture the rich lives they lead at Princeton, not only in terms of
religion, but also socially and educationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Princeton is labeled as a school Jews don't go to, but
that's not true,'' said Todd S. Rich, a junior economics major from
East Brunswick who is president of the Center for Jewish Life.
``We're thriving.''
</P>
<P>
   The center has even set up a task force to consider what it
might do ``to counter this negative image,'' said Princeton's
rabbi, James S. Diamond. ``The reality is that the quality of
Jewish life here is probably as good as anywhere in the country,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Princeton, the history of anti-Semitism is tangled with the
college's exclusive private eating clubs, whose anti-Semitism was
visible as recently as 1958, when they denied bids to nearly two
dozen students, many of them Jewish. Today, not only are Jews
welcomed at the clubs _ at roughly half now, members simply sign up
for the club of their choice _ but some Jewish students even cite
the clubs as one of Princeton's attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The comfortable intertwining was visible one recent Friday
evening when some students attended Shabbat services in tuxedos and
ball gowns; they were going directly from the Jewish center to the
eating clubs, which celebrate the last day of classes with
black-tie dinners.
</P>
<P>
   The changes in the clubs are not the only sign of Princeton's
openness to Jews. William G. Bowen, Princeton's president from 1972
to 1988, signaled his interest in drawing more Jewish students in
several ways. He visited Jewish day schools. He invited the
chancellor of the Jewish Theological Seminary to deliver the annual
year-end baccalaureate address. He created a kosher dining hall on
campus. And he initiated plans for the Center for Jewish Life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was very important that Princeton be much more
inclusive in all of dimensions than it had been, and I and others
made an effort to make the place be more welcoming to Jews and
others,'' Bowen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about it in terms of numbers,'' he added. ``I
thought about it as a group of students who were outstanding and
who weren't coming to the university in the numbers they should
have, based on what they had to offer. Or if they came, they
weren't getting involved in the life of the university.''
</P>
<P>
   Some faculty members say that after Bowen's departure, there was
a relaxation of efforts to reach out to high school students _
including Jews _ who might otherwise see Princeton as an
upper-crust enclave where they would not fit in. ``The point about
perceptions and images is that you have to work hard to maintain
them,'' a history professor said. ``In the '70s and '80s they were
beginning to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is advocating affirmative action for Jews. Fred A.
Hargadon, Princeton's dean of admissions, says his office does not
consider religion at all and does not view the religious
composition of other colleges as a useful measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``No two colleges do it the same way,'' he said, ``and we don't
all admit the same 1,000 kids.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He says his office visits Jewish schools like any other high
school. This month, for example, he visited the Hebrew Academy of
the Five Towns and Rockaway High School in Cedarhurst on Long
Island, a meeting that drew nearly 600 students and parents.
Princeton took one of the academy's three applicants this year and
put another on its waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Vitow, the high school's principal, said the five-hour
visit was evidence of Princeton's interest in his students.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a senior admissions person to do this sent a very clear
message that he's very favorably disposed to our kids,'' Dr. Vitow
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Albert Goetz, a college adviser at another Jewish day
school, the Ramaz School on Manhattan's East Side, says Princeton
seems less interested in his top students than 10 or 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Princeton is a Garden of Eden for our kids,'' he said. ``It's
close to New York. It's beautiful. And you can be Jewish there. We
just can't get access.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Princeton's Jewish faculty members say the discussion
about Jewish students has put Harold Shapiro, the university's
president, in a difficult position because he feels that as a Jew
he cannot recruit Jewish students as actively as Bowen did.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said he saw no bias against Jewish students in
Princeton's admissions procedures. But he added, ``If there's
something we're doing that consciously or unconsciously
discriminates against any religion, then we should stop it, but no
one has presented me with any evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   He goes further, expressing dismay that anyone should think
about students based on their religion. ``As you know, I'm Jewish,
and not only am I Jewish, but I'm very active in the Jewish
community,'' he said. ``I know how dangerous it is to be
categorized this way.''
</P>
<P>
   One answer to those concerned about the number of Jewish
students may be an expansion of the student body. A faculty and
administration committee that studied Princeton's admissions
process last year concluded that the college was turning away many
desirable applicants because of its size. (Princeton takes about
1,150 freshmen, compared to about 1,600 at Harvard and 1,350 at
Yale.)
</P>
<P>
   The committee recommended that the college expand its entering
class by 125 to 150 students. President Shapiro and Dean Hargadon
both back such expansion and the trustees are studying the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
