<HEADLINE>
MORALES CASE DRAWS INTEREST OF FEDERAL GRAND JURY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A federal grand jury in Austin has subpoenaed
records from Attorney General John Cornyn dealing with his
investigation of Dan Morales' hiring of Houston lawyer Marc Murr in
the state's tobacco lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn has accused Morales, the former attorney general, and
Murr of falsifying signatures and backdating contracts to try to
fraudulently secure $260 million in legal fees for Murr, a longtime
Morales friend.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who succeeded Morales on Jan. 1, has repeatedly said
that the FBI was looking into Murr's role in the tobacco case. But
the subpoena is the first independent confirmation that the federal
investigation has reached a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the subpoena is ``hard evidence'' that grand jurors
are going to try to determine ``if allegations of civil fraud rise
to the level of criminal fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle obtained a copy of the subpoena from the
attorney general under an open records request.
</P>
<P>
   It was unknown if any other subpoenas had been issued.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators have consistently declined to acknowledge
an investigation, and neither Morales nor Murr returned phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has previously denied Cornyn's allegations. He also has
insisted that Murr played a crucial role in the landmark tobacco
case, often as a behind-the-scenes adviser.
</P>
<P>
   But other lawyers have said that Murr did little work on the
case, and his name didn't publicly surface until about the time the
lawsuit was settled in January 1998. The settlement netted Texas
$17.3 billion from tobacco companies, payable over the next 25
years.
</P>
<P>
   Murr withdrew a claim for about $260 million in legal fees on
May 6, one day after Cornyn alleged, in a filing in federal court,
that Murr's contracts had been doctored.
</P>
<P>
   But Murr still stands to receive $1 million from the case. That
amount, which is to be paid by cigarette makers, was awarded in
December by a national arbitration panel, which set legal fees in
the tobacco litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The same national arbitrators awarded $3.3 billion to a team of
five other outside lawyers hired by Morales for the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn's subpoena, which is dated May 20, calls for him to
produce ``any and all documents relating to internal investigations
conducted by the attorney general's office involving Marc Murr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These documents should include, but not be limited to,
affidavits, statements, correspondence, computer records, phone
records and visitor logs,'' the subpoena states.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn was directed to provide the documents by June 15. The
attorney general said he didn't believe he was required to
personally testify before grand jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, whose jurisdiction is primarily civil, said his
investigation of the Murr case ``for all intents and purposes'' has
been completed.
</P>
<P>
   He said most of his investigation was focused on Murr, not
Morales. Cornyn, a Republican, has said previously that he never
could determine that Morales, a Democrat, would have personally
benefited from Murr's legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn has alleged that two purported contracts between Morales
and Murr were fakes, created months after they were dated.
</P>
<P>
   One, dated Oct. 17, 1996, provided Murr a 3 percent contingency.
The second, dated Jan. 31, 1997, which purportedly replaced the
1996 agreement, provided a ``reasonable fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said that the Jan. 31, 1997, document had been produced
by doctoring a different contract that Morales actually had signed
that day with Murr and Dallas attorney Will Pryor, a former top
assistant to Morales.
</P>
<P>
   That contract provided that Murr and Pryor would share a 6
percent contingency for representing the state in the tobacco suit.
But Pryor said he soon quit the case because it became obvious he
wouldn't have much work to do. He said he also was concerned that
his close association with Morales could raise questions.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said he didn't know how much work Murr did on the tobacco
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Morales told the Texas Lawyer newspaper that he simply modified
the Murr-Pryor contract to include only Murr and to change some
other terms of the agreement. Morales' comments were made in April,
before Cornyn made his allegations, the newspaper said in an
article published May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said his findings were strengthened by Morales' office's
response to an open records' request that Cornyn, then a candidate
for attorney general, submitted in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Cornyn asked for a list of all outside lawyer
contracts approved by Morales. He received two responses from
Morales' office, one dated Jan. 8, 1998, and the other, Jan. 23,
1998. Each covered the same period from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said he assumed then that Morales' office had
accidentally sent him duplicate lists.
</P>
<P>
   Recent inspection by Cornyn's office, however, showed that the
Jan. 8 list, which was sent before the tobacco settlement was
announced, didn't include any contracts with Murr. But the Jan. 23
list, sent after the tobacco agreement was negotiated and Murr had
filed a claim for legal fees, included a contract with the Houston
lawyer, the purported Jan. 31, 1997, agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Both lists included the well-known 1996 contingency agreement
with the five other outside lawyers hired by Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter, who was Morales' top state lawyer on the tobacco
suit, told Cornyn's office during the investigation that Murr
admitted to him only a few weeks before the case was settled that
he didn't have a contract to represent the state against cigarette
makers.
</P>
<P>
   A tobacco company lawyer said in a sworn affidavit last year
that Morales told him that Murr _ who is neither black nor Hispanic
_ was hired to add ``diversity'' to the Texas trial team and
perform public relations chores.
</P>
<P>
   Phone records and sign-in sheets obtained by the Chronicle
earlier this year indicate that Murr infrequently visited the
attorney general's office and was only occasionally called by
Morales on state phones until shortly before the settlement was
reached.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
