<SLUG> BC-NY-TICKET-SCALPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL PASSED TO EXTEND CURRENT TICKET-SCALPING LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Failing to reach an agreement on a new law to
stiffen penalties for ticket scalping, the Legislature on Tuesday
completed passage of a bill that would extend the current law for
another year.
</P>
<P>
   The current law expired at 12:01 on Tuesday morning, and the
State Senate passed a bill on Tuesday that would reinstate it. The
Assembly passed an identical bill last week before adjourning for
the Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Critics who have long pushed for tougher restrictions were
deeply disappointed by the failure to reach an agreement on a new
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a year when the Legislature can't seem to get anything
done, they punted on this issue,'' said Blair Horner, legislative
director for the New York Public Interest Research Group, who has
lobbied against extending the current law. ``They have taken the
path of least resistance and extended a seriously flawed law.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to Gov. George E. Pataki, whose aides have
said he will sign it into law. Had the Legislature failed to pass
an extension of the current law, it would have been replaced with
an old set of ticket-scalping restrictions widely viewed as
difficult to enforce and thus ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed on Tuesday reinstates a seven-year-old law that
limits markups on the face value of any ticket to a maximum of $5
or 10 percent, whichever is greater.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators' disagreement on a new ticket-scalping law has
largely centered on the question of whether brokers should be
allowed to set their own prices for the resale of tickets to
Broadway shows, concerts, sporting contests and other special
events.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the State Senate have been pushing to largely
deregulate the resale of tickets, saying that approach would
encourage more brokers to enter the business and thereby drive
ticket prices down through free-market competition. But the
Democrats who control the Assembly have opposed the Senate's
approach, asserting that it would cause ticket prices to increase
rapidly and would allow large ticket brokers to take control of the
market at the expense of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate has in part been generated by the powerful
constituencies that have been lobbying both sides on this issue.
The Democrats have come under intense pressure from consumer
advocates and members of the state's entertainment industry who are
concerned that the free-market approach would disrupt the industry
significantly and shortchange customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
