<SLUG> BC-EDUC-MAINE-VOUCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEDERAL COURT DENIES VOUCHERS TO FAMILIES AT PAROCHIAL SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the first school voucher case to be decided at so
high a level, a federal appeals court has found that Maine families
are not entitled to public subsidies to send their children to
parochial schools.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, by a three-judge panel of the 1st U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals on Thursday, was the latest in a string of cases that
are propelling the issue toward the Supreme Court. Also last week,
Ohio's Supreme Court overturned the Cleveland program that offers
vouchers for low-income students at both public and parochial
schools, although the ruling dealt primarily with a technical issue
of state budget rules. Wisconsin's Supreme Court has upheld
vouchers for religious schools in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine ruling comes a month after the state's Supreme Court
denied a constitutional appeal on an almost identical case, in
which a group of Maine families claimed the voucher program
discriminated against them for sending their children to sectarian
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Because many Maine towns do not have their own public high
schools, the state has long provided reimbursements for students
who must attend private schools or schools in other districts. In
this case, three families from Minot, a small town in southwestern
Maine, sued the state to allow them to use the money for tuition at
a Roman Catholic school. Last year a federal District Court judge
ruled against them, and on Thursday the appellate panel here upheld
the ruling, citing separation of the church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writ simple, the state cannot be in the business of directly
supporting religious schools,'' Chief Judge Juan Torruella wrote in
the opinion. Calling direct payments by the state to sectarian
schools ``a quantum leap'' in legal judgment, he wrote, ``Creating
such a breach in the wall separating the state from secular
establishments is a task best left for the Supreme Court to
undertake.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the ruling broke along familiar lines. Americans
United for Separation of Church and State, a nonprofit group that
joined the suit in Maine's defense, called it ``a monumental ruling
in the battle over taxpayer support of religious schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the other side, the Institute for Justice, which
represented the families in last month's state case, said the
ruling was ``merely redundant.'' And Jay Sekulow, chief counsel for
the American Center for Law and Justice, which represented the
families, said he was disappointed but not surprised by the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Court of Appeals has done is basically treat
religious people as if they're subversive to the American Public,''
he said. ``It is penalizing religious people and religious
values.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
