<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKERS-FBI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI RAIDS SHAKE UP TEEN HACKERS IN HOUSTON AREA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Shortly before 2 p.m. Thursday, FBI agents shut off
electrical power to a home they were about to raid near
Channelview, Texas. More than a dozen armed agents wearing
FBI-emblazoned, bullet-proof vests then burst through the door.
</P>
<P>
   Their target: A 17-year-old computer programmer who lives with
his parents. The teen sat on a couch for an hour before agents
began questioning him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to wait till my mom could come home,'' said the teen,
who goes by the nickname LoopHole on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to speak on the condition that his identity not be
revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Wednesday, FBI agents in Houston raided the homes of
four suspected computer hackers, including the 18-year-old founder
of Global Hell, a hacker group that succeeded in getting into the
White House Web site May 10.
</P>
<P>
   No one was arrested in the raids, but agents seized computers
and other equipment. The FBI has declined to comment on the ongoing
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The raid was part of an 11-city crackdown on computer hackers
suspected of a variety of misdeeds, ranging from defacing
government Web sites with boastful taunts to teleconference fraud
involving $250,000 in losses.
</P>
<P>
   Another Houston teen whose home was raided last week goes by the
Internet nickname of MostHated. The high school dropout, who
founded Global Hell last summer, also spoke on the condition that
his identity remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   He said agents who raided his home Wednesday morning questioned
him about fellow Global Hell members and Web site hacking. He said
the group once numbered as many as 20, including a handful of
international members, primarily in Europe. Most members, he said,
were kids trying to make a name for themselves through Web hacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be four left now,'' he said. ``As far as I know,
Global Hell is no more now.''
</P>
<P>
   MostHated said FBI investigators were most interested in
information about teleconference fraud. The fraud cases involve
hackers who steal personal identification numbers and credit card
numbers to make teleconference calls. He said the teleconference
calls could include up to 30 participants talking long distance for
several hours.
</P>
<P>
   The other Houston teens whose homes were raided included a
16-year-old boy who goes by the nickname SpaceGoat and a
16-year-old girl who was a friend of the alleged hackers, but was
not one herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just around the wrong people, I guess,'' MostHated
said.
</P>
<P>
   John Vranesevich, founder of AntiOnline, a clearinghouse for
computer security issues, said most of the FBI targets are
teen-agers who spend hours on their computers trying to get into
Web sites just to boast that they did.
</P>
<P>
   Vranesevich compared them to kids armed with cans of spray paint
looking for the biggest building they can tag with graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he said, hackers are unaware of the damage they
do to companies that lose money in stolen services or spend large
sums to hire security consultants or install new system software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people are doing serious things, but most of
them are just kids who are finding themselves far over their heads
in trouble,'' Vranesevich said. ``The best thing that could happen
to them is being raided by the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the FBI comes to their homes with their guns drawn, that
becomes a big shock of reality to them real fast. It becomes a
wake-up call,'' he said. ``When most of these young hacker kids get
that wake-up call, that's it. This has been a big wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   In his ``Hydro hoax programmers'' Web site, LoopHole writes,
``The F.B.I. raided me and SpaceGoat last Thursday, and we're still
waiting for results. But anyways, im 100% legit now and im only
going to program.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he said he was not surprised by the agents because
he had known about the raid at MostHated's home the day before and
that agents had asked about his involvement with Global Hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power went off and I was like, `whoa,''' he said. ``I
didn't open the door for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the agents believed he was a member of Global Hell
because whenever the group hacked a Web site they left ``shout
outs,'' or greetings, to friends, including him.
</P>
<P>
   He said agents seized a word processor and six computers,
including one his older sister had just bought.
</P>
<P>
   The incident, coupled with his mother's anger afterward, has
cured him of doing anything remotely illegal on the Internet, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally against all that crap,'' he said. ``I'm out of all
that forever now.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike fellow hackers who have vowed to launch an all-out attack
on the Web against the federal government, LoopHole and MostHated
said they understand why they were raided and do not fault the FBI.
They simply got caught, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Vranesevich described the teen-age hackers as rebellious
youngsters who are not out to undermine the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no intent to bypass any classified system, to get hold
of sensitive information. Their only mission is peer recognition,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is no longer as open as it once was, when hackers
had access to databases and information stored by companies on the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like back in the '80s and '90s when people did it
mainly for information and stuff like that,'' MostHated said. ``You
can't really get to that as easily as you could back in those
days.''
</P>
<P>
   MostHated, who is trying to start up his own computer security
consultant business, said the visit by the FBI has forced him to
step back and reevaluate his actions on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these people don't understand the knowledge that they
have, they can use that to get a real good job,'' he said. ``They
don't look at it that way. They look at it as trying to get a name
on the Internet. Now look at what it got them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
