<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RAMIREZ-BAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMIREZ A SILENT STAR IN BAT-MYSTERY THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Compact disk player in hand and headphones attached
to his ears, Manny Ramirez strolled through the visiting clubhouse
at Yankee Stadium Tuesday as if he were strolling through a mall on
his lunch hour. Ramirez watched some videotape of Roger Clemens,
spoke with a few teammates and turned down or ignored interview
requests about whether he had used a corked bat on Monday, as some
Yankees have charged.
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half hours before Tuesday night's game, Ramirez sifted
through a bulky blue bag and fiddled with a handful of bats. It
took Ramirez about three minutes before he took a black bat, placed
it against a pillar and then resumed his afternoon stroll. Ramirez
did not look even slightly irritated by the attention swirling
around him and his bats.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians were much more ornery. Manager Mike Hargrove called
the charges by some anonymous Yankees ``sad,'' Jim Thome said they
were ``ridiculous,'' while David Justice implored Ramirez not to
speak at all and Omar Vizquel said Ramirez is the least likely
player to use a corked bat because he routinely uses his teammates'
bats. The controversy gave an already high-profile series extra
drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it cheapens anything Manny does,'' Hargrove
said. ``I hoped this thing would be put to bed today because it's
not true. There's not a basis of fact in it. I think it's sad that
any team, not just the Yankees, would openly accuse a person
without more evidence than one game. That's what I find a little
interesting, and a little sad.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ramirez stretched over the plate to hit Orlando Hernandez's
low slider 412 feet over the center-field fence, the Yankees
suddenly became curious.
</P>
<P>
   They thought the ball sounded different off the bat and they
wondered why Ramirez used another bat in his next plate appearance.
But the Indians countered these assertions, saying that the
210-pound Ramirez, who used Sandy Alomar Jr.'s bat to hit the
homer, has a pure swing, has tremendous bat speed and can flick a
baseball 400 feet. Remember, they said, he is one of the top
hitters in the American League with a .350 average, 14 homers and
63 runs batted in, a major league best, entering Tuesday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they're trying to play the head games because Manny
always plays good against them,'' Roberto Alomar said. ``Manny is
not a small kid. Manny is pretty big. He's over 200-something
pounds. People don't realize it. The guy has a lot of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Alomar was much more talkative about Ramirez's bat than Ramirez
was. When a reporter asked Ramirez if he had time for an interview,
Ramirez cordially said, ``Not right now.'' When the reporter asked
Ramirez if he would be available later, he said, ``No.'' So the
reporter subsequently asked Ramirez if he was upset that the
Yankees claimed he had corked his bat and he oddly uttered, ``No,
thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Because cork is lighter than the wood it replaces, a hitter
placing it inside his bat can swing it faster. The greater the bat
speed, the farther a ball will travel.
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel marveled at Ramirez's strength, saying that he broke his
bat and still hit a ball to the center-field warning track at
Jacobs Field last week. ``He's just unbelievable,'' Vizquel said.
``He's strong, and he does everything perfect at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove added, ``If Manny was corking his bat, as strong as he
is, I'd hope he'd have more than 14 home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre was unusually silent when asked about Ramirez
and reeled off a series of ``I don't knows'' to queries about
whether he believed Ramirez used or uses a corked bat. The Yankees
did not ask the umpires to check Ramirez's bat after the homer, but
by raising the issue, they have probably prevented Ramirez from
even considering using an illegal bat in this series and could be
trying to disrupt him.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove doubted that the Yankees would check one of Ramirez's
bats, but invited the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody is welcome to walk into our clubhouse at any time,
unannounced, today, tomorrow, next week, next month or next year
and check any bat that they want to in the house,'' said Hargrove,
who added: ``Manny doesn't cheat. Manny doesn't have to cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel, whose locker was beside Ramirez's empty locker and was
flanked by the reporters Ramirez would not talk to, said Ramirez
was so unflappable that he could hit a ball while standing naked in
the jungle surrounded by lions. The shortstop surmised that the
attention about Ramirez's bat would not rattle him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manny can go deep with any bat any time,'' Vizquel said.
``He's so messed up that he can go 3 for 3 in one game and change
the bat and go deep. Sometimes he goes to the other team and uses
bats from his friends on the other team and he goes deep. So it
could have been one of the Yankee bats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-ANTLEY-COX     06-01 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ANTLEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Belmont Stakes: Antley's ride of his life
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ To this day, no one's sure who came up with the
nickname. It was likely one of the Livingstons, Terry or Jay, who
first saw Chris Antley repeatedly run past their Bender Mender auto
repair shop last fall and wondered, ``What is that fool doing? He
looks just like Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was Bill Cox, who owns the Hazlewood Market next door
to the Bender Mender and came to expect Antley's arrival several
times daily, ``Always pouring sweat. I'd say, `OK, Forrest, what do
you need?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was Connie Trakas, who works nights and weekends at
the market and regarded Antley as a human sundial. ``If you saw him
in the morning, he'd be jogging in place while he was here buying
his water,'' said Trakas. ``By nighttime, he'd stand still. You
could tell what time of day it was by how much energy he had. He'd
come by in the morning, later in the morning, afternoon, at night.
It was like, `Damn, Forrest Gump, do you ever sit down?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever, whatever, the nickname fit. Like Forrest Gump, Chris
Antley ran and ran, then ran some more, a jockey desperate to lose
weight and regain his livelihood. For him, life had indeed become
like a box of chocolates. Not unpredictable. Fattening.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Antley is still a lot like Forrest. He keeps popping
up unexpectedly in the most historic photographs: In the winner's
circle last month at the Kentucky Derby. In the winner's photo two
weeks later at the Preakness. Saturday at the Belmont Stakes,
Antley will again be aboard Charismatic, who'll try to become the
12th Triple Crown winner in thoroughbred racing history, the first
since Affirmed in 1978 and perhaps the most unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want so badly to do it for America,'' said Antley. ``But
more than that, to do it for myself. It's been a long, hard
struggle to get back into racing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All this winning and stuff is great,'' said Antley's father,
Les. ``But the most important thing to us is Chris is back and
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chris, the long road back to racing began here. On these
neighborhood roads and streets on the southeast side of town (and
later on the treadmills and stair-steppers at a health club once
his knees pained him too much for the pavement), Antley literally
ran for his life.
</P>
<P>
   He became a familiar sight: Long-sleeved sweatshirt and pants, a
tan stocking cap pulled low on his forehead, a yellow Walkman
strapped to his right biceps, earphones piping in music to perspire
by.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Antley flew home unannounced from California last
September, he was unrecognizable, a bloated and broken man. When
Les first spied his oldest son on the couch, ``I didn't even
recognize him. He was as heavy as I'd ever seen him. His face was
fat. He didn't have a sparkle in his eye, didn't have much to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-3 Antley weighed 147 pounds, 33 pounds over his
riding weight. He had not ridden since August of '97. Once a golden
boy, Antley led all North American riders in wins with 469 in 1985.
In '87, he became the first to win nine races in one day. In '89,
he rode at least one winner for 64 straight days. Despite substance
abuse problems with drugs and alcohol (he tested positive for
cocaine in 1988), Antley won the 1991 Kentucky Derby aboard Strike
the Gold.
</P>
<P>
   But by '96, Antley was having trouble maintaining his weight. He
also suffered from depression. By last August, unable to lower his
weight to resume riding at Del Mar, Antley found himself in ``lost
bewilderment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew in the back of my mind I was in trouble, I was finished
and the game was over for me,'' he said. ``It had vanished into
thin air.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a couple of million dollars Antley said he's made
trading stocks on the Internet, he was down and out of racing.
``I'd never seen him so big,'' said his stepmother, Annie. ``But
what struck me was the way he acted. He was very depressed. He
didn't want to do anything or see anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks, Antley simply lay around. He shied away from
family gatherings and kept mostly to himself. He tried to avoid
watching races on TV, after unintentionally seeing one ``and
actually getting nauseous and feeling I was going to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to avoid racing altogether. He slept in the
downstairs bedroom that Les had redecorated a few years back,
including photos of some of his Chris' greatest victories.
Sometimes, Chris told Les, ``Dad, you're killing me with these
pictures. I'll wake up in the middle of the night and look at them
and lie there in a cold sweat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't treat him any different than our other kids,'' said
Les. ``We didn't feel sorry for him, or wait on him.'' Chris was
given daily chores: Cleaning the bathrooms. Taking care of the
kitchen. Vacuuming and dusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need him back,'' said Annie, smiling. ``He was a real good
little housekeeper. He's a neat freak.'' Chris awoke at 4 or 5 each
morning, to study stocks on the Internet, watch CNN, fix coffee for
the family. Les and Annie told Chris he didn't need to return to
racing, that he should consider doing something else with his life.
</P>
<P>
   But one day, determined to return to racing and already on a
no-carbohydrate diet, Chris went out for a run. Slowly. He rarely
stopped. First in the neighborhood, then beyond. ``He'd get lost,''
said Les. ``Sometimes he ran so much he didn't know where he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Lesley(cq) Moss, Chris' sister, got used to walking into her
backyard and finding her oldest brother collapsed in her hammock,
taking a respite from a run. Sometimes, Lesley ran with him, or
rode a bike beside him as Chris pushed her sons, Leyton and Hayes,
in a two-seat stroller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like every time I drove anywhere, there he was,''
said Trakas. One day, she spotted Antley running five miles away.
``He just played Forrest Gump that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times each day, Antley stopped by the market on his runs
for a bottle of spring water and, once a day, a quick snack.
``Probably once a day, he had a Snicker's. For energy,'' said
Trakas. ``Not the big one. A little one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd just run till he couldn't run any more,'' said Les. ``He
had a goal and he said he was going to make it or die trying. He
ran so much, he tore his knees up.''
</P>
<P>
   Les again urged Chris to try another profession. His son
responded by buying a membership for himself, and his sister, at
the Columbia Athletic Club on Forest Drive. They began going
together at 5:30, 6 in the morning to workout. ``I'd have to leave
but he'd stay,'' said Lesley. ``Some days, he'd stay five, six
hours. He'd tell me he ran 20 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would run and run and run and run and run,'' said Coley
Brown, the club manager. Antley ran on treadmills, worked on
low-impact stair-steppers and elliptical trainers. People
approached F.D. Mudd, the club's fitness director, and ask, ``Is
there something wrong with this guy? I was here this morning and
just came back, and he's still running the same speed on the same
treadmill.''
</P>
<P>
   By late January, Antley had turned 33 and lowered his weight to
118. Annie knew he was ready to return to California, and riding.
``We knew he was doing good when he started wearing my clothes and
jeans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Antley began getting some mounts. Among the trainers
who used him: D. Wayne Lukas. In April, he told Antley he had a
Derby mount for him in Charismatic, who in February ran as a
$62,500 claimer but on April 18 won the Lexington Stakes. Even
Antley sees the irony in horse and rider: ``He was washed out in
the game and became a claimer. I was washed up in the game and put
out to pasture.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, at 31-1 odds, they won a cavalry charge in the Derby.
Then Antley gave another fine ride to an even finer Charismatic in
the Preakness, the chestnut winning by 1-1/2 lengths. ``Now,'' says
Antley, ``if I can put the cherry on top and win the Triple Crown,
it can unite so many people who are not in the sport and they find
an enthusiasm or a goal in life, that anything can be achieved in
life if you put your heart into it.''
</P>
<P>
   As they were at the Derby and Preakness, Les and Annie will be
at the Belmont. ``If he wins,'' Les said, ``it would be great.''
But nothing can replace that moment a couple of hours after the
Preakness, when father and son were walking across the parking lot
to their ride. ``He looked me straight in the eyes,'' said Les,
whose eyes welled and voice broke. ``And he said, ``Thank you,
Dad.' That's all. But when you hear those words from your kid, you
can imagine what it means.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
