<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9053 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONY-AWARDS-ART-3TAKE     06-01 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR BROADWAY BECAME THE BOONIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6)  
 (af)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When did Broadway become the provinces?
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion has been hovering for several decades, now that
the once-sophisticated mecca of American theater is really just a
mall in Squaresville: a forum for automated theme park shows, with
doses of high culture provided by visitors from more adventurous
places.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, when the Tony Award nominations were announced
last month, they seemed to offer especially disheartening
confirmation of the idea, giving off what Lorenz Hart once
described as ``the faint aroma of performing seals.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that there won't be things to celebrate at the Gershwin
Theater Sunday night, when the awards are handed out. (The live
telecast will begin at 8 p.m. on PBS for one hour, followed by two
hours on CBS.)
</P>
<P>
   This was, after all, a season in which the straight drama,
unembellished by song and dance or eye-numbing special effects,
reasserted itself as a potent box-office contender on Broadway, at
least when propelled by the power of a known star.
</P>
<P>
   And within that context, majestic instances of a breed of purely
theatrical performance _ overblown but dazzling, and nothing that
could be contained by a film or television screen _ flourished,
testimony to stage acting as an art with its own transcendent
rules, from Brian Dennehy and Elizabeth Franz in ``Death of a
Salesman'' to Zoe Wanamaker in ``Electra'' and Kevin Spacey in
``The Iceman Cometh.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, cast your eyes over the list of nominations in nonmusical
categories, and it's like reading a series of thank-you notes from
the Colonies to their mother country, Great Britain, for graciously
exporting its talent. As for the roster of musicals, well, one can
only shudder at the lineup of misfired, pandering revivals and
bland, sanitized revues that suggest nightmares of elevator music
assuming physical forms.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays, all imports and all still running, towered over
Broadway this season as examples of how theater can move, stir and
unsettle in a way that no other art form can. It should be pointed
out that they were all written at least a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are two exquisitely reconceived revivals, which found an
enduring pulse in marmoreal classics: Arthur Miller's ``Death of a
Salesman,'' directed by Robert Falls, which came out of the Goodman
Theater in Chicago, and Eugene O'Neill's ``Iceman Cometh'' in a
production first seen, with a partly different cast, at the Almeida
Theater in London under Howard Davies's direction.
</P>
<P>
   The third was a more unlikely act of resurrection: the English
director Trevor Nunn's bruising, life-giving production of ``Not
About Nightingales,'' a drama written by the young Tennessee
Williams that remained unproduced for more than six decades and was
seen here, after previous stagings in London and Houston, as a
collaboration among two British companies, the Moving Theater and
the Royal National Theater, and the Alley Theater of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   There are dated elements in all of these works, particularly in
``Nightingales,'' which Williams had consigned to a desk drawer
years before ``The Glass Menagerie'' made his name. Yet all three
represent an intersection of stagecraft, heightened language and a
playwright's personal obsessions that can continue to inflame an
audience's imagination. People still sob at ``Salesman,'' gasp in
the last moments of ``Iceman'' and sweat sympathetically through
the torture sequences of ``Nightingales.''
</P>
<P>
   These productions, like that of Sophocles' ``Electra'' (also of
British provenance, natch), seen earlier this season, represent a
fluent, illuminating dialogue between past and present. It is an
essential dialogue, a vital part of our cultural conversation, not
unlike what is represented by the evergreen repertories of opera
houses around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been enriching contributions to that conversation
since the age of O'Neill, plays that were born and reflective of
their own times. That such works continue to be created in the
United States is not something you would know from the Tony
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   This is perhaps the firmest evidence that the awards are an
anachronism as long as they remain limited to the small town known
as Broadway, a place that is less likely to make news than to Xerox
it.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new works that opened in Broadway houses this season
do bear an organic relation to the soil from which they sprang, but
the soil, for the most part, is British. (Of those currently
running, only ``Side Man,'' Warren Leight's sympathetic, twilight
evocation of jazz artists, is American-born.) Now it may seem in
itself provincial to suggest, in these days of ever-extending
global reach, that a good play be judged by other than universal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no denying that a lot of what seemed provocatively
hot on London stages felt tepid when it got to Manhattan. The
corrosive sex comedies, David Hare's ``Blue Room'' (whose success
was much boosted by the presence of a nude Nicole Kidman) and
Patrick Marber's ``Closer,'' were anticipated with eagerness and
then watched, at least by some, with a been-there, done-that ennui.
</P>
<P>
   Sex is an empty game in which no one is a winner? Haven't slews
of the hipper American movies been trafficking in that conceit, in
more varied and original ways, for the last decade? And since both
works were more intent on peddling their cynicism than creating
fully formed characters, there wasn't a lot to occupy a New York
theatergoer's attention once the point had registered.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The love of theater that pervaded ``Amy's View,'' Hare's
portrait of a London actress played by the sublime Judi Dench,
faced no similar cultural gap, but the work's attendant diatribe on
the decline of English values did, sticking out like a set of
irascible footnotes to viewers who had no personal stake in the
political argument.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, both ``Amy's View'' and ``The Blue Room'' were
unconditional financial hits, thanks to the presence of their
gifted and conspicuous leading ladies, but they have also left a
grumbling wake of dissatisfied patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Hare's ``Via Dolorosa,'' in which the playwright turned actor
for his one-man meditation on the Middle East, was far superior, as
eloquently oblique as ``Amy's View'' was overstated, but it has
failed to generate nearly as loud a buzz. Similarly, ``The Weir,''
a heart-clutching paean to the redemptive powers of storytelling by
the young Irish playwright Conor McPherson, was apparently too
literary for the Tony nominating committee, which shut it, like
Hare's ``Dolorosa,'' out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lonesome West,'' Martin McDonagh's slapstick duet for
battling brothers in rural Ireland, came across as a cartoon
version of his triumphant ``Beauty Queen of Leenane,'' from the
previous season. Floundering at the box office, it is a cautionary
example of Broadway producers overcrowding the Anglo-Irish
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that since Tony Kushner's ``Angels in America''
won the Pulitzer Prize for drama in 1993, the award has gone
exclusively to works that were then running or had run Off
Broadway. This year's winner, ``Wit,'' the stunning playwriting
debut of a Georgia kindergarten teacher named Margaret Edson, can
be found in a theater off not Times Square but Union Square, a
block or so away from where two previous Pulitzer winners, Edward
Albee's ``Three Tall Women'' and Paula Vogel's ``How I Learned to
Drive,'' began their lives in New York at the Vineyard Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wit,'' by the way, doesn't address the subject of sex, and
while it does include nudity, it does so with no erotic intent
whatsoever. Its focus instead is death, as it follows the
dehumanizing treatment for ovarian cancer of a professor of
metaphysical poetry, played in memory-searing style by Kathleen
Chalfant. Neither theme nor heroine would seem to be commercial,
yet there is something you feel among audiences for ``Wit'' that
you seldom sense on Broadway these days: an air of committed
emotional engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Just how and why ``Wit,'' directed by Derek Anson Jones, affects
those watching it obviously has something to do with the way it
holds a mirror to a familiar aspect of contemporary existence. But
it's what the mirror is made of that gives the play its exceptional
charge, and that has everything to do with the theater: its
combination of conscious artifice and visceral immediacy, used in
this instance to convey a culture's tragic limitations in dealing
with death.
</P>
<P>
   In another vein altogether, the brilliant American satirist
Christopher Durang achieved a similarly canny marriage of form and
content in ``Betty's Summer Vacation,'' directed by Nicholas Martin
at Playwrights Horizons. In portraying a world surreally shaped by
the punchy, restless rhythms of sitcoms and tabloid television,
this anarchic comedy of manners found a toxic theatrical energy in
the American lust for nonstop entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty's Summer Vacation'' also played deftly with the idea of
the terminally short attention span, a theme that pervaded the Off
Broadway season. In the blissful new production of Tracy Letts's
salty potboiler ``Killer Joe,'' a trailer park family gave equally
serious consideration to plotting murder and to television reruns.
Diana Son's ``Stop Kiss,'' at the Joseph Papp Public Theater, was
about a commitment-eluding young woman in Manhattan who makes a
whole defense system out of refusing to focus.
</P>
<P>
   The language of evasion among young adults who have lingered too
long in adolescence inspired some of the season's most artful
dialogue, in the welcome restaging of Kenneth Lonergan's ``This Is
Our Youth'' and in ``Snakebit,'' a remarkably assured first play by
the actor David Marshall Grant that explores the unspoken elements
of a three-sided friendship.
</P>
<P>
   It seems appropriate that the old master of linguistic
slipperiness, Harold Pinter, should have been well represented this
season, with both a vivid revival of his ``Hothouse'' by the
Atlantic Theater Company and the Roundabout's elegant production of
his more recent ``Ashes to Ashes.'' The articulate pause, which
Pinter has used to such famous effect, figured prominently in two
works of electric talent and almost antithetical sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   In the willfully and stylishly disaffected ``House,'' the young
writer-director Richard Maxwell presented monotonal characters who
seemed to forget what they were saying mid-sentence, while in the
emotion-packed performance piece ``2.5 Minute Ride,'' the
monologist Lisa Kron explored the legacy of the Holocaust in her
own family, with awed silences playing as evocative a role as her
glitteringly descriptive sentences.
</P>
<P>
   In the more advanced realms of theatrical experimentation,
language was exploded into shards, an exhilarating experience if
it's a troupe as polished as the Wooster Group that has its hands
on the detonator. In ``House/Lights,'' this SoHo-based company, led
by Elizabeth LeCompte, spun an opera libretto by Gertrude Stein
into a dazzling mixed-media collage of mutating images. It was a
production designed to disorient, showing how technology has
altered forever the way we see and hear the world.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The same perception crept into more conventional works of
theater, like Marber's ``Closer'' and Craig Lucas's ``Dying Gaul,''
which both made sly use of communication by computer and its
potential for scrambling identities. Lucas plied his customary
whimsy with a new fierceness in a play that bravely measured the
corrupting, as opposed to ennobling, power of grief, as embodied by
a writer whose lover has died of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dying Gaul'' is a raw and discomforting work, and it divided
critics. But it also represented a bold, hope-inspiring willingness
to plow new territory by an established American dramatist. Other
familiar writers assumed similarly venturesome styles with varying
success.
</P>
<P>
   A.R. Gurney left the green lawns of WASP land for postwar Japan
in ``Far East,'' an uneven play that nonetheless represented one of
its author's most ambitious and emotionally direct works to date.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vogel, in a departure from the haunting, elegiac ``How I
Learned to Drive,'' shifted uneasily into Pop-flavored
cartoonishness with ``The Mineola Twins,'' a brassy satire most
notable for the spirited comic presence of Swoosie Kurtz in both of
the title roles.
</P>
<P>
   John Guare, as part of a season devoted to his work by the
Signature Theater, came up with a new play, ``Lake Hollywood,''
which, while still rough-edged, testified to this writer's singular
gift for transforming American celebrity culture into wistful
theatrical poetry.
</P>
<P>
   The prolific and popular Terrence McNally inspired headlines and
protests with ``Corpus Christi,'' a thin, preachy fable about a gay
Christ figure and his trendy disciples. The play was a snooze, but
it was gratifying to see a work of theater that didn't feature a
movie star get such extensive national news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind, for the moment, the degrees of success and failure
represented here. Just consider the scope and the vitality of this
chorus of American voices, whose existence the Tony Award
nominations scarcely hint at. And that's not even considering the
work done in such fertile institutions outside New York as the
Goodman and Steppenwolf theaters in Chicago, the Seattle Repertory
Theater and the South Coast Repertory in Costa Mesa, Calif.,
although several of the plays described above began life in such
environs.
</P>
<P>
   But if Broadway is scarcely the place to read the vital signs of
the American play, it remains the primary showcase for the American
musical. This is not a happy fact in a season that had the Tony
nominators scrambling desperately to find entries for each
category.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard, in fact, to think of a more lifeless lineup of
representatives of what is, as the splendid Encores series of
American musicals in concert continues to remind us, a very lively
genre. Expectations were not high for ``Footloose,'' a stage
adaptation of the movie, or Frank Wildhorn's ``Civil War,'' a
singing history pageant. Yet both managed to sidestep even the
satisfactions of spectacular badness, being instead merely so bland
as to fade away before your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Even under the direction of the mighty Harold Prince,
``Parade,'' seen at Lincoln Center, was little more than an
animated civics lesson, warranting the damning epithet ``worthy.''
The dance revue ``Fosse'' somehow bleached all wit and sensuality
from the work of Bob Fosse, the choreographer it celebrates, just
as the songfest ``Ain't Nothin' but the Blues'' tasted like soul
food from a can.
</P>
<P>
   Revivals ranged in tone from the synthetically cheerful
(``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'') to the shrill (``Little
Me,'' despite the enlivening presence of Martin Short) to the
tasteless (``Annie Get Your Gun,'' which squandered the talents of
its wonderful star, Bernadette Peters).
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the most exciting American musical I saw all season
was ``Oklahoma!'' That, perversely enough, was in London, in a
springtime-fresh revival directed by Nunn at the Royal National
Theater. Because of problems with Actors Equity, the show probably
won't be coming to Broadway. What is coming from London is
``Saturday Night Fever,'' another adaptation of a hit film and,
when I saw it, utterly mechanical. It should fit right in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
