<SLUG> BC-TEN-AGASSI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOS UPSET AS AGASSI SETS BACK A QUALIFIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There was a tale of two Marcelos at the French Open on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The minor Marcelo, a 140th-ranked qualifier, obediently allowed
Andre Agassi to trample him like a doormat.
</P>
<P>
   The major Marcelo, the ninth-seeded Chilean who was portrayed as
being on the cusp of his first Grand Slam title, was upended by a
30th-ranked Slovak.
</P>
<P>
   Dominik Hrabty eliminated one of the tournament's premier
players, defeating Marcelo Rios by 7-6 (7-4), 6-2, 6-7 (6-8), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Hrabty, who banished top-seeded Yevgeny
Kafelnikov from the second round in straight sets, is 4-1 against
top 10 foes this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing he does is hit hard, hard as he can,'' said
Rios, who has advanced beyond a Grand Slam quarterfinal only once
in 17 events, when he reached the Australian Open final in 1998.
Rios blamed a 3-6, 3-6, 6-3, 6-4, 6-3 winning ordeal against
Alberto Berasategui in the fourth round for the lack of physical
resolve he displayed on Tuesday. ``My legs were pretty tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Marcelo was suffering from an abdominal strain, but
Agassi is not inclined to be excessively benevolent. The
13th-seeded Las Vegan is not satisfied with reaching the semifinals
when a championship, especially the elusive French Open
championship, has begun to beckon. That's all the impetus he needed
to pulverize 140th-ranked Marcelo Filippini, 6-2, 6-2, 6-0, in 72
minutes on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old Agassi handcuffed the already injured Uruguayan
with a barrage of aggression launched from the very first game, in
which he broke his challenger, to the last game, in which he
finished things off with his favorite flourish, an ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played really solid and I played against a guy who really
didn't have the goods today,'' Agassi said upon reaching his first
Grand slam semifinal since the 1996 U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   This match was anti-climactic following Agassi's impassioned
recovery from a 6-4, 4-1 deficit against the French Open's
defending champion, Carlos Moya. And the American called it a clear
case of his playing ``the yeoman'' against the journeyman.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, after playing a Roland Garros runnerup on two occasions,
is fixated on finally winning here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going to work; there's really not much room for
emotion,'' said Agassi, who wore an impassive face until he won,
when he pranced to midcourt and, after giving the 31-year-old loser
a conciliatory tap on the back, bowed and blew kisses in all four
directions at his riveted audience. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
