<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9057 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUMUMBA-ART-2TAKES-$A     06-01 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUMUMBA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFTING UP AN AFRICAN HERO TO MYTHIC STATUS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any American old enough to have been even vaguely aware of world
events in the late 1950s will remember the name Patrice Lumumba. He
was the young firebrand African politician who led the independence
movement in what was then the Belgian Congo and pushed hard for the
strength-in-numbers ideal of a pan-African unity.
</P>
<P>
   To many in the cold war West who heard his speeches on the radio
or saw him on a grainy television screen, he was a mesmerizing but
dangerous presence. He was feared as being a Communist, in sympathy
if not in fact. And with his pin-stripe business suits, black-rim
glasses and trim goatee, he projected a radical new image of black
Africa for the modern world: commanding, polished, forward-looking,
angry.
</P>
<P>
   His career was brief. He was assassinated less than a year after
becoming prime minister of the newly named Republic of Zaire in
1960. But by that time he was already a myth and, among Africans as
well as people of African descent worldwide, a symbol of one of the
high moments in 20th-century political history.
</P>
<P>
   Something of the excitement and tension of that era comes across
in ``A Congo Chronicle: Patrice Lumumba in Urban Art,'' which is on
view at the Museum for African Art in SoHo through Aug. 15. It is a
compact and moving show of paintings that explores complex ways in
which the image of a cultural hero is both recorded and reinvented
during his lifetime and after his death.
</P>
<P>
   Urban painting, as presented here, is a hybrid of several
elements. It has stylistic roots in Western media like photography,
book illustration and advertising. But its subject matter and
approach to history are African. Usually referred to as popular
art, the work was produced, often on commission, for an urban
African bourgeoisie, in this case in the Congolese city of
Lubumbashi, and for a foreign clientele.
</P>
<P>
   The show has been organized by Bogumil Jewsiewicki, a professor
of history at Laval University in Quebec, and drawn largely from
his personal collection. It opens with an introduction to urban art
as a genre, with beginnings in the colonial period of the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   The paintings are all smallish in size, scaled to cramped living
rooms, and done in oils and house paint on ``canvases'' made of
cotton flour sacks or recycled textiles. The artists who create
them are versatile, adjusting their repertory of images to what the
market demands: advertising, portraiture, depictions of ancestral
villages or good-luck icons of the mermaid spirit known as Mami
Wata.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they repeat standardized images of well-known
historical episodes: scenes of the 18th-century Arab slave trade,
for example, or of Africans being flogged under Belgian rule.
Artists also serve as gazetteers, catching up-to-the-minute news on
the fly. And there is no question that the career of Patrice
Lumumba had the electric charge of history in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Its key events are distilled in a group of 50 vivid paintings
that form the core of the show, many of them executed by the
celebrated artist Tshibumba Kanda Matulu, others by his teacher,
Burozi, with whom he collaborated. (Tshibuma's fame outstripped
Burozi's, and, in line with common workshop practice, paintings
were usually signed with the more marketable name, no matter who
actually did the work.)
</P>
<P>
   A few of the images touch on Lumumba's early days. He was born
of poor village people and reared as a Christian. Largely
self-educated, he began working as a functionary in the colonial
government but quickly developed as a political thinker and
anticolonial dissident.
</P>
<P>
   At every step, he is depicted less as a personality than as an
emblem. In a 1950s campaign portrait, he wears both his signature
suit and the leopard-skin headdress of a tribal chief. In another
painting, he is shown as the shackle-breaking leader of a 1959
uprising, though he didn't actually take part in the event.
</P>
<P>
   In a third, at the public declaration of Congolese independence
on June 30, 1960, he speaks holding a globe of the world, while the
Belgian king, Baudouin, stands behind him, obsequious, hat in hand.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Lumumba that riveted international attention:
audacious, bigger than life, an embodied idea (as he himself came
to recognize) more than a person. He was a star, but a shooting
star, most brilliant in descent. Young and impulsive, he made
mistakes. Unseasoned as a politician, he faced ambitious rivals and
ethnic rancor at home. Meanwhile, the superpowers were already at
work sabotaging independence struggles across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1961, he was arrested, purportedly by agents of his
own government hauled off in a truck and killed. (Although it has
never been proved, the CIA is believed by many in Africa to have
been directly or indirectly involved in his death.) Lumumba was 36.
His body was never found.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Images of these last events mix harsh, detailed realism with the
ritualistic restraint of a passion play. Burozi depicts the arrest
as a drama of betrayal, with a resistant Lumumba staring fearfully
into the eyes of one of the soldiers who seized him. In Tshibumba's
much-reproduced ``Historic Death of Lumumba,'' however, the dead
leader lies on the ground, his face peaceful, a bleeding wound in
his side. A miniature Calvary with three crosses looms in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Christian references abound in the paintings. So do comparisons
of Lumumba with Moses, leading his people out of a Babylonian exile
in their own land. He is also compared with earlier African figures
like Chief Songya Lumpungu, who died fighting colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's catalogue traces these references, and pays
particular attention to the ways in which African concepts of
kingship and ancestral memory are embedded in popular art, creating
stories that refine, renew and reshape themselves with retelling.
</P>
<P>
   The hagiographic process continued after Lumumba's death and
into the present. His immediate successor, the despotic Mobutu Sese
Seko, at first sought legitimacy by claiming the dead leader's
mantle, then tried to suppress all memory of him.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most recent paintings in the exhibition, done by the
artist Banza just last year, shows Lumumba's face hovering in the
sky, shedding his light on Congo's present ruler, Laurent-Desire
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Displayed in a Western museum, such paintings are interesting
for many reasons. They offer an instructive case study in the way
political history _ created from equal parts fact, expediency and
longing _ is preserved and shaped.
</P>
<P>
   A similar investigation could fruitfully be made of popular
images of Western political martyrs who came after Lumumba, the
Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and Che Guevara among them.
</P>
<P>
   Vividly painted, these works also help broaden the definition of
African art for American viewers familiar only with ``timeless''
traditional sculpture. (In tandem with ``A Congo Chronicle,'' the
museum has mounted a splendid showcase of just such work titled
``Three African Traditions: The Art of the Dogon, Fang and
Songye.'')
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it is necessary to emphasize that these
paintings only hint at the variety of contemporary work being
produced on a continent that is itself a dizzying aggregate of
cultures, languages and ideologies.
</P>
<P>
   The show is perhaps most important, though, for restoring to
view a heady, optimistic era and an iconic figure now little
mentioned by the Western media and non-African historians, who tend
to focus on the stagnancy and violence that have devastated much of
Africa since Lumumba's death.
</P>
<P>
   Icons are complicated things: flawed, vulnerable, changeable in
meaning, gaining and losing power over time. But Patrice Lumumba's
aura seems to be intensifying rather than diminishing, in the Third
World and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, political leaders still evoke his name. His life
continues to be the subject of painting. One catches the echo of
his utopian spirit in the words of the Nigerian pop singer Majek
Fachek: ``Promised land is not Africa. Promised land is not
America. Promised land is a state of mind. I hope you are ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And increasingly one finds Lumumba's presence in America _ not
in academic studies or news reports but in a home-grown version of
urban popular art. Anyone walking through sidewalk markets or shops
in New York neighborhoods like Harlem and Bedford-Stuyvesant will
encounter Lumumba's grave, inquiring face, staring out from plaques
and posters, emblazoned on T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the specifics of his history may be hazy. But as an
emblem of liberation, he is clearer, brighter and more alive than
he ever was on those television screens 40 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
