<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      06-01 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO SHOW NATION `HIS HEART AND MIND' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush acknowledged Tuesday that he will be getting
a late start when he begins campaigning for president in key states
later this month but believes he has plenty of time to prove
himself to the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave his White House campaign a bit of a trial run one day
after the end of a legislative session that was a success for many
of his initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   At a San Antonio reception for presidential campaign
contributors, Bush sounded the themes of his unannounced campaign,
calling for an era of personal responsibility, compassion and
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The general themes were familiar to Texans who heard them in his
two successful gubernatorial campaigns. But it signaled to the rest
of the country that Bush's presidential run would focus on
broad-stroke ideas, not detailed policy proposals that marked the
Clinton-Gore campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Promising to set a tone rather than a specific agenda, the
governor pledged to show the nation his ``heart and mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream for the state and nation is to usher in an era of
responsibility,'' Bush said, ``a time that each of us are
responsible for the actions that we take.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio speech came a little more than a week before the
governor leaves for Iowa and New Hampshire to measure his popular
support. It was the first time Bush has appeared at a fund-raiser
since forming a committee to explore a presidential campaign, a
decision he made in the interest of his legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But with a generally successful session of law-making behind
him, Bush turned his attention to presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get movin,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Austin, Bush said it was important for
him to stay in the capital, tending to the state's business during
the past five months that the Texas Legislature was in session.
</P>
<P>
   The result, he said, was a ``successful and substantive''
session that not only will prove to be good for Texas but also will
help him establish national credentials as a tax-cutter and
champion of education.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature, which adjourned Monday, approved $1.85 billion
in tax reductions for Texans over the next two years and major
changes in public education, including a $3,000-a-year teacher pay
raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm late in particular states. I know I've got a lot of
work to do. I know expectations are high,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's OK. I'm a battler. I like to battle, and so I'm
looking forward to going.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to begin a campaign trip June 12 to Iowa and
New Hampshire, the two early voting states that set the
presidential race. It will be his first campaign swing out of state
since announcing his presidential exploratory committee earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even while staying at home, Bush has consistently led GOP
presidential preference polls and has collected far more campaign
money than any other Republican presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his campaign trip was designed to help him ``make sure
the sentiment (of support) that I'm told is out there is out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand these polls and expectations are out of sight,''
he added. ``As my daughter said, `Hey, Dad, you're not nearly as
cool as they think you are.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's San Antonio speech stressed families, education and tough
love for wayward kids. He called his job as a dad the most
important one he has, and said, ``I'm gonna tell people I love my
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to disappoint his solidly Republican audience, each who had
contributed $1,000 to his presidential bid, Bush spoke of limited
government and military might. At the same time the governor warned
against abandoning the poor in times of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps wary of the rough and tumble nature of presidential
politics, Bush called for an end to ``campaigns of personal
destruction.'' He described himself as man of principle and an
optimist whose sees better nation and a better world.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to lead you need to be able to set clear goals, unite
the people and see a better world,'' said Bush. ``This is a nation
that can solve any problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has been criticized by some of his opponents
and influential Iowans for not visiting Iowa and New Hampshire
earlier. All other presidential candidates have been campaigning
for months in those states, where voters have come to expect to
meet White House contenders face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fully committed to start traveling the country,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to look people in the eye and shake their hands and let
them know what's on my heart and hear what they have to say as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said other Americans will soon know more about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're eventually going to learn that I'm a
tax-cutter, that I care about education, that I feel passionately
about making sure we don't leave people behind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush received praise at his Capitol news conference from one of
the Legislature's leading Democrats, Rep. Rob Junell of San Angelo,
chairman of the budget-writing House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling in the next several months, the people of
America will find out what the people of Texas know about Governor
Bush,'' Junell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some leaders try to bully, or they grandstand. Governor Bush
works in a spirit of cooperation and respect for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Bush visited a group of kindergarten
teachers training to teach reading in a program that is part of
Bush's initiative to end social promotion in Texas schools.
</P>
<P>
   He used the opportunity to illustrate his commitment to literacy
and draw attention to the $3,000 raises for the state's teachers
recently passed by state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank you for being teachers,'' Bush told the
educators. ``You're the front line.''
</P>
<P>
   Striding confidently into San Antonio's Region 20 Education
Service Center, Bush smiled and worked his way from table to table,
shaking hands with the teachers. Followed by a throng of reporters
and camera crews, the governor said he was sorry for being so
disruptive. Then he quipped, ``No, I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
