A9061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSCRASH-CHARGES-COX     06-01 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSCRASH-CHARGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School bus driver gets traffic ticket after fatal crash
 &HT;    By Teresa Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ A school bus driver who ran a stop sign and
collided with a truck in January, killing a student and the truck's
driver, may have driven carelessly but did not commit a crime,
investigators decided Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Colletti, who was nearly killed in the crash and spent
weeks recovering in a Vero Beach hospital, will be charged this
week with careless driving, a traffic infraction that carries up to
a $500 fine, possible loss of driving privileges and community
service work.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors considered more serious charges including
felony manslaughter, Florida Highway Patrol Capt. Deryl Loar said
Colletti had no intent to cause the crash and had no drugs or
alcohol in her system. She also had an exemplary driving record
during her three years working for the Indian River County School
District.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't meet the elements of any type of manslaughter,
negligence or vehicular homicide,'' Loar said. ``There were a lot
of emotions involved, but we have to realize it's just a tragic
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the FHP's 150-page crash report won't be released until
this afternoon, Loar said the investigation revealed that Colletti
``slowed down a little'' and ``rolled through'' a stop sign before
slamming into a 13-ton citrus truck Jan. 25. In addition to the two
killed, several students were injured.
</P>
<P>
   When Colletti was interviewed, she said she didn't recall the
crash or why she may have run the stop sign, Loar said. Sixteen
students were on their way home from two elementary magnet schools
when the crash occurred in citrus groves at 45th Street and 66th
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Although careless driving is a traffic citation, Colletti will
have to appear in court because a death was involved, Loar said.
</P>
<P>
   Daughters of truck driver Sammie Hughes have filed a lawsuit
against the Indian River County School Board, claiming Colletti
``negligently operated or maintained'' the bus and caused it to
crash into Hughes' citrus truck. Loar said a check of the bus
indicates it was working properly at the time of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Lane writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
