<HEADER>
A9064 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-CLUB-FILM-2TAK     06-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-CLUB-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURING A CUBAN SOUND BEFORE IT COULD DIE OUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A sadness permeates Wim Wenders's new film, ``Buena Vista Social
Club.'' The documentary covers the lives and recent unexpected
success of a group of elderly Cuban musicians _ nearly forgotten in
their own country _ who banded together under the direction of the
American musician Ry Cooder and did the improbable: they recorded
an international hit album.
</P>
<P>
   When Cooder first encountered these musicians in Cuba in 1996,
they were disillusioned; some had abandoned music altogether (one
was shining shoes). A year later they had won a Grammy, and to date
they have sold 1.5 million copies of the album.
</P>
<P>
   It was while collaborating with Wenders on his 1997 film, ``The
End of Violence,'' that Cooder had slipped the ``Buena Vista''
album into a suitcase full of CDs that Wenders carries everywhere.
Wenders listened and was sold on the idea of capturing these
musicians on film.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, which opened in New York on Friday, features
two concerts the group performed, one in Amsterdam, the other last
July at Carnegie Hall. The music, in its acoustic beauty and power,
jumps off the screen. Wenders also interviews the musicians in
Havana and roams the destroyed elegance of the city. The musicians
play some, together and alone, and talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I heard the music, I thought it was
incredible,'' Wenders said. ``I had never heard anything like it,
contagious. I would be hanging around with Ry, and the conversation
always returned to Havana. He'd start looking wistful, his eyes
would glaze over, and I knew he was in Havana in his mind. I paid
attention, and was introduced to some very young music made by some
very old people.''
</P>
<P>
   While in New York City for the Carnegie Hall concert, Wenders
followed the Cuban musicians around. He lets the audience in on the
awe the city invokes _ the way Cuba's isolation amplified the sense
of wonder the musicians felt. As they look through the windows of
the tourist shops along Broadway, they marvel at the plethora of
things to buy, consumerism gone wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is good,'' the singer Pio Leyva, 82, says in the
film.
</P>
<P>
   Wenders filmed the concerts in a washed color that is near
black-and-white, tinted with pastels. But he filmed Cooder and his
son, Joachim, riding around Havana on a motorcycle, and the Havana
street scenes, the interviews and the recording session in a
hypersaturated color that captures the visual sensuality of the
place.
</P>
<P>
   The pianist Ruben Gonzalez, 80, wears a shirt that bristles with
oranges and yellows in an electric, geometric pattern.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, there's an attempt to make sense of what
attracts people to this music and to expand on the music, to put it
in its context. You see Leyva move, dancing just a bit to the
music. You see how the people gesture when they talk. You see the
grandeur of Havana, and the intricate intelligence and power of the
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Records are simply a storage format,'' Cooder said. ``You
can't really understand music without seeing the environment from
which it comes. All information is visual now anyway, and the film
helps you understand how people get their sound, the sound that's
them. Why they sound the way they sound, how they got to that
point. The film goes to the unconscious, for better or for worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Wenders studiously avoided the political throughout the
film, there is an ever-present sense of the continual dance that
goes on to avoid the obvious political questions and of the Cubans'
own awareness of the penalties for criticizing their government.
</P>
<P>
   Their stories, well documented and a good reason for the success
of the original album _ the musicians were marketed as old and
forgotten _ resound throughout the documentary. But to delve deeper
helps explains some of the evasions in the film.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The music, which predates the Cuban revolution, was ignored by
the state, which parcels out work to musicians. Ferrer was shining
shoes; Gonzalez did not have a piano and hadn't played since the
early 1980s. Ferrer gave up music, in part, when international
music agents coming to Cuba to look for him were told that he was
on tour or out of the city and were steered to younger musicians.
Other musicians stole his compositions, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary also includes the recording of Ferrer's solo
album, ``Buena Vista Social Club Presents Ibrahim Ferrer.''
Believing that Ferrer deserved his own album, Cooder returned to
Havana last year to work on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Wenders and his camera were in the studio with him, and Ferrer
becomes the heart of the documentary, singing boleros with his
achingly beautiful voice or singing faster, more percussive tunes,
improvising above the swell of the drums.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these people were practically forgotten,'' the trumpeter
Manuel Mirabel says in the film. ``If `Buena Vista' hadn't emerged,
nobody would remember Ibrahim Ferrer, Ruben, Compay Segundo. To see
Compay at 90 standing there playing his tres'' _ a type of guitar _
``so well and Ruben playing his piano so well. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ferrer still finds no work in Cuba. ``I owe everything to
foreigners,'' he said recently in New York. ``I still can't sing in
Cuba. I have no work there, no bookings, nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   As such, the splendor of pre-Revolutionary Cuban music is in
danger of disappearing, something not lost on Cooder.
</P>
<P>
   When he headed to Havana to record ``Buena Vista Social Club,''
Cooder had hoped to use the tres guitarist Nino Rivera, but Rivera
had recently died. Cooder went to his house and talked to Rivera's
widow, who told him story after story and showed him her husband's
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all going to vanish,'' Cooder said. ``People are dying
every day. When, in the film, Ruben says, `See you another day,'
it's not clear that that's going to happen. All this is tenuous.
Part of the importance of this film is that in puts down stories
and narrative on film, and thankfully there's plenty of footage for
a documentary on Ruben Gonzalez, for instance, if Wim wants to do
one.''
</P>
<P>
   With moments of intense poetry, the narratives of the musicians
_ who have mostly seen their careers turn to dust, then revive _
carry enormous weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who plays it has to have a sense of how to make the
imagination dance using an instrument of such limitations in its
physical design, you might say,'' says the timbales player Amadito
Valdez, describing his drums. ``It's a very docile instrument but
one which undoubtedly lends a lovely color to dance music.''
</P>
<P>
   Wenders was surprised by the verbal invention. ``I never knew
where the phrases ended; they spoke never-ending, incredible
sentences,'' he said. ``Even those who, like Cachaito and Eliades,
had a reputation of not opening their mouths,'' he added, referring
to the musicians Cachaito Lopez and Eliades Ochoa, ``they sat down
and I never had to ask a question. They just opened up.''
</P>
<P>
   So a sadness runs through the film, with time running out on the
musicians. Some, like Segundo, 91, have made peace with it and are
luxuriating in their newfound success; he has five children, he
says in the film, and, he jokes, is trying for a sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miracle, a miracle, what's happened,'' Ferrer said. ``I
have seven children, 11 grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.
I can support them all now. But what could have been, what could
have been. ...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
