<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGNER-RING-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAND-ME-DOWN `RING' ATTRACTS A STAR DIRECTOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Matthew Gurewitsch's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was
on Shakespeare in current films.  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again, the Wagnerites are descending on San Francisco for
the four-day spiritual adventure that is the ``Ring of the
Nibelung,'' offered in four overlapping cycles, beginning on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The production, unveiled in 1985, last saw service in 1990. Of
the original principals, the Wotan of James Morris remains. Along
with the new cast of other gods, giants, dwarves and assorted
demigods _ among them, the redoubtable Jane Eaglen as Bruennhilde _
the current edition also introduces a new director, Andrei Serban.
</P>
<P>
   For an original director, in this case Nikolaus Lehnhoff, to
hand off a revival, even such an important one as this, is hardly
unprecedented. In general, though, the grunt work of remounting the
show falls to someone lower on the totem pole, not always with
happy results.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Andrew Porter, then the music critic of The New Yorker,
took the Metropolitan Opera to task for entrusting its first full
traversals of its latest ``Ring'' cycle (several seasons in the
making) to a lieutenant. Porter found little to admire in the
concept of Otto Schenk, whose name was on the show, but it was the
staff director Phebe Berkowitz, the subaltern, who bore the brunt
of his indignation.
</P>
<P>
   His report ran under the headline ``The Berkowitz Ring,'' a
whole world of disapproval folded into the syllables of her
surname.
</P>
<P>
   Given how large the ``Ring'' looms in a director's resume and
how great a reputation Serban enjoys in his own right, his
willingness to accept a hand-me-down seems surprising in the
extreme. Caught by telephone between rehearsals in San Francisco,
he could only agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surprised myself by saying yes,'' Serban said. ``I've never
done anything like this before and will never again. But I thought,
how often in life is one offered a `Ring'?''
</P>
<P>
   It was mid-May, with opening night just three weeks off. Morris
had begun rehearsals only the day before. Ms. Eaglen would not
arrive for another week. Deborah Voigt, the Sieglinde, would cut it
even closer _ but then, she appears only in ``Die Walkuere,'' the
second day of the ``Ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Serban, who has never seen a complete ``Ring'' cycle in the
opera house, had been operating at full tilt for several weeks with
artists of the second cast (scheduled to sing in the third cycle):
Jeffrey Wells and Alan Held, sharing the role of Wotan, devious
chieftain of the gods; Frances Ginzer as his disobedient daughter
Bruennhilde.
</P>
<P>
   In a given day, Serban said, he might work on ``Das Rheingold''
in the morning, ``Die Walkuere'' in the afternoon and ``Siegfried''
in the evening: a sequence he likened to ``Hamlet,'' ``King Lear''
and ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as innocent in this as Siegfried was, but I hope I'll be a
little more victorious than he,'' Serban said. ``I spent six months
preparing to do this production, but it's in rehearsal that I
discover. Right now, I'm working like a doctor for a Broadway show.
Every day, the assistants _ a separate set for each opera, a whole
battalion _ show me the blocking as it used to be done. I watch and
immediately see possibilities. Then I start interfering. By the end
of rehearsal, the physical shape the scene takes is 95 to 100
percent different from what it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   What of the visuals? In good post-modern fashion, John Conklin's
original designs incorporated multiple strands of reference. The
four parts of the cycle were tied to the four seasons, from a
``Rheingold'' primavera to an icebound ``Goetterdaemmerung.''
</P>
<P>
   The architecture took up monumental motifs of the 19th century.
Much of this, Serban disclosed, will disappear. Conklin, according
to the tape on his answering machine, was off on a new project in
Sydney, Australia. Responsibility for revised sets and costumes
lies with Robert Perziola, but as Serban made clear, funds for any
major overhaul are not there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reminiscences of the Conklin sets will remain, but the whole
will be much, much simpler,'' Serban promised. ``Sometimes, budget
permitting, I've tried to bring in a different look. We're trying
to purify what seemed to me overcharged and overcrowded.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of Patrice Chereau and his centennial
``Ring'' for the festival at Bayreuth, which opened in 1876 with
the premiere of the master's maximum opus, Lehnhoff and Conklin
refracted the material through a sort of Marxist prism, emphasizing
the economic and political conflict. (The concept was not new.
George Bernard Shaw made the case for it before the turn of the
20th century.) Thus, as first conceived, the San Francisco ``Ring''
took its place proudly within a recognized intellectual tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Serban knows his theater history and does not mind acknowledging
his predecessors. ``Why hide an influence?'' he asked. ``Being
influenced, you bring in something of your own.'' On his watch,
however, the priorities are more intuitive than theoretical.
``Concept is not what I'm after, ever,'' he said. ``What I'm after
is a moment of living experience.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Serban speaks as a disciple of that guru and seeker of
theatrical essences Peter Brook, with whom he spent a formative
season in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent experiment has particular application to Serban's
more recent excursions into opera. His celebrated ``Fragments of a
Trilogy'' presented scenes from Greek tragedy in forgotten (and, in
effect, invented) tongues _ incomprehensible except as the actors
charged their lines with sharp, specific emotion. And so they did,
keening, howling, stabbing with sarcasm, unstrung with woe. This
quasi-operatic use of the voice was married to a detailed language
of theatrical movement and gesture.
</P>
<P>
   In Serban's experience, singers are not always apt to use the
full arsenal of a nonsinging actor. ``They think music alone
expresses the drama, but that's not true,'' Serban said. ``It has
to happen through you. That's why the body is so important.''
</P>
<P>
   On their first day of rehearsal together, Serban reports, Morris
(who in a decade and a half has portrayed Wotan for directors of
every persuasion) found himself perplexed. ``During the long
monologue with Bruennhilde, for instance, he's used to sitting on
the throne for a long, long time, longer than I thought it should
be in a realistic telling.''
</P>
<P>
   Serban explained. ``I offered suggestions, and he said, `But
I've never done this.' I said, `Is that bad?' And he said he would
have to take it home and think about it. Tomorrow we may have a
completely different solution.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, however, that Morris will wind up back on his
throne, internalizing all his inner turmoil. ``Physical action is a
continuation of the music,'' Serban said. ``It completes the
connection. If I can make a moment of union between music and
drama, and can make the singers really be completely alive on the
stage, with a new energy, a new dynamic quality: if I can do that,
I've already done my job. The symbolism will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially, Serban finds, in Wagner. ``In Verdi or Mozart, what
goes on in the orchestra is always so much better than what goes on
onstage,'' Serban said. ``It's hard to create an image on the stage
with the same power as the incredible music in the orchestra. But
in Wagner, a change of tempo or a crescendo will prompt me to show
something in the relationship between the characters. What's in the
orchestra is so absolutely logical. It's a musical narrative. It's
epic music. It tells you what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The creator draws the map, in other words. All the performers
need to do is take the journey. In this conviction, Serban stands
apart not only from Lehnhoff, whose staging of an opera is
commentary made visible, but also from Zen masters like Robert
Wilson, who create parallel events that converge with the score
only incidentally (or in the eye of the beholder).
</P>
<P>
   Thus, whether the outward differences between earlier editions
of the Lehnhoff ``Ring'' and its latest revival turn out to be as
conspicuous as they look to the director or so subtle as to go
unnoticed _ after all, no one has seen this show in nine years _
the results will have been achieved by a fundamentally different
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kinder, schafft Neues,'' Wagner urged his disciples late in
life: Children, create something new. What exactly he had in mind
has been much debated (though he certainly did (italics)not(end
italics) mean that they should leave his own works behind). The
injunction has become the motto of iconoclastic directors itching
to leave their mark on what may well be the most protean allegory
in the Western canon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never put my signature on this production,'' Serban
said with becoming modesty. In the brochures, his name appears
below those of the production's originators. Yet in spirit, he is
making a fresh start. And therein lies the promise of something
new. A Serban ``Ring,'' perhaps? No irony intended.
</P>
</TEXT>
