<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DISCIPLINED-PRINCIPAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENDED PRINCIPAL'S 6-YEAR FIGHT FOR JOB DRAGS ON, WITH NO END IN
SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(dal) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTROSE, N.Y. _ For the last six school years, Joanne Falinski
has collected $100,000 as an elementary school principal, but she
has not been allowed near a classroom. Instead, she has been doing
clerical work for the school district while it pursues a
disciplinary case against her that has no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The 325 children who were in her school when she was suspended
have all graduated. The superintendent who suspended her has
retired. The principal who replaced her has herself been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The one constant has been the case against Falinski herself,
which is centered on a disciplinary procedure created by New York
State. The act, known as 3020a, was intended to get rid of
treacherous, crooked or incorrigibly inept teachers and principals
but has become notorious for the time and expense it takes to reach
a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In the Falinski case, the legal bills of the Hendrick Hudson
School District, which encompasses several rustic and suburban
Westchester communities outside Peekskill, are approaching $1
million. That does not include Falinski's annual salary and
benefits for doing a previously nonexistent job.
</P>
<P>
   In six years, there have been only 64 hearing days. The three
members of the hearing panel _ whose $50- to $200-a-day pay gives
them little incentive to hold hearings or show up _ say they find
it difficult to align their schedules and those of lawyers and
witnesses. When they are held, the hearings have a lackadaisical
quality, the participants say.
</P>
<P>
   During one recent hearing, a panel member, Eugene Polinsky,
showed up an hour and 15 minutes late, explaining that he had
mistakenly crossed the date off his calendar. An hour after he
showed up, everyone broke for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``State Education Department regulations say the hearings have
to be run in an expedient manner,'' mused Polinsky, a 78-year-old
playwright who is a school board member across the Hudson River in
Rockland County. ``The most expedient manner is when everybody can
make it. It's not when everybody must make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Falinski, who had been principal at the Furnace Woods Elementary
School for 10 years until her suspension, is accused of 55 charges
of misconduct and insubordination on grounds that she discouraged
five children from receiving special education: tutoring or
counseling services for learning disabled, emotionally volatile and
physically handicapped youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Falinski's champions say they believe the charges against her
were trumped up by zealous opponents who disliked her
nontraditional ``whole language'' approach to reading. The idea is
that young readers can be cultivated by having them read and write
more instead of having them perform phonics drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a very good educator and effectively removed her from
her profession,'' said Janet Malang, who supports Falinski.
</P>
<P>
   Falinski's critics say it is she who is the zealot, refusing to
compromise her beliefs no matter what the wishes of parents and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a parent, I felt she was rigid and inflexible and she was
uncaring,'' said Edward Klopper, who paradoxically tangled with
Falinski over her decision to refer one of his children to special
education. Klopper was later elected a school board member.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the original passions that led to the charges,
almost everyone seems to agree that a more effective way should
have been found to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legal mechanism is so absurd and so impossible that the
only way out is a settlement,'' Klopper said.
</P>
<P>
   No one, for now, seems able to find a way to pull the district
out of the quagmire. But some see hopeful glimmers in the election
of new school board members in May _ Klopper was unseated _ and in
new financial pressures resulting from a request for a 70 percent
property tax reduction by Con Edison, the district's biggest
taxpayer and operator of the Indian Point nuclear plant near here.
</P>
<P>
   Falinski, 46, whose quiet manner belies a granite will, says
that a sturdy Roman Catholic faith and strong work ethic have
helped her weather her ordeal. She said she even managed to find
interest in such chores as tabulating sick days of school personnel
in her clerical work at district headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet because the festering case has been widely talked about in
educational circles, she has been unable to find another school
that will employ her and has been frozen in limbo unless she
surrenders. ``The notion of a very speedy trial in this country,
that has not been possible for me,'' she said. ``The way the case
is going, I may be suspended longer than I was principal of the
school.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Falinski was raised in Utica, N.Y., received a doctorate from
Syracuse University and served as an assistant principal in
Larchmont before being appointed in 1983 as principal at Furnace
Woods, which has perennially led the district in reading, with 88
percent of students this year reading above grade level.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1993, Falinski received a sparkling evaluation from
the superintendent, Virginia C. Rederer, one that called her a
``strong, competent leader.'' Nine months later, Rederer telephoned
Falinski at home and ordered her not to show up at school the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters point out that Falinski was not accused of an offense
requiring her urgent removal, like hitting a child or drinking on
the job. The most heinous misconduct charge was that she told a
child's parents that unless the boy was taken off the drug Ritalin,
the school would not provide counseling. Ritalin is a central
nervous system stimulant often prescribed for hyperactivity.
</P>
<P>
   The district could have handled Falinski's case internally by
superseding her on special education decisions. Raymond G. Kuntz,
the district's lawyer, said the superintendent and the school board
chose suspension because they felt what she did was ``a pervasive,
all-encompassing effort to undermine special education and didn't
believe it could be corrected with a slap on the wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were children who were put through agony because they
didn't receive services to which they were entitled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are people on both sides, though, who think Kuntz, a
silver-haired 62-year-old lawyer who looks as if he stepped out of
central casting, brought too many charges _ 125 at one point _ in
an effort to dishearten Falinski. That many charges required a
flood of documents and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   These detractors note that it was Kuntz who helped initiate the
state's other famously interminable 3020a case, against the
principal of Eastchester High School for improper use of school
employees. The Eastchester case ended in 1991, eight years after it
began, with the principal's reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Kuntz, however, faults Falinski and her lawyer, Robert
Saperstein, for dragging out the case, though he also places the
larger blame on a sluggish 3020a system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no incentive in the system for her to do otherwise,''
he said of Falinski's insistence on fighting. ``She's on full
salary, and she continues on full salary until the panel makes a
determination.''
</P>
<P>
   He blames teachers' union lobbyists for contriving laws that
make it difficult to remove teachers and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   James R. Sandner, general counsel of New York State United
Teachers, the statewide union, replied that lengthy cases occur
``when districts overlitigate their cases'' and when the chairman
of a panel does not take control of the process.
</P>
<P>
   The 3020a proceedings have slowed to a numbing pace both in the
ways they resemble and do not resemble civil and criminal trials.
The hearings are run with all the time-dragging procedures of a
courtroom, with lawyers objecting repeatedly and demanding that the
stenographer reread questions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet unlike actions in criminal and civil courts, these hearings
are not backed up by salaried judges who have powers to penalize
litigants for delays.
</P>
<P>
   Falinski is now testifying about children who have moved on to
high school and have outgrown their learning disabilities, yet she
is asked hair-splitting detail about conversations that took place
when the children were small.
</P>
<P>
   Kuntz complains that the hearings have gone on so long that the
school board members who employ him can no longer summon the
urgency that moved them to suspend Falinski. ``Time dims the
memory, I'm afraid,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Partly as a result of such protracted cases, the Legislature
changed the 3020a process in 1994. Hearings started under the new
law must be held consecutively and presided over by a single
hearing officer whose per diem payments can reach $1,000. The
losing party can be forced to pay the victor's legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say the changes have speeded hearings considerably, but
many cases still drag on for a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, about 150 disciplinary cases are brought in a year.
Most districts avoid such proceedings by working out arrangements
with unsatisfactory employees, like early retirements or transfers.
But in Falinski, the Hendrick Hudson district came across someone
who was too young to retire and too headstrong to admit to
something she says she did not do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that by walking away, I'd be giving credence to
something that didn't happen,'' Falinski said.
</P>
<P>
   When she took her stand, she felt that testing her belief would
take a year or two and cost a few thousand dollars, not six years
and the $200,000 her legal bills have totaled so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look back at the time and the way everything has
turned out, there's just a feeling of sadness,'' she said. ``A lot
of money has been wasted on me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
