</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKE-OKEECHOBEE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firm agrees to lake-spraying plan that won't kill willows
 &HT;    By Sally D. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A battle between a worried fisherman and
a company hired to spray water weeds in Lake Okeechobee ended in a
truce Tuesday when the company promised to stop killing native
willow trees along with the weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing guide Eddy Everett, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
biologists Jon Lane and Angie L. Charles and officials with the
spraying company traveled in air boats to look at damaged willows
along the east side of the lake near J &AMP; S Fish Camp in western
Martin County.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Beard and P.J. Myers of Applied Aquatics admit the firm's
sprayers hit the willows. But they insist they followed biologists'
orders to stop and said some of the willows could recover.
</P>
<P>
   Everett and the biologists maintain the company ignored orders
to stop spraying the willows.
</P>
<P>
   The lake's ongoing ``weed wars'' target water hyacinth and water
lettuce, which can grow into free-floating mats that clog locks and
canals and hinder boat navigation. The fast-growing weeds can
double the area they cover in two weeks, crowding out native plants
and marsh grasses.
</P>
<P>
   The South Florida Water Management District spent between
$670,000 to $915,000 a year during the last decade to keep the
weeds under control. This year, the corps, which controls the lake,
took over the weed-killing operation and hired the Bartow firm to
spray the weeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't justify spraying these little islands and killing
the willows,'' Everett said, ``when miles of hyacinths along the
edge of the lake haven't been sprayed. Places they should have been
spraying, they didn't spray _ and they're spraying places they're
not supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who has worked on the lake for 14 years, said high
water already had harmed the willows, and he fears the herbicide
spray finished them. The firm uses 2,4-D, an herbicide commonly
used to kill water weeds.
</P>
<P>
   The willows grow on tiny islands, surrounded by hyacinths. Myers
said the sprayers were aiming for the hyacinths when they hit the
willows, but defended the practice as part of ``keeping the
hyacinths under maintenance control.''
</P>
<P>
   The corps biologists said the firm's contract with the corps
specifies it should not kill native vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this,'' Myers said, ``we will treat the willows with the
respect we give bulrushes (a native marsh grass), even though I
think more than two-thirds of the willows will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't think it's a big deal, but we're concerned about
it,'' biologist Lane said later. ``He is under a new contract and
we are expressing what we want. I'm pretty sure he's going to do
what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane said he and Charles will continue to monitor the willows to
see if they recover. The two are visiting fish camps and meeting
people around the lake, asking for help in keeping an eye on lake
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Sally D. Swartz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
