<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKERS START GETTING READY FOR 2001 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On the morning after the Texas Legislature
finished its work, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry was talking Tuesday about
the ``homework'' he will assign state senators in preparation for
the 2001 session.
</P>
<P>
   Higher education will be one of several interim committee
assignments Perry said he will make over the next 60 days. Interim
committees research issues and make recommendations to the next
Legislature on how to solve or avert problems.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will likely be studying the structure, importance
and funding of higher education institutions in Texas, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The higher education system in the state needs to be
appreciated better by the general public (and the public needs to
know) why having an efficient and well-funded higher education
system in the state is important,'' Perry added.
</P>
<P>
   A second area that he might assign senators to study is
technology and the Internet ``and how those developments are going
to impact the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he does not know how many interim committees he will
appoint, but he is certain he will not appoint as many as his
predecessor, Bob Bullock, did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bullock knew, I think, in 1995 that 1997 was going to be
his last session,'' Perry said. ``He probably put together more
interim studies to leave his imprint on the '99 session of the
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock appointed more than a dozen interim study committees
after the 1997 session, a workload that taxed Senate coffers to pay
for all the statewide traveling, hearings, reports and other
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they tried to do too much,'' Perry said. ``They
spent a lot of money. We had budget problems in the Senate when we
first got here with all the money they spent on interim studies.
We'll try to keep that under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he doesn't know how much money was spent on those
studies.
</P>
<P>
   The interim studies will be a real test of Perry's leadership
and his political vision, said Sen. Eliot Shapleigh, D-El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to anticipate, through interim charges, what he
perceives as the next issues'' for Texas to tackle, Shapleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said he will continue looking at border issues, a subject
of key importance to lawmakers who represent the 44 counties that
border Mexico, but he has not determined whether he will make it a
separate committee assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The House will be conducting interim studies as well, but John
Bender, spokesman for House Speaker Pete Laney, D-Hale Center, said
no studies have been ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have about 16 months before reports are due. It's good to
take some of that time to let things settle down,'' said Bender,
adding that one reason for the pause is to see what bills Gov.
George W. Bush signs and vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   Laney, in coming months, will be asking House members for their
suggestions on possible study topics.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is sure to be the issue of highway speed limits. A
bill to raise the limit to 80 mph on some rural interstates almost
won passage but died on Sunday. Rep. Pete Gallego, D-Alpine, who
sponsored the measure, said he would ask for such a study. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
