<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON IS INTERVIEWING HELP FOR POSSIBLE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton on Tuesday began interviewing
New York political professionals who could serve in her potential
Senate campaign, and spent 90 minutes at the White House with the
consultant who ran Charles Schumer's successful race for a New York
Senate seat last year, according to her associates.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a growing sense among Mrs. Clinton's friends that her
candidacy is all but inevitable, the first lady reportedly also met
with Dick Riley, once a press spokesman for former New York Mayor
Edward Koch and the New York City Board of Education. Riley has
emerged as the likely press secretary for an exploratory committee
that would presage an actual candidacy, associates said.
</P>
<P>
   As has been standard for much of the last two weeks, which have
been fraught with speculation among Democrats and in the news media
about Mrs. Clinton's future, the first lady's associates cautioned
that she had still not made a final decision to run for the Senate
and that it was still possible she would choose not to.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the meetings at the White House on Tuesday seemed
significant because they came after a weekend vacation in which
Mrs. Clinton's aides said the first lady and her husband discussed
the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Before she left, her friends had said that if she decided over
the weekend not to run, she would announce her decision
immediately. Instead, she summoned New York Democrats to Washington
to discuss the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to interviewing Riley, the first lady met Tuesday
with Hank Morris, the consultant to Schumer, in the White House Map
Room. Morris and Schumer devised the aggressive campaign that
unseated former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first lady invited me down and I was pleased to talk with
her,'' Morris said after returning to his office in New York. ``She
is very smart. It was a hot day and we talked about Jones Beach. It
was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris declined any other discussion about the meeting. Riley
did not return a phone call. The third person Mrs. Clinton met
with, Gabrielle Fialkoff, has been a chief fund-raiser for Peter
Vallone, the New York City Council speaker, and could presumably
serve the same function for Mrs. Clinton. Ms. Fialkoff could not be
reached for comment Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Morris is known for his command of the current state of New York
politics, and one person familiar with the meeting said that that
was the main subject during his conversation with Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Morris, a number of political consultants have been
mentioned as playing roles in this potentially high-profile Senate
race. They include Mandy Grunwald, who has worked for the campaigns
of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. Moynihan's announced retirement at
the end of next year has created the opening that is now the
subject of attention from both Mrs. Clinton and, on the Republican
side, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Riley is said to be the leading contender for press secretary
should the first lady decide to proceed. He is currently a visiting
scholar at the Taub Urban Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   The moves by the first lady came as she prepared to return, yet
again, to New York Wednesday, for a schedule that includes two
political appearances and a commencement speech at City University.
The costs of the trip would be shared by the White House and the
political committees that are benefiting from her visit.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, Mrs. Clinton is expected to announce the formation of
her exploratory committee in early July. One adviser said that
before she does that, she will inform both Nita Lowey, the
Westchester congresswoman who intends to run for the seat if Mrs.
Clinton does not, and President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
