<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz back in winning form as Braves beat Rockies 7-2
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As much as he wants to protect his tender elbow, once
John Smoltz gets back out on the mound, the killer instinct tends
to take over.
</P>
<P>
   That the case again Tuesday night as Smoltz highlighted his
return from the 15-day disabled list with six scoreless innings _
plus a couple hits _ in a 7-2 win over the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   It took Smoltz only a handful of pitches to register 95 mph on
the radar gun. He struck out Larry Walker swinging on a fastball in
the first inning and eased doubts that his elbow needed more than
15 days off.
</P>
<P>
   A Rockies offense that has averaged only two runs a game during
the first eight games on this road trip turned out to be no match
for Smoltz, who was hungry to get back to work after being the
National League's pitcher of the month in April.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz allowed one baserunner in five of his six innings, four
on hits, but faced only one real jam. In the third inning, he
stranded Jeff Reed at third base by retiring Darryl Hamilton on a
liner to short and Neifi Perez on a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   So much for rustiness. Of the 79 pitches Smoltz threw, 58 were
strikes. He struck out five and walked none.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz also rolled up his sleeves and got dirty on offense,
igniting a three-run third inning with a leadoff double, then
making a narrow escape from a rundown on the third base line. Some
fancy footwork and a playground move to duck under a bare-handed
tag from third baseman Vinny Castilla sent Smoltz safely back to
third base after a grounder by Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   That left the bases loaded for Chipper Jones, who hit the first
pitch from Bobby Jones to left field to drive in Smoltz and Gerald
Williams for a 2-0 lead. Brian Hunter made it 3-0 when he took a
pitch in the foot from Jones with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies manager Jim Leyland got ejected after the inning for
arguing with third base umpire Mike Winters that Castilla had
tagged Smoltz in the rundown.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz ended Jones' night in the fifth inning when he drove in
the Braves' fourth run on a hit-and-run with a single to center.
</P>
<P>
   Once Smoltz left, Colorado broke up the shutout with Jeff Reed's
two-run homer off reliever Russ Springer in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies were beset with errors, committing 4 miscues in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
