<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM LAWSUITS TO TEABAGS, OBJECTIONS TO COMMUTER TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Looking to eliminate the New York City commuter
tax, elected officials from New Jersey and Connecticut unleashed an
assortment of lawsuits, legislation and tea bags on Tuesday in an
effort to demonstrate that the tax discriminates against
out-of-state commuters.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christine Todd Whitman traveled to a busy Hoboken train
station during the evening rush hour to announce that, as expected,
the state had filed a class-action lawsuit in New York State
Supreme Court challenging a new law that exempts only suburban New
Yorkers from the tax. The suit, filed by New Jersey's acting
attorney general, Paul Zoubek, charges that it is a violation of
the U.S. Constitution for New York to continue levying the 0.45
percent wage tax on the 240,000 New Jersey commuters and thousands
of workers who live in Connecticut, Pennsylvania and other states.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, two New Jersey congressmen, Bob Franks and Rodney
Frelinghuysen, introduced legislation that would ban any state from
taxing out-of-state commuters at a higher rate than its own
residents.
</P>
<P>
   And in Jersey City, six elected officials gathered outside a
PATH commuter train station and held the most peculiar protest,
emptying a few small bags of orange pekoe tea into the Hudson River
in symbolic re-enactment of the Boston Tea Party tax protest of
1773. That city's mayor, Brett Schundler, who organized the
protest, said he planned to file a class-action lawsuit in federal
court and would use a nonprofit citizen advocacy group, Empower the
People, to pay for newspaper ads urging commuters to join the court
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law creates a protectionist barrier, a tariff, against
out-of-state residents,'' Schundler said. ``And just as the
colonists dumped tea into Boston Harbor to protest taxation without
representation, we did it today to show we won't stand for this
kind of unfair treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Commuters and elected officials in New Jersey and Connecticut
have been vigorously opposing the tax since Republicans in the New
York Legislature and Gov. George E. Pataki first suggested
exempting suburban New Yorkers from the tax last month. The change
in the tax code, which was intended to help a Republican State
Senate candidate in Rockland County, will cost New York City at
least $210 million a year in lost revenue from suburban New York
State commuters. New Jersey commuters account for another $110
million, according to Whitman, and commuters from Connecticut and
elsewhere pay another $40 million in city taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Connecticut's attorney general, Richard
Blumenthal, filed a lawsuit against the tax. Blumenthal told The
Associated Press that ``Our action today will clean up New York's
constitutional mess.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor, Rudolph W. Giuliani, who was outraged
that his Republican counterparts in Albany had enacted the law over
his objections, said Tuesday that he had been expecting the
lawsuits. The mayor has also vowed to fight the law in court,
although he wants to see only the exemption repealed, and all
commuters liable for the tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really an example of shooting yourself in the foot, of
the worst kind,'' Giuliani said on Tuesday, criticizing Pataki and
other political leaders in Albany. ``In an effort to have everybody
position themselves with a particular Senate race in Rockland, and
everybody playing gotcha in Albany, what they did was get
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits announced on Tuesday are part of a growing number
of legal challenges to the law. Two private lawyers filed a lawsuit
last week in New York State Supreme Court, and Pennsylvania
officials say that they, too, will challenge the tax.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki, who says the tax exemption will help stimulate New
York's economy, believes that the courts will uphold it, said his
spokesman, Michael McKeon. ``We are confident that the law will be
upheld,'' he said. ``But even if the plaintiffs are successful, New
Yorkers will still get a $210 million tax cut.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
