<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S MUNSON EXPECTED TO GO IN TOP 5
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Will it be the Detroit Tigers or Arizona
Diamondbacks? Catcher or first base?
</P>
<P>
   Those two questions will be answered for USC baseball player
Eric Munson today when the Major League Baseball draft begins at 10
a.m. Munson, who is considered the top college hitter available, is
expected to be drafted within the first five picks, most likely by
Detroit at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   As has been his stance all season, Munson said he's not nervous
about his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't been thinking about it too much,'' Munson
said. ``It's kind of in the back of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Munson has gone through this before. He was a second-round pick
by the Atlanta Braves as a senior at San Diego's Mt. Carmel High in
1996, but he chose to attend USC. That decision paid off for
Munson, who turned down a signing bonus of close to $1 million from
the Braves three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He'll get at least $2 million from the Tigers, or the
Diamondbacks, who draft fourth. Major-league teams point to
Munson's defense as his only weakness, but USC head coach Mike
Gillespie doubts Munson will be switched to first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense for (a team) not to allow him to develop
as a catcher,'' said Gillespie, whose son-in-law Chad Kreuter
catches for the Kansas City Royals. ``His experience as a catcher
is very limited. The guy is very athletic. His chance for being a
major-leaguer is enhanced by his ability to catch.''
</P>
<P>
   In Munson, USC will have a first-round pick for the second
consecutive year; pitcher Seth Etherton went to the Angels in 1998.
Barry Zito, a junior left-hander who is 12-2 for the Trojans this
season, also has a good chance to go in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Zito, who is from San Diego and pitched at Pierce College last
year, is a logical choice for his hometown Padres, who have six of
the top 50 picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Etherton showed last year you don't have to have a
95-mile-an-hour fastball to go in the first round,'' said Zito,
whose fastball has been clocked as high as 90.
</P>
<P>
   Westlake High's Kevin Howard is the only local prep player
projected to be selected in the first three rounds. Howard has
signed with the University of Miami and is rumored to be asking a
signing bonus of $1 million from the team that picks him. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A CLOSER LOOK &QL; 
What it is: Major League Baseball's draft is held every year in
June via conference call among the 30 teams. The two-day draft,
which starts at 11 a.m. today, is limited to 50 rounds and will
finish Thursday. &QL; 
How it works: Each team has two minutes to select a player. A
player is eligible to be picked if he has graduated from high
school, or if he has played three years at a four-year university,
or if he is attending a junior college. &QL; 
Tidbits: Tampa Bay holds the No. 1 selection this year and is
expected to take North Carolina high school player Josh Hamilton.
The Dodgers' first pick is No. 37, and the Angels don't have a
first-round pick. USC catcher Eric Munson will probably be taken by
Detroit with the third overall pick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990601.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9092 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DIVERSITY-SPI &LR;      06-01 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DIVERSITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISAPPOINTINGLY, TV'S PALETTE STILL DECIDEDLY WHITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The following program is brought to you in living color.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember when those words would precede a show on NBC?
Simultaneously, the peacock would morph into a riot of rainbow
plumage and then the ``Bonanza'' theme would kick in and Sunday
nights were off and running among the Ponderosa pines.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Chinese cook, Hop Sing, was about the only
nod to multiculturalism ``Bonanza'' ever made. It was the '60s,
when TV's idea of diversity was Little Joe Cartwright's
black-and-white pinto.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, this is the '90s, almost the double-zeros, in fact,
when TV is much more reflective of our diverse American society.
And if you believe that, then you believe most black people are
felons and the rest are police lieutenants who don't have much to
say. Similarly, you think most Hispanics are felons, and the rest
are hot-blooded hunks on ``Suddenly Susan'' and ``Jesse.'' And when
it comes to people of Asian descent, well, at least you've got
Sammo Hung.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the idea of ``living color'' on network
television is as alive as the concept of letting audiences decide
whether something is funny without the aid of a laugh track. People
of color _ African Americans, Hispanic Americans, Asian Americans,
Native Americans _ make up nearly 30 percent of the U.S.
population, according to those people-counting people at the Census
Bureau. For the sake of argument, let's round it up to a third,
shall we? One-third of the American population. Eighty million
individuals, give or take. Yet most TV series don't come close to
approximating this ratio. Heck, most would have to put in overtime
just to achieve tokenism. Such as a black lieutenant. Or a Hispanic
hunk. Or a silly buffoon who traces his roots to India or Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the networks are waiting for the next century before
they embrace this idea of diversity in casting. Still, you'd think
that before the big splash next year _ surely there'll a big
splash, no? _ they could have ended the 20th century with just a
tiny acknowledgment of cultural reality. But, with only a few
exceptions, the fall slate of programming unveiled last month by
the networks is so white bread that Wonder must have an exclusive
sponsorship deal. The publicity stills for the new fall shows look
as if they came from the White Supremacy Survival Camp and Photo
Studio.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the occasional ensemble drama, such as NBC's
police/firefighter/paramedic series, ``Third Watch,'' the networks
are not mirroring society, they're mirroring their executive
suites.
</P>
<P>
   I can imagine the typical pitch meeting between a show's creator
and a network programming honcho.
</P>
<P>
   HONCHO: ``So, what's your show about?''
</P>
<P>
   CREATOR: ``It's about several white people who live and work in
close proximity to each other in an urban setting and rarely come
in contact with people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   HONCHO: ``I like it. Sounds fresh. Hip. Edgy.''
</P>
<P>
   CREATOR: ``Thanks. I was tired of all those ensemble shows with
the black guy at the lunch counter or the Asian woman at the dry
cleaner. It just didn't ring true.''
</P>
<P>
   HONCHO: ``I hear ya. So derivative.''
</P>
<P>
   CREATOR: ``Exactly. We think our approach is more organic, and
it'll resonate with all viewers because it's not about race, it's
about the human condition. Everyone can relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   HONCHO: ``So true. So true. What're you calling it?''
</P>
<P>
   CREATOR: ``Our working title is `The Whites.' ''
</P>
<P>
   HONCHO: ``Catchy. I like it. Think you could get Betty White to
play the wacky grandmother?''
</P>
<P>
   CREATOR: ``I wish. Unfortunately, CBS nabbed her for Sharon
Lawrence's series about a bunch of white people living together in
an urban setting.''
</P>
<P>
   HONCHO: ``Tough break. It's so hard to find the right talent
these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the network honchos are not oblivious of the ``color''
thing. Whenever critics ask them the racial-makeup question,
they're quick to say something like: ``We are very aware of our
responsibility to show racial and ethnic diversity in our programs.
Are we satisfied with our performance? No. But we're constantly
looking for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. And I'm looking to improve my chances of signing with the
Red Sox as their next right fielder.
</P>
<P>
   Is it going to happen?
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, I'd say my chances with the Red Sox are a little
better than a black actor's chances with the networks. Certainly
better than an Asian American actor's. That's because the networks
may be ``aware'' of their shortcomings in achieving cultural
diversity on the TV screen, but they're more acutely aware of the
spending habits of American consumers. As it happens, many people
of color still tend to be clumped together at the bottom of our
wonderful little economic melting pot, so advertisers don't target
them unless they're cynically trying to peddle lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, aside from a few shows on UPN with primarily black casts,
the networks aren't particularly interested in attracting minority
viewers because it's presumed by some wingnuts on Madison Avenue _
the people who really run the networks _ that these viewers aren't
likely to respond to an advertiser's come-ons as enthusiastically
as more affluent white viewers.
</P>
<P>
   But is that any reason to keep a show from reflecting the
increasing diversity of the American peoplescape? You wouldn't
think so, but the networks operate on the assumption that white
audiences aren't comfortable with diversity, even though the most
popular prime-time show in the country, ``ER,'' has one of the most
multi-ethnic casts on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, this small triumph is seen as a great achievement at the
networks because, just as one black actor in a sea of white faces
is seen as ``diversity,'' one multiracial cast in a sea of
all-white shows is seen as progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
