<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-2TAKES-N     06-01 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-VOLPE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLPE'S FATHER SAYS WARLIKE STRESS LED TO VIOLENT OUTBURST 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the first detailed interview since his son pleaded
guilty to torturing Abner Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn
precinct house, Justin A. Volpe's father said on Tuesday that he
believed the pressures of working in a high-crime neighborhood had
changed his son and led to the violent outburst that could result
in a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   By turns emotional and serene, Robert Volpe, himself a former
police officer, likened police work to combat during war and said
the assault on Louima was an unfortunate result of battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was war outside that night, and Justin just lost it after
being beaten, after thinking that death was imminent,'' he said of
the August night two years ago when Volpe arrested Louima outside a
club in Flatbush. Volpe had said he thought that Louima, a Haitian
immigrant, had hit him during a scuffle with the police.
</P>
<P>
   And like soldiers who lock away the memory of atrocities they
commit, his son was in a state of denial about what he had done to
Louima, Robert Volpe said. He said that only after several
courtroom witnesses offered details from that night did he recall
that he had stuck a wooden stick into Louima's rectum and into his
mouth, and then threatened his life if he told anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearly two years between that incident and the start of
the federal trial against Volpe and four other officers accused in
the case, Robert Volpe had consistently maintained that his son was
innocent. During jury selection, he angrily told reporters that his
son was the victim of a ``modern-day lynching'' by prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-and-a-half-hour interview on Staten Island on
Tuesday, Volpe said that during those two years, he had steadfastly
believed that his son had not attacked Louima. He also said he is
proud his son admitted his crime, and that now that the truth is
out, Justin Volpe is finally at peace with himself.
</P>
<P>
   He described a Memorial Day prison visit with his son, who said,
``What I did was wrong and I deserve to be punished.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his son intended to apologize to the Louima family. But
Volpe said any apology should be a limited one because he believes
that Louima is not entirely blameless. Louima helped instigate the
confrontation with the police, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an unprovoked situation,'' Volpe said. ``I'm not
condoning what my son did, and I feel for Mr. Louima, I feel for
his pain, I feel for his suffering, but this night started off as a
routine night in the 7-0 Precinct and it developed into a tragedy
for everyone concerned. There was no innocence on the street that
night.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his son took Louima to the bathroom that night because
he wanted to hit him, to continue the fight. After assaulting him
with the stick, Volpe, his father said, yelled, ``Look what you
made me do'' to Louima. At that point, Volpe said, his son entered
a state of denial.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Volpe said he went to the Metropolitan Correctional
Center to visit his 27-year-old son, the youngest of three
brothers. It was the first time the two men had spoken since May
25, the day Volpe entered a guilty plea before Judge Eugene H.
Nickerson, admitting to acts he had long denied.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said his son appeared calm and more peaceful than at any
time in the last two years. He said that by recalling and
confessing the truth, Volpe had been liberated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just more or less realized that a good man did something
wrong,'' he said. ``I think for the first time in two years, Justin
is free.''  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a visiting room, the handcuffs on the younger man's wrists
were removed and the two men embraced. Volpe told his father not to
worry about him, saying that he was prepared to pay for his
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop, right now this is my reality,'' Volpe said his son told
him. He seemed resigned to a long prison term, but told his father
he thought it would not exceed 30 years, Volpe said.
</P>
<P>
   During his first week in prison, all in solitary confinement,
Volpe said he had been treated well by the prison guards, and that
one inmate even gave him a pillow. His only complaint was about the
23 hours he spends each day in a cell measuring 6 feet by 8 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin has to get his five hugs a day,'' said Volpe, adding
that his son hopes eventually to be put with the general prison
population. ``He's a people person.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said he felt it was appropriate that he visited his son on
Memorial Day. ``Justin died a little bit each day, because he was
such a good person,'' he said of his son's time on patrol. ``He's
that Marine that jumped on the grenade.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his son hoped to spare his four co-defendants the
possibility of prison by admitting his guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin's action is not to protect anyone who's guilty,'' he
said. ``He pulled the fuse. All five men would have gone down if he
had fought to the end, and he knew that. He has sent himself free
by telling the truth, spiritually and emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said he was aware that most of the country views his son
as a symbol of police brutality, but to him and his wife, Grace,
their son is nothing less than an American tragedy. They see him as
the good son who joined the police to serve the public, but then
gradually lost his soul while patrolling the streets of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have breaking points,'' Volpe said. ``People snap.''
</P>
<P>
   No other explanation makes sense, he said, because his son was
such a well-behaved, caring, unassuming child. He did well in
school. He was popular. He was an altar boy, Volpe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them a healthy 20-year-old man,'' he said, referring to
the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   But Justin Volpe, who lived with his parents, began to change
long before the assault on Louima, his father asserted. He had
trouble sleeping, and he was disturbed by the violence and neglect
he witnessed in the streets during his midnight shifts in the 70th
Precinct in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he disappeared even before that night,'' Volpe said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Volpe never thought his son capable of such a brutal
assault. He said his son repeatedly denied any wrongdoing under
aggressive questioning by his lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg. Not once,
he said, did his son display the slightest hint of a guilty
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two years,'' Volpe said, ``I truly believed in his
innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the trial, Volpe continued to cling to the notion
that his son was a victim of a horrible lie. But then came a moment
during the testimony of Patrick Antoine, who was arrested with
Louima that same night outside the nightclub. According to Antoine,
Justin Volpe asked if Antoine thought he was acting crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I knew something happened that night,'' Volpe
said.
</P>
<P>
   For his son, he said, the turning point was the testimony of
Sgt. Kenneth Wernick, who described how Volpe showed him the stick
he used to assault Louima. ``He heard the story for the first time
and it came back to him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He denied that his son pleaded guilty in hopes of a reduced
sentence. ``Justin is going to be shown no mercy,'' he said. ``I'm
a realist. I've seen the blood hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said his son delayed entering his plea for a day so that
he could say his goodbyes to friends and family. ``Don't forget me,
but go on with your life,'' Justin Volpe told them, his father
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Since his son's guilty plea, hundreds of people have written
letters of condolence, he said. A steady stream of neighbors have
stopped by to offer comfort, hugs and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justin is not being sentenced alone,'' he said. ``He is being
sentenced with all the people who ever knew him.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe is especially upset over what he felt would be an unduly
harsh sentence for his son. Because of widespread antipolice
sentiment, he said he would become a sacrificial lamb to satisfy a
public demand for vengeance. ``Under the Constitution of the United
States, all men are created equal; unless you're a cop, and you
screw up,'' he said. He called his son ``a political prisoner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
