<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEZBOLLAH ATTACKS DIMINISH OPTIMISM IN LEBANON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAFAR FALOUS, Lebanon _ Hezbollah guerillas staged a series of
attacks against an Israeli-supported militia as it was pulling out
of the town of Jezzine, killing a militiaman and an elderly
resident.
</P>
<P>
   The casualties dampened the euphoria Tuesday expressed by the
area's residents after the leaders of the militia, the South
Lebanon Army, announced that they were ending their 14-year control
of the town. The area surrounding the town juts north of the
9-milewide swath of Lebanese land Israel has occupied since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday, there was a breeze of optimism,'' said Nadim
Salem, a Lebanese parliament member and resident of Jezzine,
exiting the Christian village on his way to Beirut. ``But now it
has gone the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah movement planted
the two roadside bombs that exploded and killed the the two
victims. Israeli warplanes responded by pounding suspected
Hezbollah strongholds, providing cover as the militia continued a
pullout from villages around Jezzine that began late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The bombs were seen as a strong signal that the Hezbollah did
not intend to let the militiamen retreat quietly, despite earlier
pledges by the Islamists group's leader, Sayyed Hassan Nasrallah,
not to ``gloat'' as the men they consider traitors withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   By midmorning the militia had abandoned posts in 25 surrounding
villages and barricaded itself in Jezzine, nearing the end of its
hold on an area of south Lebanon that had proved deadly. Five
militiamen have been killed and 34 wounded in fighting with the
Hezbollah since January.
</P>
<P>
   It remained to be seen whether the militia's unceremonious
exodus from Jezzine foreshadowed a larger withdrawal of the 1,500
Israeli soldiers who occupy the zone, set up to protect Israel's
northern border towns from guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak has promised to pull
troops from the zone within a year, a pledge that will likely
involve lengthy negotiations with Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As the militia was trying to extricate itself from Jezzine,
local residents and politicians in the mostly Christian town were
calling on the Lebanese government to send in the army after the
SLA withdraws. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lebanese military officials Tuesday ruled out such a move,
stated televised reports from Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot send the army because we do not want to set a
precedent of giving Israel any security guarantee,'' said one
military official. ``We don't want to encourage any partial
solutions to occupation.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lebanese and Syrian officials say they want to negotiate a
comprehensive peace that includes the return of south Lebanon as
well as Syria's Golan Heights which has been occupied by Israel
since a 1967 war. Last year, Beirut rejected an Israeli offer of
withdrawal from south Lebanon in return for security guarantees and
accused Israel of trying to separate the Lebanese and Syrian peace
tracks. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; On Tuesday, Lebanese traveling the road to Jezzine said they
hoped the departure of the militia would bring a bit of normality
to a region torn for so long by war that its once-thriving
population of 40,000 had dwindled to less than 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fuad Issa and his brother, Murad, said they planned to reopen a
restaurant they had closed several years ago after the SLA
militiamen harassed them and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd come in, they didn't want to pay, and they'd come in
with their arms and intimidate the clientele,'' said Issa, 45. ``We
are very happy that the region is now liberated.''
</P>
<P>
   But some residents of Jezzine were left wondering what would
happen to the 70 or so militiamen who opted to stay behind.
Hezbollah and most Lebanese consider the militiamen traitors who
should face trial for treason.
</P>
<P>
   The SLA's commander, Gen. Antoine Lahd, has been sentenced to
death in absentia by Lebanon's courts.
</P>
<P>
   But lower ranking militiamen may not face the death penalty.
Most Lebanese say the militiamen were forced into the SLA's ranks
out of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hezbollah's leaders offered to grant amnesty to
militiamen who defected and those who have since pledged allegiance
to the Lebanese army have been treated well.
</P>
<P>
   Jezzine residents expressed hopes that the retreat would prove
to be the beginning of the end of Israel's presence in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope this is a retreat from all of Lebanon,'' said the
restaurateur Issa, echoing a theme often repeated by the Lebanese
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis are here by force,'' he said. ``They entered our
country without asking questions. They must leave the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
