<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-PAK-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-01 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PAK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 1 YEAR, CHANGES APLENTY FOR GOLFER SE RI-PAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life used to be much simpler for Se Ri-pak. Early last year, she
would arrive at tournaments attracting little attention, an
unfamiliar face in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew who I was, and nobody cared,'' Pak recalled with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when Pak became the hottest player in golf in
the spring and summer of 1998. In an incredible three months, Pak
won four tournaments, including two majors, and she recorded the
lowest score for a round in the history of the Ladies Professional
Golf Association, a 61.
</P>
<P>
   Pak became a hero in her native country, South Korea, and a
celebrity in the United States. It was enough to overwhelm anyone,
especially a 20-year-old rookie on tour, adjusting to a different
culture while still trying to learn the English language, as Pak
was last year. The sudden loss of privacy and free time, the raised
expectations and the crush of international news media now hungry
for details about her life became unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Pak who will defend her U.S. Women's Open title
is not exactly the same person, or player, she was a year ago. Pak
has not won a tournament since July and she was ranked 114th in
putting on the tour through last week. Going into the Open, which
begins Thursday at the Old Waverly Gold Club in West Point, Miss.,
her best finish this year in 11 tournaments is a tie for 18th.
Since her last victory, she has split with a coach, dismissed a
business manager and learned that fame and fortune always come with
a price.
</P>
<P>
   But while the upheaval in Pak's life, coupled with the slump,
are cause for concern, they also reflect a young woman who is
taking charge of her life. Pak's career is just beginning, and she
is determined to make it long and successful, much like that of her
idol, Nancy Lopez. Her peers, her supporters and even those who
have been dismissed from Pak's inner circle expect her to win
again, to win often and to leave a special mark on women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   Her talent is immense. Her will is strong. And this week, Pak
hopes to capitalize on one of her special traits: an ability to
play her best when the stakes are highest.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week in Sylvania, Ohio, Pak explained why
she loves the majors. ``I love the huge galleries,'' she said. ``I
love the people. Everything is more tense at a major, more
difficult, especially at the U.S. Open. But somehow, I feel
stronger when it's like that. It doesn't make me nervous. It makes
it more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing in the Open will bring back warm memories for Pak, the
youngest Open champion in history. She prevailed last year at
Blackwolf Run Golf Course in Kohler, Wis., in probably the most
thrilling tournament of 1998. Pak and Jenny Chuasiriporn, also 20
at the time, finished tied through 72 holes, then dueled in a
playoff the next day that was not decided until the 20th hole, when
Pak made a 15-foot putt for birdie and the victory. When she
finally won, Pak burst into tears as her father, Joon Chul-pak,
raced onto the green and lifted her off her feet.
</P>
<P>
   It was the high point of a remarkable year. Most players would
love to win two majors in career, period. Pak won the first two
majors she ever played.
</P>
<P>
   But in the ensuing months, Pak learned valuable lessons,
sometimes the hard way. After winning the McDonald's LPGA
Championship in May 1998, she had no idea how much life would
change. All the tournament directors wanted her to play their
events. More media and fans wanted her time.
</P>
<P>
   By the summer, Pak was checking into hotels under an assumed
name to avoid late-night phone calls. By the end of last season she
was worn down, and her performance fell off after competing in six
consecutive tournaments last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The worst experience occurred on a homecoming visit to South
Korea last fall, when Pak became ill and was hospitalized,
suffering from exhaustion and a severe cold. By all accounts, Pak
was overbooked, faced with nonstop public appearances after a
21-hour flight. Her main sponsor, Samsung, was criticized for
wearing her out. Meanwhile, Pak was bombarded by the South Korean
news media even after she became ill, and some photographers gained
access to her hospital room and took pictures of her while she was
hooked up to an intravenous tube, a tear running down her cheek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned that I'd have to do a better job looking after me,''
Pak said. ``Nobody else could do it. I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsung remains one of Pak's sponsors, and in January she signed
with the International Management Group, which also represents
David Duval, Tiger Woods and Mark O'Meara. On Tuesday, she signed
her first contract under the guidance of IMG, a three-year deal to
promote Maxfli balls that is reportedly the largest ball contract
in women's golf.
</P>
<P>
   Pak said her life had become much more organized.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Song Yung Kil, Pak's former business manager, who was
dismissed last winter, said he was unfairly blamed for some things,
but he also said Pak had probably felt the need to take more
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's young, and she's experiencing a lot of things for the
first time,'' Kil said. ``There's a lot of pressure on her. People
should understand that it takes time to adjust, but I think she's a
golfing genius. When her mind is right, she can win any week.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak bought a home in Orlando, Fla., last year, a three-minute
drive from Arnold Palmer's Bay Hill Golf Club and Lodge, where she
does most of her practicing.
</P>
<P>
   After winning $872,170 last year, has money changed her?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Pak said, flashing her warm smile. ``I bought a
house. I pay more taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   This week begins a crucial five-week stretch for Pak in which
she is defending three titles, two of them majors. With powerful
legs and a fluid swing, the prevailing notion is that Pak's malaise
is only temporary. David Leadbetter, Pak's former coach, who has
worked with major winners like Ernie Els, Nick Faldo, Greg Norman
and Nick Price, knows special talent when he sees it. And according
to Leadbetter, Pak is very special.
</P>
<P>
   ``She creates tremendous power without trying to hit the ball
extremely hard, what you might call effortless power,'' Leadbette
said. ``She's a very good athlete, partly due to her track and
field background. She's strong, but she's also flexible, a great
combination. She can call on that extra 10 or 15 yards when she
needs it, plus she has a good imagination, and we all know she
doesn't get flustered very easily on the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always tough for a young player to follow up a great year
with another. This is a phase she'll have to fight her way
through.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
