<SLUG> BC-OKEFENOKEE-FIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As wildfire burns on, rangers hope for rain
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wildfire crackled through the deep cypress swamps and
upland pine plantations of the Okefenokee National Wildlife Refuge
again Tuesday, bringing to 58,300 the acreage burned in Georgia and
Florida this year.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 22, when the current fire _ nicknamed ``Friendly
Fire'' for its origin at the Friendly Hunting Camp in Olustee, Fla.
_ jumped the Florida-Georgia border, it has destroyed more than
8,000 acres of the Okefenokee.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Georgia Forestry Commission dispatched 71
firefighters and heavy equipment to help contain the fire, said
Alan Dozier, chief of forest protection for the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Of paramount worry to Dozier and park rangers is the severity of
the drought in southeast Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give an idea of how severe, consider the Keetch-Byram
Index. Zero on the scale means water-saturated soil; 800 means no
moisture all the way down to 8 inches. Most of southeast Georgia is
above 700,'' Dozier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take 10 inches of rain over the next several days to
get that region back to zero, and right now the rain chance is very
slim,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, despite daily forecasts of thunderstorms, the line of
rain heading toward the Okefenokee has played out in Valdosta.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put out this fire, we would need 4 inches of rain to fall
in one or two days' time,'' Dozier said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia forestry officials are severely limiting outdoor burning
permits because of the high risk of wildfires. A 300-acre fire
occurred Monday in Jeff Davis County after someone burned a leaf
pile. It was one of six wildfires to blacken 976 acres in Bacon,
Jeff Davis and Wayne counties on Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephen Foster State Park in Charlton County, Chief Ranger
Jackie Clay said she is not allowing campfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of year, park traffic tends to thin out anyway,
due to bugs and heat. So far we have not experienced any changes in
air quality or animal patterns because of the fires in the National
Wildlife Refuge,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No park facilities have been destroyed by the wildfires, but
Dozier predicted a substantial portion of the swamp will be
destroyed if drought conditions don't soon improve.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
