<HEADER>
A9105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-PAK-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      06-01 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PAK-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: way through.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Pak is fighting her way through without Leadbetter. After
leaving South Korea in 1997 to work with Leadbetter in Florida, the
coach and player split late last year, partly because Pak felt that
Leadbetter no longer devoted enough time to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great coach, but he was always busy,'' Pak said. ``He
was out of town a lot, taking care of business, taking care of
other players. There were times when I felt like I needed him, and
he wasn't there. Right now, I'm still looking for a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Leadbetter believes Pak may have made a hasty decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most players usually don't change coaches when they're playing
well,'' Leadbetter said. ``She's a wonderful person. I wish her all
the best. But at the end of last year, I saw things I didn't like.
I thought she needed a break, so I told her to rest. The next day I
saw her practicing. She told me she talked to her father and that
he said she needed to practice. She had a lot of people telling her
a lot of different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak's father admittedly drove his daughter hard to be a
champion. Pak first touched a golf club when she was 11, but by the
time she was 14, she was winning tournaments. Pak's father would
make her practice for hours, even on days when it was cold enough
for icicles to form in her hair. To make Pak mentally stronger,
father and daughter sometimes camped out together in a tent at
night at a local cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   But to this day, father and daughter remain close. They speak on
the phone daily, and Pak's parents will be in Mississippi this week
to watch her at the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may have the impression that her father is hard, but
he's very supportive,'' said Jay Burton, Pak's business manager.
``I mean, she hasn't won this year, but he hasn't raced over here
to see what's wrong. When you're a parent, your children eventually
grow up, and then it's up to them. I think he's realizing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak resents the notion that her father is putting too much
pressure on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad understands how hard golf is,'' Pak said. ``There's a
lot of pressure on him, too. People in Korea are just waiting. Even
though I won four tournaments last year, they're waiting for No. 5,
then No. 6. They love me, but they want to know, how long do we
have to wait? That makes me unhappy. It's not easy to win
tournaments; it's not easy to be one of the top 10 players.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Women's Open has the potential to be memorable
again, with many players looking ready to win. Karrie Webb, who
leads the LPGA money list, has won four times this year. Meg
Mallon, Juli Inkster and Rachel Hetherington have each won twice.
Lopez will again be the sentimental favorite, trying to win her
first Open. Two-time Open champion Annika Sorenstam can never be
overlooked, while Chuasiriporn will be making her pro debut after
helping Duke University win the collegiate championship in May.
</P>
<P>
   But Pak has proved what she is capable of. And despite the bumps
in the road, she is still enjoying the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see other 21-year-olds, and I realize I've given up some
things,'' Pak said. ``I've had to work hard, but it has been worth
it. I love golf. This is the life I want. I don't want to have just
one good year. I want a great career. Sometimes when you push hard,
things get worse. But I feel my best is still ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
