<SLUG> BC-BOYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA BOYS RANCH LICENSED FOR 1 YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
 RANCH-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT FLANNERY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A smaller, less hard-bitten Arizona Boys Ranch was granted a
one-year state license after regulators concluded the controversial
boot camp has been made safer since the death of a student last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you have a rogue employee, something like the Nicholaus
Contreraz case should never happen again with these reforms,'' said
James Hart, assistant director of the Arizona Department of
Economic Security. ``The whole basis for the reforms is to ensure
the safety of children.''
</P>
<P>
   The new operating license, which had been denied by the state
for 10 months, is expected by Boys Ranch officials to boost
enrollment at the 50-year-old home for troubled kids. Enrollment
dropped to 43 from more than 600 after Contreraz, a 16-year-old
Californian, died March 2, 1998, at the Oracle campus from an
untreated lung ailment.
</P>
<P>
   A state investigation found that his pleas for medical help went
unheeded as he was punished and taunted as a laggard by some school
employees.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, regulators concluded that there was ``a
pattern of abuse and neglect'' at the school fueled by management's
disregard for the rights of youngsters placed in their care.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators and school officials last November agreed to a
settlement and nearly three dozen changes to end the
confrontational disciplinary style that once was a source of Boys
Ranch pride.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, DES officials expressed cautious optimism that
permanent changes are afoot to make the program safer and more
accountable to regulators. They said Boys Ranch has put every
recommendation into effect that was requested by DES and
independent consultants who evaluated the program last year.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Vega of Sacramento, Contreraz's mother, said the state
should nonetheless keep a close eye on the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they keep on monitoring them and they run the place
like it's supposed to be, it'll be alright,'' Vega said.
</P>
<P>
   Criminal trials are still pending against three former Boys
Ranch employees who were charged in Contreraz's death. Linda Babb,
a nurse, faces manslaughter and child abuse charges in Pinal County
Superior Court. Troy Michael Jones and Montgomery Hoover face child
abuse charges.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Babb, Jones and Hoover were reduced from
murder last month. Charges were dropped entirely against two other
former Boys Ranch workers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Charles Ratliff, a spokesman for the Pinal County Attorney's
Office, said no trial date has yet been set.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious difference in Boys Ranch since Conteraz's death
is in its size. Boys Ranch development coordinator Casandra McCray
said 43 boys are enrolled at the Queen Creek campus. Other campuses
have been shut down, economic casualties of Contreraz's death, when
students were withdrawn and new referrals dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Boys Ranch brought in new management and stayed open under an
extension of its old license. But McCray said welfare agencies and
courts in and out of Arizona withheld new referrals until a
decision was made on a permanent license. Only three current Boys
Ranch students are from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to continue to grow,'' McCray said. ``What this
does is open doors to people who wanted to wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Board chairman Robert Johnson said in a prepared statement that
``rebuilding'' efforts would include partnerships with juvenile
referral agencies in Arizona. He said Boys Ranch intends to ``move
forward with renewed vigor and dedication.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the student population will be much smaller, reflecting
a feeling by consultants that Boys Ranch had grown too fast in
recent years, Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   The new license will permit only the Queen Creek campus
southeast of Phoenix to operate. The student population is capped
at 268. In early 1998, Boys Ranch ran seven campuses with more than
600 students.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators feel the most notable change to date involves how
child abuse is reported. Boys Ranch employees must now call DES'
Child Abuse Hotline if they witness abusive behavior or injuries on
campus, and they must file a written report to Boys Ranch managers
within hours of witnessing a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, reports _ often oral _ went to Boys Ranch
administrators, who decided whether to pass information on to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an opportunity for cases to fall through the
cracks,'' Hart said. ``This is a major change.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking with years of tradition, the school also retooled its
policy on physical discipline. Where daily confrontations and
hands-on discipline were once the norm, Hart said employees now may
use physical force only if the student poses a danger to himself or
to others, or is damaging property.
</P>
<P>
   In such cases, problem students are forcibly taken to a cottage
for disruptive students, where they are counseled by
specially-trained employees. Each incident must be reported, and
reviewed by a behavior management review board.
</P>
<P>
   State officials and independent consultants will still keep tabs
to be sure the new policies are strictly followed. Recent
unannounced visits by DES workers found workers adhering to the
changes, Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Flannery can be reached at (602) 444-8629 or at
pat.flannery(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
