<SLUG> BC-RUN-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEGAS GUIDES BRUINS TO NCAA MEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA throwing coach Art Venegas has guided
athletes to 24 NCAA individual titles. His Bruins have participated
in the NCAA championships every year since his arrival in 1981, and
he claims Jackie-Joyner Kersee, John Godina and Jonathan Ogden as
pupils.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1984 championships, John Brenner unofficially opened the
Venegas era with victories in the discus and shot put. In 1995, his
athletes won an astounding five of the seven throwing events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat there in disbelief,'' said Venegas, a Cal State
Northridge graduate and San Fernando Valley resident since 1962.
``No matter how much you prepare, things can go wrong. Kids get
sick, or have foul trouble, or someone from the other teams does
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Venegas isn't sure what to expect when the NCAA Track and Field
Championships begin today in Boise, Idaho. The UCLA women are
ranked No.1 in the nation according to the U.S. Track Coaches
Association, and they could bring home the Bruins' second NCAA
title in a week, following the softball team's victory Monday in
Oklahoma City. UCLA men are rated sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Venegas has several athletes hoping to add to his sensational
title tally, most notably junior Seilala Sua, ranked first in the
nation in the shot put and discus. Senior Luke Sullivan, ranked
fifth in the discus, also has a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get to the NCAAs, I'm more like a fan,'' Venegas said.
``I want them to show me what they can do. Can they surprise me?
</P>
<P>
   ``On the men's side, we have good throwers, but they aren't
overwhelming. We do have a superstar in Seilala, and I expect her
to bring home some titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Bruins expected to challenge for NCAA individual titles
include senior Joanna Hayes (100- and 400-meter hurdles), freshman
pole vaulter Tracy O'Hara, and sophomore Shakedia Jones in the 200
meters.
</P>
<P>
   However it ends, with more titles or a twinge of disappointment,
Venegas won't waste much time preparing for next season. In fact,
he might have a few more responsibilities. Men's head coach Bob
Larson is expected to retire after the season, sources said, and
Venegas is the leading candidate to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN junior Brandi Prieto, who helped the Matadors women win the
Big Sky Conference outdoor championship last week, is competing in
Boise in the triple jump. Her leap of 42-11} at the Big Sky meet
ranks eleventh in the NCAA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
