<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIR-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FATIGUE AND THE FAA'S METABOLISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, June 2:
</P>
<P>
   Pilots, airlines and safety experts have long prodded the
Federal Aviation Administration to modernize its 1985 rule
requiring pilots to get at least eight hours of rest in the 24
hours before the end of their flight duty. Since 1989 the National
Transportation Safety Board has urged the agency to develop new
standards that better reflect research findings about sleep, the
body's circadian rhythms and fatigue countermeasures. Yet
throughout this decade, the FAA's efforts to draft new rules have
floundered. The one action the FAA can, and should, take
immediately is to outlaw two practices known to contribute to
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial aviation in the United States enjoys an enviable
safety record, and fatigue is by no means a major cause of
accidents. Even so, two accidents in the last few years, including
one in 1993 in Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, demonstrate that fatigue can
impair pilot performance and decision-making. At Guantanamo Bay, a
cargo airliner struck the ground about a quarter-mile before it
reached the runway, destroying the plane and seriously injuring the
crew. The FAA cited impaired judgment and flying ability as
probable causes, noting that the crew was suffering from
``disruption of circadian rhythms and sleep loss, which resulted in
fatigue. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 draft rule would have cut a pilot's on-duty hours from 16
to 14 a day. Within that it set 10 hours as the maximum for flight
duty, up from 8. The daily rest period would have expanded from 8
hours to 10. Pilots opposed the flight-duty increase. The airlines,
via the Air Transport Association, disliked the price tag. They
said that the draft rule would cost more than $1 billion for new
pilots in the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, however, approved of two anti-fatigue provisions.
One would rid the rules of language that can be used to supersede
the limit on flight time. The other would end the ability to exceed
the limit on flight time by assigning pilots to so-called tail-end
ferrying, moving near-empty planes from one locale to another.
These anti-fatigue measures would help prevent another Guantanamo
Bay. Both ought to be added to the FAA's books promptly. Then the
FAA should revise the overall rest-and-duty rules based on the
latest scientific evidence. There is no need for further delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2312EDT &QL; 
