<HEADLINE>
LEAH RAY WERBLIN, 82, VOCALIST, RACEHORSE OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., N.J.)   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leah Ray Werblin, one of the country's best known vocalists in
the Big Band era and later, with her husband, the owner of the
Elberon Farm in thoroughbred racing, died in her sleep last
Thursday at her home in Rumson, N.J. She was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Werblin, the former Leah Ray Hubbard of Norfolk, Va., was a
singer with Tommy Dorsey, Phil Harris and other bands as Leah Ray
when she met and married David ``Sonny'' Werblin, an agent with
Music Corporation of America. They were married for more than 50
years.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Werblin later became an officer of Monmouth Park race
track and president of the New York Jets football team, built the
Meadowlands Sports Complex and was chairman of Madison Square
Garden. He and his wife raced many outstanding horses, including
the 2-year-old champion Silent Screen.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Werblin died on Nov. 21, 1991. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Werblin is survived by two sons, Thomas of New York and
Robert of Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
