<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-01 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9262 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-INDICT-AZR &LR;      06-01 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-INDICT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTSDALE DISTRICT EMPLOYEES INCLUDED IN CRIMINAL INDICTMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   State authorities announced the criminal indictments Tuesday of
several current or former school officials, saying Arizona children
are being robbed by a ``culture of complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictments accuse nine people _ including four with ties to
the Scottsdale School District _ of fraud, bid-rigging and misusing
public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Among the accusations: Public school officials catered a private
party with cafeteria food and workers, used credit cards to pay for
gambling trips and even paid themselves salaries while they served
time in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about public monies for the education of our
kids,'' Attorney General Janet Napolitano said Tuesday in
announcing the indictments. ``It's our job to make sure those
monies are spent in the classrooms, on the teachers and on the
students where they were meant to be spent, and not on personal
benefit for personal gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictments involve districts of varying size and wealth and
from both urban and rural areas. Napolitano said she doesn't see an
epidemic of problems with violations of procurement laws by
district officials, but she said that other cases are still under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first wave of cases,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano, whose office handled the investigations, said the
grand jury indictments focused on four Arizona districts:
Scottsdale Unified, Sunnyside Unified in Tucson, Paloma Elementary
near Gila Bend and Humboldt Unified in Yavapai County.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general issued ``letters of concern'' to three
other districts ordering them to correct potentially illegal
activities. Mesa Unified, Bouse Elementary near Parker and Yuma
Elementary were sent such letters.
</P>
<P>
   Napolitano said the indictments stemmed from investigations by
her office's School Fraud Task Force, which she formed after her
election in January in response to complaints from around the
state.
</P>
<P>
   None of the indictments announced Tuesday appeared to involve
huge sums of money, but Napolitano said they indicated that a
``culture of complacency'' has been allowed to flourish, allowing
the alleged violations to occur without being detected by district
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more extreme cases involved officials in the food
services department at Tucson's Sunnyside Unified District. Juan
Flores, former director of food services, is accused in an
indictment of allowing the use of district food, facilities and
employees to cater a private party for 250 people.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, who retired early last year, couldn't be reached for
comment Tuesday. District officials said they conducted their own
investigation into the allegations, but no corroborating witnesses
came forward until after the attorney general's investigation
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been aware of the investigation for a number of
months, and we have been cooperating with the attorney general,''
said Monique Soria, a district spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In the Paloma Elementary District near Gila Bend, former
superintendent Frank Solano was indicted in the theft of nearly
$5,000 from the district. He is accused of issuing himself a check
for writing and administering grants even though he already was
being paid for those services as part of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Solano, who reportedly moved to Nevada last year, also is
accused of accepting $1,500 in pay for days he was actually in jail
for failing to pay child support. And he is charged with using a
district credit card to pay for gambling trips.
</P>
<P>
   The largest number of indictments involve former employees of
the Scottsdale Unified District. It was sued eight months ago by
the Attorney General's Office after investigators discovered cases
of fee-splitting, kickbacks and bid rigging in the district's
contract process.
</P>
<P>
   The district admitted to illegally awarding $11.7 million in
contracts and agreed to pay a $300,000 civil penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale indictments announced Tuesday focused mainly on
Edward F. Biszantz, the district's former building services
director. He and his wife, Shirley Henry-Biszantz, are charged with
theft and fraud for allegedly using a district-owned laptop
computer for her private business and then trying to conceal it by
erasing files and making false statements to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Biszantz, who retired from the district in January, also
was indicted with Dennis J. Peloquin for allegedly concocting a
bid-rigging scheme to ensure that Peloquin's business, Amer-X
Security, would be chosen to provide the district's security
system.
</P>
<P>
   In the more than yearlong investigation into the Scottsdale
district's finances, auditors found the couple accepted a discount
on personal and business security systems and monitoring services
worth $2,707 three months after school officials asked for sealed
bids on security services. Auditors cited procurement violations
worth $103,112.
</P>
<P>
   The Biszantzes were unavailable for comment Tuesday. Tod
Schleier, attorney for the couple, said he was reviewing the
charges and planned to meet his clients later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly they look forward for an opportunity to defend
themselves and have this matter heard by a jury,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peloquin did not return phone calls. His security company has
been a Scottsdale district vendor for more than five years.
</P>
<P>
   District Board President Barbara Newby said she doesn't expect
the indictments to bring closure to the scandal that has rocked the
school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over in my mind until I hear from them that we are
all done,'' said Newby, who months ago admonished school
administrators for not formally charging Biszantz or putting him on
paid leave.
</P>
<P>
   Two state legislators who backed a bill earlier this year to
strengthen school district procurement laws said they would pursue
plans to hold more hearings on the issue this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Marc Spitzer,
R-north-central Phoenix, said his committee would meet to hear
testimony on alleged violations. The committee might use the
Legislature's power to subpoena witnesses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big reservoir of complaints,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barry Wong, R-north-central Phoenix, also said he would
like to conduct joint House-Senate hearings on the issue. Wong
joined Spitzer and Sen. Ruth Solomon, D-Tucson, in supporting
legislation that gives more enforcement power to the attorney
general and the auditor general in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to continue that work,'' Wong said. ``We'll probably
also look at charter school issues, too. It is important to shed
more light on this.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
