<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAWDIE ACCENTUATED THE POSITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Every so often a column attempting to look on life's
brighter side results in a particularly troubling response.
</P>
<P>
   These are the ones from members of the clergy implying that it's
insensitive, or even heartless, to express the view that while life
in America isn't perfect, each generation has it better than the
last. The columns in question challenge widely publicized efforts
by the chronically lugubrious to make the case that today's
beleaguered working class is losing ground.
</P>
<P>
   Such contentions are at odds with ubiquitous signs of prosperity
even though the authors use myriad statistics to prove their
claims. Columns challenging these claims bring considerable
response from well-meaning folk saying it's bad form to gloss over
the plight of the struggling classes.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally these reproofs come from ministers. What made the
most recent ministerial admonition ironic was its arrival about the
same time a family member was helping me track down a copy of a
column written 16 years ago during similar circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Columnists are probably best served by resisting the urge to
explain themselves, but criticisms occasionally strike a personal
nerve so deeply it becomes impossible not to give in to these
urges. Like this one, the column back in May 1983 focused on
another clergyman. His name was Harvey Orr, and he had more
influence on my life than any other person. His call came
relatively late in life, prompting him to abandon a promising
career as an executive with the Pennsylvania Railroad to become a
Presbyterian minister.
</P>
<P>
   He was my mother's father and his family called him Dawdie, a
nickname bestowed by one of his four daughters who had trouble
saying Daddy. Dawdie was a country preacher ministering to rural
flocks in Virginia and West Virginia. Those who worshiped in
Dawdie's churches were working people, mostly of limited means,
like Dawdie.
</P>
<P>
   None likely considered themselves disadvantaged, however,
because they accepted the struggle of keeping body and soul
together as life's norm. Dawdie never earned much, but his
propensity for thrift allowed him to work miracles with what he
had. One of his most remarkable achievements was sending four
daughters through college during the 1930s. He did this despite the
economic challenge posed by the Great Depression and the cultural
challenge posed by a society that didn't encourage higher education
for women.
</P>
<P>
   Dawdie's legacy to me was a respect for hard work and an
optimism based on the enduring conviction that no matter how bad
things get, they could always be worse. When things don't get
worse, it's cause for joy and thanks.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the stuff of a make-believe Pollyanna. It's a matter
of being able to look around and appreciate your own particular
place in the overall scheme of things. My feedback over the years
leads to the conclusion that those preoccupied with life's downside
are entirely focused on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dawdie's world included a lot of people who were disadvantaged,
by the standard of any generation. He never, however, pitied them
or patronized them. What he did was try to appeal to the best they
had to give on their journey through this life.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, he seemed to succeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
