<SLUG> BC-CERNER-CORP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CERNER CORP. OFFICER SAYS MEDICAL SOFTWARE BUSINESS REGAINS
MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Cerner Corp.'s medical software business has
bottomed out, and the company's financial fortunes are headed back
up, Cerner's top officer told shareholders Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Neal L. Patterson, the North Kansas City medical software
company's chairman, president and chief executive officer, said he
didn't expect the upward trend to emerge quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Some potential Cerner customers have delayed purchases until
they finish fixing problems related to the year 2000 computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   But while Y2K problems should fade next year, health providers
are ``in for a couple of very tough years'' because of cutbacks in
Medicare payments, Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balanced Budget Act of 1997 took out $115 billion of
payments that were previously targeted toward hospitals, doctors
and home health agencies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Providers must deal with the Medicare cuts along with tighter
reimbursements from managed care companies, Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Patterson said Cerner would market its software as a
tool that hospitals and other providers can use to save money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our technologies are positioned to be part of the answer for
these health-care systems to get through this very tough time
they're heading toward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner's HNA Millennium software is designed to loop together
the information systems of hospitals, pharmacies, laboratories,
doctors' offices and other health-related entities, thereby cutting
paperwork and streamlining services.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual meeting, Patterson, Thomas A. McDonnell and former
U.S. Sen. Jack Danforth of Missouri were re-elected to the board of
directors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
