<HEADER>
A9267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOBBY-DONATE-2TAKE     06-01 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOBBY-DONATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ALBANY, LEGISLATORS MINGLE WITH LOBBYISTS BEARING GIFTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Soon after the New York Legislature recessed for
the day recently, the Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, set up shop
in a secluded room at a hotel near the Capitol. There he stood for
more than an hour, flanked by aides and other prominent lawmakers,
a receiving line of Democrats with the power to give bills wings or
slap them into the trash. The price to enjoy such company: a $2,500
campaign contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Silver and his colleagues were thronged by the very lobbyists
who lobby them by day, including that day. Need to follow up on a
chat in a Statehouse corridor, buttonhole an elusive committee
chairman, smooth the way for a contentious proposal? In the Albany
tradition, buy a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important part of the system,'' said Robert Malito,
a ubiquitous lobbyist who attended the fund-raising event, as well
as a Republican one, here that night. After receiving donations, he
said, legislators ``are more apt to bring you in and say, `What's
on your mind?' later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers of both major parties have long sponsored fund-raising
events while the Legislature is in session, realizing that
lobbyists looking for help on legislation would be reluctant to
rebuff requests for contributions. But the practice is more
prevalent than ever in Albany, even as more than 20 states have
banned similar fund-raisers, decreeing it unseemly for legislators
to collect donations in their capitals while they are in session.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising, in fact, is one activity that has not bogged down
in Albany in a year when almost everything else has. Legislative
leaders and Gov. George Pataki are so at odds that the state budget
is two months late, significant decisions on health care policy and
other major issues have been shoved aside, and lawmakers are having
one of their least productive sessions in recent memory. Not so
their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   With the cost of political races rising, members are asking for
higher donations and holding far more events than they did only a
few years ago, many lobbyists say. There are 211 lawmakers, and by
the scheduled end of the six-month session on June 16, most will
have passed the hat in the capital area _ even though none of them
face the voters until next year. The political committees run by
the legislative leaders will also have held several events,
including the one at the hotel the other night, sponsored by the
Democratic Assembly Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the cocktails and hors d'oeuvres, it was a scene that
could have been transplanted from the foyer outside the Assembly
chamber. There was Malito, a lion of the lobbying establishment
(whose clients range from Philip Morris to the American Diabetes
Association), greeting Assemblyman Herman Farrell Jr., chairman of
the Ways and Means Committee. Nearby was Lester Shulklapper
(Bankers Association, Beer Wholesalers, et al), as well as
lobbyists for hospitals, doctors, securities firms, funeral
directors, teachers and state workers, to name just a few.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raisers are not exactly a secret in Albany, but neither
are they widely publicized, and several lobbyists at this one
grimaced when a reporter asked why they attended, as if they had
been questioned about their weight. They then declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The more active lobbyists frequent most lawmakers' fund-raisers,
sometimes half a dozen a night. So it was no surprise that the cast
at the Democratic fund-raiser was similar to one at an affair
sponsored the same evening by state Sen. Michael Balboni, a Nassau
County Republican ($300 a ticket).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really social,'' Balboni said of the practice, playing
down any link to lawmakers' decisions. ``I really mean it. I know
there is a perceived connection.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raisers are not intended for ordinary folks eager to
take part in the democratic process. Lawmakers often draw
invitation lists from the state's index of registered lobbyists,
and ticket prices range from $150 for events benefiting one
lawmaker to $2,500 for the private receptions held by the
legislative campaign committees. At those prices, a legislator can
raise $5,000 to $25,000 in a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Such largess is not available to challengers in elections, for
whom lobbyists have little use. This is one reason incumbents are
rarely defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and other statewide officials also occasionally sponsor
fund-raisers in Albany, but they are less dependent on them. For
high-ranking politicians, lobbyists are more willing to travel.
</P>
<P>
   A few renegade lawmakers, led by Assemblyman Alexander Grannis,
a Manhattan Democrat, have proposed in recent years that New York
emulate other states and prohibit the Albany fund-raisers. But
legislative leaders of both major parties have quashed the bill in
the past, and it appears to have little chance this year.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers generally oppose changing the state's
campaign finance rules, and assert that there is nothing improper
about the events. State Sen. Serphin Maltese, a Queens Republican
who is chairman of the Elections Committee, said of a ban, ``I
don't think that accomplishes anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides declined to say whether the governor favored a
ban.
</P>
<P>
   Even Silver, a supporter of tighter restrictions on fund-raising
in state politics, and the Assembly Democratic leadership see
nothing wrong with the events. ``I don't think it makes a
difference where you hold a fund-raiser,'' Silver said, taking a
break from shaking lobbyists' hands the other night.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois, where the politics is as rough-and-tumble as in New
York, many lawmakers maintained that view until an
influence-peddling scandal embarrassed Illinois politicians. Last
year, the Illinois Legislature passed an ethics measure that barred
both lawmakers and statewide officials from collecting donations
during the session in the capital, Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of appearance,'' said state Sen. Kirk Dillard, a
Republican from a Chicago suburb who was a sponsor of the measure.
``The public doesn't believe that you should be holding a
fund-raiser breakfast in a morning and two hours later going over
to a capital building casting votes on legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, at times, there seems to be only the narrowest divide
between the work of the Legislature and the political campaigns of
its members. Fund-raisers are sometimes held in state-owned
buildings a few hundred yards from legislative chambers during a
break in legislative action in the middle of the day. One day last
month, just before the state Senate went into session, members of
the Republican majority and lobbyists trooped down to a privately
run restaurant in the state-owned mall connected to the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   For a $500 donation to the Republicans' committee, the lobbyists
hobnobbed at a luncheon sponsored by Joseph Bruno and other
Republican senators. Afterward, many of the participants returned
for the session in the Senate, where some of the lobbyists assumed
their customary positions on the couches outside the chambers,
continuing their talks with the Republican senators who
occasionally exited the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Grannis of Manhattan, who does not sponsor
fund-raisers in Albany, said ``this money hustle is shameful,
really shameful.'' (Similar criticism is also heard in Washington,
where members of Congress routinely hold these types of affairs).
</P>
<P>
   To most lobbyists, the events are practically a price of working
here. Some readily acknowledge the benefits of attending, spending
tens of thousands of dollars on tickets annually _ both their own
money and their clients'. Yet in the same breath, they insist that
money plays no role in lawmakers' decisions about whom to meet or
how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps with access,'' Shulklapper said. ``It's best to show
your face.'' But he added that ``nobody is bought by a fund-raiser.
There is nothing sinister going on. It's a social event.''
</P>
<P>
   Shulklapper said he opposed a ban on Albany events, particularly
if the alternative would be having to attend fund-raisers in
districts across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the fund-raisers are social events or arm-twisting
sessions, many lobbyists would probably not miss them if they were
banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not particularly pleasurable,'' Margaret Boepple,
chief lobbyist for Nixon, Hargrave, Devans &AMP; Doyle, one of the
leading firms in the capital, said of the events. ``But until
things change here, they are a necessary part of doing business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
