<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW APPROACH TO NORTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 2:
</P>
<P>
   North Korea can improve relations with the United States by
responding positively to the offer William Perry, the former
defense secretary, delivered last week. Perry carried a letter from
President Clinton offering to phase out American economic sanctions
and begin steps toward diplomatic recognition of North Korea. But
Washington will do so only if Pyongyang commits itself to give up
its nuclear weapons ambitions and long-range missile programs.
</P>
<P>
   Perry got a warm welcome, although he did not get to meet with
the North's leader, Kim Jong-il. Pyongyang should be given
reasonable time to reply to the Clinton proposal, but would be most
unwise to reject it.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's new offer goes well beyond the 1994 agreement that
froze North Korea's nuclear weapons program in exchange for help in
constructing Western-style power reactors. The North continues to
comply with that agreement, as shown again last week when American
inspectors found no evidence of building at a site Washington once
feared was being prepared for new nuclear installations.
</P>
<P>
   But provocative North Korean actions in other areas, like last
year's surprise test of a long-range missile, and repeated requests
for large sums of money in exchange for further arms control
progress, have left Washington wary of making further incremental
deals with the North.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea, for its part, feels that it was led to expect some
progress toward ending sanctions and moving toward recognition in
1994 and that Washington has not yet followed through on these
issues. The administration can return to these questions now
because of a recent change in South Korean policies toward the
North. Kim Dae-jung, who became South Korea's president last year,
favors a conciliatory policy toward Pyongyang, including an end to
American sanctions. He hopes that expanding economic and diplomatic
ties will encourage gradual change in the North and decrease the
chances of a new war on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is right to coordinate America's policies with
Seoul's by also offering better ties. But there can be little
progress unless the North abandons its nuclear and missile
ambitions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
