<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA OFFICIAL PESSIMISTIC ABOUT DODGERS TRAINING CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ A leading state official said Florida Gov. Jeb
Bush's vetoing of a $7.5 million funding bill killed Vero Beach's
efforts to keep the Los Angeles Dodgers training at Dodgertown.
</P>
<P>
   Indian River County administrator Jim Chandler said Bush's
surprising decision last Thursday to ax the bill leaves the city
and county without a way to come up with the needed $20 million in
funding. They have $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state funding was going to be absolutely critical in
trying to retain the Dodgers,'' Chandler said. ``Without that
funding, at least from our perspective at this time, it kills our
effort to keep the Dodgers here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision also strengthens the bargaining position of the
Fort McDowell Indian Community, which is trying to lure the Dodgers
to the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials will meet with city and county representatives
today in Vero Beach to discuss the next step, but Chandler said he
doesn't believe the Dodgers will remain at Dodgertown ``unless
there's a dramatic change.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers want the city and county to purchase Dodgertown from
the ballclub and renovate the facility. However, the land itself
was appraised by the Dodgers at $14.5 million, and the local
government said it has no other funding available.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Callan, managing director of Dodgertown, said the meeting
was called by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've planned a meeting with them to go over all of the
events, and see if there's anything we can do to keep the Dodgers
in Vero Beach,'' said Callan, a Dodgers employee who lives there.
</P>
<P>
   Callan was asked if this was the last meeting between the
Dodgers and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope not, but it all depends on how the meeting
goes,'' Callan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers began spring training in Dodgertown in 1948 and are
the only major-league team to own its own facility.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in Arizona said the Fort McDowell folks are eager to
take a more aggressive role in negotiating with the Dodgers in the
next few weeks. A spokesperson for the Yavapai Tribe, which owns
the land near Phoenix, said the cost of the project can be cut from
$50 million to near $30 million if the facility is built for one
team instead of two.
</P>
<P>
   Other significant, periphery cutbacks can be made if the Dodgers
make some concessions, such as lowering the number of proposed
housing units from 260 to approximately 100.
</P>
<P>
   Brown starts Friday: The Dodgers, who are off Thursday, will
keep right-handers Kevin Brown and Chan Ho Park on their regular
rotation of four days rest while pushing lefty Carlos Perez back in
the pitching sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Brown will pitch Friday's series opener against the Angels. Park
pitches Saturday. Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said Sunday's
starter is undecided because of various circumstances, ranging from
Ismael Valdes' blister to Darren Dreifort's ailing shin.
</P>
<P>
   Draft talks: The annual amateur draft begins today, and with it
comes the first significant opportunity for the Dodgers' new regime
to begin upgrading their minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers lost their first-round pick (20th overall) to the
San Diego Padres as compensation for signing pitcher Kevin Brown
during the offseason. Their first pick is a ``sandwich'' pick
between the first and second rounds (37th overall). The Dodgers
also have picks at 69th and 83rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to increase our athleticism, increase our raw talent,
our raw speed,'' said Bill Geivett, Dodgers assistant general
manager and minor-league director. ``Those are the impact tools.
That's something we need to focus on throughout the system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' minor-league teams entered Tuesday with an
aggregate mark of 96-110 and few good prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: The Dodgers announced Dodger Stadium
will be the first major-league ballpark to display publicly Mark
McGwire's record-setting 70th home run baseball when they host the
Angels this Friday through Sunday. It kicks off the club's 13th
annual Think Blue Week.... Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall's triple in
the third inning extended his hitting streak to 12 games, matching
a career high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
