<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CUNY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CUNY'S WORST ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 2:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki's appointment of Herman Badillo as the
chairman of the City University of New York has incited outrage
from some of CUNY's longtime supporters. The man they call CUNY's
``worst enemy'' or ``the purveyor of chaos'' is now in charge. For
all their worry, however, Badillo's reputation could be one of his
assets in today's political environment. A close ally of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani and a supporter of Pataki, this experienced
politician might be able to wangle more state and city support for
the 200,000-student complex. The problem is that CUNY is a lot
easier to criticize than to fix. Badillo's formidable task will be
to add much-needed value to a CUNY degree without destroying New
York City's traditionally open ``gateway'' to a college education
and its rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo, a City University graduate himself who promotes a
by-your-bootstraps philosophy that he says helped bring him into
power in New York, will first have to find a four-star chancellor.
He needs a forceful and independent-minded educator to take over
CUNY's 6 community colleges, 11 senior colleges and a law school,
medical school and graduate school. High-quality candidates may be
difficult to find, given the dangers of political interference
through Badillo's allegiances to the mayor and governor, the
questions about whether his CUNY chairmanship is a prelude to
running for New York City mayor in 2001 and Badillo's own hot
rhetoric on the subject of city education.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo, who was appointed on Saturday by the governor, said he
would push forcefully to end the ``remediation industry'' at CUNY.
He would make certain that CUNY phases out remedial classes for
most senior colleges and requires students to pass reading, writing
and mathematics exams with the help of ``immersion'' programs run
by CUNY before they can enter CUNY's bachelor's degree programs.
The new chairman also said he planned to ask for extra funds to
expand the College Now program that allows CUNY's professors to
help high schools around the city better prepare their students to
graduate and go on to college.
</P>
<P>
   While giving the CUNY degree more clout, however, Badillo and
his colleagues should not destroy the openness of CUNY or the
freedom that allows some students, such as working mothers, to take
longer than customary to get their degrees. The new chairman must
also find ways to encourage confidence in him by the CUNY faculty
and the Board of Regents. He has already begun saying, as he did
Tuesday in an interview at The Times, that ``we have no secret
agenda to close down CUNY or anything of the sort.'' Those
comforting words, like his sharp criticisms in the recent past, now
compete for reality as Badillo begins his charge at the city's
university system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-99 2335EDT &QL; 
