<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG DOING WORSE ECONOMICALLY TWO YEARS AFTER HANDOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two years after being taken back by China, Hong Kong
is doing better politically and worse economically than was
expected in 1997, according to a delegation visiting Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Four Hong Kong spokesmen, two associated with the Hong Kong
government and two from the opposition Democratic Party, addressed
the Asia Society in Seattle Tuesday. While they didn't agree on
everything, there was some consensus.
</P>
<P>
   First, the economy continues downhill. Economist Joseph Lian, a
member of the Hong Kong Government's Central Policy Unit, said
output declined last quarter and that unemployment is at a 15-year
high of 6.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lian said the economy should be ready to rebound, but that the
rebound would be slow. Because the Hong Kong dollar is pegged to
the U.S. dollar, he said, price adjustment has been slower than in
countries that have devalued currencies. Hong Kong rents have
fallen by a quarter and condo prices by about half. But he said,
``Wages have not adjusted downward.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong has had nothing like the U.S. Social Security or
unemployment insurance programs. Sin Chung Kai, the Democratic
spokesman for the economy, said the territory will start a
mandatory retirement fund next year that would take 5 percent of
wages each from private sector employees and employers.
</P>
<P>
   Because it stepped into the markets in the currency crisis of
last summer, the Hong Kong government owns 17 percent of the stocks
traded locally. Sin said the government plans to reduce that to 5
percent, ``which is a good move.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong also has about 36,000 unsold condos, the highest in 10
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the political side, Lau Siu Kai, chairman of the sociology
department at Chinese University and a former adviser to China,
said the return of Hong Kong to China has gone reasonably well.
Polls of Hong Kong people show that China's leaders, Jiang Zemin
and Zhu Rongji, are ``even more popular than C.H. Tung,'' Hong
Kong's appointed governor.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's political parties, once defined by being
``pro-China'' or ``anti-China,'' are having to realign themselves
on socioeconomic issues _ and not doing well at it. ``There seems
to be a sense of chaos in our politics right now,'' Lau said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats (the ``anti-China'' party) are more critical of
the transition. James To, party spokesman for law, said China had
agreed that Hong Kong's courts would have jurisdiction over all
local affairs. Yet in the recent kidnapping case of a tycoon's son,
a criminal dubbed ``Big Spender'' (Cheung Tze Keung) was arrested,
tried and shot in China for a crime committed in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   As for Tung, To said the Beijing-appointed governor ``does not
feel human rights and democracy are important,'' but ``may feel the
rule of law is more important'' because business values it.
</P>
</TEXT>
